<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-PETTITTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS SAID TO BE TRYING TO TRADE PETTITTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The Yankees are actively trying to trade the
left-hander Andy Pettitte, and they will probably want to do so
before the July 31 trading deadline, according to officials with
other teams.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte has 72 victories over the past five seasons, more than
any other Yankee pitcher, and he pitched well in important
postseason victories in 1996 and 1998, when the Yankees won the
World Series. But he is 5-7 with a 5.56 earned run average this
year, and over his last 27 starts _ dating to July 14 of last year
_ Pettitte is 9-13 with a 5.56 ERA and has been inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general manager, would not comment
on whether Pettitte was being dangled to other teams; Cashman
almost uniformly does not discuss possible trades in the month
leading up to the July 31 deadline. But other major league
executives, who spoke on the condition that they not be identified,
insist that the Yankees are making it clear they want to move
Pettitte, and move him now.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Stottlemyre, the Yankees' pitching coach, said Tuesday that
he had seen some good things from Pettitte. But the Yankees'
attempts to move Pettitte are probably as much related to payroll
concerns as they are to worries about his inconsistency.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte, 27, is making $5.95 million this year, and because he
will be eligible for salary arbitration in the off-season, he could
be in line to make from $7 million up next year _ when the Yankees
will be facing significant budget issues.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter and Mariano Rivera, who both won their cases in
arbitration in February, must be kept, and as the Yankees' most
dominant assets, they will be in line for large raises over the $5
million and $4.25 million they are earning.
</P>
<P>
   David Cone, who was expected to be named to the all-star team on
Wednesday and who has proved that his arm is sound, can become a
free agent after this season; Cone will probably want to stay, and
the Yankees will try to keep him.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens has the option of demanding a trade after this
season, and to keep Clemens in the fold, the Yankees may have to
renegotiate his $8.25 million salary.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Stanton, the Yankees' only left-handed reliever, will be a
free agent after this season, and the Yankees will want to re-sign
him or pursue a comparable left-hander, like Baltimore's Arthur
Rhodes.
</P>
<P>
   There are few ways for the Yankees to cut payroll to offset
these expected increases. Joe Girardi, their backup catcher, will
presumably not be kept at his current $3.4 million salary. Paul
O'Neill, the 36-year-old right fielder, could retire after this
season; but then the Yankees would have to identify and pay another
run producer to replace him.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte is one of the few pricey Yankees who is not locked into
a long-term deal, and he has been among the least efficient players
this season. So long as the Yankees believe it will be difficult
for him to rebound _ and their willingness to push his inclusion in
the Clemens trade talks last winter and, recently, in cursory
discussions regarding Anaheim's Chuck Finley suggest they have made
this decision _ they will gain payroll flexibility by moving
Pettitte in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are probably trying to move Pettitte now because
they do not want to be boxed into a negotiating corner during the
off-season. If the Yankees wait until after the season to trade
Pettitte, other teams could be less willing to make a deal, knowing
the Yankees might eventually choose not to tender Pettitte a
contract for 2000. Dealing Pettitte now places the Yankees in a
less desperate bargaining position.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte is the only left-hander in the Yankees' rotation, but
the Yankees are grooming another lefty in Triple-A. Ed Yarnall, who
began his career in the Mets' organization, has been throwing well
for Columbus, going 9-3 with a 3.46 ERA, allowing 90 hits and
striking out 104 in 101 1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Yarnall, 23, does not have Pettitte's track record, or his
experience in the postseason. But considering Pettitte's recent
troubles _ and his particularly poor regular-season performances
against possible October opponents, Cleveland and Texas _ the trio
of Clemens, Cone and Orlando Hernandez would be the team's three
top postseason starters.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are also expected to continue their pursuit of
Finley, a 36-year-old left-hander, who is eligible to become a free
agent after this year. He is 4-9 with a 5.52 ERA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
