<SLUG> BC-YANKS-TIGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS SURVIVE SLUGFEST WITH TIGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ When Tiger Stadium closes this fall after its 88th
season, most of the misty-eyed reminiscences will be told by
hitters. Remember how the stands jutted out from right field, they
will say, and turned fly balls into home runs? Remember those short
power alleys in right- and left-center, and that blue background
framing every pitch, as if to place it on a tee?
</P>
<P>
   Batters will miss this old place, which will be replaced next
year by a park expected to favor pitchers. The Yankees and Tigers,
likely sharing their last series in Tiger Stadium, slammed away at
each other Tuesday night, in the 941st game between the two teams
here, in a celebration of offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who collected 17 hits, held leads of as many as
five runs before the Tigers' Bobby Higginson tied the score with a
two-out home run off Mariano Rivera in the bottom of the ninth, the
first home run allowed by Rivera since Aug. 14, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But then the Yankees answered in the 10th, Chili Davis hitting a
single to score Bernie Williams with the decisive run, in a 9-8
victory.
</P>
<P>
   At the midpoint of the 1999 season, the Yankees are 50-31, on a
pace to finish the year 100-62.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch, the Yankees' second baseman, had a couple of
hits, but he left the game after being hit by a pitch on his left
elbow in the seventh inning. Knoblauch _ who has been hit by
pitches 15 times this year, tied for the most in the American
League _ went to first base in apparent pain, and in the bottom of
the seventh, he was replaced on defense by Luis Sojo.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch was hit an inning after Detroit's Damion Easley had
been hit, and after Easley was hit again in the eighth, the
Yankees' Chad Curtis was nailed by a pitch in the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees held an 8-4 lead going into the bottom of the eighth
inning, but Mike Stanton allowed a single and a walk, and with one
out, Mariano Rivera, the Yankees' closer, relieved Stanton, in a
rare eighth-inning appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The situation for the Yankees went from bad to worse: Rivera hit
Easley with a pitch, loading the bases; it was only the second time
in Rivera's 32 appearances that he allowed the first batter he
faced to reach base. The Tigers went on to score three runs in the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees 8, Tigers 7.
</P>
<P>
   It was only the fourth time this season Rivera had entered the
game in the eighth inning, and his strength may have waned as he
pitched in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera retired the first two batters in the inning, went to a
full count on Higginson and then threw a fastball right down the
middle. Higginson turned his hips and swung.
</P>
<P>
   The ball rocketed toward the right-field stands; there was no
question it was a home run. It was Higginson's first in 36 games,
and he slapped his bat to the ground. Rivera turned and gave one
big kick at the dirt, like Joe DiMaggio when he robbed of a home
run in the 1947 World Series. George Steinbrenner, watching from
the stands, grimaced. With the Yankees and Tigers moving into extra
innings, the game dragged past the four-hour mark.
</P>
<P>
   Williams beat out an infield hit with one out in the 10th, and
Tino Martinez and Davis followed with singles, Williams racing home
with the go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had this game in hand _ twice. Detroit starter Brian
Moehler (7-9), suspended earlier this season for having a piece of
sandpaper taped to the left thumb of his glove hand, needed a
foreign substance Tuesday night: the Yankees pounded him. Ten of
the 14 batters he faced reached base, most of them hitting the ball
very hard, to all the various spaces within Tiger Stadium, other
than the grandstands.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter doubled and so would Paul O'Neill. Bernie Williams
singled and Tino Martinez doubled and by then, the Yankees led,
6-1. Detroit pulled within two runs, at 6-4, but the Yankees added
two more runs in the seventh, in a rally built around three walks
and a hit batsman.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
