<SLUG> BC-WITCH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILMMAKERS OF `BLAIR WITCH PROJECT' SAY EMOTION WAS KEY TO SCARY
MOVIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The premise is simple enough.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 21, 1994, three Montgomery College film students hike
into Maryland's Black Hills Forest to shoot a documentary on the
local legend, ``the Blair Witch.'' They disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, their film footage is found. It may be simple, but
it's a premise that warrants goosebumps even in the telling. It's
as chilling onscreen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Blair Witch Project'' moved critic Roger Ebert to write:
</P>
<P>
   ``When was the last time you went to a movie and were actually
scared? Not spooked, shocked or having fun at being scared, but
completely horrified?''
</P>
<P>
   It's also taken on a life of its own, achieving near-cult status
with a Web site and hundreds of fans tapping into the history and
mythology of the Blair Witch even before the film opens in theaters
on July 16.
</P>
<P>
   This ``virtual reality'' phenomenon and scarefest is the
brainchild of two young University of Central Florida film
graduates, Dan Myrick and Ed Sanchez, who have known each other
since 1990 and who still call Orlando home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We met at film school, first semester,'' says Sanchez who,
with Myrick, recently visited Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez is the more outgoing of the duo and he shoots from the
hip with his stream-of-consciousness opinions. Myrick is thoughtful
and reserved. They have a finely balanced relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our best stuff comes when Ed comes to me with an idea. It's a
natural collaboration and makes the end product of what we do
individually even better,'' says Myrick.
</P>
<P>
   The two would be thrilled if their film became a regular on the
midnight movie circuit and they're also happy about the early,
positive praise after a screening shook up the Sundance Film
Festival in January. Yet they're wary of the overly lavish hype
that can kill a small film with unreal expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an experimental film,'' reminds Sanchez. ``We shot it
in October of '97. We shot it in only eight days. But we started
casting it in 1996. We thought of the idea in 1993.''
</P>
<P>
   It took a year to edit because the pair had 20 hours of footage,
all shot in real time in the forest and in a car.
</P>
<P>
   It also took a year to cast because they needed actors with
exceptionally strong improvisational skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a film where we essentially threw our actors out there
in the woods and let them make our movie for us,'' laughs Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   Myrick says they were initially concerned with the big buzz at
Sundance because ``at the time we didn't want to let people down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's worse to build a thing up and be let down than to not
expect anything. We're just happy the hype control mechanism is in
place as much as it can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he notes proudly ``The Blair Witch Project'' is one of
the few times ``where a movie is just one part of an overall
world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We created a realm that people can interact with, especially
with the Web site. There's even a comic book coming out. It's
become an alternate world that the movie itself is just a part of.
It proves if something is cool, entertaining and insightful as well
as emotional, people will engage.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez enthuses, ``There's even a guy at a software company who
has 1,500 employees and he's downloaded `Blair Witch' screensavers
on their computers and he's giving his employees the Friday opening
a half day off so they can go see the film.''
</P>
<P>
   All for a little movie based on old '70s TV shows like ``In
Search Of.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' admits Sanchez. ``Anything with Big Foot, the Loch
Ness monster or the yeti ... scenes with UFOs. That inspired us
more than any conventional film.''
</P>
<P>
   So what, besides the fascination with being scared to death,
makes this movie so different from say, ``Scream'' or ``Nightmare
On Elm Street?''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you try to scare people on film, the first couple movies
in a series are a trick,'' notes Sanchez. ```Blair' throws the
rules away and says you can't expect anything because you don't
know what's coming. There are no flags or triggers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've done,'' explains Myrick, ``is make an emotional
film. It operates on an emotional level. A lot of films coming out
now are full of techno-wizardry and that's cool if you're an
animator, but good films, whether scary, funny or whatever, tap
into some key emotional core.''
</P>
<P>
   The star of too many Hollywood horror films is no longer the
horror, Sanchez says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a monster, the star, the effects and that's not what
scares you. It's impressive, it looks nice. But what it ultimately
means when there's so much special effect is the filmmakers don't
trust their audience.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a prime directive to keep it real,'' says Myrick. ``We
also discussed `what do we show if we don't show the monster'? We
built this reality process and then trusted the instincts of our
actors. We hoped that the reality-based way we shot the film would
be scary. We took a risk. In the end it was what we wanted in that
we captured the moments off-camera.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fear is a lot easier to capture than drama or comedy because
it's primal,'' he adds. ``I mean, what scares the hell out of you?
It's universal. We've not all been in love but we've all been
scared. I love to hear about people, after they've seen the film,
who have some sense memory about a recollection from childhood. And
that's what the movie does. There's something subtextual about
knowing what happens to these people in advance.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez says they'll take the same approach no matter what kind
of movie they make together.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's at the heart of a film?'' he asks. ``Our next movie is
a comedy. So we ask each other `what makes us laugh?' We basically
just strip away the rules. If the film winds up following
convention, it does. There's no formula.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, we weren't taken seriously before `Blair' and we
didn't ever take ourselves seriously. We just wanted to prove we
aren't afraid to take chances. More than being thought of as
directors, I'd just like our production company, Haxan, to be
thought of as a place where you can't predict what's coming next.''
</P>
<P>
   Myrick adds, ``Yeah, where no matter what, if you see one of our
movies you'll know we had our hearts in what we did. It may flop,
it may not, but it'll be a ride. That's what I like about Jim
Jarmusch and John Sayles. They take chances and you have to respect
that. That's all I can ask for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
