<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUS-AFTERMATH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE EMERGENCY CREWS LEARNED LESSONS FROM BUS SHOOTING,
ACCIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ At just after 3 p.m. the day after Thanksgiving last
year, a gunman put a bullet into a Metro bus driver, sending the
bus plunging off the Aurora Bridge and triggering a chain of events
that would test the limits of Seattle's emergency medical services.
</P>
<P>
   Although emergency response crews are used to seeing
mind-chilling injuries from falls, shootings, suicides, collapsing
buildings, auto accidents and hazardous material spills, they
seldom find them all at once.
</P>
<P>
   The Aurora Bridge bus incident had all the characteristics of a
terrorist attack, said A.D. Vickery, deputy chief of special
operations for the Seattle Fire Department. ``It had mass
casualties, a crime scene, and the need for a coordinated
response.''
</P>
<P>
   The bus incident, which left three people dead, and the
department's response was the subject of a cover story in the June
issue of the Journal of Emergency Medical Services. In the
emergency response community, there has been steady interest in how
the bus incident was handled and what could be learned from it,
said Vickery, who has fielded calls from about 30 other emergency
departments around the country since the bus shooting six months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the shooting and bus plunge, the department
has made several changes in the way it handles MCIs, or ``mass
casualty incidents,'' including a proposed plan for better tracking
good Samaritans who respond to accidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took a good hard look and found some ways to make the
operation more efficient,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of those rare, sunny November afternoons in Seattle
when Metro's Route 359 bus headed south onto the Aurora bridge
carrying 35 passengers toward downtown Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was a ``pow, pow,'' and the bus swerved.
</P>
<P>
   In the seconds that followed, the 40,000-pound articulated bus
careened into oncoming traffic, striking a van and turning around
before plummeting over the bridge deck and smashing into an
apartment building 50 feet below. In a surreal twist, the bus tore
apart, landing in a shrieking wreck just under the gaze of the
Fremont troll, a community landmark that lurks beneath the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Had gunman Silas Cool started shooting a few seconds later, the
bus and its passengers would have sunk into the Lake Washington
ship canal.
</P>
<P>
   Those killed were Mark McLaughlin, Herman Liebelt, a passenger,
and Cool, who turned the gun on himself. Thirty-two people were
injured.
</P>
<P>
   Vickery was off-duty at home when he got the call at 3:13 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first call said there was a ``bus in a building,''' he
said. As chief of special operations, his job was to plan for the
unplanned. He immediately headed for the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Driving toward the scene, his first thought was the bridge.
Already, his mind was planning for contingencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought possibly the bus might be hanging off the bridge,''
he said. ``My job was to make sure we got enough resources there.''
</P>
<P>
   The original response was designated ``heavy rescue _ major.''
</P>
<P>
   In a ``heavy rescue major'' incident, the department sends five
engine companies, two ladder trucks, a heavy rescue unit with
equipment to lift and move apart heavy objects, two aid cars, two
medic units, two battalion chiefs, a safety chief, and an aid unit
to resupply air for firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   As Vickery approached the scene, however, there were signs this
was going to be more than a heavy rescue operation. Three blocks
from the location, he was flagged down by a middle-age couple who'd
found a man in his mid-20s wandering in the street, cut, dazed and
disoriented. It was an ominous sign _ one of the first tasks in an
emergency response is to secure the scene to keep victims from
wandering away and potentially endangering themselves further.
</P>
<P>
   Vickery scooped the victim into his car and kept going. A block
later, he encountered the next of many unanticipated events that
day.
</P>
<P>
   Police, responding to the shooting, had already arrived at the
scene, but their unattended vehicles were blocking routes to the
accident site. Vickery went the rest of the way on foot.
</P>
<P>
   As medic units began arriving, they too had to abandon their
vehicles. One of the first aid units to arrive tried to squeeze
through on a narrow sidewalk, blowing out two tires.
</P>
<P>
   According to the incident report, ``responding units had to use
several alternate routes into the location or park away from the
scene and carry equipment in.'' The blocking problem also slowed
the inital set-up of a base of operation.
</P>
<P>
   Since the incident, the Seattle Fire Department has improved its
coordination with police to ensure access routes are preserved at
crime scenes, Vickery said.
</P>
<P>
   Within 15 minutes of the accident, Vickery and the incident
commander on scene upgraded the response to an mass casualty
incident.
</P>
<P>
   An MCI designation automatically dispatches two more medic
units, a medical services officer and administrator, another aid
car and additional ambulances. In all, 22 fire department units
responded to the accident scene as well as about 20 ambulances.
</P>
<P>
   What didn't get to the scene, however, was the MCI trailer, a
critical piece of equipment with backboards and other emergency
supplies for taking care of 30 patients.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the accident, the MCI trailer had to be hooked to
an engine and dragged to the scene. With all units already
dispatched, there were none left to hook it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was available, but we couldn't get it transported,''
Vickery said. Consequently, there was a shortage of backboards at
the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the department has begun outfitting a special MCI
van with enough equipment to take care of 100 patients. The van
will be able to get to the scene of an accident independent of any
other units, he said.
</P>
<P>
   There were other lessons learned from the bus incident.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the department has refined its system of patient
triage to speed it up. Rather than waste precious time taking vital
signs, first responders will rely more on what they can see and
touch to determine which patients need the most help. That will
streamline the process of getting patients to staging areas where
medics can stabilize them for treatment or transport.
</P>
<P>
   Another lesson that came out of that tragic afternoon was the
need for better identification of people's roles at the scene of an
accident. In the chaos that followed the crash, it was difficult to
tell who was who, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The department is considering equipping its new MCI van with
special vests to identify good Samaritans, especially those, such
as doctors or nurses, who are qualified to assist patients. It has
also purchased larger signs to mark patient treatment zones so
there's a clearer boundary between the most critically wounded
(``red'' priority), those needing immediate attention (``yellow''
priority) and the walking wounded (``green'' priority.)
</P>
<P>
   A review of the incident also recommended the department get
vests to identify supervisors in charge of triage, treatment and
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the department is looking at ways to track good
Samaritans after they've left the scene.
</P>
<P>
   The need for such a system was brought home after health
officials discovered one of the victims on the bus was
HIV-positive.
</P>
<P>
   The department's post-incident analysis may have yielded areas
in need of improvement, but overall, the response was handled in a
safe, orderly and efficient manner, Vickery said.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-nine minutes into the accident, the last patient had been
transported to one of the seven emergency rooms taking bus victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the job we do, we're dealing with emergencies as they
develop. We can't allow ourselves to be overwhelmed,'' Vickery
said. ``We take it in pieces and control it piece by piece.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
