<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1340 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNITY-SPI &LR;      07-07 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNITY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA HIRING OF MINORITIES NOT MATCHING MAKEUP OF U.S., FORUM
TOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It was billed as a town hall meeting open to the
public, but some of the most poignant moments at a forum Tuesday on
minority representation in the media occurred before the
question-and-answer session ever got started.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: Dolores Sibonga, columnist for the Filipino
American Herald, told the audience about her days as a journalism
student in the 1950s, when there were three students of color in
her class.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our radio/television professor sat down with us one day and
said, `You know, we weren't sure whether we were going to let you
graduate, because we weren't sure if you could get jobs.'''
</P>
<P>
   Case in point No. 2: Newsweek contributor and columnist Ellis
Cose told how he was going through the memos of his predecessor
after he joined the New York Daily News many years ago as head of
the newspaper's editorial pages. One of the memos, Cose said, was
``an edict'' declaring that the paper could run no more than one
black columnist per day.
</P>
<P>
   ``What that illustrated to me,'' Cose said, ``was that he had in
his head an idea of how much diversity was enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Up and down the panel of six minority journalists, the stories
were strikingly similar, making for a kick-in-the-consciousness
launch to UNITY '99, the largest gathering of journalists in the
country. UNITY is an alliance of four organizations representing
minority journalists, and this week's meeting of an estimated 6,000
participants in Seattle is the second such cooperative convention
whose aim is to improve minority representation in the media.
</P>
<P>
   Catalina Camia, president of UNITY and a Washington, D.C.,
reporter for the Dallas Morning News, said editors have pledged for
years that they value diversity in their hiring and their news
content.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as America becomes more ethnically and racially diverse,''
she said, ``the media have been slow to keep pace with this dynamic
change. Most of the people who cover the news and make the decision
about what gets covered are still overwhelmingly white and male,
and the reality is that as America becomes more diverse, many
people of color believe they are being excluded from the front
pages and evening news. That is a disturbing fact for this
industry, which must discover a way to address this disparity or
lose credibility with the communities they serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Camia's concern is supported by industry figures that show
hiring of minorities in newsrooms across the United States has
leveled off after enjoying a growth spurt in the early '90s. While
the Census Bureau says people of color now make up 28 percent of
the general U.S. population, they account for only 11.5 percent of
newsroom employees at daily newspapers and 19 percent at commercial
television stations. These figures, provided by the American
Society of Newspaper Editors and the Radio &AMP; Television News
Directors Association, have not changed markedly in the past five
years, despite efforts by both organizations to encourage minority
hiring.
</P>
<P>
   ASNE, in fact, created a goal more than 20 years ago to reach
minority-representation ``parity'' in the newspaper industry by the
year 2000. It has since pushed back the target date to 2025 ``or
sooner,'' if possible. For nearly three decades, meanwhile,
broadcasters were under Federal Communications Commission rules to
diversify their newsrooms or risk losing their licenses. That 1969
rule has since been ruled unconstitutional but RTNDA president
Barbara Cochran says radio and TV stations remain committed to
diversity.
</P>
<P>
   The slow progress toward matching the minority makeup of the
nation now has some newspaper editors thinking about ASNE's goal of
diversifying newsrooms not as a matter of hiring but as a matter of
journalistic accuracy. David Yarnold, executive editor of the San
Jose Mercury News, said that if a paper doesn't truly reflect its
community, is it really being accurate in its coverage?
</P>
<P>
   By phrasing the issue this way, Yarnold said, ``we think we've
hit a nerve _ (using) diversity as a core journalism value, a
dimension of accuracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some of the panelists were skeptical of ASNE's goal.
</P>
<P>
   Cose said journalism institutions must undergo a ``huge and
fundamental change'' in how they operate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not so much call it a matter of accuracy as a matter
of comprehensiveness,'' he said. ``What needs to happen is that
communities of color need to be treated the same way that white,
upper-middle-class communities are treated.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Sibonga added: ``I don't think things will change until
ownership changes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 0050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 00:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1341 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BBA-REDSOX-DEVILRAYS-BOS     07-07 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
END NOT A RELIEF FOR RED SOX?
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-REDSOX-DEVILRAYS-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By MARK BLAUDSCHUN 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Different script, slightly different
story. But when it comes to playing the Devil Rays, it was the same
old frustrating ending for the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay may look like normal lower-echelon fodder to most
folks, considering that the Devil Rays are 12 games below .500 and
mired in fourth place in the AL East.
</P>
<P>
   But to the Red Sox, who are 4-7 against Tampa Bay this season,
Tuesday night's 6-4 loss was just plain aggravating.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're tough,'' sighed Red Sox manager Jimy Williams after
watching a 4-3 lead turn into a loss when reliever John Wasdin
threw a less-than-great fastball to Paul Sorrento, and the ball
landed just beyond the grasp of Damon Buford, who tried to pull the
ball back into play over the center-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   But as has been the case most of the season against the Devil
Rays, who clinched the season series with the victory, it wasn't
quite enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had a lot of close games with them,'' said Williams. ``They're
a good team.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the Red Sox, they're better than good. The Devils Rays
may be going nowhere but home come the first week of October, but
you couldn't tell that to the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night was frustrating because the Red Sox came so close
again as they grinded through another game minus some key players,
wasting some good efforts, and coming up a little short.
</P>
<P>
   For example:
</P>
<P>
   They again played without All-Star starting shortstop Nomar
Garciaparra, who is bothered by a pulled left groin that has kept
him out of four straight games.
</P>
<P>
   They wasted a good performance from rookie pitcher Jin Ho Cho,
who worked a solid five innings before departing after throwing 81
pitches and holding a one-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   And they wasted another clutch hit by first baseman Mike
Stanley, who ripped a three-run homer, his 11th, into the
right-field seats in the third for a 4-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But essentially, the game came down to one pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays had nipped at Cho's pitches for five innings and
had closed to within 4-3 when Williams went to his bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   First up was Pat Rapp, who went two strong innings before a
one-out walk to Wade Boggs in the eighth brought Williams out of
the dugout and Wasdin into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Wasdin knew what to expect; he was the designated setup guy for
the night. ``Derek Lowe pitched (Monday night),'' said Wasdin. ``So
I knew there was a pretty good chance I would get in the game
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   So in he came. With one out and the tying run on first, Wasdin
allowed a bloop single to shortstop Aaron Ledesma, putting runners
on first and second and bringing up Sorrento, a New Englander who
seems to find a way to beat the Red Sox with his bat at least once
a year.
</P>
<P>
   Wasdin threw a couple of setup pitches and then went to his
fastball, which he wanted to throw high and tight, but instead came
in low and away into Sorrento's power area, and he cracked his
second homer in less than a week off Wasdin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played well,'' said Wasdin. ``My job was to come in and
shut them down. It didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, I was just trying to make solid contact,'' said
Sorrento, a Peabody native. ``It had been a long night before that
(0 for 3). He just happpened to put a pitch over the plate, a
fastball, and it just hit the good part of the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom of the eighth was typical of what has happened to the
Red Sox against the Devil Rays this season.
</P>
<P>
   So was the entire game. The Red Sox pounded starter Wilson
Alvarez for seven hits in the first three innings, highlighted by
Stanley's blast.
</P>
<P>
   Cho, coming off a horrendous effort a week ago against Tampa in
which he was rocked for eight hits and four runs in 3 2/3 innings,
turned in a solid effort.
</P>
<P>
   But the Devil Rays picked up two runs in the fourth on a two-out
double by catcher Mike DiFelice and another in the fifth on an RBI
groundout by Jose Canseco.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, the Red Sox did enough things right and hung on
for a 4-2 win. Tuesday night, it turned out the wrong way again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get enough runs,'' said Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Not enough runs, not enough hits. Not enough good pitches at the
right time.
</P>
<P>
   But with Pedro Martinez going Wednesday night, it would appear
that the Red Sox are ready to right their ship.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, you never know with the Devil Rays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
