A1344 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-TOBACCO-NYT &LR;      07-07 0296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TOBACCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: OBSTACLE TO A TOBACCO SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, July 7:
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has been exploring ways to bring a
lawsuit against the tobacco industry to recoup the billions of
dollars spent treating smoking-related illnesses under Medicare and
other federal medical programs. Forty-six states reached a $206
billion settlement with tobacco companies last year to recover
state Medicaid costs connected to smoking. A successful federal
suit could bring in new revenues that would shore up the Medicare
trust fund and help reduce smoking by raising cigarette prices.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the Senate Appropriations Committee refused in
its spending bill for the Commerce, Justice and State departments
to finance the administration's $20 million request to proceed with
the suit. Worse, the committee's report contains ambiguous language
that might be read to prohibit the Justice Department from pursuing
the litigation at all. The report expressly says that no funds are
provided for expert witnesses in any tobacco lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Richard Durbin, D-Ill., and Bob Graham, D-Fla., both
strong proponents of tobacco control, are expected to offer an
amendment on the Senate floor to make clear that nothing in the
appropriations bill prevents the tobacco lawsuit. If the vague
language in the committee report is used to stop the administration
from pressing legitimate claims, that would amount to giving the
tobacco industry immunity from the federal suit. It would also set
a dangerous precedent in other cases where lawmakers might be
tempted to run interference for companies or industries that are
faced with government litigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 0056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1346 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-KASHMIR-NYT &LR;      07-07 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KASHMIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NEW PROMISES ON KASHMIR 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, July 7:
</P>
<P>
   After a timely intervention by President Clinton over the
weekend, Pakistan may be ready to bring about the withdrawal of
hundreds of armed Islamic militants fighting Indian soldiers in the
mountains of Kashmir. The pledge to take ``concrete steps'' on the
border with India, including the withdrawal of the militants from
Indian territory, was made by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif after a
hastily scheduled meeting with Clinton in Washington. It was a
welcome promise that could defuse tensions. But Sharif could have
difficulty executing it. In the face of continued fighting in the
mountains, he must persuade the army and supporters of the
militants in Pakistan that it is the right course.
</P>
<P>
   Since independence and partition in 1947, India and Pakistan
have fought two wars over Kashmir, a coveted region of lakes, lush
valleys and snowy mountains. The Kashmiris themselves seem to want
outright independence. A guerrilla uprising has raged for most of
the last decade, killing thousands as Indian troops have been sent
in to put it down. But Pakistan badly miscalculated if it was
hoping to draw the world's attention to Kashmir by sending in
several hundred guerrilla fighters this spring. India has been
right to demand withdrawal of the militants before any further
negotiations on Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   For most of its history, Pakistan has been ruled by military
dictatorships, and the Kashmir operation may have been carried out
by elements of the army. If that is the case, their motive may well
have been to humiliate or undercut Sharif, who took the bold step
of inviting the Indian prime minister, Atal Behari Vajpayee, to
Lahore earlier this year for a meeting to reduce mutual tensions.
The fear in Pakistan now is that if the insurgents in Kashmir are
forced to withdraw, they and their allies could train their sights
on Sharif's government, throwing Pakistan into turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif needs to persuade the Islamic militants and their
supporters that the infiltration has backfired, alienating
traditional Pakistani allies like China and drowning out Pakistan's
demands for a mediated settlement. Sharif can also claim to have
achieved progress in Pakistan's drive to draw the United States in
as a mediator. After meeting with Sharif, Clinton promised to take
a renewed ``personal interest'' in intensifying talks between these
two rival nations.
</P>
<P>
   India has responded with firmness and restraint to the recent
threat, though it has lost several hundred lives while trying to
dislodge the militants from their mountain redoubts. Now India can
make a withdrawal easier by not firing on militants if they leave
and by pledging to reopen talks on Kashmir and other issues.
Kashmir is a seemingly intractable dispute of religion, ethnicity
and borders. But as the world learned in Kosovo, these disputes can
spin out of control. India and Pakistan, now armed with nuclear
weapons, have no choice but to resolve their disagreements
peacefully.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
