<HEADER>
A1348 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEING-RACE-SPI &LR;      07-07 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-RACE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR DEPARTMENT ACCUSES BOEING OF WITHHOLDING RECORDS IN BIAS
CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The U.S. Labor Department accused The Boeing Co. of
interfering with its investigation of discrimination at the
aerospace giant in three lawsuits filed Tuesday, opening another
chapter in the company's effort to settle charges of racial bias.
</P>
<P>
   Federal lawyers charged that Boeing denied investigators access
to records and facilities tied to allegations of racial
discrimination by Paul Coston, a Boeing employee. Coston is also
involved in a proposed $15 million settlement of racial
discrimination charges at Boeing, although he objects to the
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department, however, is investigating charges of bias
in a different arena. Under federal law, the agency is permitted to
look into allegations of discrimination at any company that secures
federal contracts. Boeing, the second-largest U.S. defense
contractor, earned $11 billion in federal work in the last fiscal
year, the department said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denying us that access cannot _ and will not _ be tolerated,''
said Labor Secretary Alexis Herman in a prepared statement after
the suits were filed at the Labor Department's Office of
Administrative Law Judges.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing attempted to resolve charges of racial bias on Jan. 22,
when it announced it was settling two class-action lawsuits brought
by a group of African American employees who charged they were
discriminated against at the aerospace giant.
</P>
<P>
   The suits complained of a racially hostile work environment in
which blacks were the object of slurs, crude drawings and
intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's action includes two other suits in which the Labor
Department charged Boeing with interfering in compliance reviews in
Mesa, Ariz., and Wichita, Kan. In all three cases brought Tuesday,
the Office of Federal Contract Compliance Programs, a division of
the Labor Department, was denied access to records, according to
the lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing officials claim the Labor Department is seeking an
unreasonable amount of information that goes beyond Coston's
original claims, according to Peter Conte, a spokesman for the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing argued that if the courts eventually approve the
settlement, brokered in January with the help of civil rights
leader Jesse Jackson, Coston's claims will be addressed, according
to Conte. In that case the Labor Department lacks the authority to
continue reviewing Coston's charges, Conte said.
</P>
<P>
   Coston was unavailable last night for comment on the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The violations, if proven, could carry hefty penalties. The
government can cancel contracts or bar a company from future
federal work. However, both sides said they were hopeful they could
settle the issues without imposing sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing officials added that they would like to resolve the
matter ``informally'' and are talking with federal officials about
the cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what gives us a reasonable belief that we can work
through these issues,'' Conte said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Boeing has never lost a contract because of an
assessment that it failed to comply with federal equal opportunity
and affirmative action laws, Conte said.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear what effect the lawsuits will have on the separate
proposal to settle discrimination charges at Boeing. The plan,
brokered by Jackson, is pending in U.S. District Court.
</P>
<P>
   In May, U.S. District Court Judge John Coughenour granted
opponents of the pact four months to investigate allegations that
it doesn't go far enough. Coston is one of the employees who
objects, according to lawyers working on the case.
</P>
<P>
   The federal judge has scheduled another hearing for Sept. 23,
after lawyers depose a handful of witnesses, which could include
Boeing's chairman and chief executive officer, Phil Condit.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to $15 million in payments, Boeing promised in the
settlement to improve the way it selects and promotes workers,
promised to adopt a new system for handling complaints about
discrimination, harassment or retaliation and hire a consultant to
assess how well the changes work.
</P>
<P>
   Some employees, led by Philadelphia-based lawyer Alan Epstein of
Jablon Epstein, said the proposal didn't go far enough, charging it
lacked the teeth to enforce the changes. They also questioned
whether the monetary award was large enough, according to Mary
Roberts, another lead lawyer in the case, representing Frank Rosen
Freed Garfinkel &AMP; Roberts based in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The initial suit was brought by 43 black workers who said
discrimination was common at Boeing plants in the Puget Sound area.
</P>
<P>
   Later, black workers for Boeing in Philadelphia and Wichita
joined the suit. A second suit also was started. Nearly 13,000
blacks worked for Boeing around the country as of January. The
total work force is currently about 214,000.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed settlement, 20,000 current and former
employees of Boeing and its subsidiary companies would be eligible
to share in $7.3 million in payments.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing also agreed to spend $3.65 million on improved training
and changes in the way it selects managers and makes other
promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing must also pay $750,000 over three years to finance the
monitoring of the settlement, according to lawyers for the
plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the 35-page document, Boeing denied it ever
engaged in any pattern of racial discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Boeing is facing 10 open compliance reviews and three
complaint investigations, according to Conte.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 0100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
