A1350 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMOKE-CRACKDOWN-LADN     07-07 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOKE-CRACKDOWN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. WILL LIGHT INTO SMOKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH SULLIVAN AND JESSE HIESTAND  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Eighteen months after a state workplace-smoking
ban took effect, Los Angeles launches its enforcement program
Wednesday with two full-time city smoking inspectors for more than
3,000 bars and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've got the teeth to the ordinance now, and we've
got staffing to follow up on the complaints whereas before we had
the ordinance without an enforcement mechanism,'' said Fire Chief
William Bamattre.
</P>
<P>
   The state ban on smoking in public bars, restaurants and other
eateries took effect in January 1998. But the city lagged in
cracking down on violations, with no formal enforcement program.
</P>
<P>
   Fire officials cannot say how many citations the department has
issued.
</P>
<P>
   After months of planning, two fire inspectors were assigned to
investigate complaints of smoking in public bars and eateries, and
to issue citations to owners, employees and patrons who break the
ban.
</P>
<P>
   Fines start at $81 and can run up to $500.
</P>
<P>
   ``A quite overdue effective enforcement program is being put in
place,'' said Councilwoman Laura Chick, who chairs the City
Council's Public Safety Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had this state law in effect for a year and a half.
Better late than never, but this should have been running sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's new inspectors made a trial run in search of smoking
ban violations Thursday, fire officials said, but issued no
citations. They will begin the program in full force today.
</P>
<P>
   The program, with two inspectors and a clerk, costs $250,000 a
year and is paid out of the city's general fund. The city has
sought additional money from the county and from national tobacco
settlements to educate the public about the smoking ban, but those
funds remain uncertain, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The enforcement system begins with a letter notifying restaurant
and bar owners of the enforcement program, according to a Fire
Department report released Tuesday. Businesses then must post signs
bearing a toll-free number that patrons or employees can call to
report violations.
</P>
<P>
   After the first such complaint, the establishment gets a notice
of violation. After the second complaint, it gets a visit from Fire
Department inspectors within three days.
</P>
<P>
   If inspectors catch someone smoking, they will notify City
Attorney James Hahn, whose office will decide whether to file
criminal charges against an owner or employee.
</P>
<P>
   Penalties for businesses range from $100 for a first offense to
$500 for a third offense, and could escalate up to $7,000 if the
problem is serious enough for Cal-OSHA _ the state Occupational
Safety and Health Administration _ to get involved, said fire
Captain Mark Gozawa.
</P>
<P>
   Fines against patrons range from $81 to $324, depending on
whether it's a first offense or a repeat offense.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year and a half, the City Attorney's Office has
issued 325 letters of violation, and referred 106 cases to the Fire
Department, said City Attorney's Office spokesman Mike Qualls.
</P>
<P>
   Fire officials said they do not know how many of those cases led
to citations, but one of those cases went to prosecution, Qualls
said.
</P>
<P>
   Among those welcoming the new enforcement efforts is Brian
Wilke, 36, a nonsmoker from suburban Van Nuys. Wilke said he was
glad no one was smoking in the Robin Hood British Pub in Van Nuys
while he was eating a cheeseburger and having a pint of beer.
</P>
<P>
   But he was more interested in the fire inspectors' efforts
because he believed it would be fairer for those bars and
restaurants that abide by the law and lose business to neighboring
establishments that let patrons smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't just have one place doing it and another not doing
it,'' Wilke said. ``There has to be consistency among everybody for
it to be a fair law.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the San Fernando Valley, some barkeepers would
rather risk a fine and permit smoking than lose business.
</P>
<P>
   At a small bar in Sherman Oaks, three of the eight customers
were openly smoking Tuesday afternoon with no objection from the
bartender.
</P>
<P>
   The bartender, who asked that the business not be identified out
of fear of being targeted by inspectors, said the bar had banned
customers from smoking for a few months after the law passed. But a
steady decline in business and little evidence of enforcement
forced it to gradually rescinded the ban, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had four notices of our first warning,'' said the
bartender, who said he figured the anti-smoking crackdown in Los
Angeles was inevitable after officials in San Diego launched a
similar effort.
</P>
<P>
   At most, he said he reminds customers that it is illegal to
smoke in the bar and he refers to ashtrays as ``candy dishes.''
</P>
<P>
   He believes it is inevitable that he will be inspected and fined
for allowing smoking, but has seen no reason yet to restrict
patrons' desire to smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to happen. They're going to come in here and I'm
going to get fined and the customers are going to get fined,'' he
said. ``But what can you do? Look over your shoulder all the
time?''
</P>
<P>
   A patron of the bar, Tom Millican, 65, a retired accountant from
Sherman Oaks, said the mere threat of a fine was not enough to get
him to snuff out his Marlboro. Instead, he would wait to see how
strict the inspectors would be in coming months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see if they enforce it,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 0102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
