<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-CARE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULATIONS HAVE HOME HEALTH CARE SYSTEM IN A TAILSPIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; tx:WASHINGTON _ Until she reached 92, Mildred Bengston
maintained her independence.
</P>
<P>
   She lived alone in the same Kansas City, Kan., neighborhood she
had called home for 40 years. And with her daughter and
grandchildren nearby, help was always at hand. But in spring 1996,
she became bedridden with assorted ailments.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's home health-care system, which through Medicare has
helped many elderly patients stay out of costly hospitals and
nursing homes, stepped in to help. A nurse treated Bengston at home
three times a week.
</P>
<P>
   But the system now is in a tailspin, rocked by financial and
regulatory restrictions. For millions of in-home patients
throughout the country, the outlook is unsettling.
</P>
<P>
   The home health-care industry and its advocates say more
patients are losing services and more are forced to seek expensive
treatment elsewhere, while some _ the number is not known _ are
disappearing through the cracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is safe to assume we really don't know where these patients
are or how their health status has been affected,'' Barbara Markham
Smith, a health-policy analyst, told a Senate hearing on home
health care last month.
</P>
<P>
   Health care has become a front-burner political issue as the
2000 elections approach. President Clinton has proposed that
Medicare recipients receive prescription drug coverage, and
Congress is wrestling with HMO reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Home health care arose as an issue last week as Sens. Kit Bond
of Missouri and Susan Collins of Maine, both Republicans, offered
legislation to ease some of the restrictions Congress placed on the
industry two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters estimate that about 2,000 home health-care agencies
have shut down since Congress passed the Balanced Budget Act of
1997, which contained new controls and cutbacks in Medicare
spending.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, nearly a third of the more than 300 home
health-care agencies closed, including the Visiting Nurse
Association of St. Louis. In Kansas, the toll has been 47 agencies
out of more than 200 _ including Bengston's original provider.
</P>
<P>
   She now is being cared for by another agency, but sees a nurse
only once a week. Her daughter, 68-year-old Woodyne Mann, retired
from teaching elementary school to stay home and care for her. It
was either that or send her to a nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made up my mind that I would keep her here in my home,''
Mann said.
</P>
<P>
   The full impact of the reforms, however, appears to have been
unanticipated. The goal was to make the program more efficient, and
the Congressional Budget Office originally concluded that the
changes would cut Medicare home health expenses by $16 billion over
five years. That estimate has swollen to nearly $50 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the federal Health Care Financing Administration,
which oversees Medicare, argue that the impact has not been as
serious as the industry and its advocates portray.
</P>
<P>
   The reforms have ``helped control what was widespread fraud,
waste and abuse, and put us in a position to better protect
vulnerable beneficiaries and improve the quality of home health
care,'' Kathleen Buto, a Health Care Financing Administration
executive, told the Senate at the June hearing. ``We, to date, do
not have objective evidence that...access to care has been
compromised.''
</P>
<P>
   A General Accounting Office report in May stated that the same
number of home health agencies operating in 1996 _ more than 9,000
_ were operating as of Jan. 1 of this year. Even as agencies were
closing in a handful of states, more were opening, the report
stated. The closings occurred largely in urban areas where patients
still had many choices.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith, the analyst involved in a study of the Medicare
changes on home health care, said the zeal to ferret out fraud has
affected both the ``fraudulent provider and the honest provider.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The result is, in the name of controlling fraud, they are
imposing a payment system that will have a very serious effect on
the ability of the sickest to get care, because it...links high
cost with fraud, when that is, in fact, a false linkage,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bond and Collins agreed. Their bill, which has bipartisan
support, would eliminate a 15 percent across-the-board cut in
federal home health-care payments scheduled for Oct. 1, 2000. Bond,
Missouri's former chief executive, called the provision ``similar
to a last-minute pardon from the governor. I fear this cut would
truly be the death knell for the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 reforms created an Interim Payment System that changed
federal home health reimbursement practices. Instead of paying
agencies according to the cost of their services, they get a
predetermined limit per patient. But that limit is based on what
they received in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   By October 2000, the system will reimburse home health-care
agencies according to a uniform code of treatment costs.
</P>
<P>
   But the fallout from the interim system severely hit patients
who need long-term care, because they are more expensive. Many
agencies are operating under government-imposed caps of around
$3,000 annually per patient. That's less than it can cost to see a
long-term patient just once a week for a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Interim Payment System was devastating the system, to say
the least,'' said Mary Schantz, executive director of the Missouri
Alliance for Home Health Care. ``It had a chilling effect on an
agency's ability to accept higher-cost patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the fraud and abuse that regulators and members of
Congress said was so rampant has been called into question. The
National Association of Home Care, the industry's trade group,
noted that federal investigators backed off somewhat on their
original claim that 40 percent of the home health services paid by
Medicare should not have been covered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear all these wild stories about fraudulent (operators)
caught going off to vacation in the Bahamas,'' said Linda Lubensky,
executive director of the Kansas Home Care Association. ``That's
not the case in Kansas. These are small businesses just making
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Lubensky said any extra funds get invested in equipment upgrades
or are used for indigent people who otherwise would not have access
to home care.
</P>
<P>
   Eileen Van Tasell, who operated agencies in Overland Park and
Kansas City, North, was the original provider for Bengston. She
said the new rules have made it nearly impossible to keep clients
like Bengston who require more complex medical services or
increased attention. Van Tasell is a nurse who has been in the
health-care business for 31 years, but she sold her 7-year-old
business in May to John Knox Village because of the new
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   She once had to turn down aid for an elderly woman who was blind
and diabetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her blindness and diabetes were not going to go away,'' said
Van Tasell, who now operates a private-duty nursing service. ``I
was in an ethical dilemma. What Medicare doesn't pay me, I have to
pay for. Do I put my family and my company at the risk of
bankruptcy, or do I become financially responsible for someone I've
never seen before?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
