<SLUG> BC-MOSEN-FUNDS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASHCROFT LEADS CARNAHAN BY NEARLY $1 MILLION IN FUND-RAISING
DOLLARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sen. John Ashcroft has jumped to an early fund-raising lead in
his bid to retain his seat by collecting nearly $1 million more
than Democrat Mel Carnahan.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft, a Missouri Republican, reported Tuesday that from the
time his campaign began through June 30, he has raised $3 million.
Carnahan, the incumbent two-term governor, said he had taken in
$2.1 million since his campaign began in November 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft had been running for president until early this year,
when he switched to running for Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans praised Ashcroft's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are astonishing results, especially with Mel Carnahan
using every bit of his power and leverage as governor to pull in
every possible dollar,'' Missouri GOP Chairwoman Ann Wagner said.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan spokesman Roy Temple countered that the Democrat would
have enough to get his message out. He compared Carnahan's fund
raising to that of fellow Democrat Charles Schumer of New York, the
congressman who defeated GOP Sen. Alfonse D'Amato in 1998. Schumer
had raised about $2.2 million at this point in the last election
cycle, Temple said.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Nixon, the Democrat who lost to Sen. Kit Bond last year, had
raised less than $500,000 at the same point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody always anticipated that as an incumbent U.S.
senator, Ashcroft would be able to raise more than the Carnahan
campaign,'' Temple said.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft said that in the first six months of the year he raised
$2.2 million, compared with Carnahan's $1.4 million for the same
period.
</P>
<P>
   Neither campaign has released its cash-on-hand totals, the
figure that indicates how much money each candidate has in the bank
after paying expenses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
