<SLUG> BC-THIRD-DISTRICT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS TALK TURNS TOWARD 2000, GOP NO LONGER SEES DENNIS MOORE AS A
FLUKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They called Dennis Moore a fluke.
</P>
<P>
   A Democratic congressman from Republican-rich Johnson County? A
duck in the Sahara?
</P>
<P>
   But as the talk turns toward 2000 and Moore's re-election bid,
even Republicans are acknowledging that the first Democrat to win
the 3rd District in four decades will be tough to oust.
</P>
<P>
   The rationale for that belief:
</P>
<P>
   - Unlike his predecessor, Republican Vince Snowbarger of Olathe,
the freshman has proved to be an aggressive fund-raiser. Next week,
Moore will report that he has $300,000 in his campaign account. At
the same time in his first term, Snowbarger had $9,600 on hand and
$26,000 in debts.
</P>
<P>
   - A slow-moving Congress has yet to force Moore to take many
stands on prominent issues, though Moore recently voted against a
bill that sought to make it illegal to burn the American flag. The
congressman deemed the decision his most risky vote so far.
</P>
<P>
   - GOP candidates are slow getting out of the gate. In fact, more
Republicans are opting out of the 3rd District race than are
jumping in.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, at least to the Cook Political Report, a
Washington political newsletter, is that the district ``leans''
toward re-electing Moore.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the rating comes early in the election cycle, and a
lot can change. Republicans insist, for example, that their nominee
will get a big boost from the large number of voters who will want
to vote for president. In the 3rd District, most of those voters
will be Republicans, and many will be inclined to back the GOP
candidate for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the odds of beating Dennis are greater than 50-50 but
are by no means certain,'' said Kansas GOP Chairman Mark Parkinson.
</P>
<P>
   As in 1998, the race for the 3rd District, which covers Johnson,
Wyandotte, Miami and parts of Douglas counties, will be one of the
premier contests in the country. Republicans, who hold only a
12-seat edge over the Democrats in the House, view this seat as
prime GOP territory and will provide ``virtually unlimited
support'' to their nominee, Parkinson said. Democrats are likely to
do the same.
</P>
<P>
   With the stakes so high, potential GOP challengers have been
sizing up their chances since shortly after the 1998 election.
Consultants have been interviewed, an in-depth poll has been taken,
and GOP leaders have struggled to find a consensus candidate who
can appeal to conservative and moderate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   So far, three likely Republican contenders have emerged: state
Rep. Phill Kline of Shawnee, Overland Park City Councilman Greg
Musil, and Overland Park surgeon Jeff Colyer. However, none has
formally entered the race.
</P>
<P>
   Of the three, Kline, a conservative, is said to be the most
certain to run. The 39-year-old has earned kudos for his
tax-cutting work in the Legislature but was recently dumped as
chairman of the House Appropriations Committee after a dispute with
the House speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's winnable,'' Kline said of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Musil, who would have the backing of the moderate GOP
establishment, said this week that he, too, was leaning toward the
race, although some Republicans have counseled him to stay out.
They would prefer to see Musil run for mayor of Overland Park in
2001, a contest he might be favored to win.
</P>
<P>
   Colyer, a 39-year-old reconstructive surgeon who plies his trade
in some of the world's trouble spots, said he was ``exploring'' the
race. He is regarded as a conservative.
</P>
<P>
   All three acknowledge that knocking off Moore would be tough. At
least one independent observer, University of Kansas political
scientist Allan Cigler, is skeptical about their chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm not seeing the kind of high-profile person where
there's a pretty good consensus that this is the candidate,''
Cigler said.
</P>
<P>
   Others are surprised that so few candidates have stepped
forward. Among those who have considered the race, then backed out,
are GOP national committeeman Dwight Sutherland and former Johnson
County Commissioner David Wysong. State Sen. Nick Jordan of Shawnee
said he was interested but was inclined to run for a state Senate
leadership post.
</P>
<P>
   Snowbarger, the man Moore beat in the hard-fought 1998 race, is
another potential contender. He isn't hinting what he will do,
saying only that he will announce his plans in a few weeks. Other
Republicans, though, said they did not expect him to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still trying to figure out if it's a race I can win,''
said Snowbarger.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Walter of the Cook Political Report said formidable
Republican challengers had already emerged elsewhere in the country
in suburban districts where Democrats narrowly defeated GOP
incumbents in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Of Kansas' 3rd District, she said: ``I would have thought there
would be a long line of candidates saying this guy (Moore) is in
the wrong district. I don't know where they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Walter said, a candidate could wait until December or
January before jumping in and still make a strong bid.
</P>
<P>
   Moore isn't making himself an easy target. Many Republicans
concede that he hasn't made a huge misstep so far. And they credit
him for remaining highly visible around the district.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's everywhere,'' Wysong said.
</P>
<P>
   Another concern for Republicans remains the intraparty feud
between conservatives and moderates. Some conservatives remain
angry that moderates abandoned Snowbarger for Moore in 1998. They
may be disinclined to back a moderate this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party split is worse than ever,'' Sutherland said.
</P>
<P>
   Moore said his energetic fund-raising showed thathe had learned
from history. Snowbarger's sorry campaign balances at the same
point two years ago placed a huge bull's-eye on Snowbarger's back
and practically invited a strong Democratic challenge. Moore has
often said that if Snowbarger had had $200,000 on hand, the
Democrat would have stayed out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't intend to make the same mistakes that Mr. Snowbarger
made,'' Moore said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
