<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELDERLY-LAW-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS LAW FIRM LOOKS OUT FOR ELDERLY AND DISABLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ William G. Hammond got a firsthand look at
the problems of the elderly about five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That's when his mother-in-law broke her hip; suffered a series
of strokes; and moved in with Hammond, his wife and five children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would try to get answers to questions about things like
benefits, insurance, Medicaid,'' he said. ``We would get little
snippets of the answers, but no one seemed to be able to put it all
together. I thought there was a crying need for someone to do it
right.''
</P>
<P>
   The experience prodded Hammond, a lawyer, to found The Elder &AMP;
Disability Law Firm in 1997. The two-lawyer, Overland Park-based
firm focuses on issues such as wills, trusts, probate,
guardianship, estate planning and how to find a nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   The firm has honed in on a growing need _ people 85 and older
make up the fastest-growing segment of the U.S. population.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, elder law is one of the fastest-growing segments
of the legal profession, said Frank Johns, president of the
National Academy of Elder Law Attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   ``The special needs of these people are significant and highly
complex,'' said Johns, who is based in Greensboro, N.C. ``If you're
going to do a proper service to the people you counsel, you must
have a substantive grasp of 14 areas of law,'' including rules
related to Medicare and other government benefits.
</P>
<P>
   It also takes a grasp of how to deal with people. Hammond said
many of his elderly clients were confused by the intricacies of
Medicare and Medicaid. Their grown children also may feel
frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   Hammond said his firm employed a holistic approach toward
clients and their families. For example, he said his elderly
clients might be under tremendous stress. To put them at ease, he
will spend 30 or 40 minutes discussing family and related topics
before getting down to brass-tacks legal issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``How to find a nursing home is a huge issue,'' he said. ``How
to get good care in a nursing home is another issue _ and how to
pay for it without going broke.''
</P>
<P>
   Another example of Hammond's approach is having a registered
nurse, Mary Helen Gautreaux, on staff. Gautreaux's duties include
participating in care-planning sessions at nursing homes and then
assessing how the nursing home resident is progressing under that
plan.
</P>
<P>
   If a nursing home attempts to discharge a client who still needs
to be there, Hammond and Gautreaux will go together to face the
nursing home officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can be snowed on legal issues and he can be snowed on
clinical issues, but between the two of us they can't snow us,''
Gautreaux said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Gautreaux said, elderly clients are apt to listen
to her advice because she's a registered nurse.
</P>
<P>
   The staff also includes Peggy Tener, a former social worker and
nursing home administrator who maintains her licenses in both
fields.
</P>
<P>
   Gautreaux and Tener serve on an in-house ethics committee of the
Tutera Group, a Kansas City, Mo.-based operator of nursing homes,
assisted-living centers and other retirement facilities around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both very knowledgeable about resident rights and add
a lot to the discussions about ethical dilemmas we face in the
industry,'' said Randy Bloom, Tutera's director of facility
operations.
</P>
<P>
   The law firm works with the Kansas City-based Midwest Bioethics
Center on projects involving long-term care and issues involving
the death of an elderly family member. Don Reynolds, director of
special projects for the center, said he admired the firm's
approach to doing business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like the idea of having the clinical issues and legal
issues and financial issues on the table at the same time,''
Reynolds said. ``We think that's the way you get to decisions that
are informed by ethics.''
</P>
<P>
   Hammond, 44, earned his law degree from Notre Dame University in
1980. He moved to Olathe the same year and worked in financial
planning before founding his firm.
</P>
<P>
   Practicing with Hammond is lawyer Karen H. Weber. Lawyer Robert
W. Loyd is scheduled to join the firm in August.
</P>
<P>
   One of the firm's clients is Dorothy Bernhardt, a 77-year-old
Overland Park resident who contacted the firm last year. Her
husband, Robert Bernhardt, was suffering from Alzheimer's disease
and could no longer live at home. To further complicate matters,
Robert Bernhardt had never made out a will.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like my back was against the wall,'' Dorothy Bernhardt
said. ``I needed an attorney to get some protection so I could go
on living.''
</P>
<P>
   Hammond's firm set up a will for Robert Bernhardt and helped
find a nursing home where he now lives. It also provided help in
other areas, such as possible future nursing home care for Dorothy
Bernhardt and future provisions for a disabled son.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're caring and understanding, the way they do it,'' she
said. ``I know that if I have any problems, I can go to them and
I'm sure they'll help me through it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the way firms in the elder law field are supposed to act,
said Johns, with the National Academy of Elder Law Attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Infrequently do lawyers look at the quality of life and the
needs of the person,'' Johns said. ``They look at documents and
money. We believe that a holistic view of a client demands that we
look at the quality of life of the client and the quality of
services being delivered to that client.''
</P>
<P>
   And while he may deal with an elderly person's children, Hammond
said his goal was to determine what's best for the parent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elderly people need someone who is committed to dealing with
them during times of great stress, giving them straight answers and
doing it with a gentle spirit,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
