<SLUG> BC-VANGUARD-EXPANSION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VANGUARD AIRLINES CONSIDERS EXPANSION AT CHICAGO OR KANSAS CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Vanguard Airlines is considering Kansas City
and Chicago as expansion sites as the low-cost carrier adds
airplanes over the next 18 months, a Vanguard executive said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The carrier has also held discussions with two other cities
where the airline may establish another ``minihub'' comparable to
what it already has in Kansas City and Chicago, said Russell
Winter, Vanguard's vice president of marketing and planning. He
declined to identify those cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at a point where we're exploring where the next phase of
growth will be,'' Winter said.
</P>
<P>
   Winter commented Tuesday after a report Monday in Crain's
Chicago Business said Vanguard was talking to aviation officials in
Chicago about expanding its presence at Midway Airport. The article
also suggested that Vanguard might move its corporate headquarters
to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Russell called the Crain article ``premature,'' but he
acknowledged that Vanguard was talking to several cities as it
prepared to add to its fleet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been talking to authorities in Chicago, evaluating the
options there,'' he said. ``But I would say the discussions in
Kansas City are along the same lines as what's happening in
Chicago. Obviously, this is all at an early stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Winter said Vanguard, currently based in Mission, would at least
for the near term maintain its headquarters in the Kansas City
area.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard leases one floor that houses about 40 administrative
employees at its Mission office building, at 7000 Squibb Road. That
lease will expire at the end of August, but the company is holding
talks with the Kansas City Aviation Department about moving to an
office at Kansas City International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard recently renewed its lease for other space in the
Mission building and plans to keep its 120 customer reservations
employees there, Winter said.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard has 23 flights daily at KCI and 19 at Midway. The
discount carrier in recent months has expanded in Chicago, adding
flights to Buffalo, N.Y., and Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Winter said expanding at Midway or KCI presented problems that
Vanguard was trying to address with officials in the two cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more underserved markets we can serve out of
Chicago, but we don't have access to gates there,'' Winter said.
``In Kansas City, we have access to gates, but we have competitive
pressures when it comes to entering new markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Another consideration for Vanguard is hangar space, Winter said.
As Vanguard gets bigger and expands its maintenance operations, the
carrier wants to acquire its own hangar. Part of Vanguard's
discussion with Chicago's aviation officials is about hangar space
at Midway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicago has a hangar,'' Winter said. ``In Kansas City, we
occasionally have gotten access to TWA's facility. However, the
issue there is union labor. We use non-union labor, which is not
allowed at TWA's overhaul base.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Aviation Commissioner Mary Rose Loney could not be
reached for comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City aviation and economic development officials said
they were surprised by reports of Vanguard's interest in expanding
at Midway.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the first we heard of it,'' said Phil Brown, Kansas
City's acting aviation director. ``We're working with them right
now on finding space to move their corporate headquarters to the
airport.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the Aviation Department was trying to establish
office space for Vanguard at KCI's Trans World Technical Academy,
which Vanguard occupies with TWA.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sage, acting president of the Economic Development Corp. of
Kansas City, said his agency was working with Vanguard to relocate
some of its Mission employees to Kansas City. However, Sage said he
was unaware of a potential move of Vanguard's headquarters to
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be flabbergasted if that happened,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard reported its first operating profit in its four-year
history last year. The airline, which has 11 Boeing 737-200s in its
fleet, expects to add bigger planes later this year. Vanguard is
counting on having 13 planes by year-end and 18 aircraft by the end
of 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
