<SLUG> BC-INTERSTATE-BAKERIES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERSTATE BAKERIES IS BUYING CANADIAN BAKING COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Interstate Bakeries Corp. is buying Montreal-based Culinar Inc.,
a Canadian baking company that should add more than $200 million to
Interstate's annual sales of $3.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Culinar makes 100 products, including snack cakes, tarts,
cookies and crackers, which are sold at more than 12,000 locations,
mostly in central and eastern Canada. An estimated one in seven
Canadians buys a Culinar product each day.
</P>
<P>
   Culinar operates five bakeries, including three in the Montreal
area. Unlike Interstate, Culinar does not make bread products.
Interstate Treasurer Paul Yarick said it was not yet known whether
the acquisition would affect any of Culinar's 2,300 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Interstate is the largest wholesale baking company in the United
States. Its brands include well-known names such as Wonder bread
and Twinkie snack cakes. Interstate operates 69 bakeries in the
United States and has 35,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Interstate Chairman Charles Sullivan said that Culinar's
corporate offices would remain in Montreal and that its president,
Gaetan Lussier, would remain at the helm. Terms of the deal were
not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said he saw many cross-selling opportunities for the
companies, including selling Interstate products in Canada and
distributing Culinar products in the United States. Culinar already
distributes Hostess products in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Culinar products are unique,'' Sullivan said. ``They are
different from what we offer elsewhere and, over time, we expect
them to complement our premium snack-cake brands.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, one Culinar product is a chocolate snack cake with
a peanut butter-flavored filling. Interstate has no such product.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first transaction between the companies.
Interstate bought Drake's, a New Jersey baker, from Culinar last
year. Drake's makes such brands as Devil Dogs and Yankee Doodles
snack cakes.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street didn't react much to the news. Interstate's stock,
traded on the New York Stock Exchange under the ticker symbol IBC,
closed Tuesday at 23 9/16, down 5/8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
