</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENERGY-SAVINGS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITY OF KANSAS PROGRAM HELPS MANUFACTURERS SAVE ON ENERGY AND
PRODUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A University of Kansas program has helped manufacturers identify
more than $25 million in energy and production savings since it was
founded in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The university's Industrial Assessment Center, part of a
national program sponsored by the U.S. Department of Energy, has
helped companies in parts of Kansas, Missouri and Nebraska find the
savings.
</P>
<P>
   The center develops recommendations for small to medium-size
manufacturing plants. It has performed more than 520 audits since
it began in Lawrence nearly 18 years ago, resulting in actual
annual cost savings averaging $20,000 a plant, said Jerry D.
Swearingen, director of the Industrial Assessment Center at KU.
</P>
<P>
   The assessments are provided at no charge to the companies, and
any proprietary information is protected. Also, a company has no
obligations to act on the recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   The Industrial Assessment Center serves manufacturing plants
within 150 miles of the Lawrence campus. The plants must have gross
annual sales of less than $75 million, fewer than 500 employees at
the plant site, annual utility bills of more than $75,000 but less
than $1.75 million, and no in-house professional staff to perform
the assessment.
</P>
<P>
   The center's assessment team visits a plant for a day and issues
a report within 60 days detailing its findings and recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   According to Swearingen, the national assessment program began
in 1976 and KU's program was one of the early teams. There are now
30 participating universities across the country.
</P>
<P>
   KU's assessment team works with companies in the eastern half of
Kansas (including Salina; Manhattan; Kansas City, Kan.; Emporia;
Pittsburg; and Topeka), extreme western Missouri (including Kansas
City, St. Joseph, and Barton and Dade counties north of Joplin),
and the southeast tip of Nebraska (including Lincoln).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
