r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCCER-FEVER-LADN     07-07 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCCER-FEVER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TICKETS SELL OUT AS U.S. WOMEN PREPARE FOR SOCCER FINAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: Staff Writer Karen Crouse contributed to this story.) 
BY PHILLIP W. BROWNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Soccer fever is sweeping Los Angeles as the World
Cup finals between the United States and China at the Rose Bowl on
Saturday promised to break attendance records for a women's
sporting event.
</P>
<P>
   The 85,000 seats set aside for Saturday's game went quickly.
World Cup organizers offered an additional 3,000 _ which sold out
in three hours. That hasn't stopped scalpers from hawking ducats
for as much as $1,000 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Even President Clinton plans to be at the game, deciding Tuesday
to extend his seven-state trip through the weekend so he can attend
the championship, at the invitation of the U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, like all Americans, he's been caught up in their
success and wants to be there personally to cheer them on,'' said
White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Seizing on soccermania, Secretary of Health and Human Services
Donna Shalala joined World Cup and youth soccer officials to
encourage girls in Los Angeles to participate in sports and avoid
``at-risk behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   During a break in their practice and workout in Pomona, U.S.
players said they are only now beginning to realize the extent of
their celebrity _ and are elated to be thought of as role models.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so flattering. It makes you want to be a better person
because you see these people are looking up to you,'' said team
member Tisha Venturini.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the best compliments we can receive. I didn't have
any role models when I was growing up,'' team member Shannon
MacMillan chimed in. ``My older brother was my role model. It's all
been unknown for us, so it's great to think for the young girls
growing up there's something tangible for them to hold on to.''
</P>
<P>
   That was no more evident than among hundreds of young fans
gathered at the Pomona workout in search of a glimpse of their
favorite star and perhaps even an autograph.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a Beatles environment out there. Girls have been
screaming like crazy at the games with all the other fans,'' said
Steve Vanderpool, vice president of communications for the 1999
Women's World Cup. ``I think it's a sport that's been brewing for
years, and the fever is finally spreading.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, a day after the U.S. team secured its berth in the
championship match, the 85,000 Rose Bowl seats sold out, but
organizers put 3,000 more on sale. The seats, which are not in
prime locations, were opened up because of customer demand and went
on sale for $45 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is more than a championship game now. People want to be
there to wave a flag, paint their face and be a part of history,''
said Richard Finn, a spokesman for the Women's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always knew that the Rose Bowl had a larger capacity than
what we sold and, even though these seats aren't great, the
customers demanded it.''
</P>
<P>
   Women's World Cup organizers were expecting a record-breaking
85,000 to 90,000 fans to attend the Saturday event. The current
record is 78,972 _ for a World Cup doubleheader at Giants Stadium
in East Rutherford, N.J., on June 19, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Those without tickets can always pay a premium price from ticket
agencies and people looking for a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Gomez is offering his four for $1,000 apiece in a newspaper
classified advertisement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had more than 10 calls for these tickets. The phone has
been going crazy,'' said Gomez, 43, of suburban North Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soccer fever is really out there, but I lost interest in the
finals when Brazil lost,'' said Gomez, a Los Angeles Department of
Water and Power employee. ``I paid $250 each for them, so if worst
comes to worst I will go and take my family.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet was buzzing with World Cup ticket sales on eBay,
Yahoo and Netscape Netcenter, where pairs of tickets ranged between
$165 and $500.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles ticket agencies were cashing in as well, with single
tickets ranging between $150 and $700 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tickets had been on sale since June 1998, but when the U.S.
won on Sunday, the remainder of the final match tickets sold very
quickly,'' said Women's World Cup spokeswoman Gina Davis.
</P>
<P>
   To date, more than 568,000 fans have attended the 30 Women's
World Cup matches across the country, with millions more watching
on television around the globe. The U.S. women _ the 1991 Women's
World Cup champions and 1996 Olympic Games gold medalists _ beat
out Brazil in a 2-0 victory on Independence Day.
</P>
<P>
   They face China, winner of two of the past three games against
the United States and silver medalists in the 1996 Atlanta
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest day is still yet to come,'' said Marla Messing,
president and CEO of the World Cup organizing committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Saturday, the Rose Bowl will be awash with pageantry,
music and thousands of World Cup fans. It will be an occasion to
remember for women's sports.''
</P>
<P>
   The game will be televised nationally on ABC with coverage
beginning at 12:30 p.m. PST. Closing ceremonies will be held
between the third-place match and the final match, featuring a
performance by singer-actress Jennifer Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   Before the final match, Norway will play Brazil in the
third-place game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
