A1366 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREST-DONATION-SPI &LR;      07-07 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREST-DONATION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAST-MINUTE DONATIONS HELP FOREST PRESERVATION FUND REACH GOAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Thanks to major last-minute gifts from technology
millionaires and 5,000 smaller donations from around Washington
state, preservationists have raised enough money to spare from
logging a major wilderness area along the U.S.-Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   With $1.5 million added to the cause Tuesday, the campaign to
buy logging rights to 25,000 acres of the state-owned Loomis Forest
has raised $13.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have done shows that people in this state care deeply
enough about their forests to give until it hurts,'' said Mitch
Friedman, executive director of the Northwest Ecosystem Alliance, a
Bellingham-based conservation group that spearheaded efforts to
save the forest.
</P>
<P>
   Although it appears to have saved the Loomis Forest from
logging, the campaign hasn't made it entirely out of the woods yet.
</P>
<P>
   The state must complete one final appraisal of the forest before
the state Board of Natural Resources can approve the sale of
logging rights to the remote land.
</P>
<P>
   A previous appraisal pegged the value of timber in the two
segments of land marked for preservation at $13 million to $17
million.
</P>
<P>
   The resources board agreed Tuesday to spend six months
completing the revised appraisal, and to give conservationists
another year _ until July 1 _ to raise more money if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The Loomis Forest Fund was more than $3 million short of its
goal just a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   It was rescued by a series of last-minute gifts from present and
former executives at Microsoft, RealNetworks and Amazon.com, and
from former King Broadcasting Co. Chairwoman Patricia Bullitt
Collins.
</P>
<P>
   The Loomis Forest is a lofty, out-of-the-way corner of Okanogan
County, just east of the Pasayten Wilderness Area in Washington
state. It adjoins the equally wild Snowy Mountain-Snowy Crater
region of the Similkameen Valley in British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Inhabited by wildlife rarely seen in Washington, it is a
particularly choice domain for such small predators as the Canadian
lynx, the pine marten and fisher. Wolverine tracks were recently
spotted between two high lakes.
</P>
<P>
   The area has a winter moose population, and there have been
occasional grizzly-bear sightings nearby in the Pasayten.
</P>
<P>
   In saving part of the Loomis Forest, conservationists will have
preserved a 75-mile-wide stretch of wild land along the U.S. side
of the border.
</P>
<P>
   The protected areas would begin in rain forests and ridges of
the Mount Baker Wilderness Area east of Bellingham, and stretch to
where slopes of Chopaka Mountain drop 6,700 vertical feet into dry
steppes of the Similkameen Valley in Okanogan County.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign has run into opposition, mainly from cattle and
timber interests in northeast Washington, and school boards in
Okanogan County.
</P>
<P>
   Although timber in the area is mainly small-dimension lodgepole
pine, critics have charged that the Department of Natural Resources
has underestimated its value.
</P>
<P>
   ``This borders on fraud of the people,'' state Sen. Bob Morton,
R-Orient, a critic of selling timber rights to preservationists,
told the Board of Natural Resources Tuesday. Morton claimed to have
information suggesting that the Department of Natural Resources and
state Land Commissioner Jennifer Belcher were withholding the
forest's true value if it is cut down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not withheld information from the board,'' said
Belcher, who has appeared in a video prepared by preservation
advocates.
</P>
<P>
   The 134,000-acre Loomis Forest has already been heavily cut.
Active logging extends as high as 6,000 feet on the south slopes of
Chopaka Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Only a tiny portion of the state forest currently enjoys
protection. The state has created a 2,800-acre natural area around
summit meadows of 7,882-foot Chopaka Mountain and nearby Hurley
Peak.
</P>
<P>
   The wild 25,000 acres marked for preservation come in two
parcels. The larger, the North Fork Conservation Area, adjoins the
Pasayten Wilderness to the east. It is a land of high lodgepole
pine forests, tundralike alpine meadows and rounded summits
reaching to more than 8,000 feet in elevation.
</P>
<P>
   A little more than half the money raised by conservationists
would go, in lieu of timber sales, to the Common School
Construction Trust Fund, which pays to build public schools across
the state.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining money would be used by the state to acquire
alternative timberlands for logging.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's $1.5 million gift that allowed the Loomis Forest Fund
to reach $13.1 million was from an anonymous donor. Fund organizers
still don't know the identity of a $2 million anonymous donor
earlier in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign for the forest has revealed powerful conservation
sentiments by leading figures in the state's technology industries.
Bruce Jacobsen, a former Microsoft and RealNetworks executive, gave
stock valued at about $612,000. The William H. Gates Foundation
gave $250,000. Other gifts have included $400,000 from Jabe
Blumenthal, $160,000 from Floyd and Judy Rogers, and $180,000 from
Bill and Cheryl Pope. Blumenthal, Floyd Rogers and Bill Pope are
former Microsoft executives.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Gardner, the state's former first lady, held one of many
fund-raising parties around the state that collected donations as
small as $10.
</P>
<P>
   If conservationists still need money after the new appraisal,
said Friedman, they will ask the Legislature to provide it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 0115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
