</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HEAT-3RDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT SETS RECORDS, CLAIMS LIVES AND STRAINS UTILITIES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to insert new 6th and 7th grafs re blackout in upper
Manhattan and Giuliani's tour of the area. Updates ambulance calls
to 170 in 8th graf.)   (See also HEAT-EAST-COAST, HEAT-ELECTRICITY) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As much of the eastern United States sagged Tuesday
under a second day of record high temperatures, officials
attributed at least eight deaths to the heat, and the New York
region struggled with maddening power failures that trapped people
in stifling elevators, cut air-conditioning to thousands of homes
and commercial buildings, and knocked out some subway service.
</P>
<P>
   In some of the New York City's poorest neighborhoods, many
residents huddled in darkness when, just after 10 p.m., power
suddenly failed in the entire area north of 155th Street in
Manhattan, a densely populated area of about three square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Petta, a spokesman for Con Edison, said the power failure
occurred after six of 14 high-voltage cables that supply the area
failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You now have the same amount of electricity traveling across
far fewer lines,'' he said. ``Those lines are designed to carry a
certain amount of electricity, and when they begin to carry far
more, that is what is an overload. What happens is, in effect, like
giant fuses blowing, and then the whole network lost power. It is
very rapid.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday night, Con Edison officials still did not know how
long it would take to restore power to the area. ``I don't recall
in recent memory anything like this happening,'' Petta said.
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department sent hundreds of extra officers into the
blackout area, but early Wednesday morning there were no reports of
looting or disturbances. Fire officials, however, reported several
minor fires in the area. Subway lines through the neighborhood were
also out of service late Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani toured the blackout area Tuesday night.
He praised residents for remaining calm, and criticized Con Edison
for the power failure. ``I find it incredible, after years and
years of blackouts, that enough power can't be supplied to the
city,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ambulance crews in New York City responded Tuesday to more than
170 calls from people complaining of cramps and exhaustion from the
heat, and emergency officials said the heat may have contributed to
a number of heart attacks and at least three deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service reported that the temperature in
Central Park reached 101 degrees at 3:11 p.m. Tuesday, breaking the
record of 98 degrees for the date set in 1986. Temperatures were
expected to moderate this week with a cool front moving through the
region Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Summer school was canceled in Washington on Tuesday, the lights
were dimmed in much of the Massachusetts Statehouse and block
captains checked on the elderly in Philadelphia's row houses.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Giuliani said, ``This is one of the more difficult
days the city has ever had in regard to heat.'' He canceled a
political fund-raising trip to Nantucket in Massachusetts to deal
with the heat emergency.
</P>
<P>
   In the city's first confirmed heat-related death, an autopsy
Tuesday revealed that Julia Johnson, 79, of Manhattan had died of
hyperthermia on Monday, said Ellen Borakove, spokeswoman for the
office of chief medical examiner. Mrs. Johnson was found
unconscious at home by a health care worker.
</P>
<P>
   Her body temperature was 108.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said two other people may have died from the heat. They
were described as a 40-year-old man whose Brooklyn home had a
temperature in excess of 108, and a 27-year-old man who died at
Interfaith Medical Center in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Their names were not released, but neighbors identified the
40-year-old as Samuel Mitchell, a handyman from the Park Slope
section of Brooklyn, who died early Tuesday morning at Brookdale
Hospital Medical Center. Neighbors were told that dehydration was
the cause of death. Herma Passely, 59, who shared a house with
Mitchell, said he never woke up after a back yard Fourth of July
party. ``He said he was tired, went to sleep early and that was
it,'' Mrs. Passely said.
</P>
<P>
   City officials said that while they expected the death toll to
climb, they were confident it would come nowhere near the hundreds
of deaths that Chicago experienced during a brutal heat wave in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``That number might grow a bit, but certainly it will not
approach what happened in the Midwest,'' said Jerome Hauer, the
director of the Mayor's Office of Emergency Management.
</P>
<P>
   The heat wave, combined with record demands for electricity, put
enormous pressure on the power system in the New York region and
elsewhere. Transformers overheated and burst into flames. Power
lines melted through from the heat and high use. In the dense
humidity, bolts of electricity arced across power lines, causing
short circuits.
</P>
<P>
   Utility companies first issued urgent appeals for customers to
conserve energy. Later, to ease the strain on power lines and
transformers and because of insufficient power reserves, the
companies reduced their voltage output by 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, power failures were reported throughout New York City,
Long Island, Westchester County, New Jersey and Connecticut. At
least 150,000 people were affected, officials estimated.
</P>
<P>
   Eugene McGrath, chairman of Con Edison, attributed the power
failures to equipment breakdowns, not the power cutback. ``Those
problems come about from the cables overheating,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani scolded Con Edison officials for not giving city
officials more explicit warnings about the extent of the power
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Con Ed is its own entity unto itself, and sometimes they
notify us late and sometimes they notify us only when the problem
has already started,'' the mayor said. ``I think it's a cause of
great frustration, for me and my administration and every other
mayor that's ever had this job. They call you about 10 minutes
before there is a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   New York City activated its emergency operations center Tuesday,
and Giuliani appealed for residents to avoid strenuous activity and
stay indoors near fans and air-conditioners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember hotter days than the last several and
particularly hotter nights,'' he said at a news conference at City
Hall. ``We would like everyone to be very, very careful.''
</P>
<P>
   On average, city ambulances respond to 3,000 calls a day, but
fire officials said they expected to handle more than 4,000 calls
Tuesday. ``It could be the busiest day in the department's
history,'' one fire official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a great stress on our emergency system,'' Giuliani
said.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent cars from overheating in traffic, city officials shut
down some highway construction. To keep people from overheating,
sprinkler caps were placed on open fire hydrants, extra ambulances
were pressed into service, and cooling centers were opened in
dozens of senior citizen centers and community centers operated by
the New York City Housing Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, officials opened 15 schools across the city where
anyone could sleep in the comfort of air-conditioning, Hauer said.
Cots, food and blankets were supplied by the American Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   He and other city officials credited a heat plan devised in the
aftermath of the Chicago heat wave with averting a similar disaster
in New York City. Still, there were major concerns Tuesday night,
including worries about the low water pressure in some parts of the
city. The low pressure threatened to hamper firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   On a normal day, New York City consumes 1.2 billion gallons of
water. Tuesday, the city consumed about 1.8 billion gallons, much
of that additional use spilling from open fire hydrants, Hauer
said.
</P>
<P>
   The high water consumption left some areas, especially in
Brooklyn, vulnerable to fire. ``There are some areas we are still
concerned about,'' Hauer said, adding that fire officials were
combating the problem by installing more sprinkler heads on
hydrants.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   According to meteorologists, a heat wave of this size and
intensity requires three main ingredients, and all three were
present this week. The first two are clear skies and a large mass
of hot air. But the third ingredient is the most important: a wind
from the west, a wind that comes off the Catskills and the
Appalachian Mountains, compressing and heating as it descends, then
overwhelming the cooling on-shore breeze from the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the type of pattern that generates extreme heat across
the Northeast seaboard,'' said Todd Miner, a meteorologist for
Pennsylvania State University.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Tuesday was another day of unwelcome records, both
for weather observations and for power use. Though Tuesday's high
fell short of New York City's record of 106 in 1936, back-to-back
days of temperatures above 100 degrees are rare. The last time it
happened was in July 1993. On July 9 it was 101; the next day, it
was 102.
</P>
<P>
   Despite pleas to conserve energy, both Con Edison and the Long
Island Power Authority reported record demand for electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Across the city, building managers embarked on ``load shedding''
_ shutting down two elevators in a bank of eight, or turning off
unneeded pumps and exhaust fans. On Long Island, officials
persuaded the Long Island Rail Road to slow the acceleration of its
electric trains, also to save power. But those actions were not
enough.
</P>
<P>
   In Westchester County, 10,000 customers were without power late
Tuesday afternoon. Among the hardest hit were the towns of
Harrison, Rye, Port Chester and New Rochelle. The Westchester
Medical Center in Valhalla was forced to use backup power
generators.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, a spokesman for Public Service Electric and Gas
Co. said about 9,000 commercial and residential customers had no
power Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   In the most serious incident, the spokesman said, the Englewood
Hospital was reported to be without power for a period because a
backup power generator failed. Fire officials there knew of no
deaths resulting from the power failure.
</P>
<P>
   And in Connecticut, most of the city of New London and parts of
several nearby communities _ about 20,000 residents _ were without
electricity Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only once in every five years would we see an equipment
failure that would be this significant,'' said Deborah Beauchamp, a
spokeswoman for Connecticut Light and Power.
</P>
<P>
   In the Washington Heights section of Manhattan, about 15,000
homes were without power.
</P>
<P>
   At dusk, at several intersections in Washington Heights, teams
of officers were deployed with riot gear, night sticks and helmets.
</P>
<P>
   Here and there, tempers were fraying as the heat combined with
the effects of prolonged local blackouts. On Hillside Avenue, a
quiet residential street beneath one of the steep rock ridges
splitting the area, manholes popped at 11 p.m. Monday as short
circuits blew out power to several buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Two young women sat on a stoop, staring at a new Goldstar
air-conditioner still in its box. Lourdes Espinal, a 28-year-old
purchasing manager in Manhattan, laughed as she recalled how she
spent her lunch hour Tuesday hunting all over for an
air-conditioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't use it,'' she said ruefully. No electricity.
</P>
<P>
   The power failure forced sections of the subway to be closed.
Late Tuesday morning, the 1/9 train was closed from 168th Street to
242nd Street, and the A train was closed from 168th Street to 207th
Street.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
