<HEADLINE>
CROMER RETURNS FOR HEART TESTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Dodgers utility infielder Tripp Cromer returned to Los
Angeles for further examination Tuesday after he was diagnosed with
an irregular heartbeat. He was placed on the 15-day disabled
(retroactive to Monday) and shortstop Mark Grudzielanek was
activated.
</P>
<P>
   Cromer, 31, will undergo tests and be evaluated by team
physician Dr. Michael Mellman today at 4 p.m. at Centinela Hospital
Medical Center to determine the cause of the irregular heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a precautionary thing,'' Cromer said. ``I don't
think I'm in any immediate danger.''
</P>
<P>
   Cromer said he noticed something was wrong two weeks ago during
the Dodgers' series in San Francisco June 25-27.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something that's been every day for two weeks. It
hasn't happened for a few days,'' Cromer said. ``It's really hard
for me to describe. It's just a type of irregular heartbeat. Just a
fluttering thing. I lose my breath for a second or two.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago Cromer wore a monitor on his chest for 24 hours
in hopes the doctors would be able to detect the problem. But
Cromer said the condition did not show itself.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers trainer Charlie Strasser said Cromer didn't do any
treadmill activity to see how the heart responded. Strasser said
tests done on Cromer on three occasions were inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said the decision to send Cromer
back to L.A. was made after the two spoke before Monday's game
against Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``My anxiety is if I play him, something may happen bad at the
plate,'' Johnson said. ``I'm hoping there's nothing bad. He said he
feels better, but he doesn't feel 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Used primarily as a defensive replacement and in
double-switches, Cromer is batting .208 with two homers and eight
RBI in 29 games. He is eligible to come off the disabled list July
20. The All-Star break begins Monday, and Cromer said that was one
of the reasons he elected to go on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's anything major,'' Cromer said. ``But I
needed to get it checked. I can play baseball for four or five more
years. I have a family. I want to be around for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Grud nearly grounded: On-field fiascos are one thing, but now
poor fortune is affecting the Dodgers away from the ballpark.
Grudzielanek was in the starting lineup Tuesday against Colorado
but only after missing two flights at LAX because the United
Airlines computer randomly chose him for a bag search. Grudzielanek
was originally scheduled to board a flight at 10:40 a.m. He missed
that one and the next one before taking off at 12:10 p.m. He
arrived at Coors Field three hours before the first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty chapped,'' Grudzielanek said.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Grudzielanek, who hit .284 before the injury, was
anxious to get here. He's been on the disabled list since breaking
his hand when he punched a wall in frustration during a June 2 loss
at Pittsburgh. Johnson said last week when Grudzielanek returned,
he would reclaim his starting shortstop position from Jose
Vizcaino.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was driving me nuts to do nothing,'' said Grudzielanek, who
singled in a run in his first at-bat after missing 28 games.
</P>
<P>
   __ FYI.: For the third time this season Todd Hollandsworth
started at first in place of Eric Karros. . . . Dodgers
right-hander Antonio Osuna (elbow surgery) will pitch one inning in
a rehab start for Class-A San Bernardino tonight. . . . Colorado
right fielder Larry Walker, who leads the NL in batting at .377,
was out of the lineup with the flu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
