<HEADLINE>
FOCUS IS ON CHINA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLAREMONT, Calif. _ All along, Brandi Chastain wanted China.
</P>
<P>
   Not because China would be an easier opponent than Norway, but
because China brings out the best in the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say it; I prefer to play the Chinese,'' said Chastain
after Tuesday's workout at Pomona-Pitzer College. ``I enjoy the
type of soccer they play. I think it's the most challenging for us,
in terms of team organization, both attacking and defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Both China and the U.S. finished their first training sessions
since arriving in Los Angeles after their Women's World Cup
semifinal victories last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   They will meet Saturday at the Rose Bowl for the championship.
</P>
<P>
   Since China blistered Norway, 5-0, some are wondering if the
Chinese have become the tournament favorites. The U.S. defeated
Brazil, 2-0, in the other semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't thought about that,'' Chastain said. ``We've been
concentrating on what we need to do to win the game, and not so
much who's predicting us to win or who's saying whether we will win
or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus right now is China. Everyone's so excited to play
them because they're so good. And I'm glad China's doing well
because it's getting people excited about what kind of game this
can be, or has the potential to be. For me, as a soccer player and
fan, that's the most exciting thing to be a part of.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. coach Tony DiCicco wasn't surprised at China's victory over
Norway. He was, however, surprised with the result.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw a very good China team dismantle the world champions,''
DiCicco said. ``I expected them to win. I always thought they were
a better team than Norway, but I didn't expect it to be 5-0.''
</P>
<P>
   At the 1996 Olympics, the U.S. beat China in the final to
capture the gold medal. But many feel that China is the most
improved team since that tournament. They have beaten the U.S.
twice in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain explained what the U.S. needs to do, particularly
against China's speedy front line that exposed Norway:
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be organized defensively so we can win the ball.
And our transition from defending to attacking is going to be the
key because they are so quick and so organized. We're going to have
to keep them off-balance.''
</P>
<P>
   China's biggest threat is Sun Wen. The prolific scorer has seven
goals in the tournament, and finished with two against Norway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to give her the same amount of respect we gave Sissi
(Brazil),'' Chastain said. ``They both have the potential to score
any time they touch the ball, so we have to be extra conscious when
she gets into the attacking third.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very sneaky, tricky and quick. And she enjoys doing the
little extra things that allows her to get open in front of the
goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Midfield general Michelle Akers has seen her share of China over
the years. She says this is the best Chinese team she's ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to be on fire and at the top of our game
on all parts of the field if we're going to win Saturday,'' Akers
said. ``I have a general understanding of how to play against
China, but in a game like this, emotion plays a big part.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
