<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move these additional stories for
use by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, July. 07. If you have any questions, please call
Patricia Hardin on the Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4753.
</P>
<P>
   SUPERINTENDENT-REJECTION (KANSAS CITY, Mo.) For the second time
in less than a week, the top choice for Kansas City school
superintendent has abruptly withdrawn from consideration. Lawyers
for the district and for Pascal Forgione Jr. negotiated throughout
the day Tuesday but were unable to reach agreement before the
school board convened in a closed meeting Tuesday evening. By
PHILLIP O'CONNOR and MATT STEARNS. Story will move in the ``a''
category.
</P>
<P>
   LAYNE-ACQUISITION (Undated) Layne Christensen Co. on Tuesday
announced the acquisition of two Louisiana-based oil and gas
service companies. Layne, based in Mission Woods, Kan., purchased
the assets of Vibration Technologies LLC and Toledo Oil &AMP; Gas
Services Inc. Terms of the deals were not disclosed. By RANDOLPH
HEASTER. Story will move in ``f'' category.
GRAPE-HAVEN (OVERLAND PARK, Kan.) For many teen-agers who think
they suffer a woeful fate by being from Johnson County, a sliver of
salvation sits in the middle of an Overland Park strip shopping
center, flanked by a Hy-Vee market and a Tanner's Bar &AMP; Grill.
While their urban peers flock to Westport area coffee houses, some
Johnson County youths have carved out a place for their suburban
version of a kaffeeklatsch _ the Grape Coffee House and Bar. By
MHARI DOYLE. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
NOEL-POPULATION (NOEL, Mo.) Elias Ozuna remembers the exact date he
and his wife, Marciela, arrived in this small town in southwest
Missouri: Jan. 26, 1995. The Ozunas had come north from the Rio
Grande valley in Texas, drawn by the promise of jobs at the local
poultry processing plant. They found the jobs. Housing wasn't so
easy. For almost six months the couple lived at Ginger Blue, a
deserted resort that housed many of the Hispanic workers who came
to Noel to work at the Hudson Foods poultry plant, now owned by
Tyson Foods. The Ozunas shared their room with two other persons.
Soon they moved into a one-bedroom apartment managed by the Noel
Housing Authority. By TRISHA L. HOWARD. Story will move in the
``a'' category.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
