<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1378 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUPERINTENDENT-REJECT     07-07 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERINTENDENT-REJECTION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE AGAIN, KANSAS CITY'S SCHOOL SUPERINTENDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR and MATT STEARNS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ For the second time in less than a week, the
top choice for Kansas City school superintendent has abruptly
withdrawn from consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the district and for Pascal Forgione Jr. negotiated
throughout the day Tuesday but were unable to reach agreement
before the school board convened in a closed meeting Tuesday
evening.
</P>
<P>
   Forgione's withdrawal prompted former Mayor Emanuel Cleaver to
call on U.S. District Judge Dean Whipple to take drastic steps to
fix the school district. But he made no specific recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaver called the district's latest efforts to recruit a
superintendent ``a national embarrassment.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before Tuesday's school board meeting, Forgione faxed a
letter to board President John Rios, saying he no longer was
interested in the position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears to me that the gap is so broad in our negotiations
that it cannot be bridged without creating so much acrimony and
animosity that will compromise my ability to work successfully as
your superintendent,'' Forgione wrote. ``In the past I have worked
constructively and productively in partnership with boards.
However, the prospects of being cast in an adversarial role so
early in my relationship with this board is not one that I relish
or am willing to contemplate.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that he was withdrawing ``rather than continue an
unproductive interaction that will lead to more irritation and
division.''
</P>
<P>
   Forgione, a former U.S. commissioner of education statistics and
state superintendent of schools in Delaware, did not return calls
to his Washington home. His Kansas City lawyer, Norris Greer, could
not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   If Forgione does not reconsider, the board again will have to
scramble to find a superintendent. The Desegregation Monitoring
Committee, the three-member court-appointed panel that oversees the
district, has set a Friday deadline for hiring a superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   Rios said the board had directed its attorneys to find out
whether another finalist for the post, Benjamin Demps Jr., still
was interested. Demps is a retired state official from Oklahoma.
The board also asked its attorneys to seek guidance from the
Desegregation Monitoring Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Committee member Charles McClain said Tuesday night, ``It's kind
of shocking to learn that another candidate has withdrawn...I'm
very disappointed...''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would talk with the two other monitoring committee
members this morning and then try to give the school board some
guidance.
</P>
<P>
   Rios said he was trying to contact Forgione by telephone to find
out why he withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   Board members Lance Loewenstein and Lee Barnes Jr. said the
board offered Forgione a base salary of $165,800, performance
incentives that could total $33,000 a year and more than $20,000 a
year in benefits.
</P>
<P>
   That would have exceeded the salary and benefits package paid to
former Superintendent Henry Williams. Rios said the board also met
Forgione's request for a three-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   Rios said he would continue to try to persuade him to take the
job.
</P>
<P>
   But Barnes said Forgione withdrew without even making a
counteroffer.
</P>
<P>
   The board initially chose retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Jay T.
Edwards to be superintendent. But he withdrew last week after
traveling to Kansas City to meet with the school board. Edwards and
board members were unable to reach agreement on a contract. In
addition, several leaders in the minority community who met with
Edwards said he was unqualified to lead an urban district.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the black community have advocated Cleaver for the post.
But Cleaver held a press conference Tuesday to say he had no
interest in the job.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaver said he would be interested in helping to revamp how the
school district is run. The Desegregation Monitoring Committee
oversees the district, in addition to the nine-member elected
school board and the superintendent. Some board members and
previous superintendents have said that structure hamstrings the
board and the superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter who gets the job. The car is broken, and the
color of the driver doesn't matter,'' Cleaver said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who takes the job under the current conditions will not
succeed,'' Cleaver said. ``He or she will be besieged by a
community that feels it's been left out of the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaver singled out the school board as the district's biggest
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't have the kind of acrimony and name-calling and
race-baiting that goes on in the school district and expect it to
function,'' Cleaver said. ``It's ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   If hired, Forgione would have had to unite a board and a
community that was divided over his selection. As late as Tuesday,
some board members still were advocating other candidates for the
job.
</P>
<P>
   In a radio interview Tuesday morning, board member Lee Barnes
Jr. expressed his support for Grandview Superintendent John Martin.
The Grandview educator was one of four finalists considered by the
board.
</P>
<P>
   Martin at one point said he no longer was interested in the job,
but recently said he would consider it if the board could not agree
on another candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Terry Riley also criticized Forgione's lack of
experience as an urban district superintendent. He said the
district needed someone with experience working with Missouri state
proficiency tests. Martin was the only one of the four finalists
with such experience.
</P>
<P>
   Several board members said Forgione received strong
recommendations from several prominent African-Americans in
Washington and in Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very pleased with what his references said,'' said board
member Patricia Kurtz. ``It only confirmed in my mind that this is
the right person for the job and he will get along with all the
people in the community and will make sure all of the children are
included in terms of upward movement in education. He will not
leave any children behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Rios said he considered Forgione someone who could quickly
recruit and organize a quality staff and lead the district out from
under court control.
</P>
<P>
   He also said Forgione was high on accountability and would ``not
put up with the bureaucracy and what's been going on in this
district.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaver said if a school district is functioning, a person of
mediocre talent can run it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But right now,'' he said, ``think of top superintendents in
the country who would apply for this job. They're not coming to
Kansas City.''  &LR; tag1:The Star's Lynn Horsley also contributed to
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
