r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAPE-HAVEN-KAN &LR;      07-07 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAPE-HAVEN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAPE COFFEE HOUSE AND BAR ACTS AS HAVEN FOR KANSAS TEENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MHARI DOYLE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ For many teen-agers who think they suffer
a woeful fate by being from Johnson County, a sliver of salvation
sits in the middle of an Overland Park strip shopping center,
flanked by a Hy-Vee and a Tanner's Bar &AMP; Grill.
</P>
<P>
   While their urban peers flock to Westport coffee houses, some
Johnson County youths have carved out a place for their suburban
version of a kaffeeklatsch _ the Grape Coffee House and Bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an oasis in a sea of absurdity,'' said Joe Sandor, 19, a
graduate of Shawnee Mission East High School. ``It's a haven for
those who feel they don't mesh with Johnson County....You really
get to meet people (here) who don't fit the norm or the standard.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson County has plenty of teen hangouts, including other
coffee houses. But Grape fans say no other place has that special
blend of hipness, youth and coffee beans.
</P>
<P>
   The Grape, provides the stage for hundreds of Johnson County
teens and young adults to act out their daily dramas _ from
political debates to gossip to discussions about where to go next.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the gray stucco walls of the coffee house, young coffee
drinkers wearing athletic shoes or tie-dyed T-shirts clash with the
Grape's antique touches, such as vintage tea sets and Victorian-era
cabinets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never thought about the location,'' said Kate Oland, 18,
a St. Thomas Aquinas High School graduate. ``I'm just so used to
walking down to Hy-Vee to get something to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandor travels to the Grape from Lawrence, where he will attend
the University of Kansas in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years we've accumulated so many people,'' Sandor
said. ``One of the regulars might know 90 percent of the people
here. It started to become a family.''
</P>
<P>
   Oland goes to the Grape because all her friends are there, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll say, `I'll see you there,' and you don't even have to
say we're going to the Grape,'' Oland said. ``There's such a wide
range of people here. We all have the Johnson County background,
but we're not the typical spoiled brats.''
</P>
<P>
   On most nights, the small coffee shop is packed with teens,
unmindful of the line of SUVs headed for the grocery. They usually
slurp down Grape specials _ frozen mocha drinks with whipped cream
_ as they talk with friends and inhale cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   The Grape sells alcohol and tobacco, including many types of
cigars, and owner and manager Kurt Nabity said he kept a vigilant
watch over who bought and consumed what. He said most underage
teens don't try to flout the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``For kids that are 18 and who can't get into bars, this is a
smoking establishment,'' Nabity said. ``I keep an eye out for
underaged smokers and drinkers. I pretty much know the kids. I know
what age they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Bishop, who works behind the counter, said that because so
many of the teens are regulars, underage smoking and drinking isn't
a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a real tight-knit group,'' he said, standing next to a
sign that forbids minors from sitting at the bar. ``We don't have a
problem with kids trying to get alcohol. We know them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis Buckley said that although he is 21, he doesn't go to the
Grape to drink.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've become acquainted with the people here,'' he said,
sitting at the bar with a tattered notebook. ``I come here to write
various prose and poetry. There's an ambiance that is conducive to
my writing.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria Wurtenberger, 18, said she and her friends talked, read or
played card games, checkers and chess.
</P>
<P>
   Sandor said that although Grape patrons were generally accepting
of one another, some social cliques had formed, such as groups
Sandor jokingly called the ``leftists,'' the Goth crowd or the
hippies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really not labeling, though,'' he said. ``Cliques do
form, and they take on certain characteristics....But there's no
discrimination among cliques. No matter who you are, you come here
to talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Roman Goykhman, 20, and Jonya Sablin, 21, have been going to the
coffee house since they were exchange students at Shawnee Mission
West High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good place to hang,'' said Sablin, who is from Ukraine.
``And we meet people before we go places.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley Robertson, 19, a graduate of Blue Valley Northwest High
School, feels secure at the Grape, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always going to be the Grape,'' Robertson said. ``There
are people here I can relate to, and this is where I've gotten
accustomed to. I won't stop coming.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
