<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOEL-POPULATION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSING AUTHORITY FINDS WAYS TO HELP NEW POPULATION IN NOEL, MO. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TRISHA L. HOWARD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NOEL, Mo. _ Elias Ozuna remembers the exact date he and his
wife, Marciela, arrived in this small town in southwest Missouri:
Jan. 26, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The Ozunas had come north from the Rio Grande valley in Texas,
drawn by the promise of jobs at the local poultry processing plant.
They found the jobs. Housing wasn't so easy.
</P>
<P>
   For almost six months the couple lived at Ginger Blue, a
deserted resort that housed many of the Hispanic workers who came
to Noel to work at the Hudson Foods poultry plant, now owned by
Tyson Foods. The Ozunas shared their room with two other persons.
</P>
<P>
   Soon they moved into a one-bedroom apartment managed by the Noel
Housing Authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the only opportunity we could find at that moment,''
Elias Ozuna said.
</P>
<P>
   That opportunity has led to others. Later this summer the Ozunas
will move into their new home, a three-bedroom ranch house they
bought from the housing authority.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase marks a first for both the Ozunas and the housing
authority. It also provides a benchmark for how far the housing
authority _ and its community _ have come in the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   The Noel Housing Authority, once on the brink of bankruptcy and
struggling to serve the community, provides housing and literacy
services for a growing Hispanic community. Its efforts have earned
it two nominations for the Department of Housing and Urban
Development's Best Practices awards, which are given to local
agencies that use their resources wisely and creatively.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Noel's population was overwhelmingly white. In the
mid-'90s, Hispanic workers flocked to the town.
</P>
<P>
   Noel's growth came at an inopportune time for the housing
authority. By 1995, it had $7,000 in savings. Only 66 of the
authority's 100 units were occupied. The Department of Housing and
Urban Development had designated the authority as ``troubled.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, even five vacancies are rare. Reserves are up to $88,000.
A literacy program has begun, and the authority's next project
focuses on moving public housing residents into homes of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Former Mayor James Carroll remembers the first year of the
city's population boom. New workers rented garages, sheds, even a
camper shell mounted on concrete blocks _ anything for shelter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seemed like people kept coming and coming and
coming,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The housing authority's offerings were little better, said Joyce
Short, the executive director who took over the agency in March
1995.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic residents often would not report problems with their
utilities. One woman spent an entire winter without hot water,
Short said. When asked, the woman said she didn't want to bother
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Ana Leland, retention coordinator for Tyson, said the housing
authority went to great lengths to make the Hispanic community feel
welcome. In addition to Leland's work for the town's multicultural
committee, she translates the housing authority's announcements
into Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no obligation for anyone in public housing to give
these services,'' said Leland, who came to the United States from
Mexico in 1995. ``If this community is advancing, it is because
Joyce has done a great effort.''
</P>
<P>
   This year the housing authority established a home-ownership
program that will start with the Ozunas. The authority bought a
three-bedroom house, appraised at $50,000, for almost half that at
a tax auction. The Ozunas turned in a bid, and the board of
directors agreed to sell the house to them for a little less than
market value.
</P>
<P>
   The authority will use the profit from that house to buy more
houses, renovate them and sell them to the authority's residents,
Short said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to get into the real estate business,'' Short
said, ``but I want to be sure that our residents can be put in
touch with the people who can get them into home ownership.
Homeownership makes a community stable.''
</P>
<P>
   Housing isn't the only topic on the authority's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the authority celebrated its family literacy
center's grand opening. The housing authority's $500,000 grant for
the center was rounded out by contributions from Crowder College in
Neosho, the HeadStart program in Joplin and the McDonald County
Library, all of which offer services at the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``This brings a level of services you might find in a larger
community to a small community like Noel that still has needs,''
said Jeff Goldammer, director of HeadStart for the Economic
Security Corp. in Joplin.
</P>
<P>
   If not for the housing authority, Goldammer said, HeadStart
could not afford to offer its program in Noel.
</P>
<P>
   The library and a computer lab are next to the classroom where
Crowder College provides courses for adults.
</P>
<P>
   Across the way, the children of those students play in a
HeadStart classroom, where the signs are written in English and
Spanish. Class breaks are timed so parents and children can spend
time together.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are young parents,'' said Carolyn Stogsdill, who teaches
the adult classes. ``If they were across town, they could be
sitting here worrying about their children instead of their
classwork.''
</P>
<P>
   Several adults who take classes here live at the housing
authority. When people apply for residence, the staff tells them
about all the other available programs _ GED, HeadStart, English as
a Second Language. The programs are open to Noel community members.
</P>
<P>
   The authority's overall goal, Short said, is to ensure not only
that its new residents have shelter but that they see a future in
Noel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
