u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-NEIGHBORHOOD-BLACK     07-07 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NEIGHBORHOOD-BLACKOUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACKOUT STOPS TRAINS AND ELECTRICITY FOR 200,000 IN UPPER
MANHATTAN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was a mix of chaos and calm on the streets of
upper Manhattan Tuesday night as an area including some of the
city's most impoverished and densely packed neighborhoods was
plunged into darkness.
</P>
<P>
   As of late Tuesday night, there was no violence reported in
Washington Heights or Inwood, the two affected neighborhoods, which
have more than 200,000 residents. The power failure severed subway
service above 125th Street, and at least one train was trapped in a
tunnel at 180th Street.
</P>
<P>
   For at least 40 minutes, New York Prebyterian Hospital's
emergency room lost its power. While nurses and doctors in the
emergency room had light only from hand-held flashlights, no lives
were lost.
</P>
<P>
   Power to the hospital's emergency generators was restored just
before midnight.
</P>
<P>
   With lampposts and traffic signals dead above 155th Street,
drivers crept through intersections and along dark streets, with
conditions made even more perilous by water spewing out of hundreds
of uncapped fire hydrants.
</P>
<P>
   What began as a day of sporadic power failures affecting 15,000
customers north of 155th Street turned into a total blackout at
10:10 p.m., when the remaining cables feeding the area were
overwhelmed by spiking demands for electricity, Con Edison
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   With their homes thrown into darkness, their fans and air
conditioners dead, thousands of residents poured into the streets
to marvel at a sky so black that the stars seemed startingly
bright.
</P>
<P>
   People gathered at major intersections to watch as police
officers directed traffic with flashlights and whistles. The George
Washington Bridge was illuminated only on the New Jersey side, its
New York half eerily invisible.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir said that an additional 400 to
500 officers had been sent to the area from other precincts.
Emergency police units were setting up powerful flood lights at key
intersections while city workers, using lists, were going to the
homes of those on life support to see if they needed assistance. He
said it was fortunate that the neighborhood was subjected to
partial blackouts during the day, which gave the city extra time to
prepare.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipated a worst-case scenario and the worst case
happened,'' Safir said at a news conference in Washington Heights
Tuesday night. Standing at his side, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani praised
the residents for maintaining calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've handled it in a very cooperative, very peaceful way,''
he said. ``They have really been wonderfully patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Guillermo Linares, who represents Washington Heights on the City
Council, said, ``Fortunately, people have been very calm,'' he
said. ``This is a very overcrowded community, and it has a number
of high rises, so it's a very dangerous situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the residents, the mayor criticized Con Edison for
failing to do more to prevent the blackout. ``I find it incredible,
after years and years of blackouts, that enough power can't be
supplied to the city,'' he said, as city officials braced for the
possibility of other major power failures in the Williamsburg
section of Brooklyn and Long Island City in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Lyn Rossano, 37, an epidemiologist at New York Prebyterian who
lives on 168th Street and Haven Avenue, said she was sitting at her
computer when the power failed. She said the screen flickered a few
times and then everything went dead. ``I just sat in the dark for a
while completely stunned,'' she said. ``Then I went outside to
check on what was going on and nobody seemed to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Some residents and especially shop owners were clearly nervous.
Rolando Alicia, who runs a deli at 168th Street and Broadway, said
as soon as the lights went out, he told everyone to leave his
store, locked the doors and nervously awaited the police. ``I've
experienced two previous blackouts,'' he said. ``I'm not crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   At New York Prebyterian, one nurse described a chaotic scene in
the emergency room as staff members tried to assess patients with
flashlights, and used battery powered defibrilators. ``They were
coding people in the dark,'' said the nurse, who did not give her
name.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome M. Hauer, director of the Mayor's Office of Emergency
Management, said no patients died because of the emergency room
power outage. Lights were restored about 11.45 p.m. Tuesday night.
``The hospital staff did an excellent job,'' Hauer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
