<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MABRY REMAINS IN ADJUSTMENT MODE AS M'S UTILITY MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ There is a .300 hitter inside John Mabry. The
Mariners utility man is sure of it.
</P>
<P>
   Mabry had a .286 career average when he signed with the Mariners
last winter. But for most of this season, he's hung around .250,
never much better, never much worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a role player or whatever, and you play every
three or four days, it just takes at-bats,'' Mabry said. ``I'm a
guy that doesn't walk very much, and that's going to have an
effect. The thing is, when you go in there and go 1-for-4 every
day, you're going to hit .250. But when you've got 200 at-bats, a
4-for-4 can put you at .270.''
</P>
<P>
   Mabry was a late addition to Tuesday night's lineup, starting in
right when designated hitter Edgar Martinez was scratched because
of a tight left hamstring. On Monday, Mabry homered for the first
time in two months _ but also struck out four times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy to see him drive the ball, because he's been
struggling a little bit,'' said manager Lou Piniella. ``We haven't
been able to play him on a regular basis, which I don't think helps
matters. But (Butch) Huskey has been swinging well, and Russ
(Davis) has picked it up a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers have been getting ahead of Mabry by working him away,
Piniella said, and Mabry needs to cover that part of the plate
better.
</P>
<P>
   There have been plenty of other adjustments. Mabry is getting
used to seeing more change-ups and breaking balls than he did in
the National League, where he played for the St. Louis Cardinals
from 1994 to '98. He came to the M's with just 31 career games at
third base, and has made 12 starts there this season. It's a
complicated position to learn on the fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the toughest things to do, coming off the bench, is to
play third base,'' Mabry said. ``Hopefully I'm getting better and
better every day, but it's still tough. It's not instinct for me
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither is the notion that he's a utility player. When you've
been successful as a starter (Mabry batted .307 and .297 in 1995
and '96), how do you accept it?
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't,'' Mabry said. ``It's tough _ you don't ever want to
give in and say I can't play every day, because in your mind you
think you can. Everybody wants to play every day. If you don't, you
shouldn't be out here. But some teams, that's just the way they're
built, and that's the way you've got to approach it. Just go out
and work as hard as you would if you played every day.''
</P>
<P>
   ZIMMERMAN DISABLED: The Mariners have been afflicted by a pair
of unusual injuries in recent weeks _ one travel-related, one
autograph-related.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Jordan Zimmerman stepped on a suitcase at the team's
Anaheim hotel Monday, spraining his right ankle. The injury was
minor, and well-timed, since the M's were looking to clear a roster
spot for Tuesday night's starter, Gil Meche. They placed Zimmerman
on the 15-day disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's two or three days away from being able to fully land on
it,'' Piniella said. ``At the same time, we've suggested some
changes, and he'll be able to work with Stan when he's ready. Then
we'll send him out on a rehab, probably in a week to 10 days.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners would like Zimmerman to change the grip on his
slider, add a curveball and change the angle of his delivery on
some of his pitches.
</P>
<P>
   The autograph-related injury is Piniella's, who aggravated his
back before the trip while bending over to pick up a stack of
Safeco Field posters he had signed. Trainers and a chiropractor
have reduced the soreness, and Piniella said he's feeling better.
</P>
<P>
   ALL-STAR M'S? Piniella said he expects the Mariners to have more
All-Stars than just Ken Griffey Jr., who will start in center
field. The American League reserves will be announced Wednesday,
and one starting pitcher _ Freddy Garcia or Jamie Moyer. Plus
shortstop Alex Rodriguez, catcher Dan Wilson and designated hitter
Edgar Martinez all would seem to be candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect one of our pitchers to make it, I really do,''
Piniella said. ``I would think that Alex has a very reasonable
chance of making it as a reserve, and I think Danny should be
considered. If they take more than one DH, Edgar should be
considered also.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez has made four All-Star teams, Rodriguez three and
Wilson one. For Moyer and Garcia, it would be their first
selection.
</P>
<P>
   UNIT ON SCHEDULE: Regardless of whether he pitches in the
All-Star Game, Randy Johnson likely will start against the M's in
the Arizona Diamondbacks' series in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   According to media reports in Arizona, if Johnson pitches in the
All-Star Game, he probably would start July 18 at Safeco Field. If
he does not pitch in the All-Star Game, Johnson would start July 20
at Safeco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
