<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1390 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-LYNX-COMETS-HNS &LR;      07-07 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-LYNX-COMETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The game plan, said All-Star forward Sheryl Swoopes, was for the
Comets to show the expansion Minnesota Lynx who belonged on the
Compaq Center floor Tuesday night and who didn't.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``With Minnesota being in our same (Western) conference, we
wanted to go out and not even let them think they could play with
us,'' Swoopes said.
</P>
<P>
   It worked. On a day when three of the Comets were selected to
start on the Western Conference team in the first WNBA All-Star
Game, the Comets got virtuoso performances from nearly everyone who
played in an 80-54 win over the Lynx.
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes, the top vote-getter in the fan balloting for the
All-Star Game, contributed 15 points. Fellow All-Star Cynthia
Cooper, the second-leading vote-getter, led all scorers with 21
points and had a season-high nine assists.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Thompson, the third Comet who will start at New York's
Madison Square Garden on July 14, scored all of her 14 points in
the second half. And point guard Sonja Henning looked like an
All-Star, scoring 14 points on 6-for-8 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Even the bench brigade of Janeth Arcain, Tammy Jackson, Jennifer
Rizzotti, Amaya Valdemoro and Nyree Roberts combined for 11 points,
two steals, two assists and eight rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the first half, the Comets (11-1) had played so
well on defense, holding Minnesota to 9.5 percent shooting from the
field, it appeared they might be on the way to breaking the WNBA
record they set Saturday in beating New York 65-50 when they held
the Liberty to a league-record 21.9 percent shooting and 14 field
goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York missed a lot of shots,'' said coach Van Chancellor,
``but tonight Minnesota missed some shots because we were harassing
them. We harassed them a little better than we did against New
York.''
</P>
<P>
   The Comets go on the road for games against Sacramento and
Phoenix, two Western Conference foes they haven't faced this
season, armed with a stout defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still trying to search for our identity, what kind of
team we are, where we're going to hang our hat,'' said Lynx coach
Brian Agler. ``I think Houston is a team that has a lot of
confidence right now and they're playing well together. I think at
this point, everybody's trying to catch them and will be for a
period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no catching the Comets on Tuesday. Cooper and Henning
combined for 24 points in the first half to stake the Comets to a
36-22 lead by intermission, thanks to the game plan Swoopes
revealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had played them at their place (on June 19, a 69-55 Comets
win) and knew what to expect tonight, what they were going to do,''
Swoopes said. ``They were going to be very physical, and every
player was going to play every position.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense is a subject Chancellor loves to discuss. And he does
incessantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say it all the time,'' he said, ``you're going to win
championships when you play good defense. Defense will win for you
when you're on the road; it'll win when you're not playing good.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to imply the Comets played poorly against the Lynx
(5-5). Quite the contrary. The game was close for only about four
minutes. Henning's second basket of the night, both resulting from
Cooper assists, forged a 10-3 Comets lead.
</P>
<P>
   The lead was 34-19 with two minutes left in the first half. The
Lynx were not only having trouble scoring, but starting forward
Brandy Reed had picked up her third foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naturally,'' Chancellor said, ``we wanted to go out and stop
their big guns, (leading scorer Tonya) Edwards and (third-leading
scorer) Katie Smith. But I was really worried about Brandy Reed.
What hurt Minnesota was early foul trouble. Something I always harp
on is you cannot get your key people in foul trouble. If you do,
you remove them from the game. And I thought that hurt them.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, Reed and Smith were averaging a combined 44.1 points
per game. But when the first half ended, they were a combined
4-for-21 from the field for only 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets applied the clinching blow with a 10-4 run to open
the second half. Henning knocked down a 3-pointer off an assist
from Polina Tzekova for a 46-26 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
