<HEADER>
A1391 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRK-TECH-SHOLARS-HNS &LR;      07-07 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRK-TECH-SHOLARS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANNY ROBBINS  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Texas Tech track and field coach Greg Sholars, who last month was
arrested and charged with assaulting a female assistant coach, has
resigned, Tech athletic director Gerald Myers announced Tuesday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Myers' announcement _ a two-paragraph news release that gave no
reason for the resignation _ came three days after the Chronicle
reported Sholars had been charged with misdemeanor assault as a
result of a March incident in which he allegedly bit and punched
assistant coach Trece Hayslett. Despite the timing of the
announcement, Sholars said his resignation was unrelated to the
assault charge and was something he had been contemplating before
the criminal case became public. He said his plan is to return to
Fort Worth, his hometown, so he can be closer to his mother and
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole deal is very simple,'' he said Tuesday from
Lubbock. ``I've really enjoyed the opportunity I've had to work out
here at Texas Tech. My resignation was planned because of family
and personal decisions. It's very untimely that this (the assault
charge) has come out at the exact same time. It has nothing to do
with my decision to leave Texas Tech.''
</P>
<P>
   Sholars, 33, came to Tech as men's track coach in 1995 from the
University of Texas, where he had been an assistant coach in the
women's program. Tech gave him oversight of its men's and women's
programs in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   On June 11, Sholars was arrested and charged with assaulting
Hayslett, 28, a member of Sholars' staff for two years and also a
former UT employee. Hayslett told Tech police May 5 that she had
been bitten, punched and scratched by Sholars during an incident
that occurred March 16 in a parked car on the Tech campus.
</P>
<P>
   According to the offense report prepared by Tech police,
Hayslett said she was attempting to get Sholars to return a gun he
had taken from her apartment and had brought with him to the Tech
campus. The report quotes Hayslett as saying she had taken a pair
of Oakley sunglasses belonging to Sholars from his car to her own
and was bitten and punched by him when he tried to retrieve the
sunglasses, which had fallen to the floor of the car.
</P>
<P>
   The report states Hayslett reported the matter to Judith Henry,
Tech's associate athletic director/senior woman administrator, and
was led to believe the university would investigate. Hayslett told
police she tried to ``ride things out'' until the end of the
semester but wound up contacting police because she believed she
had suffered various acts of harassment by Sholars and members of
the track coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   The report cites photographic and other evidence indicating
Hayslett had teeth marks and a bruise on her left leg after the
incident. The report also quotes Henry as saying Sholars had
acknowledged to her that he had bitten Hayslett.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after reporting the matter to police, Hayslett took
a leave of absence and moved to her parents' Memphis, Tenn., home.
She told the Chronicle she subsequently was required to return all
items that had been issued to her by Tech and was informed by Henry
that June 30 would be her last day of employment at the university.
</P>
<P>
   Sholars, while declining comment on specific aspects of the
case, said Tuesday he did not assault Hayslett.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Hayslett was a very close friend of mine,'' he said,
``and this was not an assault. It was like a brother and sister
having a squabble. And once the wheels got turning (in the legal
process), it got out of control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was her choice for it to go to this point,
nor was it mine. This thing has snowballed, and it is making me
look like a villain when I'm definitely not. To be honest, this was
two friends having a squabble, and in the end it has been blown way
out of proportion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
