<HEADER>
A1392 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     07-07 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
IT was in the fall of 1983 when Carol Vermeil took her husband for
a drive into the gorgeous rolling countryside near their suburban
Philadelphia home.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Vermeil was less than one year removed from being the
hard-driving, no-sleeping, videotape-devouring head football coach
of the Eagles, a job he took a little more seriously than life and
death.
</P>
<P>
   As the miles rolled beneath the wheels of the car, and the
landscapes _ in an explosion of autumn reds and yellows and oranges
_ slid past the windows, Dick Vermeil turned to his wife and asked:
</P>
<P>
   ``What's wrong with the trees? Are they dying?''
</P>
<P>
   Ten years after the tunnel-visioned Vermeil introduced the term
``burnout'' to the world of sports and walked away from the
sidelines in the prime of his career, the very successful Joe Gibbs
quit as head coach of the Washington Redskins, citing a need to get
away from the all-consuming pressures of the lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Now, sheer physical and mental exhaustion forces Rudy
Tomjanovich to give up his post as coach of the USA national
basketball team in the Olympic qualifying tournament that starts
next week in Puerto Rico. And the only real question is why it
hasn't happened sooner and to more of his peers.
</P>
<P>
   These are times when coaches and managers in sports are being
paid outrageous sums of money but are under incredible pressure to
produce. Which means a bigger commitment, which means ridiculous
hours. Which can mean you are left with the hollow-eyed,
raspy-voiced, limp-as-a-dishrag figure that was Tomjanovich a week
ago on the night of the NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   This has been a most strange and disturbing year to be in charge
of a Houston sports team. First, the horrible scare with Larry
Dierker and his grand mal seizure in the Astros' dugout. Now,
Tomjanovich pushes himself to the brink and has to be told one
unfathomable word by the Rockets' medical staff: Stop.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that, in many ways, they are cut from the same bolt
of cloth, a pair of former heroes for the very teams they now
manage. Both are down-to-earth and unpretentious yet as good as it
gets at what they do. Tall and strapping, bright and fun-loving,
they are the last two guys you expect to see ailing.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker's problem with a tangled knot of blood vessels in his
brain was, at least, congenital, and the prognosis is for a full
recovery and a return to the dugout in a matter of weeks.
Tomjanovich's condition, though certainly less life-threatening,
could be more difficult to overcome in the long term and may
present bigger questions in the not-too-distant future.
</P>
<P>
   The public sees Rudy T in designer suits and fancy ties in front
of the Rockets' bench. It sees the $5 million annual salary, the TV
commercials and his face up on billboards.
</P>
<P>
   What the public doesn't see is the time spent living out of an
office, skin sallow, eyes glazed over, mind numb from watching
miles of videotape or drawing up X's and O's, with sleep coming
maybe two or three hours a night on a sofa bed.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a plea for sympathy. But how long does the hamster
race around the tiny wheel inside the cage before he drops?
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that Rudy T is one of the driven, maybe
compulsive, ones. When he succeeded Don Chaney as Rockets coach in
1992, he said it was only a short-term venture. But as the years
have gone by, the coaching game, the search for more, has sunk in
its hooks and has him addicted like the strongest drug.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt the back-to-back championships raised the bar,
not only in his own mind but on the expectation levels of a city.
To many, the 1996-97 season that ended against Utah one game and a
few seconds short of another trip to the NBA Finals was seen as
utter failure. Since then, there have been two first-round playoff
losses, and nowadays, to some, any season that doesn't conclude
with a parade isn't worth remembering. Which is why the Rockets _
club owner Leslie Alexander included _ were willing to wheel Hakeem
Olajuwon out to the curb.
</P>
<P>
   Those two weeks of wrestling with the Olajuwon decision took so
much out of Rudy T, emotionally and physically. But then,
everything takes its toll because he does nothing halfway.
</P>
<P>
   Which makes you wonder, even after an imposed rest, how much
longer he can _ or wants _ to go on. Or how soon he works himself
to the nub again.
</P>
<P>
   Does executive vice president of basketball Carroll Dawson
retire or move over in the front office, giving Tomjanovich room to
assume general manager duties full-time? Does assistant coach Jim
Boylen get the reins to the club?
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured, over the next three to four weeks, these are
questions that will have to be asked.
</P>
<P>
   Exhaustively.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
