<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS BANKING TOO HEAVILY ON THEIR YOUNG ARMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Fans of irony as well as major league pitching struck
the motherlode this week.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time Randy Johnson was losing his third straight
decision for the Arizona Diamondbacks, despite allowing only four
runs and striking out 43, Mariners pitchers rang up back-to-back
shutouts.
</P>
<P>
   Dunno what the odds were for those events happening
independently, much less together, but I'll bet they were higher
even than for finding a Mariner owner who could pass a lie-detector
test.
</P>
<P>
   Both pitching developments crossed the threshold into utter
astonishment. Johnson was twice thwarted by St. Louis rookie
pitcher Jose Jimenez, a heretofore nondescript figure except for
bearing the name of a popular character created by 1960s comedian
Bill Dana.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing that the ferocious Big Unit was brought asunder by Jose
Jimenez was a little like learning that economist Alan Greenspan
had been out-forecasted by Scooby Doo.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Mariners, whose pitching has been a
compass-rose-embossed version of the train-wreck scene in ``The
Fugitive,'' drew consecutive shutouts from John Halama and Jeff
Fassero (the latter with ninth-inning help from Paul Abbott).
Records show it has been almost three years since the Mariners last
achieved the feat, although most fans would pin the previous event
somewhere between the signing of the Magna Carta and the beginning
of the Industrial Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, both shutouts were against division rivals Texas
and Anaheim, who owned the Mariners a year ago when they found
themselves in the divisional basement, 13 games out. Although early
July is hardly a pivot point in a pennant race, the Mariners
entered Tuesday night's activities four games out.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with the frustrations of their former No. 1 hurler,
Fassero, now a semi-human 9-6, optimists might suggest that the
fortunes of the most neglected aspect of the franchise have finally
turned a corner, even without acquiring Johnson's pitching
equivalent.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for you, none of that silly optimism will be found
here.
</P>
<P>
   Latest evidence against the runaway yippies took the mound
Tuesday night: Gil Meche.
</P>
<P>
   The prized phenom of the organization, coveted by multiple
rivals in numerous proposed trades, made his major league debut.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the game's outcome, it's too soon for Meche.
</P>
<P>
   Despite impressive statistics and reported uncommon maturity,
Meche has no business in the current mess.
</P>
<P>
   While I have no knowledge of Meche beyond what's been published,
any layman's awareness of human nature coupled with the high
attrition rate of 20-year-old major league pitchers, not to mention
Lou Piniella's ham-fisted handling of young pitchers, suggests that
Meche is being shoved into a phone booth rich in untrained pit
bulls.
</P>
<P>
   It is hardly coincidence that Meche's arrival coincides with the
imminent debut of the new ballpark, the latest moment of
desperation for a franchise with a 23-year history in desperation.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis du jour is that, as was pointed out by multiple
speakers at Monday's ribbon-cutting ceremony for the Guilty
Pleasure, the franchise owes the community a World Series, now that
the community has ponied up a world-class ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Ridiculous? Perhaps, but no more ridiculous than the ballpark's
final tab. And it is anything but ridiculous given that that is the
requirement suggested by Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex Rodriguez for
staying in Seattle after 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than respond to the crisis by seeking more expensive
talent in the offseason, ownership has decided to rob the pitching
cradle. Meche will be the fifth Seattle rookie to make his
big-league pitching debut this season.
</P>
<P>
   If he were to tread water in the next few starts, he is presumed
to become the third rookie in the starting rotation, along with
Halama and Freddy Garcia. To suggest that this is a rotation to
take into a September pennant race is even more incredible than the
owners' recent attempt to further pluck the public pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Redoubtable as have been Garcia and Halama, they still have not
survived a full season in the Piniella crucible to prove they are
not merely the next names in the Fleming/Torres/Wolcott/Cloude line
of Mariner prospects come to naught.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Mariners, they still have an out _ the July
31 trading deadline. If Meche flops in the manner of most club
farmhands, the Mariners will have a chance to go after help more
appropriate to a pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   As has been mentioned endlessly by the Mariner brass, all of
baseball is short of pitching. But by the end of this month, it's a
virtual certainty that Texas, Cleveland, Boston, Anaheim and the
Yankees will have found veteran patches for their weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   And those teams have no particular crisis in which they must
deliver quickly unto their public partners the kind of quality
their partners have delivered unto them.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
