<HEADLINE>
SIX-RUN EIGHTH LIFTS ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK WELCH  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ When the Anaheim Angels clinched their second
American League West title in 1982, a giddy 12-year-old boy from
Huntington Beach savored the moment by running around the infield
collecting fistfuls of dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen years later, Mike Fyhrie, who was born in Long Beach,
got another chance to step onto Angels' home turf. But this time he
was the home team's starting pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   And the 29-year-old Fyhrie pitched well in his first big league
start, giving up two runs and six hits in seven innings as the
Angels defeated the Seattle Mariners, 8-2, Tuesday night at Edison
Field.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Glaus' RBI single off Mariners' reliever Frankie Rodriguez
with one out in the eighth inning snapped a 2-2 tie. Glaus' liner
to right field scored Randy Velarde and gave reliever Mark
Petkovsek (8-2) his club-leading eighth win. Petkovsek pitched the
final two innings in relief of Fyhrie.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Huson followed Glaus with an RBI single one out later to
score Garret Anderson. Gary DiSarcina and Darin Erstad each added
back-to-back, two-run singles to cap the Angels' six-run inning.
</P>
<P>
   The win also meant the Angels (38-44) cut the Texas Rangers lead
in the A.L. West to 7{ games.
</P>
<P>
   Fyhrie, the right-hander who was called up from Triple-A
Edmonton Monday, gave the Angels what they were looking for -- a
solid outing and a good number of innings.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching in front of 22,444 that included about 25 family
members and friends, Fyhrie drew raves by striking out Ken Griffey
Jr. with the bases loaded and two outs in the top of the fifth. He
struck out six and walked one while throwing 121 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels tied the game at 2-2 in the sixth inning when Seattle
starter Gil Meche, making his major league debut, walked Orlando
Palmeiro with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Fyhrie, who attended UCLA, was making his third big-league
appearance and first as an Angel. He pitched two games for the New
York Mets in 1996. Fyhrie was 8-5 with a 3.40 earned run average at
Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   Fyhrie shut down Griffey Jr. (0-3), but had trouble with
hot-hitting shortstop Alex Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez had an RBI double and hit his third solo homer of the
series off Fyhrie.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, who had limited success against Meche, the pride of
the Mariners' farm system, got a run in the bottom of the third
when Erstad's sacrifice fly scored Matt Walbeck. Walbeck doubled
down the left field line to open the third.
</P>
<P>
   The Angel offense, which was limited to three hits by Jeff
Fassero and Paul Abbott (one inning) on Monday, was again punchless
until breaking through in the eighth inning off Rodriguez (2-3).
</P>
</TEXT>
