<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-HARDY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARDY A KING AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Mark Hardy spent the majority of his 14-year NHL
career playing for the Los Angeles Kings. Today, after three
seasons as an assistant coach with the Long Beach Ice Dogs, Hardy
is expected to return to the Kings, this time as an assistant
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really excited about it,'' Hardy said Tuesday night.
``I've always been a King at heart. I've worked hard to get here.
It's my next step in life and I'm looking to be as successful as I
was with the Ice Dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardy, 40, is expected to receive a three-year contract. The NHL
source who confirmed the former defenseman's hiring said the other
assistant on new coach Andy Murray's staff will be 37-year-old Dave
Tippett, who this season coached the Houston Aeros to the
International Hockey League's Turner Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   With Murray overseeing the team, Hardy's responsibilities are
expected to be defense and penalty killing. Tippett, who could not
be reached for comment, will focus on the offense and power play.
Tippett played for Hartford, Washington, Pittsburgh and
Philadelphia during a 721-game playing career from 1983-94.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
