<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 02:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1434 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-ALL-STAR-A     07-07 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-ALL-STAR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PAIR OF ALL-STARS  
 BELL JOINS WILLIAMS,THANKS TO ONLINE VOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanks to their friends in cyberspace, the Diamondbacks can make
a claim unmatched in the National League: They will have two
starters in next Tuesday's All-Star Game at Boston's Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Matt Williams has been pretty much a lock through
most of the voting process by the fans. But second baseman Jay Bell
staged the biggest rally this side of Harry Truman in 1948,
overtaking Houston's Craig Biggio to earn the starting nod.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first time any Diamondback has been named an
All-Star starter. Center fielder Devon White, now with the Dodgers,
was the first Arizona player to be named an All-Star. He was
selected as a reserve last season.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona could have two more players added today when the
pitching staffs and reserves are named for both leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Randy Johnson is expected to be selected by NL
Manager Bruce Bochy of the San Diego Padres and left fielder Luis
Gonzalez, who had a 30-game hitting streak this season, is a solid
candidate for a reserve spot. Despite an aggressive write-in
campaign around the state, Gonzalez was not among the top 10 in
voting released Tuesday by Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely surprised,'' Bell said before Tuesday's game.
``Craig has been the fair-haired second baseman in the National
League for a long time, and he has deserved it. To be elected over
him is an honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 33, finished with 1,310,799 votes and had a
comfortable margin over Atlanta's Chipper Jones, who had 653,197.
Bell, who trailed Biggio by 38,919 votes a week ago, finished with
1,203,902 to Biggio's 1,171,574, a difference of 32,328.
</P>
<P>
   Bell, also 33, was able to make up the difference and pass
Biggio due in large part to voting over the Internet. Most of the
Internet votes were not tabulated until this week. Each Internet
vote was worth 22 votes to match the average number of home games
at which ballots were counted.
</P>
<P>
   The voting was even more rewarding for Bell, who played most of
his career at shortstop but switched to second base this season.
</P>
<P>
   He responded by hitting his career-high 23rd home run in the
sixth inning against Biggio's Astros on Tuesday night at Bank One
Ballpark. Bell, who entered the game hitting .279 with 56 RBIs,
also singled in the first inning and made a tough defensive play
behind second base to force Biggio for the final out of the fifth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about whether the online voting could have helped him,
Bell smiled and said, ``My three kids have been on the Internet
constantly.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggio was gracious in his second-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a close race all the way. I knew it would be close down
to the end,'' he said. ``I'm happy for Jay. He's having a heck of a
season. I know how much it means to be voted in. It gives you more
pride.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be Bell's second All-Star appearance. While with
Pittsburgh in 1993, he was selected as a reserve shortstop, but
wound up playing second base.
</P>
<P>
   He is looking forward to renewing acquaintances with players
around the league. The other starters are St. Louis first baseman
Mark McGwire, Cincinnati shortstop Barry Larkin, New York Mets
catcher Mike Piazza, and outfielders Sammy Sosa of the Chicago
Cubs, Tony Gwynn of San Diego and Larry Walker of Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just hanging around, going to the workout the day before,
that's the fun part,'' Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   When it's 7:30 on Tuesday night, ``that's when it gets
serious,'' said Williams, who will be making his fifth All-Star
appearance, third as a starter. He was hitting .321 with 21 homers
and 75 RBIs entering Tuesday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked real hard to get here,'' Williams said. ``The fans
have been very supportive and when they vote for you, that makes
you feel good. We hope to represent the team, ourselves and Arizona
in a positive way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're both students of the game and we realize the tradition
of the All-Star Game and the ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   Managing General Partner Jerry Colangelo said that the two
players will each get a bonus of $50,000 for being elected starters
and Johnson also could receive that with a selection today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be money well-spent,'' Colangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo said he thought back to last season, when the team
struggled to a 65-97 record and Williams and Bell took heat in the
wake of signing big contracts, Bell at five years for $34 million
and Williams with a five-year, $45 million extension that began
this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
