<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-DIAMONDBACKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIMA SHORT-CIRCUITS DIAMONDBACKS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The monsoon that swept through the Valley on Tuesday didn't cut
out the electricity inside Bank One Ballpark. But another opposing
pitcher did.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks again were without much power and another solid
starting pitching effort was wasted in a 3-1 loss to the Houston
Astros before 31,672.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Jose Lima, working on only three days' rest, picked
up his first victory in five starts, but No. 12 came with relative
ease, as he cut through the Diamondbacks' order in seven innings,
his only mistake a change-up in the sixth that Jay Bell knocked
into the left-field seats for his franchise-record 23rd homer of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Lima struck out nine and yielded just four hits.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Jay Powell and left-hander Billy Wagner limited the
Diamondbacks to a single in the final two innings. Wagner, throwing
some wicked 99 mph fastballs, retired all four batters he faced,
striking out Matt Williams, Steve Finley and Travis Lee in the
ninth to pick up his 21st save in 22 opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't solve Lima,'' Manager Buck Showalter said.
``Somewhere along the line, we've got to be able to beat guys like
him, too. We weren't able to do it, and, when you get into Wagner
area, it's pretty tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston (47-35) is 2 percentage points behind Cincinnati in the
National League Central. The Diamondbacks (45-39), who have lost
their grip in the West to the San Francisco Giants, are trying to
string some consistent games at the plate and take some of the heat
off the starters.
</P>
<P>
   Bell's homer ended a 15-inning scoreless drought for the
Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   It's been feast or famine lately for the Diamondbacks. One day,
they're setting a club record for runs. The next, they're scoring
none.
</P>
<P>
   This time, left-handler Omar Daal fell victim, as the offense
fell flat.
</P>
<P>
   Daal's only mistake was a two-run homer he gave up to left
fielder Richard Hidalgo on a 3-2 pitch in the sixth that gave
Houston (47-35) a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Daal gave up six hits, struck out seven and walked none in seven
innings.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the Diamondbacks score a club-record 17 runs in a
rout of the St. Louis Cardinals, left-hander Randy Johnson was
provided two hits in a 1-0 loss to the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   In Daal's last start, in Cincinnati, he gave up just four hits
in eight innings and didn't figure in the decision, a 2-1 loss in
10 innings.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first defeat for Daal (7-5) in nine starts. He had
a personal-best four-game win streak snapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty obvious we haven't swung the bats like we did
earlier in the year,'' Showalter said. ``It's tough to keep that
pace up, but we've gone a long way from that pace right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Daal has been reminded of last year when he was the
hard-luck loser, getting little run support.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying so hard to keep the scoring down,'' Daal said.
``Last year, it happened to me a lot of time. You have to keep
working hard and try to do the best I can to help the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Daal said he got a slider up over the plate to Hidalgo.
</P>
<P>
   Lima, who likely will be selected today as one of the NL
pitchers for the All-Star Game, was so happy to get the offensive
support that he was dancing in the clubhouse while salsa music
blasted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Lima time,'' he said about the music. ``It was one of my
best games of the year, especially since I was only on three days'
rest.''
</P>
<P>
   His start was was pushed up in the rotation because of Mike
Hampton's wrist injury.
</P>
<P>
   If the Diamondbacks were going to get to Lima, it would have to
be in the first inning when he threw 36 pitches. But he managed to
get out of it without giving up a run. He helped himself by picking
off Tony Womack at first base.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next four innings, Lima threw a total of 44 pitches and
retired 11 of the 13 batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   Daal retired 13 of 14 batters from the first to the fifth
innings and was aided by a brilliant play at second by Jay Bell,
who robbed another Bell, Derek, of a base hit.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Bell snagged Derek Bell's high hopper deep in the hole
behind second base and threw to shortstop Andy Fox for the forceout
at second to end the fifth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
