<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOKIE MECHE STARTS STRONG, BUT ANGELS ERUPT LATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Lou Piniella called Gil Meche into his office
at Edison Field several hours before Tuesday night's game. The
Mariners manager went over the Anaheim Angels' hitters and talked a
little baseball with his rookie starting pitcher, and offered some
encouraging words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him we've had some success here with some young
pitchers,'' Piniella said. ``And he can join in on the fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners and young pitchers? An unlikely match, but thanks
to Freddy Garcia and John Halama, it's been mostly successful this
year. That's a good way to sum up Meche's major league debut: he
was mostly successful.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't enough for the Mariners to win, as they fell to the
Angels, 8-2, before 22,444 fans. But the 20-year-old right-hander
gave the manager what he wanted: he pitched into the sixth inning
and gave the M's a chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   Meche worked 52/3 innings, allowing two runs on four hits and
five walks. Anaheim won the game by breaking a 2-2 tie with a
six-run eighth off reliever Frankie Rodriguez (2-3). Because the
Texas Rangers lost at Oakland, the Mariners remain four games
behind in the American League West.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought there would be more jitters,'' said Meche, who was
four levels below the majors at this time last year. ``I didn't
think I'd make that many good pitches that early in the game. It's
what I expected it to be. I knew I had to make good pitches
tonight, and I did at the right times. The only difference is being
so relaxed out there. I thought I would be a little tense.''
</P>
<P>
   There was one area in which Meche was disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked more guys than I intended to walk, which was
hopefully none,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Five pitches into the game, he fell short of that goal. Leadoff
hitter Darin Erstad walked, which Meche said was more the result of
adrenaline than nerves. He didn't walk another batter until the
fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Through five, Meche had a 2-1 lead, courtesy of a run-scoring
double in the first and a solo homer in the fourth by Alex
Rodriguez. But that was all Angels rookie Mike Fyhrie would allow.
Fyhrie, nine years older than Meche but making his first big league
start in the same game, allowed two runs on six hits and a walk in
seven innings. One of his six strikeouts was of Ken Griffey Jr.
with the bases loaded in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just far enough outside and just far enough up to keep
us off,'' said right fielder Butch Huskey, a teammate of Fyhrie's
in the New York Mets organization. ``There weren't too many cookies
he gave up.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said of Meche, who gave up a few long outs
early in the game, but just one extra-base hit. He was driven from
the game not by the Angels but by his wildness: he walked Troy
Glaus to load the bases in the sixth, then walked Orlando Palmeiro
to score the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   Meche had success throwing two-seam fastballs away from
left-handed hitters. That was his plan against Palmeiro, but the
ball sunk more than he wanted it to.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in tough situations early, I just threw the ball
right through (catcher) Dan (Wilson),'' Meche said. ``That time
(against Palmeiro), I cut some off and as a result, my fastball was
in the dirt a little bit. Maybe I was pressing a little too much at
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Rodriguez preserved the tie by getting Jeff Huson to
ground out, but he struggled in the eighth. Randy Velarde led off
with a single to second on a ball that second baseman David Bell
said ``should have been an out, no question about that.'' With
runners on first and second after an intentional walk, Glaus
singled to right to drive in the go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   A walk and three more singles would follow, and by time Velarde
ended the inning with a pop out, the Angels had put the game out of
reach.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome, this night would be memorable because of
Meche, the Mariners' No. 1 draft choice in 1996 who began the year
at Class AA New Haven.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a first outing, I think he was outstanding,'' Wilson said.
``He came up with a lot of expectations and was highly touted. I
think he met the challenge tonight. For a 20-year-old kid, he did a
great job and showed a lot of poise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
