<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CASSTEVENS-ALL-STAR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIAMONDBACKS FANS VOTED EARLY, OFTEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine if we elected our presidents the way we select the
starting lineups for baseball's All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I vote again?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why, of ``course'' you can. How many ballots would you like?''
</P>
<P>
   Before you answer, the volunteer working at the polling site
smiles and says, ``Here. Take a hundred. We've got plenty more if
you need them.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtain drawn, you vote and vote and vote again, demonstrating
the persistence of an Arizona baseball fan pulling the lever on a
straight Diamondbacks ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Congratulations.
</P>
<P>
   D-backs fans, take a bow.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks mostly to you, Matt Williams and Jay Bell received more
votes than any other players in the league at their positions.
</P>
<P>
   The second-year Diamondbacks are the only National League team
that will have two starters at next week's All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' election wasn't a surprise. The Diamondbacks third
baseman had been leading in the voting. He won in a landslide.
</P>
<P>
   Bell's victory was unexpected and left him grinning like an
underdog winner on election night. A week ago, the second baseman
trailed Houston's Craig Biggio. But a late surge of votes came in
like Tuesday's dust storm. Bell finished more than 30,000 votes
ahead of Biggio, who is in town this week with the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whattaya do?'' Biggio said, accepting the outcome with a
gracious smile.
</P>
<P>
   It is not known whether 1,203,902 of you cast one vote each for
Bell or whether one person voted 1,203,902 times.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely Bell and Williams were swept into the starting
lineup by thousands of Diamondbacks fans who voted early and often
for the veteran infielders. Both are having All-Star seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says a lot for the people of Arizona,'' Luis Gonzalez said.
Gonzo also has played well enough to make the team but he had
little chance of being elected (despite a write-in campaign)
because the Diamondbacks left his name off the ballot. The league's
third-leading hitter (.364) hopes to be selected as a reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans take the All-Star voting seriously. Every year
the balloting generates lively debate, righteous editorials and an
occasional stabbing. Invariably, some players get their feelings
hurt. Juan Gonzalez of the Texas Rangers is pouting this year,
vowing not to play because he isn't starting.
</P>
<P>
   Every year questions are kicked around. Should the fans vote?
Should the players select the team? How about the media? Americans
say the fans deserve to pick the starters. And most would rather
let the Red Chinese select the teams than entrust that
responsibility to sports writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to have the fans involved,'' Biggio said. ``They
deserve to see who they want out there. It's good for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   So the fans spoke again this year, loudly, especially in
Cleveland. The Indians who sell out every game have four starters.
Cleveland fans almost voted in three others.
</P>
<P>
   Arizonans got into the civic spirit, too. ``Our ushers were
``armed'' with ballots this year,'' said Jeff Golner, Diamondbacks
game operations manager. Fans dutifully voted at Bank One Ballpark.
They also logged on and voted repeatedly (up to 22 times, the
maximum allowed) on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Their All-Star duty done, baseball fans soon will have the
opportunity to select (drumroll) the All-Century team. From
July-September Americans can cast their votes from a list of 100
nominees.
</P>
<P>
   Ballots will be available at Kmart, in special advertisements in
``TV Guide'' and ``Sports Illustrated'' and on Major League
Baseball's Web site. The team will be announced during the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   But get this. Banned players, like Pete Rose, will be eligible
for the team, but if elected will not be able to participate in any
ceremonies or functions.
</P>
<P>
   How silly is that? &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at david.casstevens(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 0235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
