<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-GEDNEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEDNEY OUT FOR SEASON AFTER SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tight end is no longer one of the deepest positions on the
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   The team lost Chris Gedney for the season after he underwent
colon surgery Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Gedney, who will be hospitalized a week to 10 days, will have
more surgery in two to three months.
</P>
<P>
   Team officials hope that Gedney can make a full recovery and
return in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   He has suffered from ulcerative colitis, an inflammation of the
colon, for several years. His condition had been in remission, but
he was hospitalized in the past week and doctors discovered a
perforation of the colon, which required surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little shocked,'' offensive coordinator Marc Trestman
said. ``I talked to Chris Gedney in the hospital a week ago and he
was getting out. I'm disappointed for him as much as anything. I
know he was looking forward to this season.''
</P>
<P>
   Gedney has been the team's top pass-catching tight end the past
two seasons, with 45 receptions for 532 yards and five scores. Last
season, he had 22 grabs for 271 yards and one touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has such a value to this team with his multiple role in
this offense,'' Trestman said. ``He gives us flexibility. We were
able to move him around and cause some matchup (problems). We will
lose some of that. We will lose his value in the locker room and
his great practice (work) ethic.''
</P>
<P>
   With Gedney gone, Johnny McWilliams and second-year pro Terry
Hardy will be counted on heavily. The only other tight end on the
roster is Jarius Hayes, who spent most of last season as a blocking
fullback.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals likely will sign another tight end before training
camp opens July 30 in Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   McWilliams, who signed a one-year deal, had his best season in
1998 with 26 catches for 284 yards and one score.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy, a fifth-round pick from Southern Mississippi a year ago,
caught no passes last season but impressed the coaches and was
expected to battle for playing time this year.
</P>
<P>
   McWilliams has been slowed this summer by an ankle sprain, and
Hardy is coming off shoulder surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our depth (at tight end) is a bit diluted now,'' Trestman
said. ``But if Johnny continues to progress after last season and
Terry reaches his potential, I think we will be just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Vince Tobin and tight ends coach Hank Kuhlmann are on
vacation and could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Gedney, a 6-foot-5, 257-pound seventh-year pro, was scheduled to
earn $650,800 this season _ $516,700 in salary and $133,300 in
pro-rated signing bonus _ all of which will count against the $57.3
million salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Gedney had been injury-free the past two seasons after injuries
shortened his first four seasons. He suffered a broken collarbone
in 1993, a broken left leg in '94, an ankle sprain in '95 and a
stress fracture in his right foot in '96.
</P>
<P>
   With Gedney out, the Cardinals will be missing three key pieces
from last year's offense. Also gone are left tackle Lomas Brown,
who signed with Cleveland as a free agent, and fullback Larry
Centers, who signed with Washington on Tuesday as a free agent
after the Cardinals cut him. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 0236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0066 </DOCNO>
