<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REDSKINS_CENTERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENTERS DOUBLES PLEASURE  
 SIGNS WITH SKINS TO FACE CARDS TWICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's no secret why former Cardinals running back Larry Centers
picked the Washington Redskins as his new NFL team Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to play against the Cardinals, NFC East rivals, twice a
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you know Larry, you know why he did what he did,''
Cardinals strong safety Tommy Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   Centers will be taking a pay cut from the $2.5 million he was
scheduled to make with the Cardinals in 1999 to a one-year deal
with the Redskins worth $675,000 _ a $425,000 signing bonus and
$250,000 in salary. Centers had also talked with the Seahawks, who
expressed some interest, and the Giants, who did not.
</P>
<P>
   With incentives, Centers, who was cut by the Cardinals on June
18, could make as much as $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming (to Washington) was a chance to play the Cardinals
twice,'' Centers said at a Washington news conference. ``This is a
business and things happen. You can't take it personally. So, I'll
just be the professional I can be.''
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledges he'll be excited Oct. 17 when the Redskins
meet the Cardinals in a nationally televised (ESPN) game at Sun
Devil Stadium. They play again Dec. 12 at Washington's Jack Kent
Cooke Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I (have) love for the fans in Phoenix,'' said Centers, a 1990
fifth-round draft pick of the Cardinals who spent nine seasons in
the Valley. ``They will be missed.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals players don't think the fans will forget Centers, the
team's all-time leading receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to have as many fans as the Cardinals do,'' said
Cardinals deep snapper Trey Junkin of Centers' return to Sun Devil
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll be shouting, `Larry, Larry,' '' running back Mario
Bates said.
</P>
<P>
   Centers said being released by the Cardinals has not shattered
his confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look down on myself because of what happened,'' said
Centers, who was cut for salary-cap reasons. ``I'm confident in my
ability to help the (Redskins) win games.''
</P>
<P>
   He will be joining a Redskins team that hasn't been to the
playoffs since 1992. But they have narrowly missed the playoffs in
two of the past three seasons when they finished 9-7 and 8-7-1.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Redskins went 6-10, including two close losses to
the Cardinals. They lost 29-27 at Sun Devil Stadium and 45-42 at
home, with Centers catching a touchdown pass in both games, his
only scores of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been a thorn in our side for many years,'' Redskins
General Manager Charley Casserly said. ``Larry Centers is one of
the premier backs in this league. In our eyes, now we're a better
football team. He's a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   In his career against the Redskins, Centers has 72 catches,
including 10 games in which he has five or more receptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just managed to do some things to knock the Redskins out,''
Centers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is on the cusp of being a great football team. But
from what I saw the last couple of years, the focus went away at
times. Hopefully, I can not only bring some talent to the football
team but also in the locker room.''
</P>
<P>
   Centers is expected to compete with Larry Bowie for the starting
fullback job.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins also have halfbacks Skip Hicks, a second-year pro;
Stephen Davis; and Brian Mitchell, who like Centers has been a
third-down, pass-catching specialist.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals players are certain Centers can help the Redskins in
many ways. They consider him one of the best pass-catching backs in
the league and a tough blocker on rushing defensive linemen or
blitzing linebackers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to miss Larry on the field,'' Junkin said. ``We're
going to miss Larry even more on the plane, in the locker room and
on the practice field. There are only a handful of guys in my 17
years who practiced as hard as Larry Centers.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Redskins having a bye the week before they play the
Cardinals, Centers will have two weeks to get pumped up for his
return to Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope he's not playing special teams that day,'' kicker
Joe Nedney said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 0237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
