<SLUG> BC-BKL-MERCURY_ALL-STARS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMMS IS SURPRISED BY ALL-STAR BERTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jennifer Gillom received almost 10,000 more votes, but Mercury
teammate Michele Timms got a starting nod in the inaugural WNBA
All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Timms (39,171) was second to Houston's Cynthia Cooper (80,806)
in fan balloting for Western Conference guards. They will start
July 14 in New York with Los Angeles center Lisa Leslie (66,219)
and Houston forwards Sheryl Swoopes
</P>
<P>
   (84,632) and Tina Thompson (58,286).
</P>
<P>
   Leslie beat out Gillom (48,703), who has played forward all
season but was listed at center. Gillom, averaging 17 points and
7.9 rebounds per game, is a virtual lock to be named as a reserve
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie was the all-league first-team center and Gillom second in
1997. They reversed positions in '98, when Gillom was runner-up as
league Most Valuable Player.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento's Yolanda Griffith (26,061), the league's
second-leading scorer (19.9) and leading rebounder (12.8), was
third in voting at forward.
</P>
<P>
   Chosen as the East starters were the New York trio of Teresa
Weatherspoon (49,332), Rebecca Lobo (38,779) and Kym Hampton
(55,432) and the Washington duo of Chamique Holdsclaw (62,841) and
Nikki McCray (38,051).
</P>
<P>
   The 36-year-old Hampton, who has talked about this being her
final season, is Arizona State's career scoring and rebounding
leader.
</P>
<P>
   Because Lobo suffered a season-ending knee injury in the first
minute of play, a replacement starter will be named by East Coach
Linda Hill-MacDonald. The West coach will be Houston's Van
Chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   Timms, with an 8,729-vote edge over Sacramento's Ruthie
Bolton-Holifield, took her selection as a compliment and a surprise
because she was not on the all-league team in 1997 or '98.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sort of surprised that the public likes my game,'' said
Timms, 34. ``Maybe it's the Australian thing. The accent sounds a
little bit different, I guess. The Americans really like us and are
kind to us. The accent goes a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   Timms and Gillom, 35, were the first two players allocated to
the Mercury in January 1997 and have been instrumental in the
team's being a two-time playoff qualifier and '98 league finalist.
</P>
<P>
   Both made off-season training commitments for an expected
championship push, only to agonize through a 3-7 start that has
Phoenix at risk of midseason playoff elimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would give anything just to be 7-3,'' Timms said. ``As a
team, we've got a lot to work on, so while it's an honor and it's
exciting because it's history once again being made, what we need
right now is for Jen and me to be here training with the team and
not having any days off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a few things we have to work on, and that would have
been a nice week to be able to do it in.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
