<HEADLINE>
OLSON SAYS HE'LL BE READY THURSDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 and DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Gregg Olson says his back feels fine and he expects to be able
to pitch Thursday when he is eligible to come off the disabled
list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good now,'' he said. ``The spasms have subsided.''
</P>
<P>
   Olson said he never had back spasms before this episode. He said
he believes the pain is the result of slipping on the mound last
week in Cincinnati while warming up in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   He has been doing exercises for his lower back and has been
taking ground balls. He said he threw three straight days in the
bullpen in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pushing it,'' Olson said. ``It's just a matter of getting
ready to go in Thursday.''
</P>
<P>
   Olson said he woke up one day in St. Louis and his back hurt.
But he said he felt good Tuesday morning when he awoke in the
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me think that the bed was making me feel a lot worse
than it is,'' Olson said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, reliever  &UR; Darren Holmes, who has been on the DL since
June 24 because of tightness in his lower back, received a second
anti-inflammatory shot Tuesday and is expected back after the
All-Star break next week. &QL; 
Shoulder checked &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander  &UR; Nelson Figueroa, who is 7-3 at Triple-A Tucson,
received good news Tuesday when a magnetic resonance imaging test
showed no rotator cuff damage in his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Figueroa, who was checked out by Diamondbacks head physician
 &UR; David Zeman, said he has inflammation and less than a 10 percent
tear in a ligament in the back of his shoulder. Figueroa said after
two weeks of rest, he should be able to resume pitching for the
Sidewinders.
</P>
<P>
   Figueroa returned from the DL and pitched six strong innings for
Tucson on July 1. Two days later, he said he had pain in his
shoulder. &QL;  &QL; 
Trade talks continue &QL;  &QL; 
General Manager  &UR; Joe Garagiola Jr. met with staff members on
Tuesday in an attempt to narrow the focus of trade possibilities.
The team continues to seek bullpen help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we accomplished what we set out to do. Now it's a
matter of continuing to work the phones,'' Garagiola said.
</P>
<P>
   Garagiola said last week that something likely will occur soon
as opposed to near the July 31 trading deadline. Something might
happen even before the All-Star break, which begins after Sunday's
interleague game against Oakland. &QL;  &QL; 
Astros stay the course &QL;  &QL; 
The second half of the season can't get much worse for the Houston
Astros.
</P>
<P>
   They lost outfielder  &UR; Moises Alou because of a knee injury to
start the season. Third baseman  &UR; Ken Caminiti has been on the
disabled list. And Manager  &UR; Larry Dierker suffered a seizure in the
dugout on June 13 and had brain surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be where we are just shows how much character we have,''
second baseman  &UR; Craig Biggio said. Its victory Tuesday night lifted
Houston into a virtual tie with Cincinnati for first place in the
National League Central.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker visited the team's clubhouse shortly after the surgery
and will attempt to rejoin the club after the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was extremely lucky to get the good care he received, that
things have gone well for him,'' Biggio said. ``It was tough to
watch, but nobody wants him back more than we do.'' &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
