<HEADER>
A1442 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-D-BACKS_SCHULTE-A     07-07 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-D-BACKS_SCHULTE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS' VOICE BEATS CANCER, SECONDARY ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GINTONIO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's just another face in the crowd. You might have a neighbor
who looks like him.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Schulte has never been flashy. He has had to fight his way
through the haze and mist of being the man in the shadows. For a
quarter-century, it seemed that he was born to play the role of the
proverbial second banana.
</P>
<P>
   Then, suddenly, it was show time, and he was in the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Schulte, the radio voice of the Diamondbacks, is ``a real
warrior,'' said Jerry Colangelo, the team's managing general
partner.
</P>
<P>
   And it was that warrior mentality that enabled Schulte, 47, to
accomplish two things: He overcame big odds to get the job he
dreamed of as a kid in Illinois, and along the way, he defeated
even bigger odds to stay alive.
</P>
<P>
   It has been more than seven years since Schulte was diagnosed
with lymphoma, the same malady that struck the Atlanta Braves'
Andres Galarraga. Schulte, who still sees a doctor every six
months, is healthy, but his ordeal is something that is never far
from his thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think about it,'' he said. ``In a sense, I feel lucky.
I'm glad it was me and not one of my family members. I was able to
get through it. I never stopped and asked, `Why me?' It happens to
many other people. I just took it and then did the best I could.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt about it, it helps put things in perspective. I
appreciate my family much more now, and every chance I get during
the season, I spend time with them. I always look at the bright
side. When I wake up every morning, I think, `Boy, it's a great
day.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Schulte and wife Nancy have a son, Scott, 19, who will be a
sophomore in college, attending classes at both ASU West and
Glendale Community College, and a daughter, Stephanie, 14, who will
be a freshman at Glendale High School.
</P>
<P>
   Schulte met his wife, who also was born in Moline, Ill., at an
informal softball game before his sophomore year at St. Ambrose
College in Davenport, Iowa. She was the pitcher when he came to
bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave up a home run,'' she said. ``Then he asked me out a
little bit later.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether she thought the date would have materialized had
she struck him out, she laughed and said, ``I would hope so.''
</P>
<P>
   Schulte has come a long way from a June day in 1992 in a San
Diego hotel room when he stepped out of the shower, turned and
heard his right femur snap. The day before, he had to hobble around
Sea World, refusing to use a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had had pain in my knee before, and I had seen a doctor,''
Schulte said. ``We had pretty much determined that it was a wearing
away where the bones came together in the right knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty painful when it happened. It was determined at
the hospital that it was a tumor that snapped the bone, and they
diagnosed the fact that I had lymphoma.''
</P>
<P>
   Schulte eventually wound up with eight screws and a rod in his
leg. He underwent radiation and chemotherapy, and he said the only
side effect was the little stubble of hair that remained.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Schulte discovered a few things about human
behavior. His partner on Arizona State broadcasts, Tom Dillon, now
the play-by-play voice of the Car dinals, shaved his head, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a show of friendship, and I almost cried when I saw him
do that,'' Schulte said. ``He kind of teased me about it, and he
walks in one day and had a shaved head. That made me feel good. I
was still at KTAR at the time, and I was able to continue to do my
work on the Suns and ASU football.''
</P>
<P>
   Dillon said it's always gratifying to see someone like Schulte
pull through in ordeals like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good people, a lot of them, get tested at times,'' he
said. ``Greg is just a terrific person, a good father, husband and
family man. When the cancer came, it was basically a test for Greg,
and obviously he passed with flying colors, as most good people
will do.''
</P>
<P>
   What made Schulte's ordeal even tougher was the timing. One of
his close friends, ASU baseball Coach Jim Brock, died in 1994 while
Schulte was still in the midst of his own treatments.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Schulte has lost almost 40 pounds, has begun
to eat healthier, and he exercises about an hour and a half a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm healthy,'' he said. ``I was religious before all this
happened, and I still say my prayers and thank God that everything
is going good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm past that five-year mark now, but the doctor wants me to
come back every six months, but I think that's because she's a
Diamondbacks fan. The doctors have always been real positive about
it, and I think we've got this thing stopped. Everything looks
clean.''
</P>
<P>
   Another thing Schulte has adapted to is criticism. He's able to
shrug it off quickly and hold no grudges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing bothers me at all,'' he said. ``What I've been
through, it's a situation where criticism doesn't bother me.
Hopefully, I've learned something. And I have learned a lot from my
mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   He makes no effort to hide his enthusiasm for his work. It's a
dream that began when he was a youngster who listened to Jack Buck
and Harry Caray do St. Louis Cardinals games on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my mom and dad when I was 8 years old that I wanted to
be a baseball broadcaster,'' he said. ``It took a lot of years to
get here. I was fortunate to work with Al McCoy (Suns voice) and
Tom Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me now, it's exciting every night. The job is a lot easier
now. When you're really tested is in the 14-0 games and when the
team is on a five- or six-game losing streak. The ballclub is
tested, and you're tested. We all fail a lot of tests. It's how you
come out of it that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Schulte tries to spread his positive message at speaking
engagements around the Valley. He wishes he could do more of it,
and each time he does more, people, including ballplayers, learn
for the first time what he has endured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more conscious of things now,'' he said. ``I like to keep
an eye on people and talk to people who have had some problems. We
had a tour with the Diamondbacks to Las Vegas, and we went to a
hospital and saw kids with cancer. That's the hardest thing for me
to deal with. I had it myself, but when you see a little one, it
bothers me the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo could see Schulte's workmanlike effort and
dependability from the start of their relationship, and he knew
that when the Diamondbacks became a reality that he would find a
place for Schulte.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew of his great love for baseball,'' Colangelo said.
``When he went through his health problems, we all prayed that he
would be able to make it. He went through the worst scare, when you
think about it. He was able to beat the odds and come back, and
we're all very thankful for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Schulte said he never minded being in the background all those
years. Now that he's achieved his goal, he takes nothing for
granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I have a pretty big part here, but I still kind of
shake my head sometimes,'' he said. '`I have to pinch myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
