<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 03:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1443 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHILIPPINES-REBELS-SF     07-07 1794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILIPPINES-REBELS-SFCHRON(SECOND </SLUG>
 OF 2 PARTS)  
 MORO REBELS THREATEN WAR IF ESTRADA FAILS ON PROMISES  &HT;     By BENJAMIN PIMENTEL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP ABUBAKAR, Philippines _ A boy in fatigues, a rocket
launcher resting on his thin shoulder, stood guard outside Salamat
Hashim's rebel headquarters on the southern Philippine island of
Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
   Hashim, chairman of the Moro Islamic Liberation Front, commands
the largest insurgent army challenging President Joseph Estrada's
authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't feel uneasy hearing the sound of bombs and artillery
_ fighting is our normal life,'' said the 57-year-old Muslim
scholar, as he sat surrounded by his lieutenants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Estrada's administration is still young, but we don't think he
is aware of the trouble here in Mindanao.''
</P>
<P>
   Mindanao, the country's second-largest island, represents
Estrada's best hope and worst fear. The island is rich in natural
resources, with a dynamic economy that could help pull the
Philippines out of Asia's financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But it is a troubled land, where the actor-turned-president
faces a resilient rebellion that could drag his year-old government
into a debilitating war.
</P>
<P>
   The MILF is fighting to establish a separate Islamic state on
Mindanao. The insurgency, which has raged for 30 years, is rooted
in the Muslim minority's struggle against the Christian migration
that displaced Muslims over the past century.
</P>
<P>
   It is also about economic opportunity. The rebels seek a greater
share of Mindanao's riches for Muslim communities, which are among
the poorest in the country and have been largely ignored by the
central government.
</P>
<P>
   The movement claims to have 120,000 troops, but the government
places its strength at only one-tenth of that. Either way, the MILF
operates an impressive 13 major camps.
</P>
<P>
   They include Camp Abubakar, which is not really a camp but a
mountainous region covering seven municipalities. Defended by 5,000
troops, it is a virtual mini-state _ with a Muslim court, a
military academy and a college offering courses in Islamic studies
and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Within its perimeter, armed guerrillas carrying M-16 rifles roam
freely among students, farmers and veiled women in traditional
Muslim attire.
</P>
<P>
   At the military academy, veteran fighters listened to a lecture
on the importance of ``secrecy and surprise'' and ``favorable
terrains'' in battles before taking a break for their afternoon
prayer.
</P>
<P>
   In the college, Muslim students studied Arabic in a classroom
divided by a plastic sheet _ one side for men, the other for women.
</P>
<P>
   The MILF claims to have full control of the 37-square-mile area,
which has a civilian population of 20,000. Along lush green
mountains, 50-caliber machine gun emplacements stand ready against
attack by helicopter gunships or jet fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Benjie Midtimbang, director of the MILF's military academy,
boasted that the rebel army, which once used hit-and-run tactics,
can now go head to head with the Philippine military in
conventional warfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are no longer adopting guerrilla warfare,'' he said. ``We
seldom step backward now.''
</P>
<P>
   The movement attracted international attention early this year
when it was reported that the MILF had purchased 3,000 anti-tank
rockets through funds received from Saudi fugitive Osama Bin Laden,
the alleged mastermind of the bombing of two U.S. embassies in East
Africa last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden is reported to have visited MILF territory, but the
rebels deny it, although Al Haj Murad, chief of staff of the MILF's
military wing, says Bin Laden has given humanitarian aid to Muslim
communities in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
   The MILF's ties to the wider Muslim world are strong. The
rebellion has received military aid from Libya. During the Afghan
war, MILF volunteers fought alongside mujahedeen. Hashim himself
spent years in exile in Egypt and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   The Mindanao Muslims, who call themselves the Bangsa Moro
nation, organized the Moro National Liberation Front to demand
independence from the Philippines in the late 1960s. Then-President
Ferdinand Marcos responded with a brutal military campaign that
caused more than 100,000 deaths over two decades. Most of the
casualties were Muslim civilians.
</P>
<P>
   A split within the MNLF between top leaders Nur Misuari and
Hashim led to the creation of the MILF in 1977. The MNLF signed a
peace accord with former President Fidel Ramos in 1996, and Misuari
was elected governor of a new autonomous region running on the
ticket of Ramos' party.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptical of autonomy, Hashim's movement has refused to give up
the fight for independence. The MILF signed a cease-fire agreement
in 1997, and Estrada has pursued peace talks begun by Ramos, but
there are still skirmishes between rebel and government forces.
</P>
<P>
   About four-fifths of Mindanao's population of 17 million is
Christian. The MILF wants to create a new state out of the Mindanao
provinces and municipalities where the island's estimated 3 million
Muslims are the majority, including territories now covered by
Misuari's autonomous government.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no solution to the problem in Mindanao except the
granting of independence,'' said Murad.
</P>
<P>
   The Estrada administration hopes to persuade the rebels to
accept some form of autonomy, similar to the agreement reached with
the MNLF.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to maintain the territorial integrity of the
Philippines,'' said presidential spokesman Jerry Barican. ``We are
hoping for a permanent solution.''
</P>
<P>
   But the talks have bogged down. Murad complains that Estrada is
unpredictable, has no experience negotiating with rebel groups and
his machismo doesn't help the process.
</P>
<P>
   When the peace negotiations stalled last year, Estrada declared:
``If they want war, then war it is.'' According to Murad, that was
interpreted by some local Philippine military commanders as a
signal to launch offensives, and fighting broke out.
</P>
<P>
   Hashim doesn't place a lot of trust in Estrada.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that what he is doing is the work of an actor,'' the
MILF chairman said, shaking his head. ``Many times, he just talks,
and it seems that he is not seriously thinking of what he's talking
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Presidential spokesman Barican defended his boss this way: ``He
perhaps doesn't use diplomatic language, but he is very frank and
open.''
</P>
<P>
   The fear is that Estrada's unbridled frankness could lead to
full-scale war. The peace talks could collapse, or the intermittent
encounters between MILF and government forces could escalate.
</P>
<P>
   That threat reverberates throughout the island. ``We hope it
doesn't happen,'' said Joji Ilagan-Bian in Davao City, Mindanao's
trade and commercial center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business will slow down,'' said Ilagan-Bian, chairwoman of the
Mindanao Business Council, which represents the island's chambers
of commerce. ``Investors will pull out.''
</P>
<P>
   War could reverse Mindanao's dramatic rise. The once-backward
region is now booming. Private investment has increased almost
tenfold since 1990, to about $2.2 billion in 1998, according to
Growth with Equity in Mindanao, a think tank funded by the U.S.
Agency for International Development.
</P>
<P>
   The island accounts for more than one-third of the Philippines'
agricultural output and close to 50 percent of its domestic food
trade. Estrada considers Mindanao critical in the fight for
national self-sufficiency that he calls ``food security.''
</P>
<P>
   The island also plays a key role in the prosperous East Asian
Growth Area, a special economic zone covering regions in Indonesia,
Brunei and Malaysia. Known as EAGA, it boasts a market of 45
million people.
</P>
<P>
   EAGA has made life rosier for Hadja Bulawan Abangon, a Muslim
merchant in Davao who sells Indonesian batik dresses, shirts and
jewelry. She said her monthly earnings have doubled since the zone
opened in 1994. And she's worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``The MILF are Muslims, but why are they causing trouble?'' she
asked.
</P>
<P>
   In Ilagan-Bian's opinion, if war erupts, the fighting would
directly affect only the small area in southwest Mindanao where the
MILF is active. But the conflict would reinforce the old images of
Mindanao as the Philippines' Wild West, too unstable for long-term
investment.
</P>
<P>
   And the MILF could broaden the conflict by setting off bombs in
Davao and other cities, analysts warn.
</P>
<P>
   The prospects for peace hinge in part on the success of the new
autonomous government under Misuari. Hashim said he and his
movement are not impressed with the progress so far.
</P>
<P>
   The government promised billions of pesos in infrastructure
investment for such projects as airports and irrigation systems,
but many of the projects are stalled. Misuari accuses the
government of blocking the release of funds, while the government
blames his inexperience as an administrator.
</P>
<P>
   With cash-strapped Manila caught in the region's economic
crisis, Mindanao's development could come too slowly to satisfy the
rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not simply a case of not resuming war,'' said Raphael
Lotilla, an undersecretary for socioeconomic planning, ``but how do
we manage the expectations of the MILF? What kind of development
can be introduced?''
</P>
<P>
   Mindanao historian Rudy Rodil, who helped negotiate peace with
the MNLF, said the government has funded projects in MILF
territory, including irrigation systems and a nine-kilometer
mountain road connecting Camp Abubakar to the national highway.
</P>
<P>
   But veteran MILF fighter John Abubakar scoffed at the claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you seen any bulldozers or tractors intended for
development in our area?'' he asked. ``What we have seen are tanks,
armored vehicles. We hear the sound of helicopter gunships (and)
mortars. How can we believe that the government is sincere?''
</P>
<P>
   Murad, the MILF chief of staff, said that if the rebels settle
for less than independence and the government does nothing to
develop the area, they could lose popular support and become
irrelevant. In that case, ``some other group will pursue the
struggle, so there will be no peace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That may have happened already with the MNLF, some of whose
members are said to have joined the MILF. Then there's the smaller,
more radical Muslim group Abu Sayyaf, which has staged bold raids
against government troops and kidnapped foreigners for ransom. Last
month, Abu Sayyaf abducted two Belgian visitors. The MILF helped
negotiate their release.
</P>
<P>
   Walden Bello, professor of sociology at the University of the
Philippines, believes that the rebellion will continue until Manila
alters what he calls the ``colonialist'' attitude that sees the
Moros as second-class citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless there is major change, I think Mindanao will be caught
up in permanent insurgency,'' he said. ``That will always be a very
unstable area.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 0300EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 03:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1444 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHILIPPINES-ESTRADA-S     07-07 2412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILIPPINES-ESTRADA-SFCHRON(FIRST </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ACTOR PRESIDENT LIFTS HOPE OF PHILIPPINE UNDERCLASS
</HEADLINE>
 OF TWO PARTS)   &HT;     By BENJAMIN PIMENTEL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANILA _ Julie Angeles was describing life under Philippine
President Joseph Estrada when an oncoming train interrupted her.
</P>
<P>
   Casually, she stepped off the tracks three feet from her
scrap-wood shack in Manila's San Andres Bukid district and waited
for the train to pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been some change but life is still hard for us, the
poor,'' said the 32-year-old widow, who washes clothes to support
her four children. ``Erap won't be able to solve everything.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Estrada, a former movie star known by the nickname
``Erap,'' derived from the Tagalog word for ``buddy,'' won a
landslide victory campaigning on the slogan ``Erap Is for the
Poor.''
</P>
<P>
   But playing champion to the country's impoverished masses is a
tough act, even for a president who used to play a street-smart
defender of the underdog in action movies.
</P>
<P>
   Although Estrada has turned the national spotlight on the
poverty issue like no other Philippine president, and he remains
popular with the poor, he has yet to make an impact on their lives.
There are some who fear he never will _ because of his ties to the
rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a president who undoubtedly still has a strong base
of political support,'' said Temario Rivera, a political science
professor at the University of the Philippines. ``But Erap is
hobbled by his ties to vested interests _ his cronies.''
</P>
<P>
   About a third of the archipelago's 75 million people live in
extreme poverty, many in slums along railroad tracks or on garbage
dumps.
</P>
<P>
   Their numbers have grown during the past year. A decline in
manufacturing resulting from the Asian financial crisis cut tens of
thousands of jobs. Unemployment is at 9 percent, up slightly from
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Estrada intends to reduce the number of poor Filipinos to a
quarter of the population by the end of his six-year presidency in
2004. He speaks often of ``poverty eradication'' and ``food
security.''
</P>
<P>
   Estrada's anti-poverty campaign has three major components:
</P>
<P>
   -- Agrarian reform. Two-thirds of the poor live in the
countryside, where they work as sharecroppers for large landowners.
</P>
<P>
   -- Infrastructure improvements. An $80 billion program focuses
on water systems, housing for the poor and communal irrigation.
</P>
<P>
   -- Job creation. The government is counting on an annual
economic growth rate of 5 percent during the next six years to
boost employment.
</P>
<P>
   To stimulate social reforms at the grass roots, Estrada turned
to the country's network of nongovernmental organizations. They
helped convene the National Anti-Poverty Commission, which drafted
his social reform agenda and is supposed to implement it.
</P>
<P>
   But Ana Maria Nemenzo, the commission's vice chairwoman,
acknowledges that the war on poverty is stalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't done much,'' she said. ``It's been frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Estrada, the panel's chairman, puts the blame on lack of money
and the fact that the economy is still reeling from the Asian
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, the economy has remained stable in the 12 months
since he took office, growing by 1 percent in the first quarter of
1999 after declining for almost a year.
</P>
<P>
   The inflation rate _ 7 percent _ is down slightly from the
previous year. And the Philippine Stock Market has doubled in size
to about 2,500 points since Estrada took over in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But Estrada's government faces a $1.8 billion deficit this year
alone, and the country is paying off a $48 billion foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very frustrated when I cannot give and implement
projects which I promised to the people due to lack of funds,''
Estrada said at a May forum for journalists in Manila. ``All
projects boil down to funding.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the anti-poverty campaign gets under way, it will be
implemented by a sluggish government bureaucracy in a political
culture vulnerable to corruption and shallow theatrics.
</P>
<P>
   Similar campaigns failed in the past because politicians
diverted funds to their own pockets or used them for insignificant
projects, such as bus stops or basketball courts in rural barrios,
that served as billboards for their ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   And in many cities and towns, alleviating poverty has been a
quid-pro-quo exercise: Politicians give the poor handouts and
expect loyalty _ and votes _ in return.
</P>
<P>
   Estrada, who was a township mayor for 17 years before becoming a
senator, comes from that tradition. ``Erap doesn't understand
poverty,'' said journalist Sheila Coronel, who has written
extensively on the Philippine presidency. ``The most he has done
for the poor was the handouts he gave as mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics say he's doing it again as president. One of the goals
of his anti-poverty campaign is to identify and assist the 100
poorest families in every town and city. The plan has been called
paternalistic and vulnerable to manipulation by unscrupulous local
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous,'' said Pancho Lara, a social activist and
consultant to the Department of Agrarian Reform. ``If you target
only 100 families, they're the only ones you'll reach.''
</P>
<P>
   Estrada has served notice that he won't tolerate corruption,
delivering a tough ``don't test me'' warning to friends and family
members. The statement has come back to haunt him. He has awarded
government positions to relatives and friends, many of whom are
either unqualified or have shady backgrounds _ or both.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Jimenez, a presidential assistant for Latin American
affairs, is wanted by the U.S. Justice Department for tax evasion
and making illegal campaign contributions to President Clinton's
1996 re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Another presidential consultant, Cecilia De Castro, a relative
of Estrada's, was accused of being involved in a much-publicized
corruption scandal. She allegedly was linked to a group that tried
to bribe government officials to release about $5 million for a
textbook project. The case is still under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   With Estrada in power, some of his friends _ including powerful
industrialists and landlords with links to former strongman
Ferdinand Marcos _ appear to have gained more influence.
</P>
<P>
   The most prominent, Eduardo Cojuangco, was a Marcos crony who
fled with the late dictator during the 1986 People Power uprising.
Cojuangco's holdings, including the prestigious San Miguel Corp.,
one of the country's biggest and oldest companies, were then
confiscated by the government of former President Corazon Aquino.
</P>
<P>
   Cojuangco returned to the Philippines several years ago and has
been trying to recover his assets. Just days after Estrada took
office, Cojuangco was elected chairman of San Miguel's board. The
move was not illegal, but critics called it a corporate coup _ and
evidence that Cojuangco felt he had nothing to worry about with
Estrada in power.
</P>
<P>
   Lucio Tan, owner of a major cigarette company, who  &LR; also had
links to Marcos. Tan was a target of tax evasion cases filed by the
administration of former President Fidel Ramos. But after Estrada
took over, the cases either stalled or individual claims against
Tan were drastically reduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``The face of cronyism is clearly in place in the first year of
the Erap administration,'' said Rivera, the political science
professor.
</P>
<P>
   He believes Estrada inevitably will find himself torn between
the reforms he espouses and the interests of his friends.
</P>
<P>
   An important test case is the government's plan to redistribute
some 21/2 million acres of land to the rural poor, part of an
agrarian reform program that began in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   But the Congress, which is dominated by landowners, slashed this
year's budget for land acquisition by about 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Cojuangco, who owns some of the country's biggest plantations,
has joined other landowners in pushing an alternative plan that
would allow them to maintain control of their estates through joint
ventures with poor farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Estrada's agrarian secretary, Horacio Morales, a respected
social activist, has been critical of such schemes, fearing that
the farmers would be manipulated into signing unfair agreements.
</P>
<P>
   While the dispute has yet to be resolved, leaders of
nongovernmental organizations were chagrined when Estrada praised
Cojuangco's plan, calling him the ``godfather of land reform.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Will the likes of Morales and the younger,
development-oriented technocrats and legislators prevail over the
likes of Cojuangco?'' Rivera asked. ``Being a product of the old
corrupt order, Erap is constrained. I think that the powerful
conservative cronies have the upper hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Estrada vehemently denies that he coddles cronies. But the
perception has cost him some support with the middle class, the
nongovernmental organizations and the business sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``If before we were open to the possibility that this is going
to be a truly pro-poor government, we have more doubts now,'' said
Corazon Juliano-Soliman, chairwoman of the Caucus of Development
NGOs, a major coalition. ``The inconsistency is more and more
pronounced.''
</P>
<P>
   Businessman and political analyst Antonio Gatmaitan, who is
based in Makati City, the country's financial center, spoke of ``a
growing unease'' among some business leaders about Estrada. He
described Estrada's relationship with entrepreneurs and investors
as ``cool and a bit distant.''
</P>
<P>
   Estrada's controversial lifestyle has not helped.
</P>
<P>
   Middle class Filipinos frown at his reputed penchant for
late-night partying, which has made him miss appointments. He
showed up late at a dialogue at the presidential palace in May with
Manila bishops and businessmen. Then he was impatient when a
businessman expressed concern over layoffs and other social costs
of opening the economy to foreign competition.
</P>
<P>
   While past presidents were college educated, formal in demeanor
and given to flowery speeches in English, Estrada, a college
dropout, speaks street Tagalog and has an aversion to long
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Estrada asks his critics to be patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everything is going the right way now,'' the president
said recently. ``I've only been 10 months in office. Please give me
a little more time. I cannot solve this all at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   That request resonates with poor Filipinos, including many in
San Andres Bukid, where most people don't have steady jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is just starting, but there are many people attacking
him,'' said 41-year-old Cesar Valdez, standing on the same train
tracks that Julie Angeles had stepped off. ``Erap is for the
masses.''
</P>
<P>
   And the masses are for him. Estrada's approval rating was 67
percent in March, up from 61 percent last September, according to
the Social Weather Station, a respected research organization in
Manila. Analysts attribute the high numbers to his lingering
celebrity as an actor who once played working-class heroes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very challenging because the president is someone who
connects with the poor more than we do,'' said Juliano-Soliman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He personifies the macho savior of the poor. The poor identify
with him. ``But that does not make him a good president.''
</P>
<P>
   Some nongovernmental organization leaders see opportunities for
small but meaningful changes under Estrada. De la Torre says the
president has budding instincts for social reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``His deepest source of personal frustration is that he doesn't
feel he's got a solid working program for the poor _ which speaks
of his value system,'' De la Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Estrada has made an impact already just by moving poverty to
center stage in Philippine politics. In past administrations, the
issue was peripheral to the goals of industrialization and rapid
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Coronel, the journalist, said Estrada has forced other
politicians to pay attention to the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pointed out the voting power of that constituency and, in
the future, other leaders will have to address that constituency,''
she said. ``It furthers the democratic process.''
</P>
<P>
   But businessman Gatmaitan warned that ``the day of reckoning is
approaching when people will be less forgiving in their criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``That goes for the underclass that supports him,'' Gatmaitan
added. ``Their patience may be much longer _ but, eventually, he
has got to deliver.''
</P>
<P>
   If Estrada doesn't, more poor Filipinos could turn to a
historically attractive alternative: the armed left.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, the communist New People's Army thrived in poor
barrios and slums through its militant Robin Hood tactics of
attacking rich landlords and organizing workers and peasants. Now
weak and divided, the armed left has no real chance to grab power,
but analysts believe it can stir unrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Estrada is competing with the left as far as that constituency
is concerned,'' Gatmaitan said. ``There are discordant notes that
are beginning to appear.''
</P>
<P>
   An entire chorus can be heard in a slum neighborhood called Tent
City, located across the street from the House of Representatives
in Quezon City.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Tent City's 600-plus squatter families campaigned and
voted for Estrada, who they hoped would help them find new homes
and jobs. But the community's leaders accuse the president of
breaking his promise to give each family about $4,000 for
relocation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Erap is for the poor? It's been the reverse _ Erap is for the
rich,'' said Moises Talisik, the chairman of Tent City's community
organization.
</P>
<P>
   His sentiments are shared by others in Tent City.
</P>
<P>
   As rain fell outside her makeshift shack, Felicidad Roque, 75,
wiped tears from her sunburned face as she spoke of how she helped
campaign for Estrada _ but got nothing in return.
</P>
<P>
   She pointed to where rain leaks into the cramped home she shares
with her son and granddaughter. Sometimes, they eat only once a
day, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day, one eat _ I don't lie to you,'' she said, choking
back tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people here are suffocating,'' she said. ``I hoped for big
things from Erap _ but that hope is broken.''
</P>
<P>
   Near the busy street dividing the poor community from the
government compound on the other side, Lito Buta, a 21-year-old
construction worker, sat with neighbors and relatives in front a
white coffin. Buta said it contained the the body of his mother,
who died of an ulcer at age 62.
</P>
<P>
   ``She often went hungry, and we couldn't afford medicine,'' he
said. ``I really idolized Erap. But he's not listening to us now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
