 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No. 436 -- July 7, 1999 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY -- No. 436 -- July 7, 1999 We are offering
the following articles for sale. Please contact us for availability
your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. WHAT THEY SAY ABOUT STANLEY KUBRICK After Stanley Kubrick
died in his sleep of a heart attack on March 7, even the New York
tabloids reported the news with an auteur slant, headlining the
director's generally bleak view of life. Words like ``secretive,''
``reclusive,'' ``strange,'' ``mysterious'' and ``cold'' were
repeatedly used to describe him. On the eve of the U.S. opening of
his last film, ``Eyes Wide Open,'' starring Nicole Kidman and Tom
Cruise, the people who knew Kubrick best reminisce. By Peter
Bogdanovich. From The New York Times Magazine. Full-length (9,000
words) + edited article available.
_____________________________________________________________ 2.
SALMA HAYEK GOES 'WEST' Mexican actress Salma Hayek's profile will
be higher than ever as she opens opposite Will Smith and Kevin
Kline in ``The Wild Wild West,'' this summer's comedy/action film.
Hayek encountered a lot of prejudice in her career at first, as she
could not speak English well. Now she harnesses her
visibility-raising energies on behalf of Mexico. By Jay Carr. From
The Boston Globe. 1,400 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 3.
THE DARK SIDE OF HOLLYWOOD'S SUPERTHIN,
</P>
<P>
   SUPERSTARVED SUPERSTARS Many actresses have recently been
photographed looking rake-thin. And if you think they look skinny
on camera (which traditionally adds 10 pounds,) you should see them
in real life. ``Boys with breasts,'' Tom Wolfe calls them. ``This
may be politically incorrect, but I find it fascinating how ugly,
starved, bony women can be considered attractive,'' says Dr. Arnold
Anderson, director of the Eating Disorders Unit at the University
of Iowa College of Medicine. Writer/producer David Kelley, who
created hit TV shows ``The Practice'' and ``Ally McBeal,'' is well
aware of the controversy over his stars' appearance. By Ivor Davis.
1,300 words + photos. (N/A Great Britain and Australia.)
_____________________________________________________________ 4.
THE BIG PICTURE For super-sharp 3D images, throw away your lens. A
three-dimensional computer image of a plastic dinosaur might be the
first step towards bringing viewers television in true 3D. You
won't need a front row seat for your favourite sports game when you
can have a 3D viewer at home. By Charles Seife. From New Scientist
magazine. 500 words. (N/A Brazil, Australia, New Zealand.) 5.
AMATEUR HOUR For centuries, it has been noted that musical training
is a helpful background for training in the sciences. It is no
accident that the 92 contestants in the first Van Cliburn
International Piano Competition for Outstanding Amateurs included
lawyers, professors, computer whizzes, a TV anchorman, plus
numerous doctors and medical specialists. (The winner, Joel
Holoubek, is a French coin dealer.) By Richard Dyer. From The
Boston Globe. 1,900 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 6.
RAY PARK : YOU'VE GOT MAUL ``Han Solo always got the girl and he
was very cool,'' says Ray Park, the soft-spoken Scottish actor who
portrays Darth Maul in ``Star Wars : The Phantom Menace.'' (Darth
Maul is the Sith Lord audiences love to hate.) ``I wanted to be Han
Solo, but with Jedi powers and a lightsaber. It's a bit ironic that
I'm playing Darth Maul. ... I didn't think Darth Maul would be so
big.'' Only 24 years old, Park holds a second-degree black belt and
is a veteran of numerous martial arts competitions. By Ian
Spelling. 1,000 words + photos.
_____________________________________________________________7.
DONNY OSMOND COMES TO TERMS WITH FAME At the height of his fame,
singer Donny Osmond had a squeaky-clean, bright-and-smiling image,
but few people have witnessed the flip side : a history of
self-doubts, debilitating fears and serious reversals of fortune.
Now the 41-year-old father of four is setting the record straight
with his candid autobiography ``Life Is Just What You Make It.'' By
Christopher Loudon. From TV Guide Canada. 1,300 words + photo. Q&AMP;A
format.
_____________________________________________________________ 8.
JACKIE COLLINS' HOLLYWOOD LIVES With 200 million copies of 21 books
sold in more than 40 countries, Jackie Collins is the McDonalds of
the bestseller lists. The sister of actress Joan Collins, Jackie
has been a star in her own right since she published her first
novel, ``The World Is Full of Married Men,'' in 1968. Such
provocative tales as ``Hollywood Wives'' give her readers the
delicious illusion of inside knowledge on Tinseltown's dirty little
secrets. By Ivor Davis. 1,300 words + photos. Q&AMP;A format. (N/A
Great Britain and Australia.)
