<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 09:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1573 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES0     07-07 0233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: The all-purpose hater
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his brief but effective bid for the Let's Hate Each Other
Hall of Fame, Benjamin Nathaniel Smith materialized in one
frightful moment as a kind of equal-opportunity assassin. In the
few minutes it took, Smith killed two people and wounded nine the
other day in the region around Chicago. The blacks, Jews and Asians
he gunned down were all the same to him.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 21-year-old Smith had achieved some small notoriety
for bigotry at Indiana University, pitifully little is to be
learned from Smith's brief killing spree. He is dead by his own
hand, and cannot discuss his grievances. In a free society, no
screening procedure was likely to have found and stopped him.
</P>
<P>
   There is a lesson in this. And that is that the religious and
racial minorities Smith targeted _ and those he lacked time for _
don't have a moment to bicker with each other. The result so far
seems to have been a debilitating struggle over who gets to occupy
society's lowest rung. No one has time. We need to see an assault
on one as an assault on all, not someone else's private lookout.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
Email: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
