<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, July 7, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Thursday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORMONS-GAYS (San Francisco) _ A city official has asked the
city attorney and the state attorney general to determine whether
the Mormon Church is illegally campaigning for an upcoming
initiative on the California ballot to ban gay marriage. By RACHEL
GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   REAGAN-PLATE (Sacramento, Calif.) _ A drive to put a picture of
Ronald Reagan on a special California license plate is speeding
through the Democratic-controlled state Legislature with only muted
complaints. About 7,000 people already have signed up to pay $50
for the new Reagan plates, which would carry a portrait of the
former president and support the Ronald Reagan Presidential
Library. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   MASSAGE-PARLORS (San Francisco) _ The city of San Francisco may
transfer regulation of massage parlors from the police department
to the public Health Department. Among other things, it would
eliminate the requirement that people applying for a permit to
practice massage disclose all criminal convictions. As it stands,
the Police Department turns down applicants who had a
prostitution-related conviction in the past five years. By ULYSSES
TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   O'BRIEN-OBIT (Berkeley, Calif.) _ Mark O'Brien, a Berkeley
writer whose determination to work and live independently from an
iron lung was captured in an Academy Award-winning documentary, has
died. He was 49 years old. By KATHLEEN SULLIVAN.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAREERS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Next time you hear politicians
speak, listen to what they're not saying, former Texas Gov. Ann
Richards says. One thing that Richards didn't say, for example, is
that hearing the unspoken is one of the most useful career skills
you can have. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES/LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SINGLES-THERAPY (San Francisco) _ Through the ages, men and
women have found diverse places to meet _ at bars, through friends,
on the Internet, at work. And now, at the shrink's. Psychotherapist
Jim Wolfe is recruiting singles through a Web site for a new
concept that is part group therapy, part workshop and part dating
service. By ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MANGO-MOOD (Houston) _ You can devour a mango plain, or you can
glamorize it and present it at a formal banquet. In between are the
many moods of mango. By ANN CRISWELL. (Photo available on the NYT
database.)
</P>
<P>
   LEAN-PORK (Houston) _ In the case of new leaner pork, pigs did
fly. New Smithfield Lean Generation pork tenderloins are the result
of English hogs being flown to the United States and used for
selective breeding. By ANN CRISWELL.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTLAND (Edinburgh, Scotland) _ Scotland is a land where past
and present blend as smoothly as a barrel of fine Scotch whiskey.
There's still a wee bit of the Highland rebel in the hearts of many
loyal Scots. And for visitors, the rich traditions, coupled with
the green hills, the rocky Highland crags and the friendly people,
and their wonderful accent, that makes it such an entice land. By
KAREN DAVIS.
</P>
<P>
   With: SCOTLAND-IF-GO
</P>
<P>
   SCOTLAND-CLANS (Newtyle, Scotland) _ Scottish clans are the
stuff of romance. That's evident from the popularity of historical
romantic novels with Scottish themes and films such as ``Rob Roy,''
and the television's time-traveling ``Highlander'' series. By KAREN
DAVIS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-MINOR-LEAGUES (Pittsfield, Mass.) _ In two books, ``In the
Ballpark: The Working Lives of Baseball People,'' published in
1998, and the upcoming ``The Ball Players: Life and Culture in
Professional Baseball,'' anthropologist George Gmelch has trained a
scholar's eye on the national pastime. Getting there wasn't easy
for this onetime player who would never made it to the big leagues.
By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-EXPOS-SURVIVAL (Montreal) _ There is a growing sense in
Montreal that the Expos organization is knowingly, willingly and
gladly sabotaging baseball. The mission, some people believe, is
twofold _ low attendance could help the club convince voters that a
new stadium must be built for it in downtown Montreal, or the
franchise will be sold and relocated, probably to Charlotte, N.C.
By TIM REYNOLDS.
</P>
<P>
   X-GAMES (San Francisco) _ The X Games went over big here and
aren't about to go anywhere _ at least not in 2000. An initial
two-year agreement between ESPN's Extreme Games and San Francisco
will ``most assuredly'' bring the games back to San Francisco next
year. By GREGORY LEWIS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ If you want a reality check in
Cleveland or Chicago, you probably talk to a machinist or
meatpacker on the next bar stool. How do you do a reality check in
San Francisco, the city where reality checks bounce? Basically, you
have to check into all kinds of people's reality. One of my reality
checks is occasionally having breakfast with Wally Shore. By ROB
MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Thousands of San Franciscans and
millions of ESPN viewers may have viewed the extreme sports X Games
as totally awesome and cool; Alan Young wishes they'd never come
near him or his business. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   WONG-COLUMN (Oakland, Calif.) _ Saturday's final game in the
Women's World Cup between the United States and China ought to be
sporting entertainment at its finest. Our world being what it is,
however, it could also be the latest loyalty test for Chinese
Americans and perhaps many other Asian Americans. By WILLIAM WONG.
</P>
