A1625 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KELSO-COLUMN08-COX     07-07 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The time is out of joint in Austin
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ If you're new to Austin, you should know that
this city has its own unique time zone. It's pretty simple. Austin
Standard Time or Austin Daylight Saving Time both run about 15 or
20 minutes off from Central Standard or Central Daylight Time.
</P>
<P>
   Being a punctual person, the unofficial Austin time zone is
annoying to me. But it's like the heat. It's a part of living here
that you have to accept or go crazy, and here's how it works:
</P>
<P>
   If it's, say, 8 p.m. in Dallas, Houston or Lubbock, it's around
7:40 or 7:45 p.m. in Austin. Or at least Austinites think it is.
This is why everything starts late in Austin, and everybody runs
late. Because of AST and ADST, people think they have more time
than they actually do.
</P>
<P>
   When you go to a club in Austin for the 10 o'clock set, don't be
surprised if the band doesn't show up on stage till around 10:15 or
10:20 p.m. If you go out to dinner and the maitre d' tells you
there will be a 20-minute wait, there will be a 40-minute wait.
</P>
<P>
   This is all because of our unusual little time warp here in this
mecca of tardiness. I don't know what causes it. I suspect it's the
mold spores.
</P>
<P>
   So I was not surprised when I arrived at World Gym in Southwest
Austin around 9:45 Monday morning to find the place closed, even
though the sign on the door said the gym was supposed to open at 8.
</P>
<P>
   The building was locked, the lights were turned off, and there
was nobody around _ except for the angry group of about 40 club
members in workout clothes waiting out front to get in.
</P>
<P>
   These people were like your lips after water-skiing _ real
chapped. They were mad. They clearly did not understand the concept
of Austin Standard or Austin Daylight Savings Time.
</P>
<P>
   I felt sorry for the poor guy named Russell, I'd guess in his
mid-20s, a World Gym employee who showed up in front of the place
to appease the crowd at about 10 minutes to 10 a.m. _ with no key
to open up the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``My name is Russell,'' said Russell, confronting a tough
audience. ``I overslept. I'm sorry.'' Then Russell announced
someone was supposed to be coming soon with the key.
</P>
<P>
   ``How far away does he live?'' a gal in the crowd asked in a
get-a-rope tone of voice.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these people had been waiting in front of the building
since 8 in the morning, and they were in a
``I'm-writing-a-letter-to-the-corporate-office'' mood. I could
sympathize with them. No one had told them about AST or ADST.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so World Gym screwed up. But let's put this in Austin time
zone perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say that running this gym requires a crew of about, oh,
say, a half-dozen minimum-wage college kids who spent the previous
night going from one Sixth Street dive to the next, enjoying bands
with names like Mange Puppy.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say each gym employee saw two different bands, and each
band started playing 20 minutes late. Add it up. That's four hours
accumulated ADST late time right there.
</P>
<P>
   So when World Gym finally threw open its doors at 9:55 Monday
morning, when it was supposed to open at 8, it was really opening
about two hours early. By Austin standards. Y'all need to know
these things if you're going to remain sane in this town.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso's writes humor columns for the Austin
American-Statesman. He can be reached at (512) 445-3606 or at
jkelso(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
