r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN08-COX     07-07 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delivering the message of `contraceptive equity'
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ In many ways, our society seems light years away
from 1968, when Mary Brookins started working at Planned Parenthood
of the Miami Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Her job title back then was ``information specialist,'' but what
she really did was walk door to door in neighborhoods all over the
city to inform women about the agency and its services. Most women
had never heard of Planned Parenthood. Many had never heard of the
birth control pill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the husbands didn't want anything to do with birth
control, so the women didn't make appointments,'' Brookins
recalled. ``But some came to see us, after all, on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   How times have changed since then _ or have they? Last week, as
Brookins retired from Planned Parenthood after 31 years, The New
York Times published a front-page story on ``contraceptive
equity.'' The gist of the story: It is only now, as Viagra is being
quickly included in many insurance plans, that state legislatures
are taking a taking a serious look at coverage for women's
contraceptives.
</P>
<P>
   When she started working at Planned Parenthood at the age of 32,
Brookins had recently given birth to her sixth child _ unplanned _
and needed the extra income, as well as an excuse to get out of the
house. She had no idea that for the next three decades she would be
a foot soldier in the battle for contraceptive equity _ a battle
that, as The Times' story indicates, is far from over.
</P>
<P>
   ``That little blue pill gave the birth control pill that's been
around for 40 years great crediblity as an issue,'' California
Senator Jackie Speier told The Times.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the Viagra controversy, more than a half-dozen
states have passed legislation requiring carriers that cover
prescription drugs to pay for contraceptives for women.
</P>
<P>
   It figures. It just figures. Even at $10 a pop, that little blue
pill gains instant respect from insurance companies. For four
decades, meanwhile, women have paid out of pocket to control their
childbearing destiny.
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of thing that makes us younger feminists want to
spit tacks. ``Back in 1968, when Mary started, everyone thought of
birth control as this great beginning, an opportunity for women to
control their lives, and how many children they have,'' said Noreen
Willhelm, director of special projects for the Planned Parenthood
Association of the Greater Miami Valley. ``Thirty-one years later,
it is still women's responsibility, and it has been women's
financial responsibility. Women's health care expenses are
astronomical compared to men, largely because of birth control
pills.''
</P>
<P>
   Brookins takes the long view. Having spent nearly half of her
life at Planned Parenthood, Brookins can see how much progress has
been made, as well as how much remains to be achieved. ``She's the
most calm, unflappable person,'' Willhelm said. ``She's everybody's
hero.''
</P>
<P>
   Brookins noted with a chuckle, ``I had six children in eight
years; I didn't know anything about Planned Parenthood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love all my kids,'' she added, ``but I'd have found a way to
space them better, if I could. Back then, even if you had six
children, your husband had to sign for you if you wanted your tubes
tied.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first year on the job, Brookins persevered with her
door-to-door message despite the slap-in-the-face racism of some of
the people who answered the door, like the woman who said, ``It's
people like you who are having all these babies.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, she assumed various roles at Planned Parenthood,
from clinic manager to her most recent role as family planning
assistant. She was there during the dynamic tenure of Faye
Wattleton, who in 1978 went on to become president of the Planned
Parenthood Federation of America. ``She was wonderful,'' Brookins
recalled. ``I knew she was going places, but I didn't know she was
going there.''
</P>
<P>
   As a family planning assistant, Brookins served as a patient
advocate, helping them with paper work and accompanying them to
appointments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love my job,'' she said. ``I love having the contact with
the young girls. I'm like a mother figure to them. I can talk to
them when they're upset, and listen to them. Some girls just tell
you everything you don't want to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Brookins has been invaluable, Willhelm said, as someone who
``sees what real life is about, someone with incredible amounts of
experience, both personal and professional.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that work must go on without her. Brookins plans to enjoy
retirement in her Lower Dayton View home, spending time with
husband Edward, with her nine grandchildren and five
great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   A lot has happened in the 31 years since Mary Brookins took her
message door to door.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that it's not only the obvious disparity in
insurance companies' coverage that's bringing about change. The New
York Times reported that ``the speedy success of so many
contraception bills reflects only good timing but also the rising
power of women in state legislatures.''
</P>
<P>
   Their work is possible because of front-line people like Mary
Brookins, who delivered the message door to door, patient by
patient, day by day.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
