r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN08-COX     07-07 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Whether you crank it or zip it, car radios are a part of life
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Late one summer night in 1949, my father fell
asleep coming home from work and ran his V-8 Ford into the back of
a parked car.
</P>
<P>
   He wound up in the hospital, and from that point on we wound up
with radios in our family cars.
</P>
<P>
   Radios did not come as standard equipment on all cars in the
1940s. Still, they hardly were novelty accessories.
</P>
<P>
   My father thought car radios were a waste of money. There was
nothing on the radio that he wanted to hear.
</P>
<P>
   That made absolutely no sense to me. Practically everything I
wanted to hear was on the radio. Most importantly, there was good
music on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   Even before rock 'n' roll, radio stations catered to the music
preferred by young people. Those stations were required listening
for teens and pre-teens. I was a pre-teen.
</P>
<P>
   I have no idea who made the requirement that young people must
listen to certain radio stations. I don't know how we all
simultaneously knew that certain radio stations were required
listening, but we knew.
</P>
<P>
   One clue might have been that any radio station our parents
couldn't stand was one we probably should like.
</P>
<P>
   My father particularly disliked disc jockeys and their
insufferable attempts at humor. ``Insufferable'' was his word.
Although I could see he had a point, I still thought
``insufferable'' was a particularly harsh assessment of DJs who
were directing their energies toward entertaining young people.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he thought it preferable to suffer the intellectual
indignities of a car radio than risk falling asleep again at the
wheel late some night on the way home from work.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the next struggle was getting him to turn the darn
thing on whenever he drove us to town, on Sunday evening drives or
on family vacations.
</P>
<P>
   By himself, he evidently preferred his own thoughts to the
distractions of a radio. With others, he might still have preferred
his own thoughts except he generally encouraged family
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   I would have much preferred to listen to the radio than be asked
about my school studies or be drawn into discussions about world
events that were more like school lessons.
</P>
<P>
   When I got old enough to buy my own cars and live on my own, I
always installed the biggest, loudest most technologically advanced
sound systems that I could afford. That'll show him.
</P>
<P>
   Even years after his death, I remember wondering what my father
would think when I crammed enough speakers and amplifiers into my
car to make me fear that the lug nuts would vibrate off the wheels.
</P>
<P>
   When CD players first came on the market, I rigged one up in my
car. That's was several years before CD players were manufactured
for automobiles. The contraption never did work very well because I
couldn't cushion it enough to prevent it from skipping. But it was
roundly hailed as an extremely powerful technological marvel when
the car was sitting still.
</P>
<P>
   In my house, I installed a stereo system that would knock the
spackling off the ceiling. That was years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago I purchased another car. A longtime friend who
lives in another city asked if I had the car long enough to put in
a state-of-the-art sound system.
</P>
<P>
   No, I said, the radio that came with the car is good enough for
me. I never turn it on.
</P>
<P>
   Why? I don't know why.
</P>
<P>
   It was never a conscious decision, but over the past several
years I kept turning down the volume. Finally, I quit turning the
darn thing on.
</P>
<P>
   I now prefer my own thoughts to the distractions of a car radio,
tape deck or CD player. It's strange how things turn out.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: rnethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
