<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The fireworks may be over, but grill's still the way to go
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even now that Memorial Day and the Fourth of July have come and
gone, the siren song of sizzling meat over hot coals continues
inexorably to draw us outdoors. While eating on porches, patios, at
poolside or under a favorite backyard tree adds immeasurable
enjoyment to the season, there are certain necessary adjustments
that should be made to summerize your kitchen routine.
</P>
<P>
   Upgrading your grilling skills, revising your summer recipe file
and food safety factors should all be considered as the season
swelters on. Here are a few Internet sites to get you up to snuff
for a summer of outdoor dining.
</P>
<P>
   MAKE-AHEAD RECIPES
</P>
<P>
   A warm and cozy kitchen may be a magnet during winter, but a
cook can get pretty lonely in a hot summer kitchen while everyone
else is outdoors enjoying themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Preparing as much food as possible ahead of time and getting
familiar with make-ahead and quick-fix summer salads will go a long
way in getting you out of the kitchen and outdoors to join the fun.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Find a long list of cool summer salads
</P>
<P>
   /Health/HEALTHYWAY
</P>
<P>
   /recsal.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Add spice to your summer salad repetoire. Visit www
</P>
<P>
   .intlfoods.com/recipes/med
</P>
<P>
   /ssmenu.htm for a list of easy-to-fix Middle Eastern salads.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  You don't usually think of salads coming from the grill, but
at www.homearts.com/cl
</P>
<P>
   /cooking/08grilf1.htmgrilling you'll find just that.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Summer is the season of marinades. See www4.enter.net
</P>
<P>
   /rburk/sauce-rub-marinade
</P>
<P>
   /marinades/ for info and recipes.
</P>
<P>
   GRILLING
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Whether you're an old pro who just wants to refresh your
techniques or a novice to the coals, here are some grilling sites
you may want to check out:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  An excellent all-in-one-site is Better Homes and Gardens
Online's Summer Cooking School, at www.bhg.com/food
</P>
<P>
   /grillschool. It covers everything from flare-ups to smoke
enhancers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  To sign up for a weekly e-mail newsletter with the latest on
outdoor grilling, see bbq.about
</P>
<P>
   .com/index.htm?COB
</P>
<P>
   &QC; home&AMP;PID &QC; 2757.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Meat isn't the only thing meant to be grilled. At www
</P>
<P>
   .vegkitchen.com/grilling
</P>
<P>
   .html, there's a list of grilled vegetable recipes that sound
just as savory as the meatier kind.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For a taste of the real thing, check out ``TexasCookdotCom''
at 216.71.126.168.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If it has to do with outdoor cooking, you'll find a related
link at members.aol.com
</P>
<P>
   /BBowman646/bbq.html. It has information about pit cooking and
solar cooking, and enough barbecue and grilling recipes to last the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   SAFETY CONCERNS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Get up to speed on summer food safety with the U.S. Department
of Agriculture site ``Cooking Up a Safe Summer'' at
ificinfo.health.org/insight
</P>
<P>
   /safesum.htmUong. It also provides a phone number to call so you
can ``grill'' the experts on summer food safety. Call the USDA's
Meat and Poultry Hotline at 1-800-535-4555.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  And don't forget about dealing with insect stings, at allergy
</P>
<P>
   .mcg.edu/ALK/tips.html.
</P>
<P>
   Makes servings Preparation time: minutes Cooking time: minutes
</P>
<P>
   Brushed with a citrusy chili-infused dressing, this salad's
succulent fresh sweet corn, zucchini, yellow squash, and tomatoes
acquire robust flavors from the grill. Lightly grilled
cheese-and-onion-filled flour tortillas round out the meal.
</P>
<P>
   Chili-Lime Dressing:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons lime juice
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   Vegetables:
</P>
<P>
   4 small ears yellow corn
</P>
<P>
   2 6-ounce zucchini
</P>
<P>
   2 6-ounce yellow squash
</P>
<P>
   4 small ripe plum tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   4 6-inch-round flour tortillas
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons shredded sharp Cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 green onion, cut crosswise into 2-inch lengths, then
lengthwise into thin strips
</P>
<P>
   Lettuce leaves
</P>
<P>
   Heat outdoor grill. Coat grill rack with nonstick vegetable
cooking spray.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare Chili-Lime Dressing: In jar with tight-fitting lid,
combine oil, lime juice, chili, cumin, salt, and garlic powder
until well mixed. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Carefully pull back husks from corn, leaving them attached at
base and remove all the silk. Brush corn with some Chili-Lime
Dressing. Place corn on tray while preparing other vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Cut zucchini and squash crosswise in half. Cut halves lengthwise
into 1/4-inch-thick slices. Place vegetables on tray with corn.
Brush slices on both sides with some dressing. Cut tomatoes
lengthwise into halves and brush with some dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Place corn about 4 inches from medium-hot coals so husks hang
off the edge of the grill. Using the husks to turn ears
occasionally, grill corn until kernels are lightly browned _ 8 to10
minutes. Transfer corn to a tray once it's done.
</P>
<P>
   Grill zucchini and yellow squash, turning occasionally until
lightly browned _ 2 to 3 minutes. As they are done, transfer to
large tray. Grill tomatoes, turning once, just until softened _ 1
1/2 to 2 minutes in all. Transfer tomatoes to tray with other
vegetables and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Heat flour tortillas, one at a time, over low coals, turning
often just until softened _ 15 to 20 seconds. Sprinkle 2
tablespoons shredded cheese and one fourth of green onion strips on
half of tortilla. Fold tortilla in half and grill just until cheese
softens. Fold tortilla in half again and transfer to tray with
corn. Repeat to heat, fill, and fold remaining 3 tortillas.
</P>
<P>
   Just before serving, line 4 plates with some lettuce leaves. Cut
corn kernels off cobs and set aside. Arrange one-fourth of zucchini
and yellow squash alternately with each other on one side of each
plate. Mound corn in center and garnish with tomato halves and
folded tortillas. Pass remaining Chili-Lime Dressing.
</P>
<P>
   _ From www.homearts.com/cl/cooking/08grilf1.htmgrilling .
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 469 calories, 10 grams protein, 10 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, xx), 42 grams carbohydrates, 15
milligrams cholesterol, 469 milligrams sodium, 7 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Copper Penny Carrots
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings Preparation time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10-12 minutes Chilling time: 12 hours
</P>
<P>
   This is a terrific make-ahead salad for a crowd. The dressing,
which resembles a Catalina dressing, can be used on other salads as
well.
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds carrots, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 green pepper, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 10 3/4-ounce can condensed tomato soup
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon prepared mustard
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   In a large pan, cook carrots in salted boiling water until
crisp-tender, about 5-7 minutes. Rinse in cold water to stop
cooking. Arrange layers of carrots, green pepper and onion in a
container with a tight lid.
</P>
<P>
   Combine all remaining ingredients in a saucepan and bring to a
boil, stirring until thoroughly blended. Pour this marinade over
the vegetables, cover and refrigerate until flavor is absorbed, at
least 12 hours. Salad will keep for weeks in the refrigerator;
leftover marinade may be used again. _ From
bbq.about.com/index.htm?COB &QC; home&AMP;PID &QC; 2757
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 66 calories, 1 gram protein, less than 2 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 33), 15 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 124 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
