<HEADER>
A1665 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN     07-07 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Light ale for those with taste for brew
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Greg Kelly does more than play defense man for his
amateur hockey team. First he donated the team's name, the Laughing
Skulls. Then he began donating the after-game beer. Whatever his
contributions on the ice, you have to say Kelly's doing his part.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, the founder of Atlanta Brewing Co., maker of Red Brick
Ale, Laughing Skull pilsener and other beers, has made his hockey
mates a kind of test market. These are men who can still call
themselves young for a few more years (``most of 'em are in their
late 30s and early 40s''), expend more energy than the couch
potatoes arriving at middle age ahead of schedule, and guess what
their beer of choice is?
</P>
<P>
   ``Kelly's Lite is first, then Laughing Skull and then Red Brick
Ale,'' the team's provisioner of malts and hops proudly declares.
</P>
<P>
   It's been five years since Atlanta Brewing Co. debuted its Red
Brick Ale, one more craft beer among dozens of others. Kelly, a
former sales manager for Guinness, was intent on bringing craft
beer to Atlanta, but _ by his own admission _ he was no hophead. He
still isn't. What sells in Seattle and Portland doesn't necessarily
sell in Atlanta _ or it doesn't sell in the volume that will
satisfy someone who is first and last a businessman.
</P>
<P>
   While others were celebrating highly hopped ales from the West
Coast and elsewhere, Kelly couldn't help noticing how many people
nonetheless drank ``light'' beer. In fact, light beer, introduced
more than 20 years ago, now commands more than a third of the
market. If anything, its mass-market success threatens to embarrass
the very people who created it. Light beer was meant to be a brand
on the side, not a competitor to a company's flagship beer. Yet
Miller Lite outsells anything else the company makes. The once chic
Coors, a beer that was light-bodied to begin with, is outsold by
Coors Light.
</P>
<P>
   And, although no one's placing bets, Bud Light _ No. 2 with 11.4
percent of the market _ has been slowly gaining on none other than
the King of Beers, with 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   This is the market that Kelly, risking some of his credibility
as a craft brewer, has set his sights on. It's also one he has
found hard to penetrate.
</P>
<P>
   At a Publix grocery store last week, you could have found any of
the brand-name lights, along with less familiar ones. But you
couldn't have found Kelly's Light. At a party in my neighborhood
recently, you would have noticed one person after another sipping
lights from cans encased in Styrofoam _ but no one was drinking
Kelly's Light.
</P>
<P>
   What's surprising about this is that Kelly's Light is far better
than Bud Light, Miller Lite, Coors Light, Busch Lite, Michelob
Light, Natural Lite. It's the only light beer that actually tastes
like beer, and yet not many people besides a few amateur hockey
players know what it is.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Peck, who works at Mac's Beer &AMP; Wine in Atlanta, is among
those who have recommended it to customers shopping for a light.
``That beer actually has some malt quality to it, and it's not
watery,'' Peck says. Unlike most mass-market light, it's made
entirely from barley, with no additions of corn or rice. And the
stone brewing _ superheated stones immersed in the brewing kettle _
imparts a slight nutty flavor.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact is that most people don't ``shop'' for a light in
the way many would shop for a chardonnay or a cabernet sauvignon,
an India Pale Ale or a stout. They pick it off the shelves as they
do soda pop. It's a matter of stimulus and response. Eyes catch
familiar label, arm extends, hand grasps. Not a lot of gustatory
consideration goes into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found it harder than we expected,'' Kelly says. ``In a
lot of places, it hasn't been discovered yet.'' Kelly knew
light-beer drinkers bought the label more than the beer, but he
believed a light that was flavorful and well-made would find its
audience. Even so, Atlanta Brewing Co. has been careful not to
advertise the fact that Kelly's Light is an ale and not a lager.
``We were afraid it would frighten people off,'' Kelly says.
</P>
<P>
   But basic distinctions between ale and lager, talk of two-row
barley, the different properties of various hops _ light-beer
drinkers aren't interested. For these folks, beer's beer, and it's
to sip or guzzle but not really enjoy for its own sake.
</P>
<P>
   And in a calorie-counting culture, the lighter the beer, the
better. Assured of its ``lightness,'' many blithely assume they can
drink twice as much without getting drunk or fat. So they buy it in
``suitcases,'' big 12-packs and, now, 18 packs. Nothing light about
that.
</P>
<P>
   Light beers aren't for me, but they're obviously for many
people, from sweaty goalies to neighbors picnicking over barbecued
pig. I've often wondered why they didn't just drink a Coke _ it has
more flavor. (Ah, but no alcohol.) I wouldn't wonder that about
someone drinking a Kelly's Light. I might suggest he move up a
notch to Red Brick Summer Brew, whose malts and hops are
practically the same, but at least he has a taste for beer.
</P>
<P>
   PICK OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   John Maier not only likes to push the stylistic envelope with
his beers but have fun with them in other ways, too. ``What's this
Pacman yeast you use?'' someone asks him, reading the detailed
ingredients on the 22-ounce silk-screened ceramic bottle. ``Oh,
that's a joke,'' Maier says. ``It's just our proprietary yeast.''
</P>
<P>
   Other beers in the Rogue line commemorate friends and locals in
the Pacific coastal town of Newport, Ore., where Maier has won
medal upon medal for his individualistic beers.
</P>
<P>
   Brutal Bitter was brewed in honor of a friend and publican in
Portland, and quickly acquired a following in the Northwest. New to
Atlanta, Brutal Bitter is vintage Maier: hoppy, unfiltered, layered
with exotic malts, and in a stylistic category all its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to do a kind of Imperial Bitter,'' he says. He knows
there's no such thing, and laughs. He only means the equivalent in
a bitter to an Imperial Stout _ a beer at the apex of its style.
What resulted is one with the dryness and subtle maltiness of a
bitter, but also the hoppiness of an India Pale Ale. And yet you
wouldn't call it an IPA, and neither would you call it an Extra
Special Bitter. It's another Maier original, pleasingly bitter but
not really brutal ... not brutal enough, a fan might plead.
</P>
<P>
   From start to finish, Maier uses a single hop, an unusual
approach among craft brewers. But the Crystal hop, Maier says, is a
triploid, developed from the Hallertau, Cascade and Brewers Gold
varieties. The result is an ale with the citrusy character of the
Cascade but also the earthy, slightly spicy quality of the
Hallertau.
</P>
<P>
   The barley, imported from Britain, was malted on the floor in
the old-fashioned way, with a maltster raking over it continuously.
A pinch of wheat from France is added to the grist. And that Pacman
yeast, whatever it really is, imparts an estery fruitiness that's
disarming in a beer whose name tells you to brace yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
