<HEADLINE>
SEC INVESTIGATING HOW MICROSOFT CLASSIFIES ITS RESERVE REVENUES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DAN RICHMAN   
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A federal agency is investigating whether Microsoft
has been setting aside revenues in flush quarters to shore up
earnings reports in lean quarters, the Redmond company's chief
financial officer disclosed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   At a hastily called news conference, Greg Maffei said the
investigation by the Securities and Exchange Commission began
several months ago.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the SEC would neither confirm nor deny that an
investigation is under way.
</P>
<P>
   Maffei speculated that the investigation was triggered by a Jan.
14 story in The Wall Street Journal. That story related allegations
by Charles Pancerzewski, a former Microsoft internal auditor.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Journal story, Pancerzewski charged in a 1997
wrongful-discharge suit that Microsoft manipulated revenue reserves
totaling hundreds of millions of dollars to make its profits appear
more stable.
</P>
<P>
   The story says the suit alleges Microsoft put aside revenue in
healthy quarters to cover costs like future product returns and
promotional rebates, and added them back in during leaner quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Pancerzewski was traveling Wednesday and could not be reached.
His lawyer, Pete Vial, said Pancerzewski had been in Washington,
D.C., but said he could not confirm whether his client had spoken
with the SEC because of a confidentiality agreement in the
settlement of his lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our understanding is (the investigation is) related to
reserves and reserve policies,'' Maffei said Wednesday. ``Reviewing
the financial records of every company is certainly within the
SEC's practice. I wouldn't claim to know how common investigations
or inquiries into reserves and reserves policies are.''
</P>
<P>
   A company spokesman said this is the first time the SEC has
investigated Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of reserves is to reflect a company's true revenues
_ how much it will actually end up collecting in a given period if
customers return merchandise or fail to pay their bills.
</P>
<P>
   But these accounting practices do ``open up the door to earnings
management, if not done right,'' said Jack Ciesielski, who writes
the Analyst's Accounting Observer, a Baltimore newsletter on
accounting.
</P>
<P>
   In Microsoft's case, the company may have reserved too much,
which would mean that it may have understated its actual profits.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has set aside about $4 billion in what it calls
``unearned revenues'' as a result of the way it sells both its
Windows operating system products and its Office suite of software
applications.
</P>
<P>
   Maffei said he didn't know how long the investigation would last
and declined to provide further details. He said he believes the
investigation will have no material effect on Microsoft's business
or financial condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very happy with the current pace of business,'' he told
the conference call of analysts and reporters. ``I'm comfortable
that we're at least going to make analysts' estimates.''
</P>
<P>
   William Epifanio, an analyst at J.P. Morgan Securities, agreed.
``I'm not too worried about it yet,'' he said. ``They have a good
reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft stock closed Wednesday at $90.19, up $2.19.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC has been aiming to eliminate corporate manipulation of
earnings at least since last fall. In November 1998, the SEC's
chief accountant, Lynn Turner, told an accounting industry group
that the agency's division of corporation finance had formed an
earnings-management task force to coordinate and focus the SEC's
filing reviews on abusive reporting practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The division of enforcement has also stepped up their focus on
earnings management,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   One financial analyst expressed surprise upon hearing of the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft has been extremely conservative in its earnings
estimates _ based on what I know about them, it's hard to
believe,'' said Greg Bailes, an audit partner with
PricewaterhouseCoopers in Seattle. ``Anything done to smooth
earnings is not only unacceptable to the SEC but isn't even within
generally accepted accounting principles.''
</P>
<P>
   During Wednesday's news conference, Maffei disclosed the SEC
investigation after a lengthy recital of two changes being made to
accounting procedures at Microsoft. He denied the changes are
related to the SEC investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In one of those changes, Microsoft will reclassify how it
reports revenues and costs for four items: product support,
consulting services, training and certification of system
integrators, and fees for accessing the MSN Web site. Henceforth,
the customer receipts will be dealt with as revenue, and costs that
vary directly with revenue will be classified as cost of revenues.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the costs of the first three items were reported as
sales and marketing activities, and customer receipts were reported
as cost recoveries.
</P>
<P>
   The reclassification causes revenue to be 5.1 percent higher for
fiscal 1997, 5.4 percent higher for fiscal 1998, and 5.8 percent
higher for fiscal 1999 year to date than it would have been under
the prior model. Revenue from each of the four areas ranges from
$150 million to $300 million annually. In total, revenue for the
first three quarters of fiscal 1999 will be about $761 million
higher because of the reclassification, Maffei said.
</P>
<P>
   The second procedural change relates to accounting for unearned
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   To comply with a recent change in accounting rules, Maffei said
Microsoft will change the initial earned and unearned revenue
percentages and the timing of revenue recognition for its Windows
operating system software and Office productivity suite.
</P>
<P>
   These changes, both of which have been reviewed by the SEC,
together will create 1 cent of additional revenue during the
current quarter and the same additional amount in fiscal 2000,
Maffei said.
</P>
<P>
   This report includes information from The New York Times and
Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-01-99 0043EDT &QL;
