<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOW UPDATES ON NOTEBOOK MAY MEAN YOU BOUGHT A `PASSIVE-MATRIX'
DISPLAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DWIGHT SILVERMAN   
 c.1999 Houston Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I recently bought a notebook computer _ a Toshiba Satellite
4525 CDS. I am not happy with the way the screen updates.
Everything is very slow. Also, whenever the system has been idle
for a while, a Toshiba ad comes up as a screen saver. What can I do
to speed things up?
</P>
<P>
   A: In general, the displays on most notebook computers _ and
particularly ``value'' models, such as that one _ are not going to
be as peppy as those on desktops. Some displays are faster than
others, however.
</P>
<P>
   You didn't say whether the notebook you bought has an
active-matrix or passive-matrix (sometimes called a dual-scan)
display. However, from your description, I suspect it's
passive-matrix, and that may be your problem.
</P>
<P>
   Passive-matrix displays are, by nature, quite slow and are not
as bright as active-matrix screens. For example, if you try to play
a fast-paced game on a passive-matrix system, you'll see a lot of
ghosting and blurry images as the screen tries to keep up. With a
quality active-matrix display, the screen is virtually as speedy as
a traditional desktop monitor.
</P>
<P>
   With an active-matrix screen, each pixel on the display has its
own transistor controlling it. On a passive-matrix screen, one
transistor may control many pixels. Thus, the graphics are not as
nimble. I generally recommend that users avoid passive-matrix
portables _ though they are likely to be much less expensive. The
active-matrix version of the 2545 is $500 more than the
passive-matrix model, according to Toshiba's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   If, however, you have the active-matrix model, you can try
turning off all the background programs _ virus checkers, etc._ and
reduce the number of colors in the display to 256. (Right-click on
the open desktop, choose Properties, then Settings. Click the
colors drop-down box to change it to 256.) While this won't look as
good as having high or true color, it will speed up your display.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When I boot my PC up, at the end I get the following message:
CSUSEM32 has performed an illegal task. I then click OK and nothing
seems different about my computer. What is CSUSEM32?
</P>
<P>
   A: This file is part of CleanSweep, the utility from Symantec
(previously from Quarterdeck) that lets you remove programs and
clutter from your hard drive. The file is part of a component
called the Usage Monitor that tracks to see how often you use
programs. It uses the information to recommend seldom-used programs
you might be able to remove from your drive to gain space.
</P>
<P>
   It runs in the background (along with another component of
CleanSweep that watches for software installations), and if you
read these pages regularly, you know how I feel about background
programs _ they are more trouble than they are worth. My
recommendation would be to turn this off. There should be a setting
to do so in CleanSweep's preferences. Or, if it places an icon in
the Startup folder, remove it from there.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, you can usually determine what program a component
like this belongs to by doing a search for it with the Windows Find
feature (right-click on the drive in My Computer, choose Find). The
folder that holds it should give you a clue as to the parent
program.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Dwight Silverman can receive
electronic mail via the Internet. Address your comments and
questions to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000
and enter access code 1001. &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR; XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
