<HEADLINE>
HERE'S WHY TO HAVE EUDORA LOVE AFFAIR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DWIGHT SILVERMAN   
 c.1999 Houston Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ask any techno-pundit to name the ``killer app'' for the
Internet, and you're likely to get one of two answers _ e-mail or
the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   You can put me in the first camp. While e-mail may not be as
sexy as the Web, it's the most-used _ and the most useful _
application. For most folks, it's the one thing that makes them
understand the importance of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic mail is responsible for bringing distant families
together, speeding negotiations, even running whole businesses. It
has completely changed our expectations of how quickly people
communicate with each other. The U.S. Postal Service earned the
derisive nickname of ``snail mail'' because e-mail is just so
darned fast.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most popular e-mail programs is Eudora. One of the
first e-mail programs available for Macintosh and then Windows
Internet users, it was initially free. Qualcomm, best known for
communications equipment and cellular phones, develops it, and it's
definitely a sideline.
</P>
<P>
   While there's still a free version, known as Eudora Lite, it's
the commercial version, Eudora Pro, that is the star.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
OTHERS PALE TO EUDORA
</P>
<P>
   I've been a serious Eudora user since I first got on the
Internet in 1992. I've tried every other e-mail application that's
come along since, including Netscape's Messenger; Microsoft's
Exchange, Outlook Express and Outlook; America Online's e-mail
component; even Pegasus, the other top free mail software program.
None of them comes close.
</P>
<P>
   The latest version of Eudora Pro, 4.2, is the best yet. It's an
update to the version you're most apt to find on store shelves,
which is 4.1, for about $39. But its new features are so compelling
and so well done that this is more than just a minor upgrade. It
puts Eudora Pro in a class by itself.
</P>
<P>
   However, let me add a caveat. I would not recommend Eudora Pro
4.2 for everyone. It has a fairly complex set of features, and the
interface can seem cluttered to some. If you like your e-mail
software simple, you probably don't need this.
</P>
<P>
   But if you are a relatively sophisticated e-mail user _ perhaps
one who is overwhelmed by e-mail volume, or who has multiple e-mail
accounts _ then Eudora Pro can make life much easier.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it does all the things you'd expect a modern-day
e-mail program to do _ displays HTML-based and Rich Text Format
e-mail messages; includes a comprehensive address book; works with
either POP3 or IMAP e-mail servers; includes a spell-checker; and
will launch a browser when you click on a Web address in an e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
EUDORA COMPLETES THOUGHTS
</P>
<P>
   Among the new features in 4.2 is auto-complete, which will
attempt to finish an e-mail address as you type it. It gets this
information from recently entered e-mail addresses. If Eudora
thinks the address being entered is similar to several different
ones, it offers a drop-down box list to let you choose.
</P>
<P>
   Automatic spell-checking also has been added. As you type,
misspelled words are underlined in red. If you want to add special
words _ such as names or unusual spellings _ to the dictionary,
Windows users can right-click and choose Add from the menu that
appears. (Macintosh users would click-and-hold with their
inadequate, one-button mice!)
</P>
<P>
   Qualcomm also has beefed up the search functions in Eudora Pro.
You can now perform complex searches using Boolean terms, a type of
standard search language. If you use your e-mail folders like I do
_ as a kind of database for information you've received from others
_ this feature makes it much easier to find that needle in the
haystack.
</P>
<P>
   Eudora has always had one of the best systems for filtering
e-mail into folders as it comes into your system. This can be used
to pre-organize information or to banish junk e-mail. But fans of
filters know there's a problem _ sometimes you forget to look in
those folders to see what's new.
</P>
<P>
   Eudora Pro 4.2 solves this with a unique solution that turns
text into speech. You can turn on a feature that will let the
computer read aloud the subject lines of e-mail being filtered into
specific folders. This can get annoying if you turn this on for a
folder that receives a lot of mail _ if you filter spam, you
wouldn't put this on your trash folder, for example _ so it's best
used for mail that's very important.
</P>
<P>
   Eudora Pro also is the best e-mail software for managing
multiple accounts. Using a drop-down box available in the From:
field in the composition window, you can change the identity of the
sender. For example, you can pull in an e-mail from an account at
work and answer it via a personal account.
</P>
<P>
   If you already own Eudora Pro 4.0 or later for Windows or
Macintosh, you can upgrade for free to 4.2 by downloading an
updater at www.eudora.com. There's also a demo version of Eudora
Pro 4.1 at that same address, if you want to check out the look and
feel of the program.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000 and enter
access code 1001. &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
