<HEADLINE>
AFTER SKIMMING THE MANUAL, SETTLE DOWN WITH THE BOOK  
 FCC OFFICIALS SAY MERGER ISN'T A DONE DEAL  
 A GOOD NERD THESE DAYS MUST BE ABLE TO STREAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With each new generation of software, user manuals get skimpier
in inverse proportion to the addition of new features. The user
manual for MS-DOS in 1982, for example, was 486 dense pages; the
manual for Windows 95, with tens of thousands more features, was a
stingy 95 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Software companies insist that they now produce programs so
intuitive that manuals are unnecessary, and that besides, built-in
help systems are far more useful.
</P>
<P>
   But sales of aftermarket computer books say consumers think
otherwise. In fact, Microsoft Office 2000, the recent upgrade of
the world's best-selling suite of business software, is turning out
to be the 1999 Full Employment Act for writers, editors and
publishers of computer books.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Bennett, president of MacMillan Publishing USA, says his
company has 56 titles dedicated to Office 2000 _ 14 percent of all
its titles this year. IDG Books, best known for its ``... for
Dummies'' series, is also unleashing a torrent of Office 2000
books. The lure for both companies is the estimated $1.1 billion
consumers will spend on technical books this year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, tying a book's fortunes to software sales can be risky.
``Windows 98 met with a resounding ho-hum,'' Bennett noted.
</P>
<P>
   _ ROB FIXMER
</P>
<P>
   Two FCC Officials Say Merger Isn't a Done Deal
</P>
<P>
   The media coverage of last week's merger-approval deal between
the staff of the Federal Communications Commission and SBC
Communications Inc., which is trying to acquire Ameritech Corp.,
rubbed at least a couple of the five commissioners the wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   Though at least some news organizations, including The New York
Times, said the agreement meant that SBC had cleared a big hurdle
in winning approval for the merger, two of the commissioners said,
in effect, ``Not so fast.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Contrary to the suggestion of some press accounts, neither we
nor the full commission has indicated even tentative approval of
the SBC-Ameritech transaction or conditions,'' Commissioner Gloria
Tristani, a Democrat, and Commissioner Harold Furchtgott-Roth, a
Republican, said in a statement on Wednesday. ``Indeed, to do so
before the record has even closed would be improper.''
</P>
<P>
   According to people close to the commission, the deal was
negotiated by the agency's staff under the supervision of the FCC's
chairman, William Kennard, and Ms. Tristani and Furchtgott-Roth
were apparently upset by the assumption that the other four
commissioners would simply rubber-stamp the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   That said, few people in Washington expect the deal to get voted
down after the commission hears public comments on the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tristani is considered a strong supporter of Kennard, while
Furchtgott-Roth is often at odds with the chairman. But people
close to the commission said that Ms. Tristani and Furchtgott-Roth
often join forces on procedural matters.
</P>
<P>
   _ SETH SCHIESEL
</P>
<P>
   A Good Nerd These Days Must Be Able to Stream
</P>
<P>
   A generation ago, they might have been the budding engineers who
built model rockets or maintained the high school's lone film
projector as screwdriver-carrying members of the AV Club. A decade
ago they would have been the geeks setting up the school computer
lab.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, the tekkie nerds have gone online and multimedia
_ at least judging from three Dearborn (Mich.) High School students
who were in New York last week. The young men attended the
Streaming Media convention at the Sheraton New York, where they
demonstrated last term's project from their advanced video
production course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get the kids who are the weirdos,'' their avuncular,
68-year-old teacher, Russ Gibb, said approvingly as three of his
students demonstrated a wearable computer with a Webcam that they
and others in Gibb's class built for $5,500.
</P>
<P>
   Besides functioning as a standard personal computer, the system
contains a wireless transmitter that can send streams of video and
audio data to a Web-server computer. When worn in the halls and
classrooms of Dearborn High, the unit can transmit everything the
wearer hears and sees to the school's Web site
(www.dearbornschools.org/wdhs) _ potentially useful for letting a
sick schoolmate monitor a class from a home computer, for example.
</P>
<P>
   The computer runs the Linux operating system favored by the
technically adept of all ages who wish to make an anti-Microsoft
statement. But the machine also runs Microsoft Windows 95. That's
because most multimedia software is designed to work with Windows,
explained one of the students, Brandon Gheen, whose business card
lists his title as Student Computer Engineer.
</P>
<P>
   One of his card recipients at the conference was Anthony Bray,
general manager of Microsoft's Streaming Media Division, who said
he was impressed with the students' project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Audio, video and animation are the second wave of Internet
technology,'' Bray said. ``I expect that a large percentage of
innovative new content, services and applications will come from
young entrepreneurs, and these three kids give us a glimpse of that
future.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Gheen pronounced Bray ``cool.'' But he and his
fellow students, Patrick Murray and Alex Fisher, subsequently
critiqued what they see as the shortcoming of Microsoft's own
multimedia strategy _ with a specificity and technical vocabulary
too abstruse for a model-rocket-era reporter to process in a single
stream.
</P>
<P>
   Had they shared these opinions with the Microsoft executive?
``There's a time and a place for everything,'' Fisher said, wise
beyond his 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   _ TIM RACE
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-04-99 1814EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
