<SLUG> BC-ELECTRONIC-GAMES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWLY RELEASED GAMES PUT TO TEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ First, the Electronic Entertainment Expo swept
into Los Angeles in late spring with oodles of game stuff. Then, a
series of new games washed in for the summer. Here are breakdowns
on some of the recent releases: &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
PC
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Midtown Madness (Microsoft) _ Take a VW Beetle, a Caddie, a
city bus or other vehicles on a crazed run through downtown Chicago
in this somewhat offbeat racing title. Navigating a digital version
of the real Chicago streets is pretty cool (though I'd love to see
what they'd do with a  &UR; !ital! &LR; real driving town such as Los
Angeles). Online-only ``cops and robbers'' is one of five play
modes. Stoplights are for wimps.
</P>
<P>
   Yoot Tower (Sega PC) _ The terrific successor to SimTower comes
out on PC, after an initial release on the Mac. Build hotels,
resorts or office buildings, decide what mix of businesses to have,
and try to grow your business into a five-star destination. A
well-done, if Japan-centric, simulation.
</P>
<P>
   Milton Bradley Board Games and Parker Brothers Card Games
(Hasbro Interactive) _ Computer versions of Hasbro board games such
as Pente, Parcheesi, chess and checkers, and card games such as
Spades, Cribbage, Mille Bornes and Rook. The best aspect is
Internet play, a boon for slow-twitch game lovers who need a
partner to play Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Aliens Versus Predator (Fox Interactive) _ Fox took a couple of
its meanest movie killer species, and turned them into the basis
for a first-person shooter. Oh, and throw in a particularly nasty
colonial marine as your third option in this winner-survives-all
killfest. You'll need an accelerator card, however, to see all the
cool high-end graphics that have been packed into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Links Extreme (Microsoft) _ Who would have thought the Big Mouse
in Redmond has a sense of humor? They've taken the excellent Links
LS golfing game and transformed it into an entertaining
alternative, complete with exploding golf balls, deathmatch play
and monsters on the fairway. Tee this one up when you get kicked
out of the country club.
</P>
<P>
   Extreme Boards and Blades (Head Games) _ An extreme sports title
for skateboarders and in-line skaters. Decent graphics, fun ska
soundtrack, a fair variety of tricks.
</P>
<P>
   Extreme Rodeo (Head Games) _ If getting hurled off an angry
Brahma bull seemed fun but a tad unhealthy, try this title. Six
different events, 35 animals, force feedback and multiplayer
options. So-so graphics, but definitely different.
</P>
<P>
   Extreme Winter Sports (Head Games) _ Snowboard, ski and
skimobile over a variety of tracks. Decent gameplay, but given the
Web links to merchandise, more marketing than game.
</P>
<P>
   Machines (Acclaim) _ A 3-D strategy game based on a sci-fi
future where humans are gone, but their machines clank on, fighting
to control the galaxy. The 3-D views let you get much more
involved. Nice array of units, fun special weapons, and even room
for very non-machine-like subtleties such as espionage and
sabotage. Bad news: It requires a hardware accelerator.
</P>
<P>
   Puzzle Pack (Sega PC) - Sega pulls together three basic puzzle
games _ Dr. Robotnik's Mean Bean Machine, Columns III and Lose Your
Marbles. Nothing fancy here, but this inexpensive title should
appeal to those who like to impose order on a chaotic universe. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
Mac or Mac/PC hybrid
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Railroad Tycoon II (Gathering of Developers) _ Build your own
railroad empire in this awesome simulator moved over to the Mac
after a best-selling run on the PC side. Really a wonderful game
that forces you to balance commercial considerations with
challenges such as train accidents, the Franco-Prussian War and
Jesse James robberies. Best of all, ``sandbox'' mode lets you build
to your heart's content. Beautiful and very cool.
</P>
<P>
   Imperialism II (SSI) _ Head one of eight colonial powers
beginning in 1500 and develop your resources and trade
relationships; explore, conquer and develop the New World; ally
with or fight other Great Powers and generally build an empire upon
which the sun never sets. Politically incorrect, but well done,
with excellent depth, good graphics and a nicely handled turn-based
approach.
</P>
<P>
   Sports Car GT (Electronic Arts) _ A terrific-looking racing sim,
with more than 50 cars, and the ability to download more. Eight
U.S. and European tracks, lots of customization and terrific
graphics. Mia, the Search for Grandma's Remedy (Kutoka Kids) _ A
truly gorgeous educational game for children ages 5 to 9 that
follows a winsome 3-D mouse on her quest through a house and its
yard to find medicine for her ailing granny. I was knocked out by
the graphics, and my children enjoyed the adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Freddi Fish 4: The Case of the Hogfish Rustlers of Briny Gulch
(Humongous Entertainment) _ Another terrific educational game for
children ages 3 to 8 from Humongous, who seems to do these things
pretty well. Freddi has to find the hogfish, and a great deal more,
in an adventure that also builds logic and puzzle-solving skills. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
Playstation
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 3Xtreme (989 Studios) _ Take your pick of in-line skating,
skateboarding or freestyle biking in this extreme sports racing
title, with a little bit of fighting as part of the gameplay. Fun
combat racing game, with bonuses for great tricks.
</P>
<P>
   Street Fighter Alpha 3 (Capcom) _ And the hits (and kicks) keep
coming. The market for fighting games seems inexhaustible, and this
one, chock-full of characters and combos from the durable Street
Fighter franchise, gives all the brawling choices you could want.
</P>
<P>
   Centipede (Atari/Hasbro Interactive) _ The latest classic arcade
to be updated, the result is great, with a 3-D perspective and
adventure mode that are excellent additions to what was always an
insanely addictive game. For the tragically nostalgic, the arcade
version is included (no quarters needed). &UR;  &QL; 
Nintendo 64 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Star Wars Episode 1 Racer (LucasArts) - As with the movie, the
game is very fast and fluid, particularly with the Expansion Pak
memory upgrade. It initially plunks you in the movie's most
exciting sequence, the rocket pod race, then provides a wide
variety of other courses to challenge you. You'll be hard-pressed
to move up without canny piloting and smart equipment upgrades. A
must for ``Star Wars'' fans, pretty close to that for racing fans.
</P>
<P>
   Lode Runner 3D (Infogrames) _ The venerable side-scroller gets
an extra dimension, and remains a fun, if slow-paced puzzler,
complete with red-robed mad monks, bombs and blasters, and dozens
of levels to work through. If you liked earlier versions of Lode
Runner, you should enjoy this one.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr.'s Slugfest (Nintendo) _ A great game that takes
excellent advantage of the N64's graphics power. Create your own
player _ heck, your own roster _ and play through a wide variety of
game options, authentic parks, weather effects, even a home-run
derby. Good controls, too. There's also an excellent Game Boy
version of the game for up to four people.
</P>
<P>
   A Bug's Life (Activision) _ The well-done game from
Pixar/Disney's massive animated film hit comes to the N64
relatively intact. This version looks good, and it handles much as
the PlayStation and PC versions do. N64's limits have forced some
changes, including interstitial mini-bonus rounds. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Game Boy
</P>
<P>
   Barbie Ocean Discovery (Mattel) _ The world's biggest toy
company makes a first foray into the handheld market for girl
gamers with an underwater adventure where Barbie solves puzzles,
mazes and other challenges to recover a lost treasure. It looks
great and is a nice change of pace from the blast-away crowd, but
it didn't hold my 8-year-old (Barbie-loving) daughter's interest
for long.
</P>
<P>
   The Smurfs' Nightmare (Infogrames) _ Hefty Smurf has to solve
puzzles and gather objects to wake his fellow short blue people
from their bad dreams. A color-only Game Boy title, my son in
particular loves this challenging little adventure, though adults
with a high tolerance for blue can enjoy it as well.
</P>
<P>
   Prince of Persia (Red Orb) _ The classic adventure puzzler hops
to Game Boy, and in good form. You have to figure out how to work
your way through fiendishly challenging dungeons without getting
smushed, speared or run through.
</P>
<P>
   V-Rally Edition '99 (Infogrames) _ A color-only racing game with
good variety in everything from weather conditions to tracks, as
well as official cars from several big-name racing teams. This
title is actually a great fit for the Game Boy Color.
</P>
<P>
   Conker's Pocket Tales (Nintendo) _ Nintendo's in-house game
wizards at Rare Ltd. have come up with this hybrid
action/adventure/role-playing game featuring a squirrel. Kids
should adore this one, and it sprawls far and wide. Recommended. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
