<HEADER>
A1682 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-FIBER-CHANNEL-TEC     07-07 1376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-FIBER-CHANNEL-TECH-ART-935&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN DATA LINKAGE, IT'S SPINOFF VS. PARENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ H.K. Desai, president and chief executive of
Qlogic Corp., has a ready answer when asked what he thinks of his
competitor, Emulex Corp. ``In my culture,'' quips Desai, a native
of India, ``we are not allowed to say bad things about our
parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Qlogic was indeed part of Emulex until a 1994 spinoff, and even
today the companies occupy adjacent buildings in Costa Mesa,
Calif., sharing a courtyard, a conference room and a Ping-Pong
table. But parent and child are now becoming head-on competitors in
one of the hottest new areas in computer data storage.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies are vying for leadership in fiber channel
technology, a new industry-standard approach to high-speed data
transfer between computers and separate data-storage disk drives.
With corporations needing ever faster access to larger amounts of
data, particularly to run Web sites, fiber channel sales look set
to soar.
</P>
<P>
   The shares of both companies, in fact, have already soared.
Qlogic stock has rocketed from less than $14 a year ago, closing
Friday at $139.50, while Emulex shares have zoomed from less than
$6 to Friday's close of $103.
</P>
<P>
   Other fiber channel companies have also captured investor
enthusiasm. Brocade Communications Corp., a San Jose, Calif.,
company that makes switches for networks that connect disk drives
to computers, went public at $19 a share on May 24. On Friday, its
shares closed at $103.75.
</P>
<P>
   Fiber channel is viewed by many in the computer industry as the
likely successor to the existing, longtime standard known as the
small computer systems interface _ written inelegantly as SCSI and
pronounced even more inelegantly as ``scuzzy.'' As its name
implies, fiber channel uses optical fibers for high speed
transmission, although there is also a more limited version that
uses copper wires.
</P>
<P>
   Fiber channel allows data to flow at 1 billion bits per second,
somewhat faster than SCSI. But its real advantage is flexibility.
SCSI is limited to 15 data storage devices, all within a few yards
of one another. Fiber channel can connect hundreds, and the disk
drives can be as far as six miles away from the computer.
</P>
<P>
   That flexibility is allowing corporations to link disk drives in
what is being called a storage area network, or SAN.
</P>
<P>
   With SCSI systems, each data storage device, usually an array of
disk drives in a single box, is connected to a single computer that
is known as a server and might be shared by many users. With a SAN,
multiple servers can connect directly with any disk drive array,
avoiding bottlenecks and providing redundancy in case one server
malfunctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more of the storage is going into mission-critical
applications _ things connected to the Internet that have to be
available 24 hours a day,'' said Robert Gray, a research director
at International Data Corp., a market research firm in Framingham,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   EMF Associates, a market research and consulting firm in Half
Moon Bay, Calif., projects overall sales of fiber channel equipment
to mushroom to $23 billion in 2002 from $3.5 billion in 1998. Much
of that will be for the data storage devices themselves. Another
big part will be switches that direct traffic between drives and
servers in the storage area network, such as those made by Brocade,
Ancor Communications of Minnesota and Gadzoox Networks Inc., a San
Jose, Calif., start-up company.
</P>
<P>
   Qlogic and Emulex make circuit boards known as host adapters,
which enable computers to be connected to fiber channel networks.
That is still a relatively small part of the business, worth about
$80 million last year, according to International Data.
</P>
<P>
   But those sales are expected to grow to $800 million by 2002.
And for small companies like Qlogic and Emulex, with annual
revenues around $100 million, that is a big market indeed. Right
now, they are the leaders along with Jaycor Networks Inc., a
privately held company in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Qlogic and Emulex did not see themselves as competitors when the
spinoff occurred. Qlogic was the semiconductor division of Emulex,
a company that originally made disk storage products for Digital
Equipment Corp. minicomputers. But Emulex got out of that business
in the late 1980s and began selling circuit boards to connect
printers to networks. It decided it no longer needed its own
semiconductor division, and so it cut loose Qlogic.
</P>
<P>
   Emulex has had the tougher time of the two. With its other
businesses shrinking, Emulex bet its future on fiber channel,
bringing out its first products several years ago. But only
recently has the growth from its fiber channel products been enough
to offset declines in its other businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The company had revenues of $18.2 million in the quarter ended
in March, up 21 percent from $15 million a year earlier. But sales
of fiber channel products more than doubled, to $11.2 million, and
accounted for 62 percent of total sales. Net income was $1.36
million, compared with a loss from restructuring charges a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Qlogic _ the ``Q'' is said to stand for quality or quickness _
was making chips and circuit boards for the SCSI system.
</P>
<P>
   Desai, who was Qlogic's head of engineering, left in May 1995,
unhappy with the company's direction. Three months later, with the
company losing money, he returned as chief executive. He ended
retail sales and began development of fiber channel products.
</P>
<P>
   Profits have risen for 15 consecutive quarters and Qlogic raced
past its former parent in sales and market value. Qlogic has a
market capitalization of $2.5 billion, compared with Emulex's $840
million.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Qlogic's fiber channel business accounted for only $7.3 million
of its $35.1 million in revenues in the March quarter. It does not
break out profits by product line, but Desai said the fiber channel
business was profitable. And even though the SCSI business is still
growing, the fiber channel business is growing faster, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is enamored of fiber channel. Adaptec Inc., the
leader in the SCSI business, sold its fiber channel business to
Jaycor Networks, although it retains a small stake in Jaycor.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Frymyer, a spokesman for Adaptec, said that two new data
input/output technologies under development could compete with
fiber channel. One is Future I/O, supported by Compaq Computer,
Hewlett-Packard, IBM and other companies. Another is Next
Generation I/O, supported by Intel Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Another risk for Emulex, Qlogic and Jaycor is that big computer
and disk drive makers might decide to make their own adapter cards,
as Sun Microsystems and Hewlett-Packard are doing to some extent,
rather than buy from outside suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   Right now there is plenty of business for both Qlogic and
Emulex, and they say their rivalry is friendly. ``It's more like a
family type of feuding,'' Desai said. ``We still have a lot of
respect for each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, with their businesses so clearly converging, one
wonders whether the spinoff was necessary in the first place. But
the executives express no regrets. ``I don't think we'd be where we
are today if we hadn't been independent companies,'' said Paul
Folino, the president and chief executive of Emulex. ``It allowed
us to get there faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, for shareholders it has been a good deal. An owner of
one share of Emulex worth $12 before the spinoff would now own one
Emulex share and two Qlogic shares worth a total of $382.
</P>
<P>
   Executives also dismissed any thought of combining again. In any
case, that will get harder. Qlogic, in need of more space, is about
to cut the final apron strings by moving to a new, larger
headquarters elsewhere in Orange County. Parent and child will
continue to compete in the marketplace but no longer at the
Ping-Pong table.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-04-99 1736EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 1251EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
