u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-COLLEGE-BOOKS-ONL     07-07 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COLLEGE-BOOKS-ONLINE-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKSELLER IS READY TO OFFER TEXTBOOKS ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By LISA GUERNSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An online bookshop has a new offer for college bookstores that
are struggling with the fickle business of textbook sales: Why not
let us sell those books for you instead?
</P>
<P>
   The company, Varsitybooks.com, plans to announce this week that
it has signed contracts with nearly a dozen small universities,
colleges, preparatory schools and distance-education programs to do
just that.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the arrangements mean that schools are completely
closing their book-selling operations and sending their students to
the company's Web site to buy their textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   In each deal, the institutions will earn an undisclosed
percentage from the sale of each book through the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can outsource this and quite literally shut the door on
their bookstores,'' said Eric Kuhn, the president and chief
executive of Varsitybooks, based in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, students in large campus towns have always had the
option of buying textbooks from bookstores off campus, if they
could find ones that stocked the books they needed. But for
colleges, particularly smaller ones, there is an allure to turning
over sales of the textbooks that teachers order for their courses.
Textbook sales are the least profitable part of the business of
running a college store, according to the National Association of
College Stores.
</P>
<P>
   And the squeeze is becoming worse, some store managers say, now
that they are facing competition online from merchants like
Varsitybooks and other Internet start-up companies such as
Bigwords.com, in San Francisco, and Ecampus.com, in Lexington, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this tough business environment, though, Jerry Buchs, a
spokesman for the National Association of College Stores, said that
most universities were not ready to relinquish their book selling
to an online company. Instead, he said, they will try to establish
a Web presence while maintaining their physical stores to provide
``one-on-one customer service.''
</P>
<P>
   Follett, a bookstore chain based in River Grove, Ill., is taking
that approach. It has built a Web site, www.efollett.com, that
provides online ordering for 600 brick-and-mortar stores that it
already manages and for about 150 others that pay Follett to be
part of its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Varsitybooks' Web site, which opened last summer, features book
lists from more than 200 colleges _ although, until now, not as the
exclusive sales agent for the schools.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the 11 institutions that have been willing to entrust
Varsitybooks with their textbook sales operations are small private
universities like Alaska Pacific University, preparatory schools
like St. Agnes Academy in Houston and distance-education programs
like ISIM University in Denver.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Kuhn started the company with Tim Levy, a friend from his
law-school days at George Washington University. The men, both in
their 20s, said they wanted to give students an alternative to the
bother of standing in line for textbooks. They made a deal with
Baker &AMP; Taylor, a huge textbook distributor in Charlotte, N.C., to
fulfill orders placed through Varsitybooks.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska Pacific University in Anchorage is one of the four-year
institutions that have signed up with Varsitybooks. Brian Douglas,
the university's assistant business manager, said he had asked for
the company's help in part because students were already starting
to shop online.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't participate, it is going to happen anyway,''
Douglas said. ``We'd rather do it in an organized fashion that
helps our students.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-04-99 1647EDT &QL;
</P>
