<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-CENTERPIECE-SUITE06-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Suite deal: The right office software can make business jungle a
garden 
By Charles Haddad  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They're called ``office suites,'' but this type of
software is more like a warehouse, offering features in bulk.
</P>
<P>
   No longer do these suites simply let you write memos and analyze
numbers. With these programs you can now add complex tables to
reports, convert numbers into colorful 3D charts and publish
documents on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   While powerful, these programs are also overwhelming. Your eyes
glaze over reading down the list of features. How, then, do you
choose which one is right for you or your business?
</P>
<P>
   To help guide your decision, we took a close look at the latest
versions of the top three office suites: market leader Microsoft
Office 2000, WordPerfect 2000 and SmartSuite Millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The three are more alike than different. Each includes a word
processor, spreadsheet, a limited personal information manager,
presentation software and a database.
</P>
<P>
   To varying degrees of success, each of these programs lets you
paste a spreadsheet in a report, add written notes to spreadsheets
or publish database numbers in a document table.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, each program offers toolbars of buttons that let
you automate routine tasks. At the click of a button you can add
styles to a document, correct spelling errors and total up columns
of numbers.
</P>
<P>
   WordPerfect and SmartSuite also will easily read and convert
Office 2000 documents. Neither program could survive as an Office
alternative without this ability.
</P>
<P>
   And, ever in tune with what's fashionable, all three programs
let you publish documents on an in-house network or on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are taking about here are hairline differences between
the different programs,'' says Michael Lasky, senior associate
editor at PC World. He has worked with and reviewed all three of
the suites over the years.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest difference among the three programs is price. Office
2000 is the most expensive, with its minimum version costing $499.
On the other end of the scale is WordPerfect. Its most expensive
package is only $209.
</P>
<P>
   Another key difference among the three programs is in feel and
approach. Office 2000 lets you customize just about every feature
in a mind-boggling array of choices. In contrast, SmartSuite favors
a simpler interface but limits how much you can customize the
program.
</P>
<P>
   While offering identical packages of software, the suites are
not uniform in performance. WordPerfect is considered by many to
have the best word processor in terms of features and ease of use.
Office 2000 remains the leader in spreadsheets with its Excel
program.
</P>
<P>
   What follows is an analysis of each suite's strengths and
weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   Office 2000
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, Microsoft's suite is the standard by which the
other two suites are judged. That's because Office makes up 90
percent of the market for suite software.
</P>
<P>
   Office's greatest strength is its vast feature set. That is also
its greatest weakness. Many users are simply overwhelmed by the
choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a jungle in there,'' says Lasky about Office 2000's inner
workings. ``You have to navigate such a thicket of features just to
write a letter.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Office 2000 strength is something called cross platform
compatibility. That means PC and Mac users can easily open each
other's documents created in Office.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of Office remains the suite's Word word processing and
Excel spreadsheet programs, which remain largely unchanged from
earlier versions. Microsoft, however, has added several helpful
enhancements in its latest version, released earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Top of the list is something called multiple clipboards, which
lets you save up to 12 different things simultaneously. This is a
new feature for a PC program, although Mac word processor Nisus
Writer has been able to do this for years.
</P>
<P>
   Another Office 2000 innovation is smart menus. The program
observes how you work and then lists it in its pull-down menus only
those commands most used. The idea is to cut down on the clutter of
functions.
</P>
<P>
   Other Office 2000 innovations include the ability to insert text
or graphics anywhere on a page and a feature called self-repair.
The program will automatically replace key files mistakenly
deleted.
</P>
<P>
   WordPerfect 2000
</P>
<P>
   Believe or not, there was a time when WordPerfect was the
leading word processor. To this day it remains a strong program and
retains a loyal following.
</P>
<P>
   One of the features that makes WordPerfect's word processor so
strong is its use of the NaturallySpeaking voice recognition
technology. Developed by Dragon Software, NaturallySpeaking lets
WordPerfect type as you talk. You must, however, first train
NaturallySpeaking to recognize your pronunciation.
</P>
<P>
   Office 2000 doesn't yet include any voice recognition
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Another WordPerfect innovation is something called RealTime
Preview. This is a feature that lets you edit, changing text and
margins, a document in the print preview mode.
</P>
<P>
   WordPerfect will also let you drag and drop images, sound and
video clips into an electronic scrapbook.
</P>
<P>
   The software's weakest link is its spreadsheet program, Quattro
Pro. That's not to say Quattro Pro is bad. It's just not as strong
as those in SmartSuite and Office.
</P>
<P>
   SmartSuite
</P>
<P>
   SmartSuite strengths are threefold: great Web publishing and
groupware tools and exceptional integration with Lotus Notes,
SmartSuite's sister e-mail program.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of SmartSuite's Web publishing tools is a feature
called FastSite. It lets users easily and quickly convert print
documents into Web pages. For example, FastSite automatically adds
Web navigation tools to converted documents and builds a home page
and a table of contents.
</P>
<P>
   ``SmartSuite's Internet features and ease of use leaves other
suites in the dust,'' PC magazine said in a recent review of the
software.
</P>
<P>
   The second strength is a set of groupware tools. These tools let
several users worked simultaneously on the same document,
highlighting who made what changes and keeping track of them.
</P>
<P>
   Office 2000 also has groupware tools, but they're not considered
as strong as those in SmartSuite.
</P>
<P>
   SmartSuite has a good, if less feature-rich, writing program in
Word Pro. Its spreadsheet program, 1-2-3 is considered second to
Office's Excel.
</P>
<P>
   SmartSuite also has voice recognition technology, called
ViaVoice. ViaVoice is considered harder to train and less accurate
than NaturallySpeaking. But it does have one advantage over
NaturallySpeaking. ViaVoice can read back text.
</P>
<P>
   What SmartSuite lacks is the high-level of automation offered by
Office 2000. It's also hard to customize. SmartSuite's scripting
language is daunting to anyone but a professional programmer.
</P>
<P>
   So what program is best suited for you? It depends on your
needs.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to march in step with most of the corporate world
than Office 2000 is your choice. In addition, Office 2000 remains,
overall, the most powerful of the suites.
</P>
<P>
   However, if price is a big consideration, you should give
WordPerfect a close look. It delivers the most bang for the buck.
</P>
<P>
   And, if you need to publish a lot online, then SmartSuite might
be best for you.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
