<SLUG> BC-CPT-MAC-REPORT06-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Better OS eases sharing, surfing 
By Charles Haddad  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Imagine a Mac that several users could share, with
each maintaining a different configuration of folders, applications
and even desktop patterns.
</P>
<P>
   What if that shared Mac could switch among these individual
configurations based on the voice of the user?
</P>
<P>
   Such power is part of the latest upgrade to the Mac OS, or
operating system, scheduled for release this fall. It will come
less than six months from the last upgrade, OS 8.6.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in the past 18 months, Apple has done a great job in
releasing regular and reliable upgrades to its OS. The OS controls
how your Mac works, from the look of the screen to how you navigate
through the hard disk. The better the OS, the more a Mac can do and
do well.
</P>
<P>
   The fall upgrade, code-named Sonata, will include major
improvements to the Mac's ability to support multiple users and Web
connectivity. Sonata will be released commercially as OS 8.7.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Apple Computer is saying little about Sonata. But
beta testers of this upgrade have been talking plenty with others.
Reports about Sonata and its key features are proliferating across
the Web, featured at such sites as Apple Insider, MacIntouch and
Webintosh.
</P>
<P>
   Following is a summary of the most reliable information gleaned
about Sonata from these sites.
</P>
<P>
   Sonata's biggest change will be an expanded ability for Macs to
handle multiple users. With Sonata, several people will be able to
share a Mac and keep separate, password-protected work
environments.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, no one but you _ or a system administrator if
your Mac is on a network _ will be able to change your setup. Among
the things you'll be able to customize will be look, file access
and Internet configuration.
</P>
<P>
   You can sign onto a Mac configured for multiple users via a
written password or through voice recognition. Sonata will include
a new control panel called Voice Password Assistant.
</P>
<P>
   With Voice Password, you select a spoken code word and say it
until the system understands your voice and the code word. Then a
user can sign onto a Mac by selecting his or her name and saying
the correct password.
</P>
<P>
   Another OS feature getting an overhaul is Apple's new Sherlock
search technology. Sherlock lets users search not only their hard
drive but the Internet from their computers.
</P>
<P>
   Sonata will add two new important searches to Sherlock. The
first is for people. Sherlock will search via the Web telephone
numbers and e-mail addresses. What it finds will be listed on your
computer in the Sherlock window.
</P>
<P>
   The second new search is for e-commerce. Type the name of a
product into Sherlock, and it will search the Web for varying
prices and availability of the product, listing the results on your
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Many more changes are coming with Sonata, many of which are
minor enhancements and bug fixes. To learn more about this upgrade,
check out Apple Insider at www.appleinsider.com
/macos8.7.shtmlreports.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
