<HEADLINE>
MANY SITES FAILURES AT USABILITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DAVID HOYE   
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Do you know Jakob Nielsen? &QL; 
Probably not. But you should, especially if you ever plan to make
money from a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The Northern California resident has been called one of the
Web's 10 most influential people, a group that also includes the
likes of America Online's Steve Case, Jeff Bezos of Amazon.com and
William Kennard, chairman of the Federal Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen is the guy the ``New York Times'' once dubbed the ``guru
of Web page usability,'' a man for whom Web design is not a matter
of taste or aesthetics _ it's a matter of science.`
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen, who was in Phoenix to address an annual meeting of Web
usability experts from around the country, has made a career out of
studying what makes a Web site work and what makes a site fail.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing the difference between the two is crucial for anyone
venturing into the largely uncharted seas of e-commerce, or buying
and selling online.
</P>
<P>
   E-commerce has quickly gone from being an experiment involving a
few companies to a requirement for any business that wants to
succeed. International Data Corp. recently estimated that online
spending will hit $1 trillion by 2003. Sales people already know
that success means outselling their company's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Despite signs that e-commerce is booming, Nielsen says the vast
majority of business-related Web sites are failures at usability.
Generally, that means average users find it too difficult to
navigate the sites, find the products or information they want and
spend money.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the Web, the power rests with he or she who clicks the
mouse,'' Nielsen said during an interview last week. ``If (a Web
site) is difficult to use or you can't find anything, what's the
customer's reaction? It's to go someplace else. You lose your
chance at the next generation economy if it's not easy to use your
site.''
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen said the problem affects Web sites operated by companies
of all sizes. Having cash to spend on fancy designs doesn't seem to
matter.
</P>
<P>
   The most frequent mistakes he finds include:
</P>
<P>
   - Using the latest in Web technology despite the fact that it
does nothing to enhance the usability of the site.
</P>
<P>
   - Depending on complex URLs, or Web-page addresses, that include
strings of numbers and symbols instead of simple words that users
can remember.
</P>
<P>
   - Outdated content that shows users nobody is minding the online
store.
</P>
<P>
   - Opening new browser windows when the user clicks on a link,
something Nielsen equates with a vacuum cleaner salesman who begins
a visit by dumping an ashtray on your carpet.
</P>
<P>
   - Slow servers and pages that take too long to download.
</P>
<P>
   Fixing problem Web sites, he says, has to be done on an
individual basis. No single format can work for every online
business. But basic steps all follow the same thread.
</P>
<P>
   Design for the user, not the guys in marketing or the boss
upstairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason why some sites get famous, like Amazon.com, is that
they make usability the primary focus. What makes it easy for
people to buy a book or CD?'' Nielsen said. ``They are not
geniuses. I've noticed them doing stupid things. But if they make a
mistake, they fix it immediately. They know what works and what
doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   While designing or redesigning a Web site, Nielsen urges that
the ``feel'' of the site needs to be given more importance than the
``look.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Feeling dominates over the look,'' he says. ``It's freedom to
navigate and move around. Do the users feel empowered? Or are they
sluggish, like they are swimming in a sea of oil? Do they feel lost
and abandoned?''
</P>
<P>
   One quick way to test the feeling of your site: Find out if
users know what's going to happen when they click on a link or
button. If they do, that's good. Your site is open and predictable.
If the user gets surprised and says, ``Oops!'' there's work to be
done.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen said he has developed three main rules to follow in
determining what works on a Web site and what doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   They are:
</P>
<P>
   - Test your site with representative customers, not the guy in
the next cubicle who already knows all there is to know about your
company.
</P>
<P>
   - While testing your site, have the representative customers do
real tasks or solve real problems. If it's an airline site, have
them try to book a flight.
</P>
<P>
   - Shut up. Let the users do the talking. If they keep clicking
the wrong buttons, change the buttons. ``If the customer clicks on
the wrong button,'' he says, ``it's not because they are stupid,
it's because your design is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Want to know more? Nielsen runs his own Web site, which is
packed with information and links to related studies and Web sites.
He also writes a regular column. Find it all at www.useit.com.
</P>
<P>
   `PC' readers rate PCs
</P>
<P>
   If you're in the market for a new computer, check out the July
issue of ``PC'' magazine. Beginning on page 183, you'll find the
results from the magazine's 12th annual Readers' Choice survey for
service and reliability.
</P>
<P>
   In grading desktop computers, Dell, IBM and Quantex were given
the highest mark, an A rating. In the B category were Apple,
Hewlett-Packard, Micron and Sony. The largest group, C, included
AT&AMP;T, Comp-USA, Digital, Gateway, NEC, Toshiba, Zenith Data
Systems, ZEOS and machines locally built.
</P>
<P>
   The D group included AST, Compaq and MidWest Micro. Rounding out
the desktop rating list were Acer and Packard Bell in the E group.
</P>
<P>
   As for notebook computers, IBM and Sony were rated A, Compaq,
Dell, Gateway, Micron and Toshiba earned a B rating, Acer, Apple,
Digital, Fujitsu, Hewlett-Packard, Hitachi and NEC completed the C
category, Texas Instruments and WinBook were given D ratings and
AST got the only E rating.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the computer makers might complain about their rankings.
But it's interesting to note that, for the most part, the rankings
have remained fairly constant for most of the vendors since 1993,
according to a chart published with the magazine story.
</P>
<P>
   In the desktop category, for example, Dell has earned A marks
each time the survey was taken, except for a single B rating it
received in 1995. Packard Bell, meanwhile, has earned a steady
stream of D and E ratings,except for a single C rating in 1995. &QL; 
David Hoye can be reached via e-mail at dhoye(at)home.net.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-05-99 1542EDT &QL;
</P>
