<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-HEALTHNET07-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Health care information varies on Web 
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Seemingly endless oceans of information _ it is the
Internet's greatness and its most frustrating flaw. Type in a topic
and watch your powerful search engine come back with tens of
thousands of possible links. And it is true that sometimes people
who sail the Net arrive with a surplus of time and curiosity,
hoping for selections reaching to the horizon. But if a user just
wants a pressing question answered, then that sea can seem like an
infinite swamp. Then, he or she can be overwhelmed by an overeager
search engine. One reason to seek out a specialized site _ for
health care or whatever your interest _ is to narrow the view, to
have experts screen out enough of the flotsam so you can find what
you really need. We went to a number of the health care sites on
the Internet, wondering what kind of information would be offered
to an interested, but not expert, consumer. All the sites offer
links to other sources of information. All have lists of suggested
topics and while some had arthritis listed as a subject we could
click on, not all did. To compare, we found their search function,
typed in ``arthritis treatment'' and clicked. Here's some of what
we found.
</P>
<P>
   Adam.com (www.adam.com)
</P>
<P>
   Adam now aims to provide a wide-ranging site for many kinds of
users. However, the company made its name with graphics and data
for the health care professional, so it should be no surprise that
the 10 matches found were pretty specific. All 10 were links to
articles about treatments for types of arthritis: Psoriatic, viral,
rheumatoid, juvenile rheumatoid and so on.
</P>
<P>
   CareData.com (www.caredata.com)
</P>
<P>
   CareData does most of its work with institutions that want
access to its huge databases. But CareData has branched out to
consumers with its Citeline engine, coming up with 52,427 responses
to our query. Some links (like Colorado HealthNet) are pitched at a
narrow audience. Some sound intimidating (Arava Leflunomide
Recommended For Approval By FDA Advisory Committee). And some are
aimed at a broad swath of consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery Health (www.discoveryhealth.com)
</P>
<P>
   About 25 links came up. Some were technical, but most seemed
pitched at a general audience, including a number of
question-and-answer pieces, fact sheets and some news stories.
First up on the list was a cautionary article aimed at patients
that set the tone: ``In general, if you suffer from arthritis, it
is prudent to approach health claims made by most products with
healthy skepticism.''
</P>
<P>
   DrKoop.com (www.drkoop.com)
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to its namesake, former Surgeon General C. Everett Koop,
this site is one of the best-known. Eleven links were offered for
our inquiry, leading with a story about federal approval of a
dialysislike treatment for rheumatoid arthritis. Koop also proposed
several general articles about the condition, a suggestion that
education is key in controlling pain and several pieces about
particular versions of arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   Intelihealth (www.intelihealth.com)
</P>
<P>
   Intelihealth is attached to another of the brand names in health
care: Johns Hopkins. The search for arthritis treatment produced a
list of dozens of documents. The first was a to-the-point, consumer
friendly introduction to basic treatments like medicine, diet and
exercise. Others provided lists of specialists, medications and
looks at some new and somewhat controversial approaches like
glocosamine. Intelihealth also offered some articles that seemed
completely unrelated. (For instance, why the stories about breast
cancer?)
</P>
<P>
   WebMD, Inc. (www.webmd.com)
</P>
<P>
   More than 5,100 links came up, starting with a series of
definitions and summaries of articles about drugs. Near the top of
the list were anti-inflammatory medicines like fenoprofen and
fluriprofen, as well as, something called galvanotherapy.
References were fairly specific, some of them pretty technical for
the average layperson.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
