<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASS-ACTION-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAREHOLDER SUITS FLOURISH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Berman DeValerio &AMP; Pease seemed on the brink of extinction in
1995. Congress was considering a bill that would sharply cut the
number of class-action lawsuits filed by disgruntled shareholders _
the firm's lifeblood. Partner Glen DeValerio recalls saying one day
that summer, ``Oh my God, we're goners.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill passed. But more than four years later, the firm is not
only alive but prospering. It has emerged as one of the nation's
leading firms that specialize in representing individuals who
believe a downturn in a particular stock was caused by corporate
wrongdoing or poor management. The Boston firm has doubled its
staff, opened an office in California, and completed a renovation
at its pricey Liberty Square address.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an assumption that bill would put all of us low-life
plaintiffs' lawyers out of business,'' DeValerio says now. ``None
of us had any idea things would turn out like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the 1995 law _ which critics concede has eliminated some
meritless suits _ shareholder actions have thrived in part because
the Internet has given law firms the power to reach masses of
disgruntled investors willing to join a class of plaintiffs in the
hopes of getting a big settlement. Internet chat rooms are filled
with company gossip provided by investors _ gossip that's sometimes
used by lawyers to bolster a claim.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, public companies, especially high-flying high-tech
firms, are under more pressure than ever from Wall Street to meet
profit expectations so exacting that companies falling short by
even a penny a share can see their stock price crash. As companies
strain to meet quarterly projections, some have found themselves
embroiled in public battles with government regulators or their own
auditors over accounting methods, leaving them open to shareholder
suits.
</P>
<P>
   More than half the record 332 class-action lawsuits filed last
year on behalf of shareholders claimed companies had committed some
kind of accounting fraud. Faced with the prospect of a lengthy
trial, most firms chose to settle for amounts that were on the
average double what they were five years ago, observers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``These lawyers go out and find companies in that kind of bind,
and when they do it's not that hard to convince them to settle,''
says Louis Thompson, president and chief executive of the National
Investor Relations Institute, which represents about 2,600 public
companies nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Not all firms settle, however. Last year, Berman DeValerio &AMP;
Pease lost a high-profile suit they brought against Biogen Inc.,
alleging the company misled investors by touting the prospects of
an experimental drug that later was dropped after a series of
disappointing tests. That case was the first shareholder suit to
actually go to a jury in Massachusetts in about a decade.
</P>
<P>
   The recent rise in suits has renewed an age-old feud between the
lawyers who bring them and those who defend the companies targeted
by the actions. Shareholder attorneys claim they protect the
investing public from fraud and deception by big corporate
interests. But critics say the plaintiffs' attorneys exploit greedy
investors to drain companies that have done nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their suits are conceived in sin,'' says Jeff Rudman, a
prominent corporate defense attorney at the Boston firm of Hale &AMP;
Dorr, of his nemesis lawyers at Berman DeValerio &AMP; Pease. ``The
lawyers at that firm are honorable people, but I hate the business
they're in. I disagree with everything they stand for.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the controversy, industry observers say, surrounds
ambiguities in accounting rules. Under pressure from Wall Street,
many high-tech companies in recent years have interpreted the rules
in ways that allow them to record revenue earlier rather than
later. Alarmed, the federal Securities and Exchange Commission has
said the practice is blatant fraud and launched investigations of
companies across the country. Public auditors have frequently
demanded companies revise their earnings to reflect a more
conservative reading of the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many companies subjected to shareholder suits for
accounting fraud say they have done nothing worthy of being sued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Accounting is an art, not a science,'' says the investor
relations institute's Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of room for interpretation. As soon as there's
some kind of indication of a controversy, the lawyers are in there
with a suit.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies have continued to lobby for more protection in
Washington, where just last week President Clinton said he would
sign a bill that includes some protections to companies whose stock
prices fall because of Y2K computer glitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind that's just another example of the investing public
losing rights,'' says Peter Pease of Berman DeValerio &AMP; Pease.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defendants, the companies being sued, will say that all
these suits are frivolous. Instead of saying, `We need to protect
the investing public,' it's become very popular to say, `What we've
got to do is get rid of all the lawyers.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The debate over the legitimacy of shareholder suits has been
around at least since the 1920s, legal historians say. Laws meant
to protect stock market investors in the wake of the 1929 market
crash produced a wave of suits. They were brought by shareholders
who wanted to recover losses from companies they claimed had misled
them about their earnings prospects or had broken laws that sent
stock prices spiraling.
</P>
<P>
   But the practice also brought out a breed of lawyer much hated
in corporate boardrooms because they prowled the ticker tapes and
filed lawsuits against any company whose stock price fell.
</P>
<P>
   In more recent times, companies have been sued for any number of
reasons _ from accounting fraud and insider trading to making a
merger deal that didn't yield as much value as investors wanted.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1990s, shareholder lawyers had become so aggressive one
critic in 1995 congressional testimony said they were ``the scourge
of the earth.'' Some firms kept lists of so-called ``frequent
fliers,'' investors who bought small stakes in many companies and
were known to be willing to join class-action suits whenever stock
prices fell. One legendary class-action attorney was so feared in
corporate boardrooms that he was known simply as ``The Devil.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1995 law _ known as the Securities Litigation Reform Act _
was meant to get rid of the worst suits by requiring shareholder
lawyers to cite specific abuses at a company, not just that stock
prices fell.
</P>
<P>
   Most industry observers say it accomplished that. But critics
bitterly point out that the law also inadvertantly opened the door
for more suits with a provision requiring shareholder lawyers to
publish the fact they were bringing a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   By publishing on the Internet instead of newspapers, something
Congress didn't anticipate, attorneys have drawn thousands of
investors to class-action suits.
</P>
<P>
   With such huge classes, shareholder attorneys say, they've found
new clout in the suits they file, contributing to a trend toward
ever-larger settlements.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of power in numbers,'' says Michael Lange,
another partner at Berman DeValerio &AMP; Pease, where the average
settlement is now nearly $10 million, double the average amount
five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet also has enabled shareholder lawyers to operate
with unprecedented speed. With slick Web sites and chat rooms for
disgruntled investors, lawyers can identify a suspect company,
collect information for a detailed complaint, and assemble a class
of thousands of investors in a matter of days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has revolutionized our practice,'' DeValerio says. ``We are
able to receive information and disseminate it at a speed that
would have been unheard of before. The ability to find evidence of
fraud is much easier today than it used to be. Shareholders do a
lot of investigating themselves and post this stuff on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, when we see a substantial decline in a stock price, we
can know in a few hours whether we've got a situation where we can
take an action.''
</P>
<P>
   Shareholder attorneys have pounced at the first sign of an
earnings restatement, a move they say they interpret as practically
an admission of accounting fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much of it out there right now, certainly more than
anything in my lifetime,'' says Pease.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most recent examples, Berman DeValerio &AMP; Pease
scurried to file a suit against Pegasystems Inc. after the
Cambridge, Mass. software company last year announced earnings
revisions that revealed profits to be lower than it previously
announced.
</P>
<P>
   A string of accounting revisions since then contributed to a
long, precipitous slide in the company's stock price from 30 to 4
1/4. Last month, the Nasdaq Stock Market halted trading for five
hours while market officials questioned the company about a federal
investigation into its accounting practices and trading in the
firm's stock.
</P>
<P>
   The suit is currently pending, and both sides refuse to discuss
it.
</P>
<P>
   While some companies have railed against law firms' predatory
actions in those cases, industry observers say that in those cases,
at least, the firms are serving as a check on bad company
practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is how the system is supposed to work,'' says Joseph A.
Grundfest, a professor at Stanford Law School and a former
commissioner of the US Securities and Exchange Commission. ``The
plaintiff's bar is made up of profit-seeking attorneys. They're out
to make money. Their job is to push the system as far as it will
go, and in those cases where they discourage a bad practice, the
system works.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 1318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
