<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1760 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUNDS-QUARTER-BOS &LR;      07-07 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNDS-QUARTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL-CAP, GLOBAL STOCKS BLOW PAST THE BLUE CHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mutual funds, the plain vanilla investment option in a world of
exotic temptations, might well be the most appetizing choice after
all. Recent fund returns are anything but bland.
</P>
<P>
   Investors gained a sizzling 10.2 percent with the average
domestic stock fund in the just-ended quarter, according to Lipper
Inc., the fund tracking firm. Smaller-stock funds, which had been
anemic for years, swelled double that amount.
</P>
<P>
   The harvest may be bitter for some investors. More than a few
Americans have turned up their noses at conservative,
professionally managed portfolios in recent months and plunged into
cyberinvesting, do-it-yourself stockpicking, and other riskier,
more exotic alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   But the recent returns bonanza, the product of a giant shift in
stock markets during the spring, is likely to alter investor tastes
again. While overall fund sales are still lean compared to those in
recent periods, investors are slowly coming back to the table,
according to recent data.
</P>
<P>
   ``People see the returns, and they want back in,'' said Carl
Wittnebert at Mutual Fund TrimTabs, a Santa Rosa, Calif., firm that
tracks how much money investors put into and take out of funds.
</P>
<P>
   In a dramatic shift, the US stock market has widened to give
more types of shares _ and the funds that invest in them _ bigger
gains. New faith in the surging US economy and a rebound in Asian
markets, as well as disillusionment with the high valuations of the
most popular stocks, are behind the transformation.
</P>
<P>
   The result: After several years in which funds exposed to a
handful of giant, household-name companies or flashy Internet
shares hogged all the returns, investors now face a feast of
plenty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest story last quarter was the broadening of the
market,'' said John Ballen, president of MFS Investment Management
in Boston, a large fund firm. ``This is a major reversal.''
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the changes, funds invested in small-company shares
rose a hefty 15.6 percent in the second quarter, whose three months
ended June 30. Those devoted to micro-cap stocks, or companies with
market capitalizations of less than $300 milllion, gained a
whopping 22 percent _ the best-performing domestic stock category.
</P>
<P>
   On the opposite end, funds that had garnered the lead position
in recent years slipped to the back burner. Growth funds focused on
large, fast-growing companies rose a comparatively low 7.1 percent.
And funds that mimic the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index _ still the
flavor of the moment among investors _ gained only 6.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Such returns, of course, are nothing to sneeze at, especially
when compared with the average domestic stock fund's skimpy 0.9
percent gain in the first quarter. Stock investors can historically
expect to gain around 10 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   The market's changes were captured in the performance of the
nation's most widely-held equity funds. Janus Twenty, a $24.9
billion fund devoted to large-caps and a top performer in recent
periods, lost 4.3 percent last quarter, one of only two funds among
the nation's 25 largest funds to lose money for the period. By
contrast, Fidelity Equity-Income, a $24.2 billion portfolio full of
so-called undervalued stocks that have been out of favor, gained
10.6 percent, one of the best performers among the behemoth funds.
</P>
<P>
   The white-hot performance of funds last quarter may light a
firecracker under the $5.8 trillion fund industry, a business with
more assets than bank savings accounts.
</P>
<P>
   After months in which Wall Street seemed to be telling investors
they should simply chase hot funds focused on blue chips, last
quarter's message is that diversification among types of funds
works.
</P>
<P>
   Total, or net, sales of long-term mutual funds, which do not
include short-term money-market portfolios, declined 45 percent to
$82.1 billion over the first five months of this year compared with
1998 levels, according to Financial Research Corp., a consulting
firm in Boston. The figures reflect gross sales minus sums
investors redeemed from funds.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are still buying funds, but they have also been
pulling cash out to buy individual stocks, often through Web-based
brokerages, or to spend profits on big-ticket consumer goods such
as homes and vacations.
</P>
<P>
   On one level, the phenomenon has constituted a rejection of the
principle of professionally managed money and of the buy-and-hold
strategy that had led millions of Americans to place retirement and
college savings in funds.
</P>
<P>
   But according to David Haywood, an industry analyst at Financial
Research, redemptions reflect not disenchantment with funds in an
era of flashy cyberbrokerages and Internet stocks, but confidence
that the market _ and stock portfolios _ will continue to perform
well. Investors, he said, feel confident that the bull market will
make up for any money cashed out.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, inflows into domestic equity funds in May, at $14.9
billion, were nearly even with May 1998, according to Financial
Research. And net sales for the second quarter were double the
previous quarter's $30 billion, according to estimates by TrimTabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody expected it, but the flows are picking up,'' said
TrimTabs' Wittnebert. ``The main factor is performance.''
</P>
<P>
   The hottest returns last quarter were for funds invested in
international stocks, a category battered in recent periods. Funds
invested in the Pacific region, but not Japan, gained 37.6 percent,
while emerging markets funds soared 24.9 percent. Portfolios
devoted to European stocks stood still, rising only 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   There were other surprises. Natural resources funds gained 18.4
percent, bettering by more than four percentage points glitzy
science and technology funds.
</P>
<P>
   Among bond funds, returns were middling to unhappy. Domestic
long-term Treasury bond funds slipped 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the past years' worst investment categories are up,''
said Reginald Green, publisher of the Mutual Fund News Service
newsletter in Bodega Bay, Calif. ``And many investors are going to
learn from the last quarter that nothing lasts forever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
