<HEADLINE>
WOMEN, SOME OF THEM, CO-OPT `BITCH' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VANESSA E. JONES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The song starts with a grooving techno-Afro beat. But it's the
words that follow that make you take notice of Missy Elliott's new
hip-hop single.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She's a bitch
</P>
<P>
   You can't see me Joe
</P>
<P>
   Get on down while I shout my flow
</P>
<P>
   She's a bitch
</P>
<P>
   When I do my thang
</P>
<P>
   Got the place on fire burning down in flames
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elliott doesn't sling the b-word around in the misogynistic way
of her male hip-hop cohorts. Instead, Elliott reclaims it, making
it the description of choice for strong women. As Elliott, a
sought-after producer, songwriter, and performer, told Ms. magazine
in a recent interview, ``I became a bitch in power because when I
walked in, I asked for what I wanted. And at the end of the day, if
this is the way I want it, this is the way I'm going to have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott isn't the only person embracing the b-word these days.
After a new wave of feminists dragged it back into the public
lexicon in the early 1990s, the once-vitriolic term that some
people still have trouble uttering has gone the mainstream path of
``hell'' and ``damn.''
</P>
<P>
   Turn on the telly and you're likely to hear it slip out of
someone's mouth. It was the punch line of a joke in the film
``Armageddon'' and a rude term of endearment bandied about by the
male friends in ``Good Will Hunting.''
</P>
<P>
   A group of female legislators in Washington state feistily call
themselves Mean Old Bitches. A recent book by Elizabeth Wurtzel and
a 'zine are both called ``Bitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Peruse the newsstands and you'll find Honey, a new magazine for
young African-American women that boldly named its column for
unsigned female artists ``Bitches Brew.'' And a year before
Elliott's ``She's a Bitch'' hit the radio airwaves, the masses
exuberantly sang along to Meredith Brooks's bluntly titled pop song
``Bitch.''
</P>
<P>
   The word's broad acceptance follows a well-worn path of
reclamation. Homosexuals have done it with ``queer,'' lesbians with
``dyke,'' feminists with ``girl,'' and African-Americans with the
n-word.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the people out there in the culture using (the word
``bitch'') are doing it in the way that fat people make fat jokes
or Margaret Cho makes Asian jokes,'' says Amelia Richards, 29,
cofounder of Third Wave, the New York-based national organization
of young feminist activists. ``It's done, I think, from a position
of power.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a broad-based cultural embracement of the word is bound to
have an impact on young women. Take, for example, the girls gustily
rapping along with Elliott's ``She's a Bitch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was 21 . . . I would be thinking that Missy is about the
coolest chick in the universe,'' says Danyel Smith, who is in fact
34 and the editor in chief of the hip-hop magazine Vibe. ``And I
would think `If she's using it and it's no big deal to her, then
it's no big deal to me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Yet for some it is still a big deal. As with those other words,
not everyone mouthing the derogatory term uses it in a positive
manner. Despite explanations from Elliott, Brooks, and company, the
b-word still summons up images of not only a powerful woman, but a
cruel or sexually aggressive one. And those are just some of the
nicer meanings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's like a woman's trip,'' says Joan Morgan, 34, author of
``When Chickenheads Come Home to Roost: My Life as a Hip-Hop
Feminist,'' published in March. ``I don't think that we can then
make the leap that it's really going to change or impact the way
that men see and use the word. The word is firmly embedded in the
lexicon of male language that's used to disparage women.''
</P>
<P>
   Richards agrees. ``The problem is when context is missing,'' she
says. ``There are still too many people out there that use `queer,'
that use `girl,' that use `bitch' in a context that is not only
negative and woman-hating but also potentially dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Negativity isn't the goal of the Washington state
representatives, senators, lobbyists, and staff members who call
themselves Mean Old Bitches. In fact, members offended by the
b-word simply call themselves Mean Old Broads.
</P>
<P>
   But broad is not the name their opponents use when complaining
about the tenacious female politicians. Since the early 1990s, MOB
members have used their humorous moniker to soften those digs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hear stories coming back that we're called these names
because we're willing to stand up and take the body blows,'' says
state Rep. Karen Schmidt, 53, who was given her MOB pin six or
seven years ago after a bitter legislative battle over a
transportation issue. ``If you think of it on the negative side,
it's going to depress you. If you make it positive, it kind of
makes you smile. And you do need to smile about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Years ago women would never laugh off that term. For centuries
the word described a female dog or was a vicious put-down aimed at
someone considered ``excessively'' sexual women. By the 20th
century, people had also adapted the word to describe a malicious
woman.
</P>
<P>
   Gay men were the first to use it in a positive way, says Camille
Paglia, the controversial self-described feminist who claims to
have ``legitimized the word bitch'' in the 1990s. In the 1960s gay
men ``would say admiringly of Barbra Streisand, `She's such a
bitch.' I loved their usage of that,'' says Paglia.
</P>
<P>
   The word began seeping into the mainstream in the 1970s. Elton
John applied the word to himself in 1974 in his song ``The Bitch Is
Back.'' And R &AMP; B fans got an earful of it when Millie Jackson
released her 1977 album ``Feelin' Bitchy.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite such inroads, it continued to be a pejorative term.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one would ever laughingly refer to a . . .'' says Barbara
Smith, 52, a feminist author who still can't bring herself to do
more than allude to or spell out the word. ``I mean amongst friends
perhaps, but it would not ever be a public assertion and you
certainly would never have heard it on television.''
</P>
<P>
   These days it's not surprising to hear the word slipped into a
Jay Leno monologue or voiced by one of the cop characters on ``NYPD
Blue,'' usually in a spiteful way. And cable _ it definitely goes
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same thing happened with `hell' and `damn,' '' says
Morgan. ``I think that as words become used throughout the culture
more broadly, their impact and shock value tend to decrease.''
</P>
<P>
   Richards gives a good example of how the term for female dog has
lost its teeth. A few years ago she remembers chastising a woman
who used it with ease. These days Richards thinks it's such a
catchall word, she hardly says it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't want to be sisterly to a woman,'' says Richards,
``I'd probably find a lot harsher words to be using or a lot more
honest words because I do think the word has a generic
connotation.''
</P>
<P>
   It's so generic, women can hear hip-hop artists such as Ma
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
