<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERGED BANKS MUST RENEW COMMITMENT TO COMMUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the economic scheme of things, The Federal Reserve board of
governors plays the College of Cardinals to Alan Greenspan's Pope.
</P>
<P>
   Where he leads, they must follow, unless massive rebellion
overwhelms collegiality, which is exceedingly rare, as heretics
don't get promoted to the rank of cardinal. So when the Federal
Reserve convenes a public meeting Wednesday (July 7) on the merger
of Fleet Bank and BankBoston, there will be a predisposition to
approve the confluence of New England's two largest banks.
</P>
<P>
   Because to shoot it down, on one pretext or another, would
disrupt the glacial momentum of consolidation in the finance
industry. Banking regulators are no more powerful against economic
tides than are shorefront property owners glumly regarding waves
eroding their beachfront. You can make a little difference here or
there, toss in some rip-rap, but in the end, the tides win.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a line of local worthies lining up to support the
big bank merger, and there will be the opponents, whose realisitic
intent is not so much to prevent the inevitable, but to extract a
pound of flesh for this cause or that. Wresting financial
commitments from merger-bound bank executives is one of the final
hurdles. Then comes the Justice Department's OK of the plan to
auction off bank branches to pare the new colossus down to the
requirements of the antitrust diet.
</P>
<P>
   Like the oldest oak in the forest, BankBoston, the direct lineal
descendant of the first bank in this country, is about ready to
fall. The bank which enabled colonial New England to find its
fiscal feet is being merged into Fleet, the regional powerhouse
assembled by Terry Murray.
</P>
<P>
   As Brian Mooney sketched with awesome specificity in Saturday's
Globe, BankBoston will become the 451st stand-alone bank to be
swallowed in the Fleet maw. There were quaintly-titled itty-bitty
outfits like Orange National, Worcester Mechanics, Workingmen's
Cooperative, First National of Winchendon, and larger chunks, Bank
of New England, Shawmut and BayBanks.
</P>
<P>
   The banking business has changed. Consolidation is the rule.
ATMs replace tellers, on-line banking displaces passbooks, credit
and debit cards displace checkbooks. To buy the computers and
tekkies to run them, banks need to get bigger. It's dog-eat-dog,
and the bigger dog always wins. If it wasn't Fleet absorbing
BankBoston, it would have been one of the giants to our south or
west. To many in business, the devil they know (Fleet-BankBoston)
is preferable to the out-of-region devils they don't know.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Congress seems serious about obliterating the
Glass-Stegall barriers between banks, brokerage houses and
insurance companies, the pressure to get bigger is even greater.
But the absorption of BankBoston has one potential downside. Even
before Chad Gifford took over BankBoston, that outfit had an
outstanding national reputation for community involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Murray is expected to match that. So his executives have crafted
a plan to commit $14.6 billion over five years for projects that
require more banking leeway than a cold-eyed credit check. ``We are
commiting to keep the spigot going for the next five years the way
it's been open for the past three, at the peak of the economic
cycle,'' said Jim Mahony, a Fleet executive.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet is bankrolling a study by MassInc. that was requested by
Cardinal Bernard Law to examine ways to increase the housing supply
in Massachusetts. The Cardinal's point man on affordable housing is
Msgr. Michael Groden, who runs the Archdiocese Planning Office for
Urban Affairs. The big bank merger coincides with the archdiocese
``trying to fashion new mechanisms to create affordable housing for
low and moderate income families, the elderly and those with
special needs,'' said Groden. The problem now is not mortgage
money, but lowering the ever-escalating costs of housing to
increase supply.
</P>
<P>
   Groden said his talks with Mahony dwelt on ``new strategies such
as equity instruments that can reduce the cost to the buyer or
renter, thereby creating a greater range and depth of
affordability.'' He said the pair ``focused on several major
housing developments presently on the drawing board.'' He added
``they include one major family development and several assisted
living programs which would provide a majority of the units to low
and moderate income elderly.'' One of them is a 100-unit
assisted-living development proposed for the St. John of God
hospital grounds in Brighton.
</P>
<P>
   Mahony said Msgr. Groden broached the notion of so-called
``patient money,'' that would have the merged banks commit certain
sums up front to reduce the cost of an apartment, with the bank
waiting for repayment. ``We've been working with the Cardinal on
affordable housing. His hypothesis is we need more on the supply
side, the supply is so tight that prices are high.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahony said ``What Mike Groden and others like Tom Callahan at
the Massachusetts Affordable Housing Alliance do, this is their
life, creating affordable housing, and improving living conditions
for people. We have a great deal of respect for them, and will be
working with them as partners. We don't have the infrastructure to
develop affordable housing, that's what Mike Groden does, so we'll
work with him.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
