<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-BULGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BULGER IS BASKING IN LIMELIGHT OF UMASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- As makeovers go, it's not the new Nixon of 1968, or
even the new Dukakis of 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in its own way, this transformation is fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   The new Bulger.
</P>
<P>
   During his 17 years as president of the Massachusetts Senate,
William M. Bulger was reviled outside of the narrow confines of his
district and Beacon Hill.
</P>
<P>
   But no more. Bulger has assumed a softer public persona, thanks
to his more than three years as the University of Massachusetts
president.
</P>
<P>
   That has become evident in the university's own survey, taken
late last month. It shows the public's view of UMass has jumped
dramatically since Bulger took over in early 1996. Nearly
two-thirds of those surveyed think UMass provides a
good-to-excellent quality of education. In early 1996, only 46
percent expressed those feelings.
</P>
<P>
   The university's new standing with the public seems to have
spilled over personally to Bulger who, now far from the nasty
political wars at the State House, regularly generates positive
media coverage for himself.
</P>
<P>
   No longer the lightning rod for liberals, reformers,
Republicans, and term-limit proponents, Bulger is announcing
popular programs and appearing in upbeat ads promoting UMass, while
staying far way from any bad news that comes out of the system. He
has raised the endowment and academic standards at the university,
and cut tuitions three years in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Even a hefty pay raise the board of trustees gave him earlier
this year _ hiking his salary to nearly $300,000 from $189,000 _
failed to spark much public outrage.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, the late Paul Tsongas, the former US senator, pegged it
right when Bulger's name first surfaced as a candidate for the
UMass job. ``This is one of those ideas that is either going to be
a phenomenal success or a phenomenal failure,'' Tsongas said.
</P>
<P>
   For many in the higher education field, the first half of
Tsongas' take on the appointment has proven true.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it has worked out fabulously,'' said Daniel A. Taylor,
a Boston lawyer and former UMass trustee. ``He has a steadfast
focus on how to build a great state university.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not out of the ordinary for an official's image to change.
Richard Nixon craftily reinvented himself for his successful 1968
presidential race. And Michael Dukakis won back the governorship
from Edward King in 1982 after convincing voters he was a new,
humble, more mellow figure ready to listen.
</P>
<P>
   Bulger's transformation has not taken place in those starkly
political terms. No one is even speculating that he craves a return
to politics.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his success at UMass is a personal triumph for the former
legislative leader who often hissed at the media and appeared as a
petty, iron-fisted martinet with his opponents on Beacon Hill.
During his long State House career, he often seemed a dark,
brooding figure, defining much of the world according to his
experiences in Boston's busing crises and fending off challenges to
his integrity.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, who as counsel for former governor Michael Dukakis had
worked with Bulger on Beacon Hill, said Bulger's public image
transformation does not surprise him. The media had attributed to
the South Boston lawmaker a reputation that he did not deserve,
Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   The positive numbers in the university's McCormack Institute
survey also reflect Bulger's ability to survive _ even thrive _ in
a highly politicized state public education world that buffeted two
of his conservative colleagues, James Carlin, chairman of the Board
of Higher Education, and John Silber, chairman of the Board of
Education. The trio had been the choices of then-governor William
F. Weld to shake up the state's education establishment.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, Carlin, citing health reasons, stepped down;
friends say he was frustrated by his battles, some of them with his
old friend Bulger. Silber left last winter in the middle of an
angry public storm he helped create. He threw himself on his sword
after he and Governor Paul Cellucci couldn't secure their candidate
as the new education commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   But Bulger endures. Not only that, but in a development that
defies all the predictions when he was appointed, he has won the
warm approval of the very people who opposed his appointment.
</P>
<P>
   That speaks to Bulger's leadership style. Throughout his career,
his first instinct has always been to protect whatever institution
he is a part of, be it South Boston or the state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   That's how he succeeded on Beacon Hill. By using his charm and
political skills, he retained the loyalty of his colleagues, so
much so that he was able to beat back a reform challenge from
then-senator William Keating in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a different story among the public. Bulger's worst
period in office came a decade ago, when he was nearly devoured in
a media feeding frenzy over the 75 State Street controversy. A
Globe poll showed his favorable rating was an abysmal 15 percent,
his job performance rating, even worse, at 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   What a difference a decade makes. One source said a private poll
taken for an education group has placed his approval rating well
above 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The public's warmer feelings about the university can be traced
to several factors. Clearly, the first surge came after the
university basketball team made the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   An expensive television ad campaign that Bulger's office aired
also helped. The ads have saturated the airways for more than a
year, with prominent university graduates _ entertainer Bill Cosby,
General Motors chief executive John Smith, and General Electric top
chief, John Welch _ touting the university.
</P>
<P>
   The ads end with Bulger, surrounded by smiling students, saying,
``Let us be part of your success story.''
</P>
<P>
   But the turnaround may be more than a public relations gimmick.
Bulger gets credit for hiking fund-raising by 77 percent. The
Amherst campus has risen to 59 on the U.S. News and World Report
rankings. The SAT scores and grade-point averages of incoming
students are up.
</P>
<P>
   He also has increased UMass's cachet by offering full
scholarships to the top two academic achievers at each of the
state's high schools.
</P>
<P>
   The board of trustees chose Bulger, the politician, after a long
string of mostly out-of-state academics tried and failed to lead
the university. It was risky. But if UMass's own polls are correct,
the public feels the risk was well worth it.
</P>
</TEXT>
