<HEADLINE>
FOR THE REST OF '99: LET THE GOOD TIMES ROLL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like the Red Sox, the American economy and stock market had a
much better first half of the year than anyone expected. As the
second half of the year begins, the obvious question to ask is: Can
the good times continue or will something come along to burst our
bubble?
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to remember, but as 1999 began, the outlook for the
year was decidedly mediocre. And why not? The US economy had just
completed its third straight year of roughly 4 percent growth, a
performance that dramatically exceeded all forecasts. With the
world economy in trouble, the betting was the United States could
not remain ``an oasis of prosperity'' as Federal Reserve chairman
Alan Greenspan so elegantly put it.
</P>
<P>
   Back in December, the forecasters at DRI Standard &AMP; Poor's in
Lexington, Mass. predicted growth of 2.1 percent in the first half
of this year _ basically a return to something like the norm.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations for the stock market were much the same. The market
had just turned in its fourth straight year of 20 percent or better
returns, an unprecedented string of good fortune. Investors needed
to set their sights lower, the strategists said.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 13 percent as of
Tuesday; the Dow Jones industrial average and the Nasdaq index were
up more than 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even better from an investor's point of view, the strength in
the stock market in the first half was broad-based. Technology
stocks did well, but so did small-cap stocks and stocks of basic
industrial companies. Aluminum maker Alcoa, a company no one will
confuse with an Internet high-flier, has seen its stock price rise
70 percent over the past four months.
</P>
<P>
   What explains the market's strong showing? ``What was supposed
to be an average economic year has turned out to be another stellar
year,'' says Mark Zandi, chief economist at Regional Financial
Associates, a Pennsylvania forecasting firm.
</P>
<P>
   When the final numbers are tallied, economists now expect the US
economy will have grown at a 4 percent pace in the first half of
the year. Zandi and others say they were wrong because they
anticipated that weak economies in Asia and Latin America would act
as a brake on the United States. Instead those economies recovered
surprisingly quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Investors and consumers breathed a collective sigh of relief at
the news and the good times continued. ``People still feel great
about things,'' says Maureen Allyn,'' chief economist at Scudder
Kemper Investments, a mutual fund company.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation did tick up a bit in the first six months of the year
and the Federal Reserve last week boosted interest rates slightly.
But when the Fed signaled that it saw no immediate need for more
rate hikes, investors read it as a sign that the party isn't over
yet.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Freedman says some of that optimism may be justified. An
executive at John Hancock Funds, Freedman likes what he sees ahead.
``I am still very upbeat on this economy,'' he says. ``And as long
as interest rates don't go to the moon, I think the market should
be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters now expect solid growth for the second half of the
year as consumers keep spending and companies keep investing. Most
analysts see some slowing as the year progresses, in part because
of higher interest rates, especially on home mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   Under the best of circumstances, the economy will grow fast
enough to keep corporate earnings on track but not so fast as to
trigger higher inflation and more Federal Reserve rate hikes. Call
it the best of all worlds scenario.
</P>
<P>
   What could upset this rosy forecast?
</P>
<P>
   One possibility is a growing concern about stock market
valuations. At the moment the stock market is trading at a
price/earnings ratio of 31, the highest of all time. A high
price/earnings ratio indicates optimism about future earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Allyn says some of the rise in the ratio can be explained by
hard numbers. ``But you can't explain the whole thing on
fundamentals,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   David Wyss, chief economist at DRI, makes a similar case. His
model of the stock market, which is based on interest rates and
earnings, currently shows stocks to be 32 percent overvalued. Says
Wyss, ``The question is: Is this a bubble or has something
fundamentally changed?''
</P>
<P>
   If it is a bubble and that bubble should burst, the results
could be bad for both the stock market and the economy, say
analysts. Greenspan and others say part of the economy's strength
has been fed by the strong stock market. Should the market fall,
the economy could weaken, which in turn, could drag the market
lower still. Put simply, what went up together could go down
together too.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, most forecasters think the greatest danger to the
market and the economy is not weakness, but too much strength.
Their arguments goe something like this:
</P>
<P>
   If the economy keeps going like gangbusters, the Federal Reserve
will feel compelled to hike interest rates _ not once or twice, but
a series of times. So far the stock market has been able to shake
off a rise in rates. But should rates rise enough, say forecasters,
the market would swoon, much as it did back in 1994, the last time
the Fed boosted rates significantly.
</P>
<P>
   Given their recent track record, most economists and market
strategists are a bit humble about predicting the future. And if
they do get it wrong again, they hope they goof the way they have
for the past four years _ by being too pessimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really isn't a bad time to be a forecaster,'' says
Nicholas Perna, chief economist at Fleet Financial Group. ``When
things turn out better than you predicted, people don't get mad at
you.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE RED HERRING
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back in February, Chris Felipe and John Brennan, two very hot
money managers, said goodbye to MFS Investment Management, the
Boston mutual fund firm.
</P>
<P>
   The pair weren't angry. They just wanted to start _ what else? _
a hedge fund.
</P>
<P>
   Just over four months later, the hedge fund is open for
business. The company, called Sirios Capital Management, has raised
more than $500 million from investors, say those close to the firm.
The fund will invest in mid-cap and large-cap domestic stocks and
will take short positions in some stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Felipe and Brennan Tuesday declined to comment on their new
venture.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be e-mailed at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
