<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1767 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-ORGANIC-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     07-07 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-ORGANIC-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 SOUTHWICK, Mass.: ... fool's paradise.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until two weeks ago, when Diana Flynn was teaching, she rose
early, headed out to school, then worked the fields until dark. Now
she's outside all day. She got her organic certification last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   She also makes breads and cookies to bring along to the farmers'
markets. A walnut-scallion baguette is popular, she says. Some of
her baked goods go to the local health food store.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put myself on a schedule. I bake two times a week. It's
difficult working full time and trying to get things
accomplished,'' she says, passing by an outdoor table where
seedlings are still waiting to be planted. ``Most of these are
flowers. And flowers are at the bottom of the list.''
</P>
<P>
   Flynn began going to farmers' markets as soon as school was out.
In June, she was still trying to establish a routine for all the
bits and pieces a market entails: enough ice to keep the highly
perishable produce _ like lettuce and kale _ cool all day; plastic
bags for customers; a little something to give away so she could
chat with the customers. Throughout June, her giveaway was garlic
stems. Shoppers who bought something else got a few tucked into
their sack, with an explanation on how to slice them down to the
flower and add them to a pan of sauteed vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   In the first weeks, she brought chard and lettuce to the market,
along with snap peas and snow peas. She picked flowers and
fashioned little $1 bouquets. Later in the season she'll sell
golden and red raspberries, endive, radicchio, mesclun salad mix,
bee balm, lovage, bulbs of fresh garlic, yellow and purple beans,
hot and sweet peppers, eggplant, summer squash and zucchini, and
little yellow cukes. In the fall she'll have winter squash and
pumpkins.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn has heard about growers driving into Boston and earning
hundreds of dollars in one afternoon, but her operation is so small
now she might not have the inventory. Her little farm stand outside
her house opens on Friday for the weekend. Her biggest take at
market now is around $100, and she pays about $40 for a seasonal
market fee.
</P>
<P>
   She tried selling at a market in Chicopee and was disappointed
that it was held at the edge of a mall parking lot. She brought
home $30. A few days later, in Holyoke, her spot was at the end of
the short row of trucks. That meant less revenue because customers
don't want to walk the length of the market. On two recent trips to
Holyoke, she made $45, then $57.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets to you. Today I didn't leave home until noon. I was up
at 7, picking, then driving 40 minutes, setting up, packing in.
Say, from 8 in the morning until 6 at night. That's a 10-hour day.
You have to figure your gas cost, your livelihood cost. I was very
frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyoke, whose market is held Thursday afternoons, has a large
Hispanic population. Flynn says that being organic isn't an
advantage there. But she's staying. She'll try to do the
Springfield market on Wednesdays, which would give her two markets
a week. ``I don't have enough stuff to do Wednesday, Thursday, and
Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   For each market, she has to come up with the annual fee, plus $7
every time she brings her truck. The Holyoke market manager, who is
also a grower, comes over to collect her annual fee. ``Seven for
today,'' he says. ``And the 40 next week?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, of course,'' she answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't forget,'' he says, too sternly. ``Forty next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Flynn nods. The manager notices a reporter nearby taking notes.
``Next week,'' he says. Then, hesitating, ``or the week after.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, when Flynn was feeling dispirited and too far away
from her family, her mother came east to cheer her up. Terry Flynn,
who runs an auto-body shop in Vista, Calif., says, ``She's always
been a family girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Diana Flynn says her friends wonder when she'll grow up ``and
live my own life.'' She says, ``You never outgrow your need for
your family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a great childhood,'' she says. When she was young, her
parents owned a ranch they named Rancho Poco a Poco (Ranch Little
by Little). Everything got done in its time, she says. ``Me and my
brother would pack up a lunch and go horseback riding all day on a
Saturday. It was open country. A lot of it was orchards.'' She
laughs now, remembering the two kids charging through the fruit
trees on their horses. ``We had to duck so we wouldn't ride into
the cobwebs. Those were the days you could be gone all day and no
one would worry.''
</P>
<P>
   Her parents divorced when she was 11. For high school, she
boarded at Cheshire Academy in Cheshire, Conn. (class of '85), then
returned to California, where she attended four junior colleges.
When she was 21, she came east again to go to Holyoke Community
College. Eventually, she graduated from California State University
at Chico, with a major in environmental education. Afterward, she
went to Guatemala, which really worried her parents. ``She was down
there for four months, and we weren't very happy,'' says Terry
Flynn. Then she went to work on an organic farm. ``My parents
thought I was crazy,'' Diana Flynn says.
</P>
<P>
   She was raised by a mother who also wasn't afraid of hard work.
After the divorce, Terry Flynn took over the auto-body shop she and
her husband had run together. ``Talk about a man's business,'' says
Diana Flynn. ``A lot of people are surprised that she succeeded
because no (woman) had.''
</P>
<P>
   Flynn is sitting cross-legged alongside a row of lettuce,
pulling out weeds and letting them drop back onto the soil so
they'll work as mulch. Lee Warren is in the hayfield. Kristopher
Fournier is dashing all around. In places, the weeds look taller
and grander than the greens. ``If you don't time it right, you get
a mess of weeds,'' Flynn says. The afternoon is hot and she hasn't
brought water out to the fields, so she has to walk back to the
house to get a cold drink. Then back outside to weed some more.
</P>
<P>
   She's bent over, and her glasses have tipped down to the end of
her nose. In the hot sun, she moves slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poco a poco,'' she says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
