<HEADLINE>
BLODGETT SET TO HELP COACH BU HOOP TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Margaret McKeon was named new women's basketball coach at
Boston University last April, she promised to kickstart the
stuggling program. She's not wasting any time.
</P>
<P>
   Maine graduate and WNBA player Cindy Blodgett appears to be the
latest addition to the Terriers' staff, according to the Bangor
Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Tuesday how things stand in relation to the reported move,
McKeon said, ``They stand quite well.''
</P>
<P>
   Although no deal is official yet, McKeon acknowledged that she's
heard a lot about Blodgett and her accomplishments ever since
McKeon attended a basketball camp in Maine at Colby College.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had heard of Cindy, she was always mentioned,'' said McKeon.
``Then when I coached at George Washington, we played Maine twice.
We beat them both times, but she played quite well. And she was
player of the year in this conference (America East) three times.''
</P>
<P>
   McKeon said she's heard more good things about Blodgett from
Maura McHugh, as assistant coach at the Sacramento Monarchs _
McKeon was as assistant coach at Arizona State in 1987 when McHugh
was head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Blodgett, who was drafted by the Cleveland Rockers last year,
was traded to the Sacramento Monarchs in May. She's been averaging
1.5 points, one steal and 4.3 minutes per game, and had no points
in the Monarchs' 76-63 loss to the New York Liberty Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Since the WNBA season is from June through August, Blodgett
could coach during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   McKeon said she's convinced adding a player of Blodgett's
stature to BU's staff would mean a lot to the Terriers, who
finished with 5-22 last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make sure people know we are serious about
basketball at BU, and I think this would send a message,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trade is off
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In other WNBA news, the trade of UConn alum Kara Wolters from
the Houston Comets to the Charlotte Sting has been voided. Wolters
was to go to that team in return for center Rhonda Mapp. But after
Wolters underwent an MRI at her physical, Sting physicians
determined that she had patellar tendonitis in her right knee.
Since Charlotte wouldn't be able to immediately activate Wolters,
the trade was called off . . . Smith College will host the 50th
anniversary conference of the International Association of Physical
Education and Sport for Girls and Women through Saturday. The
association, founded by Smith graduate Dorothy Ainsworth, now has
members in more than 40 countries. This will be only the second
time the summit will be held in the US. Jill Ker Conway, former
Smith president and a director of the Nike Corporation, was to give
the keynote address Wednesday at 6 p.m. at Sage Hall.
</P>
</TEXT>
