<HEADLINE>
ON THE RUN _ FOR 100 MILES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHFIELD, Mass. _ Mary Kate Shea would like to bike across the
country. Take off for four months and hike the Appalachian Trail.
Do something long, arduous, adventurous.
</P>
<P>
   However, Shea has four children who need to be shuttled to
hockey practice, soccer games, dance lessons. There are muffins to
be baked, swings to be pushed, cartwheels to be admired, hugs to be
handed out, tears to be dried.
</P>
<P>
   So, at least for now, the 37-year-old wife, mother, Sunday
school teacher and freelance writer will have to concentrate on
something she considers more manageable: a 100-mile run.
</P>
<P>
   Observed a friend, Madeline Gaughran: ``I shudder to think what
her next goal might be.''
</P>
<P>
   To most people, the idea of running 100 miles _ the distance
between Boston and Hartford _ falls somewhere between outlandish
and out of the question. The idea of getting ready to run 100 miles
while taking care of four busy children between the ages of 4 and
12 falls somewhere even beyond that. But to Shea, a lifelong
athlete known among her friends and family as physically strong,
mentally tough and amazingly organized, it seems a perfect _ if
ambitious _ fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no need to settle,'' Shea said. ``You can be happy
with your life, have your children, have your work, and still want
to set goals that challenge you physically _ and, in this case,
mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge will officially begin at 4 a.m. on July 17, when
Shea steps off from the still-dark starting line of the Vermont 100
Mile Endurance Race in South Woodstock. With any luck, it will end
about 24 hours, 15,000 feet of ascent, 15,000 more feet of descent
and several successful medical checks later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be a huge mental thing,'' said Shea, who
quickly corrected herself. ``I know it's going to be a huge mental
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Shea shrugs off what many would see as the equally daunting
challenge of eking out time to train amid tending to Patrick, 12,
Richie, 10, Kate, 8, and Erin, 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having the kids,'' she said, ``you can never look at it as
saying I have to do this, this and this. It's more like, what do I
have the opportunity to do? What can you do with what you have? And
what I have is four kids.''
</P>
<P>
   That what she does is exceptional doesn't seem to dawn on her,
perhaps because she comes from a Weymouth family of nine children
that includes a sister who played rugby at Bowdoin and a brother
who played professional lacrosse, the latter of whom once stopped
to eat a burger in the middle of running the Boston Marathon. If
they take her 100-mile plans in stride (``Have fun,'' was the sole
reaction of another brother, who has climbed mountains in South
America), why shouldn't she?
</P>
<P>
   So, she trains on the treadmill after the kids have gone to bed.
During the school year, she gets her long runs in during the week.
Now that it's summer, she does them on the weekends. When her
husband, Richard, gets home from work, she heads out the door.
Running four or five days a week, Shea averages 45 miles most
weeks, and has gotten in as many as 70.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to give it the priority it deserves,'' said her
husband, who among other support efforts has taken over all
Saturday-morning duties. ``She'll always be trying to put (the
children) first, but she has to be sure to cover her own needs as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Training partner Rich Boretti of the Marshfield Road Runners,
who is preparing for his third Vermont 100-miler, said Shea
shouldn't worry about not being able to run more. ``The key is
doing a long run, and she does at least a three-hour run on
weekends,'' he said. ``That's really the key, just being out on
your feet. I'm really amazed she does the training she does. Most
people who run in the ultras are in their 40s and don't have kids.
There are very few moms who do it.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't surprise Gaughran, a runner who has three young boys
of her own. ``It's almost like you could never picture Mary Kate
having (just) one or two children, because that wouldn't be
challenging enough,'' she said. ``She's got to have five balls to
juggle.''
</P>
<P>
   An 800-meter runner in her days at Holy Cross who last year
finished the Boston Marathon in 3 hours, 33 minutes, Shea joined
the Marshfield running club in spring 1997, having moved back to
Massachusetts after 12 years following her husband's military
career to Germany, Virginia, and Texas. It was there she met
Boretti and others who had already done the Vermont race. These
people are crazy, she thought. But soon enough, she was talked into
trying a 50-mile race last October, which turned into 50-plus miles
when she got a little lost. Despite the detour, she finished in 10
hours, 40 minutes _ well under the 12-hour qualifying time required
by the Vermont 100 _ and loved it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember thinking, this will be the longest race I'll ever
run,'' said Shea, who was especially taken with the cooperative
spirit of the event compared to shorter races. ``Then, at the end,
I'm running fast, thinking 100 miles is doable.''
</P>
<P>
   Step by step, it has all come together. If she is worried, she
is, typically, keeping it to herself (``She makes the best of any
situation,'' said Gaughran, ``whether it's a dreadful situation or
a wonderful one''). As she tapers her workouts with the race
approaching, she reflects on training runs where everything has
been in tune, fluid, effortless _ the days when she felt she could
just run for hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which,'' she laughs suddenly, ``is what I'm going to have to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, and amusingly, Shea is already looking beyond the
100-miler. As if the Vermont race isn't challenge enough for one
summer, next month she and Gaughran will pack their seven children
into a couple of cars and drive to Montana, where Gaughran's
parents will babysit while the women compete in a strenuous trail
run that reaches an altitude of 9,600 feet above sea level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's only like 23 miles,'' said Shea, ``so it's a
short race.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
