<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1775 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATE-SHIFT-ART-BOS &LR;      07-07 1715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATE-SHIFT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`24-7' ECONOMY IS RESHAPING EMPLOYEE WORK SCHEDULES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is 4:20 a.m. when currency strategist Paul Podolsky sets out
for work on his 18-speed bike, entering Boston's Financial District
before the sun's first rays.
</P>
<P>
   His colleague Jeremy Fand, a 33-year-old senior foreign exchange
strategist at BankBoston, has already been on the telephone since 4
a.m. Long before the rush-hour commute begins, the two men, who
work a 5 a.m. to 3 p.m. shift, are monitoring fluctuations in the
dollar, the euro, and the yen.
</P>
<P>
   Over at Thompson Financial, computer operator Bill Thornton is
nearing the end of the 6 p.m. to 6 a.m. shift he works three days a
week, hours he says eliminate day care worries and costs.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by globalization and supported by new technology and a
booming economy, US businesses from retailers to investment houses
are now operating 24 hours a day, seven days a week. For many
white-collar professionals, that means working new shifts geared to
the 24-7 operation.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, say specialists, these nontraditional shift
workers include service employees with professional, technical,
clerical, or supervisory positions in law, retail sales, computer
operations, or finance.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is catching on. About 25 million US workers have
nontraditional hours, says the Washington-based National Sleep
Foundation. Of those, 3.2 million have full-time night jobs, up
from 3 million in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The Bureau of Labor Statistics reports the proportion of the
nation's 106.5 million work force with flexible schedules is 27.6
percent, up from 15.1 percent in 1991. Furthermore, 21.4 million
working Americans _ about one in five _ are now shift workers.
</P>
<P>
   Clark University sociologist Robert J.S. Ross attributes the
shift change to globalization, around-the-clock computing, and an
increase in the use of flex time.
</P>
<P>
   A tight labor market and a keen interest in holding on to
valuable employees are prompting some employers to design work
shifts that fit their companies' needs while also allowing
employees to attend to personal and family needs, said Ross.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain institutions have always operated 24 hours a day,'' he
said. ``What we are seeing now is a growth in those kind of
operations in industries other than manufacturing.''
</P>
<P>
   Office supply superstore chain Staples launched 17 new stores in
March, all 24-hour operations. Many supermarket chains, copy
centers, retailers, express mail services, and legal institutions
are riding the 24-7 bandwagon in an attempt to grab a bigger share
of the consumer market.
</P>
<P>
   Now the 24-7 trend is spreading into the high-powered financial
sector. Investment houses, banks, and other institutions are
finding they have to operate around the clock to compete on line
and in the global marketplace. Even the New York Stock Exchange is
considering evening and weekend hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``In today's environment, there are now people who work until 6
p.m., put the kids to bed, and then go back to work,'' said Jim
Peters, president of US retail operations for Staples. ``We want
those people to shop with us when it is most convenient for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Some workers, pointing to a need for flexibility, prefer
nontraditional hours and shifts. For others, however, 24-7 means
schedules that change from week to week, or late-night hours that
reduce family and personal time and cut into much-needed sleep. For
some, particularly low-wage women and minorities, the ability to
choose or redefine one's work schedules remains a luxury.
</P>
<P>
   Sociologist Harriet Presser, a professor at the University of
Maryland, says the shift from 9-to-5 to 24-7 is increasing within
the service sector, and will likely expand among poor women
employed as cashiers, nurses aides, food servers, telemarketers,
and cab drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Presser worries that such changes will strain marriages to the
breaking point and disrupt relations between parents and children.
In a June 1999 article in the journal Science, she wrote that men
employed at night and married less than five years are six times
more likely to divorce or separate within the next five years than
are men in traditional, 9-to-5 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When women work nights and have been married more than five
years, the odds of divorce or separation are three times as high
(as for the male night workers),'' said Presser.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's the workers' choice, fine,'' said Sarah Nathan, a
spokeswoman for the Massachusetts AFL-CIO. ``But some workers
barely have enough time to spend with their families. Others choose
the schedule because they realize that if they can work nights,
they won't have day care costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Capen, 38, fits the latter category. She oversees legal
secretaries and word processing staff as they prepare documents for
the Boston law firm Hale and Dorr. Her work week: Monday,
Wednesday, and Friday, 4:30 p.m. to 2 a.m., and Thursday from 4:30
p.m. to 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to work Monday through Friday, 9 to 5,'' said Capen.
``But when I began to have children, I changed my schedule to
weekends and then went to nights. My kids have never been in day
care. I've helped out at school, in the classroom, and I've been to
their school plays. I'm there when my kids get on the bus, and I'm
there when they get off.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton, the computer operator at Thompson Financial, says his
hours made it possible for him and his wife to avoid up to $1,000
per month in day care costs.
</P>
<P>
   Computer operator Michael Thomas, 31, took the 6 p.m. to 6 a.m.,
three-day-a-week job at Thompson for a different reason: He wanted
to switch from customer service work to the IT field.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Koen, founder of Round-the-Clock Systems: The 24-7
Solutions Co. in Portland, Maine, says some employers are expanding
work hours internally while others are getting 24-hour coverage by
linking time zones around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the regular day shift ends, employees may transfer
records to an employee in Ireland who then transfers work to
someone in India and then back to New York.''
</P>
<P>
   One example: BankBoston's Fand and Podolsky.
</P>
<P>
   The bank's global foreign exchange department was still in its
infancy when Fand, a 1988 graduate of Swarthmore College, joined
the financial institution three years ago. Now, he manages a
seven-member strategy team that works out of offices in Boston,
Singapore, and London. Together, the team tracks events that affect
the world's currencies 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   Fand is briefed by a team member in London just before dawn.
Podolosky, by contrast, begins and ends his day with calls to and
from Singapore. Their findings, culled from a nonstop flow of news,
stock quotes, and currency pricings, are presented to the bank's
trading floor at 7 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Currency markets are always open. They never close,'' noted
Fand, whose team members carry beepers, cell phones, and
``clickers,'' palm-size devices that provide real-time, 24-hour
pricing of currency, stocks, and bonds along with the world's top
headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Podolsky, a former Dow Jones writer, wears the clicker all the
time, including weekends. He reasons that if XYZ Co. is considering
a billion-dollar acquisition in another country and needs to
convert dollars to euros, a 1 percent change in the cost of the
currency could increase _ or decrease _ the transaction by $10
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that happens, customers want to know, any time or
wherever they are, whether they should ignore it or pay
attention,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, such devotion to work has some experts worried. They say
Americans' preoccupation with TV, the Internet, and their jobs is
taking too much time away from sleep. The National Sleep Foundation
reports 20 percent of the 25 million workers who have
nontraditional hours _ other than 9 to 5 _ routinely fall asleep at
work. And of those who struggle to keep their eyes open during the
day, 34 percent are dangerously drowsy, resulting in the yearly
loss of $18 billion in production.
</P>
<P>
   Fand, whose wife likes that he is home by 4 p.m., acknowledges
that he doesn't always get enough sleep but says his hours aren't
to blame. An Orthodox Jew, he observes the Sabbath on Saturdays and
sleeps 12 to 15 hours to make up for the late hours he keeps.
``Other than that,'' he said, ``I lead a night owl's life.''
</P>
<P>
   Podolsky, by contrast, is usually in bed by 10 p.m. He says his
schedule allows him to spend a significant amount of time with his
son before bedtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a while your body gets used to living on limited
sleep,'' said Capen, who works the 4:30 p.m. to 2 a.m. shift.
``When my kids are in school, I babysit for my sisters' kids. I get
out at 2 a.m., home by 3 a.m. and I am back up by 7 a.m. I get
about four hours of sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Capen says she gets more sleep on Tuesdays, when she is off.
That night, she's in bed by 9 or 10 p.m., trying ``to play
catch-up.''
</P>
<P>
   Some companies have gone the extra step to hire consultants to
help workers cope with their new shifts.
</P>
<P>
   Take Sipex, a Billerica, Mass. manufacturer and designer of
analog semiconductor circuits. Last year, it hired Round-the-Clock
Systems to teach its shift workers strategies to keep them alert
and productive during the third shift.
</P>
<P>
   Sipex night-shift manager Kathy Bourne, 39, says the course
taught her to avoid red meats and heavy meals at night; when to
sleep; and how to get the most out of the time she spends with her
children and husband, who works days.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion of shift work has sprouted a host of
consultancies. Circadian Technologies Inc. of Cambridge, Mass.
publishes a calendar and newsletter geared to spouses who work
different hours and counsels employers on developing new shifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Organizations usually need to make two major changes,'' said
Koen of Round-the-Clock. ``The first is in culture. The second is
placing a higher value on their workers. Most companies still
orient everything toward day operation, creating a sense among
shift workers that they are second-class, when, the truth is, they
make the company's operations run.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
