<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-NIALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE OTHER WORLD WAR I BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last year's 80th anniversary of the end of World War I inspired
a publishing boomlet in Britain, with entries ranging from ``The
Virago Book of Women and the Great War'' to a battlefield
travelogue bearing the unavoidable title, ``Trench Fever.''
</P>
<P>
   The book that got the most attention was Niall Ferguson's ``The
Pity of War: Explaining World War I.'' Published in the United
States in April, it offers a relentlessly revisionist
interpretation of the war's origins, conduct, and consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson (first name pronounced NEEL) is a fellow and tutor in
modern history at Oxford University. Among many other controversial
arguments, he contends Britain would have fared better as a
noncombatant and that German victory might well have resulted in a
prototype of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times has described Ferguson, 35, as ``the most
talked-about British historian of his generation.'' John Keegan, a
friend, calls him ``terribly delightful and charming.'' Ferguson, a
Glasgow native, writes often for the popular press (his wife, Susan
Douglas, is a well-known London journalist) and makes frequent
radio and television appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most historians would benefit from the discipline of having to
address a mass audience,'' he says during a telephone interview
from his office at the Bank of England, where he's researching a
history of bond trading. ``The best history is the history which
has been discussed publicly, and not just in narrow academic
seminars.''
</P>
<P>
   Finance has been an important theme in Ferguson's work. His
first book, ``Paper and Iron,'' examined the interrelationship
between inflation and politics in Weimar Germany. ``The World's
Banker: The History of the House of Rothschild'' is a massive
account of the famed European banking firm.
</P>
<P>
   World War I has a personal meaning for Ferguson, whose
grandfather fought in the trenches. ``It is, from a British point
of view, the worst war _ perhaps you might even say the worst
historical experience _ of all.. . . I'm born 50 years after it
started, but the first thing I do seriously at school as a project
is about the trenches in the Western Front because there's that
combination of oral tradition and the literature, which makes it
still seem like `the big event.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
