<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1780 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      07-07 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN VS. MEDIA; OLD NOTES FROM DOWN BEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a media-saturated age, major news events invariably unfold in
three acts: first the event itself, then the commentary on the
event, then the commentary on the commentary.
</P>
<P>
   After we've been pummeled with opinions by the punditocracy, it
can be cathartic when they're indicted for a rush to judgment. A
vivid example, of course, was Monicagate, which produced a few
squirmy moments for Sam Donaldson and other talk-show oracles when
Bill Clinton's presidency survived after all.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the Columbine High School massacre, much
op-ed and airwave commentary has focused on whether violent images
produced by pop culture contribute to real-world violence. And here
comes a wave of post-commentary commentary in this month's
Harper's, where MIT's Henry Jenkins and NYU's Thomas de Zengotita
argue that pundits, along with parents and lawmakers, are looking
through the wrong end of the telescope.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins's piece, composed as an e-mail to MIT students,
describes his testimony before a Senate committee whose members
were intent only on ratifying their assumptions about the cultural
impact of video games, movies, and the Internet. But commentators
and politicians have missed the ``key issue,'' Jenkins argues,
which ``isn't what the media are doing to our children, but rather
what our children are doing with the media.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, simple cause-and-effect equations fail to
reflect our complicated relationship to pop culture. Placing the
blame for Columbine on video games is misguided, according to
Jenkins; we need to answer why some alienated or picked-on youths
are drawn to ``brutal images'' rather than focus on the images
themselves, because when it comes to influences on young people's
behavior, ``real life trumps media images every time.''
</P>
<P>
   Zengotita approaches from another angle. He believes media
images are more powerful than ever because they are more pervasive
than ever, with better ``production values'' ratcheting up their
intensity, and asserts that virtual violence has effects even among
kids who don't act out a la Columbine: ``They go ironic rather than
psychotic.''
</P>
<P>
   But Zengotita says most mainstream pundits who talk about the
effects of media images on behavior miss the larger point that the
line between simulation and reality is quickly vanishing _ ``They
can't believe that virtual reality is real'' _ and that their glib
answers in the wake of tragedy conceal the cold reality that ``we
are at an utter loss.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's some fascinating stuff in the July issue of Down Beat,
which is celebrating its 65th anniversary by reprinting old stories
about the hallowed likes of Louis Armstrong, Billie Holiday, Duke
Ellington, Dizzy Gillespie, and Thelonious Monk.
</P>
<P>
   Because these are contemporaneous interviews and essays, we get
a glimpse of the giants of jazz when they were working musicians,
before they disappeared beneath layers of legend. For instance, Nat
Hentoff's 1955 interview with Ella Fitzgerald reveals a singer in
the throes of despair, longing to host her own TV show but knowing
it was unlikely because of ``the way things are,'' her career
stalled because her record company was giving potential hit songs
to other singers. ``I'm so heartbroken over it . . . . There must
be something I can make that people who buy records would like to
hear,'' she said. (There was: The next year, she would record
``Ella Fitzgerald Sings the Cole Porter Songbook'').
</P>
<P>
   Events now embedded in jazz history regain the flavor they had
at the time. Anguish pervades the 1955 appreciation by Leonard
Feather that begins: ``The agony of living is over for Charlie
(Yardbird) Parker.'' The tensions between big-band musicians and
bebop pioneers are manifest in a 1949 item about Buddy Rich firing
what he called the bop ``element'' in his band. When Holiday split
from Count Basie in 1938, Down Beat weighed in with gusto, blaming
producer John Hammond for ``engineer(ing) the whole mephitic
business,'' lamenting the blow to Basie, ``a hell of a swell egg,
deserving better breaks,'' and concluding that while Holiday had
landed a new gig singing with Artie Shaw, ``it is a damn shame she
has to waste her talents with a band of that caliber.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like scorpions in a bottle, the players of Monicagate can't stop
trying to give each other one last, mortal sting. This month, the
battle for the final word is being waged by proxy, as Linda Tripp's
two children, Allison and Ryan, take to the pages of George
magazine for a stirring defense of Mom and, not so incidentally, a
few nasty digs at Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The portrait they paint is not so dissimilar from the portrait
Lewinsky (inadvertently) painted during her interview with Barbara
Walters: that of a supremely self-absorbed airhead. Ryan Tripp
claims that Lewinsky routinely called his mother 30 or 40 times a
night, and even tracked the family down during a Lake Placid
getaway so she could whine about her troubles. Amusingly enough,
Tripp says he called it the ``All Monica, All the Time Show'' _ the
very label critics would later give TV's obsession with the story.
</P>
<P>
   But laudable though their familial loyalty is, the Tripp-lets
are not persuasive in arguing that their mother was a selfless
angel of mercy who was ``ministering'' to Lewinsky. And if they
wanted to be free of the suspicion of agenda-laden malice that
clings to their mother, they really should have refrained from the
wisecracks about Monica's sexual technique.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even discounting for hype, the Internet Gold Rush is a
fascinating spectacle to watch, a marriage of high-tech idealism
and get-rich-quick schemes.
</P>
<P>
   Wired, the Web-head bible, excerpts Po Bronson's new book on the
modern pioneers stampeding to Silicon Valley, ``The Nudist on the
Late Shift,'' in which he tracks the rise and failure to rise of
several would-be entrepreneurs in their mid-20s. All of them share
a cockeyed optimism that their product will be one the Net can't
live without, and all possess what Bronson calls the essential
valley trait, a ``willingness to throw oneself into situations most
people would feel are out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   Bronson's use of the first-person seems driven more by authorial
ego than narrative necessity, but that annoyance aside, he creates
absorbing portraits. There's a guy who funded his startup by
growing marijuana in western Massachusetts, a fellow who subsists
on pancakes because he agreed to forgo his salary in a bid to
attract investors, and a guy who won't get paid unless he finds
$500,000 in investment capital for his firm. All seem to work 70
hours a week, all seem to love risk, and all could end up
millionaires _ or big-time busts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 1334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1782 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-KEEGAN-BOS &LR;      07-07 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-KEEGAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NONCOMBATANT JOHN KEEGAN CONVEYS THE FEEL OF BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ World War I puzzles John Keegan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no huge issues at stake,'' he says of the subject
of his latest book, ``The First World War,'' during a recent lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very difficult to explain why the war was fought, why it
went on so long, why people were so passionate to submit to it.
It's a war where people are writing the war aims several years
after the war has begun, as the Germans did, at the insistence of
the Austrians, in 1917.''
</P>
<P>
   Such puzzlement on Keegan's part is, in a way, a tribute to the
conflict. For there are few things he does not know about military
history. Keegan, the author of 20 books on the subject, spent
nearly three decades teaching at the Royal Military Academy,
Sandhurst (the British equivalent of West Point), and for the past
13 years has been defense correspondent of The Daily Telegraph
newspaper of London.
</P>
<P>
   Keegan's fellow military historian Stephen Ambrose, speaking
from his Montana home, ranks him at ``the top'' of their
profession. Former Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger professes
``enormous admiration for his work.'' Keegan, Weinberger says from
his Washington office, ``combines literary craftsmanship of a high
order with a wide-ranging technical and historical knowledge that
enables him to convey with remarkable realism the sights and sense
and sounds and feel of battle.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes such mastery of his subject so striking is that, as
Keegan wrote in the first sentence of what remains his most famous
book, ``The Face of Battle'' (1976), ``I have not been in a battle;
not near one, nor heard one from afar, nor seen the aftermath.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1934, Keegan grew up in the shadow of war. His father
and two uncles fought in World War I; and World War II ``had a very
formative influence on me,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But military service was ruled out. At 13, Keegan was diagnosed
with tuberculosis of the hip and spent much of the next four years
in a hospital bed. While an Oxford undergraduate, he underwent a
hip fusion after the disease recurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm lame,'' Keegan says quite matter of factly. ``That was a
terrific advantage because I could ask about things, and people
would tell me when they might have said `Look, go and find out for
yourself.' They didn't say that because they realized I wasn't in a
position to.''
</P>
<P>
   For many years, Keegan had a slight limp. His condition worsened
considerably three years ago. ``My back gave out,'' he shrugs. He
now requires a cane and walks almost doubled over.
</P>
<P>
   Keegan scoffs at the suggestion that studying warfare was a
compensation for being unable to pursue soldierly derring-do. ``I
think those are little-boy feelings. I might have been prone to
them as a little boy, but I think the reality of being on a
battlefield nowadays is that you spend a lot of time cowering in
shelter and not striking a heroic figure at all.''
</P>
<P>
   A broad grin covers Keegan's face as he says this. A man who
likes to laugh early and often, he is decidedly convivial and
enjoys good talk. His conversation ranges far and wide, as befits
his specialty. ``Wars on land embrace every aspect of the life of
nations and peoples and societies,'' he says. ``In a way,
everything is relevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of two hours, the discussion ranges far from
World War I and matters martial. He happily discourses on the
Pentagon as a work of architecture, the psychology of Alger Hiss,
the relative merits of Richard Nixon, the culinary attractions
(such as they are) of Abilene, Kan., the nature of Bill Clinton's
charm, and how Americans' mania for rules are the dark underbelly
of their love of freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The last topic hits close to home. Having asked a waitress with
mock urgency, ``Can't we get something a little stronger?,'' when
she inquires whether he would like water to drink, Keegan learns he
must extinguish his cigarillo when she returns bearing his gin and
tonic. ``What's a drink without a puff,'' he sighs.
</P>
<P>
   She lets Keegan finish his smoke, perhaps charmed by his
port-and-Stilton tones. Indeed, it's an accent worthy of Gielgud or
Guinness, with a vocabulary to match. Words such as ``chap,''
``righto,'' and ``shirty'' pepper Keegan's sentences, and a
languorous ``terribly'' is his adverb of choice.
</P>
<P>
   Keegan's next book will be on the influence of
intelligence-gathering on military operations. ``It'll be largely
about the 20th century,'' he notes, ``because secrets only became
totally accessible when you got radio, when you could start
listening in and crack codes.''
</P>
<P>
   Originally, Keegan hoped to become a naval historian. One
venture into the field excepted, ``The Price of Admiralty'' (1989),
it's a path he chose not to follow. ``Naval history is a completely
different subject from the history of warfare on land,'' he
explains. ``It's so dominated by technology.. . . I've discovered
that if you make the slightest technical mistake 500 Patrick
O'Brian fans fall on you from a great height, screaming, `Fool!
Idiot! Stupid! Don't you know the difference between a shroud and a
backstay?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Keegan entered military history much in the way one enters
retail sales or any other less exalted field: through the help
wanted section.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose when I came down from Oxford I didn't really know
what I was going to do.. . . As soon as I discovered you could get
a job as a military historian, I decided, well, that's what I'll
try to do and I eventually did. I saw an advertisement in The Times
(of London) and I wrote and they said (at Sandhurst), well, it's
actually not for military history _ I think it was for modern
languages or something _ but there would be an opening the
following year. . . I waited, had an interview, and was offered a
job.'' The rest is all _ military _ history.
</P>
<P>
   It would be nearly two decades, though, before Keegan published
``The Face of Battle.'' That book's enormous critical and popular
success _ ``it was a main choice of the Book-of-the-Month Club,''
Keegan cheerfully recalls, ``so I received a vast check _ made him
realize that he could make a career of writing as well as teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hadn't imagined that I had the gift to be a writer at
all. I'd always thought that writing was a very arcane business.. .
. There was some special secret to it. Of course, I now know there
isn't, at all, actually. If you have a certain facility, if you can
put words together in a certain order, it's just a question of
sticking at it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 1335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1783 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-HOUSES-BOS &LR;      07-07 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-HOUSES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HOMES, DETRITUS OF WAR IS LEFT BEHIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEC, Yugoslavia _ Every house in Kosovo holds a story of the
war, and many of the tales are not yet told.
</P>
<P>
   In Jeton Bala's home, Serb soldiers left behind tools of
violence and destruction, sinister calling cards of the uninvited
houseguests.
</P>
<P>
   The 50 or so Serb militia who took over Bala's home during the
war did not bother to clean up when they departed, and the filth
they left is a chilling reminder of what was done inside the house
while Bala was waiting out the war as a refugee in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Inside a cabinet is a grenade, tucked into a belted leather
holster. Dozens of bottles of gasoline, oil, and other substances
to set houses afire litter the front garden.
</P>
<P>
   A military vest was left behind, as were dirty, military-green
socks. A metal box for bullets was dumped in the den floor, along
with some ammunition and a rope baton, presumably for beatings.
Drugs and a hypodermic needle lie strewn on a bookcase, and Bala's
coffee cups, used and not washed by the Serbs, are on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The windows are covered with blankets. The cellar was turned
into a bomb shelter and apparently a place for mixing Molotov
cocktails, judging by the glass bottles and rags found lying
around. A suspicious cable, which Bala fears is attached to a mine
or booby-trap, snakes through the overgrown backyard grass.
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy, sleeping in the same house the enemy used as a
base to destroy his ethnic Albanian neighbors' homes and, perhaps,
kill some of them.
</P>
<P>
   But Bala has nowhere else to sleep, and feels lucky that there
is enough of his house left standing that he can restore it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess my house was not burned because they were living
here,'' muses the 22-year-old Bala. He points to his mattresses and
sofa-beds the Serbs left undone, places where Bala now spends his
nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where else to sleep? All I can do is clean it all out,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tahira, 72, is also sleeping in a bed used by Serbs. But it is
not her own home, which was burned to the ground by Serb
paramilitary, her neighbors told her, just hours after the peace
deal between NATO and Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic was
signed last month.
</P>
<P>
   So Tahira, who did not want her real name used, moved into an
apartment abandoned by Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   It's much smaller than the grand house Tahira lived in with her
extended family. Like many Kosovar Albanian families, Tahira's clan
had put much of their money and effort into their home, which
housed several generations and an endless stream of houseguests.
</P>
<P>
   Her apartment now is grim and utilitarian, the walls bare of
photos, the furniture cheap. The windows have been criss-crossed
with masking tape, a feeble effort by the departed Serbs to keep
the glass from shattering in case of NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably with more time to pack, the departing Serbs left an
apartment that was clean, yet cleaned-out of anything valuable,
save a TV and VCR.
</P>
<P>
   Tahira does not like laying her head on a Serb's bed, in a
Serb's apartment, in what had been a largely Serb housing block.
She does not like the feeling of eating from Serb plates, in a Serb
kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   But ``what else can we do?'' Tahira asked, weeping softly as she
caressed her grandson's hair. ``If we don't use this apartment, we
will have to sleep on the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most Serb houses and shops were undisturbed during the war, but
the return of Albanian refugees, some of them angry and vengeful,
meant the Serb properties were not safe for long.
</P>
<P>
   Some Albanian families, like Tahira's, moved into the houses of
Serbs, who themselves fled in fear of retribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``KLA Commander Here _ Don't Touch!'' says a note inked into the
wooden door of one formerly Serb apartment here. Other apartments
have handwritten Albanian names pasted on the door, covering the
names of the one-time Serb occupants.
</P>
<P>
   Other Serb residences have been set afire, either by Albanians
or by Serbs who would rather raze their houses than provide shelter
for Albanians, NATO officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have many, many reports of houses burning, but always it is
too late'' to stop the damage by the time Kosovo Force
peace-keepers get there, said K-FOR spokesman Major Vincente
Dalmau. In the area around Pec, the western Kosovar region where
the worst reported Serb atrocities occurred, there are as many as
20 reports of house-burnings a day, Dalmau said, and sometimes
entire villages have been burned.
</P>
<P>
   With so many Serbs gone from Pec, the Albanians here now fear
their fellow Albanians. One Pec man returned June 17 to find that
his home, also used as a base for Serb forces, had been looted of
nearly everything, except for some valuable Oriental chairs and a
dressing screen. By the time the man's father returned to begin
repairing the house, it had been looted again, this time, by
Albanians, who said they would kill the man if he tried to retrieve
his things.
</P>
<P>
   Linda, a young Albanian woman, returned to her Pristina
apartment to find that an Albanian family had bunked there, though
she said the family was prepared to leave now that she was back.
</P>
<P>
   Bala said he sleeps in his unfinished home because he is afraid
Albanian neighbors will steal his furniture. Tahira's greatest fear
is that the KLA will burn the Serb apartment she now occupies,
unaware that an Albanian family now lives there.
</P>
<P>
   For those who managed to stay in their own homes during the war,
the memories can be nightmarish. Sandwiched between two Serb
militia bases, one of which was Bala's place, Safet Idrizi said she
saw it all: the firebombs being made in Bala's house, then thrown
into Albanian homes. The house across the street was used as a
prison by the Serbs, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The house on the other side of Bala's place was a telephone
center, and Serbs lured girls inside by telling them they could
call their families, she said. Behind the heavy door, the girls
were raped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard them screaming. I heard their voices inside,'' said
the 36-year-old Idrizi, her seven children clutching at her dress.
</P>
<P>
   Idrizi still can not believe she is alive. Bala sorts through
instruments of death. And Tahira hopes she will be alive long
enough to again live in her own home, and not the cast-off of
Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they come back, we will leave,'' she said. ``But we have no
place to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
