<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1785 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-ORGANIC-2TAKES-A     07-07 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-ORGANIC-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREAMS AND DIRT 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHWICK, Mass. _ Three years ago, on a springlike day in
mid-March, Diana Flynn and her family and friends in Vista, Calif.,
celebrated her 30th birthday. Then she hooked a trailer onto her
old pickup, packed her worldly possessions, put her dog and cat
into the cab with her, and raced across the country in 3 1/2 days.
Her destination was this little town south of Springfield on the
Connecticut line.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn was about to become an organic truck farmer _ to grow
vegetables and take them to market. ``I was on a mission,'' she
says. ``I wanted to start that season.''
</P>
<P>
   What she found was cold and wind. It was much too early to
plant. ``This isn't California,'' she told herself one chilly day.
</P>
<P>
   She had moved 3,000 miles bent on becoming the next generation
at Flynn's Farm _ land her Connecticut-born dad had bought 17 years
ago. ``Since I was 15,'' she says, ``we talked about this place
being a generational thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The first thing she did was pick a new name. Flynn's Farm became
the Thankful Earth Organic Farm. Her sign replaced her father's.
</P>
<P>
   Like the women 300 years ago who worked this land against all
odds, Diana Flynn is something of a pioneer. She operates on a
shoestring, largely alone, practicing organic techniques she
learned in California, and trying to turn the farm into a viable
business. She races to keep a row ahead of weeds that threaten to
dwarf her produce; she has no irrigation in one of the dryest,
hottest summers on record; and there are days when she misses her
family so much, she has to call home for a pep talk.
</P>
<P>
   None of this shows.
</P>
<P>
   Athletic and strong, Flynn is mellow in the way only someone
raised in southern California can be, and she seems genuinely happy
on the land. Kristopher Fournier, the 10-year-old grandson of a
friend, is spending time with her this summer, and he uses the farm
as a giant playground, rushing to show her his latest discovery.
Two of Flynn's potbellied pigs are nibbling her plants, and she
laughs at how silly they look. ``Aren't they hilarious?'' she asks.
``They only eat weeds.'' Journey, her dog, is being chased by Lexi,
her boyfriend's dog, and both come to a grinding halt in the row of
lettuce she has just finished weeding. ``Hey, guys,'' she says,
without raising her voice, ``not here.'' One of the three roosters
is crowing. (Two live in a tree outside her bedroom window and
begin their routines very early.) The duck is chasing the goose.
``They're mated for life,'' she explains.
</P>
<P>
   Thankful Earth Farm is a child's paradise, and one day Flynn
hopes to host children there. ``I love children,'' she says. In the
off-season, she works for the local school system as an aide to a
4-year-old nonverbal autistic boy she describes as ``a character, a
happy, very loving kid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to be involved with special-education kids,'' she
says. Flynn is studying at neighboring Westfield State College to
get certified in teaching. One day, she says, she'd like to plant
``a kid's garden with no rules, where they can do whatever they
like.''
</P>
<P>
   There's an old A-frame in the back woods of the farm, and she
imagines a program in which teenage girls could stay overnight. At
one point, she thought about starting a camp. ``But farming
overtook that a little.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, she weeds _ and, in the heat, she weeds like crazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The term `farmer' gets reduced to `weeder,' '' says Flynn's
boyfriend, Dudley ``Lee'' Warren, 43. Warren spends weekends in
Southwick working the farm, fixing machinery, and mowing the 40
acres where organic hay grows. During the week, he works at a
printing company on the Connecticut coast. He hopes to find another
job closer to Southwick so he and Flynn can live together. ``A big
part of what I do involves Lee,'' says Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   The hay feeds two untrained horses, a brother and sister named
Rocky and Brandy. No one can ride them now, but sometime this
summer Flynn will do a trade with her student's mother: While Flynn
works with her son, the mother will train the horses so they can be
led with halters. Then, when the weather turns cold, Flynn will be
able to walk the horses from the field to the barn. ``I can walk
one now, but the other scares the dickens out of me,'' she says.
``And I've had horses all my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocky and Brandy grazed on the three acres that Flynn now
cultivates for produce, and she's sure that contributes to the good
soil. A pond and a well are on the land, so if she ever decides to
irrigate, she has water. She's not worried about the dry spell.
``We don't irrigate. If you start, you have to continue. If you dig
down,'' she says, ``the soil can be moist a couple inches down. It
depends on what your soil is like.'' Hers, she says, ``has a rich
humus and lots of good compost.''
</P>
<P>
   Thankful Earth Farm's 61 acres are located in the ``Southwick
Jog,'' where the horizontal border between Massachusetts and
Connecticut dips slightly, the result of a 17th-century surveying
error. A pocket of the Bay State is surrounded on three sides by
Connecticut. ``This farm is in the extreme southwest corner of that
land,'' says Warren, who is the president of the Connecticut
chapter of the Northeast Organic Farming Association.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn's father, Patrick, who was raised in nearby Bloomfield,
Conn., bought the farm with the intention of working it after his
retirement. For many years, he spent seven months here selling hay,
usually breaking even. He expects to help out in early October when
his daughter plans a pumpkin celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Flynn pays the mortgage on the land when Diana can't.
``When she needs help, she asks for it,'' he says, ``but she wants
to do it on her own.'' She comes up with money for her living
expenses, truck fuel and maintenance, seeds, farm insurance, and
machinery repairs. ``Lee has also put a lot of time and money into
this farm,'' says Diana Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   Her father put the farm into an Agricultural Preservation
Restriction program, which means that the state owns the
development rights so no one can build on it. If the land were
sold, Patrick Flynn would have to buy back the development rights
from the state. ``But I'm not going to do that,'' he says. ``The
farm is going to be hers anyway _ hers and her brother's.''
</P>
<P>
   The preservation program, says Diana Flynn, ``is a good
incentive for young families. It's land. How many single women can
afford to buy land?''
</P>
<P>
   She's not entirely alone out here. Flynn aunts and cousins live
nearby, though she doesn't see them very much. When, as a teenager,
Flynn would come east with her brother and father, her mother would
say, ``You guys are going to fool's paradise.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
