<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-HILLARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `ULTIMATE BALANCING ACT': CANDIDATE AND FIRST LADY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A typical day last week in the life of the most
active and activist first lady went like this:
</P>
<P>
   A millennium event on preserving historical documents at the
National Archives. A White House meeting on the effect of Medicare
cuts on teaching hospitals. A drop-by at Treasury Secretary Robert
Rubin's farewell party. A family outing with daughter Chelsea and
husband Bill to the quarterfinals of the Women's World Cup. And
many, many phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Now, into what aides say is this superwoman schedule, Hillary
Rodham Clinton is about to wedge one more thing _ a campaign for an
open US Senate seat in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are used to juggling many roles every day, and I have no
doubt that Mrs. Clinton will be able to juggle one more
undertaking,'' said Melanne Verveer, the first lady's chief of
staff. ``In actual practice, we have to see how it evolves. It will
be the ultimate balancing act.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, ``Where's Hillary?'' is about to become a
favorite parlor game. Tuesday, Mrs. Clinton made history when she
filed papers with the Federal Election Commission and officially
launched a political exploratory committee aimed at capturing the
seat in 2000 of retiring Democratic Senator Daniel Patrick
Moynihan. Wednesday, as she sets off from the senator's farm in
Oneonta, N.Y., for a four-day ``listening tour'' of the state, a
new chapter opens on the country's most controversial and
scrutinized first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``The listening tour will put her face-to-face with New Yorkers
in small settings,'' Howard Wolfson, Mrs. Clinton's campaign
spokesman said, adding that the first lady's get-acquainted trips
to her adopted state will span most of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   It has been clear for some weeks that Mrs. Clinton had made up
her mind to do what few of her close friends expected and what Carl
Sferrazza Anthony, a biographer of first ladies, called
``unprecedented'' and more. ``It is amazing, it is overwhelming,''
Anthony said. ``But if any woman could handle being first lady and
a Senate candidate, Hillary Clinton is the one.''
</P>
<P>
   It is generally agreed that Mrs. Clinton has set a new standard
for what it means to be first lady and political partner to the
president. But the implications and consequences of her likely run
for the Senate are just starting to sink in.
</P>
<P>
   For example, how will she coordinate her ceremonial White House
duties with what is expected to be a bruisingly partisan campaign
against New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani? Where will she live? How
will she handle an aggressive press corps that for years has been
held at bay by a very protective White House staff and the
unofficial status of her job? Who pays for her travel and how will
she utilize the perks of the White House? What role will the
president play? And how often will she be at odds with or try to
influence Clinton administration policy?
</P>
<P>
   ``From now on, everything she does as first lady is going to be
viewed through the prism of `does it help her or hurt her in New
York?' '' said Paul Costello, who was first lady Rosalynn Carter's
press secretary. ``There are apt to be situations where the White
House makes policy that runs counter to New York, and it will be
interesting to see how Mrs. Clinton balances it and weighs in.''
</P>
<P>
   That has happened already. Mrs. Clinton was invited by New York
political and labor union leaders to join them at a White House
meeting last week in arguing that the administration's plan to
overhaul Medicare would cut payments to New York's teaching
hospitals. Mrs. Clinton did not dominate the session, her press
secretary told reporters, but she did share the hospitals'
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   During a news conference the same day, President Clinton said he
will not be offended if Mrs. Clinton goes public with some of the
policy disagreements they have had in private. ``That's the way
democracy works,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to laugh: On one hand, Hillary Clinton is criticizing
some aspect of her husband's Medicare plan, and on the other we
hear that the president is going to be one of her most important
political advisers,'' said Sheila Tate, former press secretary to
first lady Nancy Reagan. ``I think it's schizophrenic, and it's a
good example of how strange and peculiar Mrs. Clinton is making
life for herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Tate says she cannot imagine that Mrs. Reagan ever contemplated
a run for public office.
</P>
<P>
   But historians say Mrs. Clinton, a lawyer by training and a
policy advocate by experience, has redefined the role of first lady
to the extent that this political race is not so extraordinary.
Mrs. Clinton has spearheaded an ambitious but unsuccessful
health-care reform plan, championed women's rights in dozens of
foreign countries, raised millions of dollars for Democratic
candidates, testified before an independent counsel's grand jury,
and advised the White House on strategy through a sex scandal and
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Clinton has done some good things, but I think now there
will be this nagging question that maybe everything she did in the
second term was inherently political,'' said Myra Gutin, author of
``The President's Partner'' and a professor at Rider University in
New Jersey. ``I think her Senate candidacy will really affect her
legacy and how she is perceived.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the public supports the first lady's pursuit of a
political career. A recent NBC/Wall Street Journal poll found 68
percent of Americans believe the first lady can perform her White
House duties while running for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton has told her staff she has no plans to give up her
policy issues, her causes, her travel, and her entertaining in and
restoration of the White House. ``She has said to all of us that
while this is a new process, she is not intending to give any of
her responsibilities as first lady short shrift,'' Verveer said.
</P>
<P>
   But the West Wing of the White House has come under fire from
the Republican Party and some public-interest groups for an alleged
misuse of federal resources to support Mrs. Clinton's frequent
political trips to New York. GOP chairman Jim Nicholson last week
asserted that Mrs. Clinton's flights on military aircraft had cost
the government more than $220,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillary's flying military jets, but it's the taxpayers who are
being taken for a ride,'' Nicholson said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House insists the exploratory committee, which allows
Mrs. Clinton to raise money, will pay for future travel, a
headquarters and separate staff in New York, and any other expenses
her campaign incurs. But the first lady will not be able to
reimburse the Secret Service for the security and logistical
support it is required to provide her, and she may never convince
New Yorkers that the Manhattan traffic nightmares created by her
presidential-sized entourage are absolutely necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Clinton's stature as first lady will enhance her Senate
race, but it will also reinforce her status as an outsider in New
York,'' Costello said.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, a political scientist at Claremont
Graduate University, said that beyond the serious issues of White
House perks is the ethical question of whether the first lady is
trading on her position, and even on her misfortune in the wake of
the scandal involving Monica S. Lewinsky, to advance a political
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may be prudish about this, but it seems to me that this
particular first lady allowed herself to be part of a campaign
promise and package to the American people _`elect one, you get
two,' '' Jeffe said. ``Now, I wonder if her candidacy would be so
real if people didn't perceive her as the wronged woman, and that
this is her way, and the electorate's way, of getting back at the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Letitia Baldrige, who was first lady Jacqueline Kennedy's social
secretary, remembers Mrs. Kennedy carried out her duties ``through
thick and thin,'' and took an unconventional route _ taking up with
Greek tycoon Aristotle Onassis _ at a appropriate time after her
government role had ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has never been a first lady running for office, and
maybe there shouldn't be,'' said Baldrige, a doyenne of
Washington's dwindling white-glove manners and good taste.
``Hillary Clinton has a huge job right here in the White House, but
she will have to shirk her duties _ she certainly won't be the
hostess with the mostest _ if she is off in New York somewhere,
giving a campaign speech.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 1341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1790 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-BROWN-BOS &LR;      07-07 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-BROWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL EYES, SOME NAYS ON BROWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Elinor Gatto, a lifelong San Franciscan,
considers Mayor Willie L. Brown Jr. a sure-fire winner, and she
could hardly contain her excitement at having won him for part of
the day.
</P>
<P>
   The grandmother of eight and the first-term mayor were slated to
have lunch on a recent afternoon _ her prize for the highest bid in
a parochial school auction. She called it her chance do good and
also to thank Brown for bringing style back to both the city and
City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``That he came out to the school really touched me,'' said
Brown, who was accompanied by her oldest grandchild. ``I just like
him. He's got style.''
</P>
<P>
   But as he gears up for next year's mayoral elections, Brown has
found that his colorful, press-the-flesh style may not as easily
satify other voters this time around. Although the election remains
his to lose, with supporters as well as many opponents predicting
victory, the adoration of the early days has waned even as San
Francisco continues to enjoy an unprecedented economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   Known for his impeccably tailored suits and brimmed hat, the
mayor was once hailed as a hero around San Francisco. As one of the
most powerful Democrats in the state, the former California
Assembly speaker still commands attention. President Clinton has
already given his endorsement. But recent polls find only about a
third of voters saying they expect to vote for him Nov. 2 _ half
the two-thirds support that swept him into office in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not bet against Willie at this point just because his
ratings aren't as high as they were,'' said Bruce Cain, a political
science professor at the University of California in Berkeley.
``Willie will survive by keeping out a competitor, or at least
keeping out competitors on the left. . .But I don't think he's
taking anything for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Brown faces no formidable competition on either end of
the political spectrum. Only Clint Reilly, a real estate magnate
who made millions working as a Democratic political consultant,
even merits a mention from most political observers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the filing deadline is almost a month away, and any
number of name candidates could still emerge. The entrance of
openly gay Board of Supervisors President Tom Ammiano, as expected
by some despite the Brown camp's claim that it has his word
otherwise, could siphon off votes and force an election runoff in
December.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is a candidate, or a potential candidate,
out there who can build the coalition Willie Brown has built,''
said Brown campaign spokesman P.J. Johnston. `` His politics and
personality fit with this city. . .But we have to remind our
supporters and instill in our volunteers that this is no
cakewalk.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in no other major city would a mayor overseeing such
prosperity need even entertain uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Since Brown took office in January 1996, unemployment has been
cut in half. Surging city revenues have transformed budget deficits
into surpluses. At $4.2 billion, his latest budget calls for more
than 1,000 new city jobs. Crime is down. Building is booming.
Property values are soaring. Public works projects include a
massive airport construction project.
</P>
<P>
   But San Francisco is no typical city. Socially liberal, more
conservative fiscally, with enough political factions to merit the
term Balkanized, residents tend to grumble about whoever is in the
mayor's office. They turned out each of Brown's last two
predecessors after one term.
</P>
<P>
   Now they are holding the current mayor accountable for not
solving the homeless problem or fixing the public transportation
system as he pledged to do in 100 days. Paul Boden, executive
director of the San Francisco Coalition on Homelessness, estimated
that as many as 14,000 homeless people sleep on the city's streets
on any given night. Despite some improvement, the buses and trains
still do not run on time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are disappointed in the mayor, especially in
regard to his ability to resolve some intractable problems,'' said
veteran pollster David Binder. ``They had their hopes raised that
Willie Brown being the consummate Sacramento politician with all
his power and trappings could be the one to bring real change.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many others, Binder said that Brown's personality reflects
the city's: flashy, flamboyant, quick with a quip. He also called
the mayor uniquely suited to keep the peace among San Francisco's
inevitably warring factions.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, disputed that Brown has brought the city
together, saying he has made criminals of the homeless and pitted
the working class against the wealthy as housing prices rocket. The
man who ran the Assembly for 15 years has now turned City Hall into
his own personal fiefdom, they complained.
</P>
<P>
   ``This administration carries a tremendous amount of clout, more
than anything I've ever seen,'' said Boden. ``At the same time, his
style of leadership is incredibly dysfunctional. Every city
department hates each other. There are power grabs and money
fights.
</P>
<P>
   Said Tom Pier, Clint reilly's campain spokesman, ``This has
become Willie Brown's machine town. There is no organized
opposition to his tenure. He controls all of the institutions, all
of the money, all of the people, be it business or political. .
.Who else is going to try to take him down?''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, David Lee, executive director of the Chinese
American Voter Education Commission in San Francisco, said he would
have called the race a ``sweeper'' for Brown, who won with support
that cut across racial, ethnic and class lines. Now, with the
mayor's poll numbers so low, Lee is waiting to see what other
candidates jump into the race. Still, Brown's support among the
city's large Asian American community remains strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Willie Brown has the power of incumbency, the greatest name
recognition,'' Lee said. ``Everyone knows him. They don't all like
him, but everyone knows him. Barring any major developments, he
should be able to sail in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
