<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, July 8:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBS (Belgrade) _ A news analysis: With high level of
misery throughout Serbia and with nothing for people to do, the
anti-Milosevic movement is growing much faster than organizers had
anticipated. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   PENTAGON-EUROPE (Washington) _ The Pentagon is aggressively
pursuing a policy encouraging trans-Atlantic mergers in the defense
industry, using its Kosovo experience to talk directly with
European allies and major defense contractors in Europe in a new
push for cooperative agreements. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-BARAK (Jerusalem) _ On his first working day in office,
Prime Minister Ehud Barak announces a series of meetings with Arab
leaders to restart stalled Middle East peace efforts: Egypt's
Mubarak on Friday, the Palestinian's Arafat on Sunday, Jordan's
King Abdullah next week. Then he sees President Clinton next
weekend in Washington. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-LIBYA (London) _ Britain announces that it will resume
ties with Libya, which agreed to pay compensation for the killing
of a policeman outside its London Embassy in 1984. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-CHINA (Tokyo) _ Japan's prime minister, Keizo Obuchi,
leaves Thursday for a major visit to China that aims to soothe
relations between the two great powers of East Asia and to boost
the prospects of admitting China into the World Trade Organization
by the end of this year. By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-KIM (Tokyo) _ North Korea marks the fifth anniversary of
Kim Il Sung's death, using occasion to further bolster Kim Jong Il,
``who filled an aching void in the hearts of the people left by the
demise of the President.'' By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE-REBELS (Abidjan, Ivory Coast) _ Sierra Leone
rebels, who have waged a guerrilla war for nearly a decade, today
accepted an offer of four cabinet seats in a national unity
government in return for laying down their arms. By Norimitsu
Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POVERTY (Pine Ridge, S.D.) _ President Clinton tours an
Indian reservation where unemployment is 80 percent, then heads for
Phoenix on day 3 of his poverty tour. By Peter T. Kilborn. (Eds,
may sub dateline)
</P>
<P>
   With a sidebar
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TORTILLA (Phoenix) _ On the tortilla factory Clinton
visits. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   MASS-DRUG-PLAN (Boston) _ As the federal government debates
plans for coverage of prescription drugs for the elderly, the
governor of Massachusetts has proposed his own plan, in which
seniors would pay a basic premium and get unlimited prescription
drug coverage once their bills exceed $1,500. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ALZHEIMER-VACCINE (Undated) _ A drug company that had
engineered mice which develop the brain anomalies typical of
Alzheimer's Disease says it has developed a vaccine that can
reverse them. Though it remains to be seen if the vaccine improves
mouse cognition, or if it will work at all in people, the work has
aroused excitement among researchers. By Lawrence M. Fisher. (1200
words)
</P>
