<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTRONIC-GIVING-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTRONIC GIVING BOOSTS CHURCH COFFERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SARA NEUFELD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At St. Peter's Lutheran Church on Cape Cod, the faithful still
drop dollar bills and checks into the collection basket.
</P>
<P>
   But a new program soon could push aside the collection plate as
the preferred way for some congregants to show their Christian
charity.
</P>
<P>
   Starting this month, members of the Harwich, Mass. congregation
can give glory to God electronically by having funds automatically
transferred from personal accounts to the church's account.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of savvier congregations are tapping into
high-tech ways to boost their coffers. At least 1,500 churches
across the country have started electronic funds transfer programs,
which many Americans use to pay everything from mortgages to cable
bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps us to be better givers and more consistent givers,''
said the Reverend Jane O'Hara Shields, pastor of St. Peter's. ``No
more leftovers.''
</P>
<P>
   There is some early evidence that high-tech giving programs tend
to loosen the wallets of churchgoers.
</P>
<P>
   One national program run by a Lutheran organization that has
enrolled more than 1,000 churches found that the average monthly
electronic offering is about $190.
</P>
<P>
   That compares with a monthly average of $33 that Protestant
Christians typically give their churches every week, according to
one recent study by Empty Tomb, an Illinois-based Christian
research group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response has just blown us out of the water,'' said Royce
McEwen, an assistant vice president with Lutheran Brotherhood,
which is based in Minneapolis. ``We just can't get caught up on the
voice mails with congregations wanting information on how to get
enrolled in the program.''
</P>
<P>
   At one Roman Catholic Church in Minneapolis, for example, an
electronic funds transfer program started five years ago generated
enough income to allow the parish to create larger programs to help
the poor and homebound seniors, set up extra Sunday school classes,
and start a Sunday night Mass.
</P>
<P>
   About 500 of the 4,600 members at Basilica of St. Mary now
participate in the program. Many of them are young parishioners who
had not donated regularly in the past, said Thomas Green, the
church's director of finance and administration. Younger Catholics
who have grown up surrounded by computers seem to be comfortable
with the idea of electronic giving, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some church officials said this new style of collecting means
worshipers can concentrate on the word of God without worrying
about how much cash they have on hand to toss into the collection
plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got less clutter in their mind and heart to properly
prepare to celebrate the liturgy when they come to church on Sunday
mornings,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   But the increasing popularity of electronic funds transfer
programs has drawn criticism from some church officials who say the
practice takes away from the religious significance of giving.
</P>
<P>
   In many Sunday services, ministers typically lean on the Bible
and appeal to Christian responsibility to encourage members to
donate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a further distancing of the people from the personal
and mysterious aspects of worship,'' said William Albert Taylor,
stewardship director for the Church of God in Christ, a
predominantly African-American Pentecostal denomination based in
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Donating to churches electronically, some church officials said,
reduces something that should have religious significance to an
action as routine as paying the telephone bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many people, that tangible act of putting something in the
offering plate is the act of giving thanks for what God has given
them,'' said Terry Parsons, stewardship officer for the Episcopal
Church in America.
</P>
<P>
   At St. Peter's, which has 475 members, Shields acknowledged that
some more traditional-minded Christians might balk at embracing the
new technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a stigma and that will need to be overcome, like
anything else that's a change and a new way of thinking,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Though her church is starting an electronic giving program, the
old-fashioned collection basket will still be available for those
like Walter Walek, 68, who prefer to put their hands on the money
they donate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I just don't think that way,'' said Walek, St. Peter's
treasurer, adding that he doesn't pay any bills electronically. ``I
like to keep a little better handle on what's happening month to
month.''
</P>
<P>
   But St. Peter's congregant Wesley Schneider, 72, said electronic
giving ensures that churches are not shortchanged.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many times, people take care of all their necessary
expenses and then if there's something left over, they say, `Let's
give something to the church,' '' Schneider said.
</P>
<P>
   And though it might not be as visible as placing cash or checks
into the collection plate, Shields believes electronic giving can
be just as spiritual.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's why it's given and to whom we're giving it and how
generous we are with it,'' Shields said.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid making it seem that people who donate electronically
are giving nothing, the Lutheran Brotherhood electronic funds
transfer program provides envelopes with turquoise stickers bearing
the name of the program, ``Simply Giving,'' to put in the
collection plate.
</P>
<P>
   While local congregations in various denominations offer
automatic giving programs set up through individual banks or
electronic banking firms, so far only the Lutherans have
established a nationwide program.
</P>
<P>
   Since it was launched last September, 1,150 of the nearly 19,000
Lutheran churches in America have signed up for electronic giving,
including 14 in New England.
</P>
<P>
   A main goal, McEwen said, is to give churches a more predictable
income flow even when church attendance dips during the summer
vacation season, or in the winter when people leave northern
climates for warm-weather destinations.
</P>
<P>
   To donate electronically, church members simply fill out a form
designating how much they will give on a weekly, semimonthly, or
monthly basis.
</P>
<P>
   Churches that have started programs say participants tend to be
their most generous donors.
</P>
<P>
   Vanco Services, a Minnesota-based electronic banking company
that administers the program for Lutheran Brotherhood, has created
similar programs for dozens of Catholic, Episcopal, Evangelical,
Methodist, and other Christian congregations.
</P>
<P>
   In Vanco-administered programs, individual congregants are
charged $1 to enroll in electronic giving programs, while churches
must pay 25 cents for each transaction. Lutheran Brotherhood,
however, picks up the tab for the Lutheran congregations.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who are leery of electronic giving acknowledge that
tradition may not be able to stop technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all going to be doing this within five to 10 years
because of the generational shift, the way in which we transact
business,'' Parsons said.
</P>
<P>
   Shields said electronic giving seems to fall in line with
today's lifestyle. ``Writing checks is going out the window,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
