<SLUG> BC-NEW-MAFIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BOSTON MAFIA, ANOTHER STEP BACKWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY RAKOWSKY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- For decades, Boston sported a branch office of La Cosa
Nostra, complete with a North End clubhouse, hangouts in East
Boston and Revere, and a sub shop in the Prudential Center.
</P>
<P>
   Like other Mafia thugs, they stole, extorted, and murdered, but
there was a home-grown characteristic to the crime organized by
familiar bad guys like Gennaro ``Jerry'' Angiulo and Charles
``Charlie Q'' Quintina.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, however, with generations of mobsters and wiseguy
wannabes behind bars, Boston hasn't been able to groom a new
godfather.
</P>
<P>
   The result, say law enforcement officials, is a new low in local
control of the Mafia _ last week's arrest of a Boston Mafia
hanger-on who's accused of sharing drug profits with a
(itals)Philadelphia(unitals) crime family.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something new,'' said Linda Vizi, FBI spokeswoman in
Philadelphia. ``We've seen the tentacles of the mob reach beyond
the immediate area in the past, but not into New England.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only is Angiulo's generation of leaders behind bars, but so
are many of his successsors, like reputed boss Francis P.
``Cadillac Frank'' Salemme, who hardly had a chance to rule before
he was indicted on racketeering charges four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Into the breach rushed such brash upstarts as Robert Luisi Jr.
of Medford, the only one left standing after the noontime massacre
in the 99 Restaurant in Charlestown four years ago that killed his
father and cousin.
</P>
<P>
   It was Luisi who was arrested June 28 along with Philadelphia
crime boss Joseph ``Skinny Joe'' Merlino, his alleged boss in
long-distance crime. A complaint filed in US District Court in
Boston accuses the two, and three other Boston area men, of
conspiring to sell cocaine to an undercover FBI agent.
</P>
<P>
   Crime experts say they doubt the incursion into Boston was
invited, making it akin to a hostile takeover attempt. And that
could doom Luisi and Merlino, whose father was an underboss before
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not only an embarrassment, that kind of violation of the
rules would really tick off a guy like Frank Salemme,'' said Dennis
O'Callaghan, the FBI's former organized crime chief supervisor.
``If I were Luisi and Merlino, I would be happy I was locked up.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Boston has been off-limits to outside crime
families. Law enforcement authorities have tracked Boston visits in
the past few years by John A. ``Junior'' Gotti, the reputed boss of
the Gambino crime family in New York, and by a West Coast-based
member of New York's Genovese crime family.
</P>
<P>
   Until the late 1980s, Boston had long been a wholly-owned
subsidiary of the Patriarca crime family based in Providence, which
held regional dominion over racketeering. The one exception was the
area west of Worcester, which was formally shared with the Genovese
family.
</P>
<P>
   Merlino's foray into Boston, which led to FBI arrests in
Philadelphia and here, is testament to the weakness of the New
England family, law enforcement officials say, and the breakdown in
discipline throughout the Northeast, which was carved up into
underworld turf in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia traditionally has been an organized crime
stronghold, with more members than New England and a seat on ``The
Commission,'' sort of the Joint Chiefs of La Cosa Nostra. New
England has always had to derive its power through Genovese
representation on the board.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI in Philadelphia said it has evidence that Luisi, who is
not believed to be a made member of the Mafia in Boston, was not
only inducted into the Philadelphia family but promoted to
``capo,'' or captain.
</P>
<P>
   Luisi apparently finagled that role by claiming he controls
day-to-day Mob activities in Boston, according to tape excerpts in
court documents.
</P>
<P>
   If Luisi's claims to power are nothing more than
self-aggrandizement to make a drug deal, he could be in real
trouble, said O'Callaghan.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Mawn, FBI special agent in charge in Boston, said it is
surprising that anyone would utter a claim that he is in charge of
a Mob organization, given the bureau's strategy of picking off
anyone who flirts with leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're in a state of disarray, but because of the money
involved and the prestige, there are still a number of people
scrambling to position themselves in power,'' Mawn said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
