<HEADER>
A1807 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-COUNTRY08-COX     07-07 0303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-COUNTRY08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    June Carter Cash re-creates homespun sounds for '90s
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Toting an autoharp, praising Jesus and mangling the
pronunciation of ``Quentin Tarantino'' in one typically
idiosyncratic lyric, June Carter Cash isn't merely the queen of
old-timey traditional music _ she's a Holy Goof. It's her blessing
and her curse. As a member of country's founding family, the
Carters, and a collaborator with husband Johnny Cash, the vocalist
is at once sassy and reverent, high-spirited and humble. Her
cornball streak worked fine in the 1960s, when country radio
thrived on hits such as ``Jackson,'' but it was always her
gravel-throated mate who put the fear of God in everyone _ until
they forgot about him, too.
</P>
<P>
   Much as Johnny Cash reinvented himself in the '90s by going back
to his bare-bones origins (and accepting songs from a new
generation of rock songwriters), so June re-
</P>
<P>
   creates the traditional acoustic sounds she first made with the
Carter Family. Famous friends _ including Marty Stuart, former
son-in-law Rodney Crowell and string wizard Norman Blake _ drop by
for an informal session that unreels like a musical autobiography.
Carter Family staples (rough-hewn spirituals such as ``Diamonds in
the Rough,'' ``Meeting in the Air'') share the disc with true-life
Elvis reveries (``I Used to be Somebody''), rustic signatures
(``Ring of Fire'') and a comical ode to a granddaughter (``Tiffany
Anastasia Lowe''), warning her to stay away from a certain
filmmaker who ``makes his women wild and mean.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a hoot, pure and simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Press On''
</P>
<P>
   June Carter Cash. Risk/Small Hairy Dog. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Dollar
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
