<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1809 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-MINIS08-COX     07-07 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD mini reviews
 &HT;    Staff reports
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``Venni Vetti Vecci''
</P>
<P>
   Ja Rule. Def Jam. 20 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Considering how often Ja Rule says he's a skillful murderer,
it's surprising how often he misses on this debut. The gruff
rapper's unofficial bow on Jay-Z's ``Can I Get a ...'' was fine
enough. And this album's first single, ``Holla Holla,'' is a hit
that gurgles with pop dance floor appeal even while it speaks
lyrically to the street corners. But a lot of this lengthy effort
could be placed out on the curb. It's like Ja Rule saw these 20
tracks as 20 opportunities to say ``It's murder'' in a different
way. Once that's accomplished, if the blowhard happens to change
his delivery (``Let's Ride''), stumble upon some impressive
production (``Kl 'Em All'') or actually come up with another
potential hit (``Nz Theme'') _ hey, lucky shots.
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  BLUES
</P>
<P>
   ``Rising Son''
</P>
<P>
   Big Bill Morganfield. Blind Pig.
</P>
<P>
   12 tracks. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   When blues wailer Big Bill Morganfield groans, ``it must be that
same thing'' (that makes a preacher put his Bible down), he mangles
the consonants until it sounds more like ``bust knees of seven.''
So as a former English teacher, he's all washed up. But this debut
CD from the son of the late McKinley Morganfield (better known as
Muddy Waters) shows that as a musician Big Bill is ripe and ready
to rock. A beefy voice, a tight band (including four of Waters'
former sidemen) and bare-bones production (``I Just Keep Lovin'
Her'' sounds like it was recorded in a closet) all produce a
likable opening salvo for this Atlanta resident. Morganfield romps
through a good-time selection of original material and blues
standards, including his dad's cheerful ode ``Champagne and
Reefer,'' and his own droll lament, ``Dead Ass Broke.''
</P>
<P>
   _Bo Emerson
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``The Soft Bulletin''
</P>
<P>
   The Flaming Lips. Warner Bros.
</P>
<P>
   14 tracks. Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Lead Lip Wayne Coyne and his band mates make pop music that is
both challenging and gorgeous, with a healthy disregard for current
trends. Musical genres as disparate as country and progressive rock
are fodder for the psychedelic soup of ``The Soft Bulletin.'' Each
track is suffused with so much melodic and instrumental invention
that it takes several spins to wrap the mind around it all. There
hasn't been a more sublime song released this year than
``Buggin','' bursting with tunefulness like the overgrown child of
Big Star and XTC. Like fellow New York state residents Mercury Rev,
the Lips have no problem reconciling experimentation and song
craft. With a dearth of new ideas in so much recent music, this
band sounds willing and able to make up for the deficit.
</P>
<P>
   _Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
