<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-POP08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    George Jones faces up to `Cold Hard Truth'
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's been shot, cut, smashed up in cars and pickled in alcohol.
But if country's most legendary bad boy ever decides to hang up his
guitar, George Jones has a promising second career _ as a
tent-revival preacher.
</P>
<P>
   This new CD, recorded in the weeks before Jones' near-fatal car
accident last spring, is a starkly beautiful package of
cigarette-in-the-ashtray country songs about regret, forgiveness,
redemption and love. Standing on the edge of old age, the
67-year-old Jones takes his stronger-than-ever, lonesome baritone
and exorcises his demons into the microphone.
</P>
<P>
   As in most great country tunes, the lyrics are the narcotic that
sets the hook. In ``Choices,'' he confesses, ``At an early age I
found/I liked drinkin'/
</P>
<P>
   and I never turned it down.'' (This was the eerie tune Jones was
listening to when he crashed his sport utility vehicle with an open
bottle of vodka on the floorboard.) On ``Bed of Roses,'' he wails,
``Someone is always left behind/when this life closes/So I sit
alone and watch it rain/on our bed of roses.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of album that makes you realize just how far
today's pop-flavored country has strayed from the home place. But
Jones isn't living in the past. He's staring at it, rolling the
mistakes around in his head. As a result, he sings with the
heartfelt insight that only age and experience bring.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome back, George _ one more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cold Hard Truth''
</P>
<P>
   George Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Asylum. 10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   _Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
