<P>
   POLITICAL
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY _ WEST DAVENPORT, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton has been
to New York a dozen times this year as the nation's first lady, but
on today's trip she's a candidate for the Senate. For her first
official campaign appearance, Mrs. Clinton chose the homestead of
the man she hopes to succeed, Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan. It is
the first stop on what aides describe as a summer-long ``listening
tour'' of the state. (Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-JOURNAL _ PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ The carnage in Kosovo
was the first story I have covered that was bigger than it looked
on television. In Hurricane Andrew, in 1992, the casualties were
limited and life continued in many parts of Miami. December's
bombing of Iraq provided good televised fireworks, but most Iraqis
were barely inconvenienced. But Kosovo was a story of blind ethnic
hatred -- the poison that germinates with simple bigotry and
transforms so easily into bloodshed. Its ravages are not confinable
to a television screen. The acts of evil were too numerous for a
journalist to report and too vast to escape. (Kaplow, Cox News
Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Moving in (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Mug of Kaplow available.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CARE _ CARE staff members joke it's the Australian word for
chaos and CARE workers, it seems, are people who enjoy going about
doing good, especially if it involves a lot of going about. But
behind the flurry, there is a method and a commendable motive.
(Graham Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
