<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-AFFLICTION08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nolte, Coburn add power to `Affliction's' visceral punch
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Affliction'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   If you've got family problems, this is absolutely a must-not see
video.
</P>
<P>
   Adapted and directed by Paul Schrader from the novel by Russell
Banks (the same writer responsible for ``The Sweet Hereafter''), it
stars Nick Nolte as Wade, a small-town lawman who manages to screw
up every relationship in his life. That list includes his
girlfriend (Sissy Spacek), ex-wife (Mary Beth Hurt) and daughter
(Brigid Tierney), whom he manages to misunderstand or disappoint
with startling regularity. Already poised on the brink of violent
delusion, things get worse when a hunting accident brings out
Wade's paranoia. It doesn't help that he has a killer toothache.
</P>
<P>
   Nolte was justly nominated for a best actor Oscar, and unjustly
(like Ian McKellen in ``Gods and Monsters'') was overlooked in
favor of that Benigni fellow. But his portrait of a man
disintegrating from the inside out is unforgettable.
</P>
<P>
   So is James Coburn's Oscar-winning turn as Wade's abusive,
drunken dad, the source of all his son's problems. Though the movie
is a little sloppily shaped (compounded by an out-of-place
voice-over narration by Willem Dafoe, playing Nolte's brother),
``Affliction'' is still a terrific, feel-bad movie. (VHS priced for
rental; available on DVD, $29.98.) Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
