<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1826 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WONG-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-07 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WONG-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA VS. USA: REMEMBER, IT'S ONLY A GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM WONG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Saturday's final game in the Women's World Cup
between the United States and China ought to be sporting
entertainment at its finest.
</P>
<P>
   Our world being what it is, however, it could also be the latest
loyalty test for Chinese Americans and perhaps many other Asian
Americans. The question of whether Chinese Americans are loyal to
the United States has cropped up in the news media glare over
suspicions that a Chinese-American scientist may have illegally
passed U.S. nuclear secrets to China.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, the question lurked in the foreground when a
handful of Chinese Americans were accused of illegally soliciting
or funneling hundreds of thousands of dollars from Asian sources to
President Clinton's 1996 presidential campaign and to the
Democratic Party. On the basis of the alleged spy scandal and the
campaign finance dust-up, many Chinese Americans and other Asian
Americans feel the ripple effect of the complicated post-Cold War
political atmosphere in which China looms as the new Evil Empire
for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Now we have the potential of a women's soccer game serving as a
metaphor for allegiance to national interests.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. women's team has caught the American public's
imagination. It is the embodiment of gender equality in American
sports. Its image is that of a selfless team of mature athletes, in
sharp contrast to the greedy petulance of athletes playing, say,
professional basketball or tennis. The Chinese women's team, much
less well-known to Americans, is said by soccer analysts to be
quick and fast. This would not be the first time that athletic
teams representing different nations have worn the mantle of
political and cultural nationalism. It happens every four years at
the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Purists say sport should be sport and politics politics and
never the twain meet. Purists do not live in the real world. In the
United States, athletes of Asian descent are still relatively rare,
although growing in numbers. The most famous today are golfers
Tiger Woods (who has Asian, African, and European bloodlines) and
Se Re Pak, ice skaters Kristi Yamaguchi and Michelle Kwan, tennis
player Michael Chang, baseball players Hideo Nomo and Hideki Irabu.
</P>
<P>
   The prevailing stereotypes about people of Asian descent are
that we are small, short, mathematically and scientifically gifted,
unsexy and unathletic. We are sometimes thought to be invisible,
despite our growing visibility in all lines of endeavor, athletics
included.
</P>
<P>
   It is with those stereotypes in mind that the viewpoints of a
few Chinese Americans I have talked with about the forthcoming
U.S.-China women's soccer game make for provocative fare. My survey
was totally unscientific and, consequently, has a huge margin of
error. But it is nonetheless reflective of reality and truth. One
Chinese-American woman said she is rooting for the Chinese team
because ethnic Chinese people in the United States have rarely
gotten recognition for their achievements.
</P>
<P>
   Another Chinese-American woman said she would root for both
teams as a sign of international friendship. She said she has a
friend who is an accomplished soccer player, but she also wants to
cheer for the Chinese team out of cultural identity and because
Asians have such a low profile in this country.
</P>
<P>
   A Chinese-American man had an interesting twist. He said if the
United States went to war against China, he would be loyal to the
United States. But on the matter of the upcoming soccer game, he
will be cheering on the Chinese team based on physical
characteristics he shares with its players and not with the
American players (all of whom are white except for the goalie who
is black).
</P>
<P>
   He does not view his support of the Chinese team as an act of
disloyalty to the United States. ``It's only a game, an
entertainment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope Chinese Americans who root for the Chinese team won't
be branded as disloyal in what, after all, is truly only a game,
not life and death or a matter of national security.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (William Wong is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is wongink(at)earthlink.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
