r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-07 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESSES ARE LOSERS IN THE X GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Three days after the X Games street luge event
was over, Alan Young was not surprised to find two ESPN trailers
still taking up space in a small parking lot off Point Lobos
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me they would have everything out of here by Sunday
night, but they didn't,'' Young said. ``That's typical of the way
it's been since they first told us of their proposal to close the
street.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of San Franciscans and millions of ESPN viewers may
have viewed the extreme sports X Games as totally awesome and cool.
Young wishes they'd never come near him or his business.
</P>
<P>
   A retail gifts dealer, Young has owned the souvenir shop at the
Cliff House for 26 years. Only once before, he said, did an event
close Point Lobos and Lincoln Highway: ``Streets of San Francisco''
spent a day filming there.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was at least 15 years ago,'' he said. ``They gave me a
check for $1,000, which didn't make up for the lost day (of
business), but it did make my expenses. I didn't have to lay
anybody off.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so with the four-day closure for the X Games. Business was
so bad, Young told three of his five employees to stay home.
</P>
<P>
   Tour buses _ the life blood of his business _ could not get down
the street to make their Cliff House stop. Tourists in private cars
couldn't get near the place either.
</P>
<P>
   ``The week before, during the same four-day period, we took in
$15,447,'' Young said. ``The four days that ESPN closed the street,
we did $5,337.44.''
</P>
<P>
   And much of that came from selling faux X Games T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   On March 25, 1998, a week after Mayor Willie Brown announced
that he was making a ferocious bid for the '99 X Games, ESPN
officials met with business owners in the Cliff House area. (The
city already had made space available for ESPN's planning offices
on Treasure Island.) A few days later, Young got a letter from Tim
Reed, the X Games operations manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``The X Games organization is very sincere about making this
event work for you,'' Reed wrote. ``We are more than willing to do
everything in our power to make this a positive experience for all
of the businesses and residents in the greater Richmond area.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed asked for a personal meeting ``in the very near future ...
in order to assure that every detail regarding your establishment
is addressed. The X Games organization prides itself on superb
planning and we want nothing to be overlooked.''
</P>
<P>
   In April, Young said, an ESPN executive paid him a visit and
Young reemphasized his dependence on tour bus access. ESPN's
proposed solution _ golf carts to ferry bus passengers a few blocks
down to the Cliff House _ was unworkable because buses only stop
for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Young said, ESPN held more informational public
meetings. An associate attended one and told Young, ``It was just
like the first one.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the weeks Young said he called ESPN at least five times and
left messages. No one called back. He sent a certified letter. Then
a Fed Ex. Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Young said, ESPN called a meeting for June 18.
</P>
<P>
   Convinced that the street closing ``proposal'' had never been in
doubt, Young wrote asking for an $18,000 deposit against whatever
money he might lose during the four days.
</P>
<P>
   He was told he ``should have written this letter weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed did not return two messages I left for him, but, in all
fairness, he and the ESPN staff were deep into staging and
broadcasting the games.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one of Young's business neighbors, Ralph Burgin, the
general manager of the Cliff House restaurant, said he found ESPN
``very accommodating.'' Every night X Games workers cleared the
area of luge ``walls'' so the restaurant could have its parking
back. On a Saturday afternoon, they allowed a wedding party with 40
cars to drive down and unload.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe they want to come back next year,'' Burgin said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, the Cliff House barely broke even and wouldn't
have done that well if he hadn't sold food from stands on the
street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our waiters were very unhappy,'' Burgin said.
</P>
<P>
   Young admits that he can be cranky, but he swears, ``I don't
really jump up and down just to jump up and down.''
</P>
<P>
   He just finds it ironic that the X Games are sold to cities as
great for business yet he, a longtime San Francisco business owner,
``got shafted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had all the time in the world,'' he said, ``I'd call
around to small businesses in San Diego and Providence (previous X
Games sites) and find out how many happy campers there aren't
there. But no one would care. When it's little tiny stores,
nobody's going to care.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
