<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REALITY CHECKS THAT DON'T BOUNCE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If you want a reality check in Cleveland or
Chicago, you probably talk to a machinist or meatpacker on the next
bar stool. How do you do a reality check in San Francisco, the city
where reality checks bounce?
</P>
<P>
   Basically, you have to check into all kinds of people's reality.
</P>
<P>
   One of my reality checks is occasionally having breakfast with
Wally Shore. He's a retired typesetter and jack of all trades who
lives on Social Security with his cat and his library of hundreds
of books in a government-subsidized hotel at the corner of Jones
and Eddy.
</P>
<P>
   Shore has managed, against heavy odds, to construct a decent
life for himself at this most dangerous and substance-addled of all
San Francisco corners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a containment zone,'' Shore said. ``People who hang out
there can do whatever they want to each other as long as they don't
do it to others.''
</P>
<P>
   We went up to the Olympic Cafe on Geary, where you can get diner
food of the genuine non-Fog City type delivered by a waitress named
Hedy, who makes you feel like a million bucks, the way a genuine
diner waitress should.
</P>
<P>
   Shore and I talked about the lives of those without a million
bucks in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   We talked about how badly kids are educated in this town and
elsewhere in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's on purpose,'' Shore said. ``They don't want them to get
smart. They want them to get just smart enough, just literate
enough to be computer literate so they can sit in a cubicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Data entry is the new ditch-digging,'' said this one-time
ditch-digger.
</P>
<P>
   We talked about life in his hotel. He said that recently he
dialed 911 and the emergency operator grilled him for minutes
before sending an ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man had a long medical history and many things wrong with
him, but they didn't want to send an ambulance because of the
address,'' Shore said. ``They thought he might just be drunk.''
</P>
<P>
   Shore told of woman he knew who was kicked out of a drug rehab
center because she kissed a guy in the lobby. Shore said busybodies
inflated it to an orgy, and she was immediately kicked out, with no
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   So you get the picture. If you're down and out in San Francisco,
you're not only short of money or lack a place to live, but you get
no trust, privacy or other human considerations.
</P>
<P>
   Shore pulled out some newspaper clips on the proposal that the
city issue vouchers for room and board instead of cash to those on
General Assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vouchers, another controlling insult for the poor,'' said
Shore, who is not on General Assistance himself. ``The presumption
is that the poor are spending money on booze and drugs. What about
money to get around?''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the Department of Human Services says that more than
half of welfare recipients have a medical disability other than
substance abuse. Lord help them if they have to buy prescription
drugs on their income.
</P>
<P>
   One hotel owner has claimed that sometimes thousands of hotel
rooms go empty at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not likely,'' said Shore. ``We probably have a thousand fewer
rooms because of recent fires.''
</P>
<P>
   Shore and I talked about dozens of subjects under the fog.
</P>
<P>
   One thing he said struck home: ``I keep hearing a lot of talk
about `ordinary people' and `regular people,' as if the poor and
the rich aren't regular people.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ___ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In other reality checks: On Friday, a welfare-to-work street
sweeper gave me a big ``Good morning,'' and I asked him if San
Franciscans were still slobs. ``You wouldn't believe it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look what I found today.''
</P>
<P>
   He held up a pair of handcuffs (gay parade litter or a sign of
lax police work?) and said, ``I've got to get a real job.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ___ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rashad Williams, a student at Archbishop Riordan High School in
San Francisco, recently delivered $18,000 he raised by running the
Bay to Breakers race to Lance Kirklin, the student who was badly
wounded at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a news report on Rashad's trip, a single donor gave
$15,000 to Lance's medical fund.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, Lance and his father will head to the San Francisco
area to visit Rashad and his family. On July 18, Rashad will throw
out the first pitch to Lance when the Oakland A's play the Colorado
Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes reality is very good indeed. A production company even
has talked to Rashad's mom about making a reality-based television
movie.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
