<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1830 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-EUROPE-$ADV11-CO     07-07 1678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-EUROPE-$ADV11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BELGIUM'S COKE SCARE LATEST SYMPTOM OF EUROPE'S FOOD HYSTERIA
 &HT;    With EUROPE-BOX-$ADV11.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., July 11 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Sometime in mid-January, a farmer in West
Flanders noticed that some of his chicken eggs had failed to hatch.
</P>
<P>
   From the ones that did hatch emerged deformed chicks. He called
a veterinary inspector, who had the eggs and chicks tested. To the
inspector's shock, the tests revealed dioxin -- a notorious
carcinogen -- in concentrations several hundred times greater than
accepted levels. Thus began what some Belgians call
``Chicken-Gate,'' a complex affair that helped bring down a
government and ended the career of a veteran prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   It also set off a chain of events that so far has cost
Atlanta-based Coca-Cola Co. $60 million and incalculable damage to
its image.
</P>
<P>
   The Belgian food scandal, which is highlighted by nightly news
footage of piles of pink chicken and pig carcasses buried in pits,
has reverberated far beyond the borders of this country of 10
million.
</P>
<P>
   Across Europe fears about food and drink have become a potent
force in the '90s, dividing nations, terminating political careers
and making every sip and bite an unappetizing source of
contemplation.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Coca-Cola with a lapse in quality control sufficient
enough to make some of its bottles and cans to smell and taste like
rotten eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Coke's misadventure came with the a public in near panic and a
discredited government grasping for the appearance of competence
and honesty.
</P>
<P>
   These virtues seemed sorely missing in the government's handling
of the dioxin crisis, which came to light months after the initial
discovery when the news was broken by a television reporter. The
level of outrage among the public simmered to full boil by late
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Voters vented their fury at the polls June 13, ending the
government of Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene(CQ, the respected
politician who held together a fractious coalition for seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the crisis, government ministers dropped like dinner
chickens. In late May with the chaos in full blossom, Luc Van den
Bossche, a dour, battle-tested bureaucrat and deputy prime
minister, was assigned to fill the vacant posts atop the ministries
of environment, social affairs and health.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after the chain-smoking former prosecutor was
parachuted in to sort out the mess, the Coca-Cola file hit his
desk.
</P>
<P>
   On June 8, a dozen students at a Catholic school in the
prosperous town of Bornem were taken to a local hospital
complaining of vomiting, nausea and headaches after drinking small
bottles of Coca-Cola during their late morning break.
</P>
<P>
   During the day another 21 kids trickled in; and overnight six
arrived at the hospital. Fifteen of the 39 were admitted.
</P>
<P>
   A Belgian Coca-Cola executive came to the school in the
afternoon after getting a call from its headmaster. Samples were
gathered and dispatched to labs in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The next day the company faxed a letter to the school
acknowledging that the illnesses may have had something to do with
its products.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, eight students at a school in Brugge, a favorite
tourist destination, reported getting sick after drinking Coke
products. This incident prompted Van den Bossche to pay closer
attention.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, 30 students of about the same age in the town of
Lochristi 20 miles away from Bornem reported similar symptoms after
drinking cans of Cokes and Coke products from a vending machine.
They were transported by ambulance to Ghent, the largest city in
the region.
</P>
<P>
   Images of retching children being rushed to hospitals were
featured on the evening news.
</P>
<P>
   Similar reports began to flood the government -- 112 students
from five schools reported they were getting sick after drinking
Coke products.
</P>
<P>
   In Van den Bossche's office, it was becoming obvious that the
Belgian government had a potential new crisis on its hands. ``I'm
eating dioxin and drinking Coca-Cola,'' said one bureaucrat as the
new crisis joined the old one.
</P>
<P>
   Coke began withdrawing some of its products, but the reports of
illnesses persisted. In all, 249 people sought medical attention in
Belgium for symptoms they associated with drinking Coke products.
</P>
<P>
   In the first week, government officials complained that Coke was
neither sensitive to the government's position nor forthcoming with
explanations.
</P>
<P>
   On June 14, a clearly exasperated Van den Bossche surprised
everyone by banning the sale of all Coca-Cola products until
someone could tell him out why all these people were getting sick.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, he was telling aides that the soft drink company
deserved what it was getting for not being more open and failing to
understand the sensitivity of public sentiments about food safety.
</P>
<P>
   Van den Bossche also found it irritating and arrogant that Coke
would not divulge its secret formula, which raised suspicions that
something may have gone awry with the syrup.
</P>
<P>
   Very early on, an advisory panel of doctors advised him that the
Coca-Cola crisis could be explained as a mass psychosomatic
reaction -- now the broadly accepted explanation -- but he was
unwilling to risk the wrath of Belgian parents by telling them that
it was all in their children's heads.
</P>
<P>
   He also expressed concern about appearing soft on the American
corporate giant. ``Coca Cola is a big company, it's a symbol, it's
the United States,'' said Michel de Muelenaere, the home news
editor for the national daily Le Soir.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it soon became clear that government scientists, who tested
the beverages for 15,000 toxins, could find nothing to warrant a
continued ban. Coca-Cola provided its own explanation that the
bottles had become contaminated with sulfur-laced carbon dioxide
gas and the cans had come in contact with a fungicide on wooden
pallets. Neither substance was found in high enough levels to
explain the symptoms, adding credence for the psychosomatic theory.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, to the vexation of Coke executives assembled in a war room
at the company's suburban Brussels plant, Van den Bossche agreed
only to ease but not lift the restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the minister feared to lose face,'' said Benoit
Nemery, a toxicologist and a member of the government's advisory
team of doctors. ``After being so radical, it would have been very
difficult for him to say, 'Sorry, that wasn't really necessary.'''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as the air of suspicion continued in Belgium other
countries either joined in restricting Coke products -- as in the
case of France -- or took pains to reassure their citizens that
Coke products sold in their countries were safe.
</P>
<P>
   Within days, Coke had a full-scale crisis on its hands.
</P>
<P>
   While executives in Belgium seemed to understand the perilous
environment in Europe, the situation seemed to be grasped slowly by
Coca-Cola executives in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after the ban was enacted, Coke finally responded in a
big public way with chairman Douglas Ivester issuing an apologetic
statement. Two days after that, Ivester arrived in Brussels to
focus his personal attention on the crisis -- 10 days after it
began.
</P>
<P>
   Philippe Lenfant, a Belgian Coca-Cola executive, said the
company perhaps reacted too slowly. ``I admit we perhaps lost
control of the situation to a certain extent,'' Lenfant said during
a television interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a crisis-management strategy,'' Lenfant said. ``But
the crisis was bigger than any worst-case scenario we could have
imagined. The first couple of days of the crisis we didn't know
(the cause), and I humbly admit that we should have said so more
clearly.''
</P>
<P>
   The ban was lifted June 23, even though Van den Bossche lamented
that no one had yet given him sufficient explanation as to why so
many people fell ill.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Atlantans could be forgiven for failing to master
the mind-numbing nuances of Belgian politics -- one frustrated Coke
executive observed: ``You don't have to have banana trees to have a
banana republic.'' -- or comprehend that the concern over food
already bordered on hysteria.
</P>
<P>
   The dioxin scare is only the most recent in a series of such
crises involving European governments and failures either to
adequately inform the public of a risk or to color the truth enough
to lose all credibility. After the mad-cow disease scare in
Britain, occasional bouts of e-coli, fears over hormone-laced beef
from the United States and even aspersions of beef blood
derivatives used in French wine, consumers don't know what to
believe.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, consumers for months have had to eat breakfast
contending with newspaper reports on the creeping threat of
Genetically Modified food -- called ``Frankenstein Food'' by
tabloid headline writers.
</P>
<P>
   The public rejection of such foods has been intense -- even
though they are common in the United States and have not been shown
to pose any health threats. Two major European food producers
decided to capitalize on the concern. Nestle and Unilever are
introducing lines of ``GM-free'' foods, while other companies have
decided to pull their products containing these genetically
modified foods from store shelves.
</P>
<P>
   All this has created an atmosphere both complex and hostile for
companies such as Coca-Cola, to whom image is everything.
</P>
<P>
   Had this all occurred before that farmer observed the problems
with his eggs and chicks, Coke's problems would have been greatly
reduced, said Muelenaere, the Le Soir editor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been something because it is Coca-Cola,'' said
De Muelenaere, whose newspaper featured Coke stories side-by-side
the dioxin stories for a week last month. ``But you would not have
seen the government behave as aggressively as it did or the media
causing so much -- I don't want to use the word 'hysteria' --
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
