<HEADLINE>
SCOTLAND: WHERE THE PAST MEETS THE PRESENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (With: SCOTLAND-IF-GO and SCOTLAND-CLANS.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KAREN DAVIS  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDINBURGH, Scotland _ Precisely at 1 p.m. Monday through
Saturday, a cannon booms from the windy ramparts of Edinburgh
Castle.
</P>
<P>
   Residents can set their watches by the cannon blast as they
stroll among the shops on busy Princes Street, 425 feet below. The
gunfire _ blanks, of course _ has been tradition since 1861, when
ships used it to set their chronometers before leaving the River
Forth. (The gun was fired at 1 p.m. instead of noon because it was
cheaper, and quieter, to fire one round instead of a dozen.)
</P>
<P>
   Today, ship crews no longer need to listen for the cannon to set
their clocks, and most residents probably set their watches by the
radio or a clock at home.
</P>
<P>
   But the tradition continues. It's a fitting symbol for Scotland,
a land where past and present blend as smoothly as a barrel of fine
Scotch whiskey.
</P>
<P>
   There's still a wee bit of the Highland rebel in the hearts of
many loyal Scots. The movies ``Rob Roy'' and ``Braveheart,'' both
profiles of Scots who rebelled against the English, were hits here
as well as in the United States, and helped boost tourism in
Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Queen of Scots, who defied Elizabeth I of England and
eventually lost her head for it, is remembered fondly here.
</P>
<P>
   On May 12, Scotland made modern history by reconvening its
Parliament after an absence of 292 years and Queen Elizabeth II
presided over the formal opening of the Parliament on July 1. The
Scottish Parliament was dissolved in 1707 and Scotland became part
of Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's the spirit of independence that charms visitors
from the United States, which had its own struggles with the
British. But more likely, it's the green hills, the rocky Highland
crags and the friendly people, and their wonderful accent.
</P>
<P>
   All that, and the 500-plus golf courses in the country most
commonly associated with the origin of the game. And the 100-plus
whiskey distilleries, many producing varieties you can't find
anywhere but Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Avid golfers can book a golfing tour of Scotland through a
travel agent or buy a golfing pass from tourist agencies in
Scottish towns. These passes, which start at about 50 British
pounds ($85 U.S.) entitle the holder to play on a variety of
courses in the area for a specific number of days.
</P>
<P>
   St. Andrews, the most famous course in Scotland and perhaps in
the world, will be the site of the British Open on July 20-23,
2000. It's located in the town of the same name, north of
Edinburgh.
</P>
<P>
   There actually are two St. Andrews courses _ the Old Course (par
72), founded around 1400, and the New Course (par 71), opened in
1895. And there are five other courses in the immediate area.
</P>
<P>
   Some American golfers say St. Andrews is a bit rough for their
taste, and experts advise that you make reservations at least a
year in advance if you want to play the Old Course. But other
courses at St. Andrews and elsewhere, such as the four at the
Gleneagles resort northwest of Edinburgh, have easier access. And
even small rural courses are well-kept and often challenging.
</P>
<P>
   The large Gleneagles hotel complex includes other diversions _
shooting, falconry, a spa and exercise area and two
off-road-vehicle courses.
</P>
<P>
   We found the falconry particularly interesting. Harris hawks are
used to hunt rabbits and birds in the surrounding woods. If you
don't want to hunt, you can don a thick leather glove and have one
of the birds fly from a nearby perch to land on your wrist. Despite
their size, the hawks only weigh about 1 1/2 pounds because they're
mostly feathers and their bones are hollow.
</P>
<P>
   When it's time for a drink, you'll find a wide variety of Scotch
whiskeys in the restaurants and pubs. The Scotch Whiskey Heritage
Center, on the Royal Mile just outside the Edinburgh Castle gate,
has a store stocking numerous varieties, and there's also a bar
where you can do your own sampling. If you want something more
elaborate, you can reserve a tasting session with a member of the
center staff.
</P>
<P>
   Our tasting session was educational and fun. First, we were
given 10 small glass bottles, each containing a cotton ball
drenched with a different scent.
</P>
<P>
   We were told to write down the name of each substance as a test
of our ``nosing'' ability. Most of us got only a few right.
</P>
<P>
   After that, we tasted three varieties of Scotch, from a light,
almost lemony variety to a heavy, smoky brand. It's safe to say
that all of us were in an excellent mood by the time we finished.
</P>
<P>
   A tour of the center explaining how Scotch is made costs the
equivalent of about $4.25 for children, $6 for students and $8.50
for adults. A tasting costs about $9.35 _ adults only.
</P>
<P>
   If you want a closer look at the process of making what the
Scots sometimes call ``the water of life,'' you can visit some of
the distilleries and get a free tasting at the end of the tour.
</P>
<P>
   We visited Glenturret distillery, near Crieff in Central
Scotland. It's the country's oldest highland malt distillery,
established in 1775.
</P>
<P>
   It's also one of the smallest, with the production handled by
only six people. Glenturret is along what's known as the Malt
Whiskey Trail, a 70-mile route featuring eight distilleries.
</P>
<P>
   At Glenturret, you can walk from room to room, following the
distilling process. Early on, the mixture foams and smells like
beer in huge wooden vats. After fermenting for two days, it's tubed
to the giant copper distillery next door. The liquid goes through
distillation twice, and the best of it eventually winds up in oak
casks for aging.
</P>
<P>
   Like wine, the older whiskey is, the better. Glenturret whiskey
is sold in lots of 12, 15, 18, 21, 25 and 27 years, with the oldest
being the most expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Whiskey isn't the only product made in Scotland. You can buy
bagpipes (prices start at around $1,000 for a basic model) or a
wool kilt in any of the popular clan tartans. Some shops even offer
rental tartans for dressy occasions _ the Scottish equivalent of
the tuxedo.
</P>
<P>
   Scottish woolens are considered particularly fine, which is not
surprising in a country that has more than twice as many sheep as
humans _ 14 million sheep to 5 million people.
</P>
<P>
   At the Scottish Wool Center in Aberfoyle, north of Glasgow,
visitors can get an idea of what it's like to breed and raise
sheep, herd them with the help of Shetland sheepdogs and harvest
their wool each year. The center opened in 1992 and has separate
visitors' programs for summer and winter.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the things we learned from the humorous (and often
earthy) talk were:
</P>
<P>
   _ One shepherd now looks after about 1,200 sheep, twice as many
as in times past. The dogs help, fixing the sheep with a gimlet
gaze that dares them to disobey.
</P>
<P>
   _ Once a ewe is impregnated, owners use sonograms to determine
the number of lambs she's carrying. Then they mark the ewe's head
with a color indicating that number.
</P>
<P>
   _ A contract shearer can clip 400 bleating, wriggling sheep a
day.
</P>
<P>
   One other thing we learned at the center is how much fun it is
to shop there. I couldn't resist a plush mohair cardigan.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the other attractions, one of the most pleasurable
pastimes in Scotland is simply walking through the countryside. One
of the most beautiful areas is the Trossachs in Central Scotland.
The hills, green much of the year, turn purple in August when the
heather blooms. There are many trails where you can take off on
your own or with a group, enjoying the scenery and the silence.
</P>
<P>
   And one other thing _ take lots of film if you go to Scotland.
You'll need it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
