<HEADLINE>
CLANS EVOKE HISTORY OF BRAVURA AND ROMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KAREN DAVIS  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWTYLE, Scotland _ Scottish clans are the stuff of romance.
That's evident from the popularity of historical romantic novels
with Scottish themes and films such as ``Rob Roy,'' and the
television's time-traveling ``Highlander'' series.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Gregor MacGregor knows all about the bloody battles between
rival clans.
</P>
<P>
   His own clan was so warlike that from 1603 to 1776, it was
proscribed by the English. ``This meant all our lands were forfeit
and it was illegal to bear the MacGregor name,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the MacGregor clan survived by dodging the authorities.
They were known as ``the children of the mist'' because of their
ability to execute lightning-quick raids on English troops and then
melt back into the misty mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Today, MacGregor is the chief of his clan, a title that holds
considerably less clout than it did in the past, when the loyalty
of clan members to their chief was absolute. He lives in a historic
manor house set amid manicured grounds _ a far cry from the days
when clan members were on the run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the figurehead of this clan,'' he said. ``I get an
enormous amount of correspondence from MacGregors spread far and
wide _ New Zealand, Australia, Canada and the United States. Many
of them want to know if they're descended from Rob Roy.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Roy was an 18th-century Scotsman who rebelled against
English rule, which made him a hero to many, including some in
Hollywood a few years ago. (Liam Neeson starred in the film.)
Although MacGregor is very proper and proud of his heritage as the
descendent of numerous clan chiefs, he admits he's seen the movie
``Rob Roy'' and enjoyed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good wild Western set in Scotland,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Is he a Rob Roy descendent?
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course not,'' he said. ``He was a younger son.''
</P>
<P>
   Tradition holds that Gregor MacGregor is descended from Robert,
the fourth son of King Alfred, who ruled Scotland in the 700s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't prove it, but we are finding out that many of the
myths are true,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he's a member of the Standing Council of Clan Chiefs.
There are 147 recognized Scottish clans. The council meets each
July to discuss such things as preventing exploitation of clan
tartans and names, which is considered a serious offense in
Scotland. It's hard to go anywhere here without seeing clan tartan
items in stores, from key chains to caps to cloth. They're great
favorites with tourists, but the clan chiefs want to make sure the
right people are producing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned with keeping things valid,'' MacGregor said.
``In Scotland, the law lays down strict procedures. You have to get
permission. If you use somebody else's name (without permission),
it's a crime, even if you don't make money from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorized clan items have a log _ a circle with three feathers.
Royalties from the sale of such items go to the clan chiefs'
council, MacGregor said.
</P>
<P>
   MacGregor said he can't answer queries form from MacGregors
hoping to establish their ancestry because he hasn't the time and
or resources. He notes, however, that there are other sources of
information, especially on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   A recent check via the AltaVisa search engine netted more than 3
million Web pages on Scottish clans, from general information to
sites on specific clans such as Douglas, Campbell, Bruce and
MacNeil. The MacGregor clan alone has more than 800,000 sites.
</P>
<P>
   All of which has not been lost on the members of the Standing
Council of Clan Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although we usually meet only once a year, we're planning a
special meeting to discuss such things as the Internet,' MacGregor
said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ___ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For information on researching Scottish clan ancestry, access
Scottish Heritage USA at www.sandhills.org/shusa/ (and click on
Scottish Links, then Family Tree Online. Or contact Jacqueline
Stewart, Scottish Heritage USA, P.O. Box 457, Pinehurst, NC
28370-0457; 910-295-4448; fax 910-295-3147.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
