<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
KERREY REINFORCES MAVERICK STATUS WITH BRaDLEY ENDORSEMENT 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You don't have to be a fan of Nebraska Sen. Bob Kerrey to
appreciate his taste for the unconventional, to savor his droll
disregard for the demands of political propriety.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, I am a Kerrey fan _ to the extent that I'm ever a
fan of a liberal Democrat. Kerrey was my first choice for the
Democratic nomination when he ran for president in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey was relegated to also-ran status that year as he watched
Bill Clinton steal his major issue, health care, en route to the
Democratic nomination and the presidency. Kerrey exacted revenge by
becoming a thorn in Clinton's side almost from the moment the new
president took office in 1993, challenging his initiatives in
Congress and often criticizing him in public.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Vietnam war hero who romanced actress Debra Winger
while he was governor of the Cornhusker State has affronted the
Clinton administration again _ this time by endorsing Vice
President Al Gore's opponent for the Democrats' 2000 presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The value of Kerrey's support for former Senate colleague Bill
Bradley is mostly symbolic, since Kerrey commands no large bloc of
primary voters and is generally viewed as a minimally influential
maverick in the Senate. But the symbolism is nonetheless
significant.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey may not be one of the most powerful Democrats in
Washington, but he is one of the best known. He is articulate,
outspoken and unpredictable _ all traits that earn him frequent
appearances on the political gabfests that dominate the TV dial on
Sunday mornings. With Kerrey in his corner, Bradley will score lots
of free plugs on ``Meet the Press'' and ``Face the Nation.
</P>
<P>
   What we can't know, of course, is whether Kerrey has sided with
Bradley because he truly believes that the onetime basketball star
would be a better Democratic nominee and/or president than Gore or
because Kerrey couldn't resist the chance to give the Clinton-Gore
team additional grief.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey does have a reputation for following his conscience in
making important decisions, so he probably ought to get the benefit
of the doubt on this one. Let's say he endorsed Bradley because it
was the right thing to do _ and that knifing Clinton-Gore in the
back was just a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   None of which addresses the question of Bradley's viability as
the alternative to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, are Democratic voters really looking for an
alternative to Gore? It would be highly unusual for the party to
reject a sitting vice president's bid to head the ticket _
especially the bid of a vice president whose administration has
presided over nearly eight years of spectacular economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's detractors are quick to point out _ and his supporters
readily admit _ that the vice president is a
less-than-scintillating campaigner. Plunk him down on a stage next
to Bradley, though, and Gore could suddenly look like a veritable
ball of fire.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was one of the great basketball players in the history
of the sport and he was an excellent U.S. senator. But the name
``Bill Bradley'' will turn up in the same sentence with the word
``charisma'' only when the purpose of the sentence is to make the
point that Bradley has no charisma.
</P>
<P>
   Should Bradley ever maneuver Gore into a one-on-one debate, the
audience might yawn itself into a coma.
</P>
<P>
   Which might be exactly the reaction Bradley has been looking for
with his low-key, long-shot campaign. Bradley's game plan could
well be to lull Gore and the Democratic establishment to sleep
while quietly going about the business of raising money and lining
up support outside the usual political channels.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of Bill Bradley overtaking Al Gore to win the
Democratic nomination for president does seem far-fetched. Well,
OK, it seems preposterous.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Bob Kerrey had the foresight to identify
health care as the next big thing long before that issue became a
national obsession. Is it possible that Kerrey has seen something
in Bradley's campaign _ or Gore's _ that the rest of us have
missed?
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
