<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1836 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-EXPOS-SURVIVAL-HN     07-07 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-EXPOS-SURVIVAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS LOSSES MOUNT, EXPOS LOOK SOUTH TO CHARLOTTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM REYNOLDS  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ At first glance, the scene seems normal enough. About
50 people, many of them donning team caps, jerseys and T-shirts,
are standing at a ticket window, trying to gain entry to Olympic
Stadium to watch their Montreal Expos play the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   They are here to watch their former star, Pedro Martinez, pitch
for Boston against the Expos. And they are growing impatient with
the wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``The service is not adequate,'' Sylvain Jade, a 20-year-old
student from Laval, says in English that's clouded by a thick
Quebecois accent. ``How are the rest of the ticket windows
unopened? I think they do not want us here.''
</P>
<P>
   Only two windows were staffed for game-night sales. Once they've
secured their tickets, fans are literally running from the window
through the turnstiles, because at this point, the game is 55
minutes old. The fourth inning has started.
</P>
<P>
   There is a growing sense in Montreal that the Expos organization
is knowingly, willingly and gladly sabotaging baseball at Olympic
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The mission, these people believe, is twofold _ low attendance
could help the club convince voters that a new stadium must be
built for it in downtown Montreal, or the franchise will be sold
and relocated, probably to Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers in Montreal have been reporting for nearly a year
that Expos general partner and president Claude Brochu is
attempting to sell the team to Charlotte businessman Don Beaver.
Charlotte is already home to the NBA's Hornets and NFL's Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   The attendance figures at Olympic Stadium are by far the worst
in baseball, perhaps because the National League team has one of
the worst records in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   At its current pace, the Expos will draw 711,909 fans this
season, or more than 200,000 fewer than last year's total of
914,909.
</P>
<P>
   The salad days of the franchise, like when the club drew 2.4
million in 1983, are as forgotten as the team's baby-blue pullover
road uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a perception, a stereotype, that Montreal sports fans
only care about one sport, that being, of course, hockey,'' said
John Martin, a Montreal-based free-lance writer and self-described
baseball historian. ``It's true that hockey is the best game in
town, but fans of sport want baseball here. They want to see the
McGwires, the Sosas, the Bonds ... and they want to have something
to be proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto Blue Jays, Canada's other major-league franchise,
also are dealing with a significant drop in ticket sales, despite
the presence of budding stars like Shawn Green and Shannon Stewart,
World Series hero David Wells and Tony Fernandez, who's making a
run at batting .400. Toronto's attendance has dipped 16 percent
this year compared to 1998, but still 24,583 people, on average,
are going to the SkyDome for games.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos would love to have the Blue Jays' problems. Montreal
has broken the 20,000 mark in home attendance once all season _
Opening Day, when 43,918 went to Olympic Stadium to see the Expos
beat the New York Mets, 5-1.
</P>
<P>
   The club made its budget for 1999 based on selling 1 million
tickets, and even allowing for $15 million (U.S. $10.2 million) in
losses, according to published reports. It appears the final tally
could be significantly worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be 15 to 20 percent below our expectations,'' said L.
Jacques Menard, the team's chairman of the board and an advocate of
keeping baseball in Montreal. ``If that happens, it could cause
many millions more in losses.''
</P>
<P>
   Brochu, who declined an interview request for this story, has
laid out his master plan for keeping baseball in Montreal, with the
cornerstone being the construction of Labatt Park, a 35,000-seat
throwback-type stadium to be located in one of the busiest sections
of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Promotional information hyping the planned stadium proclaims
``it will be the most prestigious, the most acclaimed and the most
popular gathering and entertainment venue in Quebec.'' The park
could open as early as 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Brochu's position boils down to this: If the city builds the
stadium, the club will stay; if not, it will go.
</P>
<P>
   ``If baseball would swing its weight behind us,'' Expos minority
partner Mark Rutterberg said, ``we could get this done just like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The city, however, sees no reason to invest an estimated $250
million (U.S. $170 million) of tax dollars to build a park for the
sake of keeping a penny-pinching franchise that annually gives away
talent just to keep payroll low.
</P>
<P>
   On this night, though, the only thing moving with certainty was
pencils on scorecards. Pedro Martinez did not leave victorious, as
he and the Red Sox were shelled, 13-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like losing to anyone,'' Martinez said. ``But if I had
to pick one team to lose to, this would be the one.''
</P>
<P>
   There were 19,012 people there to see Martinez, who won the 1997
Cy Young Award in his final season in Montreal. And when the Expos
blew the game open in the late innings, ``le Stade Olympique''
rocked like it was, well, any other major-league park.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the great places to play and see people do
well,'' Montreal infielder Michael Barrett said. ``When (Expos
starter and winner Mike) Thurman came up to bat in the seventh and
everyone was giving him a standing ovation, it was truly
uplifting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
