<HEADLINE>
NOW HEAR THIS: LISTENING SKILLS ARE VITAL TO YOUR CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Next time you hear politicians speak, listen to
what they're not saying, former Texas Gov. Ann Richards says. One
thing that Richards didn't say, for example, is that hearing the
unspoken is one of the most useful career skills you can have.
</P>
<P>
   At the recent Women in Leadership conference in San Francisco,
Richards described how Congress debated gun control after the
shootings at Columbine High School in Colorado. Suddenly the
argument shifted to whether the Ten Commandments should be posted
in schools. That, she said, was a deft maneuver by gun control
opponents. Whether they won or lost on the Commandments didn't
matter; they succeeded in shifting the conversation away from gun
control.
</P>
<P>
   In your career, hearing the unspoken helps in these ways:
</P>
<P>
   _ Making tough decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Smart Silicon Valley companies do this all the time to survive.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, Intel executives could see that competition made
it hard to succeed in manufacturing memory chips, so they focused
on microprocessors _ and thrived. Apple turned its business around
by cutting its product line.
</P>
<P>
   Those changes weren't popular with existing customers or
employees, groups that are often more comfortable with the status
quo _ until the company goes out of business. The executives were
listening to the unspoken promise of future customers.
</P>
<P>
   Now let's look at an industry in decline: newspapers. Do you
have any idea what draws the most coverage in newspapers? It has to
be the stock market, which gets four or five full pages of price
tables each day.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton could have an affair with O.J. Simpson on the
streets of Kosovo and it wouldn't draw four full pages of coverage
per day.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people don't even own stocks, and many others check
prices through their brokers, the Internet or even automated phone
lines set up by newspapers. But the tables remain.
</P>
<P>
   If you replaced them with five pages of news about businesses
and stories explaining what was happening in the financial markets,
any newspaper's business section would probably be far more
informative and entertaining in six months than it is today.
</P>
<P>
   But those six months would be hell, because readers and
advertisers who prefer the status quo would complain. Loudly. And
those potential new readers who thought the stock tables were a
waste of space wouldn't be saying a word, of course. So the tables
remain.
</P>
<P>
   The status quo is always the easiest alternative. That's why
it's so important to stop at least once a year and evaluate your
career (and life, for that matter).
</P>
<P>
   Are you still happy? Are you still learning? Will society need
your skills in 10 or 20 years? Are there new careers that might
appeal to you? Does your career still fit your values and
lifestyle? How will you be better off a year from now? Whether your
cliche of choice is ``thinking ahead of the curve'' or ``reading
the handwriting on the wall,'' do it. Listen to that voice inside
your head, the one that speaks only when spoken to.
</P>
<P>
   _ Job interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Think about what you really want to find out, besides obvious
things like pay and benefits. What are the chances for promotion or
mentoring? Does the company promote work and family balance or just
give it lip service? Is there a mission statement or five-year
plan? Do employees have a lot of direction or a lot of freedom?
Make sure you address the heart of your question. If your main
concern about balance is making sure you can take your 10-year-old
to her soccer games, don't let that get lost as the company tells
you about its scholarship program.
</P>
<P>
   If you are told that mentoring is offered on a case-by-case
basis, find out the guidelines. You might not get an answer that's
cast in stone, but at least it won't be cast in Jell-O.
</P>
<P>
   For anything crucial, get a direct answer from your future
supervisor. Just because the company emphasizes mentoring doesn't
mean each department considers it important.
</P>
<P>
   _ Salary negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   If you want a raise, show how you've improved in the last year,
what skills you've added and how that has helped the company. If
the boss points out weaknesses, make sure they're not just
distractions.
</P>
<P>
   If you get turned down for relatively insignificant reasons, do
some networking and find out if the boss has deeper, unspoken
concerns about your performance or if the company is having
financial problems. Those will help you determine your next move.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if you're getting a job offer, remember the
adage: Whichever side mentions salary first loses. So try to let
the employer make the first offer.
</P>
<P>
   If you've done your homework, you'll know what a fair offer
should be. If it sounds too low, explain how you stand out from the
typical applicant, and why you should be paid more.
</P>
<P>
   And when you agree on a job offer and salary, get it in writing.
</P>
<P>
   A written contract is always worth a thousand words, spoken or
unspoken.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
