<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV25-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., JULY 25, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Our house has a gable roof with large louvered vents in the
attic peaks at each end. We always covered these louvers in cold
weather in an effort to save heat, but during the past winter we
noticed some signs of condensation on the exposed roof rafters
inside the attic. We recently increased the amount of insulation on
the floor of that unfinished attic, but a knowledgeable friend
tells me that we should leave the gable vents open at all times. In
addition, in his opinion these vents alone actually did not provide
enough ventilation for that attic. How much ventilation do we
actually need, and if more is needed do we have to make the
existing vents even larger?
</P>
<P>
   A: Most codes require a minimum of one square foot of vent
opening for every 300 square feet of attic floor area _ but half of
these vents should be up near the top of the attic with the other
half down low, usually along the eaves. The best method is to
install a row of ridge vents along the top of the roof as shown
here, coupled with continuous soffit vents along the eaves. This
will allow hot air to flow out at the top, while colder air enters
from below as indicated in the illustration.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The concrete of my garage floor extends about six inches
outside the overhead door when the door is all the way down. This
exposed ``apron'' of concrete is about six inches wide and in one
long area the concrete has been eroded to the point where the
gravel and stones are showing. I believe this was caused by rock
salt being frequently used by the previous owner of this house. How
can I refinish and then preserve or protect this exposed strip of
concrete?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are a number of patching cements sold in home centers
that have bonding agents in them to insure solid adhesion so that
they can be spread on in thin layers that will bond to the old
concrete and gravel. Clean the old surface thoroughly to get rid of
dirt and debris, then mix and spread the patching material
according to the directions on the package. Allow this to cure
fully, then apply a coat of cement sealer to help waterproof the
patched area.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I live in a small condominium where all the apartments have
hardwood floors. Unit owners do not want to cover these floors
because they like the appearance of the hardwood. But noise from
people walking on the wood floors with hard soled shoes, from loud
stereo speakers, and even from squeaky floor boards, is easily
transmitted from one apartment to the one below it. This building
was built in the 1920s and has plaster ceilings. Is there any kind
of good acoustical insulation that can be blown in between the
floors and ceilings to cut down on noise transmission and effective
enough to make it worth the cost?
</P>
<P>
   A: Blowing insulation into the space between the ceilings and
floors will cut down only slightly on the amount of noise
transmitted, so I doubt that this would be worthwhile. Putting down
carpet or rugs would help a lot, as will closing up or caulking all
openings where pipes, electric wires, etc. come through from one
floor to the other.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a bathroom exhaust fan installed that vents into the
attic directly above it. I noticed signs of moisture and was told
the fan should be vented up through the roof of the house. How do I
install such a vent without compromising the watertight seal of my
newly installed roofing material?
</P>
<P>
   A: You don't have to run the vent up through the roof; you only
need to vent it directly to the outside to eliminate the moisture
problem _ rather than into the attic. In most cases the simplest
way to do this is to run the vent out through the nearest wall _ in
the attic or even through the bathroom wall. Either type of
installation would be a lot better than what you have now.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``COLD AIR ENTERS THROUGH SOFFIT VENTS''
goes with this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: For most efficient ventilation air should flow into the
attic at its lowest point, then out through vents at the top of the
attic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
