<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1857 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-JOURNAL-0708-1     07-07 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-JOURNAL-0708-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: in 18th graf, adds '...that I had followed into Kosovo on
June 13 ... '; adds reporter's tagline at end of story
 &HT;    NO TV HYPE: KOSOVO'S HORRORS TOO NUMEROUS TO SHOW
 &HT;    With Photo Mug of Kaplow.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ The carnage in Kosovo was the first story
I have covered that was bigger than it looked on television.
</P>
<P>
   The casualties in 1992's Hurricane Andrew were limited and life
continued in many parts of Miami. Last December's bombing of Iraq
provided good televised fireworks, but most Iraqis were barely
inconvenienced.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo was a story of blind ethnic hatred -- the poison that
germinates with simple bigotry and transforms so easily into
bloodshed. Its ravages are not confinable to a television screen.
</P>
<P>
   The acts of evil were too numerous for a journalist to report
and too vast to escape.
</P>
<P>
   There were body parts and weeping mothers that never made it
into my stories. Our hotel meeting place stood above a basement
strewn with the eerie debris of Serb paramilitary gangs. Nights
were punctuated by bursts of gunfire and the barking of stray dogs,
once pets, now traveling in wild packs.
</P>
<P>
   The battle lines were vague; the borders unmarked and innocent
mistakes could be terrifying. But, reality did not hit me until I
foolishly tried to take a day off.
</P>
<P>
   I rode with a fellow journalist to pick up a car her company was
sending from Belgrade. The rendezvous point got switched and we got
lost.
</P>
<P>
   We strayed across the unmarked border and wandered about 4 miles
out of NATO-controlled Kosovo into Serb-controlled Yugoslavia,
where we were held at a Serb police checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
   It was their right to stop us. We were in Serbia -- Yugoslavia's
dominant republic, and of which Kosovo is a province -- without
Yugoslav visas. But things got complicated.
</P>
<P>
   A non-uniformed Serb, drinking beer in the shade, blew up at the
site of our two Kosovar Albanian drivers. He threatened to slit my
friend's throat, then drew a pistol from a holster and threatened
to shoot. His police friends half-heartedly persuaded him to calm
down and told us to sit in the car.
</P>
<P>
   There, I fearfully and surreptitiously ate the press card issued
to me by the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army, the Serbs' hated enemy.
</P>
<P>
   We were luckier than I expected. After a trip to a police
station, we were released.
</P>
<P>
   My story is trivial in contrast to the deaths of thousands of
ethnic Albanians here. But, it taught me that there could be no
respite from Kosovo's hatred and horrors.
</P>
<P>
   So overwhelming was the nightmare that it's hard for me to
imagine that people can go on living here.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters lamented the incredible sights we left out of stories.
What about the house where Serbs used their victims blood to write
anti-NATO graffiti on the white walls? How about the dismembered
foot by the road? It was all pushed out by other items more gory or
urgent.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the echoes of war prolonged the danger.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees and journalists alike had to watch for trip wires and
land mines. Inspecting charred corpses in one burned house, we
carefully avoided a metal disk spotted beneath rubble on the floor.
To my astonishment, an Australian cameraman then backed up right on
top of it. It wasn't a mine.
</P>
<P>
   One night, I found the NATO troops that I had followed into
Kosovo on June 13 removing machine guns and detonators from the
apartment across the hall. They belonged to a couple whose sons had
been Serb paramilitaries.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, the man there threatened some Kosovar Albanians
and they split his head open. A trail of blood lead from our
hallway, down 180 steps and into a plaza nearby.
</P>
<P>
   I moved out, but blood was commonplace. In the Grand Hotel, a
dilapidated Serb-run tower that smells of urine and was home for
much of the press, blood trailed inexplicably down the marble steps
to the basement.
</P>
<P>
   The basement, including a small bowling alley, disco and
conference rooms, was used as a barracks by Serb soldiers. A friend
and I searched it and our little Maglites spotlighted their creepy
artifacts -- clothes, boots, alcohol bottles and syringes, which
were purportedly used for the amphetamines that helped the Serbs
manage their vast murderous workload.
</P>
<P>
   Above ground, almost every ethnic Albanian I met had loved ones
killed or missing. People cried unexpectedly. Death and loss became
the vehicles for bonding.
</P>
<P>
   In our spare time, Fanton, my ethnic Albanian driver, took me to
a mass grave he had discovered.
</P>
<P>
   There were four patches of loose dirt in a hilltop graveyard.
Maybe, I said and wished, they were just paupers' graves.
</P>
<P>
   When he showed me what he said was the back of a skull
protruding from the ground, I suggested it was a rock. We tapped it
with sticks. It sounded too solid for bone.
</P>
<P>
   But, we stripped away a little soil and the stench of human
decay, now familiar to me, rose from the grave. Hair still clung to
a strip of dried skin.
</P>
<P>
   Under Muslim custom, no one would be buried face down, without a
shroud and just inches from the surface. This was a murder victim.
This was a man or woman whose relatives now missed someone --if
they themselves had survived.
</P>
<P>
   Just as it was foolish of me to ever hope for a day off in
Kosovo, I had foolish to think this object in the dirt could have
been anything but a skull. It was another tragedy, lost and
anonymous among the thousands of tragedies in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   (Cox Newspapers Middle East correspondent Larry Kaplow recently
returned from reporting in Kosovo and the Balkans for nearly a
month.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
