<HEADLINE>
FEW SPEED BUMPS FOR REAGAN LICENSE PLATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ California gave the nation a car culture
and Ronald Reagan, and now the two are destined to become one on
the back of automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   A drive to put a picture of Ronald Reagan on a special
California license plate is speeding through the
Democratic-controlled Legislature with only muted complaints.
</P>
<P>
   About 7,000 people already have signed up to pay $50 for the new
Reagan plates, which would carry a portrait of the former president
and support the Ronald Reagan Presidential Library.
</P>
<P>
   With a boost from Nancy Reagan, who recently phoned a Senate
Republican leader to lobby for the bill, the state Senate
Transportation Committee approved the plates Tuesday. The state
Assembly approved the bill earlier.
</P>
<P>
   About four years ago, the Senate committee agreed to stop
approving new specialty license plates because the state was making
so many different varieties the California Highway Patrol started
complaining.
</P>
<P>
   However, as it did recently with AIDS and breast-cancer research
plates, the committee relented again _ on Nancy Reagan's birthday,
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The least we can do in California, which is Reagan country, is
have a license plate in his honor,'' said Assemblyman Tony
Strickland, a Republican from Thousand Oaks, who is the author of
the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of Democrats voted against the measure when it
passed the Assembly. Their public explanation is a steady
proliferation of special license plates compounded by a large
number of high-profile things bearing Reagan's name, including the
Ronald Reagan National Airport in Washington and a huge federal
office building there.
</P>
<P>
   The Highway Patrol, which is worried that the large number of
specialty plates will make quick identification of tags more
difficult, did not oppose Strickland's bill.
</P>
<P>
   Seven bills are now in the California Legislature to create new
license plates featuring organizations such as the Boy and Girl
Scouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous,'' Assemblyman Dick Floyd, a Democrat from
Wilmington, said of the Reagan plate. ``If this goes, then (former
Gov. George) Deukmejian is next, and then they'll go for (ex-Gov.
Pete) Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd ask for one for (former Govs.) Pat Brown and Earl Warren,
but their people would never be so gross as to ask for that.''
</P>
<P>
   The most popular environmental plate raises money to help
restore the Yosemite National Park. About 46,000 Yosemite plates
have been sold, garnering about $9 million. The second most popular
has raised about $3.8 million for arts programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
