<P>
   Circuits stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for Thursday,
July 8:
</P>
<P>
   CIR-COMPUTER-BUILDING (Undated) _ Building your own computer
from scratch: A first person narrative comparing the experiences
and frustrations of building an impressive custom machine. By
Michel Marriott.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-HACKERS (Undated) _ Internet connections like cable modems
and digital subscriber lines are an open invitation to hackers.
Because computers using these services are constantly connected to
the Internet and have a fixed address to communicate with other
computers, a hacker using scanning or ``sniffing'' software may be
able to gain access. By Ian Austen.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly computer column:
swept up in the phenomenal rush of the global Internet that it
helped create, the personal computer industry is undergoing a
fundamental transformation. Several PC makers have begun offering
free Internet access as an inducement to sell more machines, while
several Internet service providers have begun giving away
computers, or subsidizing their purchase, to entice more customers
to sign up for on-line services. The personal computer, which
gained popular acceptance in the 1980s for its ability to perform a
wide variety of business and scientific tasks, is increasingly
being recognized in the late 1990s as primarily a communications
device that enables anyone to send and receive electronic mail,
participate in discussion groups and browse for information on the
Internet's World Wide Web. And now, the PC is following the model
of the cellular phone, which is often given away or sold at low
cost to customers who sign up for service contracts. By Peter H.
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-GEEK-NOTES (Undated) _ Techno news and notes: Study of
search engines from Nature; a game company employees sells secrets
on eBay; manuals available on-line.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-SUPERMAN-GAME (Undated) _ N64's Superman has problems. A
cartoonish feel and overemphasized flying controls make the Man of
Steel more of a joke than a superhero. His walk is not so nimble,
either. By J.C. Herz.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-COMPLAINERS (Undated) _ On-line services that complain for a
fee. They take an aggressive stance for consumer rights. Sites and
costs are explained. By Jennifer 8. Lee. (Middle initial is cq)
</P>
<P>
   CIR-CAMP-EMAIL (Undated) _ Writing home from camp in the late
'90s. Some camps have access, some camps print and distribute
E-mails, others hire a service that provides computers for campers
on which to send e-mail. By Catherine Greenman.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-THIRD-WORLD-NET (San Jose, Calif.) _ The Third World worries
about Internet access. A conference, INETT 99, focuses on how to
expand coverage, but problems abound. Costs, telephone monopolies,
and lack of venture capital are cited as some of the problems. By
Katie Hafner.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-HUMAN-ANATOMY (Undated) _ Reviews of human anatomy CD-ROMs.
By Abigail Zuger.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-VIRTUAL-SCHIZOPHRENIA (Undated) _ Virtual reality helps
psychiatrists understand schizophrenia. A program has been
developed to mimic the random noises and sights that a person
suffering from schizophrenia experiences. Experts get to feel how
their patients feel. By Alicia Ault.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-ELECTRONIC-NOSE (Undated) _ The electronic nose makes its
appearance, offering chemical analysis on a chip. Using pattern
recognition similar to what the human nose and brain uses, the chip
`senses' chemicals around it. By Peter Wayner.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-ONINE-BANKING (Undated) _ On-line banking offers 24 hour
service for customers who prefer flexibility. Banks are also
offering more services on line. By Catherine Greemnam.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Techno questions answered: USB or parallel
port for a printer. By J.D. Biersdorfer.
</P>
