<SLUG> BC-MORMONS-GAYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIAL SEEKS PROBE OF MORMONS FOR POLITICAL ACTIVISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A San Francisco supervisor has asked the city
attorney and the state attorney general to determine whether it is
illegal for the Mormon Church to support an upcoming ballot
initiative that would ban gay marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Mark Leno made the request after the church recently
issued a ``Dear Brethren and Sisters'' letter asking members to
help assure passage of the March 2000 ballot measure.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was sent to church leaders in California who were
instructed to read it to their members, estimated to be 740,000
statewide.
</P>
<P>
   ``This traditional marriage initiative provides a clear and
significant moral choice,'' said the letter, which was written to
church presidents in charge of California and endorsed by Gordon B.
Hinkley, head of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints.
``The church's position on this issue is unequivocal.''
</P>
<P>
   Leno believes the action blurs the constitutional line
separating church and state and should prompt the loss of the
tax-exempt status afforded to religious organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe this is a gross abuse of their tax-exempt status,
and would like the city attorney and the state attorney general to
look into the legality of their actions, and, if appropriate, for
the IRS to consider revoking their tax-exempt status,'' Leno said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Leno said the Mormon Church should be accorded the same
treatment by the Internal Revenue Service as the Christian
Coalition, a conservative organization founded by televangelist Pat
Robertson. Last month, the IRS lifted the Christian Coalition's
tax-exempt status after ruling that it was political at its core.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mormon Church, among other Christian denominations, which
receive tax-exempt status, are essentially bankrolling political
support against the gay rights movement by urging their membership
to fight against pro-gay legislation,'' Leno said. ``If churches
want to get involved in politics, they should be held to the same
rules other organizations doing similar political work must
follow.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure on the ballot, formally known as the Definition of
Marriage Initiative, would define marriage as between a man and
woman only, and is intended to block any attempts to sanction gay
marriage. State Sen. Pete Knight, a Republican from Palmdale,
sponsored it.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Callister, a spokesman for the Mormon Church in
California, declined to address Leno's concerns, or the church's
tax-exempt status. He was clear, however, on why his church is
supporting the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``We firmly believe that this is a moral issue,'' he said. ``The
church in California is simply adding its voice to a broad-based
coalition of many who feel strongly about preserving the
traditional family.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mormons proved generous in Alaska and Hawaii on measures
similar to the Knight initiative, pumping $1.1 million into those
successful efforts.
</P>
</TEXT>
