<P>
   Sports stories from The New York Times News Service for
 &UR; THURSDAY &LR; , July 8.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN (Los Angeles) _ Sports of The Times column on
the Women's World Cup media day in Los Angeles, looking ahead to
Saturday's final between China and the United States. By George
Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-WOMEN-IMAGE (Los Angeles) _ To a large extent, the players
on the American women's soccer team have been willing participants
in the sexualization of the team in recent years. Mia Hamm has been
named one of People magazine's 50 most beautiful people. Defender
Brandi Chastain has appeared in Gear magazine, crouched behind a
soccer ball, wearing only her cleats and her rippling muscles. With
their ponytailed-virtuosity, the American players have also sent a
calculated message around the world: that women can be both
athletic and feminine in a sport that, in many places, still
carries the stigma that women who play are somehow unwomanly. By
Jere Longman.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-RHODEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column on Oil
Can Boyd, former Red Sox pitcher, now the owner of a minor league
team in Mississippi. By William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-TIGERS (Detroit) _ N.Y. Yankees at Detroit, 7:35 p.m.
EDT start. By Buster Olney.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLSTARS (Detroit) _ The remainder of the American and
National League all-stars are selected. By Buster Olney.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-METS-EXPOS (New York) _ Montreal at the Mets, 7:40 p.m. EDT
start. By Jack Curry.
</P>
<P>
   TOURDEFRANCE (Blois, France) _ To all those who have been asking
that question, Mario Cipollini gave his answer Wednesday: In his
usual place, crossing the finish line ahead of everybody else in
the Tour de France. For the fourth consecutive day, a stage ended
in a mass sprint and, for the first time, Cipollini, who is
regarded, especially by himself, as the fastest sprinter around,
proved it. By Samuel Abt.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other sports
stories from our partners: Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox
News Service, Hearst News Service, The Arizona Republic, Kansas
City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News, San
Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
