<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV11-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON: HOW LAME A DUCK? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 11)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The great unsolved mystery in the nation's capital
this summer centers around a lame-duck president's determination to
soar across the land like a conquering eagle.
</P>
<P>
   With only 18 months left in his eight-year presidency, Bill
Clinton refuses to accept lame-duck status. He is racing about the
nation as though he were just beginning his tenure rather than
limping toward the end of it.
</P>
<P>
   Since much of Clinton's moral leadership was squandered by the
Monica Lewinsky revelations and congressional impeachment efforts,
he has a lot of catching up to do. He wants to improve his legacy
by the time he leaves office _ if he can.
</P>
<P>
   By tradition, the president, banned by the 22nd Amendment from
seeking a third term and with few major legislative battles to
fight, should be slowing down in preparation for a quiet transfer
of power to his successor on Jan. 20, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton, at 52, is much younger and more vigorous than most
of his predecessors at their time of retirement. He also is
addicted to action and driven by ambition and a desire to be
remembered well by future generations.
</P>
<P>
   There is no chance that he will be ranked with such illustrious
Democrats as Franklin D. Roosevelt, Woodrow Wilson or Harry Truman,
but he could end up ahead of Jimmy Carter and possibly in a
category with his idol, John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   While the Lewinsky scandal proved destructive, he apparently
believes that his presidency can be resurrected with far-reaching
legislative achievements.
</P>
<P>
   With the economy growing at 4.3 percent in the first three
months of 1999, the budget surplus expected to reach $99 billion
this year and $3 trillion over the next 15 years and the war in
Kosovo won, the president sees this as a ``time of great hope'' and
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent news conference, he explained the force that drives
him: ``We will be judged by what we do with this opportunity _
whether we seize it or squander it in petty bickering and partisan
animosity.'' He doesn't want history to record that in his last
months as president, he turned his back on the chance to achieve
vital goals for America.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, he has unveiled a plan to improve Medicare with,
among other proposals, financial help for prescription drugs. The
Clinton plan has generated an angry political battle on Capitol
Hill, where the Republicans control both houses and the two parties
are gathering ammunition for the 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   But prescription drug payments should prove popular with senior
citizens, who vote in large numbers.
</P>
<P>
   An equally volatile fight should develop over distribution of
the budget surplus. Clinton lists saving Social Security and
Medicare as his top priority. Republicans favor a tax cut which,
like Clinton's prescription drug proposal, should prove popular
with voters.
</P>
<P>
   In a journey reminiscent of Lyndon Johnson's 1964 trip through
the valleys and villages of Appalachia to explain and dramatize his
anti-poverty initiatives, Clinton last week led a group of
corporate, civic and political leaders on a tour of ``the places in
our country which have not yet felt the surge of our economy.''
Those places, described by the president as ``America's new
markets,'' are poverty-stricken neighborhoods where tax credits and
loan guarantees presumably could provide jobs and growth.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will also battle for congressional approval of stronger
gun control and of a patients' bill of rights, which would regulate
the managed-care industry and have a strong impact on people who
are members of health maintenance organizations (HMOs).
</P>
<P>
   In this century, only Theodore Roosevelt, who left the
presidency at age 50, was younger at retirement than Clinton will
be. But TR's need to lead and bask in public adulation, plus his
restlessness with retirement, led him into an ill-fated and
fruitless attempt in 1912 to wrest the GOP nomination from his
hand-chosen successor, William Howard Taft.
</P>
<P>
   His bold quest for a return to power ended with his unsuccessful
bid for the presidency on the Progressive Party ticket. As it
turned out, he split the Republican Party and assured the election
of Democrat Woodrow Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Had Kennedy lived to be reelected in 1964 and retire in 1968, he
would have been 51 and presumably would have had many years of
public service ahead of him. The oldest retiree from the White
House was Ronald Reagan, who celebrated his 78th birthday two weeks
after leaving office.
</P>
<P>
   Although Reagan had some worthwhile legislative achievements
during his last two years in office, his record was tarnished by
the Iran-contra affair in which the United States secretly sold
arms to Iran and used the money to fund the Contra rebels in
Nicaragua. The affair, part of which Reagan denied knowing about,
raised questions about his credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is fortunate to have survived a scandal far more
debilitating than Reagan's and, to some degree, put it behind him
before entering the final stretch of his presidency. Although by
political definition he is a lame duck, he is not ready to accept
that designation or indulge in traditional lame-duck behavior.
</P>
</TEXT>
