s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-KIDDIE-POP-$ADV     07-07 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-KIDDIE-POP-$ADV11-900(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN POP BECOMES THE TOY OF TEENYBOPPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., July 11)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   She was about 11 years old and breathlessly excited, surrounded
by three girlfriends and chattering into a cellular phone.
``Britney was awesome!'' she gasped, jumping up and down. ``She was
hot!'' The girl was in the lobby of the Continental Airlines Arena
in East Rutherford, N.J., between acts at Zootopia '99, a
radio-station charity concert with a bill featuring cute boys (98
Degrees, Sugar Ray, Jordan Knight, Joe McIntyre) and a perky girl
(Britney Spears) singing about love, love, love. Britney's fan was
probably talking to another girlfriend. But at that moment, she
could have been giving dictation to the American pop marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   This season belongs to the kiddie-pop brigades. Applause is
passe; the reaction most eagerly sought by pop culture right now,
from music to television to movies, is a high-pitched squeal from a
mob of young girls. When it's directed at males, that squeal
signifies romantic fantasy while it tests out some newly active
hormonal responses. Directed at females, it's a squeal of sisterly
solidarity and fashion approval. And for the last few years, its
volume has been steadily rising until it threatens to drown out
anything with more mature audiences in mind. Kiddie-pop has always
been available to those who wanted it, but in the late 1990s, it's
turning into the only game in town.
</P>
<P>
   The mass market has been voting with its dollars for
kiddie-friendly hits with pinup potential. The Backstreet Boys'
``Millennium,'' Ricky Martin's ``Ricky Martin'' and Britney Spears'
`` ... Baby One More Time'' have been lodged in the Top 10; 'N
Sync, 98 Degrees and BWitched are million-sellers and Top 40
fixtures. At the movies, a tow-headed tyke saves the day in the new
``Star Wars'' product, which has been purged of both blood and
sexual banter that might confuse the elementary-school crowd. And
new television series are running out of teen-age actors to hire as
they jockey to become the next ``Dawson's Creek.''
</P>
<P>
   A censorious furor over comic books and rock-and-roll began in
the 1950s, and since then there have been people and groups who
want to police all the arts to a level considered safe for
children. After the high-school shootings in Colorado, Congress
debated making it a federal crime to expose a child to depictions
of explicit sex or violence. There's still plenty of nasty stuff
around, and plenty of troubled and disquieting messages from
artists and hustlers. But now, without coercion, calculations are
being made across the entertainment business that the pre-teen
audience is the key to blockbuster success.
</P>
<P>
   It could be a symptom of mass regression. Grown-ups are
slouching around in sweatsuits that are the closest thing to infant
rompers, flocking to movies full of juvenile potty humor and
listening to kiddie-pop. Meanwhile, Times Square has been handed
over to cartoon characters. (It's all too perfect that the
Backstreet Boys, 'N Sync and a stable of fellow kiddie-pop hopefuls
are based in Orlando, Fla., just like Disney World.) Youth culture
once meant culture stoked by the energy and confusion and idealism
of adolescence; now, it seems, listeners prefer to be babied.
</P>
<P>
   According to United States census figures, the number of people
aged 5 to 13 _ the core of the kiddie-pop audience _ has grown by
about 3.5 million since 1990, slightly over 1 percent of the total
population. But children's influence has grown faster than their
numbers. The entertainment business has clearly decided that
youngsters now have decisive buying power.
</P>
<P>
   Kiddie pop music benefits from a handful of interlocking trends.
There's a general return _ post-grunge, post-gangsta _ to peppy,
happy-faced pop songs: a reaction to too much self-importantly
gloomy music. (Perhaps, after a long national sex scandal, people
are also longing for more romantic, less carnal visions of love.)
There's a creative slump in rock's more aggressive styles; maybe
musicians are hoarding brilliant ideas until 2000, so they won't
get lumped in with that old 20th-century music. There's also an
all-out assault on the language barrier by comely Hispanic pop
stars (with Ricky Martin and Jennifer Lopez in the vanguard) who
polished their pickup lines and video moves before Spanish-speaking
audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there's a post-Hanson, post-Brandy, post-LeAnn Rimes
rush by recording companies to sign precocious talent: the
13-year-old classical soprano Charlotte Church, the 19-year-old
Lilith Fair contender Kendall Payne, the teen-age rhythm-and-blues
trio Blaque and the Moffatts, a four-brother group _ like Hanson
plus one _ of 15-year-old triplets and a 16-year-old brother. (Of
course, singers don't have to be teen-agers to draw squeals;
geezers in their early '20s are fine, as long as there's no show of
crudeness, chest hair, crooked teeth or condescension.) All those
tendencies converge to anoint 11-year-old girls as pop's reigning
tastemakers.
</P>
<P>
   Adults, not just little girls, are paying attention. The
Backstreet Boys, for instance, have been getting top airplay on
adult-contemporary (or ``lite'') radio stations whose presumed
audience is well over 25. For some older listeners, apparently,
kiddie pop's pledges of love stake out the romantic middle of the
road that Bread or Boyz II Men once occupied. And the performers'
youth makes them even more attractive than older saccharin
dispensers. It's easier for youngsters to act innocent, which is a
relief for some adults and a turn-on, acknowledged or not, for
others.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While a few teen-age performers, like Aaliyah and Li'l Kim, have
exploited their jailbait allure, kiddie-pop's top acts present the
image of extremely good children: ambitious and diligent and
virtuous. The CD-ROM component of Britney Spears' album, `` ...
Baby One More Time,'' includes a photo scrapbook of her training
and triumphs: dance class, gymnastics trophies, her selection at
age 10 as Miss Talent USA. She's not just a superkid. She's
obedient, too, singing the songs and hitting the marks that are
choreographed for her. So do the boy groups, synchronizing their
moves without a trace of mischief. Pop provides wish-fulfillment
for listeners, and kiddie pop can give adults the ultimate parental
fantasy: well-groomed, perfectly behaved, highly motivated
adolescents who _ fantasy of fantasies _ always do as they're told.
</P>
<P>
   Girlish enthusiasm has stoked the pop market at least since the
days of bobby-soxers swooning over Frank Sinatra. When
rock-and-roll began, many people thought its sole purpose was to
get teen-agers hot and bothered and insisted that it would never be
good for anything else. By the early 1960s, the formula for
teen-age idols was already in place: a nice young man, songs that
promised endless sublimated love, mild-mannered music and an
attitude that wouldn't scare parents. Television exposure _ the
best way for an under-age girl to get a glimpse of the product _
was a catalyst for stars from Ricky Nelson to the Jackson 5.
</P>
<P>
   In rock's early days, a hitmaker was expected to have teen
appeal; the Beatles would have been nowhere without that initial,
deafening wave of Beatlemania. But the Beatles, and rock, decided
to grow up, shrugging off teen-pop antecedents and differentiating
themselves from the unabashed commercialism of knockoffs like the
Monkees. Soon, self-conscious rockers began defining themselves
against the teen-pop recipe. They would be noisy and rebellious;
they wouldn't confine themselves to sweet love songs. They would
try to live up to every parental worry they could imagine.
</P>
<P>
   Teen idols never disappeared, but by the 1970s they had
sacrificed most respect. True rockers considered themselves artists
with careers, not mere entertainers, and it was already obvious
that the teen-idol business had faster turnover than a junior high
school. Adulation for the cute boy singer of the moment was, for
most fans, a phase between teddy bears and actual boyfriends,
something they would later look back on with a blush. And young
girls had no use for their older sisters' fleeting favorites. David
Cassidy, Shaun Cassidy, Andy Gibb and Rick Springfield flickered
across pop's short-term memory and receded, with only the
performers themselves, perhaps, expecting the squeals to go on
forever.
</P>
<P>
   Music video revitalized the teen-idol business in the 1980s.
Television exposure for pop stars was no longer available only at
the whim of a network broadcaster. It was a 24-hour presence, with
video clips displaying performers in perfectly controlled, no-sweat
vignettes. MTV gave little girls access to a whole new galaxy of
perfectly styled, spiffily packaged acts. It galvanized a new
prepubescent market for pop: little girls in the taste gap between
Raffi and Jewel. The unexpected side effect was that it also gave
them a chance to see rockers who weren't aiming for pre-teen
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Performers like Boy George, the Stray Cats and Cyndi Lauper
found they had very young fans; Duran Duran worked overtime to
portray themselves as glamorous jet-setters with deep thoughts, not
just smiling heartthrobs. Madonna may have enjoyed her littlest
wanna-bes for a while; then she sexed up her act, decisively
pulling herself out of the kiddie arena. Even would-be tough guys,
like Vanilla Ice, found themselves rapping to little girls who
couldn't care less whether he was from the 'hood. Rebels, gangstas,
grotesques, highbrows and punks were all available for home
contemplation and consumption; even Kurt Cobain could become a teen
idol, much to his distress.
</P>
<P>
   But this is the era of niche marketing, and fans and parents
would prefer that kiddie pop stay out of the post-pubertal world of
overt lust, anger and ambiguity. Although the boundary between
childish and adult (or at least late-teen) material is fuzzy, music
fans who want to feel mature generally don't want grade-schoolers
tagging along. Outside all-ages hardcore punk shows, the presence
of children suggests that the music is tame and wimpy. The
grade-schoolers, meanwhile, would rather have something all their
own. Categories reassure potential consumers, too. When kiddie pop
is neatly defined, parents can buy designated albums with a clearer
conscience, secure that their daughters won't be corrupted.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked into its sector of the pop market, kiddie pop is the
perfect niche item It's formulaic, mass-produced, marketed in
reliable ways and almost immediately obsolete. ``Watch it fizz and
pop,'' Britney Spears sings. ``The clock is ticking and we can't
stop.'' As a bonus, kiddie pop sells not only itself but all sorts
of merchandise: T-shirts, posters, videos, baseball caps.
(Merchandising is also the true Force behind the characterless new
``Star Wars'' characters.) With the Internet threatening to force
recording companies to lower their prices, merchandise could help
maintain pop profit margins.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 1547EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1919 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-KIDDIE-POP-3DTA     07-07 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-KIDDIE-POP-3DTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: profit margins.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kiddie-pop acts make ideal fodder for the current music
business. They're malleable and ripe for exploitation by the
managers and producers they depend on. And they're stepping into a
business that, with radio stations' help, is doing its best to
recreate 1961: selling singles not albums, pushing one-hit wonders
and tossing as many potential teen idols into the marketplace as it
can find. If a career lasts only a year or two _ well, there's more
in the talent pool.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the prospects for former kiddie stars are better than
they were a decade ago. Alanis Morrissette lived down her past as a
Canadian child star; Ricky Martin did his time in Menudo, the
Puerto Rican boy band. Robbie Williams, formerly of the English boy
band Take That, was a smash in England and has been moderately
successful here. Jordan Knight, a former New Kid on the Block,
recently had a Top 10 single, and Geri Halliwell, who bailed out of
the Spice Girls after two albums, has started to present herself as
an adult. Then again, for comic relief there was Vanilla Ice's
attempted comeback as a thrash-rocker.
</P>
<P>
   In its music, kiddie pop invariably looks back. It's a yardstick
for what pop styles are now considered unthreatening; the music can
be recycled and resold to audiences who never heard its past
incarnations. Leif Garrett remade 1950s hits in the 1970s; New
Edition started out emulating the Jackson 5.
</P>
<P>
   The current surge of kiddie pop can be credited to, or blamed
on, two 1980s hitmakers: the New Kids on the Block and Madonna.
When New Edition got out from under the thumb of their producer and
manager, Maurice Starr, he decided to apply the same tricks to a
white group: the New Kids. It didn't matter that their voices would
never match the Chi-Lites or the Delfonics; the New Kids were
handsome, bland and camera-ready. They danced a little, sang a
little and flirted a lot, and they left their game plan behind for
1990s groups. Johnny Wright, who worked his way up Starr's
management company, supervised the ascent of the Backstreet Boys
(whom he no longer manages) and 'N Sync as well as Britney Spears.
</P>
<P>
   For boy bands, the formula has grown so rigid that only a
10-year-old girl can distinguish 'N Sync from the Backstreet Boys
(both quintets), or 98 Degrees from C-Note from LFO (all quartets).
They need a blond, some brunettes and one moderately swarthy type;
someone, usually the swarthy one, has a little facial hair to
designate him as the group's sensitive rebel. Each guy has a single
identifying attribute _ he's an ex-Mouseketeer or a basketball
player or secretly shy _ that makes the fans feel a little closer.
And the rest is smiles, harmony and promises: ``I Just Wanna Be
With You,'' ``To Me You're Everything,'' ``Don't Wanna Lose You
Now.'' Real boyfriends never seem to be as agreeable.
</P>
<P>
   Female kiddie stars are a newer phenomenon. While little girls
may have identified with Little Peggy March or Brenda Lee, pop
moguls generally assumed that pretty boys would be the main magnet
for allowance money. Then Madonna changed their minds. Female
kiddie pop owes everything to early Madonna; the sauciness, the
bouncy beat, the show of independence coupled with come-ons. Songs
like ``Borderline'' and ``Holiday,'' smoothing out disco with
bell-toned keyboards and chirpy choruses, became templates for
singers who want to cultivate both dance-club disk jockeys and pop
radio exposure. (Boy bands like 'N Sync have listened to Madonna,
too.) The Spice Girls split Madonna's personality five ways, toning
down the toughness and losing the Roman Catholic fixations while
exploiting countless merchandising tie-ins. And now, young hopefuls
like the 16-year-old English singer Billie _ who actually has a
promising voice _ are studying the Spice Girls.
</P>
<P>
   Kiddie-pop albums are formulaic down to the song order. The
first cut is the most aggressive or suggestive one, the closest
counterfeit of adult pop. The trick is to come up with an entendre
so vague that adults can give it a sexual interpretation and
children, theoretically, don't. The Backstreet Boys open
``Millennium'' with ``Larger Than Life,'' a reflection on fame that
flatters their fans as the people whose love can make everything
right; looking at the crowd and watching the bodies swaying, they
add, ``Wish I could thank you in a different way.'' And what,
exactly, is Britney Spears being hit with when she puts on her Pat
Benatar voice to insist, ``Hit me, baby, one more time''?
</P>
<P>
   But after the opening, nearly grown-up song, kiddie-pop albums
grow sappier fast. They have you're-the-one songs and
after-the-breakup songs and self-esteem songs and dreaming-of-you
songs. Most groups also have a pious number praising God, parents
or both, all in the most unctuous harmony.
</P>
<P>
   The hand-me-down music of current kiddie pop presents an
illusion of racial assimilation. Despite their segregated lineups
(with the Spice Girls as an exception), kiddie-pop groups dress,
sing, dance and banter like rhythm-and-blues and hip-hop
performers. Just about every white boy-band stretches its vocal
melismas like George Michael striving to imitate Stevie Wonder. But
instead of pretending that they invented the style, kiddie-pop
bands are self-conscious about the racial pilfering that's as old
as rock-and-roll. At the Zootopia show, 98 Degrees followed some
rhythm-and-blues harmonizing with the Offspring's ``Pretty Fly for
a White Guy,'' simultaneously self-deflating and self-promoting.
</P>
<P>
   Kiddie pop is calculated to a fare-thee-well. Its best craftsmen
_ notably the Swedish songwriter and producer, Max Martin, who's
behind the Backstreet Boys and Britney Spears _ have some fun as
they plunder hooks and gimmicks from Abba, Michael Jackson,
Babyface, Kansas, Phil Collins, Prince, the Cars, the Eagles, Roxy
Music and other hitmakers from the 1960s to the 1990s. They know
that the music's most ardent fans come to the music with no
perception of cliches and no distrust of gooey sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   And for kiddie pop's shadow audience, the adults who are making
the albums linger in the charts long after the first rush of the
grade-school set, the music's appeal is inseparable from its
pre-fab, synthetic essence. It holds nothing new and difficult,
nothing agonizingly sincere or brutally realistic, nothing barbed
or underhanded or unruly or obtuse. At the same time, it doesn't
feel too old-fashioned, not with Britney Spears singing, ``e-mail
My heart.'' Kiddie pop provides a harmless first crush, an easy
transition to adult concerns, which will intrude soon enough in the
lives of its younger fans. The music is an intermission between
crises, and it's less troublesome than genuine rejuvenation could
ever be. Because in kiddie pop, growing pains never arrive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
