<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSIDERATIONS FOR BUILDING A CONCRETE SLAB 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A concrete slab rests on a sand base on the ground. It can be
used as a patio or as an extension to the driveway _ a space to
park your boat, say, or trailer. Because it rests on the ground and
not on footings, it cannot be used as a floor for a building like a
garage.
</P>
<P>
   Creating the slab does not require any special building skills,
but it is hard work. At least two people are required to move the
concrete, pour it, level it, then smooth and rough it. Weather is
an important consideration. Since all the work will be done
outdoors, you must pick a dry day with no rain in the forecast. The
temperature should be between 65 and 75 degrees Fahrenheit.
</P>
<P>
   Before beginning this project, check with the local building
inspector to see if the codes require a special permit. Also make
sure you know exactly where your property boundary lines are; you
don't want the pad to extend onto your neighbor's land.
</P>
<P>
   For pouring and shaping the concrete, you will need to rent the
following tools: a heavy-duty wheelbarrow, a bull float with
extension handles, a joint tool, an edging tool, a magnesium trowel
for final smoothing and a heavy-duty push broom with stiff
bristles. You will also need a few wood-working tools, a hammer,
saw and a two- or four-foot level, to build the concrete forms.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, don't forget safety gear. Wet concrete may seem like
mild, inert stuff, but it is caustic and can cause skin burns. Wear
long pants and a long- sleeved shirt, high rubber boots and
heavy-duty gloves when pouring and smoothing the concrete.
</P>
<P>
   Begin by selecting the best location for the slab. If you are
making a parking surface for a boat or trailer, then it must be
adjacent to the driveway. With a patio slab, you have more options.
View, traffic flow to the house and kitchen, orientation to the sun
and privacy are all factors. Avoid sites that are often remain
water-soaked after heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
   When you have chosen the location, lay out the perimeter on the
ground. You can do this by driving a series of stakes and running
cord between them, or you can spray a line of bright paint directly
onto the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is preparation of the subgrade, the earth beneath
the slab. This step is important, because a poor subgrade will
allow the concrete slab to settle unevenly, causing cracks or
fissures.
</P>
<P>
   Remove all organic matter, grass, sod and roots, as well as
large stones, from the site. Grade the ground so it is level, then
examine it for soft, mucky or spongy spots. Dig these out and fill
the holes with material similar to the rest of the site or with
granular material like sand, gravel or crushed stone.
</P>
<P>
   Next tamp down the ground to compress the soil, then cover the
site with granular fill. The fill should be at least four to six
inches thick and should extend at least 12 inches beyond the
perimeter of the slab. This extra extension will prevent rainwater
from undercutting the slab during heavy storms.
</P>
<P>
   Dampen the sand or gravel lightly _ there should be no puddles
or freestanding water _ then tamp the surface down. If your slab
site is relatively small, you can use a hand tamper, but for larger
jobs it is best to rent a heavy roller or a power tamper (also
called a vibratory plate compactor) for this operation. Check to
make sure that the subgrade is level. Add extra fill to any low
spots, than tamp again.
</P>
<P>
   At this point you are ready to construct the concrete forms. Use
2 by 4's that are straight, smooth and free of warps to make the
forms. Stand the 2 by 4's on edge and brace them in position with 1
by 3 stakes. Position the stakes so they are a minimum of 36 inches
apart and so the tops are level, or slightly lower than the top of
the forms. Nail the stakes to the 2 by 4's with double- headed
nails (also called duplex or stage nails).
</P>
<P>
   There should not be any gaps between the boards, and the forms
must be sturdy enough to withstand the horizontal pressure of the
poured concrete without bulging. Use a spirit level to the make
sure the forms are level. Oil the inside surfaces of the form
boards (the sides that will touch the concrete) to prevent the
boards from sticking to the hardened concrete.
</P>
<P>
   At this point you are ready to order the concrete, pour it and
surface it to make the slab. This will be covered next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
