<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Port of Choice: Easy USB's
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a new Pentium III PC and a printer that can work with
USB or parallel connections. Which should I use to hook up the
printer?
</P>
<P>
   A. The choice between the USB and parallel ports for your
printer's connection might depend on how comfortable you are with
installing hardware. The USB, or Universal Serial Bus, route is
considered by many to be easier than configuring the parallel port.
Windows 98 will automatically recognize that you have attached a
new USB device and lead you through the installation process.
</P>
<P>
   Another benefit of USB is that its data transfer speed is
usually a bit faster than that of a standard parallel port. And by
using the USB connection, you free up your parallel port for some
other device.
</P>
<P>
   USB is designed to eliminate the need for juggling extra PC
cards, settings and switches when adding devices. With the proper
configuration, it is possible to link up to 127 USB devices to one
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Early versions of Windows 95 don't offer USB functions, so you
may have to download a patch from Microsoft. Apple Computer's iMac
and its newer G3 models handle USB connections. You can find out
more at www.usb.org.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
e-mail to Q&AMP;A(AT)nytimes.com or postal mail to Questions, Circuits,
The New York Times, 229 West 43d Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959.
This column will answer questions of general interest, but letters
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 1557EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1923 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-URBAN-GARDENS-2TAKES-     07-07 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-URBAN-GARDENS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK ROOFTOP GARDENING: FEATHERING THE NEST OUTDOORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: 2 optional sidebars in 2nd take)  
 (bl)  
 By MARTHA BAKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a city like this, every square foot of open space
is a treasured commodity, and nobody appreciates that fact more
than urban gardeners. As a breed, they're a hardy lot, highly
adaptable and ready to overcome all obstacles; in these respects,
they're not so different from the gardens they create. And create
them they do: in window boxes, on terraces, in brownstone yards no
bigger than a hankie and on rooftops _ especially on rooftops (as
any aerial view of New York City will bear out).
</P>
<P>
   The challenges facing a rooftop gardener here are legion.
Daylong exposure to brutal sunlight, unfettered winds, air
pollution, shallow soil, not to mention the city ordinances
regarding weight allowances, water strictures and a myriad of other
safety factors _ it's enough to make most gardeners throw in the
trowel. But the prodigious effort is well worth the reward _ a
garden with panoramic views like few others in the world.
</P>
<P>
   When a garden sprouts from a rooftop, it acts as a forecourt to
everything around it, so that the view becomes a part of the garden
itself. (The Chinese call the concept ``borrowing the landscape.'')
One particularly fine example of the phenomenon is the rooftop
garden of Tim and Dagny Du Val, who design and install urban
gardens through their company, Plant Specialists.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, when the company was forced to move from its
Manhattan location, the Du Vals' search for a new space led them to
Long Island City, Queens. There they found the ideal site: a
mid-19th-century metal foundry housed in a complex of two-story
brick buildings covering an entire city block.
</P>
<P>
   With more than enough space for their needs, the couple reserved
a portion of it (along with the foundry's original cobblestone
courtyard) for themselves and their company, then converted the
rest into small business spaces and European-style ateliers for
artists. Today, a Starbucks commissary, Authentico, which caters
Mexican food, and a Turkish bakery coexist with Edwina von Gal, a
landscape architect, and Tom Penn, a sculptor and the son of
photographer Irving Penn.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the Du Vals' roof garden remained an on-and-off-again
affair. ``It started out as an orphanage,'' Ms. Du Val explained,
``a place for salvaging castoff plants.'' But once the garden
became permanent, it turned into what she called a nonstop
evolution.
</P>
<P>
   From the very beginning, the Du Vals' intent was to maximize the
view, which encompasses the adjacent Queensboro Bridge and an
uninterrupted sweep of Manhattan skyline. Another plus was the
rooftop's generous footage _ about 2,500 square feet. To divide it
into ``rooms,'' they defined discrete areas with different floor
materials: Mexican beach pebbles around a fountain in the garden
proper, black cast-concrete pavers in the cooking area, lighter
concrete-and-pebble pavers in the living and entertaining section
and cedar planking in the dining room. (The materials can usually
be found at garden-supply stores.) Then, to delineate transitional
routes from one area to the next, they created a series of teak
walkways.
</P>
<P>
   Before any of the floor plan could be put into place, however,
the roof had to be covered with a sealing membrane _ it might be a
silicone sealant, rubber or asphalt _ to prevent water damage and
protect the structural integrity of the building. To keep the
membrane from being punctured, the couple had to make sure that
everything they put on top of it _ flooring frame, irrigation
pipes, paving, pots and furnishings _ was lightweight and
distributed evenly over the surface.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, the roof had a 2 percent gradient, a common
construction element intended to expedite drainage, and just enough
slope to make one leg feel longer than the other and set plants and
furniture at a jaunty tilt. To level the surface, the Du Vals
installed feet, or pods, that screwed into the frame on which the
flooring was laid.
</P>
<P>
   (Another approach they might have considered is precast pedestal
pavers: paving squares that have adjustable built-in feet. They're
laid with open spaces between them to allow for water runoff.)
</P>
<P>
   To provide for shade, a must for a rooftop garden, the Du Vals'
conceived a wood-beamed pergola entwined with fragrant wisteria.
The vine is still in its infancy, but when full grown, it will
cover the structure like a lacy mantle. New-growth trees, shade for
future summers, include rooftop favorites like river birches, black
pines and Japanese cut-leaf maples, as well as the delightful
surprise of Colorado quaking aspens. A reminder of Ms. Du Val's
childhood, aspens are very hard to find here, but seem to do well.
``I've always loved the way their leaves shimmer in the wind,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other hardy plants on the roof include shrubs like Virginia
sweetspire, rhododendron and boxwood; perennials like lavender,
roses, cat's whiskers and pennisetum grass, and annuals like
plumbago, Martha Washington geraniums and clerodendrum. Vines
thrive here, as well: green blankets of Boston ivy mellow the old
brick walls, and passifloras send their wayward tendrils up wall
trellises and up the projectile-shaped  &UR; tuteur &LR;  Ms. Du Val
fashioned from copper plumbing pipe (a contrivance she refers to as
the rocket ship).
</P>
<P>
   In warm-weather months, the Du Vals' rooftop is well equipped
for entertaining. All the furniture _ from the teak ocean-liner
deck chairs to the steel-topped dining table _ is weatherproof and
meant to last a lifetime. But it was also chosen for its lightness
in respect for the weight-bearing limitations of the roof itself.
</P>
<P>
   (New York City codes restrict weight on a roof to 40 to 60
pounds a square foot, depending on the structure of the building,
and that includes people, pots, plants and pets.)
</P>
<P>
   Dinner parties aren't the only entertainments provided for here.
To amuse bird-watchers, there are feeders that attract dove
couples, finches, larks, hummingbirds, mockingbirds _ even the odd
parakeet. To induce serenity, there's a fountain made from an old
gear mechanism, a remnant of the foundry's earlier life as a
machine-parts manufactory. Du Val drilled a hole in the bottom to
insert a cord for a pump, then sealed the entry hole with silicone.
There's even an overflow pipe to correct the water level _ a handy
device for coping with heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, for warmth on chilly nights, there's an outdoor
fireplace. It is, in fact, a flue-topped barbecue, but the Du Vals
like to use it solely as a hearth _ and given the pure enchantment
of that idea in a rooftop setting, who could blame them?
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBARS FOLLOW IN 2nd TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Planters That Are Roofproof &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a rooftop, structural stress is a major concern,
so weight is a crucial factor when choosing a planter. Today,
companies like Claycraft produce high-quality fiberglass planters
that are not only as weatherproof as concrete but also 1/8 of the
weight. Unlike concrete or clay, the pots are easily repaired with
fiberglass resin, available in most hardware stores, and won't fade
or peel. And the beauty part is that they look like cement or
stone, bronze or cast iron. Prices range from $40 or $50 for a
15-inch planter, up to $225 for a 25-inch one. You can find
Claycraft products at Gardencrafters, 37 Grand St. (West Broadway);
(212) 268-0530.
</P>
<P>
   Another good source is Roundbush Casting (516 676-6236),
available to the trade through landscape designers, and known for
its fiberglass interpretations of carved stone and lead planters.
Other options include high-tech aluminum containers, available in
garden-supply stores like Mecox Gardens in Southampton. Or even the
plastic pots that plants come in will do. Placed in groups, the
pots disappear beneath the plants' leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget that potting soil can be weighty, so opt for a mix
of topsoil, peat moss and perlite. Or use Pro-Mix, a soil
substitute. But if you do, fertilize with nourishers like fish
emulsion, Bloom Booster (for roses and annuals) or Hollytone (for
evergreens).
</P>
<P>
   Irrigating A Roof Garden
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Because weight on a roof must be evenly distributed,
you'll want lots of smaller plant pots instead of a few large ones.
But since smaller pots dry out quickly, daily watering is essential
_ a problem if a garden is large and time scarce.
</P>
<P>
   The best solution: Before you put down flooring, install an
irrigation system of pipes, spaghetti tubing and timers that can be
preset to water plants automatically. Electrically operated systems
are a better choice for roof gardens than battery-driven ones,
because they can be set for the short watering times that smaller
plants need. An electrically operated system (with a battery
backup) for an 8-by-25-foot garden would cost about $1,200, Tim Du
Val of Plant Specialists in New York said. (And be sure that any
above-the-floor pipes are hidden by greenery.)
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, an irrigation system will be zone-balanced, with tubing
and timers strategically arranged to cover specific areas: one zone
for shrubs and trees, which need longer watering times; one for
small plants. For a larger garden, around 15 by 50 feet, an
electrically operated system that is zone-balanced might cost
$2,500.
</P>
<P>
   Installing an irrigation system _ or for that matter, any part
of a roof garden's flooring _ is best left to professionals. And if
your proposed garden site tops a co-op building, submit an
engineer-designed plan to the board before starting construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
