<HEADER>
A1929 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMMA-GARDEN-ART-ART-     07-07 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMMA-GARDEN-ART-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLECTING VERSATILE SOUVENIRS, ARRANGING NATURE AND ART 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ELAINE LOUIE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The first thing people notice about Robert Homma is
his three-foot-long braid. It gleams, it moves, and it ends just
below his waist.
</P>
<P>
   The second thing they notice is that he is surrounded by still
lifes. On the rooftop garden of his apartment near Lincoln Center,
there are patches of velvety moss, each in its own hand-thrown
ceramic pot. There are triptychs of 45-year-old bonsai _ juniper,
maple and elm. Heart-shaped rocks, some pale gray, others dark like
granite, nestle on another bed of moss.
</P>
<P>
   Most people collect objects for indoors. Homma, a partner in
Dimson Homma, a shop on the Upper East Side that sells Ming
furniture, celadon porcelain and rare live birds (and what is a
shop but a place for still lifes?), collects things for indoors _
and outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   For Homma, who is 51 and a third-generation Japanese-American,
collecting for himself, which is nearly synonymous with buying for
the shop, is as much a daily ritual, an exercise of the eye and the
hand, as the braiding of his hair. It began in 1952. That summer,
and for the next 16 summers, his parents packed their three sons _
Robert, then 4; Tom, 8, and Steve, not yet 1 _ into the family car
and drove from Highland Park, Ill., to visit aunts, uncles and
cousins in Pasadena, Calif. Crammed in the back of a car in the
days before air-conditioning and the Discman, what were three
squirming boys to do? Collect, their mother said.
</P>
<P>
   She handed the two older boys a tiny overnight bag and a cookie
tin. ``Every time we made a stop, we'd be encouraged to pick up a
souvenir _ a rock, a leaf, a fossil, an arrowhead,'' Homma said.
</P>
<P>
   In Highland Park, where the boys caught crayfish in the streams
and built forts in trees, Homma discovered the beauty of moss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the verdancy of moss, the greens, the intensity, the
softness,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, he studied painting at the University of Iowa, and
ikebana in Chicago. ``What that does, even more than teaching you
how to arrange flowers,'' he said, ``is train your eye to see
things in nature, the curve of a branch, the composition.'' Moving
to Manhattan in 1982, his first job was making deliveries for food
impresario Eli Zabar. Eight months later, Homma was Zabar's
director of catering.
</P>
<P>
   At home, which he has been renovating for two years, he uses
shoji screens as a serene backdrop for his collections: three
Japanese rice bowls, each carved from a single piece of wood, and
three gourds, two brought back from China and one grown on the
terrace. But the screens also hide his largest collections: 1,000
art books, stored in double rows, and 1,000 compact disks.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the 600-square-foot studio, blue predominates. It's
in the Tibetan rugs on the floor and in a French quilt on the bed.
``Some people think blue is cold,'' he said, ``but I think it's
calming.''
</P>
<P>
   If blue is the color within, a hundred shades of green and as
many shades of white rule the 700-square-foot terrace. There are
silvery green junipers, chartreuse cactuses, olive-green grape
leaves. White is the color of the fat clumps of hydrangea, the
masses of impatiens at the foot of the fishpond, and the
night-blooming jasmine, strategically placed at the door of the
studio. At night, the scent of jasmine wafts into the studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``White is the one color you can see at night,'' Homma said.
</P>
<P>
   It is not enough to collect objects, however. Homma also has
pets: Licorice, a standard poodle; Sky, a blue-gray Persian cat,
and Emil, a turtle. And don't forget the godchildren, who come from
California for a week each summer, plopping their sleeping bags on
the floor of what the owner calls ``Camp Homma.''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there are the friends.
</P>
<P>
   A studio is not necessarily a small place.
</P>
<P>
   Shelves Behind Screens
</P>
<P>
   To store his collections of books and compact disks, Robert
Homma hired a woodworker to build 14-inch-deep pine bookshelves on
four of the existing walls. The shelves, which hold double rows of
books, are adjustable and rest on pegs that fit into holes drilled
into the walls. Concealing the books and CDs are 120 square feet of
custom-made sliding shoji screens of different heights and widths.
The screens are fiberglass paper framed in pine, which Homma
stained a warm shade of brown.
</P>
<P>
   The total cost of the storage system was $7,000 _ $5,000 for the
screens and $2,000 for the shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Shoji screens can be found at Oriental Living, a 20-year-old
company whose specialty is woodworking and making Shoji screens. It
is located at 102-06 Northern Boulevard (at 102nd Street), Corona,
Queens; (718) 476-2360.
</P>
</TEXT>
