<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By LESLIE LAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Wee Bit of Heather
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'm a Scotophile, so I love the idea of heather and am
thinking of planting a clump of it on a slope on the property I've
just bought. Before I do, I'd like to know whether all heather is
purple and, if so, for how much of the year? Will it survive
below-zero tempera-tures? And most im-portant, is it soft? I want
to lie there in my kilt to write poems.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The blooms of true heather, Calluna vulgaris, usually appear
in late summer and last for six to eight weeks. The Heather
Society, an international organization headquartered in Britain,
recognizes 13 flower colors, including amethyst, beetroot, lilac,
lavender, mauve, purple, ruby, shell pink and, for variety, salmon.
White, too. You can expand both palette and bloom season by
planting other members of the Erica family, like heaths. You can
also get a lot of color from the plants themselves. There are
hundreds of heathers, many of which have very showy new growth in
spring, brilliant yellow summer foliage or leaves that turn scarlet
or orange in winter.
</P>
<P>
   Hardiness varies, but in general heathers are tough plants that
can take subzero temperatures, especially with ample snow cover to
protect them. The slope sounds promising; heather needs good
drainage. It also requires acid soil and regular pruning. Left
unsheared, it soon gets gangly and sparse-flowered.
</P>
<P>
   I'd say you'd better have both a tough posterior and some tough
heather before you try the kilt trick, but to quote David Small,
president of the Heather Society, C. vulgaris ``is tough and wiry
and will tolerate the odd person lying on it,'' though it ``would
not tolerate constant trampling.'' He added that several are named
for malt whiskies, and ``there are a number named after parts of
Scotland which might create the right atmosphere'' for writing
poetry. For best results, though, focus on height, not
nomenclature. Among the mauves, for instance, 4 inch tall
Heidepracht is likely to make a more inspiring bed than Macdonald
of Glencoe, which can approach 2 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Heather is planted in spring and fall. Sources with wide
selections include Heaths &AMP; Heathers, 502 East Haskell Hill Road,
Shelton, Wash. 98584-8429, (800) 294-3284,
www.heathsandheathers.com and Rockspray Nursery, P.O. Box 693,
Truro, Mass. 02666, (508) 349-3942, www.rockspray.com. Both
catalogs are free.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to learn more about these fascinating plants,
consider joining a group, either the Heather Society, Denbeigh, All
Saints Road, Creeting St. Mary, Ipswich, Suffolk, IP6 8PJ, England;
or, closer to home, the Northeast Heather Society, 1066 Paper
Street, Suffield, Conn., 06078.
</P>
<P>
   Mystery Irritant
</P>
<P>
   Q. Recently, while clearing overgrown honeysuckle, I pulled up
30 or 40 young thistles. Shortly afterward, I developed itchy,
localized blebs on my hands and face. Could the thistle juices on
my leather gloves have caused an allergic reaction? (In the past,
I've pulled up thistles barehanded without any problem.)
</P>
<P>
   A. Wyman's Garden Encyclopedia describes the highly invasive
Canada thistle (Cirsium arvense) as a vicious weed, and you could
probably raise a rash by rubbing your skin with its prickly leaves.
But neither this nor any other thistle shows up on standard lists
of common allergens.
</P>
<P>
   You might have an unusual allergy; almost everything disagrees
with somebody. But before you see the doctor, I suggest you
consider the likelihood of plain old poison ivy. That evil vine
often lurks unsuspected in overgrown places and is frequently seen
(or, alas, not seen) in conjunction with honeysuckle.
</P>
<P>
   The Fruiting Body
</P>
<P>
   Q. I've been told that in deadheading day lilies, it's necessary
to take off the fruiting body. What's that?
</P>
<P>
   A. Technically, a fruiting body is the spore-making part of
plants that don't flower, like mosses, or of nonplants, like
mushrooms. But the term is also often used to mean the fleshy green
seedpods (technically, the fruit) of plants not known for fruit
making. If you peel away a wilted day lily flower that's still
attached to the stem, you'll see a tiny, olive-shape growth at the
base _ the fruit. Snap it off carefully, where it meets the stem,
so you don't hurt developing buds on the same scape (leafless
flower-bearing stem that rises from ground level).
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 West
43d Street, New York 10036, or by e-mail to
gardening(AT)nytimes.com. Those of general interest will be
published. Unpublished questions cannot be answered individually. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
