<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOOR-DESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSIDE OUT AND OUTSIDE IN: A NEW GARDEN STYLE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The story goes that when Philip Johnson showed Frank Lloyd
Wright inside his 1949 glass house in New Canaan, Conn., the father
of Fallingwater and other architectural masterpieces asked if he
was meant to take off his hat.
</P>
<P>
   Today, if Wright could see what's going on outside the house, he
might be forgiven for not putting his hat back on as he left.
</P>
<P>
   The craze for picture windows and patios during the 1950s and
60s that became the gardening renaissance of the 80s that became
the boom in casual outdoor living in the early 1990s has found its
endgame: outdoor interior decoration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gone from furnishing the outdoors to decorating the
outdoors,'' said Bruce Butterfield, the research director of the
National Gardening Association in Burlington, Vt. ``What people are
trying to do is replicate the popular great rooms in their houses,
but in open air.'' Think ceilings as high as the sky.
</P>
<P>
   The garden's plants and flowers have become a genus of home
accents and accessories. In 1998, Americans bought $1.82 billion
worth of casual furniture, as the industry calls summer and outdoor
furnishings, an increase of 12.3 percent over 1997, according to
Garden Decor, a new trade publication. This was more than double
the increase from 1996 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable how big a business it's become,'' said Cindy
Sheaffer, the editor of Garden Decor. ``And there are all kinds of
retailers getting into the business, from mass merchants like
Target to new specialty stores, selling garden style for inside or
outside the home.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the furniture is out there, the walls are going up.
Trellises and other ``verticals'' are hot. So is water: decorative
fountains and sculptural sprinkler systems. Think of it as outdoor
plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   Style wars are breaking out.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going on, on the decorating side?'' Butterfield asked.
``The Mediterranean `virgin olive oil' look, the English cottage
look, the Southwestern theme, Asian theme, the Adirondack camp
look. Outdoor styles are mimicking indoor styles; the fantasy
element indoors is being brought outdoors.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith &AMP; Hawken, the Mill Valley, Calif., company that originally
sold only high-end gardening tools, was one of the first with
garden furnishings for full-scale decorating. The company's sales
just crossed the $100 million mark. According to Kathy Tierney,
Smith &AMP; Hawken's chief executive, the two weeks before and after
the Fourth of July are the apex of outdoor decorating, during which
the floor space in the company's 40 stores nationwide and the pages
of its catalogs are devoted to furnishings, not tools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fashionable interest has forced us to move off-center a
little, away from English and European, to Asian,'' she said of
this season's outdoor furnishing styles. ``It's like the food
fusion thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The other big exterior-decoration trend, she said, is
``grandmother's garden, the old-fashioned American grandma's
garden. All the plants that were declasse five years ago: zinnias,
dahlias, gladiolas.''
</P>
<P>
   All the little-old-lady furniture _ the porch gliders and
garden-variety 1940s bent-metal lawn chairs and mirrored gazing
balls _ go with them.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened to bare feet and grass?
</P>
<P>
   Americans spent over $30 billion last year on their gardens and
lawns, up 13 percent from 1997, according to the National Gardening
Association. But they are cultivating a new level of comfort. The
association says that in 1998, over 35 million households _ out of
a total of 100 million households in the United States _ bought an
``outdoor living product,'' which includes everything from
furniture to grills to arbors.
</P>
<P>
   Gardening as a style, doesn't need soil any more than hydroponic
tomatoes do. Outdoor casual living is a trend that accommodates
those who may or may not actually have a garden.
</P>
<P>
   Gardening has a strong, natural pull when it comes to pushing
non-horticultural products, said Cheryl Trine, the founder of
Garden Net Inc., a Web site for gardening information
(www.gardennet.com), with electronic advertising links to
retailers, from nurseries to ornamental garden furniture to tools
and power equipment. ``It's almost as good an appeal as sex for
selling,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Trine's online surveys have shown her that her audience is
25 to 45 years old, as likely to be living in apartments and
furnishing terraces as living in houses and spading dirt. They
include the next generation of gardeners, behind the baby boomers
who unearthed the garden-chic trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``What interests me is how successfully companies like Smith &AMP;
Hawken have equated gardening with status,'' Ms. Trine said.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by over a million visits to her site monthly, she is
introducing a pay-per-view magazine in September.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers are throwing themselves at garden style like bugs at
blue lights. There are 159 gardening magazines, according to the
Magazine Publishers of America (by comparison, there are 119
interior-design and decoration titles). Twelve were introduced last
year; five in 1997. The start-ups are attacking every angle of the
market. New Eden, which showed up in May, is a kind of Wallpaper
for the outdoors: a ``downtown'' gardening magazine. Rebecca's
Gardening, which Hearst introduced in April, is a magazine for
``garden interest,'' which includes cooking and craft projects.
Rebecca Kolls, the former television weather reporter who is its
creative director, has a syndicated television program. She is
being presented as a down-market Martha Stewart, who promises
garden projects that can be achieved in less than 30 minutes for
less than $50.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gardening's bigger than it's ever been,'' Ms. Kolls said.
``But it's bigger for a different reason. People want a beautiful
place, but `Show me how to do it easily' is what they tell me.''
Ms. Kolls doesn't use the Latin in naming plants, for instance,
which she said got her into ``a lot of trouble'' with traditional
gardeners.
</P>
<P>
   Older titles are adjusting their focus. Garden Design, the
five-year-old magazine which has consciously consolidated gardening
with issues of style, intends to double its pages devoted to
interior decoration in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Container gardens have been the big winner in the new landscape
of interest. They come in every style, from Tuscan terra cotta to
Vietnamese pottery. A new generation of durable, inexpensive,
lightweight synthetics has made them even more attractive. Sales
for containers increased 36 percent in 1998 over the previous year,
the gardening association says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of it in interior decoration terms,'' said Butterfield,
the association's research director. ``People on their decks can
bring their gardens right into their living spaces, like a bouquet
of flowers on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tierney of Smith &AMP; Hawken said that the company's SoHo store
was one of its most successful, largely because of container
gardening.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fashion element,'' she explained. ``It doesn't have to
be permanent. You can be a dabbler.''
</P>
<P>
   You can also create it quickly, then sit down and watch it over
a cocktail, instead of weeding until it's too dark to see.
Pressures on people's time has produced a shorter growing season
that has nothing to do with plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's kind of the sad part about it,'' said Ms. Kolls, now
doing double duty as a magazine and television personality, when
asked about how much time she finds to spend in her garden. ``I'm
always working in someone else's garden, for the show. Mine's kind
of thin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
