<SLUG> BC-NY-TKTS-BOOTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMES SQUARE'S TKTS BOOTH WILL BE A TOUGH ACT TO FOLLOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, the TKTS booth that
ornaments Times Square like an oversize red-and-white box kite is
one of the ``symbols of the renaissance'' of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   To Ron Silver, the actor and chairman of the official NYC 2000
millennium committee, the booth is ``Times Square's centerpiece.''
</P>
<P>
   To John Breglio, chairman of the Theater Development Fund, which
built and operates the booth, it is a ``symbol of Broadway theater
to an entire generation'' and ``perhaps one of the country's most
successful graphic designs.'' The booth sells discounted same-day
tickets for performances of Broadway productions.
</P>
<P>
   You would think they were about to nominate the innovative
26-year-old, pipe-and-canvas structure for landmark designation.
But with these words of praise on June 15, they buried it.
</P>
<P>
   The officials announced a competition for architects, landscape
architects and graphic designers to design a new TKTS booth, which
would open next year on the site of the present booth, at the north
end of Times Square, which is known as Duffy Square.
</P>
<P>
   The competition seems to doom one more facet of Broadway's
architectural past, which has been chipped away piece by piece in
recent years until very little remains of what was once a
splendidly pungent esthetic amalgam, made of dozens of incongruous
icons layered one on top of another. (In a notable exception to the
bulldozing rule, the former I. Miller Building at Broadway and 46th
Street, ornamented by four sculptures by Alexander Stirling Calder,
was designated an official landmark June 29.)
</P>
<P>
   While preservation advocates believe a landmark case could be
made for the TKTS booth, as a practical matter it is ineligible for
designation until 2003, when it turns 30. And it probably wouldn't
stand up that long.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become necessary to build a new structure,'' said Jack
Goldstein, executive director of the Theater Development Fund,
explaining the need for a new booth. ``Time and weather have taken
their toll.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials hope that a new design will speed the lines of
ticketgoers that jam Duffy Square, hundreds at a time at peak
periods; make life more comfortable for those who work inside the
cramped structure, and raise the visual profile of the booth, which
has been overshadowed by the new gigantism of Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   Even John Schiff, who designed the booth in 1973 with Robert
Mayers, believes its time may be past. Indeed, he noted, it was
meant to be temporary. ``Change is fine,'' Schiff said. ``But I
think it's going to be a tough act to follow.''
</P>
<P>
   That is true of all of Broadway's lost icons: the Parthenon-like
Rivoli Theater, the jukebox-modern Rialto Theater, the charming
neon Simple Simon and Pieman sign at Howard Johnson's, even the
utilitarian armed forces recruiting station. Each spoke in its own
eccentric, irreplaceable way of the evolution of Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   And the TKTS booth tells a tale in its slapdash, improvisational
style of a dark moment in the early 1970s when Broadway was
desperate for resuscitation but so strapped for cash that solutions
had to be crafted from bubble gum and baling wire _ the big-city
version of, ``Gee, we can use the back of the garage for a stage
and turn mom's old sheets into curtains.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Mayor John V. Lindsay, the Office of Midtown Planning and
Development lent a city-owned trailer to the Theater Development
Fund to be used as a booth for the sale of half-priced tickets on
the day of the performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a donated trailer and a can of paint,'' Schiff
recalled. The architects were instructed simply to ornament the
trailer with supergraphics. They feared such a small gesture would
look anemic in Times Square but they had almost no money to do
anything else; the capital budget was a paltry $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Then they hit on the idea of using a portion of the operating
budget to rent pipes on a monthly basis from the R.C. Mugler
scaffolding company in the Bronx. With these, they built an open
framework around the trailer, effectively quadrupling its volume
and considerably elevating its profile.
</P>
<P>
   To increase visibility further, they stretched translucent
plastic panels between the pipes, some of them woven through the
structure diagonally. And they painted the abbreviation ``TKTS'' in
a bold typeface called Helvetica, using letters six feet high.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, to keep the whole structure from blowing away, they
lashed it with steel cables to four chunky concrete anchors at each
corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took four days to install,'' Schiff said. ``We weren't
designing for the millennium. We were designing for one year.''
</P>
<P>
   The TKTS booth was an instant hit. In its first day of operation
in June 1973, it sold 155 tickets; in its first week, 6,961. Since
then _ this almost sounds like a McDonald's billboard _ more than
36.5 million tickets have been sold there.
</P>
<P>
   The booth won a design award in 1973 from the New York Society
of Architects and a Bard Award in 1975 from the City Club of New
York for merit in civic architecture.
</P>
<P>
   Ned Kaufman, an associate director of the Municipal Art Society,
said many people regard the booth as ``a classic of early '70s
design.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The sense of temporariness was part of the temper of the
times,'' he said. ``It also expresses the spirit of the enterprise,
which is, `Let's go to the theater tonight.' That sense of being
cobbled together for the moment seems very expressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Theodore H.M. Prudon, an architect who is active in the
documentation and conservation of modernist design, said the booth
is notable for its esthetic qualities, sociological role and
technological innovation. ``It's the beginning of scaffold-like,
high-tech, tensile structures,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The TKTS booth was built as the Pompidou Center was being
constructed in Paris, but Schiff said he was not inspired by _
indeed, at the time might not have even known about _ the veinous,
transparently expressed steel armature designed by Renzo Piano,
Richard Rogers and Gianfranco Franchini. In any case, the booth
opened four years before the Pompidou Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Van Alen Institute, which is administering the competition,
has called for ``a design statement as memorable as the current
booth,'' whether it ``thoroughly reinvents or reinterprets the
current design.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the jury, announced earlier this week, include the
architects Enrique Norten and Marion Weiss; the landscape architect
Kathryn Gustafson and the designers Tucker Viemeister and Tony
Walton. The institute expects to receive at least 200 entries by
the Oct. 14 deadline. The first prize is $5,000. More information
is available at www.vanalen.org.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein said he had offered the old structure to the
Smithsonian Institution ``because I myself recognize the booth
definitely as a moment in the cultural history of America and in
design history.''
</P>
<P>
   Schiff, now a principal at Einhorn Yaffee Prescott, doubts that
he will enter the competition. He and Mayers sold their practice
two years ago and Mayers has retired.
</P>
<P>
   Would they have done anything differently with the TKTS booth?
``Bob Mayers only regretted that we didn't charge a fee on the
basis of ticket sales,'' Schiff said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
