<SLUG> BC-SECURITIES-PROBE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN INVESTOR SUES TEXAS SECURITIES FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A Mexico City man has filed a lawsuit against the
San Antonio investment firm InverWorld Securities, alleging
mismanagement of an account valued at more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, investigators from the Securities and Exchange
Commission have visited the InverWorld offices and the Texas State
Securities Board is looking into the firm's activities.
</P>
<P>
   In a lawsuit filed late Friday in state district court, Mexico
City resident Cesar Garcia Mendez claims he lost $1.38 million
invested in money market funds through IWG Services, an InverWorld
affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   The suit names InverWorld chief executive Jose Zollino and four
related companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Garcia has made repeated requests to Zollino and the
InverWorld defendants to return the funds into the money market
accounts into which they were deposited, but Zollino and the ...
defendants have refused to do so,'' the suit says.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit further charges that Garcia's funds were transferred
without his permission from money market funds into ``IWG Notes,''
promissory notes issued by InverWorld.
</P>
<P>
   The suit asks for an order freezing all InverWorld accounts
holding Garcia's investments.
</P>
<P>
   The investment firm's lawyer, Sarah Foster of Austin, and
InverWorld officials have not responded to repeated requests for
information. Reporters visiting the firm Tuesday were turned away.
</P>
<P>
   InverWorld is a U.S.-registered brokerage with affiliate
operations in Matamoros, Monterrey, Guadalajara and Mexico City.
InverWorld lists affiliates or offices in Switzerland, Great
Britain, the Cayman Islands, Argentina and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   Most of its clients are wealthy Mexicans, many from the northern
states.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of worried Mexicans have visited the plush new InverWorld
offices since a June 25 announcement that its London affiliate, IWG
Services Inc., was being liquidated.
</P>
<P>
   ``IWG Services Ltd. and its affiliates have suffered severe
financial setbacks in connection with emerging markets and other
investments,'' the announcement said.
</P>
<P>
   ``IWG is currently in the process of retaining an experienced
international accounting firm to handle the wind down of IWG, the
orderly management and liquidation of its assets and to ensure that
all net funds are appropriately distributed to its customers,'' the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   The news created panic in Matamoros, resulting in the abrupt
closure of InverWorld's office there.
</P>
<P>
   A San Antonio lawyer hired by InverWorld investors said he met
with Zollino last week but couldn't get a clear understanding of
the relationship between InverWorld and IWG Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first he told us it was a sister entity, which means there
must be a parent somewhere. Then he said, `We have a contract with
them,' and later he said they are just a client, just like you have
an accountant,'' said the lawyer, who asked that he not be
identified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 1616EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
