<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1948 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-NY     07-07 1259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL HEALTH: FINDING THE RIGHT WAY TO KEEP LYME DISEASE AT
BAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (nk) 
 By JANE E. BRODY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is no time to get complacent about Lyme disease, the most
common tick-borne illness in the country. Although the Food and
Drug Administration licensed the first Lyme disease vaccine for
people in December, we continue to have problems preventing this
usually treatable but sometimes devastating bacterial disease. The
three-dose vaccine is effective but not perfect, and
disease-bearing ticks are expected to be unusually abundant this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Even if fully vaccinated, everyone who ventures outdoors in
areas where ticks carrying the Lyme bacteria are likely to be
present is at risk of contracting the disease and would be wise to
observe all the usual precautions about preventing tick bites.
These bacteria, spirochetes with the scientific name Borrelia
burgdorferi, are typically carried by tiny deer ticks that feed on
white-footed mice and lizards as well as deer, people and pets.
</P>
<P>
   The new vaccine, called Lymerix and marketed by SmithKline
Beecham, was not greeted with unbridled enthusiasm by the FDA's
advisory committee, which reluctantly recommended its approval. In
fact, the head of the committee, Dr. Patricia L. Ferrieri of the
University of Minnesota Medical School, said at the time, ``It's
rare that a vaccine is voted on with such ambivalence and such a
stack of provisos.''
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine is highly unusual. It works by attacking the Lyme
organisms while they are still in an infected tick; the attack
occurs when the tick starts feeding on the blood of a vaccinated
person. The vaccine triggers the production of antibodies to a
protein called OspA on the coat of the spirochetes. It takes 24 to
72 hours of feeding time before the tick sends spirochetes through
its saliva into an unsuspecting host. So as the tick begins to
extract its meal of blood, antibodies from the vaccinated person
are consumed along with it and kill the spirochetes before they
reach the tick's saliva.
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine is given in three doses _ the first two are a month
apart and the third comes 11 months later _ at a total cost of
about $150 (not including doctor fees). If just the first two doses
are taken, the vaccine is only 50 percent effective in preventing
Lyme disease. All three doses were shown in studies involving
nearly 11,000 people to be 78 percent effective, and a more recent
study by the manufacturer indicated that the vaccine works equally
well if the third dose is given after six months.
</P>
<P>
   This means, however, that even when people are fully vaccinated,
about one person in five remains at risk of getting Lyme disease.
Also, the immunity wears off with time, and booster doses, perhaps
given annually, are likely to be needed.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, since the tests for safety and effectiveness were
conducted on people between the ages of 15 and 70, the vaccine has
not yet been approved for use in children and the elderly. Nor was
the vaccine tested in pregnant women, so it is not known if it is
safe for them to be immunized. The manufacturer is now testing the
vaccine in children 4 to 15 years of age, a group more likely than
most adults to be cavorting in areas where ticks are found.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem involves the ability to diagnose a case of Lyme
disease accurately in a vaccinated person. The usual test, called
Elisa, may appear positive even though the person is not infected,
and doctors may have to use the more costly Western blot test.
</P>
<P>
   There are also long-term safety concerns. The human immune
system has a nasty habit of making mistakes; it sometimes produces
antibodies to its own tissues, resulting in autoimmune diseases.
The OspA protein on the spirochete's coat resembles a protein in
the human body, and there is a real concern that in some vaccinated
people, the immune system will begin attacking itself and
spirochetes, resulting in an incurable illness requiring potent
medications to control.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA advisory committee also has raised concerns about
whether vaccinated people are at greater than average risk of
acquiring treatment-resistant arthritis, neurological damage or
heart disease, all of which can occur in people with severe
untreated Lyme disease.
</P>
<P>
   Long-term surveillance _ for a decade or more _ is needed to
determine whether such risks exist, and so far vaccinated
individuals have been followed for only a few years. The Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention recommends against vaccinating
people who have had treatment-resistant Lyme arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   Lyme disease has been reported in 48 states. But Lyme-carrying
ticks are most abundant in the Northeast, the Upper Midwest and
some parts of Northern California and the Pacific Northwest. For
people who work or frequently play in wooded or overgrown grassy
areas where Lyme disease and deer are common, the prevailing advice
is that the benefits of vaccination outweigh any known or potential
risks. Travelers to such areas may consider vaccination if they
expect to experience frequent or prolonged exposure to tick
habitat.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the greatest risk of being vaccinated would be
complacency about the chances of getting Lyme disease. Remember,
the vaccine does not always work. Even if you are fully immunized,
experts say that the usual anti-tick precautions are needed: cover
up and use a tick repellent. When out in or around tick habitats,
wear long sleeves and light-colored long pants with cuffs tucked
into your socks. Spray your pants, socks and shoes with a tick
repellent, like permethrin, and use Deet on exposed skin.
</P>
<P>
   Pets can be protected with a repellent that is applied between
the shoulders each month during tick season. It spreads across the
skin and kills ticks before they can transmit Lyme disease. Ask
your veterinarian what is best for your pet.
</P>
<P>
   After every outing in tick-infested areas, take off all your
clothes and check your skin for ticks. Also check your pets and
children. In fact, making a family tick check a part of your daily
routine is a good idea, because the prompt removal of ticks can
help prevent infection. Deer ticks are very small and have
elongated bodies (the more common wood ticks are larger and round).
The deer tick, about the size of a poppy seed when it first
attaches, enlarges as it feeds. Do not touch the tick when you
remove it. Use a fine-pointed tweezer or a simple plastic
spoon-like tool called Ticked Off, sold in some pharmacies and
stores catering to outdoor activities.
</P>
<P>
   Also pay attention to every red circular rash you may develop
whether or not you have removed a tick from that area. A
``bulls-eye'' rash that often clears in the center as it spreads
outward is the hallmark of a Lyme infection. So are flu-like
symptoms. Arthritis, neurological symptoms and heart abnormalities
occur weeks to months after infection, and are considered signs of
late disease. So act fast. Get to a doctor without delay if you
suspect infection.
</P>
<P>
   Lyme disease is diagnosed definitively through a blood test,
although waiting for the results can delay needed treatment. If
Lyme disease is treated early with effective antibiotics, the
debilitating, long-lasting consequences can almost always be
prevented. Early cases are best treated with one of three
antibiotics taken for 10 to 21 days: amoxicillin (500 milligrams
three times a day), doxycycline (100 milligrams twice a day) or
cefuroxime axetil (500 milligrams twice a day).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
