<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST AND LAST ANNUAL SEXY SWIMSUIT ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 11)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.) 
(th) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Usually respectable publications _ from Sports Illustrated to
Vogue _ regularly fling modesty to the winds and publish annual
best-selling  &UR; swimsuit &LR;  issues. Because most ogling readers are
more interested in an ambience of prurience _ that is, nearly nude
women's bodies _ than in sports or fashion, these issues sell
gazillions of copies.
</P>
<P>
   And so I ask: why not an annual  &UR; swimsuit &LR;  language column? And
when did they stop calling them  &UR; bathing suits &LR; ?
</P>
<P>
   ``Her petticoat, the most important part of her  &UR; bathing
costume &LR; , dropped off,'' wrote Frances Trollope in her 1830
``Domestic Manners of the Americans,'' in what was one of the most
intriguing lines of the English author's tart sociological study.
It was also the first use of  &UR; bathing costume &LR; . Four decades later,
 &UR; bathing suit &LR;  came along and for a time competed with  &UR; bathing
dress &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Then Annette Kellerman, an Australian-born swimmer and diving
star, announced before World War I, ``I can't swim wearing more
stuff than you hang on a clothesline,'' and appeared in a one-piece
outfit with short sleeves, knee-length pants and a round high neck,
which was basically the underwear for the skirted  &UR; bathing dress &LR; .
Although Kellerman was arrested in Boston for appearing in public
in the scandalous garb, in 1913 Carl Jantzen and his partners, John
and Roy Zehntbauer, marketed a skirtless one-piece  &UR; bathing suit &LR; 
for women.
</P>
<P>
   In the Roaring '20s, just as  &UR; bathing beauty &LR;  was catching on,
 &UR; bathing &LR;  _ dipping or immersing oneself in water _ began to give
way to  &UR; swimming &LR; , propelling oneself in water with the arms. In
1926, in ``The Sun Also Rises,'' Ernest Hemingway had a character
say, ``I found my  &UR; swimming suit &LR; , wrapped it with a comb in a
towel.'' That led to the clipped  &UR; swimsuit &LR;  and the more inclusive
 &UR; swimwear &LR; . In France in the '20s, the word  &UR; maillot &LR; , possibly
based on the name of the costumier of the Paris Opera, described a
tight-fitting  &UR; bathing costume &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   In 1946, after the explosion of an atomic bomb at the Bikini
Atoll in the Marshall Islands became synonymous with a great blast,
the French lingerie manufacturer Louis Reard introduced a skimpy
two-piece suit for swimming or sunbathing that he called the
 &UR; bikini &LR; . Eighteen long years of dreary skin coverage passed before
the Austrian designer Rudi Gernreich interpreted the  &UR; bi &LR;  in
 &UR; bikini &LR;  as ``two'' and introduced the  &UR; monokini &LR;  _ one bottom, no
top.
</P>
<P>
   Lascivious lexicographers have closely examined  &UR; -kini &LR;  as a
popular combining form. The  &UR; trikini &LR;  appeared briefly _ very
briefly _ in 1967, defined as ``a handkerchief and two small
saucers.'' It reappeared a few years ago as a  &UR; bikini &LR;  bottom with
a stringed halter of two triangular pieces of cloth covering the
breasts.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent evolution of the  &UR; -kini &LR;  family is the
 &UR; tankini &LR; , a cropped  &UR; tank top &LR;  supported by spaghetti-like
strings. ``The  &UR; tank &LR;  was the early term for `indoor pool,'''
recalls Steve Fritz, now president of Jantzen, ``and you wore a
one-piece suit when you competed in the tank.'' (Annette Kellerman,
``the Diving Venus'' in her one-piece bathing suit, splashed about
in a huge indoor tank in the Hippodrome in New York City.)
</P>
<P>
   An early  &UR; tank top &LR;  citation is an article in The New Yorker in
1968 about Suzanne Farrell, describing her as ``a tall, pretty
ballerina dressed in a purple  &UR; tank top &LR;  and baggy rubber warm-up
pants.'' It has come to mean a sleeveless garment, often knitted,
with deeply scooped armholes.
</P>
<P>
   Stripping to essentials, if the  &UR; trikini &LR;  is three pieces, the
 &UR; bikini &LR;  two and the  &UR; monokini &LR;  one, when will we see the
 &UR; zerokini &LR; ? We have, and it is a practice, not a garment, called
 &UR; skinny dipping &LR; , from dipping one's naked skin in the water, a
locution cited in the Oxford English Dictionary in 1966. (I
remember it being used in Camp Copake, N.Y., much earlier, but will
name no names.)
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   On a related subject, what's going on in underwear nomenclature?
</P>
<P>
   Remember  &UR; undies &LR; ? Or  &UR; unmentionables? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   They are now mentionable, sort of. These are euphemisms for
 &UR; foundation garments &LR; , or  &UR; corsets &LR; . Ignored politicians complain
that their story was ``buried in the back of the paper with the
 &UR; corset &LR;  ads,'' but has anybody recently seen an ad anywhere for a
 &UR; corset &LR; ?
</P>
<P>
   `` &UR; Shapewear &LR;  _  &UR; Bodyslimmers &LR;  _ is the most prominent thing in
the market today,'' says Tom Wyatt, a former president of Warnaco
Intimate Apparel. In 1984, the Olga company of Van Nuys, Calif.
(there really is a Van Nuys), came up with  &UR; shapesuit &LR; , which it
also called a  &UR; Secret Hug &LR; . (It was not to be confused with a
 &UR; panty girdle &LR; , which has legs.)  &UR; Shaping &LR;  in this context has a
history; it was first used in 1564 in an English archdeaconry:
``His  &UR; shappinge apparell &LR;  was a yowlowe sattanne dublet and a
payre of housse.``
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bodyslimmers &LR; , with the ``emancipating  &UR; Hipslip &LR; ,'' are
trademarks of Nancy Ganz, who is not only creative in the naming of
her products but would _ long ago _ be hailed as ``the Girdle
Queen.'' More recently, she would be considered a leader in the
field of  &UR; intimate apparel &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   But as we all know, things formerly intimate have been outed,
and intimacy has become outimacy. That is why we refer to Ganz, and
to legions dedicated to helping men and women tuck it in and
tighten it up, as  &UR; shapewear &LR;  executives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 1621EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1951 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-ONLINE-BANKING-2T     07-07 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-BANKING-2TAKES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD WIDE BANKS: ONLINE FINANCIAL CHOICES GROW
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Mass.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By CATHERINE GREENMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jack Jackson can't remember the last time he wrote a check and
hasn't spoken face to face with a bank teller in years. Jackson has
handled his personal banking online with Bank Boston since 1989,
and he expanded to online banking for his public relations business
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Although he experienced two instances of bank errors that cost
him several hours on the phone with customer service, that has not
deterred him from banking online. ``I think I've had to deal with
the best and worst that it has to offer,'' Jackson said. ``It's
easy to set up and it can be incredibly convenient, but anyone who
has really bad financial habits may find that their problems will
be exacerbated when they go online. It's definitely not for
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   One big difference with many online banking accounts is that as
soon as you direct the bank to send out a payment from your
account, that money's gone. You can't mail out a $50 check and
figure that you can get to the bank to deposit the money to cover
the check before it's presented by the recipient's bank for
payment. But one thing online customers gain is convenience _ the
bank's always open for business.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Jackson was unusual. Although some of the
largest banks in the country, including Wells Fargo, Citibank and
Chase Manhattan, have offered their customers online bill-payment
options for nearly a decade, only during the last couple of years
have customers really started to warm to the idea of clicking on
the Send button at an online banking site.
</P>
<P>
   According to IDC, a market research firm in Framingham, Mass.,
the number of people in the United States participating in at least
one online banking function (like viewing deposits, transferring
money between accounts and paying bills) rose to 12.4 million in
1999 from 1.4 million in 1996. IDC expects that number to rise to
18.7 million by the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts cite the widespread availability of
modem-equipped computers as one reason for the increase in online
banking activity. They add that people are also finally starting to
get comfortable with the notion that entering bank account
information online is no riskier than giving a credit card number
over the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Online trading has really made people aware of how to bank
online,'' said Mitch Caplan, president of Telebank, a phone- and
Internet-based bank. ``The security issues aren't really there any
more.'' But while online trading offers discount services, many
banks charge more for online accounts.
</P>
<P>
   It has become much more convenient to pay bills and transfer
money to other accounts via computer because many banks are moving
their entire online consumer banking areas onto the Internet and
off private networks, which required the customer to use
communications software and a modem to dial directly into a
company's computer system.
</P>
<P>
   To pay bills online with Chase in 1994, for example, a customer
had to call Chase's customer service and order software disks for
logging onto a private network. Since Chase moved its online
banking functions to the Internet last February, online customers
have been able to gain access to their accounts from any PC with an
Internet connection by going to the bank's Web site and punching in
an identifying name and password.
</P>
<P>
   So what should you expect if you wean yourself from your
checkbook? Setting up access to your bank account via the Internet
is relatively simple. After securing your bank accounts with a
customer ID and a password, you enter the account numbers and
addresses of each company or person you pay regularly. As long as
you can provide that information, you can send payments to large
companies (like your cable and credit card companies) as well as to
individuals, like your piano teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Some banks charge a monthly fee, usually $5 to $15, for
unlimited bill payments, but many are providing Internet banking
access and bill payments at no extra charge.
</P>
<P>
   The convenience of online banking has won some fans, like Lisa
and Alex Giassa of Teaneck, N.J., who have had an online account
since August 1998. ``It's definitely a convenience thing for us,''
Ms. Giassa said. ``If I know I have a bill due in a few days, I can
go upstairs, pay it in a couple of minutes and not deal with any
envelopes.''
</P>
<P>
   But lest you think that the click of a Send button will
instantaneously send off your son's college tuition payment on the
day it is due, think again. Only about half of electronic payments
are actually transmitted to recipients electronically. Many utility
companies and merchants are not set up to receive electronic
payments. Such companies are sent checks via regular mail _ an
annoying lesson for those who don't make allowances for the delayed
delivery and miss payment deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   And that delay brings up the question of the ``float'' and why
there's more of a float in electronic banking. In banking terms, a
float is the period between the time you issue a check and the time
it becomes available to the recipient. If you issue a check to an
out-of-state recipient, the money will not be credited to the
account of that company or person for up to five business days
after the check gets to the recipient's bank. A recipient in the
same state gets access to the money in up to three business days
after it is deposited, while someone with an account at the same
bank will get the money within one business day.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a regular checking account and issue a check, the
money won't be deducted until it is presented to your bank by the
recipient's bank for payment. But for many electronic accounts, the
bank automatically debits your online account soon after you hit
the button to instruct the bank to issue a check out of your
account.
</P>
<P>
   ``The float is a big psychological issue for a lot of people,''
said Jim Bruene, editor of Online Banking Report, an industry
newsletter. ``The tighter someone's funds are, the more he or she
relies on it. None of this is very meaningful when you're making 2
percent interest on cash balances.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that some organization _ sometimes a bank, sometimes a
check-processing company _ is able to hang onto your money for the
length of the float means that it can make money off your money, in
very short-term investments.
</P>
<P>
   Even though a payment is taken out of an online account right
away, that doesn't necessarily mean that the recipient of the money
is paid quickly. For example, Philip Goodman, a film and video
producer in Manhattan, paid a friend $25 out of his Chase Online
checking account. His checking account was debited quickly, but the
money did not show up in the recipient's account for three days,
Goodman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say it's electronic, but it's not,'' he complained.
``They debit your account and then send a check. I can send a
check!''
</P>
<P>
   Most online banks use third-party check consolidators like
Checkfree to process the checks from online accounts, send them
along and disburse the money. In those cases, the bank pays
Checkfree the amount of the check, and Checkfree pays the company
or person receiving the check.
</P>
<P>
   If the check recipient is set up to receive payments
electronically, through a process known as electronic transfer, the
payments move through an automated clearing-house system within 24
hours, said Matthew Lewis, a senior vice president at Checkfree.
</P>
<P>
   But if the recipient is not set up to receive payments
electronically, Checkfree mails a check to the recipient's bank,
where it is processed in a transaction that can take up to five
business days if the payment crosses state lines.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve is not sure about online banking's effect on
the float. ``We've tried to do what we can to manage float, but
whatever happens with the electronic technology is still an unknown
at this point,'' said Doug Tillet, a spokesman for the New York
Federal Reserve Bank.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Knowing that money is paid out of an account right away can help
online customers if they want to make last-minute electronic
payments, he added. If the recipient of a payment is set up to
receive electronic transfers, most online banking customers can
issue a payment at, say, 4:59 p.m. on the day the payment is due
and won't have to allow for mail delivery times.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bank Rate Monitor, an online service that tracks
interest rates for credit cards and personal loans offered by major
banks, at least 215 of the 350 largest Federal Deposit Insurance
Corp.-insured banks in the country offer the ability to pay bills
electronically. But bill consolidators like Checkfree are also
providing electronic payment services to nontraditional banks on
the Internet, which means your choice of where on the Internet to
pay your bills is becoming a lot broader. Internet-only banks can
be a good choice for people who keep a lot of money in their
checking accounts because they generally pay higher interest, but
they also tend to charge higher fees for automated teller machines.
</P>
<P>
   Personal and business financial software like Quicken and
Microsoft Money offer an electronic bill-paying option via
Checkfree. Customers can also use such software, which gives a user
an overall financial picture, with many types of online accounts.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to bill payments, Checkfree and other consolidators,
like Transpoint and Cybercash, are also working with banks and
other financial sites to bring your bills and account information
to you online.
</P>
<P>
   With its E-card, First U.S.A., a leading credit card issuer,
offers customers online access to detailed information about their
credit card purchases as well as the ability to pay their bills
online. Many banks are finding ways to let customers see their
bills online as a way of offering better service than the
nontraditional banking competitors who are zeroing in on their
business.
</P>
<P>
   A type of bill-presentment service was recently announced by
Chase Manhattan Bank, First Union and Wells Fargo; they are forming
a new company that will enable people and businesses to both
receive and pay bills electronically. The company, called the
Exchange, will serve as an electronic hub that will allow companies
issuing bills to reach consumers through their financial
institutions. Consumers will be able to log on to their online
banking site and view lists of their outstanding bills, said Sharon
Osberg, executive vice president for financial services at Wells
Fargo.
</P>
<P>
   The three banks will have a customer base of 60 million and
almost 60,000 corporations, said Wendy Grover, a spokeswoman for
Wells Fargo. Ms. Osberg added that by the time the Exchange is
fully up and running next year, all electronic payments will be
settled on the day they are issued, effectively eliminating any
float.
</P>
<P>
   But whether an electronic overdue notice will be easier to
ignore than a piece of paper that says ``account past due'' in red
letters on it remains to be seen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
