<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASSAGE-PARLORS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE MAY LOSE CONTROL OF LICENSING MASSAGE PARLORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Fingerprinting, skills testing and restrictions
on prostitution arrests appear to be going by the wayside at San
Francisco's massage parlors.
</P>
<P>
   The Health Commission on Tuesday put its stamp of approval on
the idea of transferring the responsibility for licensing massage
parlors, out-call massage services and individual massage
therapists from the Police Department to the public Health
Department. The measure is before the Board of Supervisors, which
is expected to hold hearings on the matter later this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, it would eliminate the requirement that
people applying for a permit to practice massage disclose all
criminal convictions. As it stands, the Police Department turns
down applicants who had a prostitution-related conviction in the
past five years.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to move the focus of massage regulation from the
criminal realm to that of health, said Jeff Klausner, director of
sexually transmitted disease services for the Health Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key for us is that we'll be able to focus on the health
and environmental safety of the massage parlors and workers and
allow them to enjoy a safer working environment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing in the proposed change would hinder the police from
enforcing narcotics, prostitution and other laws at massage
parlors, Klausner said.
</P>
<P>
   The Health Department expects to come up with more detailed
rules governing massage establishments and practitioners after the
legislation passes. Among the challenges will be finding a way to
address the needs of massage therapists _ a growing field aimed at
health and stress-reduction, and the old-style sex-for-hire
masseuses.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting regulations could end up reinstating some of the
current requirements, such as fingerprinting or a written test,
Klausner said. They could also end up being tougher than what is
currently on the books.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation being considered would continue to require
people applying for permits provide proof of age and a diploma from
a massage program or school of massage. However, there have been
complaints of diploma mills that sell unqualified people
certificates in order for them to meet the requirements.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands, there are 81 massage establishments and 80 massage
call services licensed in San Francisco. About 700 individuals have
city permits to practice.
</P>
<P>
   V. Roy Lefcourt, a lawyer representing 13 massage parlors, said
the legislation is long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been troubling to me that there is no expertise in
the Police Department for running or being in charge of the massage
industry,'' he said. ``It's a very chilling situation, where you
feel like you must be doing something wrong if you have to check in
with the Police Department.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the department is acknowledging that sex-for-hire is
going on at many establishments, which is why the Health
Department's sexually transmitted diseases branch will be heavily
involved if the legislation passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is general community awareness that this is a common
activity,'' Klausner said. ``We are interested in applying the
concept of harm reduction _ trying to educate and inform
individuals to practice behavior that may result in less
transmission of STDs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
