<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1970 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-HUMAN-ANATOMY-2TA     07-07 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-HUMAN-ANATOMY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS OPEN A WINDOW ON THE BODY
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Texas, Iowa) (Eds: Dr. Abigail Zuger, a practicing internist, often writes about
medical issues for The New York Times.)  
(nk)  
By ABIGAIL ZUGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Human anatomy is a subject that can veer in an instant from
thrilling and chilling to dry as dust.
</P>
<P>
   During the Renaissance, public dissections provided all the
recreational titillation that we get from gory movies and roller
coasters today. In Italy, prominent people, often masked and
dressed in costume, crowded into dissection amphitheaters during
carnival time. Servants passed out flowers, oranges and sticks of
incense to dispel the noxious odors of the proceedings. Two smoking
torches illuminated the dissection table, where the professor of
anatomy, robed in red, pointed out structures of interest with a
long, tapered rod.
</P>
<P>
   Although the demonstrations were intended to provoke a mood of
solemn moral reflection, audiences tended to become a little giddy,
particularly when female anatomy was displayed. In Holland, the
medical historian Frank Gonzalez-Crussi wrote in ``Suspended
Animation'' (Harcourt Brace, 1995), laws actually had to be passed
``to check the inappropriate outbursts of persons who laughed,
clapped, asked indecent questions, grabbed the specimens prepared
by the dissector, or otherwise attempted to disrupt the solemnity
of the occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   For anatomy without a trace of pageantry or prurience, open a
copy of ``Gray's Anatomy,'' which has been periodically reissued in
all its incomparable turgor for the last century and a half.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire skeleton in the adult consists of 200 distinct
bones,'' begins Dr. Gray, and he proceeds to list them all,
followed by all the joints, and all the ligaments, muscles, nerves,
arteries and veins, totaling tens of thousands of structures, most
with long Latin names, their three-dimensional intricacy reduced to
enormous incomprehensible paragraphs with very few illustrations.
Medical students are reduced to tears by Dr. Gray and anatomists
like him who bled all the color and art from their subject and
demand rote memorization instead.
</P>
<P>
   Computers have provided the opportunity to combine the precision
of the classical texts with some of the three-dimensional thrills
and chills that kept those Renaissance audiences glued to their
benches.
</P>
<P>
   VISIBLE HUMAN CD MALE 2.0
</P>
<P>
   VISIBLE HUMAN CD FEMALE 1.1
</P>
<P>
   (Research Systems; $495 for both; Windows 3.1, 95 and 98, and
Mac.)
</P>
<P>
   Computers have had their most dramatic impact on the study of
anatomy in the National Library of Medicine's Visible Human
Project, based at the University of Colorado. The project plans to
create a complete, Internet-based electronic database of all the
organs in the human body as they appear in radiologic images and in
the flesh.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993 two bodies were found for the project _ a 39-year-old
Texas man and a 59-year-old Maryland woman. Immediately after
death, both cadavers were scanned from head to toe with CAT
(computed axial tomography) and MRI (magnetic resonance imaging)
techniques. They were then frozen, encased in gelatin, infused with
latex and passed through the scientific equivalent of a rotary saw
calibrated to slice off paper-thin sections, which were
photographed digitally.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the Visible Human Project has spared us any
pictures of that process. Instead, two CD-ROM's representing the
project's major output to date contain vertical, horizontal and
transverse cross-sections of both bodies, as they would appear to
the naked eye and in CAT  &UR;  &LR; and MRI scans.
</P>
<P>
   No mere book could ever render anatomical structures with the
extraordinary detail found in the images on these disks. Their
millimeter-by-millimeter overview of human anatomy could easily
replace entire shelves of standard anatomy and radiology atlases in
medical school libraries. An animation feature flips a set of
adjacent images like a child's flip book to make structural
relationships even clearer.
</P>
<P>
   If you have seen the MRI of that torn piece of cartilage in your
knee and are curious about what it used to look like, this disk
should be the place to find out. However, labeling is still a work
in progress. With about 70,000 labels, many of the man's structures
are identified, but there are many more to go, including the knee.
The woman is unlabeled and likely to remain so for the foreseeable
future, a company spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   For a surgeon or radiologist, access to this kind of precise
imaging of human bodies may be worth an outlay of $495 for both
disks. For others, idle curiosity about what it all looks like may
be satisfied at any of several Web sites where parts of the data
are displayed, including www.uchsc.edu/sm/chs/browse/browse.htm;
www.nlm.nih.gov/research/visible/visible human.html; or
www.visualman.com.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   BODY VOYAGE
</P>
<P>
   (Southpeak Interactive; $24.95; Windows 3.1, 95, 98 and NT, and
Mac 7.0 or later.)
</P>
<P>
   This eerie tour of the human body is about as close as one is
likely to get these days to the atmosphere of a Renaissance
dissection. Like the Visible Human disks, it uses data from the
National Library of Medicine's Visible Man project, but it plays to
the medical laity rather than the professional audience, with an
emphasis on the more sensational aspects of the project.
</P>
<P>
   No longer is the visible man's anonymity protected in standard
scientific fashion. The disk enthusiastically tells us all about
him: He was a Texan named Joseph Paul Jernigan, who murdered a
75-year old man during a robbery and was sentenced to death. Before
his execution, Jernigan willed his body to science. Many years of
body-building on Death Row had left his muscles defined to
near-perfection, an anatomist's dream.
</P>
<P>
   A computer artist selectively reconstructed the digital images
of Jernigan's body for this disk into colorized cross-sections and
airy three-dimensional renderings. The viewer can twirl the entire
skeleton on its axis, peel off layers of skin and muscle to reveal
the organs underneath and pan along the various planes of the body
as if the viewer were in a tiny helicopter traveling over, under
and through the body's terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Just knowing the identity of the face and body dancing and
weaving on the screen here can give the viewer a creepy feeling;
the enclosed biography of Jernigan, which supplies details like his
last meal, increases the effect. The background colors of black and
deep red both intensify the atmosphere and make it a bit difficult
to discern the details in many images unless the disk is viewed in
a dark room. If you do that, all you need are a few smoking torches
to be right back in the 16th century.
</P>
<P>
   Body Voyage is not the place to learn rigorous anatomy.
Structures are labeled but not very systematically, and some labels
are omitted; the hand and wrist, for example, are not part of this
voyage.
</P>
<P>
   And if you are curious about the whereabouts of the appendix,
you will not find one here: Jernigan had his removed.
</P>
<P>
   A few dozen short essays on anatomical subjects ranging from
headaches to hip replacements are like the articles in an in-flight
magazine _ amusing but lightweight compared with the all-too-real
vistas unfolding in the background.
</P>
<P>
   BODYWORKS
</P>
<P>
   (Learning Company; $39.95; Windows 95 and 98.)
</P>
<P>
   Here is an anatomy class as modern and sterile as an elementary
school hygiene lecture, complete with a large, unappetizing
disclaimer at the outset deflecting all questions aboutactual
health conditions back to the viewer's own doctor.
</P>
<P>
   On Bodyworks, a standard Windows-based format calls up a
complete set of colorful, computer-generated three-dimensional
models of human organs that can be rotated and magnified, along
with short descriptions of each organ's structure and function and
a disembodied voice that pronounces each name.
</P>
<P>
   The disk also includes discussion of how the organs interact in
basic processes like eating, breathing and reproduction, and a few
words about health topics like nutrition, aging, hospice care and
even preferred-provider organizations. An education section
introduces Dr. Bodywork, a pleasant-faced woman who, for unclear
reasons, is dressed like a cross between a bellhop and a military
police officer. With animated visual aids, she delivers short
lectures on such topics as sight, smell and touch.
</P>
<P>
   The targeted age range for this disk is hard to pinpoint. An
optional censorship function implies that younger children might be
confused by sexually explicit content, but most of the mannequins
have no genitalia, and one female figure is actually sporting a
large fig leaf. The reproductive organs are discussed in
straightforward fashion; sexual intercourse is not mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   But children are certainly going to be put off by the rampant
medical jargon, as in ``the abducens nerve is the sixth cranial
nerve and extends from the dorsal part of the pons to the lateral
rectus muscle of the eye.'' Although all possibly unfamiliar words
are in hypertext with definitions quickly available, even adult
viewers without a medical vocabulary might balk at having to click
on almost every word in some sentences. Dr. Bodywork's lectures are
of a caliber that might be found in a medical school classroom.
</P>
<P>
   There are occasional interactive non sequiturs: clicking on
``scrapes and cuts,'' for instance, elicits a picture not of scabs
and bandages but of surgical suture techniques that might be used
to close a major abdominal operation. A sizable section on health
and beauty products (``shampoo is a product used to wash hair'') is
pure stuffing.
</P>
<P>
   BRAIN SITE
</P>
<P>
   www.vh.org/Providers/Textbooks/BrainAnatomy/BrainAnatomy.html
</P>
<P>
   The anatomy of the brain is the most difficult of any part of
the body to visualize, with complicated structures crumpled
together into a space the size of a cantaloupe. Neuroanatomists at
the University of Iowa have put together a set of detailed
photographs of sections of the human brain, with schematic drawings
that allow each structure to be identified. The result is the
equivalent of a very good textbook of brain anatomy.
</P>
<P>
   AMA SITE
</P>
<P>
   www.ama-assn.org/insight/genhlth/atlas/atlas.htm
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes detailed anatomical photographs are only distracting
when what you really need is a quick idea of what it means when
you're told that a relative's stroke may have damaged Wernicke's
area of the brain. This site, sponsored by the American Medical
Association, provides brief explanations of how organs work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
