<HEADLINE>
COMPLAINT SERVICES FOR HIRE ON THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: byline with 8 as middle initial is cq.) (DW) 
 By JENNIFER 8 LEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Given the service economy's hire-someone-else mentality, which
leads some people to pay others to walk the dog and tutor the
children in baseball, it is no wonder that you can now hire
Internet businesses to complain on your behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Sites like Complain.com and Fight Back promise to write letters,
make phone calls and, if necessary, whine in exchange for a modest
_ and sometimes not so modest _ fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have tried to handle problems themselves, but
they're frustrated and angry,'' said Bill Tran, president of Caveat
Emptor (www.cemptor.com), which went on line in March. ``They want
to forget about it,'' Tran said. ``That's when I jump in.''
</P>
<P>
   One angry America Online customer, Elizabeth Huntington of
Bradenton, Fla., failed to get an erroneous AOL charge canceled
after three discussions with customer representatives over four
weeks. ``I don't think that business, especially AOL, takes me
seriously,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She turned up Caveat Emptor (www.cemptor.com) by searching for
``complaint'' on the Web. A week after Caveat Emptor sent a letter,
AOL returned $48 to Ms. Huntington, along with a refund for a $50
bank overdraft fee. ``When they got the letter from me through
Caveat, then they took me seriously,'' Miss Huntington said. She
wouldn't have got her money back without Caveat Emptor, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Companies and clients say their specialized services are more
effective than the efforts of a consumer working alone. ``The
reason the average person can't do this is that the average person
does not have the kind of resources that we have,'' said David
Horowitz, a consumer advocate who writes a ``Fight Back''
syndicated newspaper column and has a Web site at
www.fightback.com.
</P>
<P>
   With Americans buying and spending more than ever, the
inevitable result is more services, products and goods to complain
about. In addition, customer satisfaction with technology products
may be declining in the face of rising product quality, creating a
rich customer base for the professional complainers.
</P>
<P>
   Some Web enterprises will complain for clients on a budget. The
Consumer Complaint Resolution Company
(www.complaintresolution &QC; .com) bills $29.95, or a 20 percent
commission on the amount recovered. Fight Back will send out a
letter personally signed by Horowitz for $25, a flat fee the
company said covered administrative costs. Complain.com
(www.complain.com) pleads a case for only $19.95. Caveat Emptor
writes free complaint letters (but may start charging someday).
</P>
<P>
   A number of these sites, like Fight Back and Caveat Emptor, also
have complaint bulletin boards for posting complaints publicly. The
goal is to give companies and agencies an incentive to shape up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new way of handling it, where you can use the power
of the Internet and the power of mass public exposure to resolve
people's problems,'' Horowitz said. ``And so far, it works.''
</P>
<P>
   Specialized expertise can carry a hefty price tag. Gary and
Sandy Rattigan of Somerville, Mass., started Complain to Us in 1997
(www.complaintous.com). They charge $50 per hour (and a 30 percent
commission when larger sums are recovered). They say they have an
overall success rate of about 80 percent. Ellen Phillips of
Alexandria, Va., gave up teaching English in middle school last
year to turn all her attention to her business, Ellen's Poison Pen
(www.ellenspoisonpen.com). She recently raised her rates to $30 per
100 words and $65 per hour. Clients spend an average of $400 for
her services.
</P>
<P>
   An Ellen's Poison Pen customer, Jamie Urick of Frankfort, Ill.,
explained, ``If you have leg pain and you go to a physical
therapist, you go to an expert _ it's the same thing.'' Mrs. Urick
and her neighbors were frustrated that repeated pleas to state and
county officials had resulted in no action against a noisy dirt
bike track. Mrs. Phillips composed a biting letter whose recipients
ranged from the county sheriff to the governor of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff replied immediately. Even though the case cost the
complainers $240 and may still end up in court, the residents said
the sharp, professional tone of the letter was worth it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
