u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     07-07 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP EXPERTS PROVIDE VARIED INSIGHT INTO HOW MONEY GAME IS PLAYED
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating for the Rocky Mountain News and all needing) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're looking for investment ideas, consider picking the
brains of the best in the business.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you would like to chat with John Bogle, the founder of the
Vanguard Group, the second-largest mutual fund in the world; or
Mary Zweig, chairman of a $9 billion mutual fund bearing his name;
or maybe Mario Gabelli, chairman of a $10 billion mutual fund
bearing his name. Foster Friess, manager and owner of the
Brandywine Fund, the best-performing no-loan mutual fund, may also
have a few ideas for you.
</P>
<P>
   For a different point of view, you may want to talk to some of
the information specialists in investing, say, Louis Navallier, who
edits the MPT Review, a highly rated investment newsletter, or
William O'Neil, founder of Investor's Business Daily. Don Phillips,
who heads Morningstar, the leading firm for rating and tracking
mutual funds, also has his own take on the whole business.
</P>
<P>
   Round that out with a talk with Harry Markowitz, Nobel Prize
winner for developing the Modern Portfolio Theory, and you would
consider yourself well-educated in the investment business.
</P>
<P>
   Or you would have a book.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Kenneth A. Stern thought when he interviewed all of
those people for his new book ``Secrets of the Investment
All-Stars'' (Amacom, 301 pages, $25).
</P>
<P>
   The book brings you the investment insight of nine of the top
investors/market information specialists in the country. Each
brings a unique perspective to the complex world of investing.
</P>
<P>
   A simple question-and-answer format brings the reader into the
room where Stern is interviewing the investment stars, making the
book easy to breeze through.
</P>
<P>
   And the information is specific enough to be useful, yet doesn't
get bogged down in mind-numbing number-crunching and graphs. ``Each
all-star has very distinct and different views from that of their
peers,'' Stern writes. ``This is revealing in many ways. Most
importantly, it confirms to an investor that there is more than one
way to skin a cat, and more than one way to make money at
investing. It also provides a whole array of different styles and
disciplines for you to greedily absorb.''
</P>
<P>
   Take Zweig, for example. He has been named by Forbes, among
others, as a legend in market forecasting. Stern says he is
meticulous in his constant analysis of the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``To forecast the market, Zweig has probably probed, measured,
monitored ... and created more forecasting models than anyone you
will ever meet,'' Stern writes. ``Zweig would say that forecasting
the market is not so much about understanding money as it is about
creating a model, about finding a trend and sticking to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Zweig has 70 different factors in his market model, Stern
writes. The most important ones are monetary indicators, (mostly
interest rates); sentiment indicators (flows into mutual funds);
and momentum indicators (price and volume of stocks).
</P>
<P>
   Gabelli looks at the stock market in a totally different light,
Stern writes.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than changing his model to keep up with Wall Street's
trends, Gabelli makes his decisions based on something called value
investing, a strategy of picking bargain stocks that have not yet
reached their future value.
</P>
<P>
   But Gabelli adds a kicker that he calls a catalyst. An
undervalued company will likely stay there, he believes, but if an
active ingredient, an event of some type is triggered, the stock
will rise to its true value. The catalyst can be anything from the
death of the founder to regulatory changes, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Such interesting thoughts are throughout this well-presented
book. Stern ends it with a 20-point checklist, summing up how to
use ``the best of the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Investing can be a lot of hard work. Stern shows us how it can
be intriguing and fun as well.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jacket blurbs
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``High-Tech Careers for Low-Tech People''
</P>
<P>
   By William A. Schaffer
</P>
<P>
   Ten Speed Press, $14.95
</P>
<P>
   Communication is the most important skill required by the
high-tech industry, author William Schaffer found when talking to
people in the industry about his premise that people with degrees
in the arts can find a home in the high-tech world. Schaffer is an
example of this idea. He holds a degree in government and French
literature from Columbia, but works as an international business
development manager for Sun Microsystems. Schaffer offers a career
option many people may not realize they have and shows them how to
pursue it in this book.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``52 Weeks of Sales Success''
</P>
<P>
   By Ralph R. Roberts
</P>
<P>
   Harper Business, $21
</P>
<P>
   Real estate agent and author Ralph Roberts _ he says he
generates 600 sales a year, almost a hundred times that of the
average agent _ creates a sales teaching program based on a
yearlong weekly seminar he created for his Detroit company. The
author of ``Walk Like a Giant, Sell Like a Madman,'' Roberts
discusses the many tricks of the trade of selling in his latest
book. Ideas on customer retention, time management and getting out
of a slump are included.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Business the Rupert Murdoch Way: Ten Secrets of the World's
Greatest Deal-Maker''
</P>
<P>
   By Stuart Crainer
</P>
<P>
   Amacom, $14.95
</P>
<P>
   This book is one of a series of four highlighting the business
practices of Murdoch, Bill Gates, Richard Branson and Jack Welch.
All are well-written by English business author Stuart Crainer, who
has also written such bestsellers as ``The Ultimate Business
Library.'' Crainer has done his homework on these business moguls
and offers not only a detailed background on them, but also an
insight into their business practices.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
