billion the country has earned from oil since the mid-1970s been
spent here, but $50 billion of it has just disappeared overseas,
according to a U.S. official in Nigeria.
 &HT;    In Port Harcourt, Chevron's offices are in a walled-off compound
of white one-story buildings. The chiefs drop by, one after the
other, every day Hutto is here. Overall, he says, he now spends at
least 60 percent of his time on community relations. Damian Obiagu,
a chief in a town called Izombe, has been pressing Hutto to make a
Chevron contractor hire local youths as casuals. In all likelihood,
ghost workers will be hired.
 &HT;    ``They don't show up for work,'' Hutto explains. ``You don't
want them to. You don't want a person on a jack-up barge or
drilling rig who doesn't know anything about safety.''
 &HT;    But the ghost workers serve an important purpose. They allow the
chief to claim he has won jobs for his people and the oil company
to say it has hired from the community. The fiction is necessary
because it is virtually impossible to find qualified oil workers
among the delta residents.
 &HT;    At one of the wells, Chevron awarded Obiagu a contract to
provide ``security.'' But one day, displeased, the chief's men
invaded the well. ``No, no, Damian, you don't understand,'' Hutto
recalls telling the chief. ``You're our security contractor, to
protect us. You're not looking to threaten us. 'Oh! oh!' he said.
He's a nice old man.''
 &HT;    Since taking over Gulf Oil in 1984, Chevron has pumped many
billions of dollars' worth of oil in Nigeria, 418,000 barrels a day
in 1998. In 1998, Chevron Corp.'s total worldwide revenues amounted
to $30.6 billion; Nigeria's gross national product was estimated by
the World Bank to be $30.7 billion in 1997. Nigeria's GNP, while a
pittance alongside the West's economies, is one of Africa's
biggest.
 &HT;    Kingdom Dateme, the king of a town called Idama, has been
pushing for a bigger personal contract, Hutto tells Okoaye. ``He
wants a contract so that he can get a big house now,'' Hutto says.
 &HT;    ``In his village?'' Okoaye asks.
 &HT;    ``No, here.'
 &HT;    ``Here in PH?'' Okoaye laughs, adding, ``That guy, he's
something else, eh?''
 &HT;    ``He's looking for a half-million, million Naira contract,''
Hutto says, the equivalent of $5,000 to $10,000. ``With those he
can buy his own big house here.''
 &HT;    Okoaye laughs uproariously, before adding with some finality,
``He's a pig.'' Then softening up a bit, Okoaye asks his boss:
``But he doesn't really make trouble for you. He doesn't really
bother you, does he? He's just greedy.''
 &HT;    ``Well,'' Hutto says, ``they're all greedy.''
 &HT;    After work, Hutto drives home in his white Toyota Landcruiser
through Port Harcourt's ``go slows,'' or traffic jams. Boys hawking
everything from toilet paper to power tools dart to his side with
cries of ``Master!'' A Nigerian policeman, gripping a tear-gas
rifle in his hands, rides shotgun. More policemen guard Hutto's
villa, a two-story white house.
 &HT;    Never married, Hutto lives alone, not counting the houseboy in
the backyard bungalow. Inside a large freezer, he keeps the 50 New
York sirloin and T-bone steaks that he brought back from his last
visit to the United States and has been cooking, at the rate of one
a week, on a grill that he keeps in his living room.
 &HT;    A year ago Hutto accepted the assignment in Port Harcourt, a
position the company considers difficult to fill because there is
no rotation schedule, no other Americans and constant interaction
with Chevron's delta neighbors. In Lagos, the Americans live inside
headquarters, a sprawling campus surrounded by high walls, a
surreal replica of America with wide streets and suburban houses
straight out of Westchester County. Here, Hutto is alone.
