<HEADER>
A2076 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     07-07 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JENNIFER GRANT GETS A SHOW TO MATCH HER IMPECCABLE ACTING PEDIGREE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite her ``tennis-anyone?'' cheeriness and fistful of
generous press notices, Jennifer Grant has spent most of her acting
career bobbing along at the edges of mainstream attention. Her
resume is decorated with bright, too-brief moments in television
series, specials and feature films, but she has done nothing that
would constitute what you'd call a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you count her birth.
</P>
<P>
   Dad Cary Grant was 62 when Jennifer was born in 1966; mother
Dyan Cannon was 27. Opportunistic Hollywood salivated, figuring
Jennifer's bloodline was a can't-miss, bankable commodity.
Producers offered her film roles, talent unseen. She was a kid, no
more than 8, when the scripts started rolling in, followed by
agents and managers and other would-be Tinseltown parasites.
</P>
<P>
   Her parents slammed the door on everyone and everything. The way
Jennifer tells it, now that she's 33 and days from her co-starring
debut in the appropriately titled ``Movie Stars,'' a summer sitcom
series debuting Sunday on WB, her dad hated the idea of his only
daughter acting. Mom was just as leery, warning her of the constant
rejections and the industry's superficiality.
</P>
<P>
   Cary Grant was particularly critical of Hollywood's treatment of
women, saying they were required to work harder for lesser roles,
and usually with their clothes completely off or at least dangling.
</P>
<P>
   Her parents' discouragement initially worked, as Jennifer
learned early on that her sanity hinged on sidestepping the
pressure to go into the family business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just too terrified to act,'' says Jennifer, who didn't
want the pressure of gene-pool expectations or dealing with a
resentful industry questioning how she landed her roles. ``I always
wanted to. But when you're expected to do something, yet people are
envious when you do, it's a bit nerve-racking. I went to an
all-girls Catholic boarding school and was Dolly in ``Hello,
Dolly!'' Not because I wanted to be, but because the nuns literally
plucked me out of class one day and took me to audition.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I had plenty of friends who wanted to be Dolly. But they
took me and made me sing ``Happy Birthday,'' and then gave me the
part, for their own reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer tried to be a normal kid with a normal lifestyle, even
when life consisted of shuttling between her mother's stately beach
house in Malibu and her father's often star-filled mansion in Los
Angeles. (Grant and Cannon divorced a year after Jennifer's birth.)
</P>
<P>
   Parents tried to shield daughter as best they could. Back in
1993, Cannon told Time that her job was to give Jennifer
``groundwork,'' which meant letting her work in health-food stores,
buy clothes in thrift shops and keep the press away. Sure enough,
by the time Jennifer headed to Stanford University, where she
finished a double major in political science and history, she had
experienced little media fanfare.
</P>
<P>
   Lost within the good intentions was, she says now, an identity.
A purpose. A focus. After Stanford, she entered something of a
career twilight zone.
</P>
<P>
   An accomplished equestrian, she did promotional work for the
1987 Breeders' Cup; was an apprentice chef at Spago restaurant
(losing interest after a rack of lamb fell on her head); and worked
in a law office and advocacy firm, where few of her colleagues took
her seriously, having heard of a reported $30 million trust fund
waiting for her after she turned 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had so much frustration with other careers,'' she says. ``I
just couldn't seem to make anything work. And I tried hard. Besides
the fact that (my parents) had natural ideas of what they wanted me
to be, a lawyer being the biggest one. So I tried to play out their
stuff and then tried lots of other things. Finally, I just _ at the
insistence of a girlfriend _ took an acting class for fun.''
</P>
<P>
   That was in 1990. She said she felt her whole body kind of
settle. ``I thought, boy, this is what I want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   She refused door-opening help from her mother. Roles didn't come
readily. She landed a recurring part on ``Beverly Hills, 90210'' in
1993, playing the sexy game-show contestant, and a small part in
the ``Terms of Endearment'' sequel, ``The Evening Star,'' three
years later.
</P>
<P>
   Her relationship with the press has been an odd one. She gets a
lot of attention for someone who hasn't done much. But because
she's ``someone's'' daughter, the press she receives tends toward
the third-degree type.
</P>
<P>
   ``Movie Stars,'' about an actor couple trying to raise a family,
could change it all. It's certainly an ironic twist for Jennifer.
The actors _ her husband is played by Harry Hamlin _ are definitely
in the star loop, much like Grant and Cannon were. The series aims
to be satirical and sophisticated in presenting a lifestyle that
can be quite bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   Executive Producer Jonathan Axelrod says Jennifer's hiring was
hardly stunt casting. ``She blew us away in the audition, plain and
simple,'' he says. ``We wanted someone who could slide between
being a mother (and being) a sexy actress, and a believable
actress. The last thing you want to do is fill the role of an
award-winning actress with someone who can't act.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer, who looks awfully comfortable acting in the pilot,
says it was the one time she didn't mind her pedigree aiding her.
``I think when I came in to the audition, I might have had a little
bit of an upper hand, in that none of the language was bizarre to
me,'' she says. ``Is this my life? I wouldn't say that. But this
series is more about family and the day-to-day stuff. It just
happens to be natural for me. That's where I have an edge I can
accept.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
