<P>
   COX-STOCKSWAP _ Cox Communications Inc. said today it has agreed
to swap $2.85 billion in AT&AMP;T Corp. stock it holds for AT&AMP;T cable
television systems that serve 495,000 subscribers. Cox, the fifth
largest U.S. cable TV company, said it will exchange 50.3 million
AT&AMP;T shares for cable TV systems based in Tulsa, Oklahoma and Baton
Rouge, Louisiana. Cox will also gain control of Peak Cablevision,
which serves cable customers in Oklahoma, Arkansas, Utah and
Nevada, and acquire 20 percent stake that AT&AMP;T holds in a
partnership with TCA Cable. (Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
20 WITH GRAPHIC (map of Cox service area, charts showing Cox and
ATT acquistions this year)
</P>
<P>
   w/COX-SIDE _ A look at the market forces that are driving
consolidation and changes in the cable TV industry, including the
lurch into phone service. (Kannell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   COX-STOCKS _ A look at how cable stocks respond to Cox-ATT deal
announced today. Tuesday, the stocks were sliding, while the stocks
of its competitors, the phone companies, were up. (Clothier,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   COKE-SCHWEPPES _ Following developments in Coca-Cola's deal to
acquire Cadbury-Schweppes' operations outside the U.S. Coke now
wants to acquire operations in South Africa, and regulators there
have indicated that they might be open to such an agreement, which
has not been the case in some other countries. (Unger, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ERXLEBEN _ Russell Erxleben, whose Austin foreign currency
company collapsed asfter taking more than $50 million from 800
investors, faces criminal indictments for frasud and money
laundering as early as next week, according to state and federal
sources. The indictments from a federal grand jury are the product
of a task force of federal and state investigators. (Golz, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   BIZMAGS _ A rundown of the week's financial press. (Walker,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
