<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2118 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APHRODITE-BOOK-REVIEW     07-07 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APHRODITE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WAITING FOR APHRODITE:' A LITTLE-NOTICED WORLD OF WONDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) (DW) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unlike Lefty or Godot, what Sue Hubbell is referring to in the
title of her engaging new collection of essays on natural history,
``Waiting for Aphrodite: Journeys Into the Time Before Bones,'' is
neither human in form nor potentially divine.
</P>
<P>
   Her Aphrodite is instead the lowly sea mouse, named Aphrodite
aculeata (spiny Aphrodite) by the great taxonomist Linnaeus. He did
not do so, as Ms. Hubbell had assumed, because of the beauty of the
sea mouse, in her description ``an iridescent furry worm that grows
to six inches in length.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead Linnaeus, described by Ms. Hubbell as ``an unpleasant
man'' who ``often made mean jokes in his namings,'' called the sea
mouse Aphrodite to perpetuate a vulgarism, namely the supposed
resemblance of the creature to the female genitals, which, she
writes, was reflected in ``the centuries-old Northern European
slang use of the word `mouse' for a woman's sexual parts.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hubbell was waiting for her lowly Aphrodite because, as she
explains in her prologue, after years of living in Missouri she
had, on the cusp of old age, bought a house on the coast of Maine.
There, in the pools created by rock outcroppings when the tide goes
out, she began to search for the invertebrate creatures that have
always been her passion, as we know from her previous books like
``A Country Year'' ``Broadsides From the Other Orders'' and ``A
Book of Bees,'' among others.
</P>
<P>
   In the same way, the 13 essays here reflect this appealing
passion. They explore such seemingly humble animals as the
millipede and the pill bug, the sponge and the earthworm, the bee
and the horseshoe crab, the spider and the fly. They take her to
the edge of her Maine coast tide pools, and into the Smithsonian
Institution's Museum of Natural History. They take her out to sea
with a New England diver for sea urchins, and up onto a walkway
through the canopy of a rain forest in Central America.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out, as is usually the case in Ms. Hubbell's diverting
books, that there is a good deal more to the beasts she focuses on
than most of us would normally notice. The golden silk spider spins
a web that researchers from Du Pont are studying in hopes of
matching its strength. Certain millipedes fall victim to one kind
of African mongoose, Mungos mungo, Ms. Hubbell writes, which picks
them up in its front paws and, ``standing, hurls them backward
between its legs at rocks, on which the hard cuticle shatters and
uncurls, allowing the mongoose to eat the soft and tasty body parts
within.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is the character of earthworms, she writes, that Darwin,
while studying them for what some regard as his greatest book,
``The Formation of Vegetable Mold, Through the Action of Worms,
With Observations on Their Habits,'' came to regard them as both
intelligent and sensitive.
</P>
<P>
   Dipping deeper into the tide pools of her studies, Ms. Hubbell
draws lessons from the millions of insect species remaining to be
discovered, from the need to improve invertebrate taxonomy, from
the meaning of Darwinian evolution and from the desirability for
preserving threatened species.
</P>
<P>
   Darwin's true genius, she argues, ``was his ability to think of
time beyond ordinary human understanding and to realize that
through it small events could pile up and have big results.'' If
more of us would appreciate this, we would defend the threatened
species whose ecological value we don't yet understand, because,
she concludes, ``we don't even know the identities of a great many
pieces of the ecosystem and practically nothing about how the
totality works.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in her last chapter, a Maine fisherman presents her
with a sea mouse, and, having explored what little is known about
it, she concludes that despite the indignity of Linnaeus' having
named it ``for the goddess associated with the physicality of love
and creation,'' the ``last laugh'' belongs to the creature ``and,
perhaps, to the goddess.''
</P>
<P>
   Sea mice, it seems, belong to the oldest class of worms,
Polychaeta, a subdivision of the phylum Annelida. These worms in
their Precambrian form are now thought by zoologists to be an
important stage in the development of more complex life. It seemed
fitting to Ms. Hubbell that Aphrodite aculeata, ``an advanced and
specialized polychaete, should echo the name the Greeks gave to the
generative and creative principle that had emerged from the sea's
depths.'' After all, she points out, ``Aphrodite, the name, derives
from the Greek word for sea foam, aphros.''
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Ms. Hubbell writes, ``there is one curiously
non-Greek part of her story that makes using her name for our hairy
sea mouse particularly apt, and that is her aspect as Aphroditos,
noted by Aristophanes, Macrobius, Servius and others. On Cyprus,
which, as Hesiod noted, was one of her earlier stopping places, an
androgynous, hairy, bearded Aphrodite, known as Aphroditos, was
worshiped, a deity with the body and clothes of a woman but with
the beard and sexual organs of a man.''
</P>
<P>
   Aphroditos, she concludes, ``seems to have been a very ancient,
pre-Classical expression of the androgynous qualities of an
undifferentiated creative principle, of bountifulness, made
concrete as a Great Goddess with masculine traits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not bad for a six-inch fuzzy iridescent worm of ancient
lineage from the ocean deeps.''
</P>
<P>
   In this way Ms. Hubbell proceeds from her tide pool in Maine to
the Greek pantheon and beyond, or from the concrete to the
mythological and back. Along the way she reveals breathtaking
wonders. And also makes us consider the minute mechanisms making
them tick.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `WAITING FOR APHRODITE
</P>
<P>
   Journeys Into the Time Before Bones'
</P>
<P>
   By Sue Hubbell
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 242 pages. Houghton Mifflin. $24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
