<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2124 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-SUPERMAN-GAME-NYT     07-07 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SUPERMAN-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A BIRD! IT'S A PLANE! (AND IT WOBBLES?)
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Writer's publishable e-mail address: Herz(AT)nytimes.com . ) 
 (nk) 
 By J.C. HERZ 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Poor Superman. First kryptonite, now video games. Judging from a
new Nintendo 64 cartridge named for its superhero, nothing is as
detrimental to the Man of Steel as a game controller. In a virtual
environment, Superman seems all too human.
</P>
<P>
   The game gets off to an unintentionally hilarious start when Lex
Luthor, having captured Lois Lane and Jimmy Olsen, sends them
hurtling through a swirling portal into a Virtual Metropolis from
which they cannot hope to escape without Superman's help.
</P>
<P>
   ``In short time,'' he intones, ``your fate will be sealed.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the whole setup bears an uncanny resemblance to
the underground lair in ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me,''
with the dais, the spiral gateway to interdimensional travel, the
hostages and, of course, Lex Luthor, who's a dead ringer for Dr.
Evil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then there's no time to waste,'' Superman says in his
hard-sell baritone. Trapped inside Virtual Metropolis, a sprawling
urban compound with conspicuous LexCorp signs, Superman's first
mission is to fly through a series of hoops floating in midair en
route to a ticking bomb.
</P>
<P>
   That's when you discover that Superman's flying controls leave
something to be desired. In the design phase, it probably sounded
like a good idea to build pitch and yaw into Superman's flight
mechanism. But in practice, it makes him really wobbly, and he
looks, well, not too confident about flying.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if you overcompensate for a steering error, Superman's
arms will reach out and flail for balance. He looks like the
Greatest American Hero, of spoofy 1980s television fame _ or George
of the Jungle in tights. Able to leap tall buildings at a single
bound? Not likely.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that you fly through all the hoops (and let's leave
aside the circus-performer indignity of that particular task),
there are a number of indoor bad-guys-in-a-maze scenarios where you
learn that Superman can die, repeatedly, before you get to the end
of a level. Not only do bullets not bounce off him, but he actually
lurches and reels when hit. His heat vision is useless in most
situations, and he can't smash through walls.
</P>
<P>
   Also, he walks funny. The lumbering gait makes sense if you
consider Superman's pigeon build and where his center of gravity
must be _ the guy's pretty top heavy. But you never see him walk in
a comic book, and in the movies or on television he's either flying
or standing still and making some kind of superhero announcement.
</P>
<P>
   So it's unsettling to see him move with the barrel-chested
inflexibility of an ex-jock, someone who's physically strong but
not particularly nimble. Something about the stiffness of his walk
is disturbingly familiar. Then suddenly, you realize that Superman
from behind looks just like Al Gore with a cape. After that, it's
hard to take him seriously.
</P>
<P>
   But even if you're 10-years-old and politically oblivious, it's
hard to take Superman seriously. In the game, Superman doesn't just
free Lois Lane. He fights off killer robots while she walks to
safety. He doesn't kill the bad guy. Oh no, he knocks out the bad
guy, lifts him aloft and carries him to a police car.
</P>
<P>
   That may work in a comic book, where the characters are
literally two-dimensional. But in 3-D, as an interactive
experience, it's a joke.
</P>
<P>
   In a video game, you have to assume the role of the central
character. But it's tough to identify with a lantern-jawed
goody-two-shoes who has no sense of humor. No one can play Superman
with a straight face. He's too simple, too earnest, too well
adjusted. He's too slow. He's used to being the strongest thing
around.
</P>
<P>
   That sense of invincibility doesn't mesh with the medium.
Because in most video games, you are surrounded by things that are
much larger and much stronger than you, things that can hurt you
badly. Even the landscape in a video game can kill you. There are
cliffs. There are ledges. There is lava.
</P>
<P>
   You're vulnerable in a video game, not just at dramatic moments
when the kryptonite comes out, but always. So video game characters
have to be agile. They can be small. They can be female. Bulk
doesn't matter. Speed matters. Coordination matters. Curiosity and
resourcefulness matter.
</P>
<P>
   The most important principle in any video game is: exploit your
surroundings. Pick up what's lying around and use it. Allocate your
energy. Manage your resources.
</P>
<P>
   And sure, it's unrealistic to assume that there will be
ammunition and first-aid kits lying around in a crisis. But it's
equally ridiculous to assume that you're the most powerful thing
around because you come from another planet.
</P>
<P>
   It's even more ridiculous in the context of this particular game
because Superman has to ``find'' X-ray vision midway through a
mission. It's just like any other power-up or weapon, and that
seriously detracts from his aura.
</P>
<P>
   Because if Superman has to scavenge for weapons, there's nothing
inherently special about him. He's just a 3-D cartoon character in
a silly outfit.
</P>
<P>
   In Virtual Metropolis, Superman is out of his element. He lacks
the reflexive grace of characters born and bred in the video game
universe so he seems befuddled and trapped.
</P>
<P>
   Chalk one up for Lex.
</P>
<P>
   Superman; published by Titus Software for Nintendo 64; $59.95;
ages 6 and up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 1730EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
