<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2127 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SILENT-MOVIE-PIANISTS     07-07 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SILENT-MOVIE-PIANISTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS CHAPLIN OR LLOYD CAVORTS ON SILENT SCREEN, THE ACCOMPANIST KEEPS
UP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(DW) 
 By ESTELLA DURAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They cannot take their eyes off the movie screen for more than a
few seconds. Their fingers fly through action scenes and lovingly
stroke notes from their keyboards as actors gaze into one another's
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   These musicians in the New York region are among the few
remaining practitioners of a nearly lost art: composing and
performing accompaniment for silent films.
</P>
<P>
   The job calls for intense focus, stamina and a genuine love for
these old movies, said Steve Sterner of Manhattan, who has
performed at the Film Forum in the South Village for about 15
years. Sterner, 48, plays for series there about 30 days a year.
The rest of the time he works as an actor, pianist and musical
director.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just get so wrapped up in the movie and often forget the
audience is there,'' said Sterner, who has played piano for at
least 230 films. ``But it can also take a lot out of you,
especially films that have a lot of action sequences.''
</P>
<P>
   To prepare, he screens each movie on video or in the theater;
takes pages of notes on action, characters and subjects, and
composes general themes for each. He estimates that it takes 8 to
10 hours to prepare for a show.
</P>
<P>
   During a Monday showing of ``Girl Shy,'' a hopping Harold Lloyd
film from 1924 that includes an action scene nearly 30 minutes
long, Sterner's skills were put to the test. The film is one of the
most difficult he has worked with, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chase scene is just so long, it's tough to keep up with
everything,'' he said, ``and you want to get all the falls and
effects.''
</P>
<P>
   Sterner is to play for a showing of Erich von Stroheim's
``Merry-Go-Round'' (1922) at 8 Thursday night and for Lloyd's ``For
Heaven's Sake'' (1926) at 7 and 9:55 on Monday night at the Film
Forum in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Sterner and a handful of others in New York who play music for
silent films said the best compliment they could get was to have
members of the audience say they forgot about the musician after a
while.
</P>
<P>
   ``You only want to complement the film and help the viewers get
into it, not to draw attention to yourself,'' Sterner said.
</P>
<P>
   Moviegoers said he succeeded. ``He was right there near me, and
I thought it was interesting to watch him,'' Paul Zimmerman, said.
``But after a while I was just so into the movie that he left my
field of view.''
</P>
<P>
   That reaction is one Lee Erwin likes, too. A legend in the
silent film music business, Erwin, a 90-year-old organist, has
performed in theaters across the world. He has recorded scores for
dozens of silent films _ including the works of Lloyd, Charlie
Chaplin and Buster Keaton _ in his apartment near Union Square. The
recordings were added to films and sold to theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Some silent movies had scores written for them, but for many, a
pianist or an organist composed music on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   Erwin has had his eyes on silent films and his hands on organ
keys since he was 12. His love for the movies and his musical
skills helped him become the organist at the two theaters in his
hometown, Huntsville, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the job was unpaid at first, he was happy. ``It
meant I could go in and see any movie for free,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He went on to graduate from the Cincinnati Conservatory of Music
as he played for theaters there; then he studied in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Erwin beamed as he displayed his press clippings and pulled out
a list of 102 theaters in which he has played, as far away as
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were the great theaters at the time, and I played them
all,'' he said, pointing out places like the Carnegie Hall Cinema,
the Eighth Street Playhouse and the Bleecker Street Cinema, where
he played until the early 1980's.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many of these are gone now, just gone,'' he said, shaking
his head.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has not performed in nearly a year, in part because
of a hip injury, Erwin keeps the music alive, at least for himself.
He often sits at his piano-size Everett Orgatron and, as a film
unfolds in his mind, plays the organ without turning it on, he
said, to keep from bothering the neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   When he wants to screen a movie, he flips on the film projector
on top of his organ. During a recent visit, he had a reel of
Chaplin's ``Gold Rush'' in the projector.
</P>
<P>
   The most fun he has ever had was performing in the Halloween
silent film series at the Cathedral of St. John the Divine, he
said. Last year he played his composition for Lon Chaney's
``Phantom of the Opera.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people came out, and the place was packed,'' he said.
He has also played for the cathedral's summer series of silent
films.
</P>
<P>
   He has met silent film actors and even appeared in a movie
himself once, playing a roller rink organist in Woody Allen's
``Radio Days.''
</P>
<P>
   Erwin recites his performance motto like a catechism. ``The
music is not the star,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is advice followed by many in the business, including Donald
Sosin, who has performed at the Museum of Modern Art and the
American Museum of the Moving Image. Sosin, 48, who lives in
Lakeville, Conn., said he loved the spontaneity of composing on the
spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Improvising makes the experience more special for the viewer
and more interesting for the performer,'' he said. Sosin also
performs at film festivals and works as a composer and musical
director.
</P>
<P>
   Sosin is currently in Bologna, Italy, to perform in the Cinema
Ritrovato film festival. This summer he will also be at Music
Mountain in Falls Village, Conn., and at the Telluride Festival in
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Oderman, 59, of East Orange, N.J., has been playing for
silent films for 40 years, including 30 years at the Museum of
Modern Art. He has also been writing a biography of the actress
Lillian Gish, whom he met when he skipped school to go to the
theater in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wanted to know why I wasn't in school, and I just couldn't
believe it was her,'' he said. Oderman said Gish had introduced him
to silent films and encouraged him to compose piano scores for
them.
</P>
<P>
   Another influence that pulled him into the world of silent films
was the screenings at the Museum of Modern Art. ``I just became
hypnotized when I went in there,'' he said. ``When I perform, I'm
still that 14-year-old kid cutting school and going to see movies
at the museum.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Model, 36, of Manhattan also has performed music for silent
movies at the Museum of Modern Art. In addition, he has played for
his ``Silent Clowns'' series at the 78th Street Theater Lab, which
featured Lloyd and Chaplin films. The series closed last month and
will resume in September.
</P>
<P>
   Comedies, Model said, are great for pulling in new fans of
silent films.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 1732EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
