<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGLES-THERAPY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW DATE CONNECTION: GROUP THERAPY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORINDA, Calif. _ Through the ages, men and women have found
diverse places to meet _ at bars, through friends, on the Internet,
at work. And now, at the shrink's.
</P>
<P>
   Orinda psychotherapist Jim Wolfe is recruiting singles through a
Web site for a new concept that is part group therapy, part
workshop and part dating service. (Which may be of particular
interest to the bachelors of Silicon Valley; a census report last
week reported that Santa Clara County has the second-biggest
surplus of single guys in the United States, after Alaska.) Called
Single Encounters, Wolfe's idea is to bring groups of eight men and
eight women together once a week for 10 weeks to get to know one
another, talk about their dating and relationship issues _ and date
one another.
</P>
<P>
   By the end, every man will have dated every woman in the group.
Sex is a no-no, at least during the 10 weeks. And whatever happens
on the date _ it can be as little as a phone call or as much as
dinner and a movie _ becomes fodder for discussions the following
week.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the dating, Wolfe insists he isn't promising people they
will find their mate in the group. That's not the idea, although he
doesn't forbid it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to give people an experience _ something they can
really work with,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not teaching people how to flirt, or giving lessons on how
to marry a millionaire,'' he added. ``It's true that if you join my
groups you will probably be going out with other people. You will
also be getting some psycho-social material around singleness,
courtship, dating and the personal baggage you bring into
relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe has seen it all _ the busy professionals too tied up in
their jobs to meet new people; those with unrealistic expectations
who dismiss potential partners because of a tiny flaw; the fear and
awkwardness in one-shot meetings; and the paucity of places where
singles can share what it's like trying to pair up.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind the group (co-led by Wolfe and a female
psychotherapist) is to let people get to know potential partners on
a deeper level before their automatic defenses kick in. And people
can be themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a comfortable physical and emotional space to
be in,'' Wolfe said. ``You have to feel safe _ you don't have to
have your hair and makeup just right, you can just be you.
</P>
<P>
   ``You also have to have reliable information about the person.
Not the stuff they tell you after they've had three margaritas and
not the stuff in the personals where everyone is attractive and
fit.''
</P>
<P>
   In a group that gets to know one another over a period of
months, ``you find that the weird mannerisms or the personality
flaw or the strange laugh or the wry sense of humor, that when you
first hear it you think, `That guy is weird,' but when over time,
you figure that it's just that he's very smart and has a dry sense
of humor. That `flaw' becomes a characteristic, something we can
fall in love with.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe has already run two similar groups with a female
co-leader. The first, which began four years ago, continued to meet
socially for a year after the program ended. Two members of the
group also dated for three years afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a bar-hopper. I enjoy talking and meeting people,
getting to know people first, and this offered an intelligent way
of meeting people,'' said Jodie (not her real name), who joined
Wolfe's first group.
</P>
<P>
   It was also eye-opening to hear about dating from the other
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I knew pretty much about dating, but listening to
some of these guys tell about some of their bad dates. ... I didn't
realize how hurtful it is to have someone walk away and to be
rejected. It opened my eyes to realize that men are very sensitive
creatures.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe has about 250 people signed up through his Web site who've
expressed interest. Registering is free, but if they end up
participating in a group, it costs $180.
</P>
<P>
   So far, women outnumber the men who've signed up, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a woman hears about this, she'll tell three of her
friends. But when a guy finds out about this, he'll tell nobody.
They aren't going to invite the competition. For the women, the
issue is safety _ `Let's all go together and do this.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
