<HEADER>
A2131 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSTON-MUSEUM-825&AMP;ADD     07-07 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-MUSEUM-825&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON MUSEUM'S RESTRUCTURING SOWS FEAR AMONG U.S. CURATORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since Malcolm Rogers took over as its director five years ago,
the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston has been riding pretty high.
Attendance has jumped, many exhibitions have won praise, and the
museum's once-precarious finances have been shored up.
</P>
<P>
   There have been a few problems, but they have faded. Guatemala
and Mali have said that a few antiquities in the collection were
stolen from their nations, but the museum maintains that they were
acquired legally long ago, and no claims have been made in court.
And in an embarrassing moment last fall, a Monet in the museum's
blockbuster exhibition turned out to have been looted by the Nazis,
and France, which had lent the work, recently returned it to the
family that had lost it.
</P>
<P>
   But a sweeping restructuring that Rogers announced on June 25
has turned him into something of a villain to many in the art
world. He merged several departments, eliminating 18 positions and
sending two senior curators packing that afternoon. He also created
20 positions, including those of photography curator and chief
financial officer. He will add six curatorial planning and project
managers and four slots in conservation and collection management,
bringing the museum's staff to 1,043.
</P>
<P>
   The new departments, he said, are needed to improve the care and
display of the museum's collection, part of his 10-year plan to
``enhance the visitor experience.''
</P>
<P>
   But many in the art world view the restructuring differently.
``Like all of my colleagues, I'm shocked and dismayed by what has
happened,'' said William Truetter, a senior curator at the National
Museum of American Art in Washington. ``It seems like such a
takeover.''
</P>
<P>
   He and many other museum professionals see the move, which
Rogers said in a staff memo would ``transform nearly all aspects''
of the museum, as a centralization of power that devalues curators,
making them pawns to administrators who will stress bottom-line
considerations rather than intellectual content when decisions are
made on programming. They worry that other museums will follow suit
and revamp their structure, resulting in more exhibitions whose
broad public appeal is their main virtue.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Hills, an art historian at Boston University, said,
``Malcolm Rogers believes in the corporate model for a museum, with
one guy at the top who is in power making decisions and only
looking at the finances and the marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The voice of the independent curator disappears,'' she said.
``I am really concerned about the profession. Will curators be able
to be scholars or will they just be guides in a theme park?''
</P>
<P>
   Even some who accept Rogers' rationale complain that he based
his decisions on personal relationships and treated the dismissed
employees shabbily, giving them just a few hours to clean out their
desks. In a protest letter, David D. Hall, a professor of religion
at Harvard University, termed the dismissals ``vulgar and decidedly
unprofessional.'' Others, citing similar layoffs at corporations,
said they worried about morale.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, a Briton whose curatorial expertise is in British
portraiture, made no apologies. ``We handled it as well as we
possibly could,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing a different business world parallel, he said,
``Generally, restructurings are done very quickly. It's profoundly
shocking to an institution and everyone wants it done quickly.'' He
called the criticism ``inevitable when you're doing something as
radical as this.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the realignment, several independent departments that had
been organized traditionally, by art medium, have become part of
megadepartments organized geographically. The new Art of the
Americas department, for example, unites the departments of
American paintings, American decorative arts and pre-Columbian art,
while Art of Europe combines European paintings and European
decorative arts.
</P>
<P>
   Both decorative arts curators, the American expert Jonathan
Fairbanks, who had been with the museum for 28 years, and the
European expert Anne Poulet, who had worked there for 20 years,
lost their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   A new Art of Asia and Africa department joins those two
previously independent areas, and Art of the Ancient World unites
classical Greek and Roman antiquities with ancient Egyptian, Nubian
and Near Eastern art.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars and curators at other museums said that while there was
more than one good way to organize a museum's holdings, they were
surprised by the new coalitions. It is unusual to group
pre-Columbian art with American paintings and furniture, for
example, and to unite African and Asian art. These areas have
little in common and are not studied together.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said that he had used no model for the reorganization,
and that he was not concerned with what other museums do. ``I want
what's right for us,'' he said. The geographical organization will
open the way for a clear, logical layout for the museum's
collection, he explained. ``I see geography as one way to help the
visitor,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He dismissed suggestions that museum politics or frayed personal
relations led to the realignment and the dismissals. ``People will
say these things, but personalities had nothing to do with it. It's
wholly a matter of the future of the organization,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also rejected contentions that he was taking over curatorial
and programming decisions or punishing curators who were too
independent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not keen on centralizing power, but a museum needs a
central vision,'' he said. ``I see my role as setting the direction
of the museum and then providing the opportunities and resources
for curators to do great jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he expected a lot more collaboration at the museum, for
example, among departments like contemporary art, prints and
drawings, and photography, which are independent entities.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers' restructuring may also shed light on the museum's
renovation plans. In May, the museum hired the British architect
Sir Norman Foster to design a master plan for renovating its
buildings and adding a wing, but it provided no details about the
the function of the new space or how the museum's layout would
change.
</P>
<P>
   The new megadepartments send some signals. The Art of the
Americas department, for example, is big enough to fill a new
building. ``That is a good possibility, but it is by no means
certain,'' Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Rogers said, he remains confident. ``The organization
will recover very quickly,'' he said. ``The MFA is a very strong
organization and the restructuring was the right thing to do, and
most people know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert P. Henderson, the chairman of the museum's trustees, said
that the board unanimously approved the plan. ``These things were
done after a lot of thought,'' he said. ``I'm 100 percent in
favor.''
</P>
<P>
   As for critics, Rogers said, ``I ask people to watch what we
do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
