<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2140 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRAKE-ARCHAEO-NYTR &LR;      07-07 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAKE-ARCHAEO-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BODEGA BAY DIG STIRS DEBATE ON FRANCIS DRAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CHRIS SMITH   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BODEGA BAY, Calif. _ A proposed scientific dig on the inland
shore of Bodega Head may produce the next chapter in the search for
a lost grail of Western history: the proved Pacific landfall of
globetrotter Sir Francis Drake.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever it was the English explorer sojourned in the summer of
1579 to repair and provision his flagship, the Golden Hind, he was
the first European to set foot on the place and to encounter the
natives there. Drake recorded that he left at the spot an engraved
plate claiming the territory for Queen Elizabeth.
</P>
<P>
   A state parks archaeologist in Sonoma County tends to doubt the
``Drake Was Here'' plate is buried at Bodega Bay _ but he's
sufficiently intrigued by theories and a recent magnetic survey to
do some digging.
</P>
<P>
   The spot where archaeologist Breck Parkman hopes to conduct a
sample excavation is at state-owned Campbell Cove on the Bodega
Head peninsula. The spot, within yards of where Pacific Gas &AMP;
Electric Co. sought to build a nuclear power plant almost 40 years
ago, has drawn the attention of scientists and history buffs.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, a researcher piqued by the mystery of where Drake
landed on the Pacific leg of his richly successful circumnavigation
in 1577-1580, endorsed earlier proposals that the place was Bodega
Bay.
</P>
<P>
   By floating his premise, writer Brian Kelleher of Cupertino
injected himself into an impassioned, century-old debate whose
adversaries spar over whether Drake anchored at the Marin County
bay that bears his name, or in San Francisco Bay or on the Oregon
coast or at any of a score of other spots in between.
</P>
<P>
   Kelleher based his premise on a study of voyage chronicles in
which Drake described, fairly generally, the ``fit and convenient
harbor'' and the amicable Indians he and his crew encountered.
Drake stayed on for about six weeks, dubbing the region Nova
Albion.
</P>
<P>
   Kelleher's quest drew him to Bodega Bay and, more specifically,
to Campbell Cove where he searched beneath the foliage in 1997 and
came upon remnants of a stone wall he believes the Drake party may
have built during a sojourn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not uncover any definitive proof,'' he said during a
recent visit to the cove. ``I just pointed to the area. It's really
up to the archaeologists to go in and see if they can find any
artifacts there.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, researchers from the University of California
at Berkeley followed up on Kelleher's research by surveying the
site with a magnetometer, in essence a refined metal detector. Dr.
Kent Lightfoot, an archaeologist, and an assistant discovered and
plotted the locations of magnetic anomalies they said could be
archaeological artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There does seem to be something buried there,'' Lightfoot
said. Just what it might be is, at this point, anybody's guess.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are heartened by the discovery of the rock wall and
the buried magnetic anomalies, and not just because of the prospect
they may have been left by Drake.
</P>
<P>
   With or without Drake, the spot is historically significant,
because the Coast Miwok lived there, and in the early 1800s _ more
than two centuries after Drake's voyage _ Russian fur traders built
a warehouse and other structures at Campbell Cove.
</P>
<P>
   No extensive archaeological study has ever been done at the
place. Parks archaeologist Parkman said Kelleher's investigation
and the survey by Lightfoot justify a sample dig. Parkman is
pursuing a $10,000 project to hand-dig an exploratory excavation.
He said he hopes to start the dig later this year or early in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's unlikely it's Drake's site,'' he said, ``but I
sure wouldn't be disappointed if it is. It would be nice finally to
solve that mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   The mystery matters to historians and archaeologists because
Drake was a giant of his time, his accomplishment similar in scale
to Neil Armstrong's stepping onto the moon more than 400 years
later.
</P>
<P>
   Drake's expedition was the second circumnavigation of the globe,
coming about 50 years after the voyages of Portuguese-born
Ferdinand Magellan. Drake left England in December of 1577 with
five ships, only one of which _ the Golden Hind _ would complete
the 36,000-mile journey.
</P>
<P>
   He filled the holds with silver he plundered from Spanish ships
and settlements in what would become Chile and Peru. When he
reached the area of Northern California in June 1579, he needed a
safe place to wait out late-season Pacific storms, repair his
leaking ship and take on provisions.
</P>
<P>
   From the Pacific Coast, Drake sailed to Indonesia, then across
the Indian Ocean, around Africa's Cape of Good Hope and north to
England. Delighted by his victories over the Spanish and the
astounding piles of silver he delivered to her treasury, Queen
Elizabeth bestowed knighthood on the first Englishman to sail
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   That brass plate he left somewhere, be it at Campbell Cove or
wherever, is a treasure of historical proportion, if only it can be
found.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Chris Smith writes for The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.,
a member of The N.Y. Times Regional Newspaper Group. This article
was distributed by The N.Y. Times News Service. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
