<SLUG> BC-CIR-ELECTRONIC-NOSE-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS PLAIN AS THE `NOSE' ON YOUR CHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By PETER WAYNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the senses, the realm of smell remained relatively
mysterious and unexplored by technology until very recently. Now
scientists and engineers are beginning to build electronic noses,
and the race is on to create palm-size machines and find
applications for them.
</P>
<P>
   Smell has been hard for scientists to understand. Physicists
created good mathematical models of how light, touch and sound
affect the human body many hundreds of years ago. But imitating the
human nose is a much harder job.
</P>
<P>
   What is needed is a device that can first detect specific
chemicals, then decipher the often complex combinations of
chemicals that occur in nature and finally come up with the same
answer that the human brain does.
</P>
<P>
   It is now easy for scientists to identify chemicals like methane
or benzene, but it's much harder to fit them into a map of the
specific odor of a hog farm or a dry cleaner. Even something so
seemingly simple as vanilla extract can be a deep mystery, a
complex potion of chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   The new digital noses are a departure from the traditional
technique of isolating individual chemicals with expensive devices,
like gas chromatographs and mass spectrometers, that excel at
revealing the individual components of a compound.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Sunshine, the president of Cyrano Sciences, a company in
Pasadena, Calif., that has developed an electronic nose on a chip,
said in a telephone interview, ``What we're really doing is
developing a very simple chemical analysis technique. The phrase
`electronic nose' is a good descriptor, but it's not always
complete.''
</P>
<P>
   Cyrano's chip has 32 sensors wired to it, each with a different
polymer mixed with some conducting material. As the chip is exposed
to the various gases that make up an odor, different polymers
expand, changing the pattern of conductivity on the chip. A
computer then measures the pattern and compares it with that of the
patterns of known samples to determine the odor.
</P>
<P>
   The trick is coming up with 32 polymers that react differently
to a wide range of chemicals. Some polymers may be impervious to
water but very sensitive to hydrocarbons like butane or methane.
Others may be tuned to aromatic chemicals like naphthalene, a
component in mothballs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our approach is much more like the human nose approach,''
Sunshine said. ``When you go around smelling, your nose isn't
trying to figure out the components of what you're smelling. It's
making a decision on a pattern recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   Each sensor reacts with a wide variety of chemicals, and it is
not possible to pinpoint the exact gas setting off each sensor.
That limitation may prove acceptable to many users because the
traditional tools for analyzing chemicals _ like the gas
chromatographs and mass spectrometers _ can easily cost tens if not
hundreds of thousands of dollars. Sunshine predicted that Cyrano's
device would cost about $5,000 when it was introduced at the end of
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Evor L. Hines, a scientist at the University of Warwick in
England, is studying how to use a computer simulating a neural
network to aid in pattern recognition. Hines recently reported that
he and his colleagues had developed the ability to chart the
progress of bananas from green to overripe, identifying the
freshness of the fruit automatically.
</P>
<P>
   The neural network monitors how each of the different sensors in
an electronic nose reacts to a new smell and compares the results
with sensor readings in previous encounters. The network is able to
distinguish between smells if it can identify simple differences in
how the sensor array responds.
</P>
<P>
   That may be easy with smells based on very different chemicals,
but it can require subtle distinctions when the chemicals are
similar but present in slightly different amounts.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine said the latest experiments at Cyrano suggested that
the company's digital nose excelled at some problems, like
distinguishing between the smoke from different types of fires.
People are often overwhelmed by the smoke and don't pick up some of
the subtler differences, he said. That may prove useful in
fire-detection and analysis.
</P>
<P>
   He admitted that his electronic nose could not match the human
nose in some areas, like detecting the sulfur compounds inserted
into natural gas to warn people if there is a leak.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Diane Ackerman, the author of ``A Natural History of the
Senses'' (Random House, 1990) said she was intrigued by the new
technology. ``We need to get used to sharing our sensory awareness
with computers,'' she said. ``This doesn't alarm me because in a
sense human beings aren't just evolving in the usual way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ackerman said the technology would eventually extend the
range of human smell in the same way that microscopes and
binoculars extended people's vision.
</P>
<P>
   She predicted that the electronic nose would come in handy in
diagnosing disease. Doctors often use their sense of smell
(discreetly) to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems rude to have doctors sniffing around you,'' Ms.
Ackerman said. But she predicted that the electronic nose might
provide some neutral scientific basis for comparing smells.
</P>
<P>
   The electronic nose developers are already exploring the
potential of the medical market. ``We've done some work on sniffing
a cow's breath,'' Hines said. ``We were actually involved in a
collaborative project to determining the state of health of the
dairy cattle.''
</P>
<P>
   Humans are next.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
