<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV09-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH ALERT: STOP WATCHING MARTHA STEWART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Friday, July 9)  
(mk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's blonde, perky and makes you want to throw your remote
control through the TV screen?
</P>
<P>
   Too easy. Martha Stewart, of course.
</P>
<P>
   According to an Illuminations survey, 27 percent of TV viewers
say they are ``stressed'' by watching the evening news compared to
51 percent who are stressed by watching Martha Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   The alarming part of this survey, in my mind, is not that more
people would rather see bodies being dug out of the rubble of
Belgrade than watch Martha assemble a homemade Christmas wreath of
dried herbs and wildflowers. The alarming part is that 49 percent
of TV viewers are apparently able to watch Martha without diving
for the whiskey bottle or curling up in the fetal position in a
dark, quiet corner of the house.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure that the Martha Stewart phenomenon is something men
can comprehend. For us, it's just something we flip past while
looking for Sportscenter or a bass-fishing show. If Martha wants to
reel in the male demographic, she needs to teach us how to cast for
bonefish.
</P>
<P>
   My wife and mother both watch Martha Stewart and neither, from
what I've observed, derive any pleasure from the experience. After
watching Martha single-handedly rescreen her windows and plant a
half-acre vegetable garden in less than half an hour, my mother is
too tired to go grocery shopping or pick up her prescriptions from
the pharmacy.
</P>
<P>
   The Illuminations survey does not specify how many elderly women
have been deprived of their medication because Martha was
reshingling the roof while simultaneously cooking a formal dinner
for 12 that day on TV, but you've got to think it's a significant
number. I would suggest that Congress look into this but I'm afraid
that their solution would be to require that TV screens be covered
with copies of the Ten Commandments, which would make watching
baseball difficult.
</P>
<P>
   But exhaustion and dangerous medical side-effects are
preferable, in some ways, to what my wife feels while watching
Martha Stewart _ an overwhelming sense of guilt. Such is the power
of Martha that women who work at a job 10 hours a day, haul the
kids to soccer and ballet practice, do the laundry, cook the meals
and clean the house still find themselves feeling ... inadequate.
After all, Martha's hair is fluffed, there are no bags under her
eyes and she tie-dyes her T-shirts with dyes made from organic,
individually labeled vegetables grown in her garden, the corners of
which are marked by handmade plaster statues of Sumerian fertility
gods.
</P>
<P>
   I know my wife has been watching too much Martha Stewart when I
find little jars with dried rose petals sitting around the house
and she announces, without a trace of sarcasm, that it might be
``fun,'' at our next party, to float candles in the punch bowl. (I
have learned not to mention the fact that we do not even own a
punch bowl as this just makes her feel worse about herself.)
</P>
<P>
   I know that my wife is reaching dangerous levels of
Martha-Stewart-related stress when she individually buffs lettuce
leaves with a linen napkin before serving them in a salad and
starts trimming the hedge to resemble the Seven Dwarfs.
</P>
<P>
   The only known cure is to strap her in a chair and make her
watch several hours of bass fishing shows with a little baseball
highlights thrown in for ``dessert.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a drastic treatment, to be sure, but it beats coming home
and finding her making wind chimes out of hand-painted coconut
shells.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
