<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE HOME PC IS A HOMEMADE PC 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (editors: optional sidebars at end of article)  
 (bl)  
 By MICHEL MARRIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shortly after 2 a.m. on a Sunday last January, my wife and baby
daughter, and even the cat curled up at my feet, were asleep. But I
could not have been more awake.
</P>
<P>
   For hours I had been hunched over the dining room table, trying
to turn $700 worth of discount electronic components into the core
of what would be my new personal computer. I had no intention of
stopping until I had realized a shimmering, silicon dream: a
machine packing no less than a 400-megahertz chip with 128
megabytes of memory; a 10.8-gigabyte hard drive; DVD-ROM,
CD-rewritable and Zip drives, plus a 19-inch monitor, the geek's
equivalent of a muscle car.
</P>
<P>
   The early morning quiet was broken only by the prattle of the
nearby television and the sound of my voice reciting a checklist
before plugging in the partly complete computer for its first test.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after an imaginary drumroll, I pressed the computer's
On button and waited.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing: no blinking lights, no whirling cooling fans, not a
solitary beep. With a rising sense of panic, I unplugged the PC to
wiggle its wires and examine its components.
</P>
<P>
   Was the motherboard secure and properly grounded? Were all the
jumpers on the motherboard and hard drive in their correct
positions? Were the microprocessor and memory modules firmly
seated? I even sniffed for signs of electrical overheating.
</P>
<P>
   I tried the machine again, and once again: nothing. Exhausted, I
went to bed.
</P>
<P>
   This was one step on the winding yet often exhilarating climb to
constructing my own computer at home. From December to May, I
carefully acquired computer parts, watching for bargains and
comparing notes with build-your-own veterans. My wife was
skeptical, while most of my friends and colleagues had a common
response _ why?
</P>
<P>
   The answer wasn't simple. First, as a lifelong tinkerer, I was
fascinated by computers. After years of frequently upgrading my IBM
PS/2 to its design limits, I was no longer intimidated by a
computer's inner workings. And since that computer was six years
old, I was ready for a new one, but as I shopped around, I could
never quite find the perfect fit. There was always some device I
would have to add, or some part of it I would rather discard. Given
the price for the higher-end machines, around $2,800 to $3,400 late
last year, the thought of buying my own parts at discount prices
and spreading the cost out over months was intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   There were risks, however. I knew that My home-built PC, if it
worked at all, would not have any technical support and that
warranties would cover only individual parts, not the assembled
no-brand PC. And I knew I could forget the hundreds of megabytes of
free software, often preloaded, that customarily come bundled with
retail computers.
</P>
<P>
   And if I took too long to build the PC, it could start to show
its age before it even ran because of faster and more feature-laden
parts and devices coming to market. But the allure of making a
computer outweighed the cold practical concerns. The birth of home
computers 25 years ago can be traced to hobbyists who were eager to
show off their prowess with garage-made machines. The Altair 8800,
the first mass market PC, was sold as a kit.
</P>
<P>
   From upgrading experiences years ago, I knew that I could leave
the soldering iron in the tool box. Unlike those first PCs,
computers today are not so much built as they are assembled,
requiring little more than a screwdriver.
</P>
<P>
   Few if any computer makers build all the parts they need to
complete a computer. Many manufacturers produce hard drives, sound
cards and motherboards. That makes PC parts amazingly modular and
fairly interchangeable. (Macintosh computers, of course, are the
exception.) All the really hard work, like cramming millions of
microscopic transistors onto the thin slips of silicon, has been
done by the technicians. The components themselves snap into place
like Legos.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, standards vary, and not all computer parts
work well together even if they fit together. Some are downright
incompatible. Worse, there are few ways to tell which parts and
devices are incompatible until you try to get them to work together
in the same computer.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Migliore, a consultant based in Englewood, N.J., has built
a house full of computers in the last four years. But after a
recent run of compatibility problems, he is growing less
enthusiastic about do-it-yourself PCs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you start to calculate the cost of the endless hours that
go into it and the emotional strain, it adds up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   You can avoid most problems if you are experienced, pay
attention to word-of-mouth cautions and study the specifications of
retail computers. There is also something to be said for taking
your time.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   I made lists of likely key components: motherboards,
microprocessors, memory modules and hard drives. When I went
shopping, my first stop was at a sprawling computer show held at
the New Jersey Convention and Exposition Center in Edison, N.J., in
late December. A sharp eye can find top-notch computer parts and
devices like speaker systems at discounts of 30 percent to 50
percent, compared with the retail prices commonly found in computer
and electronics stores.
</P>
<P>
   The two microprocessors I was looking at the time were Intel's
Pentium II 400-MHz and 450-MHz chips and Advanced Micro Devices
K6-2 400-MHz chip with 3-D Now _ the two leading chip brands at the
time. As a PC user since the mid-1980s, I have learned that the
latest thing is not always the greatest thing. Performance gains
are usually not nearly as great as the increase in the price would
suggest. Plus, the price of a chip almost always drops
significantly after a slightly faster one comes out. And I knew
that in three months or so there would be a bigger, better chip
anyway (the Pentium III 500-MHz and 550-MHz chips and the AMD K6-3s
450-MHz and 500-MHz chips).
</P>
<P>
   I decided on the AMD 400-MHz chip after the saleswoman, who had
the attention span of a toddler as dozens of potential customers
clamored for her chips, showed it to me in a jeweler's case, as if
it were worth its weight in gold (the actual chip is worth more).
The processor has an excellent reputation, and its price, $220, was
well under its Intel counterpart's. And it fit on a socket 7
motherboard, the most common configuration of main circuit boards
that PCs use. The more common the board, my thinking went, the
greater chance I would have of finding one with exactly the
features I needed.
</P>
<P>
   The motherboard, also called the main board, is the foundation
of any computer. Everything in the computer connects in some way to
the motherboard, which manages everything. A few weeks before I
went shopping for parts, I took some build-it-yourself classes
offered at my office so I could better understand the motherboard.
The instructor, Darrell Thomas, recommended buying a motherboard
that had plenty of expansion slots. The more slots a motherboard
has, especially the newer 32-bit PCI slots, the more circuit boards
or cards you can add to the PC to give it things like exceptional
sound, graphics and Internet connectivity. The same can be said for
special DIMM slots, which hold 168-pin computer memory modules.
More memory almost always translates into better computer
performance.
</P>
<P>
   I got a ASUS brand motherboard designed to run with a AMD K6-2.
It had every feature I was looking for and appeared to be very easy
to work with. The chip and board together cost $355. For another
$10, I got a heat-sink (a device that draws heat away from the
chip) and processor-fan combination that locks to the top of the
chip to help keep it cool.
</P>
<P>
   For days I carried the instruction booklet that came with the
motherboard with me as if it were a great novel. I read and reread
it on the bus, in the subway, over lunch. Of key importance was
setting the motherboard's jumpers, tiny switches that tell the
computer things like what kind of microprocessor it will work with.
</P>
<P>
   I was on my way. At the same computer fair, I bought a snazzy
mid-tower case with a 220-watt power supply for $60 at another
vendor's stand. I preferred a tower over a horizontal cabinet
because towers have more room for expansion, and the one I bought
features a pull-out chassis that makes the PCs components easy to
reach for repairs and future installations.
</P>
<P>
   For $16 I bought a Sony 1.44-MB floppy disk drive and 64
megabytes of Synchronous Dynamic Random Access Memory (today's
standard kind of memory modules) _ an amount I would double before
May. In the next several months, I went to computer fairs twice. I
also visited major computer retail outlets like CompUSA (when I got
impatient between fairs) and computer boutiques, looking for sales.
</P>
<P>
   When my PC had failed to come on in January, I retraced my steps
and discovered that I had not properly plugged all the controls
into the motherboard. After fixing that, I added a DVD-ROM and
100-MB Iomega internal Zip drive to my PC. Around Valentine's Day,
I reworked the control plugs that connect the motherboard to the
control buttons on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Then I held my breath and tried to test the computer yet again.
Almost immediately, lights flickered and I heard the hum of cooling
fans inside. There was also the familiar mechanical cranking up
sound of the hard drive. It was running. I wrote two words in my
project journal that morning: ``Very exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   I let the computer run all night to check for problems. I moved
it to the bedroom dresser so I could peek from bed at its green and
red lights throughout the night. I also wanted to be close enough
so I could smell trouble (literally) if it flared up.
</P>
<P>
   There were problems, all minor ones, with my new PC along the
way. I learned the hard way that I had to replace all the internal
ribbon cables with longer ones so the chassis could actually be
pulled out more than a couple of inches.
</P>
<P>
   And just when I was ready to buy my first choice for a powerful
graphics card, I found out that it would not work in my
motherboard's accelerated graphics port, or AGP, a too common
problem with some socket 7 motherboards. So I had to opt for a
PCI-slot graphics card, thereby using a valuable slot that could
have been used for something else. The following weekend, using
software and other parts from my old IBM, like its keyboard and
mouse and 15-inch monitor, I began loading software into my new PC.
First came the operating system, Windows 98. Its Plug and Play
function quickly recognized all the devices I had previously added
to the PC, like the DVD-ROM and CD-R drives and 56K modem.
</P>
<P>
   Right away I was impressed by the speed and power of my new PC.
Programs could be installed on it in less time than it took for my
old PC to notice that it was being asked to install a program.
</P>
<P>
   In the next couple of months, I added more software, a cordless
keyboard and mouse for about $100. For $200, I added a three-way
surround-sound speaker system with a subwoofer almost as big as a
microwave oven. Finally, on the first day of May, I bought a
19-inch monitor for my new PC and gave my old IBM to my wife.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One thing did concern me. When I checked my microprocessor's
temperature, I noticed that it occasionally inched upward to 120
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Heat is the great destroyer of computer parts. A friend who was
building a computer for his wife told me that he had become so
worried that his PC could overheat that he dreamed about his
450-MHz chip and saw it melt like grilled cheese.
</P>
<P>
   I eventually grew so concerned that I called a troubleshooter
for AMD. He told that the company's 400-MHz chips run safely at
temperatures approaching 130 degrees. Still, I headed off any
potential problem by redesigning the ventilation system. I added
two large cooling fans inside the PC case and arranged them so they
pushed hot air out of the case.
</P>
<P>
   On May 1, six months after I started, my computer was finally
complete. It routinely runs powerful graphics programs for
collecting and editing images made by my digital camera. It plays
the latest DVD-ROM full-length, high-resolution films, as well as
the latest games and electronic encyclopedias without a hitch. And
it backs up all my vital programs and data on rewritable CD-ROMs _
all impossible on my old PC.
</P>
<P>
   Now I'm designing a logo for the empty spot in the middle of its
case. I've christened it the Drumtec-400, in honor of the first
mass communications device and denoting the clock speed of its
processor.
</P>
<P>
   In all, I spent about $2,400 for my homemade PC. I estimate that
if I had purchased a similar PC at the time I started, it would
have cost about $500 more. Because prices have continued to fall on
the parts and devices, I could build the same computer now for
about $1,800.
</P>
<P>
   It was money well spent. Each time I turn on my computer, I'm
filled with pride and that feeling best expressed by Arthur C.
Clarke when he said that ``any sufficiently advanced technology is
indistinguishable from magic.''
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, when I visit computer stores I no longer have to
wince when I look at minimum requirements for software that
interests me. My PC runs everything, so far. But then, as sure as
rain follows thunder, there will be newer computers with faster
microprocessors for even more demanding programs. As soon as it was
built, my new PC started on the road to obsolescence. I'm already
plotting possible upgrades for years to come _ a new motherboard
with even more PCI slots, a Fire Wire (IEEE) port for digital video
editing, perhaps a huge flat-panel monitor when they become a lot
less expensive and, of course, a new miracle microprocessor.
</P>
<P>
   So I suppose PCs are never truly finished. Please don't tell my
wife.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBARS FOLLOW)
</P>
<P>
   PC CONSTRUCTION TIPS
</P>
<P>
   Building a personal computer can be a fool's errand if you don't
plan your work and work to your plan. Here are some things to
remember before you start to build.
</P>
<P>
   YOUR NEEDS _ Determine what kinds of demands you are likely to
make on the computer before you start to buy parts. If the new PC
is primarily going to be used for simple word processing and
surfing the Internet the types of components needed could be quite
different from those required for a PC that is designed to run
games or business applications.
</P>
<P>
   THE CPU _ Shop carefully, starting with the single most
important piece _ the microprocessor (also called the central
processing unit or CPU). Next decide on a good motherboard that
will accommodate the CPU. That information can usually be found on
the packaging and certainly in its manual.
</P>
<P>
   PORTS _ Make sure the motherboard has at least two Universal
Serial Bus ports, important for using a slew of new devices like
high speed printers and scanners.
</P>
<P>
   CASING _ Select a case, which usually comes with a power
transformer to run the computer. Vertical cases, or towers, offer
many advantages over horizontal cases. Towers are generally larger
so they can hold more devices and are more accessible for repair
and upgrades. All cases are configured in one of two types: AT and
ATX. This has more to do with the power supplies and how they
connect to the motherboard. Make sure that the motherboard's
connector matches the case. Some motherboards have connectors for
both AT and ATX.
</P>
<P>
   Make certain the case also has enough bays, compartments for
devices like CD-ROM drives.
</P>
<P>
   MEMORY _ Besides the CPU and motherboard every PC requires
memory chips (32 megabytes minimum of SDRAM), a hard drive for
storage (4.3 gigabytes minimum although 10 GB makes more sense with
today's bloated programs) and some form of drive, usually two. That
can mean, for example, a floppy disk drive and a CD-ROM drive or a
DVD-ROM that can play DVD movies, data disks, CD-ROM's and audio
compact disks. Popular CD-rewritable, Zip and tape backup drives
are optional.
</P>
<P>
   EXPANSION ROOM _ Remember to always leave room for future
upgrades. Motherboards with at least four more slots, (32-bit PCI
slots are better than aging 16-bit ISA slots) are better than those
with fewer. More slots may cost a little more but the expenditure
will save you in grief later.
</P>
<P>
   PRECAUTIONS _ Handle your components carefully, trying not to
touch exposed circuitry. Hold them by their edges like
old-fashioned vinyl records. Also make sure you are grounded. That
can be accomplished by touching the unplugged power supply before
you touch components or by wearing a anti-static wrist band.
</P>
<P>
   KITS _ If you are feeling less adventuresome, mail-order PC kits
are available from companies like Tiger Direct in Miami that
include everything you need to build a computer, including assembly
instructions and proven parts. Monitors are seldom included,
however.
</P>
<P>
   Parts at Bargain Prices
</P>
<P>
   So you want to build a computer?
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, you will need reliable parts. In recent years, most
reputable computer stores have stocked just about everything a
computer builder needs. The downside is that you will be expected
to pay full retail prices unless the items you want are on sale.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web, services like eShopper ( &UR; www.eshopper.com &LR; )
routinely sell a wide range of computer parts, often at discounted
prices. There are also a number of online auction Web sites on
which computer parts, some used or refurbished, are frequently for
sale at reduced prices.
</P>
<P>
   At weekend computer fairs, computer components are sold like
secondhand watches. Many parts, in addition to monitors and
printers, are sold for as low as 30 to 50 percent of manufacturers'
suggested retail prices at computer fairs. But caution is advised.
While some parts may be heavily discounted because they are from
earlier generations, some components _ particularly among those
sold as OEM (Original Equipment Manufacturer) without retail
packaging _ have been found to be refurbished without the buyer's
knowledge and others are outright counterfeits.
</P>
<P>
   KGP Productions puts on some of the biggest computer fairs in
the United States, mostly along the East Coast. A schedule of shows
can be found at www.pcshow.com.
</P>
<P>
   No matter where parts are purchased make sure to get receipts
with the sellers' addresses and telephone numbers. Be clear about
the return and refund arrangements. And if you are buying at a
computer fair, run the component (at least all night if possible)
as soon as you can. If a problem develops you will have a better
chance of finding the vendor before the fair closes and leaves town
_ with your money.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MICHEL MARRIOTT
</P>
<P>
   HELPFUL PUBLICATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Determining the reliability and features of computer parts can
be tricky. One way is to read reviews of them in computer
publications like PC Computing, Maximum PC and PC Novice magazines;
another is to ask around at computer enthusiast Web sites or to ask
computer vendors and users whose judgment you trust.
</P>
<P>
   Since building a computer often means doing the job without an
instruction manual _ individual components and drives usually
include instructions only on their installation _ it could be
helpful to know the overall design of a personal computer and how
all the parts work together. The following books provide helpful
information for anyone planning to build a computer.
</P>
<P>
   UPGRADING YOUR PC, 3D EDITION (By Kris Jamsa, Jamsa Press,
1999.)
</P>
<P>
   PC UPGRADE AND REPAIR SIMPLIFIED (By Paul Whitehead, Maran
Graphics, 1998.)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTERS SIMPLIFIED, 4TH EDITION (By Ruth Maran, Maran
Graphics, 1998.)  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
