<SLUG> BC-1940S-FOOD-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: Barbecue Cooking.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   1942: U.S. consumers hoard coffee, leading to a coffee ration of
1 pound every five weeks. Sugar has already been rationed; the
weekly allowance is 8 ounces per person. Meat is also rationed.
</P>
<P>
   1942: Ideal weights are published by Metropolitan Life
Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   1942: Neil and Carl Fletcher serve their corny dogs at the State
Fair of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   1942: American plants, and the military, push candy on workers
and soldiers, believing that the energy from the sweets keeps them
awake and effective.
</P>
<P>
   1942: The frozen food industry balloons as producers look for
alternatives to metal cans during the war years.
</P>
<P>
   1942: Victory Gardens sprout throughout the country as
vegetables become scarce. They are especially hard to find in
California because two-thirds of vegetables were brokered by
Japanese-Americans, who have been relocated to internment camps.
Forty percent of all vegetables are produced in almost 20 million
Victory Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   1942: The Wrigley Co. packs military K rations that contain
canned meat, four cigarettes, compressed Graham biscuits, three
tablets of sugar and a stick of chewing gum. Ration D is a
600-calorie Hershey bar (minus the cocoa butter, so it won't melt)
fortified with nutrients. The bar could also be ``dissolved by
crumbling into a cup of boiling water, if desired as a beverage.''
</P>
<P>
   1943: Rubber, metal, paper, silk and nylon are collected for
recycling. Flour, fish, canned foods and shoes are rationed.
</P>
<P>
   1943: Ike Sewell and Ric Riccardo create Chicago-style (deep
dish) pizza at Pizzeria Uno in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   1943: Sale of sliced bread is banned. Cheese and fat are
rationed.
</P>
<P>
   1943: Florence Brobeck, in her book ``Cook It in a Casserole,''
offers a low-ration-point recipe that combines canned tuna fish
with cubed potatoes, peas, cheese and a white sauce.
</P>
<P>
   1943: Recommended Daily Allowances for various nutrients are
published for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   1943: Texas produce broker Gordon Harwell develops converted
rice.
</P>
<P>
   1943: A Trumanburger, named after Harry S., is concocted during
the dying days of meat rationing; it includes baked beans.
</P>
<P>
   1944: Meat rationing, except for steak, ends after D-Day.
</P>
<P>
   1945: Earl W. Tupper invents resealable food containers.
</P>
<P>
   1945: In an effort to give bananas a designer label, the United
Fruit Company creates Chiquita Banana, a banana-cum-Carmen
Miranda-type Latin dancer. Chiquita, swinging her hips samba-style,
sings:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Chiquita Banana and I've come to say,
</P>
<P>
   ``Bananas have to ripen in a certain way;
</P>
<P>
   ``When they are flecked with brown and have a golden hue
</P>
<P>
   ``Bananas taste the best and are the best for you.''
</P>
<P>
   1945: Although many women lose their jobs when World War II ends
and servicemen return home, the number of women in the work force
will never fall as low as it was before the war.
</P>
<P>
   1945: Food rationing end for all items except sugar. U.S.
gasoline rationing also ends.
</P>
<P>
   1945: American consumption of vegetables hits a record high as
the results of Victory Gardens supplant canned vegetables (for
which the metal had been needed in the war effort).
</P>
<P>
   1946: Frozen french fried potatoes are introduced.
</P>
<P>
   1946: Charles Kincaid opens his namesake grocery store in Fort
Worth. In-house butcher O.R. Gentry (much in the style of Hill
Country butchers who barbecued) begins selling hamburgers to get
rid of leftover ground chuck. So successful were the burgers that
Gentry bought Kincaids in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   1947: Reynolds Metals Co. uses surplus aluminum from World War
II to make Reynolds Wrap aluminum foil.
</P>
<P>
   1947: U.S. rationing of sugar ends, but President Harry Truman
urges meat and egg conservation to save grain for struggling
Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   1947: Refrigeration and the rise of suburbia are responsible for
the creation of supermarkets, where all foodstuffs can be found
under one roof.
</P>
<P>
   1947: Reddi-Wip is the first major U.S. aerosol food product.
</P>
<P>
   1947: Cake mixes from Betty Crocker and Pillsbury start making
their appearance. The first mix is for a single-layer ginger cake,
followed by the now-standard layer cake in devil's-food flavor.
Right after the war, many women had decided to stay in the work
force. People had more money and could afford the 35-cent price for
a mix. However, the first cake mixes included powdered eggs. When
cooks complained that they wanted to do more of the baking, the
mixes were changed so that cooks were required to add real eggs.
</P>
<P>
   1947: Herb Massey opens the altar to chicken-fried steaks in
Fort Worth, Massey's.
</P>
<P>
   1947: Marilyn Monroe is crowned the first Queen of the
Artichokes.
</P>
<P>
   1947: Lawyer Jesse Roach and his wife, Mozelle, open Cattlemen's
steakhouse in the Fort Worth Stockyards. He manages the altar to
red meat until his death in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   1948: V8 Cocktail Vegetable Juice is introduced by Campbell Soup
Co.
</P>
<P>
   1948: Nestle introduces instant tea.
</P>
<P>
   1948: 78 percent of U.S. homes have electricity provided by
power stations.
</P>
<P>
   1948: Dick and Mac McDonald open the first McDonald's in San
Bernardino, Calif.
</P>
