<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2163 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WRITERS-SUIT-2TAKE     07-07 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WRITERS-SUIT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A `WILD, WILD WEST' FOR EARLY TV WRITERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Four months ago, Gilbert Ralston, a top television
writer in the 1950s and '60s, lay dying of congestive heart failure
at the Sandpiper Court Yard, a home for the elderly near
Charleston, S.C. ``I've had a good life, a full life, an
interesting life,'' his son, Michael Ralston, recalled him saying.
``I don't have any issues except one. `Wild, Wild West.'''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Ralston, a retired Navy officer who was a submarine
commander, reflected that his father, who died at 87, ``had written
many scripts _ about 20 `Ben Caseys,' `Gunsmoke,' `Naked City,' a
couple of `Star Treks.' But he created `Wild, Wild West.' He knew
the movie was being made. And he was stunned and mystified and
really very upset that they said he hadn't created the series.''
</P>
<P>
   The legal battle began in July 1997. Shortly after Ralston sent
a letter to CBS, the producer of ``Wild, Wild West,'' saying he had
created all the elements of the series, the network sued the aging
writer, arguing that he intended to defraud the network when he
wrote the original series in 1964. Ralston's family and lawyer said
the CBS move was an intimidation tactic to keep him from pressing
his case. CBS declined to comment. In October 1997, Ralston filed a
counterclaim in federal court seeking redress for his rights in
connection with the series.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the Ralston case puts a focus on a common
Hollywood practice of the 1950s and '60s. At the time, television
writers who helped create popular series allowed producers or
studios to take credit for a show and signed documents that, they
said, had the effect of cheating them of millions of dollars in
royalties decades later. The royalties came from the movies, videos
and merchandising from the television shows that the original
writers had a significant role in inventing.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring what is at stake is the popularity of the new film
``Wild, Wild West,'' which withstood poor reviews last week to take
in more than $35 million and emerge No. 1 at the box office this
week.
</P>
<P>
   A Warner Brothers lawyer who spoke on condition of anonymity
said that Ralston's family had ``no legitimate claim'' to legal
action and that the late writer or his family had not made an
effort until recently to seek potentially lucrative royalties. ``We
think it's a bogus, manufactured, after-the-fact claim,'' the
lawyer said. CBS declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   But testifying for Ralston, Roy Huggins, one of television's
most respected and successful writers of the 1950s and '60s, who
created or helped create such shows as ``Maverick,'' ``The
Fugitive,'' ``77 Sunset Strip,'' ``The Rockford Files'' and
``Baretta,'' said that it was almost commonplace then for companies
to engage in machinations that duped writers. Television writers,
he said, ``were no match for the major television networks, studios
and producers, whose contracts in most instances were structured to
obliterate'' the writers' prospects for earning profits and
royalties.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Franklin, who was executive director of the Writers
Guild of America West from 1958 to 1978 and has testified on behalf
of writers for such television series as ``Hawaii 5-0'' and ``Have
Gun, Will Travel,'' said in court papers on behalf of Ralston that
many television companies used deceptive practices to defeat ``a
pilot writer's entitlement'' to his or her rights. (The Writers
Guild has not supported the Ralstons, and a spokeswoman declined to
discuss the reasons.)
</P>
<P>
   Franklin and others said that in the 1960s and even '70s, the
Writers Guild and talent agents and lawyers failed to grasp the
nuances of the contracts signed by writers and the implications
years later.
</P>
<P>
   Ralston's family also said that Warner Brothers and CBS had
filed a countersuit against the writer in his last years simply in
an effort to intimidate him to drop the suit. ``He was 86, in a
wheelchair, and they sued him in federal court for $10 million
because he asserted his rights,'' his angry son said. ``I was
appalled at the tactics used to intimidate him. Periodically my
father asked: `Can they get my Social Security? Can they get my
Writers Guild pension?'''
</P>
<P>
   A Warner Brothers lawyer said the accusation of intimidation was
untrue. ``We knew he had made the claim, and it seemed the most
expedient way to get it resolved,'' the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   No dollar figure has been attached to the Ralston family's suit,
filed in the U.S. District Court for the central district of
California, but it could amount to millions of dollars. The
family's lawyer in the case, Marc Toberoff, said that the Ralstons
were seeking ``all available remedies, which may include profits
from the film in all media, and/or enjoining further distribution
of the film.'' The case is set for trial in mid-October in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The issues involved in the suit offer a glimpse into a murky
arena in which some authors gave up their rights, sometimes
wittingly, sometimes not, to studios and production companies.
Moreover, some writers failed to foresee that what they helped
create would prove a valuable property decades later.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Ralston, who retired from the Navy in 1993 after 33
years, said his father was a CBS executive in New York in the
mid-'50s and moved to Los Angeles in the early '60s to pursue a
writing career. The elder Ralston moved to Charleston, S.C., in
1989 after his wife died.
</P>
<P>
   According to Toberoff and court papers, the elder Ralston
received a phone call in January 1995 from Dan Furie, a business
affairs executive at Warner Brothers, asking him if he had
``separation of rights'' on the television series. This is a term
meaning a writer has created an original pilot and is entitled to
royalties on every episode as well as theatrical and other rights.
</P>
<P>
   Ralston, then 85, without consulting a lawyer, said he didn't
know and would look into it. On Jan. 30 he wrote to Furie saying:
``For the record, I developed the pilot, characters therein, and
presented it to CBS and sat through the filmmaking. I developed the
locale, characters, characterizations, format, theme, pilot and
suggestions for future stories.'' He added that ``nothing was
supplied'' by CBS or Garrison Productions, which produced the
series.
</P>
<P>
   Ralston heard nothing further from Warner Brothers, his lawyer
said. Two months later he reached the widow of his former agent in
Los Angeles and related the story. The widow, Doris Halsey,
suggested that he call Toberoff, a lawyer who has specialized in
these cases.
</P>
<P>
   Toberoff said: ``He sent me his agreement. I interviewed him and
looked at the contract. And I quickly realized that this case is
exactly like numerous cases I've already seen from the '60s, in
which writers had been deprived of their intellectual property
rights.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   According to sworn statements presented by the elderly witnesses
in the case, it was commonplace in Hollywood in the 1960s for a
writer to create a series but then have an executive step in and
insist that the show was the network's or studio's idea. The
writers, many of them eager to work, acquiesced. In that way,
networks and studios held on to the rights of projects.
</P>
<P>
   Huggins, for example, said that when he came up with the story
for ``Colt .45,'' he was soon told by a Warner Brothers executive,
Hugh Benson, that Jack L. Warner, the studio chief, had actually
come up with the idea. ``I looked at Benson and said: `Really? I
think it's very strange that J.L. himself would come up with an
idea a year ago and nobody did anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Huggins recalled similar episodes with two other shows he
created, ``Maverick'' and ``77 Sunset Strip.'' On ``77 Sunset
Strip,'' for example, he said Warner Brothers, seeking to avoid
paying royalties, asked him to stretch the pilot to 90 minutes.
``Warner Brothers took that 90-minute show and previewed it in a
little town on an island in the Caribbean,'' Huggins said. ``God
knows where. I used to know. I don't anymore.'' He said Warner
Brothers then sold the movie as a pilot without making television
royalty payments to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean how much closer to real devilish machinations can you
get than to ask a guy to stretch a show to 90 minutes so you can
preview it in the Caribbean in a theater that probably only had
five people in it and then sell it as a movie?'' Huggins said.
``It's so devious I can't believe they got away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Huggins was given a credit in 1994 by Warner Brothers
as the creator of ``Maverick,'' the Mel Gibson-Jodie Foster film,
he was not paid for it. ``They didn't pay me a nickel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ``Wild, Wild West,'' Ralston said in a deposition
on May 18, 1998, a producer, Michael Garrison, phoned him in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did he tell you in that conversation?'' Ralston was
asked.
</P>
<P>
   He replied: ``Said he had an idea for a series, good commercial
idea, and wanted to know if I could glue the idea of a western hero
and a James Bond type together in the same show.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralston said he then created the Civil War characters, the
format, the story outline and nine drafts of the script that was
the basis for the television series. Ralston said it was his idea,
for example, to have a secret agent named Jim West who would
perform secret missions for a bumbling Ulysses S. Grant.
</P>
<P>
   Similar characters form the basis for the current film. (Six
writers are given credit for the film, but Ralston's name does not
appear.) Garrison died in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   CBS, in turn, contended that Ralston ``did not create the major
elements of `The Wild, Wild West' property and simply wrote a
teleplay from an `established episodic series' or `established
serial' based on material CBS or Garrison provided to him.'' CBS
also said that several former network executives were involved in
the creation of the characters, although witnesses for Ralston
vigorously denied this.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent depositions, some former top CBS executives
generally supported the Ralston family. John Cheney Rock, a network
business affairs executive in the 1960s, said: ``Gil Ralston wrote
the basic thing. At CBS we didn't have anybody employed to write in
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if people at CBS at the time believed Ralston had created
``The Wild, Wild West,'' Rock replied, ``Definitely.''
</P>
<P>
   Another former top CBS executive, Michael Dann, who was the
network's vice president for programming in 1964, said he did not
believe that former network executives wrote the show. ``We all as
a group felt that Gil Ralston was the person who supplied the
creative framework and implementation of a concept of `The Wild
West,''' West said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
