<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-JOURNAL _ PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ The carnage in Kosovo
was the first story I have covered that was bigger than it looked
on television. In Hurricane Andrew, in 1992, the casualties were
limited and life continued in many parts of Miami. December's
bombing of Iraq provided good televised fireworks, but most Iraqis
were barely inconvenienced. But Kosovo was a story of blind ethnic
hatred -- the poison that germinates with simple bigotry and
transforms so easily into bloodshed. Its ravages are not confinable
to a television screen. The acts of evil were too numerous for a
journalist to report and too vast to escape. (Kaplow, Cox News
Service). 20.
</P>
