<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, July 8, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Relief from the extreme heat that griped the Northeast earlier
this week will continue Thursday as the circulation around high
pressure over the Ohio Valley directs seasonably warm and dry air
into the region. Skies will be mainly sunny, though scattered
cumulus clouds will accompany a weak cool front crossing interior
New England. Spotty afternoon showers may briefly dampen the Green
and White mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered thunderstorms will surround a stationary front
stretching from northern Alabama to North Carolina. South of the
front, humid air will also fuel isolated thunderstorms near the
Gulf and Southeast coasts. A more concentrated area of
thunderstorms associated with a jet stream disturbance will bring
torrential rain to portions of Louisiana and eastern Texas where
some flooding may occur.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly humid air will surge north through the Plains,
setting the stage for heavy precipitation. Separated showers and
thunderstorms will likely congeal into a large complex over the
eastern Dakotas and upper Mississippi Valley on Thursday, bringing
the risk for heavy rain to the region. Localized flooding is
likely.
</P>
<P>
   Moist air in the lowest 10,000 feet of the atmosphere will spark
spotty thundershowers in the Southwest and southern Rockies.
Thundershowers will be most numerous during the afternoon as
heating of the ground and overlying air by the sun encourages
ascending currents of humid air. Abundant sun will cover northern
California and the Northwest though gentle onshore breezes will
cause clouds to cling to the Washington coast. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Desert Flooding &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At least two cars were swept away in Tucson, Ariz., on Tuesday
as flood waters as deep as 3 feet surged through city streets.
Flash flooding is a hallmark of the summer monsoon in the Southwest
as humid air streams north from the tropics, providing fuel for
slow-moving thunderstorms that produce heavy rain. But the desert
floor does not readily absorb large amounts of water due to its
sandy soil and a lack of plants. Run-off from rain can be very
rapid. In summer, an arroyo, which is a dry creek bed, can change
from a arid gulch to a raging torrent in a matter of seconds. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 1815EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
