<HEADLINE>
SEEK AND YOU WILL NOT NECESSARILY FIND  
 FAREWELL TO PALMTOP MANIA  
 UNREAL REAL ESTATE  
 ETC. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Md., Mass., Ind.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Search engines just cannot keep up with the Web. That is the
finding of two scientists for the NEC Research Institute who have
spent the past six months determining how many Web pages exist _
and how many are actually picked up by the likes of Alta Vista and
Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   Their results, which are published Thursday in the journal
Nature, paint a meager picture: Of 11 search engines studied, not
one indexes more than 16 percent of the Web. Most cover less.
</P>
<P>
   ``Search engines are increasingly falling behind in their
efforts to index the Web,'' wrote Steve Lawrence and C. Lee Giles,
the scientists who conducted the study. In a similar study two
years ago, the researchers found that the largest coverage of a
single search engine, Hotbot (www.hotbot.com), was 34 percent of
the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the current study, which are available at
www.wwwmetrics.com, show that Northern Light
(www.northernlight.com) has the largest coverage, with an index
that contains 16 percent of Web pages that can be indexed. Lycos
(www.lycos.com) and Euroseek (www.euroseek.net) appeared to have
the least, covering only 2.5 percent and 2.2 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The study revealed more about the state of the Web, particularly
about how much has become commercial: 83 percent of sites contain
commercial content while only about 6 percent contain scientific
and educational content. Only 1.5 percent have pornography, a
figure that might surprise many Web surfers.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers also found that people who are searching for
information that is less well known are probably missing out
because some search engines use the popularity of Web pages to
determine whether they should be indexed.
</P>
<P>
   To begin their research, Lawrence and Giles estimated the size
of the Web. Their tally: 2.8 million sites and 800 million pages.
They then used an automated program to plug 1,050 queries into each
search engine and tabulate the results. The queries, which included
phrases like ``smart matter'' and ``rocchio algorithm,'' were
obtained from a list of queries used by their fellow scientists at
the NEC Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not representative of general Web users,'' Lawrence
acknowledged in an interview. ``But the important issue here is
that the search engines seem to be biased toward more well-known
information.''
</P>
<P>
   What's more, they are probably finding information that is out
of date. Even the newest pages retrieved from the search engines
were as many as eight months old, according to the researchers'
data.
</P>
<P>
   For those seeking a way out, Lawrence suggested conducting a
metasearch _ one that combines the results of several search
engines. He hesitated to suggest specific names, but a search on
the word metasearch in Hotbot turned up these: www.metacrawler.com,
www.metasearch.com and www.dogpile.com. Of course, who knows what
else might be out there?
</P>
<P>
   _ LISA GUERNSEY
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard to Shut Down Production of a Cult Favorite
</P>
<P>
   Before there was Palm Pilot mania, there was Palmtop mania. The
Palmtop 200LX was the latest in the LX line made by
Hewlett-Packard. A tiny notebook (weighing less than a pound), it
was the last popular PC to be made to run on MS-DOS.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Hewlett-Packard announced that it would no longer
manufacture the Palmtop line, which had become a victim of time and
the popularity of Windows CE. But, like fans of Elvis, Palmtop
aficionados can't really believe the king is gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had to work to sell one in two years. It has one of
the most loyal followings I've ever seen,'' said Kevin Havre,
Hewlett-Packard's technical marketing manager for North America.
Unlike current subnotebooks, the Palmtop was designed to work as a
sole computer, not as an appendage to a desktop. ``It's the
smallest PC _ quote, unquote,'' he said. ``The Palmtop was a PC. A
full PC. Period.''
</P>
<P>
   Hal Goldstein, publisher of the Hewlett-Packard Palmtop Paper
(www.thaddeus.com), says the Palmtop's size and versatility made it
so popular, particularly among doctors, engineers and brokers.
``The applications were brilliant,'' Goldstein said. ``You could
customize the database so easily.'' Its fans created what he
described as a ``Linux-like library of hundreds of applications''
(www.palmtop.net), including a drug formula program for doctors and
another that allowed users to turn the horizontal screen on its
side to read a book page.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Francis, an assembly line operator in Kentucky, described
his Palmtop as ``a computer that can do everything a desktop can
do, which fits neatly in your pocket and runs for weeks on two AA
batteries.'' But he was less magnanimous about Hewlett-Packard's
decision to discontinue the line. ``Most users of the DOS LX
Palmtops abhor the Windows CE interface. For us, there is no
comparing our sleek and fast interface with the eye candy interface
Win CE provides.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Johns, a deputy sheriff with the Jefferson County Sheriff's
Department in Birmingham, Ala., probably created the most novel
uses for his Palmtop. ``It meant I could turn off my desktop and
never turn it on again.'' In addition to running criminal checks on
his 200LX, he rigged it up to an antenna made of hangers, then to
his police antenna, to talk to the Mir space station. ``How many
policemen do you know who exchange messages with cosmonauts while
driving around in their squad car?'' Johns asked.
</P>
<P>
   _ BRUCE HEADLAM
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
