<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEK-NOTES-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: Johns asked. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Videogame Worker Dismissed for Selling Fantasy Real Estate
</P>
<P>
   A popular expression about real estate is ``they're not making
more of it.'' But when it comes to virtual real estate, a videogame
employee not only made more of it _ he lost his job for selling
some over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a game software maker, Origin Systems, dismissed an
employee for earning almost $7,000 by selling fantasy real estate
on Ebay, an online auction site.
</P>
<P>
   The employee, Kevin Roseler, 24, worked for Origin and monitored
Ultima Online, a fantasy role-playing game world with 150,000
members. Using his computer privileges, Roseler generated castles
and other valuable game property, which he is said to have sold
over a month through Ebay auctions. Another Ebay user noticed the
sequence of unusual auctions and notified the company, which then
dismissed Roseler.
</P>
<P>
   The company did not require Roseler to return the money. While
his actions were not illegal, they were an abuse of privileges and
a breach of trust, said the company, which is a subsidiary of
Electronic Arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they brought me into the office, they were talking about
corporate embezzlement, but I went to a lawyer who told me that I
didn't steal anything tangible,'' Roseler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing I really stole. I broke their trust,'' he
said, adding that he considered that the ``worst part.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebay has become a vibrant market for people looking to move up
the fantasy-game ladder. Hundreds of items like castles, gold and
treasure maps are sold by more experienced players who have
accumulated properties throughout their role-playing careers.
Roseler sold property that could be converted to virtual gold. The
approximate exchange rate on auction sites is one real dollar for
500 virtual gold pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Roseler said the company had warned its employees about selling
game property on the auction sites. ``I knew that I if I was
caught, I would be fired,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had taken the risk to raise money for friends who
were having financial problems. ``In 20-20 hindsight, I wish I had
used a different way to help them,'' said Roseler, who has found a
new job.
</P>
<P>
   _ JENNIFER 8. LEE
</P>
<P>
   Summer Book Club
</P>
<P>
   Public libraries learned long ago that if you want to get
children to read books over the summer, you probably need to dangle
a prize before their eyes. Now a new Web site called Book Adventure
has brought the same concept to the Internet. The site,
www.bookadventure.com, offers prizes to children who earn points
for successfully answering online questions about the books they
have read. Points can be redeemed for prizes, like gift
certificates to Barnesandnoble.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want it to be self-motivating,'' said Brent McCallister,
program director for the site, which is sponsored by the Sylvan
Educational Foundation, a nonprofit organization based in
Baltimore. ``This is a great way to harness the power of the Web in
a safe, educational way.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball Action
</P>
<P>
   Baseball fans who cannot tear themselves away from their
computers can still catch each pitch and play of next Tuesday's
all-star game as it happens by logging on to
www.majorleaguebaseball.com and clicking on the Sportsline USA's
Baseball Live feature. Baseball Live uses animated illustrations to
add depth to coverage along with chat forums and troves of
statistics. For fans abroad, it may be the best alternative to
watching on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Young Webmasters
</P>
<P>
   It's January 1964. You have 16,500 military personnel in South
Vietnam. Your approval rating is 73 percent. So, President Johnson,
what's your move?
</P>
<P>
   That is the backdrop for Escalation
(brainsoft.ne.mediaone.net/escalation), a simulation Web site set
up by 17-year-old Nathaniel Duca of Wenham, Mass., one of eight
finalists for the first annual Ars Digita Prize. The contest
rewards teen-agers who build noncommercial Web sites. The grand
prize of $10,000 was won by Daniel Hunter, 18, of Richmond, Ind.,
for the Earlham Web Calendar (www.earlham.edu/calendar), a site
that posts events at Earlham College.
</P>
<P>
   _ JESS DHALIWAL
</P>
