<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2190 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-KOSOVO-SERBS-ART-NY     07-07 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-KOSOVO-SERBS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: GRASS-ROOTS ANGER WITH MILOSEVIC SWEEPS ACROSS SERBIA 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeats to add art note)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ More quickly than the political opponents
of Slobodan Milosevic had dared hope, grass-roots dissatisfaction
with the Yugoslav president is surfacing across much of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Hostility toward Milosevic, bubbling up this week on the streets
of the most unlikely of towns, has raised expectations among
opposition politicians that Milosevic's survival in power might now
be measured not in years, but in months.
</P>
<P>
   What has particularly raised eyebrows among political analysts,
who are beginning to doubt if opposition parties can keep up with
grass-roots anger, is the surprise eruption of large and violent
protests in the large southern Serbian city of Leskovac, a
long-time stronghold of the Milosevic regime.
</P>
<P>
   There, without the help of any political party, but with the
active involvement of army reservists who fought in the lost war in
Kosovo, more than 20,000 people marched on Monday night calling for
Milosevic to resign. On Tuesday, about 2,000 people charged the
local police station, demanding the release of the local TV
technician who organized Monday's rally.
</P>
<P>
   Police responded with tear gas and by beating demonstrators with
nightsticks. Demonstrators retreated and later attacked the home of
a local political boss who belongs to the Yugoslav Left, a
hard-line Communist party headed by Milosevic's wife. They smashed
windows in the house and destroyed its front gate, a police
official there said by phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Milosevic is in trouble in Leskovac, then he is really in
trouble,'' said Aleksa Djilas, a historian and political analyst in
Belgrade who is not affiliated with the opposition groups trying to
force the Yugoslav leader from office. ``It is like a Kennedy being
in trouble in Boston. This is the beginning of the end. I don't
know when the end will happen, but it will be months, not years.''
</P>
<P>
   The muscular involvement of Yugoslav army reservists in
demonstrations in Leskovac is a wild-card element which, if
repeated in towns and cities across Serbia, could tip the scales
against Milosevic much more quickly than opposition leaders had
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of the Kosovo war in early June, hundreds of
reservists have intermittently blocked roads and bridges in central
and southern Serbia, demanding pay for their service during the
11-week war in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The survival skills of Milosevic, who has been indicted on war
crimes charges, should not be underestimated. Although he has lost
four wars this decade while presiding over the implosion of the
economy, he remains a shrewd politician. He has weathered eruptions
of mass unhappiness in Serbia before, most recently in the winter
of 1996-97, when three months of daily demonstrations all but
paralyzed Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The two major tools in his survival kit are an enormous state
police apparatus, which is still believed to be loyal, and state
television, which is the primary source of information for most of
the country.
</P>
<P>
   There is a consensus among opposition leaders that Milosevic
cannot afford politically to use the police to arrest, injure or
kill large numbers of Serbs. As Zoran Djindjic, a key opposition
leader, said in a rally on Tuesday night in the southwest Serbian
town of Uzice, ``If there are a lot of us, they will not use
force.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they expect Milosevic to do what he has done in the
past, deploy his police and his large party apparatus to harass,
intimidate and try to buy off the opposition. For instance, to
disrupt an opposition rally planned for Thursday night in the
southern Serbian town of Prokuplje, Milosevic's Socialist Party has
called its own rally at the same place and time. He tried the same
tactic two years ago in Belgrade, without much success in igniting
street violence.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves television, which is doing what it has done so
effectively throughout Milosevic's 12 years in power. It ignores or
distorts all the news that is bad for Milosevic and his family,
while vilifying their rivals and critics as corrupt, anti-Serbian
traitors. There has been almost no TV coverage, for instance, of
this week's trouble in Leskovac or of three large opposition
rallies in Serbia in the past week.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As they have been for years, opposition leaders in Serbia are
divided about how best to plug into popular discontent, which is
rooted both in anger about the lost war in Kosovo and fear of the
collapsing economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian Renewal Movement, led by the charismatic Vuk
Draskovic, had insisted since the war in Kosovo ended that the time
was not right for street demonstrations. Draskovic, as recently as
Monday, told a news conference that he is a ``legalist'' who wants
to press for reform from within the system.
</P>
<P>
   The stunning news from Leskovac, which is controlled by
Milosevic's Socialists but where the Serbian Renewal Movement is
the main opposition group, appears to have forced the hand of
Draskovic. His party announced Wednesday that it will take charge
of a rally in Leskovac on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   A senior adviser in the party, Ognjen Privbicevic, offered this
explanation for Draskovic's sudden and seemingly opportunistic
change of strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vuk has such a good nose for these things,'' said Privbicevic.
``Things are changing so quickly here. Nothing is predictable. This
is the first rule.''
</P>
<P>
   Milan Bozic, the deputy mayor of Belgrade and a top leader in
the Serbian Renewal Movement, said that all political parties in
Serbia have underestimated both the depth of popular anti-Milosevic
feeling and its power to bring people to the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of sudden, it looks as though frustration over Milosevic
is much more deeply embedded into the national consciousness than
we expected,'' Bozic said.
</P>
<P>
   Djindjic, a key leader of the Alliance for Change, a coalition
of opposition groups, and a rival of Draskovic, delivered a
rousing, if vague, speech on Tuesday that envisioned simultaneous
daily rallies in towns across the country as well as a general
strike.
</P>
<P>
   Djindjic said he expects the Serbian Orthodox Church, which last
month demanded that Milosevic resign and which has since been
bitterly condemned on state television, will soon join the
opposition and ring church bells across the country to call Serbs
out on the nationwide general strike.
</P>
<P>
   The timing and the planning for that strike are not yet clear,
according to Milan Protic, also a leader of the Alliance for
Change. He said the opposition movement has not yet sat down with
church leaders to ask for their help.
</P>
<P>
   The Milosevic regime appears to fear the involvement of the
church in politics. Politika, its main newspaper, Wednesday
published an angry commentary that condemned church leaders for
making peace in Kosovo with ``terrorist'' Albanian leaders and
warned the church to avoid the ``murky waters'' of politics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
