<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2194 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZMAGS08-COX     07-07 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech firms crash Business Week list
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Internet has scrambled the ranking of the world's
biggest corporations, bringing to the top of the list companies
that just a few years ago barely showed up, Business Week (July 12)
says in its annual Global 1,000 report.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ego, Japanese banks, a Swiss confectioner and a
Philadelphia utility were vastly more popular with investors than
Microsoft. With a market value (share price times shares
outstanding) of $3.3 billion, the software company ranked 539th on
the 1989 list.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, after riding the personal-computer wave right into the
Internet boom, Microsoft has vaulted to No. 1,'' with a market cap
of $407.22 billion. Three other high-tech companies are in the top
10.
</P>
<P>
   After Microsoft, the world's 10 biggest companies ranked by
market value are General Electric, IBM, Exxon, Royal Dutch/Shell,
Wal-Mart Stores, AT&AMP;T, Intel, Cisco Systems and BP Amoco.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia companies in the top 100 are Coca-Cola, 11th; BellSouth,
36th; and Home Depot, 41st.
</P>
<P>
   Women still trail in earnings
</P>
<P>
   Despite three decades of political promises and efforts to
create better anti-discrimination laws, the wage gap between men
and women has narrowed only 15 cents, Working Woman (August) says
in its 20th annual salary survey.
</P>
<P>
   Women now earn 74 cents to every $1 earned by men, up from 59
cents in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are just beginning to gain ground in many male-dominated
career fields, such as science, management, sports and the clergy,
but still earn significantly less than men in fields traditionally
dominated by women, such as nursing and secretarial work,'' the
magazine reports.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a November survey of Fortune 500 companies, the
magazine found:
</P>
<P>
   _ Female media directors in advertising made 90 percent of what
men make in comparable jobs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Women physicists and astronomers made 75 percent of male
salaries.
</P>
<P>
   _ Men in computer jobs make 15 percent more than women in the
same jobs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Female surgeons earned 77 percent of what male general
surgeons make.
</P>
<P>
   _ Women lawyers were paid 70 cents for every dollar a firm paid
male lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Bloomberg Personal Finance (July/August) focuses its
semiannual mutual fund edition on high-return funds that offer
``superior investment management,'' but that manage to hold their
costs _ and fees _ down.
</P>
<P>
   _ The presidential election is more than a year away but Fortune
(July 19) says the 2000 campaign is already ``awash in cash.'' The
Republicans have a new $30 million ``soft-money'' fund that should
help Texas Gov. George W. Bush, while Democrat Bill Bradley has
raised enough to keep his bid alive should Vice President Al Gore
stumble, the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
