<HEADLINE>
BABES OR BOOTERS? SOCCER TEAM DIVIDED ON THE DIRECTION OF THEIR
IMAGE-MAKING 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Each night on his television show, David Letterman
has been showing a picture of the American women's soccer team, in
which the players are standing shoulder to shoulder like beauty
contestants and appear to be wearing nothing more than ``Late
Show'' T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soccer Moms?'' the show's announcer says as a headline flashes
on the screen. ``Soccer Mamas!''
</P>
<P>
   The players sent him the picture and they love the bit.
Letterman has proclaimed himself the team owner and spiritual guru
and has given the American women attention they could never have
expected. But, however funny, the comedy routine speaks to a larger
issue of how the team is being portrayed to the American public as
it prepares to face China on Saturday in the final of the Women's
World Cup at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   To a large extent, the players have been willing participants in
the sexualization of the team in recent years. Mia Hamm has been
named one of People magazine's 50 most beautiful people. Defender
Brandi Chastain has appeared in Gear magazine, crouched behind a
soccer ball, wearing only her cleats and her rippling muscles.
Goalkeeper Briana Scurry streaked naked through a side street in
Athens, Ga., wearing only her gold medal at the 1996 Summer
Olympics. Co-captain Julie Foudy has posed with her husband for
Sports Illustrated's swimsuit issue and has jokingly referred to
the team as ``booters with hooters.''
</P>
<P>
   With their ponytailed-virtuosity, the American players have also
sent a calculated message around the world that women can be both
athletic and feminine in a sport that, in many places, still
carries the stigma that women who play are somehow unwomanly.
</P>
<P>
   Such portrayals have sparked a debate among some team members,
soccer officials and journalists, at the heart of which are two
questions: Have we reached the point where women can show a sexual
side and still be taken seriously as athletes? Or, is it still
necessary to use sex to sell women's sports, soccer in particular,
and does that trivialize the considerable skills of the players?
</P>
<P>
   ``At least people know who we are now,'' said Scurry. ``I don't
think you have to run around naked to sell the game, but it's good
to at least be on the minds of people. I don't think it's
degrading. People who see us on Letterman and come to the game will
realize we don't just strut around in our little skirts. Women play
as hard as anybody.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 1837EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2199 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WOMEN-IMAGE-2NDTA     07-07 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WOMEN-IMAGE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LOS ANGELES: as anybody. '' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The issue of blending athleticism with a sexual presence comes
at an important moment when women's sports are booming at all
levels, and when the women's national team has established itself
at relevant points all over the cultural map.
</P>
<P>
   _ In setting new attendance records for women's sports and
drawing television ratings higher than hockey received during the
Stanley Cup playoffs, the American team has become a marketer's
dream with skilled, college-educated, funny, accessible and
attractive players.
</P>
<P>
   _ As members of the first generation of female athletes to fully
benefit from Title IX, which essentially forbid discrimination on
the basis of gender, they are role models for adolescent girls who
attend matches after appearing to have had their red, white and
blue faces painted by Betsy Ross herself.
</P>
<P>
   _ As wage earners, they underscore the disparity in pay for
women and men that remains an urgent issue in the workplace, and
most recently, cropped up as a contentious element in the Wimbledon
tennis championships. The American women would receive $12,500 for
winning the World Cup, compared with $20,000 the American men
received for simply making the 1998 men's World Cup tournament and
the $388,000 apiece they would have received for winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think about it, the women are being discounted,'' said
Billie Jean King, the tennis great and activist who has become a
confidant of Foudy, the American co-captain.
</P>
<P>
   _ As a homogenous group of mostly white women in ponytails, they
point up the limited progress soccer has made in casting a talent
net that would include more black and Hispanic players. Only two
members of the women's national team are black, the goalkeepers
Scurry and Saskia Webber.
</P>
<P>
   The sexual element of the team's portrayal stems from a sense of
self-assurance and confidence the players possess, Foudy said. No
doubt, the players have been able to pull this off, first and
foremost, because they have been successful, having won the
inaugural Women's World Cup in 1991 and an Olympic gold medal in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're never going to escape sexual references with women,''
Foudy said. ``If we can make sure we're successful on the field, I
think people will come for the product, rather than what the
product looks like.''
</P>
<P>
   However, midfielder Michelle Akers, the first great star of the
U.S. team, said she had some concerns about how the Americans were
being depicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a bit uncomfortable with Brandi's deal,'' Akers said.
``Everybody has to make their own decisions on how they want to be
portrayed. Regardless of that, it has a reflection on us as a team
and women's sports as a whole. You don't want something like that
to detract from the excellence of this team and the message that
we're striving to put out.''
</P>
<P>
   Chastain has said repeatedly that she posed for Gear magazine to
show her body as the instrument of her talent and to send a message
that women athletes can be strong, confident and unashamed of their
physiques. It is a message that some of America's top female track
and field stars are trying to conveying by posing for a nude
calendar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think these women feel strongly about breaking stereotypes
that a female athlete cannot also be an attractive, feminine
woman,'' said Marla Messing, president of the Women's World Cup
organizing committee. ``They are attractive and they're not afraid
to be strong and aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Some women interviewed at matches during the World Cup, however,
said they were concerned about what kind of message this portrays
to young girls who idolize the American players. Gwen Knapp, a
columnist for the San Francisco Examiner who has been critical of
the focus on the players physiques, said she believed the Women's
World Cup is being played ``like the talent competition in the Miss
American pageant, rather than as a sporting event.''
</P>
<P>
   King, who founded the Women's Sports Foundation, said that the
issue of posing for a magazine is a matter of individual choice,
``as long as we don't take away from the reason they're there in
the first place. The most important thing is not to diminish our
skills as athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   While she has occasionally commented during tennis telecasts
about male players being good looking, King said, ``with women it's
always there. We're kind of like sex objects first. That should be
second, third or 10th. I'm not saying it's not part of every human
being, but it shouldn't be emphasized.''
</P>
<P>
   She also said that she was concerned that female athletes feel
pressured to conform to the idealized version of bouncy femininity
represented by the pony-tailed figure that is the official Women's
World Cup logo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sportswriters still ask us about sexuality; they don't ask
men,'' King said. ``We're under a lot more scrutiny. I think it's a
way to keep women powerless, discounted. It has to change. We have
to get on with it. Women still get nervous, feeling they have to
stay feminine.''
</P>
<P>
   There is another vital subtext in play in the portrayal of the
American team _ skin color. ``The question needs to be asked, would
this team be receiving all this attention if they looked like the
Brazilian women's national team _ boyish, wholly unglamorous and
black?'' said David Hirshey, the executive editor of HarperCollins,
which published an instructional book by Hamm called ``Go For the
Goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the rest of the world, where soccer is a city game, in
the United States, women's soccer at the grassroots level is
largely middle class and upper middle class, suburban and largely
white.
</P>
<P>
   The national soccer federation has admitted that it has done an
inadequate job finding more black and Hispanic players, and has
begun a program to build 500 new soccer fields in the next five
years. Scurry, who gives clinics in the inner city, she said she
hopes African-American kids have seen her play this summer and will
be encouraged to give soccer a try.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about giving kids choices,'' Scurry said. ``You've
got to go in the inner city, where the African American and
Hispanic athletes are. You've got to get people out there finding
the talent. Then you'll have a better depiction of the country as a
whole at some point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
