<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZILIAN PRESIDENT HURT BY HIS COALITION'S LACK OF HARMONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ The Brazilian Congress has adjourned
for a midwinter recess, and probably no one is happier than
President Fernando Henrique Cardoso, who has repeatedly seen his
political program and personal prestige sapped by partisan
squabbling among the parties that supposedly support him.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of approving bills, lawmakers have been fighting over
government appointments, grandstanding at hearings and maneuvering
for advantage in next year's municipal elections and the battle to
succeed Cardoso in 2002. As a result, critical legislation needed
to keep Brazil on track for an economic rescue package signed with
the International Monetary Fund late last year are stalled, with
little prospect of passage.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Cardoso's difficulties may stem from the difficulty of
holding together a fractious four-party coalition with no common
ideology. But he has also shown himself reluctant to knock heads
and exert his authority, both his supporters and critics complain,
when nominal allies misbehave or fail to keep promises.
</P>
<P>
   One consequence is that Cardoso's personal popularity is rapidly
eroding. In a recent poll, 51 percent of the respondents described
the president's job performance as ``bad'' or ``terrible,''
compared with only 23 percent who expressed disapproval in
December, a month before he was sworn in for his second term and
Brazil's currency was devalued by 40 percent, setting off the
financial crisis he is now trying to stem.
</P>
<P>
   Columnist Luis Fernando Verissimo wrote satirically in June that
the main problem with Cardoso, a former sociology professor, is the
appearance that ``in power he is acting like an intellectual.''
After five years, he wrote, Cardoso resembles one of those
impractical types ``who end up being manipulated by less
intelligent but more crafty persons, who let the intellectuals make
the speeches while they govern the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Lacking gusto for the political fray, Cardoso has needed to rely
heavily on Antonio Carlos Magalhaes, a 71-year-old senator who has
been an astute player of power and influence for more than 30
years. But the President has paid a high price, ceding Magalhaes
carte blanche to pursue pet peeves and projects that clash with the
government's goals and timetable.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among these has been a parliamentary inquiry into the
corrupt and inefficient Brazilian judiciary. Since the courts are
immensely unpopular and the subject generates headlines, senators
have rallied enthusiastically to it, at the expense of crucial
electoral and tax reform packages that Cardoso has made the
centerpiece of his second term.
</P>
<P>
   ``The investigations have been a considerable distraction, with
a lot of fireworks and more to come,'' said Dr. David Fleischer, a
political analyst and professor at the National University of
Brasilia. ``They are necessary, but the down side is that the
Supreme Court is under heavy fire and striking back'' at a time
when the constitutionality of some of Cardoso's previous economic
reform measures is still in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Brazilian analysts say that both Magalhaes, known sometimes by
his initials ACM, and his rivals have been using the hearings to
position themselves for the next round of elections. Though Cardoso
has three and a half years left to serve in his second term, the
struggle to succeed him is already well under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``ACM's top objective is to stay in the limelight and project
himself nationally,'' said Alexandre Barros, director of an
influential political newsletter and consulting firm in Brasilia.
``He wants to be a candidate for President in 2002, or at least be
the big broker, and so he needs to grow his own strength and
diminish that of others.''
</P>
<P>
   A natural presidential candidate for Cardoso's own Brazilian
Social Democracy Party would be Mario Covas, governor of Sao Paulo,
the country's largest and richest state. But Covas is battling
cancer, and so half a dozen other governors and senators are
jockeying for advantage by putting together their own slates of
candidates in mayoral elections scheduled for next year.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting among pro-government parties has also worsened
longstanding tensions between the two chambers of Congress. That
culminated in a remarkable public exchange of personal insults in
mid-June between Magalhaes and the Speaker of the lower house,
Michel Temer, a member of another party that is also an important
government ally.
</P>
<P>
   Resentful that the lower chamber wanted to move in on his
investigation of the judiciary, Magalhaes said that ``worrying
about moral matters was never Michel Temer's strong point.'' Temer
shot back that ``when it comes to morality, I have Antonio Carlos
beat 10 to nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardoso has sought to end the squabbling, but only belatedly and
halfheartedly. After a five-hour meeting with the President on June
20, his main political operative, Communications Minister Joao
Pimenta da Veiga, announced ``new rules of behavior'' in an attempt
to bring the allied parties into line.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech here a day later, Cardoso said that decisions taken
by his government ``cannot go on being contested by anybody at any
time.'' Since then, he has dismissed the entire board of a
state-owned bank that had gone to court to challenge a financial
transactions tax the president persuaded Congress to pass in
January. There is also widespread speculation that he will announce
a wholesale Cabinet reshuffle during the winter recess.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a coach replace the whole team in the middle
of a game,'' Covas said Tuesday, discounting such reports. But then
he added that once changes in the Cabinet are announced he hopes
``it becomes quite clear that the president is in command of the
government'' since ``I do not know today'' who is running the
government team.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in April, Cardoso described his efforts to
reform the electoral system as essential to the modernization of
Brazilian politics, and expressed confidence his bill to introduce
voting by districts and prevent legislators from changing parties
would be passed during this session. He predicted the changes would
reduce the number of political parties in Brazil from more than 20
to a more manageable ``six or seven'' and make it easier for him
and his successors to govern.
</P>
<P>
   But that seems increasingly unlikely now, as does passage of
legislation that would overhaul the tax system. Because the
Brazilian constitution prohibits changes in the electoral system
during the year before an election, the introduction of voting by
districts would have to be approved and on Cardoso's desk by Sept.
30, and there is ``no way you can do a constitutional amendment in
six weeks,'' Fleischer said flatly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that these are the two issues that most
directly touch the interests of politicians,'' Barros said of the
electoral and tax reforms. ``So there is a very strong element of
`what's in this for me or what do I lose.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
