u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOYOTA-SENIORITY-NYT &LR;      07-07 0359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYOTA-SENIORITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOYOTA AIMS TO ELIMINATE SENIORITY AS A SALARY CRITERIA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Toyota Motor &UR;  &LR; Corp., Japan's largest car maker, is
negotiating with its union to eliminate seniority as a major factor
in determining the salaries of white-collar workers.
</P>
<P>
   If the company is successful, it may influence the pay practices
of companies across Japan, particularly because Hiroshi Okuda,
Toyota's chairman, is also chairman of the Japan Federation of
Employers' Associations.
</P>
<P>
   Japan has been grappling for ways to mobilize its labor force to
help the country climb out of its worst recession since the end of
World War II. Worker productivity has stagnated under a system of
lifetime employment buttressed by wages that rise in lockstep with
tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies, including Toyota, have tied the salaries of top
managers to performance, and a few, like Fujitsu, have abolished
seniority pay, but the system is still largely in place. At the
same time, companies must work harder than ever to retain talented
younger employees, who are increasingly rejecting the security of
lifetime employment with a single company in favor of employment
that offers pay and other rewards based on skills and merit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like the new system to revitalize young, white-collar
employees who have good skills and perform well,'' said Tetsuo
Kitagawa, a spokesman for Toyota.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, which affects about 20,000 of the company's
70,000 white-collar workers, compensation would be partly based on
individual capability, regardless of age or tenure at Toyota.
</P>
<P>
   The union is not likely to oppose Toyota's plans. ``It's better
because it rewards performance while protecting job security,''
Akio Nishida, a spokesman for Toyota's union, was quoted by
Bloomberg News. ``Toyota will protect employment to the greatest
extent possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has assured labor representatives that factors like
expertise and specialization, which in many cases reflect tenure,
will still play a role in determining income for the group in
question, Kitagawa said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 1841EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2205 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-HOLOCAUST-ART     07-07 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-HOLOCAUST-ART-$ADV11-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HOLOCAUST SURVIVOR WHO CAN LET DEATH GO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 11)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By THANE ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Whenever central casting is called on to fill the
role of a Holocaust survivor, rarely does it cast against type.
Indeed, whether onstage or in films, the Holocaust survivor is
often reduced to a one-dimensional cliche, a cartoon of a stock
character that seems to dominate the perceptions of those in the
dramatic arts. Apparently, filmmakers and playwrights like their
Holocaust survivors tortured, tyrannical and delusional _ often all
at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   The cast of film characters in desperate need of a mental health
professional includes Sol Nazerman (Rod Steiger) in ``The
Pawnbroker'' (1965); Arthur Goldman (Maximilian Schell) in ``The
Man in the Glass Booth'' (1975); Peter Helfgott (Armin
Mueller-Stahl) in ``Shine'' (1996), and Isaac Geldhart (Ron Rifkin)
in ``The Substance of Fire'' (1996). (Both ``The Man in the Glass
Booth'' and ``The Substance of Fire'' were originally plays, with
the lead actors reprising their roles in the film versions.)
</P>
<P>
   These are all lifeless men, unfixably broken, unrelievedly angry
and volatile; they are self-pitying, incapable of experiencing love
or generating any emotions other than bitterness, isolation and
rage. Worst of all, in some horrifying act of poetic injustice,
they are presented to the audience as persecutors themselves, men
as sadistic and numb as the Nazis and, for the most part,
completely undeserving of sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, women have not fared much better in this regard.
Henya (Gila Almagor) in ``Summer of Aviya'' (1988) and Masha (Lena
Olin) in ``Enemies, A Love Story'' (1989) _ both films _ and Rosa
Lublin (Dianne Wiest) in the 1996 play ``The Shawl,'' all prove
that there is gender equality in these fictional portraits: men and
women are deemed equally capable of going crazy after Auschwitz.
(As a Polish Catholic in Auschwitz, Sophie Zawistowska, portrayed
by Meryl Streep in ``Sophie's Choice,'' was not, however, marked
for certain death, as she would have been as a Jew.)
</P>
<P>
   But this facile stereotype seems to be gaining more nuance. Two
1998 foreign movies, ``The Truce'' (Italy) and ``Left Luggage'' (a
Dutch director, international cast) have portrayed Holocaust
survivors with greater emotional depth and complexity: capable of
returning to life; functioning, albeit with idiosyncrasy, and not
insane. There is even a tenuous, and somewhat inflated, sense of
optimism in these portraits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Truce,'' as an example, depicts Primo Levi's
life-affirming return to Italy after his liberation from Auschwitz,
though Levi, many years later, ultimately committed suicide. Last
summer, the Gesher theater company in Israel brought ``Adam
Resurrected'' to the Lincoln Center Festival. The play, while
largely set in an insane asylum, still captured not only the
grotesque aspects of what it meant to survive the camps but also
the possibilities of those lives both before the experience and
after.
</P>
<P>
   In a current play in Manhattan, ``The Gathering'' by Arje Shaw,
a Jewish Repertory Theater production at Playhouse 91, Theodore
Bikel stars as Gabe Stern, a Holocaust survivor of distinctive
emotional range. It is 1985 and Gabe, who was interned at Dachau,
is a sculptor living in New York City and working on a bust of
Muhammad Ali. He is also supposed to be preparing his grandson,
Michael, for his bar mitzvah, but instead is making chicken soup
and indulging the boy in a game of chess. Gabe is full of humor; he
is caring and attentive in ways that surpass the fatherly
affections of his own son, Stuart, a Reagan administration
speechwriter. In fact, Gabe even dances through the movements of a
rap routine in honor of Ali, hardly the choreography associated
with the usual canards about survivors.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic tension of the play ensues when Stuart reveals that
a forthcoming visit to West Germany by the President will include,
as a courtesy to the government, a pilgrimage to Bitburg cemetery,
near Dachau. The visit is to honor German soldiers who are buried
there, even though they include some former SS officers. Because
Stuart chooses to ignore the significance of the visit and his
father's indignant reaction to what the older man perceives as a
sacrilege, Gabe takes Michael to Bitburg to protest the Reagan
decision. Michael is about to receive a very different bar mitzvah,
attended by the ghosts of SS monsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gathering'' is unquestionably a play about healing and
redemption. While Gabe, wrapped in a prayer shawl, unpacks some of
the emotional baggage he has carried for so long, he encounters a
young German guard patrolling the cemetery. The two men bitterly
explore some of the larger questions of guilt, responsibility and
memory, and in doing so take some tentative steps toward mutual
understanding. Despite several heated exchanges, it is clear that
Gabe is not a madman, just someone in pain. And the vigil at
Bitburg makes it possible for this sculptor to finally chip away at
the memories that have hardened into stone over years.
</P>
<P>
   In comparing Gabe to the portrait of the Holocaust survivor in
``Shine,'' Bikel noted: ``I'm not saying there are no tyrannical
Jewish fathers, but even they are rooted in some personal grief. In
`Shine,' there was tyranny without the grief.''
</P>
<P>
   So why has it been so difficult for filmmakers and playwrights
to present more complex and varied images of those who endured the
Holocaust? Were the postwar lives of survivors ever as psychically
dire as these artists would have us believe?
</P>
<P>
   ``Holocaust survivors, and their children for that matter, do
not suffer from disproportionately high rates of mental
disorders,'' said Eva Fogelman, a New York psychologist in private
practice who specializes in Holocaust-related trauma. ``In fact,
oddly enough, psychological research suggests the opposite:
Holocaust survivors have experienced less psychosis, suicide,
neurosis, paranoia and schizophrenia than the general population.
Surely these people have been in anguish and mourning, but that
doesn't mean that they couldn't go on to lead functioning, creative
and meaningful lives.''
</P>
<P>
   In a voyeuristic culture that favors the lurid and bizarre, that
truth may not be entertaining enough. Holocaust survivors,
descended from a nightmarish place, have seen too much, and those
searing images have left them forever contaminated with madness.
While they may now live in the world, they can never again be part
of it. That is the central message of earlier dramas that depicted
Holocaust survivors as metaphorically still imprisoned behind
barbed-wire _ whether in caged pawnshops or glass booths.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, artists who sought to tell stories about the
afterlife of genocide have been loath to tinker with the formula.
But while ``The Gathering'' offers a more searching and textured
vision of the survivor, the extent to which it stretches the canvas
of the post-Holocaust universe seems to have come more by way of
accident than artistic design. The playwright, Shaw, was himself a
casualty of the Holocaust. Born in 1941, he hid with his parents in
Tashkent, then part of the Soviet Union, while his paternal
grandparents fell victim to the Nazis in Poland. Yet Shaw did not
set out to write a Holocaust play, he said, but rather one that
explores the relationship between fathers and sons and the ways
that men express themselves through anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to confess that I've seen very little Holocaust art,''
Shaw said. ``I never connected myself to these earlier artistic
representations. The fact that people view this as a Holocaust
drama is ancillary to what I had set out to do, because I had
universal themes in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Bikel and the play's director, Rebecca Taylor, agree that the
aim was not to shatter old stereotypes or conceive new strategies
for depicting what was required to rebuild life after mass death.
``If I had stopped to look at the impact of this play on the
creation of Holocaust art, I would have become too humbled and
humiliated,'' Ms. Taylor said. ``I would have simply gone back to
Indiana.''
</P>
<P>
   And that may be the deepest emotional truth of all. Examining
atrocity with fresh insight is beyond the aspirations of many
artists. Yet inadvertently perhaps, Shaw has demonstrated a
possible shift in the way some Holocaust stories can be told. This
may have more to do with his legacy as the child of a survivor than
any artistic muse, but perhaps that itself is fitting. The
Holocaust as material for the making of art has always presented
Medusa-esque risks: the subject is simply too terrible to confront
directly. Domesticating horror _ making it familiar _ is not for
everyone; human beings often cope better by putting distance
between themselves and what frightens them. Isn't that why some
people go to the theater and movies in the first place: the images
may be disturbing but can ultimately be left there. That is
precisely what audiences have been able to do over the years with
stereotypes of Holocaust survivors. Aliens from Planet Auschwitz
were as unreal as any other close encounter we could imagine.
</P>
<P>
   But wouldn't it be better if we returned home knowing a little
more about the actual lives of those whose experiences have been
fictionalized for our entertainment? Yes, many Holocaust survivors
endured unspeakable horrors. And yes, while their bodies were
liberated, their minds would never know an equivalent freedom. But
these were minds _ without pathology though ruled by memory _ that
were still capable of embracing more. And that is how life,
tentatively and miraculously, can start over.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
