<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV15-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRANDMA'S HOUSE IS A MEMORY MAKER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: W. Va.)   By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The heat index is 105 in the shade, so I'm sitting in a lawn
chair in my grandmother's root cellar, where it's at least 20
degrees cooler.
</P>
<P>
   The Fourth in Ripley, W.Va., this year has been a flop, with
sweltering heat, no rain, brown grass and a series of mishaps. The
annual fireworks tonight might set the town on fire, the way things
are going.
</P>
<P>
   I'm enjoying every minute of it.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, Jim and I swear we won't be coming back to the farm
in the summer anymore. It's too hot, too long a drive over a
holiday weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, each year, we load up the car and make the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Grandma has been dead two years now, and we're renting out the
century-old white farmhouse to my best friend, her husband and
their two young sons.
</P>
<P>
   At first, it was disconcerting to see the changes they've made,
even in the name of progress. The fading wallpaper ripped down and
replaced with drywall. The new carpet in the kitchen, over the top
of the worn linoleum. The mirror missing from the wall beside the
porch door.
</P>
<P>
   But the house also has been shored up, treated for termites,
patched and painted.
</P>
<P>
   All my grandmother's possessions, accumulated over 93 years,
have been sorted and stored or given away. Still, items rise from
the house like excavated treasures.
</P>
<P>
   Just yesterday, I found her school teacher's manual for first to
third grades, with her neat handwriting on the front.
</P>
<P>
   A diary entry was written on the inside back page from March 26,
1930. She may not have known yet that she was nearly two months
pregnant with my mother, her first child. ``The worst day of the
year. Snowing and blowing like 60. Over town and down the road last
night. Mayme, Geneva and I. Sure did hail some on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, 70 years and a season later, we have set the record for the
hottest day, coming full circle.
</P>
<P>
   The kids, sweaty but happy, have indulged in cotton candy and
kiddy rides at the carnival, run barefoot rings around the house,
splashed in well water pumped up from the spring. They've been
chased by a black snake, brought home a box turtle and spied a deer
in the field.
</P>
<P>
   The parents have hit the Cedar Lake Arts and Crafts Fair and the
flea market, buying patchwork pillows, garden candles, Chicago
World's Fair postcards, a fortune teller's teacup from England.
</P>
<P>
   We talk about grandmother, and how she would feel about the
farmhouse now _ happy that children are playing in the side yard,
mad that we rearranged her kitchen counters, perplexed by the
satellite dish propped outside the guest room window.
</P>
<P>
   My fear was that this house would set empty and have to be torn
down, a victim of neglect. Houses, I think, can die of loneliness
just like dogs and people, and I will be forever grateful to my
friends for moving their lives into this one.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that night on the porch swing, I reach out to my
grandmother for her approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you think, Grandma Freda?'' I ask.
</P>
<P>
   Here was her reply: The leaves rustling, the swing's chain
creaking, the cattle lowing and the whippoorwills repeating their
soft eventide song.
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 1846EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
