<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2212 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-OPERA-$ADV11-NY     07-07 1428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-OPERA-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUBLING UP ON STAR POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., July 11)  
(jt) 
 By LAWRENCE A. JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since the dawn of recording, combining two popular opera singers
in an album has often proved a canny business venture. From Caruso
and Farrar to Callas and di Stefano, Pavarotti and Sutherland, and
Alagna and Gheorghiu, record buyers have responded enthusiastically
to the sparks that can ignite when two musical artists with
distinctive voices, personalities and interpretive styles come
together.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in addition, label executives undoubtedly hope that in
generating such sparks, they can steal or at least borrow the fire
of the Three Tenors. Or so it appears from a handful of new CD's
pairing some of the day's most celebrated opera singers in operatic
selections and song.
</P>
<P>
   The release most heavily flogged is ``Cecilia and Bryn,''
featuring, of course, Cecilia Bartoli and Bryn Terfel (Decca/London
289 458 928-2). Highly gifted and intelligent, these singers also
present two of the most ebullient personalities on a musical stage
today, and the temptation to indulge in a tractor pull of musical
charisma was evidently irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   The music, in any case, seems almost ancillary to the
People-magazine-style presentation; only on the back cover does a
potential buyer learn that the repertory consists of selections
from Mozart and bel canto operas. There are no texts or
translations; instead, color photographs show the lovable musical
scamps and Myung-Whun Chung, the conductor, enjoying ice cream
cones and gamboling in Roman piazzas.
</P>
<P>
   Mozart makes up the lion's share of the program, starting with a
kind of suite of Susanna's and Figaro's material from Act I of ``Le
Nozze di Figaro.'' In the theater, Terfel's bluff and characterful
Figaro is a popular commodity, combining refined singing with a
winning stage presence. But here, both artists' big personalities
tend to crowd out Mozart. Terfel's ``Se vuol ballare'' is more
notable for burly vehemence than for elegant vocalism.
</P>
<P>
   Terfel changes caste with characteristic ease, adopting a darker
vocal timbre for the Count's aria. And the Count's Act III duet
with Susanna seems utterly natural in expression. Ms. Bartoli
tosses off ``Un moto di gioia'' with characteristic flair and lilt.
</P>
<P>
   Her achievements in Rossini and bel canto literature are widely
heralded, and her rapid-fire fioritura in the Act I duet from ``Il
Barbiere di Siviglia'' is jaw-dropping in its machine-tooled
accuracy. Terfel is less comfortable in this repertory, yet he
lightens his imposing instrument and sings with agility. Adina and
Dulcamara's duet in Donizetti's ``Elisir d'Amore'' is done with
fine panache.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite the good things here, it all comes back to a marked
surfeit of characterization at the expense of the music. Sudden
drops or swells in dynamics preclude a sustained line, making a
hash of Mozart's vocal writing. After a vibrant recitative, ``Il
core vi dono'' from ``Cosi Fan Tutte'' loses much of its freshness
to nudge-nudge, wink-wink hesitations and elastic legato. You are
unlikely to hear the Papageno-Papagena duet dispatched with greater
fleetness, but whether such an aggressive race serves the music is
another question.
</P>
<P>
   The Orchestra dell'Accademia Nazionale di Santa Cecilia plays
well enough for Chung, but a more dominating podium figure might
have insisted on fuller note values and reined in some of the
vocalists' interpretive excesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star-Crossed Lovers,'' from Placido Domingo and Renee Fleming
(Decca/London 289 460 793-2), offers similarly mixed rewards. The
album stems primarily from a 1998 concert in Chicago, which was
telecast last Valentine's Day on PBS. Ill-fated love may be the
theme, but an ill-fated, populist hodgepodge is what emerges. The
program lurches drunkenly from ``West Side Story'' to Gounod, from
Carlos Gardel and Duke Ellington to Lehar and Verdi.
</P>
<P>
   Although both singers are in excellent voice, in ``Tonight'' and
``Somewhere'' from ``West Side Story'' Ms. Fleming is too operatic
and heavily expressive in manner.
</P>
<P>
   Domingo's timbre possesses an inherent dramatic quality, which
makes him a compelling Otello in a Verdi excerpt but works against
him in lighter settings, his ``Three Tenors'' success
notwithstanding. He clearly loves zarzuela and lighter Spanish
repertory, yet his singing of works like Federico Moreno Torroba's
``Jota Castellana'' sounds weighty and stolid.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fleming's Ellington set seems too great a stylistic stretch
even for this versatile artist. The vocal swellings and dynamic
drops of ``In a Sentimental Mood'' sound practiced and unnatural,
and ``Do Nothin' Till You Hear From Me'' is rather arch.
</P>
<P>
   In love duets from Gounod's ``Faust'' and Verdi's ``Otello,''
both singers are more in their element: Ms. Fleming is girlish and
impetuous as Marguerite and Domingo predictably commanding in his
signature role of Otello. Still, despite solid support from Daniel
Barenboim and the Chicago Symphony Orchestra, this disappointing
disk adds up to less than the sum of its dizzyingly variegated
parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Belleezza Vocale'' features Jennifer Larmore and Hei-Kyung
Hong in a program of duets for mezzo-soprano and soprano (Teldec
3984-22801-2). As the title suggests, the emphasis is on the
lyrical. Ms. Larmore's attractive timbre and Ms. Hong's bright tone
blend gracefully, and indeed, much lovely singing is on display.
</P>
<P>
   Yet enticing as the vocalism is, a feeling of blandness emerges
over the course of the recording. In contrast to Terfel and Ms.
Bartoli, Ms. Larmore and Ms. Hong concentrate on streamlined tonal
beauty and a well-sustained line at the expense of
characterization. Listen to Elisabeth Schwarzkopf and Irmgard
Seefried in this repertory to find the spirited interplay missing
here.
</P>
<P>
   The hushed awe of nature in Delibes' ``Lakme'' is
indistinguishable from Norma and Adalgisa's female bonding in the
Bellini opera; generalized ardor is made to serve for any
quicksilver rush or spark of personality. The two extended dramatic
scenes from Donizetti's ``Anna Bolena'' and Rossini's ``Tancredi,''
clearly meant to provide dramatic ballast, are the least successful
items, lacking fire and intensity.
</P>
<P>
   The evening hymn from Humperdinck's ``Haensel und Gretel'' could
hardly be sung more gorgeously, but anyone looking for more than
surface charm will search in vain. Jesus Lopez-Cobos' dull and
literal conducting of the Munich Radio Orchestra contributes to the
feeling of lethargy.
</P>
<P>
   The disk that provides the most consistent musical rewards is
``No Tenors Allowed,'' featuring Thomas Hampson and Samuel Ramey in
a program of duets for baritone and bass (Teldec 0630-13149-2). The
booklet notes' attempts at whimsy bode ill, proclaiming the merits
of lower voices over those of tenors. ``Basses create a picture of
self-assured masculinity'' the annotator prattles, and baritones
and basses _ presumably unlike those pantywaist tenors _ ``are real
men.'' What might one give to see Ben Heppner drop-kick the
perpetrator of those fatuities?
</P>
<P>
   But the disk itself is largely successful, offering choice
rarities among the few well-known, predominantly dramatic offerings
for baritone and bass. Ramey, divorced on records from his
commanding stage presence, sometimes projects a generalized
vehemence, but here he is more varied in expression. Although
Hampson sounds stretched at the top of his range and
uncharacteristically husky at times, he sings with his customary
intelligence and commitment. The extended heroic scenes from
Bellini's ``Puritani'' and Donizetti's rarely heard ``Marino
Faliero'' come off well.
</P>
<P>
   Both singers are at their finest in the second half of the
program, devoted to Verdi selections. The ``Don Carlos'' and
``Simon Boccanegra'' scenes benefit from their stage experience.
Yet surprisingly, the famous buffa duet of Malatesta and Don
Pasquale in the Donizetti opera turns out to be the highlight of
the disk. Both singers relax into fine buffa style, spinning out
the fioritura with theatrical panache; their delightful performance
is one of the most enjoyable on disk since the classic 1932
rendition by Ernesto Badini and Afro Poli.
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Gomez-Martinez and the Munich Radio Orchestra provide
fine, spirited orchestral support. On the debit side, Teldec
continues its inscrutable policy of supplying texts only in the
original languages, without translations, a self-defeating economy
for a full-price release featuring rare repertory.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
