<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: PEACE TALKS POSTPONED
</P>
<P>
   The start of formal peace talks between the government and the
main left-wing guerrilla group has been postponed for two weeks.
The Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia said some members of
their delegation were unable to reach the site of the talks, but a
joint communique also made it clear the two sides had been unable
to agree on the role to be played by a team of international
monitors.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: TAKING ON THE TRUCKERS
</P>
<P>
   Facing possible food shortages in the nation's cities, the
cabinet met to discuss various options for ending a work action by
thousands of truckers blocking roads to protest a new vehicle tax
intended to raise the salaries of public school teachers. One
option being discussed was to deploy police and military units to
accompany truckers willing to cross roadblocks that have been set
up in at least five provinces.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: POLITICAL SPENDING LIMITS
</P>
<P>
   The governing party set a $5.8 million spending limit for each
of the four party leaders campaigning for its presidential
nomination but also announced it will not try to punish those who
spend more. The party has scheduled its first primary for Nov. 7.
Mexican campaign finance laws place no restrictions on fund-raising
by the seven politicians seeking the presidency until they register
officially next January as major party candidates.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: OPPOSITION PROTESTS VOTE
</P>
<P>
   Opposition parties in the state of Mexico will contest the
results of the election for governor, saying there was widespread
vote-buying and voter coercion. The National Action Party and the
Party of the Democratic Revolution said they would protest through
legal channels on Sunday. The governing Institutional Revolutionary
Party won with 40.7 percent of the vote; National Action was second
with 34.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: BLAIR CANCELS POLAND TRIP
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair canceled a visit to Poland next week
so that he can hold more talks on trying to resolve a stalemate
blocking the scheduled July 15 start of the new Northern Ireland
government in Belfast. Blair hopes to persuade Protestant
politicians to drop their objection to letting Sinn Fein take its
Cabinet seats before the IRA begins disarming.
</P>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS
</P>
<P>
   TEAM LEAVING FOR IRAQ
</P>
<P>
   The secretary-general's office said a five-member team of
disarmament experts from Poland, South Africa, Russia, China and
Germany would leave for Iraq on Thursday to help the United Nations
evaluate and dismantle its laboratory in Baghdad. Yielding to
Iraq's demands, the United Nations chose experts who have never
worked for the special commission charged with disarming Iraq of
weapons of mass destruction. Commission inspectors left tiny
amounts of potentially dangerous agents in the lab when they left
in December.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
