<SLUG> BC-NY-HILLARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON `LISTENING TOUR' HITS UPSTATE NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ONEONTA, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton took to the road
Wednesday with the confidence and ease of a fulltime campaigner,
stepping out of her motorcade to shake hands with well-wishers,
smiling to reporters, even admitting that her critics raise a
``legitimate question'' when they call her a ``carpetbagger.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton began the first of a four-day ``listening tour''
across predominantly Republican upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   The morning began with a picture-perfect scene: Senator Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, who is retiring from the seat that Mrs. Clinton
wants to win, endorsed the first lady as the two stood outside his
farmhouse in the hamlet of Pindar's Corners.
</P>
<P>
   After their remarks to a few dozen neighbors, 31 TV cameras and
about 200 reporters, the two walked off together to the house,
flanked by schoolchildren, the rolling hills in the background. It
was a lovely scene, but also, perhaps, the perfect opening frame
for a campaign commercial: a portrait of the torch being passed.
</P>
<P>
   Before that picturesque exit scene, Mrs. Clinton took on her
opponents' most persistent, and, according to opinion polls, most
resonant, line of attack: that she has never lived or worked in New
York and, therefore, should not be New York's senator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I suppose the question on everybody's mind,'' she said,
``is, why the Senate and why New York and why me?
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is that I care deeply about the issues that are
important to this state,'' she said, adding her hope that, with
time, New Yorkers will come to agree that ``what I am for is maybe
as important, if not more important, than where I am from.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a line that would be repeated and underscored, by Mrs.
Clinton and her aides throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   She also said the idea of running for Senate had seemed like ``a
strange idea'' at the outset to her. But the more people talked to
me . . . and the more I really understood about the kinds of issues
that New Yorkers are concerned about, the more I really thought I
maybe could make a contribution. . .
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think I have some real work to do to get out and listen
and learn from the people of New York.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, she spent 90 minutes Wednesday afternoon at the
State University of New York at Oneonta, discussing education with
a roomful of teachers, students and local Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very interested in listening and learning,'' she said,
repeating the mantra of the tour.
</P>
<P>
   She cited figures to show that she had studied up on the economy
of upstate New York. She talked children's health insurance and
remedial education. ``Let's find out what works,'' she said at one
point, ``and if it works, fine; if it doesn't, let's move on to
something else.'' To a professor who proposed government funding
for high-speed Internet wiring, she asked, ``Would you mind writing
me up some of your ideas?''
</P>
<P>
   All day, she revealed an open, gregarious, flexible manner that
clearly defied the icy, removed and dogmatic stereotype that has
often haunted her.
</P>
<P>
   Signs and posters, pro and anti, followed her along the highways
everywhere she went Wednesday, but not in any overwhelming number.
</P>
<P>
   The most heated incident took place when she stopped in for
lunch with the mayor of Oneonta at Brooks House of Bar-B-Q. A
customer yelled out, ``Go home!'' Another customer rejoined, ``You
go home!'' The first yelled back, ``I live here! And I'm not
running for senator!'' The shouting-match spread to a dozen
observers.
</P>
<P>
   When she arrived by plane in Binghamton Wednesday morning, a few
protest signs greeted her, most notably someone holding up a carpet
cut up in the shape of Arkansas. But most of the greeters were
positive, with many cries of ``You go, girl!'' and ``Run, Hillary,
run!'' when she got out of her car just outside the airport and
talked with supporters for over five minutes. She got back in the
car, saying, ``Thank you so much.''
</P>
<P>
   She got out of the car again at a rest stop, on her way to
Moynihan's farm, and talked with more people, mainly well-wishers.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan's endorsement of her was a strong one. ``I'm here to
say,'' he said, by way of introducing her, ``that I hope she will
go all the way. I mean to go all the way with her. I think she's
going to win. I think she's going to be wonderful for New York, and
we'll be proud of our Senator and the nation will notice.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, who insists that she is still just ``exploring''
the possibility of running for the office, faces a very close and
possibly brutal race next year, most likely against the Republican
mayor of New York City, Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Most polls show the two candidates running neck and neck, though
Giuliani leads by significant margins outside New York City, which
may be why Mrs. Clinton visdited the very center of the state.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the college campus, she went on to a computer
center and then to the Baseball Hall of Fame in Cooperstown.
Thursday she moves on to Rome and Utica, then to Albany.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
