<SLUG> BC-MANGOES-3TAKES-W/ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MANGO FOR EVERY MOOD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Photo available on NYT datasbase) 
 
By ANN CRISWELL 
Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can devour a mango plain, juice dripping down into the
kitchen sink, or you can glamorize it and present it at a formal
seven-course banquet. In between lie the many moods of mango.
</P>
<P>
   It's exotic in a spicy chutney, salsa or relish; provocative in
hot sauce.
</P>
<P>
   A tropical drink or ice cream displays its refreshing nature.
</P>
<P>
   It's sociable as an ingredient in a quick bread for brunch, a
sauce for grilled spareribs at a cookout or a shrimp salad for a
ladies' lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoy the mango's sophisticated mood in a sorbet or souffl.
</P>
<P>
   Mangoes have so much in common with peaches that you can
substitute equal amounts in most recipes.
</P>
<P>
   But never judge a mango by its color. It can be ripe when it's
all green, yellow and green, yellow and red, or mottled green,
yellow and red-orange. A newly promoted variety, the Champagne
mango from southern Mexico, is pale golden yellow and smaller than
other varieties (it is also less fibrous and has a smaller seed).
</P>
<P>
   Store at room temperature or in a paper bag to ripen.
Refrigerate only after the mango is ripe. They will keep whole in
the refrigerator four or five days. Peeled, sliced mangoes will
keep three to four days. Mangoes also can be frozen in freezer
containers for as long as a year at 0 degrees or lower.
</P>
<P>
   Trust your nose and hands to pick the best mango. It should have
a lush fragrance and yield to gentle pressure but remain firm. Even
a semifirm or half-ripe mango will emit some fruity perfume. Avoid
mangoes with bruises or soft spots.
</P>
<P>
   Be aware that mangoes are messy. (That's why it's the
prerogative and the pleasure of the cook to finish off the mango
over the sink, to get the last blissful bit of flesh clinging to
the seed.)
</P>
<P>
   Be aware also that mangoes are related to poison sumac, and some
people are allergic to the sap. Usually, even those who are
allergic can eat mangoes if someone else picks and peels them.
</P>
<P>
   A medium mango provides about 135 calories. Mangoes are a good
source of vitamins A and C. They are low in sodium and high in
potassium; each cup has about 12 milligrams sodium and 312
milligrams potassium.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Moroccan Chicken With Mango-Mint Relish &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A finalist in the 50th anniversary National Chicken Cooking
Contest in Dallas in May. It was created by Edwina Gadsby of Great
Falls, Mont.
</P>
<P>
   4 boneless, skinless chicken breast halves &QL; 
2 tablespoons olive oil &QL; 
1 teaspoon each: sesame oil and ground cumin &QL; 
{ teaspoon each, ground: sweet paprika and coriander &QL; 
\ teaspoon ground cinnamon &QL; 
1{ teaspoons minced fresh ginger &QL; 
1 tablespoon each: fresh lemon juice and chopped cilantro leaves
</P>
<P>
   Mango-Mint Relish (recipe follows) &QL; 
Mint sprigs and lemon slices for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Place chicken in shallow glass dish. Heat olive oil and sesame
oil over medium heat in medium nonstick skillet. Add cumin,
paprika, coriander, cinnamon and ginger; cook about 1 minute, until
fragrant. Remove from heat; stir in lemon juice and cilantro. Cool
and pour over chicken, turning to coat.
</P>
<P>
   Cover and refrigerate 20 minutes. In same pan over medium heat,
saut chicken until fork-tender, about 12 minutes, turning to brown
on both sides. Serve topped with Mango-Mint Relish and garnish with
mint sprigs and lemon slices. Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Mango-Mint Relish
</P>
<P>
   1 cup finely diced ripe mango &QL; 
{ cup finely diced red bell pepper &QL;
</P>
<P>
   cup finely diced red onion &QL; 
1 tablespoon finely chopped fresh mint &QL; 
1 jalapeo, seeded and minced &QL; 
{ teaspoon minced fresh ginger &QL; 
2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice &QL; 
1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   In medium bowl, mix mango, bell pepper, onion, mint, jalapeo,
ginger, lemon and oil. Cover and refrigerate until serving time.
</P>
<P>
   Mango Sorbet Sipper
</P>
<P>
   From Cool Cooking For Hot Days, the new Pillsbury Classic
Cookbook available in supermarkets and newsstands for a limited
time ($2.99).
</P>
<P>
   1\ cups mango sorbet (recipe developed with Hagen-Dazs) &QL; 
{ cup each: orange juice and seltzer water
</P>
<P>
   Scoop sorbet into blender container. Add orange juice and water.
Blend on low speed about 20 seconds. Increase speed to medium, and
blend 20 to 30 more seconds or until thoroughly blended. Pour into
tall glass and serve immediately. Makes 1 serving.
</P>
<P>
   Spicy Mango Chutney
</P>
<P>
   From Sam Choy's Island Flavors (Hyperion, $27.95). Choy is one
of Hawaii's master chefs.
</P>
<P>
   2 (1-pound) mangoes &QL; 
2 teaspoons each, peeled, minced: garlic and ginger &QL; 
2 tablespoons cider vinegar &QL; 
{ cup each: packed dark brown sugar and golden raisins
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lime juice &QL; 
2 teaspoons coarse Dijon mustard &QL; 
\ teaspoon salt &QL; 
[ teaspoon hot Asian chili paste, such as sambal oekek (available
at Asian markets) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peel mangoes and dice the flesh into small cubes; set aside.
Simmer garlic, ginger, vinegar and brown sugar over low heat in
small saucepan 10 minutes. Add mangoes, raisins, juice, mustard,
salt and chili paste. Simmer 20 minutes. Refrigerate. This chutney
will keep in the refrigerator as long as 1 week. Makes 2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   Mango Bread
</P>
<P>
   From ``Sam Choy's Island Flavors.'' Choy writes, ``You can make
French toast with it. You can toast it ... You can substitute
mashed banana, grated carrot or diced papaya for mango.''
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour &QL; 
2 teaspoons baking soda &QL; 
1 teaspoon baking powder &QL; 
2 teaspoons ground cinnamon &QL; 
3 eggs, well-beaten &QL; 
} cup canola oil &QL; 
1{ cups sugar &QL; 
2 cups peeled, diced fresh mango &QL; 
{ cup each: raisins, chopped macadamia nuts or walnuts, and grated
coconut &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease and flour 2
(9-by-5-by-3-inch) loaf pans. Sift flour, soda, baking powder and
cinnamon into a small bowl. In large mixing bowl, combine eggs, oil
and sugar. Combine with flour mixture; blend well. Fold in mango,
raisins, macadamias and coconut. Pour into prepared loaf pans. Bake
45 to 60 minutes or until bread is golden brown.
</P>
<P>
   Bread is done when a toothpick inserted in center of loaf comes
out clean. Let loaves cool in the pans 10 to 15 minutes, then
unmold and let cool completely on racks.
</P>
<P>
   Ribs With Thai Mango Sauce
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Great Ribs Book'' by Hugh Carpenter and Teri Sandison
(Ten Speed Press, $14.95).
</P>
<P>
   2 sides spareribs or your favorite ribs &QL; 
2 ripe mangoes &QL; 
\ cup Thai or Vietnamese fish sauce (available at Asian markets) &QL; 
\ cup each: freshly squeezed lime juice and brown sugar &QL; 
2 tablespoons flavorless cooking oil &QL; 
1 tablespoon Asian chili sauce &QL; 
2 tablespoons finely minced ginger &QL; 
3 garlic cloves, finely minced &QL; 
\ cup chopped cilantro sprigs &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Remove membrane from underside of ribs. Place ribs in
rectangular dish or baking pan.
</P>
<P>
   To make the sauce: Peel mangoes, cut flesh away from seed;
discard seed and peel. Place mango flesh in food processor fitted
with a metal blade; pure. You should have 1 cup pure. Transfer pure
to a bowl; combine with fish sauce, juice, sugar, oil, chili sauce,
ginger, garlic and cilantro. Stir well. Makes 1} cups.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Coat ribs evenly on both sides with half the sauce. Marinate
ribs, refrigerated, at least 15 minutes. For more flavor, marinate
as long as 8 hours. Reserve remaining sauce to serve with the ribs.
</P>
<P>
   To grill ribs: If using a gas barbecue, preheat to medium (325
degrees). If using charcoal or wood, prepare a fire. When coals are
covered with ash, push them to outside of grill. Place a pan of
water in the bottom of the grill among the coals and cover the
coals with the cooking grate. Place a rib rack on the grate and add
the ribs (see note).
</P>
<P>
   Cover grill; regulate heat so it remains at medium temperature.
Occasionally during cooking, baste ribs with extra marinade;
discard remaining marinade. Stop 15 minutes before removing ribs
from grill. Grill ribs until the meat begins to shrink from the
ends of the rib bones. Approximate grilling time for spareribs: 1{
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Cut each side of ribs in half, into 3 sections or into
individual ribs. Transfer to heated platter or 4 heated dinner
plates and serve at once, accompanied with reserved sauce, which
has been heated to boiling. Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; As an alternative, brush cooking grate with flavorless
oil; place ribs, meaty side up, in center of grill. Cover grill and
proceed as directed above.
</P>
<P>
   Shrimp Salad With Mango Chutney Dressing
</P>
<P>
   From ``American Favorites'' by Betty Rosbottom (Houghton
Mifflin, new edition, $18).
</P>
<P>
   Mango Chutney Dressing (recipe follows) &QL; 
\ cup chicken broth, plus 2 to 3 tablespoons more if needed &QL; 
4 to 5 large heads Bibb lettuce, cleaned, dried and torn into
bite-size pieces (8 cups) &QL; 
Salt to taste &QL; 
2{ pounds large (21-30 per pound) shelled, deveined cooked shrimp &QL; 
\ cup dried currants for topping &QL; 
{ cup toasted almonds for topping &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prepare Mango Chutney Dressing. Transfer cup dressing to a large
mixing bowl. Whisk in \ cup broth to thin it. Add lettuce and toss
well to coat greens lightly. Add salt.
</P>
<P>
   Divide greens among 8 salad plates. Divide shrimp evenly and
arrange on top of greens. Whisk remaining dressing; if it appears
to be too thick, thin with 2 to 3 tablespoons more broth. Drizzle
dressing over shrimp. Sprinkle each serving with currants and
almonds. Makes 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Mango Chutney Dressing
</P>
<P>
   You can purchase chutney or use the preceding recipe.
</P>
<P>
   1 cup reduced-fat mayonnaise &QL; 
\ cup mango chutney, chutney pieces chopped &QL; 
2 teaspoons curry powder &QL; 
{ teaspoon ground cumin &QL; 
1 teaspoon ground coriander &QL; 
\ teaspoon each: ground cayenne and salt &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Combine mayonnaise, chutney, curry powder, cumin, coriander,
cayenne and salt in a mixing bowl. Stir to blend well. Dressing may
be made a day ahead, covered and refrigerated. Bring to room
temperature 30 minutes before using.
</P>
<P>
   Mango Hot Sauce
</P>
<P>
   From ``Caribbean Light'' by Donna Shields (Doubleday, $25.95).
Made with two staple Caribbean ingredients, mango and Scotch bonnet
pepper, the sauce is slightly sweet because of the mango and
definitely hot because of the pepper. But it isn't a real
blow-your-head-off sauce. Use as an all-purpose condiment, a
dipping sauce for raw oysters, or an add-in for meatloaf, beef stew
or bread stuffing. It makes a perfect hostess gift.
</P>
<P>
   1 cup very ripe, peeled, cubed mango &QL;
</P>
<P>
   cup water &QL; 
2 tablespoons cider vinegar &QL; 
3 garlic cloves, smashed &QL; 
{ Scotch bonnet pepper, finely minced &QL; 
{ teaspoon each: turmeric, ground dry mustard and sugar &QL; 
\ teaspoon salt &QL; 
In a small saucepan, combine mango, water, vinegar, garlic, pepper,
turmeric, dry mustard, sugar and salt. Cover and simmer 30 minutes.
Pour into a food processor or blender; process until smooth and of
pourable consistency. The amount of time will vary based on the
equipment you're using. Cool to room temperature before storing in
a clean, dry bottle or jar with a tight-fitting lid. This will keep
in the refrigerator a few months. Makes 1 cup.
</P>
<P>
   Mango Cream Ice Cream
</P>
<P>
   From ``Ice Cream! The Whole Scoop'' by Gail Damerow (Glenbridge
Publishing, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   1} cups mango pure &QL; 
1 tablespoon fresh lime juice &QL; 
1 cup sugar &QL; 
1} cups sour cream &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blend pure, juice and sugar. Chill. Beat sour cream smooth and
blend in. Freeze in ice cream maker according to manufacturer's
directions. Makes about 1 quart.
</P>
<P>
   Mango Jiffy Jam
</P>
<P>
   From Houston Chronicle files.
</P>
<P>
   3 cups diced ripe mango &QL; 
5 cups sugar &QL; 
2 tablespoons lime juice &QL; 
1 package powdered pectin &QL; 
1 cup water &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Combine mango, sugar and juice in blender or food processor;
pure. Dissolve pectin in water, bring to a boil and boil 1 minute.
Add pectin solution to mango mixture and process thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into sterilized canning jars or suitable containers for
freezing, leaving 1 inch headspace. Cover and let stand at room
temperature 24 to 48 hours or until jam has set. Store in
refrigerator as long as 1 month or in freezer as long as 1 year.
Makes about 3 pints.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
