</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-CANADA-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEGOTIATORS TRYING TO AVERT STRIKE BY AIR CANADA'S FLIGHT
ATTENDANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Note deadline is 12:01 a.m. ET) (DW) 
 By TIMOTHY PRITCHARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The possibility of air travel chaos in Canada loomed
closer Wednesday as negotiators sought to avert a strike threatened
for early Thursday by flight attendants of Air Canada, the nation's
largest airline.
</P>
<P>
   Contract negotiations with the union representing the airline's
5,100 flight attendants were continuing into Wednesday night,
facing the union's 12:01 a.m. deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation industry analysts said they thought Air Canada
would seek to avoid a strike because the airline is barely
profitable and needs to keep flying in its peak season.
</P>
<P>
   But the company still made preparations for a strike, disrupting
the travel plans of thousands of Canadians and foreign visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The airline canceled all ticket sales and freight shipment
orders for the next seven days, promising to resume if the strike
was called off. Many passengers who already had tickets were being
allowed to reschedule or were being shifted to flights on other
airlines, including Air Canada's regional affiliates and its
code-sharing partners in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   But most other airlines are already heavily booked, including
Canadian Airlines International Ltd., the country's second-largest
carrier. Canadian Airlines was planning to add flights on the
important Toronto-Ottawa-Montreal and Toronto-Vancouver routes,
although not into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Air Canada accounts for almost 60 percent of flights within
Canada and a third of air travel by Canadians to the United States
and Europe. It carries 60,000 passengers a day on 675 flights with
a work force of 23,000.
</P>
<P>
   The flight attendants' dispute is the latest in a number of
labor problems at Air Canada. A two-week strike by its 2,100 pilots
last September, and a subsequent seat sale to revive business,
largely explains its $10.9 million loss in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Transport Minister David Collenette said the government
would not intervene to force the flight attendants back to work
because Air Canada is now a private company. The federal government
created the airline and owned it until a privatization program
began in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The flight attendants, members of the Canadian Union of Public
Employees, have been seeking improved pensions and working
conditions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 1900EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
