<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2231 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDER-CONGESTION-HNS     07-07 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-CONGESTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT CITES MOUNTING CONGESTION AT BORDER CROSSINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ Stepped-up searches for drugs and undocumented
immigrants have resulted in congested highways and bridges on the
U.S.-Mexico border, a federal study said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The push to control the 2,000-mile border is challenged by
commercial trade, which has doubled between the two countries since
the North American Free Trade Agreement went into effect in 1994,
according to the General Accounting Office, the investigative arm
of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's report, ``Issues and Challenges Confronting Mexico
and the United States,'' said more than 4 million trucks and 85
million passenger vehicles entered the United States over the
Southwest border in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Processing the high volume of commercial and passenger traffic
while at the same time interdicting contraband and illegal
immigrants has contributed to congestion and air pollution,''
Benjamin Nelson, GAO director of international relations and trade,
contends in the report, which is to be submitted to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Searching vehicles ``has placed pressure on the infrastructure
of local communities along the border,'' Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   As much as 60 percent of the cocaine and 29 percent of the
heroin sold in the United States last year were smuggled across the
border, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   In border cities such as Laredo, a city of more than 160,000
people, it is not unusual for cars to wait more than an hour and
commercial trucks much more as they enter from Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Vale, chairman of the Border Trade Alliance, said free trade
would never reach its potential if action is not taken to ease
congestion at border ports of entry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goals of NAFTA will not be realized if you cannot transfer
goods from buyer to seller in a safe, efficient manner,'' Vale said
from his office in Rio Grande City.
</P>
<P>
   He would like to see more border inspection personnel on duty as
well as a better use of X-ray machines for trucks, drug-sniffing
dogs, computers and other devices.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Customs Service, which works with the Immigration and
Naturalization Service to guard border crossings, declined to
comment on the GAO report until it could be reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Laredo City Councilman Louis Bruni said that while searches have
backed up traffic, he stands behind the efforts of the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is extremely congested bridges, but we do need to
address this drug problem,'' Bruni said.
</P>
<P>
   The number of tractor-trailer rigs passing through Laredo, the
busiest commercial crossing point on the U.S.-Mexico border, almost
tripled to 1.3 million in 1998 from 1995's count, Customs reported.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, South Texas leads the nation in cocaine
seizures at international ports of entry, according to a recent
Customs report.
</P>
<P>
   Since the introduction of NAFTA, Customs has taken limited
strides to expedite border crossings, including the use of giant
X-ray machines which can examine the entire contents of trucks
without unloading a single pallet.
</P>
<P>
   GAO investigators traveled the length of the 2,000-mile border
and visited with U.S. and Mexican officials to evaluate challenges
posed by drugs, illegal immigration, cross-border traffic, health
and the environment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 1913EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0278 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2235 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALZHEIMER-MONITOR-NYT     07-07 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALZHEIMER-MONITOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALZHEIMER MONITORING SYSTEM UNVEILED 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds, see also SCI-ALZHEIMER-VACCINE-NYT)  
(gm) 
 By STEPHEN G. REED   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ More than five years ago, Harry Kuiack's mother
spent time in three facilities for people with Alzheimer's disease.
Kuiack describes them as noisy, confusing places, and they left the
family feeling guilty for putting her there.
</P>
<P>
   So when Kuiack talks about Vigil, a computerized monitoring
system that's meant to protect the privacy of Alzheimer's patients
while keeping track of their movements, he speaks partly from
experience. The Vigil system helps residents retain their dignity,
yet alerts caregivers when they stray from their rooms or get out
of bed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It does not use cameras, bracelets or any other devices for
residents to wear, and doesn't require any form of restraint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tagging is for cattle, sheep and clothing. It's not for human
beings,'' Kuiack said.
</P>
<P>
   The system, which Kuiack helps market in North America, has been
installed at Heritage House in Sarasota, a new Alzheimer's care
facility on the former site of Doctors Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of the 150-bed Heritage House are still being renovated,
but this week it was given the green light to open by government
licensing authorities. It will be the first facility in the United
States to use Vigil.
</P>
<P>
   The system uses a network of motion sensors, computers and
pagers to alert nursing staff to the movements of patients in their
rooms. When patients are out of bed for more than an allotted
amount of time, for example, a staff member is automatically paged.
</P>
<P>
   Vigil can tell when residents go into their bathrooms and
whether they've come out. It can tell when someone has wet the bed.
It can tell if a patient leaves the room _ or if someone enters a
patient's room.
</P>
<P>
   Vigil's developers say the system doesn't violate privacy _ in
fact, it actually helps preserve it. Staff members no longer have
to routinely knock on doors or keep cameras on residents to monitor
movements.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that a resident can be in their room behind a closed
door and still be watched is the true advantage,'' said Dr. Bruce
Robinson, a professor of medicine at the University of South
Florida, which occupies classroom and research space at Heritage
House. ``We'd pretty much given up on that in long-term care.''
</P>
<P>
   Vigil was the brainchild of a nurse in Australia, Tricia
Shields, who asked an Australian computer firm to develop such a
monitoring system. That company, Questek, eventually installed
several of the systems in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Vigil came to North America when a Canadian nurse manager toured
Australian dementia facilities. It has since been installed in one
facility in British Columbia, and has now come to Florida.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 1919EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0279 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2237 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-NYT &LR;      07-07 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE BIG MARKET AVERAGES PUSH TO RECORD CLOSINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The three most popular stock-market averages pushed
to record closings Wednesday despite upward pressure on interest
rates and general disregard for shares of smaller companies, which
fell.
</P>
<P>
   The mixed performance was regarded optimistically by some
analysts, while others contended that competition from the bond
market would prove a drag on stocks in coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given what we had,'' said Larry Wachtel, market analyst at
Prudential Securities, referring to a 700-point rise in the Dow
Jones industrial average from June 24 through Tuesday morning, ``I
think the action is very good.'' He added, ``I think it's a sign of
underlying strength.''
</P>
<P>
   But Steven Goldman, a strategist at Weeden &AMP; Co., fretted about
the persistence of rate pressure as the government auctioned $7
billion of inflation-indexed notes, and corporate issuers readied
other big deals. ``It's hard to be a pounding-the-table bull
here,'' he said, predicting that rates were likely to offset the
cheerful reading expected when the corporate earnings season
reaches full stride next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone talks about how they are going to be terrific,''
Goldman added, ``but that doesn't mean stock prices will do well.''
</P>
<P>
   A few companies, in fact, warned Wednesday of lower profits, and
their shares plunged. Waste Management dropped 19 5/8 to 33 15/16
after trading at a 52-week low of 31 1/16, barely half its May 4
peak of 60. New Era of Networks slid 24 5/8 to 19 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, after Yahoo, a technology bellwether, closed
down 8 1/16 to 167 1/16, the company announced second-quarter
results that beat expectations.
</P>
<P>
   On the strength of a late comeback, the Dow Jones industrial
average advanced 52.24 points, or 47/100ths of 1 percent, to a
record 11,187.36, surpassing Friday's peak. General Electric, which
won a huge jet engine order from Boeing, was the biggest factor,
jumping 4 to 117 15/16. Caterpillar, up 2 13/16 to 62 1/8, and
Allied Signal, up 2 1/8 to 63 7/8, placed second and third.
</P>
<P>
   American Express, down 2 1/2 to 135 3/4, and Alcoa, down 2 3/8
to 61 3/8 after matching but not surpassing profit forecasts, were
the Dow's biggest losers.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500's 7.74-point rise to its record
1395.86 was paced by Microsoft, which climbed 2 3/4 to 92 5/16. A
total of 268 index issues advanced while 203 declined and 29 were
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   The NASDAQ market, which is dominated by high-tech stocks,
gained a modest 23/100ths of 1 percent in rising 6.26 points to its
new high of 2743.04.
</P>
<P>
   But record levels for the three main gauges masked softness
elsewhere. For example, declines outnumbered advancing issues on
the New York Stock Exchange by 1,691 to 1,307, and the Russell 2000
and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 600 each fell by nearly 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Drug, oil, retail and battered gold stocks turned in mixed
performances Wednesday while airlines were mostly higher. Delta
gained 1 15/16 to 62 1/16, AMR 1 5/16 to 72 3/4 and U.S. Airways
7/8 to 46 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   Volume on the Big Board expanded to a still-moderate 776.8
million shares, with 93 issues making new 52-week highs and 55 new
lows.
</P>
<P>
   Major markets in the Far East and Europe eased by about one-half
of 1 percent while prices climbed in Brazil and Mexico by
six-tenths of 1 percent and two-tenths of 1 percent, respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 1923EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2240 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-SENATE-HNS &LR;      07-07 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON STARTS N.Y. CAMPAIGN BY TACKLING CARPETBAGGER
ISSUE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINDARS CORNER, N.Y. _ Commencing her historic Senate campaign,
first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton moved to dampen concerns about
her carpetbagging to New York by saying what she stood for was more
important than where she was from.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton began the day at the farm of retiring Democratic Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan, who told the army of reporters gathered at
his bucolic country home that he hoped the first lady ``would go
all the way. I mean to go all the way with her.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady took a major step toward a precedent-setting
Senate bid Tuesday when she notified the Federal Election
Commission that she was exploring the idea of running for office.
The first White House spouse to seek elective office can now raise
money as a Senate candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Billed as a ``listening tour,'' the trip through the largely
rural, Republican territory was clearly an effort by Clinton, a
Democrat, to bolster support in a region where her out-of-state
status may hurt her.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton quickly moved to address the carpetbagger issue, which
has been repeatedly raised by her likely GOP opponent, New York
City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a fair question, and I fully understand people
raising it,'' said Clinton, an Illinois native who has spent much
of her adult life in Arkansas. ``I think I have some real work to
do to go out and listen and learn from people of New York and
demonstrate that what I am for is maybe as important, if not more
important, than where I am from.''
</P>
<P>
   At her first extended news conference since the idea of her
candidacy was floated, the first lady calmly fielded a host of
questions, ranging from her views on legislation signed by her
husband to her roles in various scandals that have engulfed the
Clinton White House.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady dismissed worries that scandals, such as the
unusual profit she once made in cattle futures, would dog her
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've moved beyond that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady dodged a question about whether her popularity
stemmed from voters' sympathy with her for President Clinton's
affair with a White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   She responded: ``I look forward to meeting with New Yorkers. I
think they will have a lot to tell me.'' And she suggested that
despite her out-of-state status she believed that New Yorkers might
admire her stepping into what will clearly be a challenging
situation.
</P>
<P>
   When one New York City television personality questioned whether
it took a lot of ``chutzpah'' to run for office in the state,
Clinton said: ``I'm told that characteristic is not all bad in
certain parts of New York. I may need a little of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said she did not believe that her role as first
lady would conflict with a Senate race and likened her situation to
a sitting House member or governor running for another office.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady said she would emphasize education, health care,
and economic equity around the state.
</P>
<P>
   Education was the first topic at a listening session held at the
nearby state university in Oneota, where she hosted a panel
discussion on such issues as low teacher pay, the need to provide
Internet access in the schools, and the need for more vocational
education.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans to ``listen'' through Saturday, visiting
Cooperstown, Utica, Syracuse and Albany. These are largely
Republican areas where Democrats must at least make a respectable
showing to win statewide races.
</P>
<P>
   A Quinnipiac College poll last week put Clinton and Giuliani in
a statistical tie, with Clinton at 46 percent and the New York
mayor at 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Quinnipiac poll and others show Clinton beating Giuliani in
his home turf of New York City but losing upstate and in the
suburbs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The first lady's visit in a region largely ignored by national
political figures was clearly a big deal here, even for a visiting
family from Galveston, Texas, who happened to be at a rest stop on
the interstate.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady also happened to take a bathroom break at the
same rest stop as Melinda Filidei and her two young daughters,
Harleigh and Heather McGlinchey.
</P>
<P>
   When Filidei was informed that the first lady was nearby, she
exclaimed: ``Oh my God, no way. That's the first lady who was in
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, the first lady greeted the two girls and told them,
``You've got an H name, and I have an H name.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
