<HEADER>
A2244 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NKOREA-KIM-NYT &LR;      07-07 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NKOREA-KIM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREA'S PRESIDENT AS POPULAR AS EVER _ FIVE YEARS AFTER
DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Flowers are said to be blossoming out of season in North
Korea as nature joins with the Korean people in expressing
admiration for President Kim Il Sung on the fifth anniversary of
his death.
</P>
<P>
   That is the word from North Korean newspapers and radio
broadcasts, which have been going all out to hail the anniversary
of Kim's death on Thursday. The newspapers are using the occasion
to help pass the mantle of authority to his son and successor, Kim
Jong Il.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is Kim Jong Il, identical with Kim Il Sung, who filled an
aching void in the hearts of the people left by the demise of the
president,'' according to an epic poem published in North Korea's
leading newspaper, Rodong Sinmun. ``He is the dear father who
offered the same love and affection to the people in the five years
as the president did.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his death, Kim Il Sung was renamed president last year;
given the circumstances, it is not entirely correct to refer to him
as ``president for life,'' so North Korea calls him ``president''
or ``eternal president.'' Kim, who founded modern North Korea in
the aftermath of World War II, remains the center of a huge
personality cult and his body is preserved in a huge mausoleum.
</P>
<P>
   Growing numbers are visiting the mausoleum to commemorate the
anniversary, the official Korean Central News Agency reported on
Wednesday. ``The visitors pay their deepest respects to the
president and harden their determinations to remain loyal to Kim
Jong Il, true to the behests of the president,'' the agency
declared in its slightly eccentric English.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea's newspapers have also found some space to denounce
``the Japanese government's attempt to imbue its people with
militarism'' and to scold ``the U.S. warmongers'' for ``impudent
interference and blackmail'' for urging North Korea not to test a
ballistic missile.
</P>
<P>
   Yet most pages in North Korea's newspapers have been taken up
with special essays and features and photos about Kim Il Sung, and
publishers have also marked the anniversary of his death by putting
out volumes 12 and 13 of the collection ``Undying Revolutionary
Feats of the Great Leader Comrade Kim Il Sung.'' In addition, the
government just published Volume 26 of Kim's complete works.
</P>
<P>
   The flowers that have blossomed out of season are said to
include white rhododendrons on Mount Paektu, a sacred Korean
mountain, and a pear tree growing beside a structure called Kim Il
Sung's ``Tower of Immortality.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to show that people all over the world are full of
praise for Kim Il Sung and his son, North Korea's press has carried
reports of foreigners chiming in.
</P>
<P>
   The national vice chairman of the Militant Action Party for
Sovereignty of Madagascar recently issued a statement for the fifth
anniversary of Kim's death, the Korean news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   The statement praised Kim Il Sung for defeating ``the U.S.-led
imperialist allied forces'' in the Korean War and concluded, ``His
history as a peerlessly great man, veteran politician and great
military strategist is now being creditably carried forward by the
leader Kim Jong Il.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 1934EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2246 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      07-07 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OPENS SENATE CAMPAIGN BY VOWING NEW HEALTH-CARE FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in ``a'' and ``p'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINDARS CORNERS, N.Y. _ First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton,
embarking on an unprecedented campaign to win election to the U.S.
Senate, vowed Wednesday to try again to overhaul the nation's
troubled health-care system.
</P>
<P>
   The Illinois-born first lady, who cut her political teeth in the
Arkansas gubernatorial and presidential campaigns of Bill Clinton,
used the debut of her own political career to address the
carpetbagger issue of why she was seeking election in New York
state even though she has never lived here.
</P>
<P>
   The answer to that question, she said, is that what she stood
for was more important than where she was from.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton layed out an activist agenda for government action in
areas that she has staked out during her six years as first lady _
health care and children. She promised to help retain young
teachers in classrooms, bolster public education, expand day-care
for children as young as three-years-old and reduce the numbers of
Americans living without health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton started her day with Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan,
D-N.Y., the retiring incumbent she hopes to succeed, at his 19th
century house on the 900-acre Moynihan farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have some real work to do, to get out and listen and
learn from the people of New York and demonstrate that what I'm for
is maybe as important _ if not more important _ than where I'm
from,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She then began a summer-long ``listening tour'' across New York
state, making her first stop at the College of Oneonta in nearby
Oneonta where she promised wide-ranging government action in a
talk-show-style exchange with New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who masterminded the Clinton administration's failed
health care overhaul in 1993, said she would like to try it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is something I'm still very committed to,'' Clinton said.
``We obviously have to rethink it, get everybody around the table,
try to figure out what will work and then come up with some
ideas,'' she said, adding: ``But we're not going in the right
direction in terms of the uninsured. I think as a country we have
to address this or as a country we're going to have to pay more and
more for less and less.''
</P>
<P>
   Her 1993-1994 blueprint was so controversial that it didn't even
get to the floor of the House or Senate even though Democrats were
in control of Congress. The administration's defeat on this
centerpiece program contributed to the GOP takeover of both house
of Congress in 1994 for the first time in 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, the first first lady to ever seek elected office, said
the president had telephoned his support during his visit to an
Indian reservation in Pine Ridge, S.D.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of my husband's great contributions is how he
keeps on going,'' Clinton later said, her only elliptical reference
of the day to the year-long sex and cover-up scandal that imperiled
his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   She conceded that being on her own in a political campaign was a
bit new.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's new to me is being on this side of the microphone and
talking for myself and talking on behalf of what I believe,'' she
said as she prepared to leave Moynihan's farm for her first
face-to-face encounter with New York voters since establishing a
Senate campaign fund raising committee with the Federal Election
Commission on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no illusions that it will not be a very difficult and
challenging race, but that's what should happen in a democracy,''
Mrs. Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two Republicans are jockeying to challenge her _ New York Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani and Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the college building where Clinton discussed educational
concerns for almost two hours, demonstrators held rival placards. A
woman held a sign that read, ``Hillary _ please keep your morals,
politics, and husband out of our neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Right next to her stood another woman with a sign that said:
``Upstate loves Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, dressed in a navy blue pants suit with a light blue
shirt, exhibited flashes of warmth and humor during the day. She
chatted amiably with Elizabeth Scheinman, 5, a resident of Las
Vegas, Nev., who presented Clinton with a half dozen day lilies
that she had picked near Moynihan's farm with her aunt, Irene
Gallaer.
</P>
<P>
   Gallaer shook hands with the first lady and declared: ``The next
senator from New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Beth Kutler, 32, an alumna of nearby Hartwick college who is now
a nurse practitioner, later met Clinton outside a Soccer Hall of
Fame located in Oneonta where the first lady watched six women play
keep away with a soccer ball. Clinton ``seems like a down-to-earth
person'' who ``made us feel comfortable _ like a soccer mom,''
Kutler said.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton's microphone failed at the outset of the talk
show-style event in Oneonta, she asked for an aide to fix it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe someone could come turn me on,'' Clinton quipped to the
delighted laughter of her audience.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton repeatedly underscored her status as merely a possible
candidate visiting New York to ``explore'' a possible campaign for
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Yet she readily voiced sentiments that would be expected of a
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   She replied to a question about ``chutzpah,'' saying: ``I'm told
that characteristic is not all bad in certain parts of New York. I
may need a little of that, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   She vowed as well that if elected, she would ``insure that New
York gets its fair share from Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan, the maverick Democrat elected to the Senate in a
three-way race against two Republicans in 1976, referred to Mrs.
Clinton as ``the candidate,'' adding that he would ``go all the
way'' with Clinton in her Senate bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's going to win; I think it's going to be wonderful
for New York. We'll be proud of our senator and the nation will
notice,'' Moynihan said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart Powell can be reached via E-mail at
stewart(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 1937EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2248 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      07-07 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OPENS SENATE CAMPAIGN BY VOWING NEW HEALTH-CARE FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in ``a'' and ``p'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
