<P>
   ``I have no illusions that it will not be a very difficult and
challenging race, but that's what should happen in a democracy,''
Mrs. Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two Republicans are jockeying to challenge her _ New York Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani and Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the college building where Clinton discussed educational
concerns for almost two hours, demonstrators held rival placards. A
woman held a sign that read, ``Hillary _ please keep your morals,
politics, and husband out of our neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Right next to her stood another woman with a sign that said:
``Upstate loves Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, dressed in a navy blue pants suit with a light blue
shirt, exhibited flashes of warmth and humor during the day. She
chatted amiably with Elizabeth Scheinman, 5, a resident of Las
Vegas, Nev., who presented Clinton with a half dozen day lilies
that she had picked near Moynihan's farm with her aunt, Irene
Gallaer.
</P>
<P>
   Gallaer shook hands with the first lady and declared: ``The next
senator from New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Beth Kutler, 32, an alumna of nearby Hartwick college who is now
a nurse practitioner, later met Clinton outside a Soccer Hall of
Fame located in Oneonta where the first lady watched six women play
keep away with a soccer ball. Clinton ``seems like a down-to-earth
person'' who ``made us feel comfortable _ like a soccer mom,''
Kutler said.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton's microphone failed at the outset of the talk
show-style event in Oneonta, she asked for an aide to fix it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe someone could come turn me on,'' Clinton quipped to the
delighted laughter of her audience.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton repeatedly underscored her status as merely a possible
candidate visiting New York to ``explore'' a possible campaign for
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Yet she readily voiced sentiments that would be expected of a
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   She replied to a question about ``chutzpah,'' saying: ``I'm told
that characteristic is not all bad in certain parts of New York. I
may need a little of that, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   She vowed as well that if elected, she would ``insure that New
York gets its fair share from Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan, the maverick Democrat elected to the Senate in a
three-way race against two Republicans in 1976, referred to Mrs.
Clinton as ``the candidate,'' adding that he would ``go all the
way'' with Clinton in her Senate bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's going to win; I think it's going to be wonderful
for New York. We'll be proud of our senator and the nation will
notice,'' Moynihan said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart Powell can be reached via E-mail at
stewart(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
