<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-NATO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA NAMES NATO AIDE IT HOPES WILL PASS MUSTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Russia has nominated a new military liaison to NATO
and will expand its staff at the alliance's headquarters in
Belgium, patching up problems that arose earlier this year when
NATO rejected an appointee because it believed he was a Russian
spy.
</P>
<P>
   The new Russian official, identified only as a lieutenant
general, now must be approved by the North Atlantic Council in
Brussels before taking his position at the allied military
headquarters in Mons, Belgium, a NATO official said Wednesday,
speaking on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see this nomination as a very positive development because
it reestablishes the relationship between NATO and Russia,'' said
the NATO official.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian officer will operate as a liaison between NATO
officials and Russian troops in Bosnia and in Kosovo, where 2,850
troops will be spread around the province, supported by 750
personnel at the Pristina airport. The troops will be integrated
into the Kosovo peacekeeping force, and as in the Bosnian mission,
will have the right to refuse certain orders if ``they contradict
their national policy,'' said Pentagon spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Russia nominated Major General Roman Alexsandrovich
Yepifinov as the liaison, but he was rejected because NATO
officials believed he was a high-ranking spy. The Globe's account
of the incident in Saturday's editions incorrectly identified the
officer as then-Lieutenant General Victor Zavarzin, based on
erroneous information given by NATO officials.
</P>
<P>
   Zavarzin, accompanied by Yepifinov, led 200 Russian troops into
Kosovo to take over the Pristina airport last month. Zavarzin had
been the top Russian official at NATO's political headquarters in
Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   When Yepifinov was rejected by the North Atlantic Council in
February, Russia pulled its then-liaison, Lieutenant General
Anatoly Krivolapov, and his staff from the Mons office in protest,
nearly a month before NATO strikes began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Russia will put a total of 16 officials at three NATO
military offices, including the Mons headquarters, Bacon said. The
Russians previously had fewer than a half-dozen officials in Mons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 1939EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
