<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2264 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURKEY-TOMB-ART-NYT &LR;      07-07 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-TOMB-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCHAEOLOGISTS PLAN TO OPEN TOMB THAT HAS HELD A KING FOR 2
MILLENNIUMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany, The Netherlands)  (Eds.: `Tomm' in 3rd graf is cq) 
(ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KARADUT, Turkey _ Hidden in a chamber deep inside a mountain in
remote southeastern Turkey, guarded by giant busts of gods and
kings carved more than 20 centuries ago, lies the tomb of an
ancient king that may contain great riches.
</P>
<P>
   The search for this tomb, which has been under way for more than
a century, may be nearing a climax. Over the decades the search has
combined pagan religion with modern science, archaeology with
psychic visions, and slow-moving Turkish bureaucrats with impatient
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not only very important, but also extremely exciting,''
said Tomm Utecht, a German geophysicist who has studied the site
and believes he may have located the burial chamber. ``This complex
has been called the eighth wonder of the world. It's totally
unique. Nowhere else did a king build such an elaborate holy
monument and tomb so high up on a mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very anxious to see what it looks like and what's in
it,'' Utecht said. ``People who know the story better than I do say
it may be comparable to the grave of Tutankhamen.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1920s, the burial chamber of the Egyptian pharaoh
Tutankhamen was found to contain spectacular artifacts. No one can
be sure what awaits in the chamber carved into Mount Nemrut, which
towers above Turkey's Kurdish region 500 miles southeast of Ankara.
But the wonders that have been found on the mountaintop suggest
that it could prove splendid.
</P>
<P>
   The Nemrut monument provides a remarkably rich picture of the
Commagene kingdom, which existed from 162 B.C. to A.D. 72, and of
King Antiochus, who raised it to its greatest heights and built the
monument.
</P>
<P>
   Among the towering artifacts on the mountaintop are two rows of
statues, each nearly 30 feet high and made of six-ton blocks, that
depict Antiochus and the gods he worshiped. Commagene was a border
kingdom between the Roman Empire and Persia, and Antiochus gave
each of his gods both Western and Eastern names, like
Zeus-Oromasdes or Apollo-Mithras.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a series of magnificent reliefs depicting
Antiochus' ancestors and scenes of his shaking hands with gods to
seal the treaty under which he believed he ruled. Behind one set of
reliefs is a long and extraordinarily revealing inscription in
which the King explains his philosophy, sets down rules for
posterity, and appeals for divine protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``After taking over my father's dominion, I announced, in the
piety of my thought, that the kingdom subject to my throne should
be the common dwelling place of all the gods,'' the Greek-language
inscription says in part. ``I have taken forethought to lay the
foundation of this sacred tomb, which is to be indestructible by
the ravages of time, in closest proximity to the heavenly throne.''
</P>
<P>
   The giant heads that lie scattered on top of Mount Nemrut,
having fallen from the statues long ago, were first discovered in
1881. Since then, they have intrigued and perplexed millions of
visitors and generations of scientists. One American archaeologist
became so fascinated by the place that she arranged to have her
ashes scattered here after her death.
</P>
<P>
   ``The full meaning and scope of the sacred monument on Nemrut's
summit is not yet fully understood,'' a Turkish researcher recently
wrote. Another wondered, ``What was the aim behind the creation of
a new religious culture with its own monumental shrines constructed
at unimaginably high costs with masses of people laboring for
decades under the most severe conditions?''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to answer such questions, a Dutch engineer and
architect, Maurice Crijns, has set up a foundation and recruited
private sponsors for a five-year, $4 million project that is to
culminate in opening the tomb. But first, Crijns said, urgent steps
must be taken to preserve exposed parts of the monument, which are
fast deteriorating.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most wondrous panels on the mountaintop depicts a
life-size lion together with stars, planets and a crescent moon.
Astronomers and historians have determined that their configuration
marks the exact moment of King Antiochus' coronation, showing it to
have taken place within 10 minutes of 7:30 p.m. on what would have
been July 14, 109 B.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the oldest horoscope in history,'' Crijns (pronounced
krines) said as he stood before the sandstone panel on a recent
morning. ``When I first came here in 1983, it was in perfect
condition. Now look how it's crumbling. The stars are coming loose.
The lion's rump is gone and so is most of his face. In five years
there will be nothing left.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come up here and have picnics, they make fires, they
even take pieces of the monument home with them as souvenirs.
Everything is unprotected, not just from people but also from the
rain and snow and lightning. They have a treasure here, but they're
letting it disintegrate.''
</P>
<P>
   Crijns, 44, made his first trip to Nemrut when he and his wife,
Olga, were seeking to escape from grief over the death of their
son. At a travel agency in the Netherlands, a poster of one of the
giant Nemrut heads was on display, and his wife was seized by a
need to see it.
</P>
<P>
   At the site, a guide showed Olga Crijns the head and said it
depicted Apollo-Mithras. She immediately replied that it was not
Apollo-Mithras but actually King Antiochus himself. German
archaeologists later confirmed that she was correct.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of clairvoyant trances, Mrs. Crijns has become
convinced that she knew the history of the statue because she had
lived a previous life in the Commagene kingdom. She believes that
in one trance she saw the location of the long-hidden tomb. After
Utecht made his geophysical studies years later, he found that the
location of the tomb ``does not contradict'' what Mrs. Crijns told
him before he began.
</P>
<P>
   Today just three people believe they may know where King
Antiochus built his tomb: Utecht, the scientist; Crijns, the
foundation director, and Mrs. Crijns, the possible psychic. For
now, they aren't telling.
</P>
<P>
   At a ceremony attended by President Suleyman Demirel in March,
the Turkish authorities signed a protocol with Crijns'
International Nemrut Foundation. It should have enabled the
foundation's archaeological team to begin work immediately, but the
matter is tied up in obscure bureaucratic channels, and the culture
ministry has not yet issued necessary permits.
</P>
<P>
   Until it does, no progress is likely to be made toward solving
one of the ancient world's most tantalizing mysteries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
