<HEADER>
A2269 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-STOCKSWAP08-COX     07-07 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-STOCKSWAP08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cox trades AT&AMP;T stock for cable TV properties
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The latest multibillion-dollar purchase by Cox
Communications may signal a winding down of the current round of
consolidation in the cable TV industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based operator announced Wednesday it was trading
$2.8 billion in AT&AMP;T stock for cable systems in the south-central
part of the country. The systems are now owned by that
long-distance carrier.
</P>
<P>
   These systems, adding 495,000 subscribers in Louisiana,
Oklahoma, Texas and Arkansas, fill in a cluster of cable TV systems
Cox Communications has been building in this region.
</P>
<P>
   And with that south-central cluster built, Cox Communications
has probably completed an $8.2 billion buying spree begun in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cox Communications is pretty set now,'' says Spencer Grimes, a
media analyst with New York investment bank Solomon Smith Barney.
``Perhaps they need to make one more deal to get over 6 million
subscribers, but that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   The company, when its latest deals close, will have 5.5 million
subscribers. That's up sharply from the 3.8 million customers the
company had less than three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching the 6 million mark won't be easy for Cox
Communications. Cox Enterprises Inc., owner of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, holds a controlling stake in Cox
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much left to buy,'' says Bruce Leichtman, media
analyst with Boston-based industry consultant the Yankee Group.
``Everything has been pretty much consolidated at the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, AT&AMP;T will have some 17 million subscribers, or a quarter
of the market, when its purchase of MediaOne closes later this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The long-distance carrier has spent $100 million in the past
year to become the largest cable operator, leapfrogging longtime
industry leaders such as Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   In becoming so big so fast, AT&AMP;T has become the industry
bellwether. ``If AT&AMP;T doesn't do well as a cable operator, it will
cast a pall over whole industry,'' says Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   But Grimes adds that, although AT&AMP;T has had trouble with some of
its new systems, it's too early to pass judgment on the company as
a cable operator. ``Wait another year or so,'' he says. ``Then
we'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   What triggered the latest round of industry consolidation was
the high expense of rebuilding cable TV networks to carry digital
signals.
</P>
<P>
   Digital signals, transmitted at lightning-fast speeds through
fiber-optic cable, enable all kinds of new services. Those services
include high-speed access to the Internet, telephone service,
scores of new channels and sharper screen images.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cable operators needed a critical mass of subscribers to
deliver digital services,'' says Leichtman. ``It helps in both
deploying the services and marketing them.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't, however, have to be a behemoth like AT&AMP;T. What counts
is positioning _ that is, having a high number of subscribers
clustered in several key markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're well-positioned,'' says Leichtman, ``you can still
be very successful with 5 million subscribers.''
</P>
<P>
   That, in essence, has been Cox Communications' strategy for
several years.
</P>
<P>
   The first part of the strategy was to ``monetize,'' or sell off
assets not critical to the company's core cable operations.
Wednesday's AT&AMP;T stock swap is an example of that part of its
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a holding company,'' says Cox Communications
President and Chief Executive Jim Robbins, explaining why his
company traded valuable AT&AMP;T stock. ``We're an operating company.''
Cox Communications received the AT&AMP;T stock from the sale of its
stake in Teleport Communications to the long-distance carrier last
July.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications has been an industry leader in rebuilding its
systems to carry digital services. It offers, for example,
telephone service and high-speed Internet access in Orange County
and San Diego in California.
</P>
<P>
   It's used the proceeds from the sale of nonstrategic assets to
expand its cable TV business and build clusters in the Southwest,
the Northeast and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Its two latest purchases have given the company a new cluster,
stretching from Arkansas through Oklahoma and Texas into Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all fits together pretty nicely,'' says Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, AT&AMP;T's plan is to sell cable properties and lower
its market share before it applies to federal regulators for
permission to acquire cable operator MediaOne Group Inc.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T is expected to face a brutal battle before the Justice
Department and Federal Communications Commission over its $60
billion purchase of MediaOne and its 5 million subscribers,
including about 550,000 in Atlanta. Some consumer groups and
competitors oppose the merger, saying AT&AMP;T will become dominant in
both the cable television and cable modem markets.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications closed at $38.43 3/4, up $1.87 1/2, while
AT&AMP;T rose $1.62 1/2 to $58.25.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
