<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2287 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-EAMES-STUDIO-NYT &LR;      07-07 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-EAMES-STUDIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SOUL OF THE EAMES MACHINE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to delete art note; there is no photo with this story)   By JOSEPH GIOVANNINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Fifty years ago on a bluff in Pacific Palisades
overlooking the Pacific, Charles and Ray Eames assembled their
house and companion studio from prefabricated parts ordered off the
shelf. The steel structure, prominently featured in an Eames
exhibition that recently opened at the Library of Congress, was
hailed as the prototype for an industrially produced house that
could yield a humane environment at minimal cost.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the light-filled buildings stand at the side of a meadow
of rye _ quintessential machines in the garden, built to show how
industrialization could economically elevate living standards for
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   The house was heroic in its idealism and global in its
implications, but a big terra-cotta pot brimming with marguerites
at the front door hints at another story. Flowers welcome visitors
today _ as they did when the Eameses lived there. Smaller pots with
scented geraniums, lobelias, cyclamens, fuchsias and Mexican
primroses line the front of the house, where the steel sash windows
meet the gravel. The great house, built as a rigorous thesis with
an ambitious social goal, has a soul.
</P>
<P>
   The potted flowers surrounding the house were largely Ray's
domain; she was ``the esthetic conscience'' of the office of
Charles and Ray Eames, said their former associate Deborah Sussman,
the Los Angeles graphic designer. ``Ray sensed intuitively when art
was present and when it wasn't, and that sense played a huge role
in the Eames world,'' she added. ``Everybody else, including
Charles, knew she knew.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Charles got the lion's share of the credit for the
creative work of the office, it was Ray, working with Charles out
of a bathroom laboratory, who shaped the bewitching pretzels of
plywood _ free-form sculpture molded in compound curves _ that
would lend lilt to their Eames chair. (She died in 1988, 10 years
to the day after her husband.)
</P>
<P>
   Trained as a painter with Hans Hofmann in New York, she had
perfect pitch for color. Like nature, Ray abhorred a vacuum. Over
the years, the clean-lined house on Chautauqua Boulevard acquired
constellations of small things. A miniaturist, she gardened the
interior with spoons, combs, vases and textiles. On her patios, she
cultivated botanical humility, eschewing show-stoppers like orchids
and lilies. She liked the intense orange-red-to-hot-red geranium
flower's relationship to its green leaf. When she plucked dead
leaves, she bowed straight from the waist, looking a little like a
flower, herself. Her eye delighted in a detail like the square cut
of a petal.
</P>
<P>
   On a three-and-a-half-acre lot designed to look untamed, Ray
planted the color. Her garden was pointillistic, composed of
hundreds of dots that added up to the color fields of a painter who
preferred a small canvas. Over the years, with more and more pots,
the patios filled in. What began as a spare carpet of space at the
foot of the house and studio reached what Eames Demetrios, the
Eameses' grandson, calls an ecological ``climax community.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a collection that Tina Beebe, who worked beside Ray for
years as a graphic artist, said ``always harbored little surprises
_ fraises des bois, Oxalis oregona.'' Ms. Beebe, a colorist
associated with Moore Ruble Yudell, an architectural firm in Santa
Monica, has cultivated a garden of Ray's favorites in Malibu, in
remembrance of a woman who would appear at lunches with nosegays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray taught me to love roses _ she gave me my first Belle of
Portugal,'' Ms. Beebe said. ``Ray liked flowers with little white
faces, and singles rather than doubles. She didn't avoid a flower
like tweedia because it was hard to grow. Her garden required a lot
of work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She always traveled with scissors,'' Ms. Beebe continued.
``Ray had an understanding with her neighbor, Mrs. Bailey: any
roses over the fence were fair game.'' She distributed them during
the rest of her day.
</P>
<P>
   She was a modernist with a subversive, almost Victorian,
sensibility. ``She'd give you these tiny, tiny little things
carefully wrapped in wet cotton and wax paper,'' Ms. Sussman said.
``Always this tiny little collage that was beautiful and exquisite,
and meaningful to her and therefore to you. There would be
forget-me-nots. Who has them now? The bouquets were never rigid:
she worked them like a painter, pushing and pulling. Her
understanding was in her cells.''
</P>
<P>
   She arranged the flowers on her tables at home and in the office
in a perfect relationship. ``She had as much depth and intensity of
appreciation for that little petal, the ruffly petal of a rose, as
she did for any designed object,'' said Elaine Sewell Jones, a
fellow at the American Institute of Architecture and a close
friend. ``She loved scented flowers, and whenever we traveled, she
almost always had a bouquet of gardenias or a clutch of lemon
verbena. She often wore a Cecile Bruner rose, with that teeny, tiny
bud.''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Neuhart, who contributed to ``Eames Design: The Work of
the Office of Charles and Ray Eames'' (Abrams, 1989) with her
husband, John Neuhart, and Ray Eames, recalled her work habits.
``The first thing Ray did after breakfast was to gather anything in
bloom, and bring the flowers down to the office in a basket, along
with lunch, and arrange them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Neuhart added: ``The really wild thing was they used to go out
to the west side of the office and picnic on a vacant lot. Charles
and Ray would spread their blanket in all these weeds and debris,
and she'd have a little thing of flowers, and she'd pull up her
dress to sun her legs, and he'd take off his shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Eames recorded the world around him through his camera.
In their film about the house, ``House: After Five Years of
Living'' (1955), flowers fill the house like oxygen. The
photographs _ there are 750,000 Eames stills at the Library of
Congress _ constitute an implicit record of Ray's ecosystem of
flowers approaching their climax state.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers infiltrated the office's projects, too. Ms. Sussman
opened a deck of the Eameses' building cards and discovered one of
Ray's nosegays pictured _ daisies with a bit of a geranium, some
violets and a little begonia _ ``insignificant little things made
art,'' Ms. Sussman said.
</P>
<P>
   Ray's nosegays found their way onto the stock certificates of
Herman Miller, the company that first produced Eames furniture.
Flowers started appearing at Eames exhibitions. ``She bought potted
Easter lilies, and spread them at the base of the panels in the old
IBM galleries on Madison Avenue in New York,'' Neuhart said. ``It
took a certain curse off a temporary exhibition; it relieved the
hard edges.''
</P>
<P>
   Bouquets found their humanistic way into their multiscreen film
``Glimpses of the U.S.A.'' (1959), shown in the Soviet Union at the
exhibition made famous by the Nixon-Khrushchev kitchen debate. ``In
the `U.S.A.' film, they didn't know how to end it,'' said their
grandson. ``Ray suggested an image of forget-me-nots, and they both
knew it was right. And by one of those cosmic flukes, the flowers
had the same name with the same meaning in Russian. So at the end
of the film, the seven images merged into one picture of a bouquet
of forget-me-nots, and everyone in Moscow choked up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sussman noted: ``She made you see things differently by the
way she put things together. Charles would sometimes conceptualize
about whether a color should be bright or subdued, but he was
conservative about color. It was one of her contributions to their
work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
