<SLUG> BC-MA-TOCCO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOCCO PICK IRES EDUCATORS, LABOR LEADERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Education union officials reacted warily Wednesday to
the appointment of Stephen P. Tocco to be chairman of the state's
board of higher education, saying Tocco's lack of relevant
experience makes a mockery of Gov. Paul Cellucci's pledge to be the
``education governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Labor leaders also said Tocco's history of butting heads with
unions and others would only lead to the same hostility that
characterized the state professors' unions relations with former
chairman James F. Carlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stephen Tocco has earned a reputation for himself as a
divisive figure with a long list of enemies. Clearly these are not
the types of characteristics someone holding a high-ranking
position in state government should possess,'' said Robert Haynes,
head of the state's AFL-CIO and a former University of
Massachusetts trustee. ``In addition to all that, he has absolutely
no history or background in education.''
</P>
<P>
   Trained as a pharmacist, Tocco -- who has never worked on
education policy -- will be Cellucci's chief policy maker for
public colleges and universities.
</P>
<P>
   While other labor leaders with the state's professors unions
were less critical than Haynes, they also said they simply didn't
know Tocco as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll give him the benefit of the doubt, but if the
characteristics I hear of him are true, butting heads and being
divisive, I'm not sure we're seeing anything new,'' said Bill
Murphy, president of the Massachusetts State College Association,
which represents the professors union at the bargaining table.
``The thing that we would have looked for was someone who could
have been described as understanding of the culture of higher
education, maybe coming from it somehow. What we have found over
the months in working with Mr. Carlin is a complete lack of
understanding of the culture. It's not something to be run solely
by looking at the bottom line. ... I think someone coming from it
has an understanding of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlin, who had spent nine years on the UMass board of trustees
before becoming chairman, left the post last month after 3 1/2
years and a record of cutting tuitions and raising standards _ as
well as the hackles of the professors unions.
</P>
<P>
   Tocco has a long history with the Weld-Cellucci administration,
having been brought to the campaign by Cellucci in 1991, who first
met him when Tocco was head of Associated Builders &AMP; Contractors.
Weld appointed him as head of the state's port authority in 1993.
Tocco recently became head of ML Strategies, a prominent lobbying,
public relations, and international consulting firm. He was away on
vacation Wednesday and could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Saying he had already signed Tocco's appointment letter,
Cellucci enthused about Tocco Wednesday. His remarks suggested the
governor is more interested in an agent of change than someone who
has explicit education experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted someone ... who could aggressively drive an agenda,''
Cellucci said. ``I think we've done great things in public higher
ed, lowering tuition and fees, increasing standards. I want to see
that continue. I thought we needed a strong leader to see it
through.''
</P>
<P>
   The unpaid position puts Tocco, 52, in charge of board that sets
policy for 29 campuses that includes UMass and the state and
community colleges. The board oversees the work of the chancellor
of higher education in carrying out those policies.
</P>
<P>
   While Cellucci's comments suggest the governor wants Tocco to
move ahead with the policy agenda laid out by Carlin, labor
relations will also, by necessity, be at the top of Tocco's new
to-do list. An extension on the state college professors' contract
expired last week. Negotiations, which Carlin personally conducted,
have been essentially stalemated for several months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see what the governor's interest is in having a battle
with us,'' Murphy said. ``If Tocco proves more of the same, that's
regretful.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cellucci said he thought Tocco could get along with labor,
citing Tocco's government posts and saying, ``In every one of those
positions, he worked well with all constituencies and I expect him
to continue to work well.''
</P>
<P>
   Those unions who have worked with Tocco, however, disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   As head of the building contractors association, Tocco pushed to
roll back prevailing wage laws. As Massport chief, he was accused
of trying to strongarm South Boston into allowing a new football
stadium on port authority-owned land.
</P>
<P>
   Priscilla Lyons, though, head of the higher education division
of the MTA, which counts among its membership 10,000 faculty
members on state campuses, was more willing to give Tocco time to
show he can get along with the unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think historically, the fact that someone doesn't
have experience in education is not per se a problem. We haven't
dealt with him, so we are really waiting and seeing.'' The contract
negotiation, she said, ``is obviously going to be the point at
which we see what we think.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
