<HEADLINE>
PORK GOES ON DIET, REDUCTING FAT CONTENT &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By ANN CRISWELL 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle &HT;    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ In the case of new leaner pork, pigs did fly. About
2,000 prime porkers from East Yorkshire, England, were imported to
the United States in 1991 aboard a specially built Boeing 747.
</P>
<P>
   After years of selective breeding and genetic improvement, the
pigs grew leaner, longer and more muscular. They are the source of
a complete line of fresh pork, more than 30 cuts, that is leaner
and lower in calories, fat and cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   Smithfield's Lean Generation Pork is actually the result of 25
years of selective breeding and research. It is the first fresh
pork to receive HeartCheck Certification by the American Heart
Association. It is designed to please consumers who demand flavor
and tenderness as well as nutrition, and medical experts who insist
on lower fat and less cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you read the recent news that research comparing the
impact of lean red and white meat on blood cholesterol shows that a
diet including 6 ounces of lean red meat consumed five or more days
a week may actually reduce the risk of coronary heart disease. Now
there's a switch.
</P>
<P>
   The studies show that proteins from red or white meat lower bad
cholesterol (LDL) levels and raise good cholesterol (HDL) levels,
according to researchers. The study was conducted at three sites:
Chicago Center for Clinical Research, Johns Hopkins University
Lipid Clinic and the University of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Lean Generation pork is 60 percent leaner than ordinary pork and
meets the AHA guidelines of no more than 5 grams total fat, 2 grams
saturated fat and 95 milligrams cholesterol per serving. Certified
cuts also must not exceed 480 milligrams sodium per serving.
</P>
<P>
   To compare 4-ounce servings of boneless center-cut pork: Lean
Generation provides 130 calories, regular pork 160; LG 26 grams
protein, regular 25 grams; LG 3 grams fat, regular 6 grams; LG 100
milligrams sodium, regular 75 milligrams; LG 1 gram saturated fat,
regular 2 grams; LG 65 milligrams cholesterol, regular 70
milligrams.
</P>
<P>
   But the most important thing about leaner pork to consumers is
that it tastes good and cooks 10 to 15 percent faster than regular
pork, cookbook author Betty Rosbottom said. In Houston recently as
a spokeswoman for Smithfield, she shared a recipe for Southwestern
Pork Tenderloins With Cumin Mayonnaise. Because the pork cooks
quickly, it's great for light summer meals.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find many uses for the spicy mayonnaise; it's so good you
may want to eat it on crackers. The pork adds some substance to
salads, and any leftovers are delicious in second-day sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   You can grill or roast the pork tenderloins and serve them with
other spicy accompaniments, from salsa to cranberry relish.
</P>
<P>
   Smithfield offers a chart of cooking times for roasting,
broiling, grilling or steam-grilling, sauting, stir-frying, pan
broiling, braising and stewing.
</P>
<P>
   For a free collection of summer grilling recipes and menu
suggestions, call 800-799-LEAN (5326).
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
