<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, JULY 8
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-COMPUTER-BRIEFS-NYT (moved on Sunday, June 27)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, June 27,
referred incorrectly to the damage caused by the computer virus
known as Melissa. It cost companies more than $300 million in labor
and lost productivity, according to ICSA.net, a computer security
company; the virus did not destroy data.
</P>
<P>
   BC-HEALTHCARE-KAISER-NYT (moved on Friday, June 18)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, June 18,
about plans by Kaiser Permanente, the health maintenance
organization, to discontinue operations in the Northeast referred
incorrectly to the New Jersey unit of H.I.P. Health Plans of New
York. State officials forced the unit to liquidate. It did not file
for bankruptcy protection.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CRAN-PAINTINGS-NYT (moved on Tuesday, July 6)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, July 6,
about a retrospective of work by the Canadian painter Chris Cran
misstated the ownership of the 49th Parallel, a Manhattan gallery
that showed his work in 1992. The gallery, which has since closed,
was largely subsidized by the Canadian Government. It was not owned
by Jared Sable, Mr. Cran's dealer in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   BC-KEEGAN-HISTORY-NYT (moved on Friday, July 2)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, July 2,
about the military historian John Keegan rendered a word
incorrectly in a quotation from his new book, ``The First World
War.'' He wrote that the war ``destroyed the benevolent and
optimistic culture of the European continent,'' not ``the European
conflict.''
</P>
</TEXT>
