<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-KATZENBERG-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SETTLEMENT CLOSES THE DOOR ON DISNEY'S DIRTY LAUNDRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Walt Disney Co. and Jeffrey Katzenberg, its former
studio chief, announced the settlement Wednesday of a rancorous
lawsuit filed by Katzenberg that had opened a curtain on the lives
of Hollywood moguls whose egos, financial bonanzas and personal
furies are usually kept veiled.
</P>
<P>
   It was an abrupt ending to a three-year legal battle that raised
questions about the leadership and succession problems at Disney
under its chairman, Michael Eisner. And it brought to a close the
glare of publicity that had both distracted and embarrassed two of
the most powerful men in the American entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   The terms of the settlement were not disclosed. In his lawsuit,
Katzenberg initially claimed that Disney owed him at least $250
million in bonuses, but he later raised the figure to $580 million.
Disney had already paid him $117 million.
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment industry lawyers said that Katzenberg could
eventually earn at least $200 million, including what has already
been paid to him. And the settlement might well be far more than
that, they said. But Disney executives, as well as Katzenberg and
his lawyer, Bertram Fields, declined to discuss the financial
details.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm relieved to be able to close this chapter and put it
behind me,'' Katzenberg said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Eisner termed the settlement ``acceptable,'' and said
that ``time has come to put this matter behind us and to focus on
our new business initiatives.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement ended one of the most acrimonious Hollywood
courtroom battles in years, involving combatants who had once been
friends and who together had built the Disney empire. By all
accounts, the reputation of both moguls, as well as their
companies, suffered because of the personal attacks and financial
revelations that marked the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Fields confronted Eisner on the witness stand with
evidence that the Disney chief had once said that he hated
Katzenberg and had disparaged him as a ``little midget'' and ``the
end of my pompom.'' Disney, on the other hand, sought to damage
Katzenberg, and claimed that the live-action films made under his
reign had lost $231 million, a point Katzenberg disputed.
</P>
<P>
   Even more significant, the public wrangling underscored Eisner's
apparent inability to groom an heir. Katzenberg left Disney in 1994
after Eisner, who had undergone heart surgery, declined to name him
Disney's No. 2 to replace Frank Wells, who died in a helicopter
crash.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner, who is 57, named Michael Ovitz, the former Hollywood
agent, as Disney president in late 1995. Katzenberg filed his suit
in April 1996, and Ovitz was ousted in December, walking away with
about $100 million. He recently launched a new talent-management
company.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Ovitz earned so much money _ even though his
tenure was a debacle _ left Katzenberg seething, and intensified
his efforts against Disney. Katzenberg sued Disney in 1996, two
years after he left the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does all this say about succession at Disney?'' asked one
of Hollywood's top lawyers, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
``The fact is, Jeffrey was practically groomed from childhood to
take over and didn't get it. It's like `King Lear.'''
</P>
<P>
   The bickering had become so intense that in the end, it required
two intermediaries who were not directly involved in the dispute to
resolve it. The final agreement was shaped over the July 4 weekend
by David Geffen, Katzenberg's partner at Dreamworks SKG, the movie
studio they founded with Steven Spielberg, and by Stanley Gold, a
long-time Disney board member who is close to Eisner and a longtime
business associate of Roy Disney, the Disney board's vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Geffen and Gold met at the Geffen home in Malibu for less than
an hour on Monday, and spoke numerous times on the phone Tuesday
before reaching the agreement. Geffen declined to discuss details.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the perfect definition of a settlement,'' said Geffen.
``Both parties felt they didn't get what they wanted. Disney paid
more than it wanted and Jeffrey got less than he wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   The payment to Katzenberg is not expected to affect Disney's
earnings. And Wall Street greeted Wednesday's announcement with a
yawn: Disney closed at 28 1/16, up 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   Why Disney settled now was unclear. But several lawyers not
connected to the case speculated that Eisner was seeking to avoid
an appearance next week before the hearing. His first appearance in
May proved a public-relations disaster for the Disney chairman,
especially when he was confronted with the ``midget'' comment.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Eisner and Disney were placed in a difficult legal and
public position as a result of the lawsuit. Katzenberg argued that
Disney had failed to pay him a large bonus that was called for him
in his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bonus plan, Katzenberg was scheduled to get 2 percent
of the profits of movies and television shows created when he was
in charge _ including such megahits as ``The Lion King,'' ``Beauty
and the Beast'' and ``Aladdin,'' as well Broadway and other
theatrical spinoffs, video sales and theme parks and merchandising
using characters from these films.
</P>
<P>
   To keep Katzenberg's bonus as low as possible, Disney was almost
compelled to lowball the amount of money the company would earn.
The agreement reached on Tuesday was calculated using the 2 percent
formula, but the figure awarded to Katzenberg was a fixed sum,
lawyers familiar with the negotiations said.
</P>
<P>
   But the legal battle served as a considerable distraction at the
highest levels of Disney and Dreamworks. ``Jeffrey was so
distracted that it was drawing attention away from Dreamworks,''
said one lawyer who knows Katzenberg. Katzenberg and the top lawyer
at Dreamworks, Helene Hahn, sat sat side-by-side almost daily at
the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time top executives at Disney, such as Louis
Meisinger, the Disney counsel, and Sanford M. Litvack, senior vice
president, were deeply immersed in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good that it's behind the company,'' said Jeffrey
Logsdon, a financial analyst specializing in entertainment at
Siedler Cos. ``Wall Street hates uncertainty. And once the
financial impact is buried somewhere in income statements and
balance sheets it'll be good riddance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been an embarrassing situation to have the personal
side of corporate governance so publicly portrayed,'' Logsdon said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
