u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-HIGHTECH08-COX     07-07 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-HIGHTECH08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush signals intent to compete hard in Iowa straw poll
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush, who has a fortune in
campaign cash, has outbid Steve Forbes, who has a personal fortune,
for a prime piece of political real estate in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   In a clear signal that he thinks the Iowa straw poll is
important and he has a lot of money to pour into it, Bush is
ponying up $43,500 for the best site outside the coliseum where the
Aug. 14 event will be held.
</P>
<P>
   The unsuccessful bids were kept secret, but people involved in
the bidding process said the Forbes campaign also wanted the prime
location but fell about $500 short of Bush's bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never dreamed it would go that high,'' said Ann Dougherty,
spokeswoman for the Iowa GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who was campaigning Wednesday in Utah, bought a
60,000-square-foot site at the door where most of the straw poll
participants will enter the Hilton Coliseum in Ames, Iowa.
Candidates can use the sites any way they choose. Dougherty said
some will offer musical entertainment as well as campaign
materials.
</P>
<P>
   David Beckwith, spokesman for the Bush campaign, said his man
will get his money's worth at the $43,500 site. The cash goes to
the Iowa Republican Party. ``The space is the prime location
outside the voting area,'' Beckwith said. ``It's like an
advertisement at the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' spokeswoman Juleanna Glover Weiss would not confirm that
her candidate wanted the space Bush rented.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very happy with the site we got. Governor Bush is going
to have to garner over 50 percent (of the votes) to justify that
kind of expenditure,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes paid $8,000 for a 44,500-square-foot site acknowledged as
second best.
</P>
<P>
   Monte Shaw, Iowa campaign chairman for Elizabeth Dole (who spent
$5,500 for a site away from the coliseum), was amazed at what Bush
was willing to spend.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a lot of money for renting a piece of grass for a
couple of hours,'' Shaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, Bush announced that Austinite Michael Dell will
serve as chairman of an information technology advisory council for
the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Dell will lead a panel of high-tech industry officials who will
give Bush advice on high-tech issues as well as work to bring other
industry leaders into the Bush column.
</P>
<P>
   Co-chairs selected for the panel are: James Barksdale,
co-founder of Netscape Communications Corp. and current managing
partner of The Barksdale Group; Carol Bartz, chairman and chief
executive officer of Autodesk Inc., a software firm; John Chambers,
president and chief executive officer of Cisco Inc.; Richard Egan,
chairman of EMC Corp.; Thomas Engibous, president and chief
executive officer of Texas Instruments; Robert Herbold, chief
operating officer of Microsoft Corp.; Raymond Lane, president and
chief operating officer of Oracle Corp.; and Steve Papermaster of
Austin, chief executive officer of Agillion and chairman of
Powershift Group.
</P>
<P>
   Bush on Wednesday continued a western swing with a stop in Salt
Lake City. He was joined there by six governors backing his
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is one of us,'' said Utah Gov. Mike Leavitt. ``He
understands water rights, he understands grazing and he understands
timber and agriculture.''
</P>
<P>
   Also standing with Bush were Govs. Bill Owens of Colorado, Dirk
Kempthorne of Idaho, Mark Racicot of Montana, Kenny Guinn of Nevada
and Jim Geringer of Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
