<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-SCHWEPPES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    South Africa would OK a Coke purchase of Schweppes
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Co. will receive regulatory approval in
South Africa if it consummates a deal to buy Cadbury Schweppes'
soft-drink brands in that country.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa's Competition Board said Wednesday it ``has decided
to condone the intended merging of these two interests'' because
the companies do not really compete in that market.
</P>
<P>
   While the regulatory situation appears bright in South Africa,
Coca-Cola has faced some antitrust opposition to its proposed
purchase of Cadbury Schweppes' brands in more than 100 nations.
</P>
<P>
   That particular deal _ which excludes South Africa, the United
States and most of Europe _ is now valued at $1.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In May, it was scaled back from $1.85 billion when 20 European
nations were eliminated because of regulatory concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In South Africa, the companies have had an agreement since the
1960s, permitting Coca-Cola to bottle and distribute Schweppes
products.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has, in consequence, been no effective competition
between Coca-Cola and Schweppes products,'' the Competition Board
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market leader _ Coca-Cola _ determines prices in the
market. ... Manifestly, the competitive situation post-merger will
be identical to the current situation and accordingly there are no
grounds for blocking the intended merger.''
</P>
<P>
   The board said it could reconsider its decision if new
information emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola has a market share of about 83 percent in South
Africa, while Schweppes' share is estimated at about 15 percent.
Pepsico exited the market a few years ago after the collapse of its
bottler.
</P>
<P>
   Not a done deal
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola has not yet finalized a deal in South Africa, which
analysts said could cost about $165 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in discussions with Cadbury Schweppes and its
South African entity regarding the proposed acquisition,''
Coca-Cola spokesman Randal Donaldson said Wednesday. Cadbury owns
55 percent of its South African subsidiary, with local interests
there controlling the remainder.
</P>
<P>
   If successful in South Africa, Coca-Cola would be adding an
estimated 50 million Schweppes cases a year to its system. That
would come on top of the 470 million cases covered by Coca-Cola's
existing deal to buy those brands in 106 other countries.
</P>
<P>
   That deal has met with regulatory resistance in the key markets
of Australia and Mexico. Those two countries alone represent 140
million cases annually, or about 30 percent of the existing deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still pursuing the acquisition in both Australia and
Mexico,'' Donaldson said.
</P>
<P>
   The company expects to close that deal in most of the other
nations later this month or early next month.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, Coca-Cola closed down 62 1/2 cents at $63
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
