<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUTNAM-LEE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTNAM BRINGS IN INVESTING MUSCLE OF FINANCIER LEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HEATHER KAMINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Putnam Investments, in a bold move to distinguish
itself from competing mutual fund companies, said Wednesday it has
teamed up with Boston financier Thomas H. Lee to offer alternative
investments to institutional investors and wealthy individuals who
have accumulated even more wealth in the long-running bull market.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam is the nation's fourth-largest mutual fund manager with
$328 billion under management, but the Boston firm watched its net
sales drop sharply in 1998. Although Putnam said this was not the
reason for the new offering, the fund company hopes the unusual
partnership with one of the country's most successful investors
will help retain its most affluent clients and attract money from
new investors.
</P>
<P>
   And in an era when individual investors are getting into riskier
investments, analysts say Putnam may be attempting to add pizazz _
along with assets _ to an image of being a conservative fund
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Boston-based Thomas H. Lee Co., which buys companies, turns them
around, and resells them in a risky strategy that often brings
extraordinary profits for his clients, is among the country's
best-known private investment firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Times are changing and Putnam realizes they must change with
them,'' said Geoff Bobroff, a financial industry consultant in East
Greenwich, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   The Putnam-Lee agreement is believed to be among the first of
its kind in the mutual fund industry and arose in part from a
30-year business relationship between Lee and Putnam's chief
executive, Lawrence Lasser, who began talking about the unusual
arrangement a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   With the agreement, Lee and Lasser are strengthening their
firms' ties in another way: Putnam has agreed to invest an
undisclosed amount in a minority stake in Thomas H. Lee Co., Lee's
core investment business, which will now be called Thomas H. Lee
Partners.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam's goal in teaming up with Lee, said Steven Spiegel,
Putnam senior managing director, ``is to establish jointly a firm
in alternative investments and equity business that is global in
scope and the largest and best in the investment arena.''
</P>
<P>
   Putnam said its first investment offering under the agreement
would be rolled out by year's end through a newly formed investment
partnership, TH Lee, Putnam Capital. The partnership will be 25
percent owned by Putnam and 75 percent owned by Lee. Lee will lead
the new company as chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Although the specific nature of the investments in the first
fund has not yet been determined, the focus of TH Lee, Putnam
Capital will be equity investments in a range of sophisticated
vehicles from hedge funds and venture capital funds to real estate
and European companies _ with Lee's high-profile name attached to
them.
</P>
<P>
   Although this is Putnam's inaugural run in offering a way for
clients to invest in private equity deals, many asset managers are
now recognizing the need to do so.
</P>
<P>
   For example, AIA Capital Corp., the financial advisory division
of American International Group Inc., and Blackstone Group, a
private US investment bank, recently joined forces to offer a range
of restructuring, acquisition, and financing services in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   And mutual fund companies, such as Alliance Capital Management
and Wellington Management, have added hedge funds to their plate of
offerings in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The Lee-Putnam partnership provides alternative investments
``under one roof,'' Lee and Lasser said in a joint statement.
``This is one of the first major strategic alliances between a
large investment manager and a leader in private equity,'' they
said.
</P>
<P>
   The companies said they would tap Scott Sperling, managing
director of Lee, as president of TH Lee, Putnam Capital.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also has benefits for Lee, the companies said, because
it will help him widen his operation's channels for distribution
and create a more extensive line of products.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have our own business in buyouts and we don't want to
dilute ourselves, but this venture offers other opportunities in
capital options,'' Lee said in a telephone interview Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
