<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAIN-SUMMER-SCHOOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPAIN'S LEADERS TAKE THEIR THEORIES TO SUMMER SCHOOL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN LORENZO DE EL ESCORIAL, Spain _ The Civil Guards in crisp
green uniforms snapped to attention while news photographers and
television cameramen focused on the most glamorous speakers who
were arriving for the first day of university summer school in this
former seat of royalty near Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   The health minister emerged from one dark limousine and the
secretary of state for security from another. The school director,
Dr. Alberto Portera-Sanchez, an American-trained neurologist who is
making his debut as ringmaster at what has become one of Spain's
prime summer diversions, scurried to give each a hero's welcome.
</P>
<P>
   The politicians, intellectuals and scientists here no longer
simply relax on the beach in July or August. They are asked to
speak and to be conspicuous presences at the growing number of
university summer courses across Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Much news in the peak vacation period emanates from the crowded
classrooms, which expect to attract 100,000 students this summer.
The students and the press, looking for an article while the
government and many businesses shift to idle, pore over the latest
theories by Spaniards or notable foreigners, who have included
George Bush and Oliver Stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very Spanish formula,'' said Jose Luis Garcia
Delgado, director of the oldest summer school, the Menendez Pelayo
International University, in Santander. ``We make room for
interlocutors who don't normally speak in an academic setting.''
</P>
<P>
   As school opened, Santander seemed to receive more national news
coverage than its larger rival, the Madrid Complutense University
summer course in El Escorial. Santander's knockout punch was
Spain's two main union leaders, who called for the creation of more
jobs. El Escorial could muster only the health minister to discuss
biomedical research and, in a separate room, the security chief
talking about Spain's thoroughly modern police methods.
</P>
<P>
   Both officials said after class that they speak at the courses
strictly to support higher education, and not to score political
points or make headlines. But the health minister's chief aide,
Cristina Garcia, said of the exposure, ``It all helps.''
</P>
<P>
   The courses used to be confined mainly to the two exclusive
locations, at Santander, in a building that was a royal palace
early in the century, and here in three historic buildings near the
enormous 16th-century monastery and palace 30 miles northwest of
Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   Now a cottage industry of summer courses has emerged. Forty of
the 66 Spanish universities offer a total of hundreds of classes,
and they all vie for the top speakers. The growth of the courses
also illustrates Spain's changing educational landscape. Since
Francisco Franco died in 1975, the number of universities has more
than doubled and the number of students has tripled, to one and a
half million, a third of Spaniards from 18 to 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``The young people asked for _ really demanded _ a university
education,'' said Portera-Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   The students are largely university-age participants, but they
include an increasing number of graduate students and people who
seek refresher courses. Students in degree programs may apply for
credit, but it is not always automatic.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of featuring famous speakers who make headlines arose
gradually at Santander in the transition to democracy after Franco.
By the early '80s, members of the newly elected Socialist
government used the Santander forum for major announcements, and so
many political leaders were on the summer roster that Santander
became known as the ``summer parliament.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the movers and shakers are more widely scattered, but the
concept has become entrenched as even more students attend the
classes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
