A2313 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-STOCKS08-COX     07-07 0371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-STOCKS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cox Communications rises
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cox Communications' deal to swap 50.3 million shares
of AT&AMP;T stock for 495,000 cable television subscribers was received
fairly well by investors, who sent shares of the Atlanta-based
company up 5.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications closed at $38.43 3/4, up $1.87 1/2, on
higher-than-average trading of 1.6 million shares. AT&AMP;T's stock
rose 2.9 percent, closing at $58.25. Cox Enterprises Inc., owner of
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, holds a controlling stake in Cox
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which values the customers at about $4,230 each, tends
to increase the value of other cable companies, said Gary Farber,
an analyst with SG Cowen.
</P>
<P>
   Cablevision Systems rose 62 1/2 cents to close at $71.
</P>
<P>
   Cable television companies are in a period of consolidation,
hoping to gather enough clustered customers to efficiently deploy
advanced telephone, cable television and Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's deal, if approved by regulators, would make
Atlanta-based Cox Communications the nation's fifth largest cable
operator. AT&AMP;T, the largest cable television company, is selling
systems to look less giant when regulators meet to discuss its
pending acquisition of MediaOne Group. Shares of MediaOne, which
serves most of metro Atlanta, rose $1.68 3/4 to $78.62 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Henderson, an analyst with Janco Partners, said the stocks
of cable companies have enjoyed an unprecedented run, climbing more
than 400 percent since early 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The real test for cable television companies will come in the
next 12 months when they begin offering the new, advanced features
to their customers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think in the face of the valuations, which are at all-time
highs, people should use a bit of caution,'' Henderson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The execution and deployment of these services is going to be
a lot more difficult than the market is assuming.''
</P>
<P>
   In the long term, Henderson said he thinks the cable television
companies will be better able to compete than their competitors,
which include phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
