<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE REPUBLICANS SEEK TO CUT TAX RATE ON CAPITAL GAINS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Del., N.J.)  (mk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republicans said Wednesday that they would
seek to cut the top tax rate on long-term capital gains to 15
percent from 20 percent as part of the big tax-cutting bill they
will take up next week in the face of opposition from President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   If enacted, the cut in the capital gains tax rate, which applies
to profits on the sale of stock and other assets held for more than
a year, would give a break to the growing legions of individual
investors. And it could further fuel the long bull market on Wall
Street, where stock prices hit another new high Wednesday. Rep.
Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee, said the capital gains tax cut would help keep the
economy growing by stimulating additional savings and investment.
</P>
<P>
   Archer's capital gains proposal will be one element of an $864
billion, 10-year tax-cutting plan that his committee is scheduled
to vote on next week as the Republican-controlled Congress begins a
politically charged showdown with Clinton over how to allocate
trillions of dollars in projected federal budget surpluses. The
capital gains tax reduction would account for about $50 billion of
the tax cut over a decade, congressional aides said.
</P>
<P>
   The top capital gains rate was last cut, to 20 percent from 28
percent, as part of the 1997 bipartisan tax and budget deal. Last
year, Clinton signed legislation that reduced to one year from 18
months the period that stocks or other assets had to be held to
qualify for the long-term rate.
</P>
<P>
   Prospects for the further cut in capital gains are uncertain.
The administration assailed the plan Wednesday, partly on the
ground that it favors the wealthy, who own the vast majority of
stocks and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Sen. William Roth, R-Del., chairman of the Senate
Finance Committee, is leaning against including a capital gains cut
in the tax bill that he is drafting for the Senate to consider
later this month. Roth favors other proposals to spur savings and
investment, including expanding Individual Retirement Accounts and
the 401(k) retirement savings program.
</P>
<P>
   But both Archer and Roth intend to include in their bills the
first substantial broad-based reduction in personal income taxes
since 1981. Roth appears to be settling on a plan that would
increase the amount of income that would be subject to the lowest
income tax rate of 15 percent. Archer has not divulged his
approach.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has made it clear he will veto any tax cut of the size
and shape that Archer is developing. But he has signaled his
willingness to negotiate, and many Democrats and Republicans
believe there is a good chance that the White House and Congress
will work out a deal on taxes and other budget issues this year, in
large part because the projected surpluses are so great that they
can accommodate both parties' priorities.
</P>
<P>
   While the House is bitterly divided along partisan lines over
taxes, there is considerable support among Democrats in the Senate
for a sizable tax cut this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very large numbers of Democrats and Republicans in
the Senate who want a tax cut and are prepared to meet in the
middle,'' said Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., who has co-sponsored
a bipartisan plan to cut taxes on the middle class.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has invited congressional leaders to meet with him next
week to discuss his proposal for shoring up Medicare, the health
insurance system for the elderly and disabled, and administration
officials said they expect the session to range across the panoply
of budget issues dividing the parties.
</P>
<P>
   After some wrangling among Republicans about how large a tax cut
to pursue this year, Archer agreed at a meeting on Friday with the
speaker of the House, J. Dennis Hastert, to put a price tag of $864
billion on the House's tax-cutting package over the next decade.
The tax cuts would be phased in as the projected surpluses grow,
with $5 billion available for tax cuts next year and $200 billion
over the first five years, Archer said.
</P>
<P>
   The $864 billion figure is an increase from the $778 billion
earmarked by Republicans earlier this year for a tax cut,
reflecting new estimates showing that the budget surplus will be
larger than anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, Roth is likely to limit his tax cut bill to no
more than the original $778 billion to insure that there is money
available for adding prescription drug coverage to Medicare, a goal
shared by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office reported last week that the
surplus over the next decade would be just under $2.9 trillion. Of
that amount, $1.9 trillion would come from the Social Security
system, money that both parties have agreed should go to shoring up
the retirement system and not to tax cuts or general spending.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and Republicans are battling primarily over what to do
with the other $996 billion, which represents a cumulative excess
of general tax revenues for the next 10 years if spending is kept
at current levels (a separate estimate by the White House put the
figure at just over $1 trillion).
</P>
<P>
   While Republicans want to use nearly all of the surplus for tax
cuts, the president has proposed using about $250 billion over 10
years for tax breaks to encourage low- and middle-income families
to save more for retirement. He wants to use most of the rest of
the $1 trillion to help extend Medicare's solvency and to increase
spending on education, child care, health care and the military.
</P>
<P>
   Archer said that if his capital gains tax plan were signed into
law it would apply retroactively to all sales starting July 1 of
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Under Archer's plan, the capital gains tax rate for taxpayers in
the 15 percent income tax bracket _ generally those considered low-
to middle-income _ would decline to 7.5 percent from 10 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
