<SLUG> BC-RUN-MILE-RECORD-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOROCCAN RUNNER SHATTERS WORLD RECORD IN THE MILE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By FRANK LITSKY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once, the mile was the glamour race of track and field, the race
that made international heroes of Glenn Cunningham, Jim Ryun,
Sebastian Coe and Steve Ovett. The most memorable race in history
may have been Roger Bannister's breakthrough in 1954 when he became
the first to run a mile faster than four minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, the slightly shorter 1,500 meters has been
run in most major meets, and the mile has been all but swept aside.
The attraction is still there, however, and Wednesday night the
mile regained the spotlight, at least for the 3 minmutes 43.13
seconds it took Hicham El Guerrouj of Morocco to shatter the world
record.
</P>
<P>
   The performance came during the Golden Gala meet in Rome's
Olympic Stadium. Although the 24-year-old El Guerrouj has lost only
twice in four years, he has not entranced the track and field
public, at least in the United States, like such runners as Michael
Johnson, Marion Jones, Haile Gebrselassie and Maurice Greene.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he will now. El Guerrouj broke the six-year-old world
record of 3:44.39 by Noureddine Morceli of Algeria, set in Rieti,
Italy. Had they run their record races head to head, El Guerrouj
would have beaten Morceli by 10 yards. Had El Guerrouj run his
record race against Bannister's historic time of 3:59.4, he would
have beaten the Englishman by 120 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The race Wednesday gave El Guerrouj's all four world records
outdoors and indoors in the mile and the 1,500 meters. He made it
clear before the race that he wanted this record and said, ``If I'm
helped by the weather conditions and by Roman fans, I can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   On a hot night, the spectators did their part, the Kenyan
pacesetters did theirs and Noah Ngeny of Kenya kept the pressure on
El Guerrouj over the last 200 meters. In paced races, the record
breakers usually finish far ahead, but Ngeny's second-place time of
3:43.40 was the second fastest ever. Rui Silva of Portugal ran
third in 3:50.91 and Andres Diaz of Spain fourth in 3:51.15, also
career bests.
</P>
<P>
   After the race, to wild cheering, El Guerrouj ran a victory lap,
waving a Moroccan flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just very, very happy,'' he said. ``I went so fast past
the clock that I didn't know at first what I had done. I needed to
bring some happiness to my family as my uncle died recently. Rome
is a magic track for me.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   El Guerrouj is 5 feet 9 1/4 inches tall and weighs 128 pounds.
His first big performance came in 1992, a third place in the 5,000
meters in the world junior championships. Since then, he has
concentrated on the mile and the 1,500 meters, which is almost 120
yards shorter than a mile.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, in the same Rome meet, he broke Morceli's
1,500-meter record by running 3:26.00. Conversion tables used by
track and field statisticians equated that time to a 3:42.5 mile.
</P>
<P>
   In a 10-day span in February 1997, over smaller tracks, he set
the existing world indoor records of 3:31.18 for 1,500 meters and
3:48.45 for the mile. He won the world 1,500-meter championship
outdoors in 1997 and indoors in 1995 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, when he won 12 of 13 races at 1,500 meters and the
mile, his only loss came in the Atlanta Olympics, where he fell
just before the start of the last lap and finished 12th. Morceli
won that race, but knew his successor was in place.
</P>
<P>
   The Rome winners Wednesday night included Jones, Greene, Michael
Johnson and Allen Johnson, all from the United States, and Wilson
Kipketer of Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who has not lost at 100, 200 or 400 meters in four years,
won the women's 200 easily in 22.18 seconds. Greene, who set a
world record a month ago of 9.79 seconds for the men's 100 meters,
won the Rome 100 in 9.85 seconds, a time only he and Donovan Bailey
of Canada have ever bettered.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Johnson, who missed the U.S. championships three week
ago with a strained quadriceps muscle, ran his first 200-meter race
in six weeks and won in 19.93 seconds. Allen Johnson beat
countrymen Mark Crear and Larry Wade in the men's 110-meter hurdles
in 13.01 seconds. Kipketer won the men's 800 meters in 1:42.49, the
fastest time in the world this year.
</P>
<P>
   But the star of the night was El Guerrouj, and he said he was
not done. After his race, he suggested he could run faster _ 1,500
meters in 3:24, the mile in 3:41 or 3:42.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
