<SLUG> BC-Y2K-NUCLEAR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS NUCLEAR PLANTS MAKE Y2K SAFETY CORRECTIONS &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By BILL DAWSON 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Texas' two nuclear power plants have finished all
corrective work on the Y2K computer glitch that directly relates to
safety, but some other fixes still need to be made, the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The NRC had set July 1 as a non-mandatory ``readiness target
date'' for nuclear plants to eliminate potential Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   Plants that did not correct all possible problems by that date
had to submit detailed schedules showing how they would complete
their remaining Y2K work.
</P>
<P>
   Utility officials assured the NRC that the work still left at
the two Texas plants will be complete before Jan. 1, 2000, when the
Y2K bug could cause some computerized systems and devices to
misread the date and malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   The two nuclear plants are the South Texas Project near Bay
City, about 90 miles southwest of Houston, and Comanche Peak near
Glen Rose, about 50 miles southwest of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   These Texas facilities are among 27 nuclear power plants across
the country that the NRC said still have some Y2K corrections to
make before Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the remaining work affects the ability of a plant to
shut down safely, if needed,'' the NRC announced, basing that
conclusion on reports from nuclear plant operators.
</P>
<P>
   STP Nuclear Operating Co., which manages the South Texas plant
for its four owners, told the NRC it would finish remaining
Y2K-related work by Oct. 31. The owners are Houston-based Reliant
Energy, Dallas-based CSW Corp. and the cities of Austin and San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The incomplete work at the plant involves two computer
modernization projects that were begun about five years ago for
reasons unrelated to the Y2K glitch, said Mark McBurnett, the
plant's director of quality and licensing and its Y2K project
manager.
</P>
<P>
   One project involves a computer system for inventory and
procurement of parts.
</P>
<P>
   The other is an integrated computer system that will combine
information on plant processes _ things like temperature and power
levels _ in a more convenient form for operators to monitor,
McBurnett said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of TXU Electric and Gas, the Dallas-based owner of the
Comanche Peak plant, told the agency work remains on a system for
training plant operators and on a system that purifies cooling
water at one of the two power-generating units.
</P>
<P>
   Removing impurities from this enclosed cooling system maintains
it at maximum efficiency and prevents problems that might result if
impurities built up over a long period, TXU spokesman Rand LaVonn
said.
</P>
<P>
   This Y2K correction was not made by the NRC's July 1 target date
because TXU officials decided it would be less costly to combine it
with a regularly scheduled refueling operation later this year, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
