<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2327 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-NYT &LR;      07-07 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAKISTAN'S MUSLIM GUERRILLAS VOW TO FIGHT ON IN KASHMIR DEFYING
PRIME MINISTER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CELIA W. DUGGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Three days after Pakistan's prime minister
assured American diplomats that he would seek the withdrawal of
Muslim guerrillas from the Indian-held part of Kashmir, no pullback
has taken place. Pakistan's foreign minister expressed doubts about
whether the government would be able to persuade the men to leave.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of an umbrella organization that represents more than
a dozen of the militant groups that say they are fighting in
Kashmir vowed Wednesday that they would battle on ``until the last
drop of our blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Sayed Saluhuddin, head of the United Jihad Council, said at a
news conference in the Pakistani capital, Islamabad, that Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif's promise to encourage their withdrawal was
``tantamount to stabbing the movement in the back.''
</P>
<P>
   Pakistani opposition political parties, fundamentalist groups
and retired army officials continued to harshly criticize a deal
that they said had undercut militants who were widely regarded in
Pakistan as heroic freedom fighters.
</P>
<P>
   In the battle zone, Indian soldiers continued fighting for
control of treacherous mountain peaks overlooking a strategic
military supply line in Kashmir. Indian officials said, as they
have every day for weeks, that it was not primarily Islamic
militants but Pakistani soldiers who have occupied Indian
territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are simply no indications of a withdrawal,'' said Col.
Bikram Singh, a spokesman for the Indian army. ``The enemy is
giving us stiff resistance.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pakistani army's chief of staff, Gen. Pervez Musharraf, said
Tuesday that he was waiting for the prime minister to return to
Islamabad before making any decisions about a withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif, who has paid calls on President Clinton in Washington
and Prime Minister Tony Blair in London, is expected back in
Pakistan on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   When Sharif met with Clinton, on Sunday, the men signed an
agreement that bound Sharif to take steps to restore what American
officials called the sanctity of the cease-fire line that divides
the Pakistani- and Indian-held portions of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif has not made any public statement about the agreement,
which is already causing him serious political trouble at home. In
a brief conversation with The News, an English-language daily in
Pakistan, the prime minister said nothing about the proposed
withdrawal, but did boast that Pakistan had better missiles than
India.
</P>
<P>
   ``India knows it well that Pakistan will give a befitting reply
if a war is imposed on Pakistan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days Pakistani diplomats have said their government
will fulfill the commitment Sharif made to Clinton by trying to
persuade the men they call Kashmiri freedom fighters to pull back
from the mountains where they are dug in. The government's pitch
will be that the men can leave now because they have achieved their
objective: to put the status of Kashmir back on the international
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kashmir dispute, which has caused two wars between India
and Pakistan, predominantly Hindu India claims the Himalayan
territory as a state, while Pakistan, an Islamic nation, says the
mostly Muslim area should be allowed to decide whether to join
India or Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   For two months India and Pakistan, which became declared nuclear
powers a year ago, have been engaged in heavy fighting, shelling
each other with huge artillery guns across the so-called line of
control that separates their zones of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan has maintained that the forces in the Indian portion
are militants it does not control, while India says they are
Pakistani soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan's foreign minister, Sartaj Aziz, said Wednesday in an
interview with the BBC in London that his government would use its
influence to persuade the mujahedeen, or holy warriors, to withdraw
from the Kargil and Dras sectors of Kashmir, but he said they would
listen only if they believed that Kashmir would be given the right
to join Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Asked directly if Pakistan would succeed in getting the men to
withdraw, Aziz said, ``At the moment we are not sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Aziz's comments, Indian officials accused him of
being misleading. The fighters are Pakistani soldiers who can be
recalled with a simple order, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks Wednesday, India's prime minister, Atal Behari
Vajpayee, was adamant that Kashmir would not be the subject of
negotiations until all Pakistani forces had left Indian territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The objective is one and only one,'' Vajpayee told a
conference of state chief ministers who gathered here today to be
briefed on the Kashmir conflict. ``It is the complete and
unconditional withdrawal of the intruders from our side of the line
of control. There is no other objective and no other subject that
we are discussing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
