<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2328 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-TOBACCO-SUIT-NYT &LR;      07-07 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-TOBACCO-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA JURY RULES AGAINST TOBACCO COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Florida jury Wednesday found against the nation's biggest
tobacco companies in the first class-action case to reach a
verdict, holding that they conspired to hide the danger and
addictiveness of cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   The six-member jury in a Miami state court also said that both
compensatory and punitive damages could be awarded, throwing open
the door to hundreds of thousands of potential claims by current
and former smokers in Florida that could cost the tobacco industry
billions to resolve.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's decision ended the first phase of a complex trial
that has already lasted a year. In the next phases, jurors will
review the cases of smokers and decide whether to award damages.
Claims can be filed on behalf of any Florida resident, living or
dead, who was addicted to cigarettes and suffered certain
smoking-related diseases as determined by jury decision.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier settlements by tobacco producers totaling $246 billion
to resolve lawsuits brought by state attorneys general seeking to
recover health-care costs spent treating smoking-related illnesses
did not bar claims by individual smokers or classes of them.
</P>
<P>
   The industry had initially sought such protections as the price
of settling the state lawsuits but dropped the effort when
anti-smoking groups opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   Court decisions in cases brought by individual smokers have been
mixed recently. But Wednesday's decision follows two large jury
awards against producers in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   In March, an Oregon state jury ordered Philip Morris Cos. to pay
$81 million in compensatory and punitive damage to the family of a
man who smoked Marlboro cigarettes for four decades before he died.
And in February, a California jury ordered Philip Morris to pay
$51.5 million to a woman who said her inoperable lung cancer was
caused by smoking, though the punitive damage part of that award
has since been cut in half.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for both plaintiffs and the tobacco companies involved
in the Florida case were barred by Robert Kaye, the presiding
Circuit Court judge, from commenting on Wednesday's decision. But
producers are expected to challenge the class-action proceeding as
soon as the first award against them is made.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Aronson, the president of Aronson Washington Research,
which follows tobacco litigation for institutional investors, said
that it is highly unusual for any class-action case of the
magnitude of the Florida smoking lawsuit to go to verdict because
of the magnitude of the stakes involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``With several hundreds of thousands of people lining for
claims, this could mean a lot of money,'' said Ms. Aronson. ``It
also could also block the Florida court dockets for many years to
come with smoking claims.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with Philip Morris, the defendants in the Miami case
included R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co., a subsidiary of RJR Nabisco
Holdings; Lorillard Tobacco, a subsidiary of Loews; Liggett Group,
a subsidiary of Brooke Group, and Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco, a
subsidiary of BAT Industries PLC. Two now-defunct trade groups, the
Council for Tobacco Research and the Tobacco Institute, were also
defendants.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida class-action lawsuit was filed in 1994 by Stanley
Rosenblatt, a lawyer in Miami. In 1998, Rosenblatt and and his
wife, Susan, who is also a lawyer, scored a major victory when
tobacco producers agreed to pay $300 million to settle a lawsuit
brought by them on behalf of 60,000 flight attendants who had
claimed injury from secondhand smoke.
</P>
<P>
   The six-member Miami jury, which included one smoker, heard from
more than 80 witnesses. Rosenblatt also presented thousands on
internal industry documents, including many uncovered by lawyers
preparing for Minnesota's lawsuit last year against the industry.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last July, Rosenblatt said that one thrust of
his case would be to show that the tobacco industry had attempted
``through diversionary tactics to keep alive a nonexistent
scientific controversy about smoking and health.''
</P>
<P>
   Though many tobacco industry analysts had expected that the
tobacco industry would lose the Miami trial's first phase,
Wednesday's decision, which came just after Wall Street trading
closed, sent tobacco stocks lower. Shares of Philip Morris fell
$2.625 a share to $37.875 and shares of Reynolds Tobacco closed
down $1.1875 a share at $30.875. Loews lost $0.8125 to close at
$79.167.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Feldman, a tobacco industry analyst with Salomon Smith
Barney, said he expected that cigarette producers would seek to
have a higher Florida court decertify the class-action as soon as
the first damages were awarded.
</P>
<P>
   Higher courts can decertify, or disband, class-action lawsuits
approved by trial judges if they find that there are not enough
common factors among class members or if they determine that the
resolution of a case would be legally cumbersome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe this case is likely to be decertified,'' Feldman
said. ``But if it is not, then it would be an important stepping
stone to significant monetary awards against the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Wednesday's decision, some analysts and lawyers suggested
that if the industry lost the first round of the case it would move
to settle the action if it failed to decertify the class.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami trial unfolded in a highly charged emotional
atmosphere. Many of the selected plaintiffs, crippled or disabled
by various diseases, did not testify, but took their place in the
courtroom daily. One man said he developed a circulatory condition
that led to operations resulting in the amputations of both legs.
Others, who had lost their vocal cords to throat cancer, spoke with
the aid of artificial voice boxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was ever going to be any sympathy votes it is going
to be in this situation,'' said Ms. Aronson, the analyst in
Washington who attended the trial for a week.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason for its decision, the jury decided uniformly
against the tobacco industry on each of 10 questions it was asked
to resolve. They included whether producers concealed and
misrepresented the hazards and addictiveness of smoking and whether
they conspired with each other to misled the public.
</P>
<P>
   The jury also found that the companies lied and made misleading
statements and determined that 20 of 23 possible diseases were
potentially caused by smoking.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for damage awards, the nine representative class
members and the others who will follow them must now show that they
suffer from diseases that qualify, that their health problems were
caused by smoking and that they were deceived by the industry's
conduct.
</P>
<P>
   If they succeed, the size of damage awards against producers
could easily mount into the billions. And some analysts believe
that they may lead plaintiffs' lawyers in other states to mount
similar class-actions against the industry
</P>
<P>
   ``This could embolden a lot of other lawyers,'' Ms. Aronson
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
