<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2331 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-POVERTY-NYT &LR;      07-07 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POVERTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, AMID THE SQUALOR ON RESERVATION, AGAIN PROMISES HELP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.D., Miss., Ariz., Ky., Calif.)  (See also CLINTON-TORTILLA) 
(nk) 
 By PETER T. KILBORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINE RIDGE, S.D. _ Offering tax credits, loan guarantees and
other incentives to encourage private businesses to create jobs and
housing, President Clinton on Wednesday swept into the destitute
Oglala Lakota Sioux Indian reservation, by many measures the
sickest, most hopeless, most squalid corner of America.
</P>
<P>
   To revive Pine Ridge and other impoverished communities of the
kind the president is visiting during his four-day tour of the
nation, White House aides said that over five years the president
wants to allow $980 million in tax credits to stimulate $6 billion
in private investment for businesses and housing. He is also
seeking federal appropriations of $81 million to subsidize and
guarantee loans.
</P>
<P>
   Like other federal subsidies Clinton has proposed in his
six-state trip to underwrite programs, these would require
congressional action, though Clinton has not sent all the specific
legislation to Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is on a four-day tour of the nation's poorest
communities, first in Kentucky and Mississippi, then here on the
Great Plains. Later Wednesday he moved on to Phoenix, and on
Thursday he was headed to Los Angeles. At each stop, he was
sounding alarms about how the prosperity of nearly seven years in
office has passed these areas by and stressing the potential for
help from what he called his ``new markets initiatives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about the irony'' of the conditions at places like Pine
Ridge and those of the rest of the country, with its booming stock
market, 4.3 percent unemployment, quiescent inflation and easy
credit. ``Our nation will never have a better chance'' to help
these communities, he said. ``If we can't do this now, we will
never get around to doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pine Ridge Reservation, with a population about 25,000
spread over more than 3,100 square miles, is America's own
third-world country. It has been left far behind by the current
economic boom and by all of those that came before it. The nation's
second largest Indian reservation after that of the Navajo's in
Arizona and New Mexico, Pine Ridge has institutionalized squalor,
with rampant alcoholism, diabetes, suicide and a male life
expectancy rate of 56.5 years. Children play on dirt. Only 62 miles
of road are paved.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment is traditionally rampant and unmeasurable. Clinton
used a figure of ``nearly 75 percent.'' Tribe leaders say it's 85
percent. Most of the few jobs are with the tribal bureaucracy, the
federal government or the modest new casino, which has 150 Oglala
Sioux workers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton toured hovels that people live in here, including that
of Geraldine Blue Bird, whose shack and trailer house 28 people in
five bedrooms. ``See those houses on the street?'' Ms. Blue Bird
said to him tearfully. ``You notice they don't have windows. That's
because it has to come from the pocket, and we don't have that
pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the president spoke in the sweltering heat of outside
the Pine Ridge School, where many of the kindergarten-to-12th-grade
students board because their own homes on the two-million-acre
reservation are too far away or too decrepit.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and other members of his party, including the Rev. Jesse
Jackson, Housing and Urban Development Secretary Andrew W. Cuomo,
Agriculture Secretary Daniel Glickman, and bankers and businessmen
were warmly received.
</P>
<P>
   But a sign in back of the crowd, painted on a sheet, said,
``Stop Lakota ethnic cleansing,'' a reference to the tribe's loss
of the Black Hills northwest of the reservation and their gold.
</P>
<P>
   The Oglalas are the band of Crazy Horse, the victor over George
Custer at the battle of Little Big Horn in 1876, though that
triumph soon gave way to his tribe's being relegated to this
barren, rolling grassland with no marketable resources.
</P>
<P>
   The Oglalas continue to complain of a government in Washington
with misguided policies. They see themselves as a sovereign nation,
and Clinton, Wednesday accorded them such respect, calling his a
''nation-to-nation'' visit.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time a president visited an Indian reservation
since Franklin D. Roosevelt stopped at a Cherokee reservation in
North Carolina on Sept. 10, 1936, while taking a vacation. , ``We
hope the president can open a new chapter of Indian-federal
policy,'' said Dave Archambault, a councilman of the Standing Rock
Reservation, a Sioux site that straddles the border of North and
South Dakota, ``so we can sit down as equals and enhance the
government-to-government relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the tribes need a Marshall Plan, like the one that
rebuilt Europe after World War II. ``That's how you help us become
a part of America's heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made no gestures of that magnitude. But his economic
message also marks a big change in federal policy. By enlisting the
private sector, Clinton is seeking alternatives to the largely
discredited conventions of welfare and charity formed a generation
ago by President Lyndon B. Johnson's War on Poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told the Oglalas and leaders of more than 100 other
tribes attending his speech, ``We will do our part.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``We're coming from Washington to ask you what you
want to do and tell you we will give you the tools and support to
get done what you want to do for your children and their future.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been given credit for holding a tribal summit
several years back, one of the biggest Indian gatherings at the
White House ever. Indian leaders also praise the president for
protecting tribal sovereignty in siding with Indians and helping to
block attempts in Congress to curb the power of Indian nations to
self-govern themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But the tribes also say he has deserted them on other issues. In
1995, Congress took aim at the Bureau of Indian Affairs, passing a
spending bill that slashed all bureau operations by 25 percent. It
was later pared to about half that and signed by Clinton _ much to
the chagrin of Indians who depend on the annual budget, of just
over $1.2 billion, for many of their operations and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Indians fault him for not doing a better job of cleaning
up the mess over trust funds, owned by perhaps as many 500,000
individual Indians and held in trust by the government. Documents
showing how much money is managed in these funds are missing, lost
or stolen, and the Indians have filed the largest class action suit
ever by tribes to try and clean it up. A trial is now underway. In
the course of the trial, two Clinton cabinet members have been held
in civil contempt for not producing records in a timely way for the
court case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration has been very good on sovereignty and
gaming issues for the tribes,'' said John Dossett, general counsel
for the National Congress of American Indians, the largest group
representing Indians in Washington. ``If you step back and look at
the record from afar, I would think you have to give them a good
grade.''
</P>
<P>
   But others are sharply critical, noting that thousands of
members of the Sioux tribe in Pine Ridge are part of the lawsuit to
sort out their trust funds. ``Thousands of members of that tribe
are being actively defrauded by the Clinton administration,'' said
Jim McCarthy, a consultant to tribes in the trust fund case. ``For
him to go out there and throw some crumbs off the federal plate is
really appalling, because here you have some of the poorest people
in the country being denied what is theirs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
