<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2333 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-ART-560     07-07 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-ART-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON TAKES FIRST STEPS ON HER CAMPAIGN TRAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-MRSCLINTON-SCENE) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINDARS CORNERS, N.Y. _ The first lady of the United States flew
into New York on an Air Force jet Wednesday and presented herself
as a potential candidate to replace Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan
upon his retirement next year. Standing at Moynihan's side at his
farm here in upstate New York, Hillary Rodham Clinton described
questions about her residency as legitimate and said she would
attempt to address them in the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very fair question and I fully understand people
raising it,'' Mrs. Clinton said, offering a response to the very
first issue raised at an appearance here that was part news
conference and part political spectacle. ``I think I have some real
work to do to get out and listen and learn from the people of New
York and demonstrate that what I'm for is maybe as important _ if
not more important _ than where I'm from.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton than plunged into her first day on the campaign
trail as a candidate, as opposed to the candidate's spouse. She
visited the Baseball Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, ate lunch at a
barbeque restaurant in Oneonta, and savored the generally large and
enthusiastic crowds that turned out to catch sight of the first
lady and her entourage at every stop. She also held the first of
the orchestrated Listening to New Yorkers forums that are to anchor
her schedule this summer, listening intently and taking notes
during a discussion about education.
</P>
<P>
   It was, by any measure, a remarkable day in the politics of both
New York and the nation. It began at 11 a.m., when Moynihan slowly
escorted Mrs. Clinton up the road from the old school house on his
property that serves as his office to a huge assemblage of
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   As the center of the kind of attention that is unheard of in a
race for the U.S. Senate _ or even in the early days of a race for
president _ Mrs. Clinton began molding a new public image for
herself. With each of her eight answers at the 10-minute press
conference, and then in stops throughout the day, she stepped away
from the role of political wife that she has filled since Bill
Clinton was elected attorney general of Arkansas in 1976 and began
filling in the contours of her own potential candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton rarely mentioned her husband, whose term concludes
at the end of 2000, and the president was not at her side on
Wednesday. The first lady presented herself as someone who was
ready to learn about a state she has never lived in. She also, for
the first time, offered some hint of dealing with the more
difficult questions her aides said they expect, from unresolved
questions about Whitewater to why she may, after seven tumultuous
years in the White House, seek to become the first first lady in
the nation's history to run for public office. The leading
Republican candidate to run against her is Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to be spending my time in the next days and weeks and
months listening to New Yorkers,'' Mrs. Clinton said. ``Now I
suppose the questions on everybody's mind is, `Why the Senate and
why New York and why me?' All I can say is I care deeply about the
issues that are important in this state, that I've already been
learning about and hearing about.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``I would be, if I run and am honored to be elected,
a strong and effective advocate on the part of the people of New
York.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The place where Mrs. Clinton headed first _ Moynihan's 900-acre
farm in this one-traffic-light hamlet 70 miles west of Albany _ was
a curious choice. Of all the Democratic senators in Washington,
Moynihan often had the most unsettled relations with the Clintons.
He was particularly critical of Mrs. Clinton's failed effort to
advance a national health care plan at the start of her husband's
administration, and the president's aides frequently complained at
the start that Moynihan was not helping Clinton accomplish his
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   But Moynihan and Mrs. Clinton share a senior political adviser,
Mandy Grunwald, and Ms. Grunwald joined the two of them in their
private 25-meeting before their news conference. Mrs. Clinton has,
over the course of these past few months, repeatedly visited
Moynihan's home in Washington to discuss the potential race,
effectively recruiting him as her most prominent supporter.
</P>
<P>
   As a jaunty Moynihan walked her to the microphone _ a moment
suffused with generational symbolism _ he left no doubt about who
he wanted to succeed him. That said, he almost neglected to say
that as he turned over the platform to his guest.
</P>
<P>
   ``My God, I almost forgot,'' Moynihan exclaimed, then added:
``Yesterday, Hillary Clinton established an exploratory committee
with regards to a candidacy for the Senate, the United States
Senate from New York, a seat which I will vacate in a year and a
half. I'm here to say that I hope she will go all the way. I mean
to go all the way with her. I think she's going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton was assured if self-effacing throughout the day,
taking the guidance of her advisers, who have been concerned that
she may have projected something of an air of entitlement in past
discussions about the seat. She seemed undisturbed as she
encountered a steady if small stream of protesters who challenged
the credentials of this Chicago native to seek office in New York
state.
</P>
<P>
   When Mrs. Clinton arrived for lunch, she was greeted by a small
group of people shouting, ``Go Home Hillary.'' That chant was
drowned out by a rival chant of the first lady's supporters, ``We
want Hillary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
