<SLUG> BC-BOEING-GE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING PICKS GE TO BUILD ENGINE FOR ITS LONG-RANGE 777 JET 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boeing Co. said Wednesday that it had chosen General Electric
Co. to build the world's most powerful jet engine for a new
ultra-long-range version of its wide-body 777 jetliner.
</P>
<P>
   The exclusive deal, which had been hotly contested, is a blow to
Pratt &AMP; Whitney, a unit of United Technologies Corp., and
Rolls-Royce PLC, both of which supply engines for the 777 along
with GE.
</P>
<P>
   But both engine makers said that the effect on their operations
would not be too serious because the demand for the new airplanes,
called the 777-200X and 777-300X, was limited to about 500 jets.
``The market for this airplane is very small,'' said Mark Sullivan,
a spokesman for Pratt &AMP; Whitney. ``It really doesn't justify more
than one engine.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing said that the 777-200X would be the longest-range plane
ever designed, carrying 300 passengers about 10,000 miles, 1,200
miles farther than the current model. The larger 777-300X would
carry 360 passengers 8,300 miles.
</P>
<P>
   The victory is an important one for GE, which spent $1.5 billion
to $2.5 billion earlier in the decade to develop a new engine for
the 777 but ended up selling fewer of them than its two
competitors, which each spent less by developing engines based on
previous designs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the only purpose-built 777 engine, and they have
only a one-third market share,'' said Richard Aboulafia, an analyst
at the Teal Group, an aviation consultant in Fairfax, Va. ``That's
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   While the price of the engines values the deal at $15 billion,
jet engine makers make most of their profit supplying spare parts
rather than the engine itself. In exchange for being designated the
exclusive engine supplier on the new 777, GE is helping Boeing pay
for the development of the new jets.
</P>
<P>
   James McNerney, the president of GE Aircraft Engines, said in an
interview that the deal would help GE's services business by
expanding the installed base of its 777 engine. But he denied that
the deal was a loss leader. ``Boeing makes money,'' he said. ``We
make money.''
</P>
<P>
   The new engines will present GE with a technical challenge. The
wide-body 777 holds almost as many passengers as the older 747s it
hopes to replace but it flies on only two engines instead of four.
The huge engines on today's 777s, which are the same diameter as
the fuselage of a 737, are already the world's most powerful,
generating as much as 98,000 pounds of thrust. The new,
longer-range version requires an engine that can generate 115,000
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts estimate that GE will have to invest $350 million to
$500 million to develop the engine.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing hoped to sell the longer-range 777 two years ago but was
forced to pull back after the financial crisis in Asia dampened the
interest of several Asian airlines, which are the primary customers
of the proposed jets. In the meantime, Airbus Industrie, the
European consortium that is Boeing's archrival, announced that it
was building two new long-range versions of its four-engine
wide-body A340.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has still not officially committed itself to building the
new 777s, though most analysts think it will, and Wednesday's
announcement makes the decision more likely. Boeing said Wednesday
that it was tentatively planning to have the first plane in service
in 2003. That would be in time to compete with the new Airbus jets,
which are scheduled to start flying in 2002.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 2105EDT &QL; 
