<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0324 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2339 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANK-MERGER-BOS &LR;      07-07 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANK-MERGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEET TAKES THE HEAT AT MERGER HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Hundreds of community activists and politicians
launched a volley of criticism against Fleet Financial Group Inc.
Wednesday, saying that the financial giant's proposed acquisition
of BankBoston Corp. would stifle lending to poorer neighborhoods
and reduce competition.
</P>
<P>
   The protests, voiced at a noisy public hearing organized by the
Federal Reserve Bank of Boston, included calls for industry
regulators to delay approval of the historic merger until New
England's two largest banks offer more details on how they will
serve low-income areas and small businesses after they combine.
</P>
<P>
   The speeches injected drama into the usually staid world of
banking. They also highlighted growing efforts by activists and
elected officials to influence bank mergers amid a changing
industry. Consolidation is creating huge banks that span large
areas, in turn raising questions over whether the new giants will
continue to serve their old communities.
</P>
<P>
   With the Fleet-BankBoston merger, which will create the nation's
eighth largest bank, regulators are especially sensitive to
questions over how the new behemoth will make loans to low-income
areas. With over $160 billion assets, the bank will be the dominant
lender in New England, and will hold significant sway over the
ability of less affluent borrowers to obtain affordable housing and
business loans.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet's chief executive, Terrence Murray, told the hearing that
his acquisition of BankBoston would only help New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``By increasing in size, banks achieve the economies of scale
that allow us to invest more in technology and people,'' Murray
said. ``All of us are on the verge of ensuring that New England
will enter the 21st century with a hometown bank headquartered in
this city.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics had the past on their minds as well as the future.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this decade, Fleet faced national criticism of its
lending practices. More recently, activists have produced studies
showing that Fleet reduces lending to disadvantaged borrowers after
it buys other banks.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet disputes many of the charges, saying that most of its
critics are not doing their math properly and that Fleet is the
region's biggest lender to underserved communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like BankBoston, Fleet has been a leader in small business and
mortage lending, helping to revitalize entire neighnborhoods and
create new enterprises,'' said Gail Snowden, a BankBoston executive
who will head the combined bank's community lending initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston has garnered praise for its community lending
philosophy, which looks at blighted urban areas as investment
opportunities. Still, BankBoston's record was not enough to keep
critics at bay on the issue of affordable mortgages _ the major
topic of the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have yet to hear why this merger is a forward step for this
community,'' said Mayor Thomas Menino, who offered the day's
harshest critique of the merger. Menino said he feared that the
combined bank would be more interested in lucrative foreign markets
than in needy local communities.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve hearings are a ritual for large banks seeking to
merge. While the Fed the Justice Department, which must formally
approve the merger, rarely say no to combinations, they are open to
comments. The process has in the past led some banks to make
heftier lending commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, more than 150 people testified at the
hearing, which was organized into 21 panels. About 400 spectators
and protestors packed the Fed's downtown auditorium, as Fed
officials pelted activists and bank executives with questions about
the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the state chapter of the Association of Community
Organizations for Reform Now, or ACORN, a housing group that
channels Fleet loans to lower-income borrowers, told how the bank's
low-cost mortgages had put them into permanent housing for the
first time. Lunita Mustafa, a single mother of six in Mattapan,
burst into tears as she described how a Fleet ACORN land had given
her children a safe place to grow up.
</P>
<P>
   ACORN is upset that Fleet has not said it will renew part of its
$155 million lending program when it expires later this month.
BankBoston chief executive Chad Gifford said that the combined bank
might renew the program.
</P>
<P>
   Debates over that program and the new bank's other community
lending proposals have become a lightening rod for activists and
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet has angered groups like ACORN by declining to sign
concrete loan-channeling agreements with specific groups. Instead,
the new bank plans to work with national mortgage powerhouse Fannie
Mae on new affordable mortgage initiatives, Fleet's community
investment director, Agnes B. Scanlan, said.
</P>
<P>
   Banks are required under the 1977 Community Reinvestment Act to
lend to the communities from which they take deposits.
</P>
<P>
   Still, critics are suspicious of how two banks with different
cultures and traditions will carry out their proposals. Fleet is
generally viewed as more bottomline-oriented, while BankBoston is
seen as more sensitive to community needs.
</P>
<P>
   Not even BankBoston's stewardship of the combined bank's plan to
channel $14.6 billion over five years into affordable housing,
small business loans, and community development initiatives has
impressed protesters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no problem dealing with a Fleet Bank,'' the Rev. Al
Sharpton, the New York religious leader and activist, said. ``But
we do have a problem with being fleeced by Fleet Bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barney Frank (D-Newton), the ranking Democrat on the House
Banking and Financial Services Committee, agreed. ``This merger is
a good thing on its own terms,'' he said. ``But it is not a
sufficient thing for what we need in the region'' in terms of
community investment.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Dianne Wilkerson of Roxbury echoed that theme, saying
that regulators should take note of unusually strong opposition to
the merger from local politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent housing activist Bruce Marks of the Neighborhood
Assistance Corp. of America asked the Fed to delay consideration of
the merger for several weeks while NACA polls 75,000 Fleet mortgage
recipients on their views of Fleet's practices. Marks, a
self-described guerilla activist, made a dramatic entrance at the
hearing with 150 supporters wearing yellow t-shirts that said,
``Down with loan sharks!''
</P>
<P>
   Critics also expressed concern about who will buy the nearly $15
billion in deposits and loans that Fleet and BankBoston are selling
to meet antitrust rules. Justice regulators favor a large bank
acquiring at least a large chunk of the assets.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton called on Fleet to accept a proposal from Boston Bank
of Commerce, a minority-owned bank, to purchase 18 branches. The
bank's president, Kevin Cohee, said he had financing from a New
York investment bank, Sandler O'Neill, to buy branches with $600
million in deposits.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to sell it anyway, so let's step up to the plate,''
said Cohee, who said he aimed to create the country's largest
black-owned bank in the wake of the Fleet-BankBoston merger. ``We
have a chance to be heroes here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
