<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    British women slighted by press
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A few more English accents are being detected
around Women's World Cup events this week, which means American
reporters can't resist the urge to make comparisons between the
acceptance of women's soccer here and its virtual anonymity in the
United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   FIFA spokesman Keith Cooper became the point man for U.S. media
questions Wednesday about the difficulties of women's soccer being
embraced in countries that have never done so, despite the success
of this World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do a lot to encourage the federations to provide more
resources and support, but we can't change cultural barriers,''
Cooper said at a news conference held in conjunction with a FIFA
symposium on women's soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Then the subject turned to his country, where women's soccer is
rapidly growing and has a semi-professional league but barely rates
a mention in the British media.
</P>
<P>
   ``The men's game is so dominating,'' he said. ``It's a very
tough nut to crack.''
</P>
<P>
   A handful of British media have arrived to chronicle what is
certain to be viewed as an intriguing cultural phenomenon from
their perpsective. BBC's Radio 5 Live station conducted an on-air
interview with Women's World Cup CEO Marla Messing and a few
newspaper reporters from London also are here through the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Bring on the pressure
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, existing in a male sports-dominated country
like Brazil has its advantages for the women's national team.
</P>
<P>
   Star forward Pretinha said the biggest one is being able to
enjoy the freedom of moving around without a groundswell of media
and fans. She didn't make a reference in particular, but the
Brazilian players are mindful of the circus that surrounds Ronaldo
and teammates on the men's team.
</P>
<P>
   Despite reaching the Women's World Cup semifinals, Pretinha is
doubtful that she and her teammates will be in a much greater
spotlight, although they are hopeful it can happen someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like for women's football to have more pressure,'' she
said. ``But it is fine for the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Haven't I said this before?
</P>
<P>
   They don't seem to be tiring of answering the same questions
dozens and dozens of times. Spending nearly three weeks in the
public glare apparently hasn't had a visibly wearing effect on the
U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   The elementary questions are repeated over and over again: Do
you think you're role models for young girls? Can you believe the
crowds? What do you think about the future of women's soccer?
</P>
<P>
   And yet they're answered without any hint of annoyance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's part of what we have to do,'' forward Tiffeny Milbrett
whispered with a smile before the TV lights were turned on in her
face.
</P>
<P>
   When asked how she and her teammates were coping with the crush
of media attention, she teased. ``I guess it's getting old hat for
us now. Hey, I'm just kidding. We know it's something we have to
do, so why get bothered about it?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
