<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lopez's knee passes squat test
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Braves catcher Javy Lopez continued to show progress
in his comeback from a sprained right knee on Wednesday when he got
down in the catching position for the first time since he hurt his
knee in Arizona on June 20.
</P>
<P>
   It was the next step after doing some hitting on Monday and some
running and cutting on Tuesday, and it was a big one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say it's good news,'' Lopez said. ``I was expecting
something worse. I was afraid I couldn't squat down. Today I tried
to squat and I did.''
</P>
<P>
   While he didn't block any balls, he threw some to second base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pull my body up with my right knee,'' Lopez said. ``That's a
good test.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez said there was no swelling or pain in his knee after he
gave it a good workout on Tuesday. But he knows he'll have to let
his knee dictate what happens from here on out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'll be able to finish the whole season like this,''
Lopez said. ``It's obvious if I start feeling pain I've got to
quit. After the season I'm going to get something done (surgically)
if it doesn't heal by the end of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Cox said he plans to have Lopez catch five minutes
of batting practice today. He'll do it wearing a knee brace and a
pad behind his right knee, which makes him a little uncomfortable
at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't go low because I've got the knee saver, and if I go
low it's going to hurt,'' Lopez said. ``It's all a matter of
getting used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Notable absences
</P>
<P>
   The National League All-Stars will play without Greg Maddux or
Tom Glavine this year for the first time since 1990. Glavine has
been selected six times in the last eight years, missing 1994 and
1995, and started for the National League in 1991 and 1992.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first year Maddux hasn't made the All-Star team
since 1993. He's been an All-Star seven times in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be a little strange,'' said Glavine of his three days
off. ``I'm not going to sit here and tell you I'm happy I'm not
going. I'm sure I'll enjoy the days off, but anybody who tells you
they're happy they're not an All-Star is lying. That's what we play
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Ozzie Guillen said Wednesday Andres Galarraga is set to begin
his radiation treatments today and still plans to join the Braves
as early as next month....
</P>
<P>
   Braves general manager John Schuerholz, who named Roy Clark
director of scouting on Tuesady, has yet to decide what to do with
the other part of Paul Snyder's job as director of player
development. He may promote someone from within the Braves front
office....
</P>
<P>
   Walt Weiss was 1-for-21 since returning from his sore
quadriceps, entering Wednesday night's game with one walk, one run
scored and one RBI. He was able to take batting practice for much
of the 22 games he missed but it's been slow going so far. ``I'm
just trying to find it,'' Weiss said of his swing....
</P>
<P>
   Boredom is apparent already for pitcher John Smoltz, who spent
his first batting practice since returning to the disabled list
with a sore right elbow shagging fly balls with one of Brian
Hunter's left-hander's glove.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
