<SLUG> BC-YAHOO-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YAHOO REPORTS SECOND QUARTER THAT SURPASSES EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By SAUL HANSELL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blasting away worries that the growth in Internet usage is
slowing, Yahoo reported results Wednesday for the second quarter
that were well above analysts' expectation.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which operates the most popular site on the World
Wide Web, benefited from increases in both users and advertising,
bolstered in part by its acquisition in May of Geocities, a popular
service that lets people post their own home pages.
</P>
<P>
   The company actually posted a loss of $15.1 million, or 7 cents
a share, because of $55 million in charges relating to
acquisitions. Yahoo lost $14.2 million or 8 cent per share in the
second quarter of last year.
</P>
<P>
   The company calculated its operating income at $28.3 million, or
11 cents per share. Analysts had expected operating income of 8
cents per share. (The operating income excluded both the merger
expenses and $3.5 million other ``intangible'' charges required
under accounting rules but which companies wish investors would
ignore.)
</P>
<P>
   The company's revenue of $115.2 million was a 156 percent
increase compared with last year's $45 million.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo is the first Internet company to report earnings for the
second quarter. But analysts argued that it was not necessarily a
bellwether because it is increasing its lead over competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yahoo continues to set the bar on the Internet,'' said Paul W.
Noglows, an analyst with Hambrecht &AMP; Quist. ``Across the board,
other companies may not be as strong. But this at least proves that
advertising on the Internet is alive and well.''
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo said it had 80 million unique users in June and that it
delivered an average of 310 million pages a day. In March, Yahoo
and Geocities users looked at an average of 275 million pages a
day.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding Geocities, the company's traffic as measured by the
number of pages viewed increased by 15 percent, but its revenue
increased by 25 percent, according to calculations by David
Readerman, an analyst for Thomas Weisel Partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means they are capturing more and more ad dollars for
every page they have,'' he said. ``What has always impressed me
about Yahoo is that they can bring the benefit of their audience
down to the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Readerman pointed out that Yahoo's operating profit margin
increased to 32 percent in the quarter from 28 percent in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest concern expressed by analysts was about the
acquisition of Geocities. The company said pages viewed on
Geocities site remained flat from the first to the second quarter,
at an average of 40 million a day. It declined to break out revenue
from Geocities.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition has been somewhat traumatic in that Yahoo closed
Geocities' Santa Monica, Calif., offices to integrate operations
into its Santa Clara, Calif., headquarters in Silicon Valley. And
Geocities users objected to the new terms and conditions that Yahoo
imposed, largely giving it ownership of the pages that users
created. But earlier this week Yahoo relented.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like it will take them a while with Geocities,''
Noglows said. ``But in some ways that is to be expected with new
acquisitions.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenges to Yahoo double in the third quarter as it closes
its acquisition of Broadcast.com. The company said that the cost of
that deal would reduce its earnings per share until the third
quarter of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with analysts, Yahoo highlighted the growth
of its international operations, which serve 19 countries in 12
languages. Already, one third of its pages are viewed by users
outside of the United States, although foreign operations account
for a much smaller proportion of its revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The company said that its first four international markets _
Japan, Britain, France and Germany _ were profitable, though it was
losing money it the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the company says it expects that half of the money
spent on online advertising will be outside of the United States
and it hopes that ultimately half its audience will be overseas as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo's shares fell by $8.06 cents on Nasdaq Wednesday to
$167.06, after rising in anticipation of earnings the day before.
In after hours trading, the stock increased to $172.625.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
