u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MRSCLINTON-MEDIA-440&AMP;     07-07 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-MEDIA-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
200 HEAR FIRST LADY. TOWNSPEOPLE WERE THERE, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (With NY-MRSCLINTON)  
(js) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINDARS CORNERS, N.Y. _ The likely candidate put it wryly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really excited about being able to take these long,
beautiful summer days,'' she said, looking out Wednesday toward the
gentle upstate farmland and probably the largest press corps ever
to assemble for a U.S. Senate race, ``and, you know, kind of at a
leisurely pace with, you know, a few hundred of you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Schumer campaign was never like this. The Pataki, Cuomo and
Koch campaigns were never like this. Even Hillary Rodham Clinton's
husband, the president, didn't have as large a press entourage with
him Wednesday as he traveled to a South Dakota Indian reservation
in one of the poorest parts of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But then, the trip of a second-term president with 18 months
left in office was no match for the sometimes surreal spectacle of
the first campaign-like day of the first first lady to seek
political office on her own, with her husband still in the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   By 9 a.m., four huge press buses had disgorged more than 200
reporters and television technicians from around the world on the
farm of Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, who in 2000 will vacate the
seat that Mrs. Clinton is considering. A few days ago, bales of hay
were cleared from one of Moynihan's fields to make way for an
enormous press platform that can accommodate more than 30
television cameras and eight satellite dishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I woke up this morning and went out on the front step and
saw the satellite trucks at the top of the hill,'' said Elizabeth
Moynihan, the senator's wife, ``I felt like a character in `The
Invasion of . . . ' _ you know, one of those space alien movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Although this is Mrs. Clinton's 13th visit to New York since
announcing her interest in the Senate seat earlier this year, the
trip was the first to be paid for by her Senate exploratory
committee and not the White House. Still, it seemed a strange
hybrid of an official White House trip and a traditionally bumpy
Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   There was a White House-like press pool and a press center in
Oneonta. And there were the typical trappings of a Senate campaign,
with Clinton aides _ many of them former members of the
presidential staff _ volunteering their time and complaining that
the rented cell phones and beepers were not to White House
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, the press secretary for Mrs. Clinton's
exploratory committee, would not say what the trip was costing and
how much money the committee, formed on Tuesday, had raised in the
24 hours of its existence. But he did offer that ``you don't pay
for these trips in cash.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The sight of the day was of Moynihan, who is recovering from hip
surgery, slowly walking Mrs. Clinton down the road from the
one-room schoolhouse where he has written his 18 books toward the
gantlet of press members in his field.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons and Moynihans have had a sometimes difficult
relationship in Washington _ particularly when the senator
criticized the Clinton health care plan during the president's
first term. But this time it seemed as if the senator could be
giving away a bride, or at least sending Mrs. Clinton off on her
journey across New York, a state she has never lived in.
</P>
<P>
   When the two reached the assembled members of the press, under
brilliant sunshine and cooled by the first breezes in days,
Moynihan introduced the first lady, and said simply: ``I'm here to
say I hope she will go all the way. I will go all the way with
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Then New York's senior senator took on the job of refereeing
questions from the press directed at the first lady. When Gabe
Pressman of WNBC-TV asked about Mrs. Clinton's ``chutzpah'' in
running for Senate, Moynihan said: ``Now, Gabe, we're in Delaware
County. What was this word?''
</P>
<P>
   At the first ``listening'' event of what Mrs. Clinton is calling
her summer listening tour of New York, most television cameras
slowly slipped out of a conference room at the State University of
New York at Oneonta college campus as Mrs. Clinton listened,
seemingly patiently, for more than an hour and a half as local
citizens complained about the education system, lack of high-speed
Internet access and, at one point, the manners of young people.
</P>
<P>
   But the Oneonta citizens were also impressed by the media
intensity of the event. ``We should be historically recording these
cameras for our purposes,'' said Margaret Maguire, an associate
professor of economics and business at SUNY Oneonta, staring in
amazement at the television crews that initially crowded two sides
of the room. ``I've never seen anything like it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
