u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIERRA-LEONE-REBELS-A     07-07 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-LEONE-REBELS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACTS REACHED ON CONGO AND SIERRA LEONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast _ A small nation in Africa took a big step
toward peace Wednesday and a big African nation took a small one.
</P>
<P>
   The warring sides in Sierra Leone's eight-year civil war signed
a peace agreement that gives amnesty and a share of power to a
rebellion that has waged a systematic campaign of terror by hacking
off the limbs of civilians.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the belligerents in the vast Central African
nation of Congo agreed for the first time on a framework for a
cease-fire in the year-old war there.
</P>
<P>
   Both developments occurred after negotiations appeared ready to
collapse on many occasions, and the warring sides issued countless
premature announcements of breakthroughs in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Congo, the government of President Laurent Kabila
and the leaders of two rebellions, as well as the countries backing
both sides, agreed on the points that would produce a cease-fire.
The agreement is to be signed by the various countries' presidents
and rebel leaders, though no date has been set, officials involved
in the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agreement that we have addresses most of the major
problems,'' said Bizima Karaha, a rebel leader and Kabila's former
foreign minister, reached by telephone in Lusaka, Zambia's capital,
where talks were being held. ``We think that this is very
positive.''
</P>
<P>
   According to this agreement, a cease-fire would take effect
within 24 hours of its signing. The agreement calls for a national
debate in which the Congolese government would meet with armed
rebels, as well as political opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also calls for the establishment of international
peacekeeping forces to disarm Hutu militias hiding in eastern Congo
blamed for 1994 mass killings in Rwanda. Officials in Rwanda's
Tutsi-led government have argued that they are backing the
rebellion against Kabila, their former ally, because he has failed
to address their concerns over the presence of the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process that has been launched here is only the beginning
of a long process, but it's a very important beginning to have all
the parties together, collectively laying out a road map,'' said
Howard Wolpe, the Clinton administration's special envoy to the
region, reached by telephone in Lusaka. ``Our sense is that the key
players have come to comprehend how enormously costly this is not
only to the people of the Congo but to the entire region.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the accord for Sierra Leone, a new coalition
Government will be headed by the current elected president but will
include four Cabinet posts for the Revolutionary United Front. The
head of the rebellion, Foday Sankoh, was given a position
equivalent to vice president, though not the title. He is to head a
commission on minerals and national reconstruction, according to
the plan.
</P>
<P>
   The 25-page accord _ reached after several weeks of negotiations
in Lome, Togo's capital _ amounted to a victory for Sankoh, who has
been imprisoned for the last two years. He was sentenced to death
in October, a move that pushed his men to advance on Freetown,
Sierra Leone's capital, where several weeks of fierce fighting left
thousands dead and countless ordinary citizens mutilated.
</P>
<P>
   The government and rebels agreed on the plan only after the
presidents of neighboring nations came to Lome this week to press
both sides to end a war that neither could win outright militarily.
Given this war's history, it is unclear whether this plan will be
carried out and observed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, a peace agreement between Sankoh and the current
president, Ahmad Tejan Kabbah, fell apart within months. Since
then, the rebellion and mutinous army troops intensified their
attacks on civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Pledging that this agreement will last, Kabbah, accompanied by a
little girl with an amputated arm, said at the signing ceremony:
``I shall sign it as president of Sierra Leone, but more
importantly I shall sign it for the thousands of children of Sierra
Leone.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the peace plan, the government will have to work with
members of an organization that has committed atrocities described
recently by Mary Robinson, the U.N. Human Rights Commissioner, as
worse than those in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But with essentially no army of its own and dependent on a
Nigerian-led West African force for its survival, the government of
Kabbah had come under increasing pressure in recent months to
negotiate with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolutionary United Front, believed to control half of this
country's territory, devastated villages and forced children to
join their movement. About 10 percent of the population of 4.5
million fled.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh's group long denied that it had committed atrocities. But
in an interview last month, he acknowledged responsibility, but
denied that the atrocities had been as widespread as reported.
</P>
<P>
   During the talks, government negotiators said that they had no
choice but to broker a peace with Sankoh. Continuing the war, they
said, was the greater of two evils.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations welcomed the signing of the accord, but
formally expressed reservations about the general amnesty.
</P>
<P>
   Manoel de Almeida e Silva, a spokesman for Secretary-General
Kofi Annan, told reporters in New York that Francis Okelo, the U.N.
special envoy, had signed the agreement with a notation warning
that the United Nations would not recognize the amnesty ``as
applying to gross violations of human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our view is that the amnesty and pardon shall not apply to
international crimes of genocide, crimes against humanity, war
crimes, and other serious violations of international humanitarian
law,'' Almeida e Silva said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. spokesman said that Annan would present plans to expand
its observer mission in Sierra Leone next week. Diplomats said that
final numbers for the expanded force had not yet been set, but that
the force would probably total about 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   But Human Rights Watch, based in New York, has documented the
atrocities in Sierra Leone, and its executive director, Kenneth
Roth, said Wednesday, ``The atrocities are clearly crimes against
humanity. This is a terribly shaky foundation to build a peace on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
