<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPORTS-RESTRICT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON MOVES TO RESTRICT STEEL AND LAMB IMPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite a booming American economy, President
Clinton moved Wednesday to restrict imports of two politically
sensitive products _ steel from Brazil and lamb from Australia and
New Zealand _ in response to complaints from unions and farmers
that their livelihoods are threatened by a surge of under-priced
imports.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has justified each of the moves as examples of how his
administration is enforcing dumping laws, a critical step,
administration officials say, to build support for open trade. But
abroad, Clinton's decisions are viewed quite differently, as more
evidence that the United States, while talking up the merits of
free trade, is increasingly closing its borders to imports.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's actions Wednesday underscored how trade has become an
increasingly sensitive political issue, even as the American
economy continues to lead the rest of the world. The White House _
and particularly Vice President Gore, as he tries to invigorate his
troubled campaign _ are coming under increasing pressure to aid
workers and industries hurt by a surging American trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, import restrictions have become part of a delicate
dance for the administration. It is arguing that the only way to
build public support for a free trade system is to demonstrate that
Washington is ready to halt imports of goods that the
administration determines are ``dumped'' at unfairly low prices to
be purchased by American consumers. While that may bolster the
administration at home, it is undercutting efforts to press other
nations to open their markets, particularly agricultural markets.
That will be the subject of a major new round of international
trade negotiations, starting in November.
</P>
<P>
   The action on Brazilian steel is part of a series of steps to
respond to industry and union complaints about low-cost steel from
a number of countries, including Japan, South Korea and Russia.
Under an arrangement negotiated with the Brazilian government,
Brazil's steel industry agreed to ``voluntarily'' reduce shipments
to the United States, hours before a deadline that would have
imposed tariffs of about 50 percent on its imports. Such
``suspension agreements,'' so named because they suspend Commerce
Department investigations into dumping, are also being sought with
other nations accused of selling here at cut-rate prices.
</P>
<P>
   Under the accord, Brazil will reduce shipments of hot-rolled
steel by about 28 percent, and will export no more than 295,000
metric tons to the United States. The Brazilians also agreed to
charge at least $327 a metric ton for their hot-rolled steel, a bit
above the going rate in the United States. While the administration
defends such price-fixing as the only way to avoid dumping, it has
previously responded with outrage when other countries,
particularly Japan, have sought to set floors on the price of
imported goods.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement gives some protective cover to the administration
after the defeat two weeks ago in the Senate of a bill that would
have set quotas on a wide range of steel products. The
administration had opposed that legislation, saying it was a
violation of international trade accords. But tariffs to stop
dumping and agreements like the one reached Wednesday are legal
under most circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The lamb issue ranks low by economic measures _ but it is
politically sensitive with both farmers and with New Zealand and
Australia, not usual combatants in trade wars with America.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was acting on an International Trade Commission finding
last April that a vast increase in the amount of lamb meat imported
into the United States was harming the domestic industry. So
Wednesday, in a proclamation, Clinton limited imports starting on
July 22 to 31,851 metric tons for the next year. Any imports above
that level will be hit with a 40 percent tariff. Clinton said he
would also offer roughly $100 million in aid to United States.
farmers over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The package of import relief and domestic assistance has been
carefully crafted to help our lamb industry achieve sustained
competitiveness,'' Joe Lockhart, the White House spokesman, said in
a statement released during the president's trip Wednesday to South
Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   The subject is bound to be a centerpiece of a visit next week by
Australia's Prime Minister, John Howard. The trip is meant to
celebrate the American-Australian alliance, and Australia's actions
to sidestep the worst effects of the Asian financial crisis that
began two years ago. But the lamb issue is a major one for Howard,
particularly at a time when Australia's major markets in Asia are
still hurting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
