<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2352 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BLACKOUT-SCENE-ART     07-07 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BLACKOUT-SCENE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NORTHERN MANHATTAN, BLACKOUT WAS A LESSON IN BEING PREPARED 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-BLACKOUT) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JODI WILGOREN and KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Seven months after surviving open-heart surgery,
Richard Carter had no intention of being done in by a blackout.
</P>
<P>
   The 50-year-old Washington Heights resident rushed out Wednesday
morning to buy batteries, water and a telephone that runs without
electricity, in case he needed to dial 911. With the elevator dark,
Carter stopped on the stoop before attempting the stairs up to his
fifth-floor apartment, worried not just about his own health, but
also that of his neighbors: the Holocaust survivor with the heart
condition, the old man and his oxygen tank, the elderly lady next
door, clutching her last ice pack to the back of her neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had this surgery, so anything that cuts the air and the
elevators is dangerous,'' said Carter, a professional fund-raiser,
whose apartment building at Fort Washington Avenue and 187th
Street, like several neighborhood high- rises, lacked water as well
as electricity for most of the day. ``But there are a lot of
elderly people in this building who can't even get down the stairs.
For them, this is a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   When the lights finally came back on throughout northern
Manhattan at about 5 p.m. Wednesday, residents erupted in
spontaneous celebrations, literally dancing in the streets. Tenants
of 3810 Broadway, near 159th Street, had already started a block
barbecue to get rid of their rotting foods, and the party was
reinvigorated as people saw the lights of the No. 1 restaurant
flicker on across the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be happy just to be able to stay home and sleep cool,''
said Nestor Chevalier, 55. ``We sure didn't get any sleep last
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Sylvania Ladany, 44, president of the building's tenants'
association, had organized the barbecue after buying about 50
flashlights at Home Depot to distribute to residents for the
blackout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing is, we learned a lesson,'' said Mrs. Ladany's
daughter, Sora, 18. ``We learned to be prepared. New Yorkers have
to be prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Just hours before, the normally teeming stretch of upper
Broadway was a surreal scene of shuttered storefronts as an endless
line of police officers stood at intersections, directing traffic
in place of lights.
</P>
<P>
   Residents searched for food that had not yet gone bad and ice
imported from the Bronx, as rumors swirled about what had cut off
the electricity and when it might return. One restaurateur gave up
early, setting out a free buffet on the sidewalk that fed several
hundred, before tossing at least $1,000 worth of uncooked filet
mignon into the trash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's like a holiday,'' said Raymond Guzman, who closed his
discount store on Broadway except to sell flashlights and
batteries. ``I got a day off. I never have a day off.'''
</P>
<P>
   Tell it to Jang-Hee Lee, owner of New Grace Food Market, who
said he had lost $10,000 in ruined ice cream, milk, fancy cheese
and frozen fruit. ``Who's going to get this money back to me?'' he
asked. ``Mayor Giuliani says he's going to sue to get money for the
city, but who can I sue?''
</P>
<P>
   Many residents and business owners praised the police for a
quick response to the blackout and their blanket presence overnight
Tuesday and through Wednesday. But they also complained that the
blackout had lasted even one night _ a night many spent struggling
for shut-eye on the floor to avoid the rising heat, worried about
dangers that might be lurking outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very hot, very noisy, very frustrating _ it was very
scary at the same time,'' said Anna Molina, 45, who lives in an
apartment off 181st Street with her three children, and lived
through the blackout of 1977. ``I was walking around the apartment.
I was scared. You have to be alert.''
</P>
<P>
   Robyn Nunez, who lives on 207th Street, said that she and her
family took cold showers and went to bed without drying off to stay
cool Tuesday night, but that the open window near the fire escape
made her too nervous to sleep. Eugenio Reyes took cold baths at 2
a.m., 4 a.m. and 6 a.m. Wednesday, then went to open his hair
salon, only to close it two hours later. Deborah Duffy, 50, sent
her two children to their father's office at the World Financial
Center downtown armed with computer games, and considered spending
the afternoon in her air-conditioned car.
</P>
<P>
   The crowded neighborhoods of Washington Heights and Inwood,
where some 200,000 spent 19 hours without power, include patches of
severe poverty amid grand pre-World War II buildings whose height
made the loss of elevator service particularly burdensome. The
overwhelming flavor of the area is Dominican, but there are pockets
of elderly Jewish residents who hail from another era, and young
professionals have begun to move into gentrifying blocks.
</P>
<P>
   As children frolicked around fire hydrants and teen-agers played
stickball on closed-off streets, many questioned why they were
suffering without electricity while the rest of the city sat in
air-conditioned skyscrapers. They accused both Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani and Con Edison of picking on the less-than powerful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why us? Why us and not downtown?'' said Maria de la Cruz, who
took her husband and her four children to a Holiday Inn Tuesday
night. ``I think it's racist. It has to be something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. de la Cruz's 12-year-old daughter Jhara, the oldest, was
also piqued. ``Basically, they just don't care what happens to
us,'' she said. ``Washington Heights isn't important for them.
That's what they said on the radio. That's not fair. People live
here, too.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Espinosa family sat in their sweaty living room
Wednesday afternoon under the portrait of a winking Jesus and tried
to keep their sense of humor. They were doing what they could to
stay cool, which is to say they were doing mostly nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Elida Espinosa, 59, pushed the straps of her thin nightgown off
her shoulder as she fanned herself with an old lottery ticket. Her
husband, Manuel, 66, who had earlier brought water from the bodega
downstairs to police officers stationed on the corner, sweated
through his tank-top undershirt. Five of their seven grown children
were sacked out on couches _ no work Wednesday, since the trains
weren't running reliably.
</P>
<P>
   When the lights went out Tuesday at about 10 p.m., Isaac Ben
Atar closed Bolero's, his Argentine steakhouse. He returned
Wednesday at 6 a.m. to find the place pitch-black, the food rapidly
spoiling in the refrigerators.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Atar quickly set up tables on the sidewalk and laid out his
sumptuous lunch buffet, prepared the night before, filled with
meats, chicken, lobster, salads and tiramisu imported from Italy.
Police officers and other emergency workers, along with people from
the neighborhood, gobbled it down before 10:30 a.m. Then Ben Atar
returned to the more depressing task of throwing out the raw meats
and other inventory _ too much to count, he said, but surely in the
five-figure range _ as his employees took crates of lemons,
cucumbers and plantains to a friend's refrigerator in Fort Lee,
N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no sense to keep it because it's going to go bad
anyway _ might as well let them enjoy it,'' Ben Atar said with a
shrug when asked about the giveaway. ``If I lose it, I lose it, I'm
not going to go crazy,'' he added, lighting up a cigarette. ``What
am I going to do, get sick? My health is more important.''
</P>
<P>
   Back at Carter's apartment building, health was the primary
concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't try to take the stairs, but I'll be fine as long as
I've got my ice pack,'' said Ester Landes, who lives next to Carter
and declined to give her advanced age. ``I'm not going to complain,
because my complaints aren't any different than others. We're all
in the same mess right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Several elderly residents of the six-story, U-shaped, red-brick
building left Wednesday morning to sit out the blackout at the
homes of relatives or friends. ``I'm leaving because the weather is
too wonderful here,'' joked Dorothy Gabriel, 95, as her home
health-care attendant led her to a hired car. ``I'm looking for
worse weather.''
</P>
<P>
   Herman Salamon, 89, who said he survived in a Russian labor camp
during World War II, dreamt Tuesday night that he was outside in a
breeze.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have high blood pressure and my heart is bad, but I have to
face this,'' said Salamon, who emerged from his apartment clad only
in khaki shorts. ``I do not complain because this is the best
country in the whole world. But I don't know why, if you can send a
man to the moon, you can't prevent something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Miguel de la Rosa, like many of his neighbors, said that the
blackout reminded him of his home in Santo Domingo, Dominican
Republic, where flickering lights are commonplace, but that he
never expected to experience the same thing ``in the No. 1 city in
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   When the electricity returned, de la Rosa raced inside to check
that his television was working, then joined the barbecue on the
sidewalk at 159th and Broadway to wait for his air-conditioner to
cool down his apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good because I miss my TV,'' he said of the restored
electricity. ``I'm going to go in right now and watch the Mets
game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
