<HEADER>
A2355 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-CAMP08-CO     07-07 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-CAMP08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anderson misses Falcons mini-camp
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUWANEE, Ga. _ Jamal Anderson's absence from the mini-camp was
noticeable Wednesday even before the Falcons took the field for the
opening practice.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Chris Chandler jogged slowly out of the team's
locker room, glanced at the heavens and said, ``Where's Jamal at?
Come on, Jamal.''
</P>
<P>
   The contract holdout of Anderson, who led the NFC in rushing
last year, officially kicked off the opening day of a three-day
mini-camp, which is mandatory for all players on the Falcons'
80-man roster. Anderson already had missed the team's offseason
workouts and passing camps, but they were optional.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's agent, Jim Sims, and the Falcons are in the process
of negotiating a contract extension going into the final year of
his current deal.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, right guard Gene Williams and kicker Morten Andersen
were the only no-shows on the mini-camp's first day. Williams also
desires a contract extension; Andersen was excused for personal
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamal and Gene both have contracts (for the upcoming season),
and I fully expected them to honor it and be here,'' coach Dan
Reeves said. ``It's not like we haven't had a conversation where
they didn't understand what the situation was. I am disappointed
they aren't here, you bet.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said both players will receive the maximum fine for each
day of skipping mini-camp. According to the collective bargaining
agreement, a player can be fined as much as $1,000 for the team
violation.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons officials were unsure until the start of practice
whether Anderson would attend. Sims had faxed two contract
proposals to the team late Tuesday night, and Anderson reportedly
bought a plane ticket to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   However, the white No. 32 practice jersey stayed in Anderson's
locker as his teammates went through 90 minutes of conditioning and
passing drills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm optimistic about (the negotiations with Anderson),''
Falcons general manager Harold Richardson said. ``I want to get it
done. They want to get it done. We both certainly hope we can.
Again, I'm very optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   The mini-camp lasts two more days, today and Friday. While talks
continue between the Falcons and Anderson, Richardson confirmed
Wednesday that the All-Pro running back probably would not report
to Suwanee within the next 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be hard to do,'' Richardson said. ``With a contract
that size, it is generally hard to get one done that quickly.
Again, I'm always optimistic. In reality, it is tough to wrap up
things that fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to get things done as soon as we can,'' he said.
``The bottom line is that we were the ones who initiated the talks.
There was no necessity for us to do anything. We're the ones trying
to extend his contract, just as much as he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than the comment by Chandler at the start of practice,
Anderson's absence drew few remarks by the players.
</P>
<P>
   Several said they think the no-show is no big deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's business as usual,'' cornerback Ray Buchanan said.
``Jamal is one of the thumping heartbeats of this team, and we need
him here. But at the same time, he needs to think about himself and
the contract situation. He deserves a lot of money because he has
done a lot for this football team.''
</P>
<P>
   Fullback Bob Christian said, ``Everyone understands that this is
business, and this is the way business goes sometimes. We all know
he'll come in (eventually) and won't miss a beat when he gets here.
Until then, we don't have control over it, so why worry about it?''
</P>
<P>
   Offensive tackle Bob Whitfield made light of the situation, with
an eye toward his own future contract negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm under contract, too,'' Whitfield said. ``If (Reeves)
doesn't give me more respect with this heat and all of these dang
40-yard dashes, then I am going to sit out my last two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the team needs to take care of Jamal,'' he said with a
straight face, ``just like they are going to have to take care of
me when he gets his deal. Because if Jamal makes that much more
than me, I'm holding out, too.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
