<HEADER>
A2356 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMOKERS08-COX     07-07 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOKERS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jury finds tobacco firms liable
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In a stunning setback for the nation's beleaguered
tobacco industry, a Miami jury ruled Wednesday that cigarette
makers are liable for tobacco-related illnesses suffered by
thousands of Florida smokers.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic verdict comes in the first class-action lawsuit
against the industry to go to trial and could lead to the companies
being ordered to pay $200 billion or more in damages. The amount
will be determined in another phase of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   And the huge financial hit for the industry might not end there.
The verdict could open the door for similar lawsuits in other
jurisdictions, leading to a never-ending litigation nightmare that
tobacco executives have been trying to avoid by negotiating
settlements with dozens of states.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami verdict is unrelated to those settlements because the
lawsuit was brought by a private attorney representing smokers who
live in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In language likely to shake the standing of tobacco stocks on
Wall Street, jurors found the industry liable for conspiracy, fraud
and negligence. They said the companies must pay punitive damages _
yet to be determined _ that could reach staggering amounts.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco stock prices fell immediately after the late-afternoon
verdict. Philip Morris lost $2.62 1/2, or 6 percent, to close at
$37.87 1/2 on the New York Stock Exchange. R.J. Reynolds fell $1.18
3/4, or nearly 4 percent, to close at $30.87 1/2. Loew's Corp.,
parent of Lorillard, lost 81 1/4 cents, or 1 percent, to close at
$79.06 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys in the case could not comment on the verdict because
of a gag rule imposed by Miami-Dade County Circuit Judge Robert
Kaye.
</P>
<P>
   But anti-smoking activists were vocally jubilant.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really a clean sweep, a tremendous victory for the
public health and for the hundreds of thousands of victims in
Florida,'' said Richard Daynard, a Northeastern University law
professor and tobacco industry critic.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict applies to the five largest U.S. tobacco companies:
Philip-Morris Inc., R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co., Lorrillard Tobacco
Co., Brown and Williamson Tobacco Corp. and the Liggett Group. Two
industry groups, the Council for Tobacco Research and the Tobacco
Institute, also were named in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was brought by Miami attorney Stanley Rosenblatt, who
last year settled another precedent-setting case against the
industry. In that case, cigarette makers agreed to pay nearly $350
million to settle claims by flight attendants who argued that they
were made ill by second-hand smoke endured on airliners in the
decades before smoking was banned on domestic flights.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt filed this class-action lawsuit in 1994 on behalf of
all Florida smokers and relatives of smokers made ill by the habit.
The case didn't come to trial until last summer; testimony took
eight grueling months.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of Rosenblatt's argument was that the tobacco
companies knowingly misled the public, making a deadly product that
they aimed especially at youth _ while they hid documents and
research that could have convinced the public to avoid the habit.
</P>
<P>
   ``These shameless purveyors of an unhealthy product have done
everything they could to hook people,'' Rosenblatt argued. He cited
internal industry memos that discussed ways to increase market
share among smokers called ``young adults.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They called them young adults, but those were code words for
teen-agers,'' the attorney said. ``That's where the money is, and
they know that better than anybody. If you hook a 14-year-old, look
at all the years he'll be smoking. By the time he gets to be 60, at
two packs a day, that's profit, pure profit.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry countered with the arguments that have worked
through decades of litigation: that there is no direct scientific
proof that smoking causes illness, and that people have known of
the dangers for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Heim, the industry's lead attorney, told jurors the
tobacco companies spent millions of dollars trying to develop safer
cigarettes and never tried to mislead anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 33 years there have been warnings on cigarette packages,''
he said. ``If somebody started smoking a pack a day in 1966, they
would've had the opportunity to see those warnings 200,000 times.''
</P>
<P>
   Jurors clearly didn't buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Given a complicated 10-question verdict form, after a week of
deliberation they ruled for the plaintiffs on nearly all the
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Among their findings: Cigarettes are addictive, they cause
diseases such as cancer and emphysema, and the tobacco companies
engaged in fraud and conspiracy in producing a negligent, defective
product.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict is only the fifth time a jury has found the tobacco
industry liable for its products. Most of the other verdicts have
been overturned on appeal, and it appears likely this case will be
tied up in appeals for years.
</P>
<P>
   But first, jurors must finish the current trial.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye divided the proceedings into three phases. In the first
phase, the jury was to decide whether the companies were liable.
</P>
<P>
   Having done so, they will next hear testimony on the cases of
nine individuals who represent the class, and will set compensatory
and punitive damages in each case.
</P>
<P>
   In the trial's third phase, jurors will set damages for the
entire class, which could include up to 500,000 Florida smokers and
family members of smokers who have died.
</P>
<P>
   Trial experts predicted the verdict will prompt a flood of
similar cases. Although the companies last year agreed to a $206
billion settlement with dozens of states, that does not bar
lawsuits like the one brought in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until now, the tobacco industry has suffered only sporadic
losses,'' said Matt Myers of the National Center for Tobacco-Free
Kids. ``Today's decision opens up the door for hundreds of
thousands of smokers to come into court.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
