<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: AMERICANS STILL DINE TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Back a few decades, there was a Boston Red Sox
team so dysfunctional that a night on the road was described as 25
players going off in 25 taxis.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, that condition could fit most teams in most sports.
Michael Jordan traveled with his own entourage, emerging from his
cocoon in time to catch the team bus. The noted iron man, Cal
Ripken Jr., is famous for staying in a different hotel from the
team.
</P>
<P>
   On a free night, most male professional athletes go off with
wife or girl friend, agent, lawyer, family members, designated best
friend, or some interesting combination thereof. And why not? It's
a long season, often a long career, and everybody needs some space.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, one team that still seeks that ancient state
called togetherness. In the mad gathering hurricane of the Women's
World Cup, the American players are committed to remaining as close
as they were on the long bus rides from exhibition to exhibition,
when they hoped somebody would show up to watch them play.
</P>
<P>
   This was only a few months ago, by the way. Now the women have
been discovered by crowds with fistfuls of dollars, selling out the
Rose Bowl for the final with China on Saturday. The women have been
discovered by fans who ring their telephones and knock on their
doors. They have been discovered by a chief executive who will
inconvenience tens of thousands by barging in with his phalanx of
protectors. The women have been discovered by television crews who
swarm into news conferences.
</P>
<P>
   The women have now been discovered by Americans, who are said to
equally disdain women's sports and any version of soccer, at least
according the guys at NBC who just could not bear to show this very
same team back in the 1996 Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   This event is hot and getting hotter. Last Sunday's victory over
Brazil at Stanford University attracted the largest soccer ratings
ever for ESPN, a total of 2.9 million homes compared to the
previous record of 2.7 million homes for the United States' upset
victory over Colombia during the men's World Cup in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Something is happening here, and the women feel it. ``Our lives
have changed,'' said Tiffeny Milbrett, the optimistic little
buzzbomb of the front line. ``But we want to keep focused.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no timeouts in soccer, but the women called one
anyway. On Tuesday night, they chose to go out for a team dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of family and friends around, but this was just
for the team,'' said Cindy Parlow, the tall forward who played her
best game of the World Cup in the semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   The co-captains, Mia Hamm and Julie Foudy, organized the
expedition to a Mexican restaurant near the team hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was getting tired of bland hotel food, and we just
wanted to go out together,'' Parlow said. ``We had a good time,
taking pictures of each other. People don't see how close we are
off the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Close quarters do not necessarily enhance team spirit. The
American men were cloistered in a picturesque chateau in Burgundy
last summer in France, and spent most of their time backbiting, en
route to finishing dead last in their World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   And even the American women were distracted in 1995, according
to Kristine Lilly and others, because of bickering over whether
they would wear their sponsors' shoes or the ones the national
soccer federation wanted them to wear. They had four years of bus
rides and ``friendly'' games to think about priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Now they are back in the American version of the World Cup.
Wednesday's news media day at the Century Plaza Hotel was not
exactly the same dimension as the Super Bowl production, to which
the National Football League herds every last bulked-up brute.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilians, competing for third place, sent one player. The
Norwegians, also playing for third place, sent one assistant coach.
The Chinese sent one assistant coach, Yan Zhongjian, who noticed
the Americans were late arriving, and said, through an interpreter,
``Normally, the host waits for the guest, but today we wait for the
host.''
</P>
<P>
   The two Americans, Parlow and Milbrett, finally arrived after
the long haul from their training session in Pomona. They chatted
to the swarms from the news media. They seemed happy to be there.
</P>
<P>
   They have waited four years to get back to the World Cup, and
they still like each other, and they still go out to dinner
together _ 20 players, one restaurant. What a concept.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
