<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALT DISNEY SETTLES SUIT WITH FORMER STUDIO CHIEF
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney Co. and its former studio chief, Jeffrey Katzenberg,
reached a settlement of a lawsuit that had opened a curtain on the
lives of Hollywood moguls whose egos, financial bonanzas and
personal furies are usually kept veiled. And it brought to a close
the glare of publicity that had both distracted and embarrassed two
of the most powerful men in the American entertainment industry.
The terms of the settlement were not disclosed. But entertainment
industry lawyers said that Katzenberg could eventually receive at
least $200 million, including the $117 million that Disney had
already paid him. Katzenberg had initially said that Disney owed
him at least $250 million in bonuses. He later raised that to $580
million.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET GAUGES RECORD NEW HIGHS
</P>
<P>
   The three major stock market gauges recorded new highs. The Dow
Jones industrial average advanced 52.24 points, to 11,187.36, and
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 7.74 points, to
1,395.86. The technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index gained 6.26
points, to 2,743.04.
</P>
<P>
   WASTE MANAGEMENT STOCK PLUNGES
</P>
<P>
   Investors sent shares of Waste Management into freefall, a day
after the company warned analysts that revenue and earnings for the
second quarter were much lower than anyone had expected. The
company's shares tumbled $19.625, or 36.6 percent, to $33.9375, its
lowest price since the company was formed last July when USA Waste
Services acquired Waste Management.
</P>
<P>
   FRAUD CONVICTIONS ARE OVERTURNED
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court threw out the fraud convictions of an
airline insurer and its former chief executive who had been accused
of trying to avoid financial responsibility in a 1987 commuter
plane crash in California.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING CHOOSES GE FOR JET ENGINE
</P>
<P>
   Boeing said that it had chosen General Electric to build the
world's most powerful jet engine for a new ultra-long-range version
of its wide-body 777 jetliner.
</P>
<P>
   MERGERS URGED FOR ARMS MAKERS
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon is aggressively encouraging trans-Atlantic mergers
in the military industry, beginning direct talks with European
allies and major contractors in Europe in a new push for
cooperative agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ERICSSON'S CHIEF EXECUTIVE QUITS
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive of Swedish telecommunications company
Ericsson, Sven-Christer Nilsson, resigned just 15 months after his
appointment. The news sent the company's stock down nearly 8
percent. Investors had grown concerned about Ericsson's direction
under Nilsson, who rattled them with repeated profit warnings.
</P>
<P>
   TOYOTA SEEKS TO ALTER SALARY RULES
</P>
<P>
   Toyota is negotiating with its union to eliminate seniority as a
major factor in determining the salaries of white-collar workers.
</P>
<P>
   BURGER BATTLE ON A NEW FRONT
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's threw the latest punch in its long-running food fight
with Burger King, suing its arch rival over the phrase, ``Big Kid's
Meal,'' contending the food-and-toy combo is essentially a
knock-off product.
</P>
<P>
   DEADLINE LOOMS IN AIR CANADA TALKS
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of air travel chaos in Canada loomed closer as
negotiators sought to avert a strike threatened for early today by
flight attendants of Air Canada.
</P>
<P>
   PUTNAM TEAMS UP WITH BUYOUT FIRM
</P>
<P>
   Putnam Investments and Thomas H. Lee Co. formed a partnership to
offer investments in hedge funds and private companies to wealthy
individuals and institutions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
