<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2374 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     07-07 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: OIL CAN BOYD AT PEACE WITH HIS OWN TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dennis (Oil Can) Boyd was talking about peace, and being at
peace. But Boyd, the intense, tightly wound pitcher, had never
seemed at peace or at rest.
</P>
<P>
   Peaceful, peace-loving, restful, yes. But not at peace. As a
clever right-handed pitcher for the Boston Red Sox from 1982 to
1989, Boyd became one of the most effective pitchers in baseball.
His pitching style was smooth agitation: the ball seemed to come at
batters from all angles. He pitched like his hero, Satchel Paige,
but with deception. When Boyd was sharp, batters never knew what
was coming or where it was coming from. The ball always looked
faster and harder than it really was.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd was intense and busy. Call whatever he is now a truce or a
cease fire. Not at peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't think I'm at peace with myself,'' Boyd said in a
phone interview from his home in Meridian, Miss. ``But I was only
mad about something that I loved so much, and that's baseball. I
just kept asking myself, `Why am I so good at something that I do
that treats me so damn bad?'''
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen years ago this month, Boyd _ with an 11-6 record at the
halfway point _ was on the way to his best season in the majors.
For all his numbers, Boyd was left off the All-Star Game roster.
The late Dick Howser, who managed the American League team, said he
needed extra bats off the bench. Boyd learned about the snub in the
Red Sox clubhouse and flew into a rage. The team suspended him for
three days.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to filter the 1986 explosion through a 1999 prism, Boyd,
who will turn 40 on Oct. 6, said he would not change much. ``I
thought I should be where the best are,'' Boyd said. ``An All-Star
knows he's an All-Star. I'd do it over again. I might not go as
far, but I'd be just as mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Boyd, who was known during his playing days as one who
bucked the system, owns a piece of the system. On May 22, 2000,
Boyd's Queen City Bombers begin their first season of play in the
Texas-Louisiana Independent league. They will play on a field that
Boyd owns, in a 4,000-seat stadium that Boyd is building. His team
will wear gray and silver uniforms with Negro League knickers. And
guess who will be on the mound opening day? The indomitable Can.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm making history,'' Boyd said. ``I'm the only owner that
plays, and I'm planning to play until I'm as old as Satchel Paige.
We own the land, we own the team, we own the stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bombers belong to a 13-team league, part of a growing
phenomenon of the Independent baseball circuit. The distinction
between Independent baseball and the minor leagues is talent level
and affiliation. Independent teams have no ties to major league
clubs, and the level of play is considered to be below the level of
the Class AA Eastern League. Independent ball caters to cities more
than the organization; many teams are named after the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more of a free-spirited game, more relaxed, not as much
pressure,'' Boyd said. ``Independent leagues offer a way for a
young guy to make his way back to the majors. Gives players a
second chance to prove themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Strawberry played in an Independent League when the
Yankees picked him up. Boyd played Independent League baseball in
Mexico after his major league career ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was considered a drawing card,'' Boyd said. ``I thought one
day I could do this and do it for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyd played baseball at Jackson State; he was chosen by the Red
Sox in the 16th round of the June free-agent draft in 1980. Within
three years he was in the Red Sox's starting rotation. He was an
early hit with fans, but the culmination of idiosyncrasies,
injuries and un-baseball-like outbursts wore on management and some
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd, plagued by a succession of injuries from 1987 to '89, left
Boston and went to Montreal. Boyd was traded to Texas, his final
team, in 1991 at age 32. During the 1995 strike, Boyd signed with
the Chicago White Sox as a replacement player.
</P>
<P>
   For the longest time, Boyd was consumed by anger and bitterness.
``There wasn't peace my house at one time,'' Boyd said. ``I wanted
to beat my wife, run my kids away. I was mad with the game _ I
wasn't anybody to live with for a good five years after I finished
playing. Now there's peace in my house.''
</P>
<P>
   He still wants to play, but on his terms. ``I'm not a
controllable person,'' Boyd said, ``I'm not a person who'll jump
for you. I'm not like that and never was. I appreciated what God
gave me more than what man gave me.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyd wants the Queen City Bombers to be his legacy to his
community and his family. But you wonder: how will Oil Can, the
owner, react when he confronts players who march to the tune of
their own drummer? ``I can deal with attitudes because everyone
isn't the same,'' Boyd said. ``I do it every day, and that's the
way I was in the clubhouse. Everybody in the clubhouse knew me
differently. When they played with me, they all could tell a
different story about me.''
</P>
<P>
   Oil Can, peace and the Queen City Bombers. I can't wait for this
debut.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
