CHINA-WILD-WEST, 07-07 -- A crew from the Xinjiang Production and
Construction Corps work on farmland that previously was a desert
region some 100 miles south of Aksu, China. The men and machines of
the Corps, as the construction company is known, have led China's
drive to settle and secure this alien region for nearly half a
century. (Erik Eckholm/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- July 7, 1999 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 07-07
-- Creating a concrete slab does not require any special building
skills, but it is hard work. At least two people are required to
move the concrete, pour it, level it, then smooth and rough it.
Weather is an important consideration. Since all the work will be
done outdoors, you must pick a dry day with no rain in the
forecast. The temperature should be between 65 and 75 degrees
Fahrenheit. (Edward R. Lipinski/New York Times Illustration) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WASHINGTON -- July 6, 1999 -- PUERTORICO-FIRING-RANGE,
7-06 -- Secretary of the Navy Richard Danzig, left, meets with Gov.
Pedro Rossello, right, of Puerto Rico on June 15. The U.S. Navy on
suspended all land operations at a firing range in Puerto Rico
pending an investigation ordered by President Clinton into the
risks posed to residents after a man was killed by bombs. Puerto
Rican independence activists and fishermen have staged protests at
the base since Marine jets mistakenly bombed an observation tower
in April, killing a civilian security guard and injuring four
people, including a Navy officer. (Senior Chief PhotographerUs Mate
Terry A. Cosgrove/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- July 7, 1999 -- HOMMA-GARDEN-2, 07-07 --
Robert Homma among bonsai, shells and ceramic pots inlaid with
silver in his rooftop garden near Lincoln Center. For Homma, who is
51 and a third-generation Japanese-American, collecting for
himself, which is nearly synonymous with buying for his shop
(Dimson Homma, which sells Ming furniture, celadon porcelain and
rare live birds) is as much a daily ritual, an exercise of the eye
and the hand. (Jeffrey A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- July 7, 1999 -- HOMMA-GARDEN-1, 07-07 --
Ming-style chairs and Japanese rice bowls are framed by shoji
screens that cover the windows, conceal books and open to the
Robert Homma's garden near Lincoln Center. Throughout the
600-square-foot studio, blue predominates. It's in the Tibetan rugs
on the floor and in a French quilt on the bed. ``Some people think
blue is cold, but I think it's calming,'' says Homma, 51, whose
shop sells Ming furniture, celadon porcelain and rare live birds.
(Jeffrey A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) TEANECK, N.J. -- July 7, 1999 -- CIR-ONLINE-BANKING,
07-07 -- Lisa and Alex Giassa, shown at home in Teaneck, are among
many people signing up for online banking. ``It's definitely a
convenience thing for us,'' says Mrs. Giassa, who, with Alex, has
had an online account since August 1998. ``If I know I have a bill
due in a few days, I can go upstairs, pay it in a couple of minutes
and not deal with any envelopes.'' (Norman Y. Lono/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) PASADENA, Calif. -- July 7, 1999 -- CIR-HACKERS, 07-07 --
Frank Keeney has increased security on his computer system. Two
weeks after he was first connected to cable modem service in
Pasadena, he discovered that the 24-hour high-speed Internet access
came with a potential for big trouble. ``I went to log in and found
that someone had compromised my computer,'' he recalls. ``I tried
to kill his log-in session, but it was too late. I watched while he
erased everything on my hard drive.'' (Edward Carreon/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) RARITAN, N.J. -- July 7, 1999 -- CIR-COMPUTER-BUILDING-2,
07-07 -- Shoppers at a Raritan computer fair - like the ones
frequented by the author. At such weekend fairs, computer
components are sold like secondhand watches. Many parts, in
addition to monitors and printers, are sold for as low as 30 to 50
percent of manufacturers' suggested retail prices. But caution is
advised. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- July 7, 1999 -- CIR-COMPUTER-BUILDING-1, 07-07
-- Months of work finally led to a homemade PC with lots of extras.
Paul R. Migliore, a consultant based in Englewood, N.J., has built
a house full of computers in the last four years. But after a
recent run of compatibility problems, he is growing less
enthusiastic about do-it-yourself PCs. ``When you start to
calculate the cost of the endless hours that go into it and the
emotional strain, it adds up'' he says. (Tony Cenicola/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) MITROVICA, Yugoslavia -- July 7, 1999 -- KOSOVO-SERBS,
07-07 -- French gendarmes, one pointing to an area where rocks are
being thrown, try to shield two ethnic Albanian women on Wednesday
in the town, 25 miles north of Pristina. The gendarmes were trying
to escort the women into the Serb-held side of a bridge which has
become a de facto border between the Serb and ethnic Albanian
sectors of the city. The women were unable to reach their
destination due to the unrest. (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BINGHAMTON -- July 7, 1999 -- NY-MRSCLINTON-2, 07-07 --
Hillary Rodham Clinton greets supporters outside the Binghamton New
York Airport on Wednesday shortly after her arrival. Launching her
historic campaign for the Senate, Mrs. Clinton pledged on Wednesday
to be a ``strong and effective advocate on behalf of the people of
New York.'' (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) DAVENPORT, N.Y. -- July 7, 1999 -- NY-MRSCLINTON, 07-07
-- Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., left, and Hillary Rodham
Clinton walk towards reporters on Wednesday at Moynihan's farm.
Launching her historic campaign for the Senate, Mrs. Clinton
pledged on Wednesday to be a ``strong and effective advocate on
behalf of the people of New York.'' (Keith Meyers/New York Times
Photo)
