<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2379 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-IOWA-NYT &LR;      07-07 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-IOWA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOWA STRAW POLL LURES CASH FROM BUSH
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Only days after George W. Bush said his would be a
penny-pinching presidential operation, his campaign shelled out a
remarkable $43,500 for one day's use of a plot of land outside an
arena in Ames, Iowa, so that he can greet participants arriving
there for a straw poll next month.
</P>
<P>
   To secure the premium spot, the Texas governor's representative
outbid Steve Forbes, the multimillionaire publisher, by $600 at a
silent auction on Tuesday that was conducted by the Iowa Republican
Party as a money-making venture.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Forbes spent $8,000 for a slightly smaller plot.
(The Bush spot is 60,000 square feet; the Forbes spot, 44,000.)
Other candidates spent from $1,000 to $5,500 for their spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa Republicans have never held such an auction, said Ann
Dougherty, communications director for the state party. Four years
ago, she said, campaigns drew lots for the space outside a coliseum
at the Iowa State University in Ames, but did not have to pay for
them. They used the space to greet and feed participants, and to
entertain them with music.
</P>
<P>
   This year, campaigns bid on 11 outdoor spots, generating $78,500
for the state party. That sum is all the more striking because the
straw poll, set for Aug. 14, is a nonbinding popularity contest
that has no direct impact on who wins the state's Republican
caucuses, which will be held early next year.
</P>
<P>
   The financial outpouring demonstrates the important role of
money this early in the campaign. And it demonstrates the
seriousness to which the candidates, particularly Bush, are taking
the straw poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not dream that it would raise the money that it did,''
Ms. Dougherty said. ``It shows that they are dedicated to putting
some resources into the straw poll.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll is the highest profile political event of the summer;
organizers say it will draw more than 10,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week Bush, whose campaign has amassed a
record-shattering $36 million, said in an interview that he
intended to monitor his campaign coffers carefully _ and would not
shower excessive money on the straw poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to support the Iowa Republican Party,'' said Dave
Beckwith, a spokesman for the Bush campaign. ``We didn't want to
support it that much, but that's how it goes. We heard that Iowa
people were grousing that we were throwing money around. But we're
very happy with the way it turned out.''
</P>
<P>
   Other campaigns boasted that they outfoxed the Bush operation,
spending far less for real estate that may not be quite as large,
or as close to the arena, but is perfectly adequate. The Bush
organization will also have to pay about 50 percent of the overhead
costs of the event, including outdoor toilets and electricity,
party officials said. Such costs will be divided among the
campaigns, they added, depending on the value of their outdoor
spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We clearly played the better card game because they actually
had to fork out the money,'' said William Dal Col, Forbes' campaign
chief. ``We will clearly help Governor Bush spend his money.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Kennedy, a veteran of Iowa politics who is the campaign
manager for former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander (whose campaign
spent $4,300 for its space), said, ``Bush is like the guy who came
to the poker game with too much money in his pocket and got taken
by the locals.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to respond, Beckwith said, ``We're more like the guy who
showed up late with a better mousetrap.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The campaigns also tried to outspin one another over who got the
best parcel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the best spot,'' Beckwith said, noting that the Bush
space was closest to the arena's entrance. ``There's no question
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so, insisted Alexander. ``We got the best space for
$4,300.'' Then, referring to Bush, the Tennessean added: ``He got
arguably the third best space for $43,000. It's not a reassuring
sign of how he'd handle the federal debt.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked who had the premium real estate, Ms. Dougherty, the state
party's communications director, played the diplomat. ``It's
debatable,'' she said. ``Some of them are bigger. But some are on
the main road. If you're not expecting a big crowd, you may not
want a big huge space so it looks empty.''
</P>
<P>
   Other contenders who bought outdoor spots and the amount they
spent were Elizabeth Dole, $5,500; Rep. John R. Kasich of Ohio,
$4,500; Gary Bauer, the religious conservative, $4,200; Sen. Robert
C. Smith of New Hampshire, $3,000; former Vice President Dan
Quayle, $2,000; Sen. Orrin G. Hatch of Utah, $1,500; Patrick J.
Buchanan, the commentator, $1,000, and Alan Keyes, a former State
Department official, $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   But the real winner is the Iowa Republican Party. Besides piling
up money for the spots, the party also plans to put the squeeze on
candidates for space inside the arena.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
