<SLUG> BC-OUT-BOATING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRANGE NAUTICAL AFFAIRS IN ORANGE COUNTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEREMY BAGOTT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT BEACH, Calif. _ Why do sailors always seem to have more
fun behind the Orange Curtain?
</P>
<P>
   While one group of Orange County women flags down a freighter in
the middle of the Pacific Ocean, another satirizes Bill Clinton off
Baja California. And an ordained minister who exorcises demons from
ocean-going vessels becomes a clean-energy advocate. Some people
just know how to live. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here they were, idle and alone in the Pacific, on what was
supposed to be a 17-day journey from Honolulu to Newport Beach,
with no means of sustainable propulsion.
</P>
<P>
   They were about six days out with only emergency fuel left in
the tanks when they sailed into a dead calm. The nine-woman crew _
mostly housewives and career women _ were aboard the Volcano, a
64-foot sailboat skippered by sailing instructor Karen Prioleau of
Orange Coast College in Costa Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   They made the best of the calm by preparing complicated meals,
swimming in the warm ocean and holding a masquerade party. ``When
it's that calm,'' said Prioleau, ``you see the reflection of every
star on the water at night.''
</P>
<P>
   Prioleau and first mate Cathie Mullen decided the crew would
just wait out the high-pressure system.
</P>
<P>
   After a few days of this, Prioleau understood two things: The
calm was widening and the crew's exhilaration was a wasting
commodity. Most had kids and husbands in Southern California that
needed tending to, not to mention jobs and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're in the hands of Mother Nature. When I shut down the
engine (to conserve fuel), that's when reality hit,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Then a white knight came to them in the person of one Paul
Skoropowski, captain of the 13,000-ton container ship Sealand
Challenger.
</P>
<P>
   During the journey, the women had spotted freighters and tried
to raise them on Volcano's radio but to no avail . . . except this
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the (freighter's) radio officer that while we weren't
in dire straits, a little fuel would work wonders,'' Prioleau said.
``The freighter altered its course.''
</P>
<P>
   What had been a speck on the horizon in time became a mammoth
wall of metal.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we motored up, everyone had their cameras out,'' Prioleau
said. ``Then we realized the crew aboard the Sealand Challenger all
had (begin ital)their(end ital) cameras out.''
</P>
<P>
   The freighter crewmen attached a garden hose to a heaving line
and threw it over. In a matter of minutes 100 gallons of diesel had
been transferred several hundred feet in the middle of the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Greetings were exchanged, the hoses were separated and the
freighter disappeared, leaving the women wondering whether they had
hallucinated the whole thing. But, 12 hours later, the Volcano had
motored into some wind. The sails were raised and the vessel's
motor saw no further duty on last year's excursion.
</P>
<P>
   The crew arrived only two days late into Newport Beach. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's dusk along the Avenida Lopez Mateos in Ensenada, Mexico.
Hundreds of (begin ital)norteamericanos(end ital) cram the streets
the weekend of the big Newport-to-Ensenada sailboat race. Mariachi
music emanates from Hussong's Cantina. Vendors peddle T-shirts
outside the one-time Hemingway haunt.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, a half-dozen raucous, cigar-smoking women appear,
carrying a life-size blowup doll of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Meet the Women's Impeachment Committee. With this group, it's
the inmates running the asylum. If President Clinton wanted a
legacy, he has it with this all-woman sailing crew that combines
political satire with racing. It's Jimmy Buffett meets Arianna
Huffington meets Frank Zappa.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, at the race's finish line aboard the 49-foot sailboat
Sky, the Orange County women lit footlong cigars. Suggestively
placed peaches were emblazoned on the fronts of their T-shirts (get
it, impeachment); the presidential seal accented the backs.
</P>
<P>
   But the ``odd-y-sea'' wasn't all frivolity. The Women's
Impeachment Committee scored a victory in the non-spinnaker
division of the race's cruising class.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the race,'' said crew member Jane Hoffner, ``I climbed
into the cockpit after a hard watch the night before. It was a
beautiful, sunny morning and there was only one boat in sight _
(America's Cup skipper) Dennis Connor's. We tried to get his
attention with our blow-up Billy, but he was grumpy. He wasn't
being a fun sailor.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the Newport-to-Ensenada in April, the Committee has been
honing its skills in local waters. ``Next year, we'll probably
lampoon one of the candidates,'' said crew member Susan Pickle.
``We could be (Elizabeth) Dole and the Viagra-ettes.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ben &AMP; Jerry, where are you?
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Joe Warren, skipper of the riverboat Angela Louise, is
looking for a mainstream corporate sponsor with an environmental
bent.
</P>
<P>
   His 79-passenger turn-of-the-century craft, home-ported in
Newport Harbor, is billed to soon be the first fully electric ship
of its kind in the U.S. passenger fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling snubbed by the Air Quality Management District and
Southern California Edison, Warren is turning to the private sector
for sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would think Edison, of all people, would be interested. Go
figure,'' said Warren, who was profiled in these pages earlier this
year for his flamboyant exorcisms to rid vessels of ``bad mojo.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
