<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENTAGON-EUROPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON BEGINS ENCOURAGING TRANS-ATLANTIC VENTURES IN DEFENSE
INDUSTRY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon is pursuing a new policy of
encouraging trans-Atlantic mergers and joint ventures in the
military industry, and is beginning direct talks with European
allies and major contractors in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal guess is you'll see more of these trans-Atlantic
mergers within months rather than years,'' Jacques Gansler, the
under secretary of defense for acquisition and technology, said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The policy change, described Wednesday in The Wall Street
Journal, represents a significant turn for the Defense Department,
which for years had discouraged mergers with European companies out
of fear that American technological secrets would be mishandled.
</P>
<P>
   But the battlefields of Kosovo intensified concerns about a
technology gap between the United States and Europe, particularly
in military systems, Gansler said.
</P>
<P>
   During the 78-day air war, U.S. weapons routinely outperformed
European systems, leading to heavy dependency on American warplanes
and precision weapons. Since the European and American systems are
often incompatible, NATO was forced to make several small but
telling compromises, like forcing pilots at times to talk on open
lines because some of the airplanes lacked secure communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be more willing to share our technology with our
allies, and they have to be more willing to control it,'' Gansler
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gansler said both Europe and the United States will have to keep
up with technological improvements. ``The lesson of Kosovo is we
are going to be fighting coalition warfare,'' Gansler said at a
breakfast meeting for journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time the Department of Defense was anti-mergers,''
said Paul Taibl, of Business Executives for National Security, a
nonpartisan organization. ``Now they see the mergers are inevitable
and they're trying to turn a vice into a virtue.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently the European members of NATO devote $8 billion of
their combined military budgets to research and development,
compared with $25 billion spent by the United States. In Europe it
is primarily the French who invest substantially in military
research, said Robin Laird, a consultant involved in trans-Atlantic
defense mergers.
</P>
<P>
   French, British, Italian and German government officials and
industrialists are meeting with top Pentagon officials to discuss
streamlining procedures for mergers with American companies.
France's Aerospatiale SA and Thomson-CSF, British Aerospace PLC and
DASA, the aerospace unit of Daimler-Chrysler AG, are said to be
among the companies hoping to create ventures or mergers with
American companies.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the Pentagon considered France less trustworthy
in keeping secrets than other allies like Britain. But Wednesday
Gansler was at pains to underline that France has proved itself by
protecting its own nuclear technology and by its recent performance
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   According to Pentagon officials and private analysts, the
business trade-off for the United States would be two-fold: It
would help keep the global industry competitive, keeping costs
down, and it would insure that NATO allies were producing systems
and weapons that were compatible.
</P>
<P>
   For Europeans, the benefit is obvious: the opportunity to win a
share of the lucrative American market. Most analysts argue that
the global marketplace has made it impossible to keep out the
Europeans. ``You might as well jump on the bandwagon and try to
control or guide the mergers, rather than become a victim of
them,'' Taibl said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
