<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WOMEN-IMAGE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABES OR BOOTERS: SOCCER TEAM DIVIDED ON THE DIRECTION OF THEIR
IMAGE-MAKING 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Subs to add quotes from Donna DeVarona and Brandi Chastain
and expand on the issue of women athletes as sex objects.) 
(jt) 
 By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Each night on his television show, David Letterman
has been showing a picture of the American women's soccer team, in
which the players are standing shoulder to shoulder like beauty
contestants and appear to be wearing nothing more than ``Late
Show'' T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soccer Moms?'' the show's announcer says as a headline flashes
on the screen. ``Soccer Mamas!''
</P>
<P>
   The players sent him the picture, and they love the bit.
Letterman has proclaimed himself the team owner and spiritual guru
and has given the American women attention they could never have
expected. But, however funny, the comedy routine speaks to a larger
issue of how the team is being portrayed to the American public as
it prepares to face China on Saturday in the final of the Women's
World Cup at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   To a large extent, the players have been willing participants in
the sexualization of the team _ by themselves and by the news media
_ in recent years. Defender Brandi Chastain has appeared in Gear
magazine, crouched behind a soccer ball, wearing only her cleats
and her rippling muscles. The team's co-captain, Julie Foudy, has
posed with her husband for Sports Illustrated's swimsuit issue. Mia
Hamm accepted being chosen as one of People magazine's 50 most
beautiful people.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Foudy was asked by a television reporter, ``What are
your thoughts on 13-year-old boys thinking you're hot?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop,'' Foudy said playfully.
</P>
<P>
   But it hasn't. The aura has increased as the Americans have
progressed in the tournament. Foudy herself has jokingly referred
to the team as ``booters with hooters.'' And by accommodating a
sexual element as part of their image, to go with their ponytailed
good looks and athletic prowess, the American players have sent a
message around the world that women can be both athletic and
feminine in an endeavor that, in many countries, still carries the
stigma that women who play are somehow unwomanly.
</P>
<P>
   American women's teams have commanded the athletic stage mostly
in snapshot moments of Olympic triumph _ as the United States
basketball, softball and gymnastics team did in 1996. But many of
the soccer players have been teammates for most of this decade; in
general they are older, some married, some with children. The
result is a mature, elite group of performers that has blended
athleticism and pride in their physiques, and is one game away from
a world championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least people know who we are now,'' goalkeeper Briana
Scurry said. ``I don't think you have to run around naked to sell
the game, but it's good to at least be on the minds of people. I
don't think it's degrading. People who see us on Letterman and come
to the game will realize we don't just strut around in our little
skirts. Women play as hard as anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Donna DeVarona, an Olympic swimming champion in the 1960s and
the chairwoman of the World Cup organizing committee, remembers
wearing long-sleeve shirts in public for fear of what people would
say about her muscles, and acknowledges that today's female
athletes enjoy a greater comfort level. ``I come from a different
era where we were punished for our sexuality or accused of not
having it,'' she said. ``Either way we couldn't win. I think these
players are so secure, so confident, they respond the way they
feel.''
</P>
<P>
   The development has not come without doubts among the public,
the news media and even within the team that the American women may
be devaluing their athletic accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a bit uncomfortable with Brandi's deal,'' the midfielder
Michelle Akers said of Chastain's decision to pose nude.
``Everybody has to make their own decisions on how they want to be
portrayed. Regardless of that, it has a reflection on us as a team
and women's sports as a whole. You don't want something like that
to detract from the excellence of this team and the message that
we're striving to put out.''
</P>
<P>
   Billie Jean King, the tennis great and activist who has become a
confidante of Foudy, said that posing for a magazine was a matter
of individual choice, ``as long as we don't take away from the
reason they're there in the first place. The most important thing
is not to diminish our skills as athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of blending athleticism with a sexual presence comes
at an important moment when women's sports are booming at all
levels, and when the women's national team has established itself
at relevant points all over the cultural map:
</P>
<P>
   _In setting new attendance records for women's sports and
drawing television ratings higher than hockey received during the
Stanley Cup playoffs, the American team has become a marketer's
dream with skilled, college-educated, funny, accessible and
attractive players.
</P>
<P>
   _As members of the first generation of female athletes to fully
benefit from Title IX, which essentially forbid discrimination on
the basis of gender, they are role models for adolescent girls who
attend matches with their faces painted red, white and blue.
</P>
<P>
   _As wage earners, they underscore the disparity in pay for women
and men that remains an urgent issue in the workplace, and most
recently, cropped up as a contentious element in the Wimbledon
tennis championships. The American women earn salaries and would
receive a $12,500 bonus for winning the World Cup, compared to the
$20,000 the American men received for simply making the 1998 men's
World Cup tournament and the $388,000 apiece they would have
received for winning. ``If you think about it, the women are being
discounted,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   _As a homogenous group of mostly white women in ponytails, they
point up the limited progress soccer has made in casting a talent
net that would include more black and Hispanic players. In the
United States, women's soccer at the grass-roots level is largely
middle class, suburban and white. Only two members of the women's
national team are black, the goalkeepers Scurry and Saskia Webber.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question needs to be asked, would this team be receiving
all this attention if they looked like the Brazilian women's
national team _ boyish, wholly unglamorous and black?'' said David
Hirshey, the executive editor of Harper Collins, which published a
book by Hamm called ``Go for the Goal.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, the players have been able to find their own level of
comfort, first and foremost, because they have been successful,
having won the first Women's World Cup in 1991 and an Olympic gold
medal in 1996. But King said she was concerned that female athletes
feel pressured to conform to the idealized version of bouncy
femininity represented by the ponytailed figure that is the
official Women's World Cup logo.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain has said repeatedly that she posed for Gear magazine to
show her body as the instrument of her talent and to send a message
that women athletes can be strong, confident and unashamed of their
physiques. It is a message that some of America's top female track
and field stars are trying to conveying by posing for a nude
calendar. ``I'm proud of my body,'' Chastain said. ``I have bigger
biceps and shoulders than my dad. I'm not going to hide it.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Chastain, the defender Joy Fawcett said: ``She just
wanted to get the point across that she feels good about herself,
and everyone should be able to feel good about themselves.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the women are confident that their athletic
accomplishments remain the most important part of the experience.
``You're never going to escape sexual references with women,''
Foudy said. ``If we can make sure we're successful on the field, I
think people will come for the product, rather than what the
product looks like.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
