<HEADLINE>
CIPOLLINI WINS HIS 9TH TOUR DE FRANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Italy, france, Germany, Estonia, France)  (dw) 
 By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLOIS, France _ Where's Cipo?
</P>
<P>
   To all those who have been asking that question, Mario Cipollini
gave his answer Wednesday: in his usual place, crossing the finish
line ahead of everybody else in the Tour de France and, in fact,
faster than anyone had completed a non-time trial stage since the
classic race began in 1903.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth consecutive day, a stage ended in a mass sprint
and, for the first time, Cipollini, who is regarded, especially by
himself, as the fastest sprinter around, proved it. This time
nobody pulled the claws of the Lion King.
</P>
<P>
   Forget his 29th place in the sprint Sunday, third place Monday
and 10th place Tuesday. As he explained, ``It's not always the best
man who wins.''
</P>
<P>
   That was then, of course. This was now, and it's different. ``I
was motivated,'' he said. ``The team worked perfectly for me and I
felt very strong.''
</P>
<P>
   He had to be, because Erik Zabel was motivated himself for this
fourth daily stage of 20. The German leader of the Telekom team was
celebrating his 29th birthday and desperately wanted the victory.
Instead, by half a wheel, Zabel came away with his 16th
second-place finish of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart O'Grady, an Australian with Credit Agricole, was third,
followed immediately by nearly all of the 177-man pack, including
Jay Sweet, an Australian with Big Mat-Auber, in a splendid 10th
place.
</P>
<P>
   There was a change in the overall standing, where Jaan Kirsipuu,
an Estonian with Casino, remained the leader while O'Grady advanced
to second place, switching rank with Tom Steels, a Belgian with
Mapei, who dipped to third. None are climbers and are unlikely to
remain at the top in the mountains, if indeed they stay there after
the first of two long time trials on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Cipollini, an Italian who rides for Saeco, was timed in 3 hours
51 minutes 45 seconds for the 194.5-kilometer (121-mile) flash from
Laval to the Loire Valley city of Blois. The speed, 50.3 kilometers
an hour, (31 miles an hour) exceeded the record of 49.4 kph (30.7
mph) set in 1993 when Johan Bruyneel, a Belgian who now directs the
United States Postal Service team, won the Evreux-to-Amiens stage.
</P>
<P>
   On a chilly day and before another huge crowd, the pack was
pushed along by a strong tail wind and covered 52 kilometers (32
miles) in each of the first two hours. Although that speed limited
breakaways, 10 riders tried at Kilometer 61 (Mile 38) and were left
to dangle 20 seconds ahead as the pack refused to slow and the
would-be fugitives could not physically go any faster.
</P>
<P>
   The torture ended at Kilometer 91 (Mile 56) for eight of them,
but Gianpaolo Mondini, an Italian with Cantina Tollo, and Anthony
Morin, a Frenchman with La Francaise des Jeux, persisted. They,
too, were allowed a 20-second lead until the charging pack
relented.
</P>
<P>
   Off went the two. Mondini, who ranked 158th, 20:32 behind, and
Morin, who ranked 90th, 7:07 behind, were no threats to the overall
leaders and so were left free to enjoy the flat countryside that
opened before them: the pastures and cornfields of the Mayenne
region changing to seas of wheat and the first grapevines of the
lower Loire.
</P>
<P>
   Their lead got as high as 6:20 at Kilometer 118 (Mile 73) before
the top sprinters' teams went to the front of the pack to raise the
speed and restore order. By the time the leaders took a left turn
and began racing parallel to the Loire River and its many sandbars,
the gap was a little more than three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Down and down it came, with Mondini and Morin caught about 6
kilometers (3.7 miles) from the finish. Within sight of Blois'
awesome 13th-century chateau, the pack turned right and crossed a
stone bridge into the final kilometer.
</P>
<P>
   In the first three stages, Cipollini's team has looked somewhat
ragged in organizing a pace for him in what the riders call the
Saeco train. This time they got it right and the express went to
the front.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian roared into the final 500 meters (546.6 yards)
behind two teammates and, as the first dropped off, the second,
Gian Matteo Fagnini, provided the leadout slipstream into the last
200 meters (218.6 yards). After that, it was up to Cipo.
</P>
<P>
   He pulled hard for the line and Zabel, trying to pass on the
Italian's left, could not do it. Some birthday he had.
</P>
<P>
   This was the ninth victory for Cipollini, 32, in six Tours de
France and his 123rd triumph in 10 years as a professional.
Although the finish was too tight for him to raise his arms in his
usual victory benediction for his rivals, there was no doubt that
the lion remained king.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
