<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-FRANCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS' FRANCO MAY MISS THE REST OF THE SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JACK CURRY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John Franco is facing the possibility that he may
miss the rest of the regular season with a finger injury.
</P>
<P>
   Franco, the Mets' closer, had a magnetic resonance imaging test
Wednesday that showed a partial tear to the sheath of the flexor
tendon of his left middle finger. General Manager Steve Phillips
initially said Wednesday that Franco could miss from 3 to 10 weeks,
but twice mentioned that it could be as much as 12 weeks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since Franco's finger will be immobilized for three weeks in
what he called ``one lousy, ugly looking, little splint,'' it is
highly improbable that he will return before August because he will
need to regain strength in his arm whenever the finger heals.
Armando Benitez will be the closer at least until Franco returns
and perhaps beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect John to be back this season,'' Phillips said. ``It's
a matter of how much of the season he's going to be back for. Even
if it's the outside of 10 weeks or 12 weeks, he'll be back.''
</P>
<P>
   When Phillips was asked to clarify the two-week difference in
the worst-case scenario dates, he said: ``We don't expect him to
write off the season. We expect him back.''
</P>
<P>
   The mentality of a closer is to pitch every day, something
Franco will not be able to do for a long stretch. And that is
something the 38-year-old left-hander has pondered. ``You have to
have a strong mind,'' Franco said. ``I have a strong mind from
being here for a while. It's not going to get the best of me. I'll
be back. It would be different if it was your elbow or your
shoulder. It's a finger.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Phillips said the Mets were more prepared than any
major league team to compensate for the loss of a closer because
Benitez has been impressive and they have depth in a bullpen that
is 14-7 with a 3.24 earned run average and 29 saves in 33 chances,
they are still down one reliable reliever.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how tense Franco can make the ninth inning, he had
saved 19 games in 20 chances and was a candidate for the All-Star
team until injuring himself in the ninth inning of a 16-0 loss to
the Braves last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm without him right now,'' Manager Bobby Valentine said.
``That's my plan. If someone says, `It's no big deal, we can fill
it,' I know it's a big deal. I have to fill it every day until he
comes back.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was one question about Benitez's abilities as a closer
with the Orioles, it was how he rebounded after difficult defeats.
Benitez has been superb this season with 5 saves, a 1.43 earned run
average and 72 strikeouts in 44 innings. But he has also mishandled
three save opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine spoke about this rebounding intangible as something
the Mets might lack without Franco.
</P>
<P>
   ``If things went wrong when John was pitching, he was able to
take all the heat and come back the next day and we'd be all
right,'' Valentine said. ``We'll have to see how that manifests
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said the former Mets Bret Saberhagen and Rick Trlicek
both missed about three months with similar finger injuries, but
Dr. David Altchek, the club physician, has recommended a different
course of treatment for Franco. Instead of immediately trying to
increase the finger's range of motion through exercise and
treatment, Franco's finger will be immobilized for three weeks in
the hopes it will aid the healing process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I seen what Bret went through when he was here,'' Franco said.
``It was a long process. Hopefully, it doesn't go that far. Instead
of hitting it right away, let it relax and simmer down. Maybe it'll
heal quicker that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Could Franco eventually return and find out he lost his closer
job to Benitez?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to worry about that,'' Franco said. ``I want to
get healthy first.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
