<SLUG> BC-TEN-DODO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODO CHENEY: A COMPETITOR IN PEARLS AND LACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JERRY BREWER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When she takes the court, the biggest winner in the history of
the United States Tennis Association wears lace: lace dress with
lace sleeves, lace socks and a lace wristband, and if need be, she
will bring a knee bandage lined with lace. And she always has
pearls around her neck. Dodo Cheney takes her style seriously.
</P>
<P>
   She makes the clothes herself and brags more about her sewing
than about her tennis achievements. But her life has been saturated
with tennis. Her family roots are so laced with tennis tradition
that you would think she was teethed on a racquet.
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy (Dodo) Cheney, now 82 and ranked No. 1 in the country in
the Women's 80s, has won more USTA titles _ 301 and counting _ than
any man or woman in the 118-year history of national tournament
play. Gardnar Mulloy is second with 135.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney will be at the A&AMP;P Tennis Classic in Mahwah, N.J.,
beginning July 14, competing in the Women's 80s division. In the
main event, Steffi Graf, Jana Novotna, Jennifer Capriati and Anna
Kournikova will be playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who wants to go see a bunch of grandmas in Mahwah?'' Cheney
asked recently. ``There're going to be all these great players to
see. Who wants to go see a bunch of grandmas?''
</P>
<P>
   If you respect tennis history, you should want to see Cheney.
She has been the dominant figure in senior women's tennis since she
was 40. All told, her tennis journey spans 74 years. Her body aches
more than it used to, but she still commands the court, standing in
tennis' no-man's land _ her opponents call it Dodoland, the center
of the court near the service line _ daring the opponent to whip a
winner past her.
</P>
<P>
   If you can burn her, great. But she is a grandmother with a
killer drop shot. And she has extraordinary reflexes, one of the
many skills she hones by ``doing a lot of yard work and
gardening.'' Forget the gym; swatting away flies and bugs while
tending to the flowers can work a muscle or two, she figures.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney had success in her prime, but she never became a major
star. She finished the 1937, 1938 and 1941 seasons ranked No. 3 in
the United States. She advanced to the semifinals of the United
States championships at Forest Hills four times, but she could
never go further. She says it was because she was too busy enjoying
her family _ she had two children, Brian Cheney and Christie Putnam
_ and trying to keep from being obsessed with tennis.
</P>
<P>
   It may have cost Cheney a spot in the International Tennis Hall
of Fame. Despite the pleas of fellow players and fans for the past
20 years, the Hall of Fame has not inducted her, although in the
early 1980s she was given a special citation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sort of figure your career is over before they ask you to
come into the Hall of Fame,'' Cheney said. ``So, maybe when I'm in
a wheelchair, maybe they'll say to themselves, `Dodo should be in
there.' But I hope that they don't do anything until then.''
</P>
<P>
   It might be quite a wait, given how long Cheney has played, and
played well. Sixty-one years ago, she became the first American
woman to win the Australian Championships, a forerunner of the
Australian Open. Nine years ago, at age 73, she played a
10-year-old phenom named Venus Williams, in an exhibition match.
</P>
<P>
   ``She blitzed me,'' recalled Cheney, who lives in La Jolla,
Calif. ``She just wiped me off the court. She was 10, but she
looked like she was about 15. She was big. It's good for a person
to get a sound beating from time to time. It's a leveler.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney grew up in Santa Monica, Calif. When she was an infant,
two of her brothers could not yet pronounce Dorothy and opted for
Dodo. Her parents, Thomas and May Sutton Bundy, were great tennis
players. Thomas won three straight national doubles championships
from 1912-1914 and twice earned a spot on the Davis Cup team. May,
a 1956 Hall of Fame inductee, was the first American woman to win
the Wimbledon singles, in 1905, and won it again in 1907. Cheney's
three brothers, her aunts, uncles, cousins and now her children and
some of her eight grandchildren have played tennis competitively.
Many of them have won championships.
</P>
<P>
   One day, while Cheney and one of her brothers were playing
handball outside the family's beach house, her brother's hand began
hurting. He went in the house and found one of his mom's old tennis
racquets. Cheney thought ``that looks fun,'' and found one for
herself.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney was introduced to real tennis at age 8, and she collected
a Southern California junior championship the next year. But even
then Cheney wanted more out of life than tennis success.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney tells the story of how she was leading by 5-2 in the
second set and serving for the match in a junior tournament. Cheney
began to feel sorry for her opponent, she says, and eased up. She
wound up losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave her half an inch, and she took a mile,'' Cheney said.
</P>
<P>
   At another junior tournament, she was defaulted from a match for
not showing up. She had met some teen-age boys, and they all went
fishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't that competitive as a youngster,'' Cheney said.
``Now, though, I'm quite a bit more fierce.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's first USTA national title, in the indoor doubles, came
in 1941 when she was 24, but the bulk of her titles came after she
was 55. In 1975, the USTA began awarding gold balls to the winners
of senior national championships. Before then, the senior champions
were awarded silver balls. Cheney has 301 gold and silver balls.
She has won in singles and doubles, indoors and outdoors, on clay,
grass and hardcourts. She has also won mother-daughter tournaments
with Christie.
</P>
<P>
   After capturing the indoor doubles in 1941, Cheney won the
women's clay-court singles title in 1944, her first national
singles title. In 1954, she joined the senior circuit and reeled
off 13 straight hardcourt singles championships in the Women's 40s
division. Since then, Cheney has been minting gold balls; the most
she has ever won in one year is nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's so hard to beat,'' said Patricia Stuhler, 80, who has
been playing against Cheney since the 1930s. ``I've gotten the
first set from her many times, but lost. Her racquet is always
back. She never rushes. Her anticipation is incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney plays 8 to 10 tournaments a year. If she doesn't think
the competition in the 80s is good enough, she will play in the
75s, or 70s, or the 65s. She often traveled far from her La Jolla
home, because her husband, Arthur, who died 17 years ago, was a
pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Even if she usually plays to crowds of only 50 to 100 people,
Cheney always plays to the crowd. If she hits an unforced error,
she will say: ``Oh, that's too bad.'' Also, according to opponents,
she, like Martina Hingis, is able to think three or four shots
ahead during points.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how she stays relaxed out there,'' said Patricia
Yeomans, 82, who has won nine national titles herself. ``She's very
cagey. She doesn't move more than she has to, but she makes you
move all over the place. She is just a relentless competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps one day Cheney will join her mother in the Hall of Fame.
If so, she will be easy to spot at the ceremony. She will be the
little woman, about 5 feet 1 inch tall, wearing lace and pearls. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 2218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
