u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.N.-HOLBROOKE-NYT &LR;      07-07 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-HOLBROOKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Miss., Ky., Iowa)  
 A 4th REPUBLICAN BLOCKS VOTE ON HOLBROOKE'S CONFIRMATION  
(jt) 
 By PHILIP SHENON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The long-delayed nomination of Richard C. Holbrooke
to be chief American diplomat to the United Nations hit a new snag
Wednesday, as another Republican senator disclosed that he was
blocking a final Senate vote on the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmaker, Sen. George V. Voinovich of Ohio, said he had
placed a ``hold'' on the nomination out of concern over Holbrooke's
leading role in policymaking in the Balkans during the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional and other government officials said that at least
three other Republican senators are also exercising their right
under Senate rules to block a final vote on the veteran diplomat's
nomination: Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi, Mitch
McConnell of Kentucky and Charles E. Grassley of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that Lott and McConnell, who have not publicly
acknowledged their holds on the nomination, are refusing to permit
a Senate vote on Holbrooke until the White House agrees to name a
conservative Ohio law professor to the Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Grassley, who has acknowledged his role in blocking Holbrooke's
nomination, said he would not lift his hold until the State
Department reached an accommodation with an employee he considers a
whistle-blower in a matter unrelated to Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials expressed exasperation at the
delay in the confirmation of Holbrooke, whose nomination was held
up for most of the last year as a result of federal ethics
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   The investigations ended without any criminal charges. Holbrooke
paid $5,000 to settle civil charges that he had violated federal
lobbying laws, but said he had done nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has been without a so-called permanent
representative at the United Nations since September, when Bill
Richardson left the post to become energy secretary. Holbrooke's
nomination was approved by the Senate Foreign Relations Committee
on a voice vote last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard Holbrooke is eminently qualified to be the U.S.
ambassador to the United Nations,'' said P.J. Crowley, a White
House spokesman. ``His track record in working difficult issues in
the Balkans speaks for itself. We believe the Senate should vote as
quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   James Foley, a State Department spokesman, said, ``We don't
believe that issues external to Holbrooke's qualifications should
be linked to his confirmation.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Lott, McConnell and Grassley, however, Voinovich is
questioning Holbrooke's qualifications. Voinovich has been a fierce
critic of the administration's policy in the Balkans _ and
specifically, of the NATO air strikes against Yugoslavia this
spring.
</P>
<P>
   The senator's spokesman, Mike Dawson, said that the lawmaker had
placed the hold on the nomination last week and that it would
remain in place until the senator's staff had completed a review of
Holbrooke's role in Balkans policy.
</P>
<P>
   Dawson said that Voinovich would also insist that if there is a
vote on Holbrooke's nomination, that it done by roll call, so that
each senator's vote be registered publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for McConnell did not return calls. A spokesman for
Lott, John Czwartacki, would not comment on whether _ or why _ the
majority leader was blocking Holbrooke's nomination.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
