<SLUG> BC-SOLOMON-ISLANDS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
6 ARE KILLED IN ETHNIC CONFLICT IN GUADALCANAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The Solomon Islands, the group of tropical
Pacific islands that witnessed some of World War II's most
intensive battles, is once again the scene of strife, this time of
its own making.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials said Wednesday that at least six people had been
killed and 15,000 to 20,000 people had been forced to flee their
homes by ethnic conflict on Guadalcanal, the main island and scene
of the big World War II battle.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin M. Kennedy, chief of the emergency liaison branch of the
office for the coordination of humanitarian affairs, said the
United Nations would support a mediation effort by the Commonwealth
and would help the Red Cross provide food and housing to those
displaced by the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said that according to refugees, small bands of lightly
armed militant Gwales, the majority population on Guadalcanal, had
already driven out most of the minority population of Malaitan
villagers from the countryside. The Malaitas had come to
Gaudalcanal, often a generation or two ago, from the island of
Malaita, 60 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds more Malaitas have been harassed or frightened into
fleeing to the capital, Honiara, whose population is mostly
Malaitan. Many are now sleeping on the streets, Kennedy said.
Others have sought refuge with friends or relatives on Malaita,
placing additional burdens on a population of mostly subsistence
farmers and fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   ``These terrified people are unlikely to return to their homes
any time soon,'' Kennedy said in an interview, ``and certainly not
until their safety can be assured.''
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations sent its mission in response to an appeal
from Bartholomew Ulufa'alu, a Malaitan who is prime minister and
who invited the Commonwealth to mediate an end to the dispute.
Sitiveni Rabuka, Fiji's former prime minister, has been trying to
negotiate an end to the violence.
</P>
<P>
   Occupying an area that is slightly smaller than Maryland with a
population of about 440,000, the Solomon Islands, which gained
independence from Britain in 1978, is a democracy known for its
fractious Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats said that while the ethnic tensions among Guadalcanal
residents goes back decades, fighting erupted last April when small
gangs of jobless armed men began purging the Malaitans from their
villages around Honiara Province to protest what they saw as
preferential employment treatment given Malaitans on the island,
where about 115,000 people live.
</P>
<P>
   After speaking to correspondents about the situation in the
Solomon Islands, from which he has just returned, Kennedy was taken
aback by a reporter who asked why the United Nations should spend
time and money on a place where the death toll was ``small
potatoes'' compared with the suffering in other parts of the world,
like Africa and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well it's not small potatoes to the people who've been driven
out of their homes,'' Kennedy replied. ``In the context of the
country, which has not seen very much violence in recent decades,
it's a major crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Solomon Islanders are concerned that the strife will adversely
affect the nation's struggling economy and a population afflicted
with one of the world's highest rates of malaria. In addition to
the export of palm oil, which accounts for about 20 percent of
gross domestic product, the islanders sustain themselves through
farming and fishing.
</P>
<P>
   The Solomons are a destination for some 12,000 tourists a year,
many of them World War II veterans who return to see the places
where they or their comrades fought in the six-month campaign to
regain the islands from Japanese forces in 1942 and 1943. About
6,000 American soldiers died there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
