<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2437 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOONDOCKS-SPI &LR;      07-07 1467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOONDOCKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMIC STRIP'S FANS COME OUT IN DROVES AFTER CREATOR CRITICIZED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT L. JAMIESON JR.  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A funny thing happened to Aaron McGruder on his way to
being fried in the forum.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of continuing to scorch him with insults, the public has
begun showering him with praise for creating ``The Boondocks,'' a
brash, controversial, black-oriented comic strip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clever and multilayered,'' weighs in one Seattle newspaper
reader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speaks the truth,'' praises another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thought-provoking ... makes me laugh,'' exhorts a fan.
</P>
<P>
   Plus _ his groupies point out _ McGruder is darn tootin' cute.
</P>
<P>
   So what's not to like?
</P>
<P>
   Well, plenty _ or so you would have thought from early reaction
to the strip.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, after the Seattle Post-Intelligencer and dozens of
other newspapers across the country started carrying McGruder's
provocative comic, it appeared he might have sketched himself into
a very tight corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Boondocks'' brings a spicy cast of characters to the
nation's vanilla funny pages by presenting the lives of four
urbanly hip kids who speak the language of hip-hop and live in a
Wonder Bread suburb.
</P>
<P>
   There's Huey Freeman, the black nationalist with a heart of
gold; Riley, Huey's younger brother, who projects a gangsta air;
their buddy Caesar, who totes a microphone; and Jazmine, a biracial
neighbor confused about her racial identity.
</P>
<P>
   They inhabit a strip that hits hot-button issues.
</P>
<P>
   In one recent installment, Huey, named for former Black Panther
Huey P. Newton, makes random stops of white motorists as part of
``Operation Klanwatch.'' In another strip, Riley knocks down a
white girl with a toy lightsaber and huffs: ``See?! You're still
alive! This thing is worthless!''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for the ``Boon-lash'' to register with a
vocal minority of Seattle readers. Thirty-one of 33 readers who
blitzed this paper's reader representative phone line blasted the
strip for being ``racist,'' ``indulgent'' and ``not very funny.''
And many of those readers especially hated the lightsaber strip,
which they said encouraged violence among young people.
</P>
<P>
   After the Post-Intelligencer published some of those concerns in
a lengthy story about McGruder on June 28, supporters of the strip
emerged in droves.
</P>
<P>
   More than 130 people contacted the Post-Intelligencer, using
phone calls, e-mail and snail-mail letters. A majority of them _
roughly 80 percent _ wanted to keep the ``The Boondocks'' around,
citing its timely social commentary, panache and
Japanese-influenced art style.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a breath of fresh perspective and relevant commentary on
race relations in America today,'' writes Dennis MacCoumber of
Seattle, who adds, ``McGruder gives us old dudes who have no
contact with young blacks some hint of what another culture may be
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Stacy Vennema of Bellingham writes: ``Boondocks is, in my
opinion, equal-opportunity satire, exposing attitudes and
assumptions of both white and black characters.''
</P>
<P>
   Dean Barnes says: ``McGruder strikes a nerve because he is
putting racial satire in a comic setting where most (people) expect
non-confrontational humor.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of confrontation, Sally Wolff of Coupeville saw no
racial animosity in the lightsaber strip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took it the way the cartoonist intended _ a boy who was
disappointed that his lightsaber didn't work like the ones in the
`Phantom Menace' movie,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some black readers said critics of the strip may be
unaccustomed to or uncomfortable with artistic depictions of young,
intelligent blacks who call it like they see it. Many callers said
McGruder deftly skewers those liberals who believe the race
question is passe.
</P>
<P>
   His support crosses party lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the liberals don't have a sense of humor. What else is
new,'' huffs Dave Cavanaugh in an e-mail message. ``Just for the
record, I'm a 46-year-old white, Goldwater conservative, and I
think `Boondocks' is one of the better strips around.''
</P>
<P>
   For several readers the bottom line was this: Keep ``The
Boondocks'' or lose a subscriber. (Post-Intelligencer managing
editor Ken Bunting said he is ``watching carefully'' as the strip's
story line develops.)
</P>
<P>
   Seattle resident Meri Tahset, who had been getting the strip
e-mailed to her by friends, said she would subscribe to the paper
just for ``The Boondocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Tahset, who is black and grew up in Detroit, said McGruder's
insights humorously speak to challenges she faces living in a
predominantly white city. Racial intolerance, she says, boils below
the surface in Seattle, a liberal pocket in a state that recently
passed an anti-affirmative action initiative. ```The Boondocks' has
me feeling like I can last here,'' she says, adding ``I just hope
Aaron doesn't get watered down.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, McGruder has received praise and criticism
in cities where his strip runs, including Atlanta, Chicago and Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   More than 180 newspapers carry his strip, a remarkable
accomplishment for a man who just turned 25 and lives at home with
his mother and father in suburban Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   To date, three newspapers have dropped the strip and moved out
of ``The Boondocks'': The Greenville News and The Aiken Standard,
both in South Carolina, and The Independent in Massillon, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Hunter, publisher of The Aiken Standard, which has a daily
circulation of 14,000, said ``The Boondocks'' was ``not working''
in his community 50 miles southwest of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just wasn't funny,'' said Hunter, who had ordered up
advance editions of the strip, only to discover that his funny bone
was untickled. ``Maybe it would go over well in much larger
cities.''
</P>
<P>
   In Southern California, where ``The Boondocks'' appears in the
Los Angeles Times, that paper reported nearly 100 complaints
shortly after the strip's debut.
</P>
<P>
   But after the paper published a feature story on McGruder, his
fans started popping up. To date, the paper has received more than
500 responses, split roughly down the middle between his supporters
and detractors, said Narda Zacchino, the paper's associate editor
and reader representative.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most significant contribution by (McGruder) is that people
are talking about race issues as a result of his strip,'' said
Zacchino.
</P>
<P>
   Kathie Kerr, spokeswoman for Universal Press Syndicate, which
distributes ``The Boondocks,'' says: ``The increased awareness can
only help newspapers increase the number of people who pick up the
papers.''
</P>
<P>
   McGruder is keeping his cool amid all the attention.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, he was featured in Time and Newsweek. Earlier this
week, he was on a C-Span program, where he had phones ringing off
the hook as a result of his latest strip tease that posed the
question of what is offensive.
</P>
<P>
   In the July 4 strip, McGruder took a joking poke at critics who
call his strip racist. He wrote that ``The Boondocks'' was being
replaced by a new strip that readers might find ``more suitable for
the comic pages.''
</P>
<P>
   The mock replacement featured Jar Jar Binks, the alien from
director George Lucas' summer hit ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The
Phantom Menace.'' Lucas' character, which looks like a Rastafarian
version of Joe Camel and speaks with a vaguely Caribbean syntax,
has drawn fire in the media for acting and sounding like a Stepin
Fetchit black caricature.
</P>
<P>
   McGruder left nothing to chance, giving Jar Jar the full
Buckwheat treatment: ``Jar Jar sho' nuff likes to shuffle! Ya see,
chilluns, Jar Jar besa good alien. Hesa no want no trouble. ...
O-TAY!''
</P>
<P>
   Says McGruder, with a chuckle: ``Jar Jar fans are upset? Well,
too bad.''
</P>
<P>
   He does not apologize for stepping on toes to foster intelligent
social and political satire with black themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do a black strip,'' he recently explained. ``I think white
people who want to buy into black culture would rather buy into
something that's authentic rather than something that is watered
down for their sake.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking this week from his hotel room in Seattle, where he is
attending the UNITY '99 conference for minority journalists, he
said he has much on his plate.
</P>
<P>
   After his picture appeared in national magazines, he was
approached by a ``major'' network to act in an upcoming TV pilot.
(He's weighing the offer.) He already has an animated version of
``The Boondocks'' in the works with movie director Reginald Hudlin.
</P>
<P>
   For now, he's glad to be in Seattle, away from heat _ including
the weather kind. ``He called me as soon as he arrived out there in
Seattle,'' McGruder's mother said from the family home in Maryland,
where there has been a heat wave. ``He said, `Mom, it's so
beautiful out here. It's not so hot.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 2245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0370 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2438 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUVS-SAFETY-NYT &LR;      07-07 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUVS-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORT VEHICLES CAN BE BUILT TO BE SAFER, INSURERS SAY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Sport utility vehicles can be designed both to protect
their occupants and to reduce injuries to the occupants of vehicles
that they hit, an insurance industry group said Wednesday, citing
tests it performed using six mid-size sport utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The two vehicles that did best when rammed into concrete and
steel barriers were also those with features likely to reduce the
injuries of occupants of other vehicles in collisions, the group
said.
</P>
<P>
   Auto makers have long said that this would be a difficult
balance to strike and have been reluctant to make changes that,
they say, might endanger occupants of sport utility vehicles in an
effort to protect occupants of the vehicles involved in accidents
with them.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the companies have criticized the growing
reliance of federal regulators and insurers on high-speed crash
tests into solid barriers. To pass these tests, the auto makers
contend, they must make sport utility vehicles with very stiff
bodies to keep the big vehicles' own weight from crushing the
occupants' compartments during crashes. But as federal regulators
have warned, vehicles with very stiff frames are likely to pierce
deeply into other vehicles during collisions.
</P>
<P>
   The Insurance Institute for Highway Safety, a research group
seeking to reduce the cost of accident claims, said Wednesday that
it was possible to build safe sport utility vehicles with less
rigid front ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would appear that there should be no conflicts between
doing well in this kind of test and being more compatible with
cars,'' said Brian O'Neill, the president of the institute, which
is based in Arlington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   The institute tested the Mercedes M-Class, Lexus RX 300, Land
Rover Discovery Series II, Dodge Durango, Jeep Grand Cherokee and
Mitsubishi Montero Sport. Each vehicle was crashed into a barrier
at 40 mph, with the front corner on the driver's side hitting
first.
</P>
<P>
   The two vehicles that fared best, the Mercedes and the Lexus,
had relatively soft front ends that were designed to bend and
absorb energy during a crash, O'Neill said. Rather than having
stiff bodies like most other vehicles tested, both vehicles have
stiff materials only around the passenger compartment.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes has promoted its sport utility vehicle as the first
designed to minimize injuries to other motorists. O'Neill said that
while his institute had not evaluated the performance of the
Mercedes and Lexus in crashes with cars, both had designs
consistent with reducing injuries to occupants of other vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers had a mixed reaction to Wednesday's test results. The
Chrysler Corp. had been a strong defender of stiff sport utility
vehicles, but that position has shifted since Daimler-Benz A.G.,
which makes Mercedes vehicles, took it over last November.
</P>
<P>
   Sonja L. Bultynck, a spokeswoman for DaimlerChrysler A.G., which
makes the Mercedes, Dodge and Jeep vehicles tested, said that the
company considered the stiffness of each vehicle separately.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being the global transportation company that we are, we're
going to look at each case,'' Mrs. Bultynck said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodge Durango, a stiff vehicle, received a rating of
``acceptable'' instead of the ``good'' given to the Mercedes and
Lexus vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bultynck said, ``We're going to build the Durango to have a
rigid body because it's going to be towing all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Discovery Series II was rated ``acceptable,'' and the Grand
Cherokee was deemed ``marginal.'' The Montero Sport was rated
``poor'' because it allowed considerable collapse of the occupants'
compartment, which could lead to more injuries. Its manufacturer,
Mitsubishi, said the Montero Sport had met or exceeded all federal
safety standards.
</P>
<P>
   The General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler discussed
plans last year to file a petition with federal regulators asking
that crash tests be conducted at lower speeds for large sport
utility vehicles and pickup trucks so the vehicles could be made
less stiff and therefore less dangerous to other motorists. After
the Chrysler take-over, the drafting of a petition was put on hold
until later this year.
</P>
<P>
   A study released by federal regulators in March estimated that
an extra 2,000 Americans are killed each year in vehicles hit by
sport utility vehicles, pickup trucks and mini-vans.
</P>
<P>
   Ford officials have suggested that only half as many lives are
lost in such crashes and have said that some vehicle mismatches are
inevitable in crashes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 2247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
