<SLUG> BC-GWHIZ-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: GREY OPENS STAND-ALONE UNIT TO PURSUE GENERATION Y 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seeking to bolster its presence in a market segment that is
growing faster than the number of Web sites devoted to Britney
Spears, ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,'' the Backstreet Boys or
``American Pie,'' Grey Advertising Inc. has opened a stand-alone
agency devoted to the very consumers who would consider such sites
to be ``all that'': youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   G Whiz is the name of the new unit, which is operating as a
wholly owned subsidiary of Grey, the world's No. 9 agency company,
with billings estimated at $8.3 billion, from clients like Hasbro,
Mars, Procter &AMP; Gamble and Sprint. To underline the intended
autonomy of G Whiz, the agency's dozen employees are working at an
office in midtown Manhattan that is separate from the Grey
headquarters office nearby.
</P>
<P>
   G Whiz has started with accounts, assignments and projects with
billings estimated at $20 million for brands like Elmer's glue,
Konami video games, Reebok footwear and Warner Brothers videos. All
are centered on the youth market, aiming at the demographic group
called Generation Y whose members were born between 1978 and 1998
and spend an estimated $130 billion annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are now adopting brands at a very young age, making
brands their `badges,''' said G Whiz president Barbara Martino.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just about knowing what's hot and what's not,'' she
added. ``It's about understanding the emotions that drive the
behavior that interconnects with brands.''
</P>
<P>
   The new unit is a successor to 18 and Under, which had been part
of the Grey advertising operations. The goal now is to offer
marketers who are pitching products and services to children and
teen-agers a range of so-called integrated communications that
include interactive marketing, research, promotional marketing,
brand planning and event marketing in addition to traditional
selling tactics like television commercials and print
advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Grey employees are being ``encouraged to anticipate the
marketing landscape and move beyond classical advertising,'' said
Grey chairman and chief executive Edward Meyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now 40 percent of our global volume comes from diversified
communications,'' he added. ``Our holdings in interactive and
e-commerce, media services including online media, health care,
multicultural marketing and brand asset consulting are our
fastest-growing units.''
</P>
<P>
   G Whiz joins a lengthening list of agencies that are
specializing in youth marketing as the large agency companies seek
to diversify by bolstering units in hot submarkets or niche
categories like new media and media services.
</P>
<P>
   Other examples include CME Kidcom, part of Campbell Mithun Esty
in Minneapolis, which is majority owned by Interpublic Group of
Cos.; Geppetto Group in New York, owned by WPP Group PLC; Kid Leo,
part of the Leo Burnett Company in Chicago, and Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi
Kid Connection, part of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to put more muscle behind our youth-market
efforts,'' Ms. Martino said, ``because there's a lot of opportunity
there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At 18 and Under, we were doing business while also doing our
day jobs,'' she added. ``Now we have a dedicated group devoted to
the youth marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Martino, 37, joined Grey in 1990, then helped start 18 and
Under in 1992 and Indigo Entertainment in 1994, a Grey unit
specializing in the production of TV shows for children.
</P>
<P>
   Other G Whiz executives include Brett Howlett, 39, the vice
president and creative director, and Douglas Zarkin, 29, the vice
president who manages branding efforts for clients.
</P>
<P>
   G Whiz is also indicative of Grey's efforts to freshen and
contemporize its image, often described as stodgy and traditional,
as competition intensifies among the giant agencies. A stand-alone
unit dedicated to working on youthful communications campaigns can
help ``youthify'' the Grey brand.
</P>
<P>
   One suggestion: do something about that name. G Whiz is more
evocative of the America depicted in ``The Music Man'' _ remember
when Harold Hill sang about a publication called ``Captain Billy's
Whiz Bang''? _ than of the nation whose young people will spend
most of their lives in the 21st century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
