u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOCTORS-UNION-ECONSCE     07-07 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTORS-UNION-ECONSCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC SCENE: IF DOCTORS WIN RIGHT TO ORGANIZE, PATIENTS COULD
LOSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MICHAEL M. WEINSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A closely divided American Medical Association, which represents
about a third of the nation's physicians, has voted to form a union
to represent its members in collective bargaining with health
plans, hospitals and universities. The rise of managed care has
shaken the cozy world of these high-paid, elite professionals. Now
they are seeking cover from two groups they used to shun: unions
and the Democratic Party, which is leading the charge in Congress
to clamp down on corporate managed care.
</P>
<P>
   But would unionization, as advanced by the AMA, be good for
patients? No, say antitrust officials in the Clinton administration
and many independent economists.
</P>
<P>
   Under current labor law, only salaried doctors can unionize.
About 40,000 of these salaried physicians are already unionized.
For the AMA to begin an aggressive unionization drive among
salaried doctors breaks no new ground.
</P>
<P>
   But the AMA also has something novel in mind. It plans to put
its well-financed lobbying power behind a bill, sponsored by Rep.
Tom Campbell, R-Calif., and about 130 other members of the House,
to change the nation's labor laws so that even independent doctors
could join forces to negotiate fees and working conditions with
health plans.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, a former professor of antitrust law at Stanford
University, says his legislation responds to two ``alarming
anticonsumer trends _ the increased level of concentration among
health insurers and the exclusionary contracting practices some
have followed.''
</P>
<P>
   Large health plans make local physicians a take-it-or-leave-it
offer, dictating their pay and the way they are allowed to practice
medicine. Campbell wants to offset the power of the plans by
creating a countervailing power: a physicians union. A strong
union, he says, would give doctors more power to protect patients
from denials of care by managed-care officials.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin Gaynor, an economics professor at Carnegie Mellon
University in Pittsburgh, says a union of independent physicians
would be unwise. Under the Campbell bill, physicians would be
allowed to fix prices and engage in other anticompetitive
activities that would be illegal elsewhere in the economy. ``A
physicians' union will drive up health care costs, taking money
from workers and putting it in the wallets of doctors,'' he says.
Economists also worry that unionization of independent physicians
will do something worse: severely limit the ability of managed-care
plans to second-guess doctors who practice bad medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor disputes Campbell's contention that creating a cartel of
independent physicians would help patients even if, as Campbell
assumes, managed-care plans wield monopoly power. But the fact is,
he says, managed-care plans do not exert excessive market power.
``For almost every major urban area in the United States, no HMO
accounts for more than 20 percent of the market'' Gaynor said.
``Many account for less than 10 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   He points out that there are no large profits that a physicians'
union could strip from health plans without affecting patients.
``Profit margins of typical managed-care plans were below 1 percent
in 1995 and negative since then,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a doctors' union jacks up fees,'' Gaynor continued, ``it
will force employers to pass along the added cost to workers as
lower wages.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pitofsky, chairman of the Federal Trade Commission, fears
a union of independent physicians will harm patients by giving
doctors power to refuse to deal with managed care. That, he says,
will drive out competition and drive up costs.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he says, the antitrust exemption Campbell and the AMA
seek is unnecessary. Antitrust guidelines, which he administers,
already allow independent physicians to collaborate to help
patients. They can join forces to discuss raising standards of care
or to form networks that improve care by coordinating treatment.
</P>
<P>
   At the core of the debate is patient care. After an exhaustive
review of the research, Robert Brook, a professor of medicine at
the University of California at Los Angeles, concludes that about a
third of acute care provided by physicians was wrong or
unnecessary, posing not only needless expense but also needless
risk.
</P>
<P>
   Managed care is a possible cure because physicians hired by the
managed-care companies to review treatment by practicing physicians
can correct errors, including rejecting inappropriate tests,
treatments and surgeries. Campbell's bill allows doctors in a
region to band together to block treatment review.
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor acknowledges that there are problems with managed-care
plans. Their quality is uneven, and their decisions can be craven.
But, he says, ``injecting a cartel of otherwise independent doctors
is not the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   So what is? He suggests vigorous enforcement of antitrust rules
against excessive mergers of health plans and carefully drafted
patient-protection laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 2254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
