<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0376 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2446 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISNEY-SECRETS-NYT     07-07 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-SECRETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE SOAP THAN LAUNDRY DETECTED IN DISNEY'S CASE
</HEADLINE>
 (With DISNEY-KATZENBERG) 
 (nk) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The trial of Jeffrey Katzenberg's suit against the
Walt Disney Co. was eagerly anticipated by Hollywood-watchers for
the look it would provide into the sometimes secretive operations
of the Magic Kingdom. Hollywood executives and Wall Street analysts
were astounded that Disney would even let the case go to trial,
thereby allowing the company's dirty laundry to be aired in public.
</P>
<P>
   But now that the case has been settled, analysts and executives
say there was not that much laundry after all. While the chairman
of Disney, Michael D. Eisner, suffered a bruised reputation, most
of Disney's business secrets stayed intact, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't seem as if there were really any groundbreaking
revelations that came out of it,'' said Stewart Halpern, an analyst
at ING Barings in New York. ``The headlines are a lot sexier than
the realities.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg sued seeking a bonus based on the profits of the
movies and television shows that were made during the decade he was
head of Disney's studio. Terms of the settlement were not
announced, but it is believed that Katzenberg could eventually
receive at least $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   Disney had tried to keep the proceedings secret, arguing that a
trial would disclose ``extraordinarily sensitive and confidential''
information about its business and game plans. But a California
judge, in response to a suit filed by several news organizations,
ruled that the trial should be open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Most of what was embarrassing to Disney, though, was not
financial information but personal animosity _ including testimony
disclosing that Eisner had called Katzenberg a ``little midget.''
Wednesday, a Disney spokesman, John Dreyer, said the company did
not think any significant new information about its business was
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   To some extent this could be because Disney settled in the nick
of time, before its own witnesses, including Eisner, were to
testify about the company's future business prospects. Until now,
Disney's statements at the trial had mostly been aimed at deflating
projections made by Katzenberg's witnesses. The settlement also
avoids a phase of the trial that would have looked more closely at
Disney's accounting.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there were some nuggets that will no doubt supply grist
for one or more books about Disney and for investors. In
particular, Disney's own trial statements cast doubt about the
company's ability to continue earning money from its classic
full-length animated films, properties once viewed as perennial
money-earners that merely had to await a new generation of children
to enjoy them.
</P>
<P>
   Disney disclosed during the trial, for instance, that it would
no longer re-release its animated movies to theaters because it no
longer made money from doing so. It also said that it was
lengthening to 10 years from 7 years the interval before it
released those movies to the home video market. And the company
said that DVD, or digital video disk, would only replace
videocassettes and not constitute a big new market.
</P>
<P>
   The company also painted dim prospects for business in China and
India, two markets that some analysts said the company had been
counting on for growth. Disney said that partly because of piracy,
it had not made money on a movie, even the China-theme ``Mulan,''
in either of those markets.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said that Disney's trial disclosures contradicted
the rosier projections of its growth prospects it had been telling
investors. ``They were telling us in April of 1998 that the
home-video business was terrific,'' said Jeffrey B. Logsdon,
managing director at the Seidler Companies in Los Angeles,
referring to an analysts' meeting at that time. ``In the meantime,
the home video business has slowed down dramatically for them, both
domestically and internationally.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dreyer, the Disney spokesman, and other analysts said that
some information about the deterioration of the video business had
been disclosed in more recent quarterly earnings statements. Many
analysts also said Disney was deliberately playing down its
prospects at the trial to reduce the amount it would have to pay
Katzenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg's side contended that Disney was licensing films to
ABC, the network it owns, for less than the market price, a move
that would increase the financial results of ABC but would lower
Katzenberg's bonus. According to one document that Disney tried to
keep secret, ABC had offered to pay $6 million for rights to
broadcast ``Hercules'' and ``The Hunchback of Notre Dame'' but a
Disney executive then offered to sell for only $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce O'Donnell, the attorney who represented news
organizations in their effort to open the trial to the public, said
that other evidence introduced at the trial would provide
ammunition for other people who share profits on Disney films and
might want to sue, contending that they are being shortchanged by
Disney accounting practices. O'Donnell represented Art Buchwald
when he sued Paramount Pictures contending that he had been denied
his share of profits from the hit movie ``Coming to America.'' That
trial, which took place in the early 1990s, is considered by some
analysts to be a bigger eye-opener about Hollywood's business
practices than the Katzenberg trial.
</P>
<P>
   To many analysts, what was most revealing about Disney from the
Katzenberg case was that Eisner let it get to trial, distracting
him at a time when the company is battling declining profits.
Questions were raised about whether Eisner was letting his ego and
animosity for Katzenberg get in the way of his business judgment.
But Dreyer said Disney had an obligation to shareholders to avoid
paying the huge sum _ $250 million or more _ that Katzenberg was
demanding.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's stock price has been falling in the last two months,
but analysts say that is mainly because of Disney's declining
profits, not because of the trial. Wednesday, Disney's shares moved
up only 12.5 cents, to $28.0625, on news of the settlement. ``It's
a positive from a psychological standpoint for the stock,'' said
Katherine Styponias, an analyst with Prudential Securities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
