<HEADLINE>
FULL RECOVERY EXPECTED FOR REP. JIM MCDERMOTT AFTER HEART SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Jim McDermott had major open-heart surgery
Wednesday to repair a congenital flaw in a heart valve.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Democrat was awake, breathing on his own and in
stable condition in the intensive care unit in Swedish Medical
Center in Seattle after three hours of surgery. His aides said the
congressman is expected to make a full recovery after spending
about a week at the hospital, at least two more weeks at home, and
then several more weeks avoiding strenuous activity.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott, 62, is a psychiatrist and former state lawmaker who
was elected to Congress in 1988. He represents most of the city of
Seattle, as well as Vashon Island and parts of Lake Forest Park,
Renton and Shoreline.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott is mulling over a race for the U.S. Senate next year,
and aides said Wednesday's surgery would not affect his decision.
McDermott had hoped to make an announcement in August.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott, a longtime crusader for medical privacy, asked his
staff not to discuss his surgery until after he regained
consciousness, and he declined to permit his surgeon, Dr. Edward
Rittenhouse, to speak with the news media. His press secretary,
David Schaefer, described the congressman's condition and
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   According to Schaefer, McDermott has known for years that he had
a congenital heart condition called aortic stenosis, a malformation
of the valve on the left ventricle. The left ventricle is one of
the four chambers of the heart, and is the main source of blood to
the aorta, which in turn distributes blood to the brain and other
parts of the body.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, while performing an annual physical exam on
McDermott, a physician found through an electrocardiogram that
McDermott's malformed valve had begun to calcify, a condition that
can lead to heart failure. The physician recommended
valve-replacement surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The faulty valve was removed and a mechanical valve was
installed in its place in Wednesday's surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer said there were no complications and that the surgery
was successful. He said McDermott hopes to be back in Congress by
the first week of August, when the House expects to be casting its
final votes on some spending measures before recessing until after
Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   Two cardiac surgeons interviewed Wednesday said patients who
undergo valve-replacement surgery can expect to spend from one to
three months in recovery because the breastbone, or sternum, is
broken during the surgery. They said patients who have mechanical
valves installed must take blood thinners for the rest of their
lives or risk having a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aortic stenosis is a common cardiac condition that we see
regularly, and valve replacement is the standard treatment,'' said
Dr. Frances DeRook, a cardiologist at Harborview Medical Center in
Seattle. ``The prognosis, with treatment, is very good. Life
expectancy is near normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Edward Verrier, chief of cardiothoracic surgery at the
University of Washington Medical Center, also in Seattle, agreed
that aortic stenosis is ``one of the most common congenital
anomalies'' and that valve replacement is ``a relatively routine
operation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
