<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-777-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING PICKS G.E. ENGINES FOR LONGER-RANGE VERSIONS OF 777 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Although it is still talking with potential customers
and has not decided when to officially launch the 777X, The Boeing
Co. has picked General Electric to develop the huge engines the new
plane will require.
</P>
<P>
   GE, the world's largest engine maker, said Wednesday the deal
with Boeing could be worth as much as $25 billion over 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the most significant wins for GE Aircraft
Engines in its long history,'' James McNerney, president of GE
Aircraft Engines, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Rolls-Royce and Pratt &AMP; Whitney also submitted bids to develop
the engines.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing selected GE as the exclusive supplier of the
115,000-pound-thrust engines that will power the 777X. The engine
will be a derivative of the GE90, developed in the mid 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   At the Paris Air Show last month, McNerney told reporters GE
wanted an exclusive deal with Boeing to justify the development
cost of the new engines. He said the market for the 777X was not
big enough to support more than one engine maker.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines have a choice of engines that power the 777-200 and the
stretch 777-300. Rolls-Royce, GE and Pratt &AMP; Whitney all supply
engines for the current fleet of 777s.
</P>
<P>
   The potential market for the 777X is probably about 500 planes,
according to Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Wednesday, Alan Mulally, Boeing Commercial
Airplanes president, said all three engine makers submitted good
proposals for the 777X.
</P>
<P>
   But GE, he said, ``best met the overall evaluation criteria,
including technical, schedule, customer service and business
requirements.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulally was the 777 program manager during the development of
the plane.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing executives have not said when they will launch the
longer-range versions of the 777.
</P>
<P>
   There has been much industry speculation that a decision will be
made before the end of this year, but in an interview last month at
the Paris Air Show, Mulally said he doesn't know when the green
light will be given for development of either the 777-200X, the
777-300X or both.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have an airplane like this, when you start depends on
when you need to deliver it. We will keep talking (to potential
customers),'' Mulally said.
</P>
<P>
   In its news release Wednesday, GE quoted Boeing as saying it
wants to begin delivering the 777X to customers by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Two versions of the 777X are planned.
</P>
<P>
   The 777-200X would carry about 300 passengers in a three-class
configuration, which is the same size as the current 777-200. But
the new plane would have a range of about 10,100 miles, or about
1,200 miles farther than the current 777-200ER (extended range).
</P>
<P>
   The 777-300X would carry about 360 passengers, the same as the
777-300. But it will fly 8,300 miles, some 1,800 miles farther than
the 777-300.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing believes many airlines will choose the 777-300X as a
replacement for older 747s and DC-11s.
</P>
<P>
   The 777X will have a strengthened fuselage, tail and landing
gear and a new wing tip with 76 inches of added span on each side.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is bullish on the 777X because of market fragmentation.
That's the industry term for more frequent flights and more flights
directly from one point to another, instead of big planes that fly
to hub airports.
</P>
<P>
   The new versions of the 777 would challenge the Airbus A340-500
and A340-600 now in development. But the Boeing planes would fly
farther.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
