u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-BARAK-1STLD-WR     07-07 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-BARAK-1STLD-WRITETHRU-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVING ON PEACE, BARAK ANNOUNCES MEETINGS WITH CLINTON, ARAB
LEADERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS 5th graf, The new ..., to ADD that Assad of Syria has
said he would not meet with Israeli leader until peace talks
conclud; SUBS 11th graf, At a handover ..., to ADD that Netanyahu
welcomed Barak.) 
 (th) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Moving swiftly to make good on his pledges to
restart the stalled Middle East peace effort, Ehud Barak announced
as he moved into the prime minister's office Wednesday that he
would hold a series of meetings with Arab leaders and President
Clinton in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
   Barak plans to meet with President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt on
Friday in Alexandria and with Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian
leader, on Sunday at the Erez Crossing between the Gaza Strip and
Israel, a statement from his office said.
</P>
<P>
   A meeting is also planned with King Abdullah of Jordan before
Barak travels to the United States next week for discussions with
Clinton and senior administration officials, the statement added.
Barak is expected in Washington on July 15.
</P>
<P>
   The whirl of diplomacy is intended to explore ways to revive
aborted peace talks with Syria and to move peace efforts forward
with the Palestinians. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is
expected to visit the Middle East to follow up the discussions
after Barak returns from Washington, Israeli officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The new Israeli prime minister is seeking help from the Clinton
administration and from the leaders of Egypt and Jordan, which are
at peace with Israel, to renew negotiations with Syria that were
broken off more than three years ago. &UR;  &LR; Presi- dent Hafez Assad of
Syria, which technically remains in a state of war with Israel, has
said he would not meet an Israeli leader until peace negotiations
were concluded.
 &UR;  &LR; ``These meetings symbolize Barak's determination to resume the
peace process and renew the relations of trust between the new
Israeli government and Arab leaders,'' said Haim Ramon, a Cabinet
minister who is responsible for Jerusalem issues.
</P>
<P>
   In his inauguration speech Tuesday, Barak pledged to make the
pursuit of peace with the Palestinians, Syria and Lebanon the
``supreme goal'' of his government.
</P>
<P>
   Nabil Shaath, a senior aide to Arafat, welcomed Barak's
announcement of the first meeting between Arafat and an Israeli
leader since last December.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Arafat is quite encouraged by this,'' Shaath said.
``We hope our first meeting will be successful and usher in a new
period of relations and partnership between the two leaders, if it
is followed by some practical things on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   In Damascus, a statement read on state television said: ``Syria
shares with Prime Minister Barak the same wish to put an end to
wars and establish comprehensive peace in the region. The Syrian
government is ready to match every step with a similar one and to
resume peace talks from the point where they ended as soon as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   At a handover ceremony in the prime minister's office where he
was welcomed by his predecessor, Benjamin Netanyahu, Barak said,
``There is tremendous expectation that we will know, from this room
and from this building, how to navigate the state of Israel and the
entire region to security and peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Israeli commentators suggested that Barak was moving
quickly to carry out his peace promises in order to pre-empt
possible resistance from right-leaning members of his broad
governing coalition, which spans 75 members of the 120-member
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Little is known yet about how Barak intends to go about
restoring momentum to negotiations with the Palestinians, which
bogged down in distrust and recrimination during Netanyahu's term
as prime minister. At Wednesday's hand-over ceremony, Barak said
that he would try to avoid Netanyahu's mistakes, but did not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Netanyahu suspended the latest Israeli-Palestinian
accord, the Wye River agreement signed near Washington last
October, accusing the Palestinians of failing to keep their part of
the deal. The agreement called for a phased Israeli withdrawal from
parts of the West Bank in exchange for Palestinian security
measures.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon said Barak would seek changes in the Wye agreement, but
only with Palestinian consent. Israeli press reports said Barak
would prefer to skip further Israeli troop withdrawals and proceed
directly to talks on a permanent peace _ a move that would leave
more land under Israeli control, giving Israel more negotiating
leverage, before the hard bargaining on a final settlement.
</P>
<P>
   However, Shaath predicted Arafat would reject Barak's suggestion
and insist on full adherence to the Wye agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Arafat will politely and firmly tell him no,''
Shaath said. ``If you say you are not willing to implement
agreements that have been signed, how will I trust you to implement
anything in the future? If he says I will go through with it as
soon as possible, that's enough.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Shaath said the Palestinians also expect Barak to halt Israeli
settlement activity in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, and
particularly in East Jerusalem. The future of these areas is
supposed to be decided in negotiations on a final peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines of Barak's government say that no new settlements
will be built, but that existing settlements will not be harmed and
their ``development needs'' will be met, a formula that allows for
expansion of these communities.
</P>
<P>
   As for Israeli projects in East Jerusalem, Ramon said Tuesday
that work on a housing complex for Jews in the Arab neighborhood of
Ras al-Amud should be stopped, although he did not announce steps
to do this. And he added that building would proceed at another
disputed site, a hill known in Hebrew as Har Homa and in Arabic as
Jabal Abu Ghneim.
</P>
<P>
   As Barak arrived at the prime minister's office Wednesday, other
members of his Cabinet took the reins of their ministries from
their predecessors in ceremonies whose cordiality contrasted with
the rancor of the election campaign that ended with Barak's
resounding victory on May 17.
</P>
<P>
   Barak set the tone by paying warm compliments to Netanyahu and
raising a glass to the departing prime minister and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``To Benjamin and Sara Netanyahu and to the state of Israel,''
Barak said. ``To life, l'chayim!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
