<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2569 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-2000-HNS &LR;      07-07 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    BUSH SAYS `NEW COMMANDER IN CHIEF ON THE WAY'
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 1st Ld-Writethru _ changes in 2nd and 3rd grafs  &HT;    By JULIE MASON
 &HT;    c. 1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush took steps Wednesday
to quell questions about his military service by meeting with a
heroic Air Force pilot and declaring, ``There's a new commander in
chief on the way.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting with Scott O'Grady, who was shot down over Bosnia in
1995, was not on the Republican front-runner's schedule and came as
Bush met with officials from seven Western states in the home of
the newest GOP presidential candidate, Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah.
</P>
<P>
   O'Grady ejected after a Serb missile hit his F-16 while he was
patrolling over northwestern Bosnia. He spent six days hiding from
Serb forces before a dramatic rescue by U.S. forces.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's own warrior credentials were called into question over
the Fourth of July weekend with reports that he may have received
preferential treatment in the Texas Air National Guard during the
Vietnam War. His record, and that of many of his rivals who also
sat out combat in Vietnam, contrasts with that of candidate John
McCain, the Arizona senator and combat veteran who spent five years
as a prisoner of the Viet Cong.
</P>
<P>
   Besides asking O'Grady to spread the word that ``there's a new
commander in chief on the way,'' Bush promised ``a season of hope
after years of cynicism'' and vowed to restore ``dignity and
honor'' to the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   He also questioned the Clinton administration's taking credit
for the economic boom of the 1990s, tweaking Vice President Al
Gore, the front-runner for the Democratic presidential nomination,
in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you listen to those back there in Washington, D.C., they
sound like they created prosperity,'' Bush said. ``They no more
created prosperity than they invented the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Bush were the governors of Wyoming, Nevada, Idaho,
Colorado and Montana as well as Utah Gov. Mike Leavitt. Also
present were Sen. Gordon Smith of Oregon and state and local
officials from Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Although he supports Bush, Leavitt is not technically endorsing
Bush for president.
</P>
<P>
   For Leavitt, there is the thorny problem of Hatch, who is making
a late addition to the crowded field of Republican presidential
candidates. Leavitt plans to support both campaigns, and has so far
maintained a posture of amiable fence-sitting.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, who has yet to formally announce his intentions, knows he
is a long shot and has presented himself as a ``credible
alternative'' should Bush falter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe it's not good for the Republican Party to
have a juggernaut, especially when nobody really knows what all the
leading candidate stands for,'' Hatch told the Toledo Blade this
week. ``He does appear to be very good. And certainly if he wins,
I'll be his strongest supporter. But on the other hand, that
doesn't mean we should just hand it to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also campaigned in Portland, Ore., visiting a Boys and
Girls Club and attending an evening reception.
</P>
<P>
   Bush continues his Western swing Thursday with stops in Spokane,
Seattle and Bellevue, Wash. Nevertheless, his staff told a
gathering of minority journalists convening in Seattle this week
that he would not have time to speak to them. All presidential
candidates were invited, but only Democrats Gore and Bill Bradley
accepted.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
