<HEADLINE>
IN A FEISTY TAKEOVER BATTLE, THE DEVIL MAY BE IN THE FOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo.)   (bl)  
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the world of mergers and acquisitions, the best negotiations
amount to something of a poker game. Never let your opponent know
what you are thinking. Show your hand only when you must. And
always serve good food.
</P>
<P>
   Such a game is being deftly played by the executives and
advisers involved in what is fast becoming the feistiest takeover
battle in recent years. Three weeks ago, Qwest Communications
International, the telecommunications upstart based in Denver, made
hostile offers for both U S West Corp. and Frontier Corp., two
companies that recently agreed to merge with Global Crossing Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   Teams of bankers, lawyers and corporate executives for both U S
West, the smallest of the regional Bell companies, and Qwest have
been holed up at U S West's headquarters in downtown Denver since
Saturday trying to hammer out an agreement that both companies can
live with. As of Wednesday night, neither company had signed a
confidentiality agreement that would allow an exchange of financial
information, people close to the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   But the discussions continue in earnest, including a
presentation on regulatory issues last Saturday to U S West
executives by Qwest chief executive Joseph Nacchio, said a person
close to the talks. While some people suggest that a decision from
U S West could be reached as early as next week, several issues
have yet to be resolved. One point of contention is the fate of
Solomon Trujillo, the chief executive of U S West.
</P>
<P>
   Trujillo is not interested in a combination with Qwest unless he
can be named co-chief executive and the board be split equally
between Qwest and U S West, people close to the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   Haggling for a spot in the executive suite should not come as a
surprise. Trujillo's role in a combined Global Crossing and U S
West was a major sticking point in those talks last spring. One
person involved in that deal said it was one of the concessions
Global made to get the deal done. But Nacchio has said that he does
not want to share the top spot with Trujillo, and has instead
offered him a vice chairmanship. Trujillo has turned down requests
for interviews.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,800 miles away from Denver in law offices and
investment bank conference rooms on Manhattan's East Side, a small
group of executives from Frontier, a long-distance company, and
their advisers have met with a separate negotiating team for Qwest
regarding those merger talks. On Tuesday, people close to the talks
said, Frontier representatives asked for more clarification on the
bid being offered by Qwest. The two teams met again Wednesday and
began a preliminary exchange of financial data.
</P>
<P>
   The question on the minds of some investors is whether Global
Crossing's founder, Gary Winnick, will step in and raise his
$63-a-share stock offer for Frontier. ``It's hard to imagine at the
end of the day that Frontier will be left with a $63-a-share
deal,'' a person close to the talks said. Qwest's current offer for
Frontier is $68 a share in Qwest stock and cash. But there are
other issues Frontier executives are considering, including when a
transaction is likely to close and what the regulatory hurdles are.
</P>
<P>
   Executives for Global Crossing and Frontier continue to meet
weekly to discuss their deal, which _ if Qwest does not intervene _
is expected to close in the third quarter of this year. And it is
expected that Global chief executive Robert Annunziata will take
Global Crossing's story to investors next week after it files
documents regarding Frontier with regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Winnick and Annunziata have remained silent so far. Global
Crossing has a provision in its merger deal with Frontier that
allows it a ``last look'' at any bid made by Qwest. But some people
close to the talks suggest that Global Crossing would have been
better off to close the Frontier transaction first before agreeing
to merge with U S West.
</P>
<P>
   What is unclear is how well Qwest and U S West are getting along
even in these exploratory talks. One person close to the talks said
U S West executives have chafed at the deluge of letters to
Trujillo that Qwest has issued. Qwest undertook a letter writing
campaign two weeks ago to correct what it considered to be
misleading or inaccurate information, including press accounts. But
U S West told Qwest to ``turn down the heat,'' said the person,
referring to Qwest's letter writing.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing some people commented on was that the meals in
this round of talks are far different from those during the Global
Crossing discussions. One night in Manhattan, U S West executives
had meals delivered from Shun Lee, one of the city's priciest and
best-regarded Chinese restaurants. When Qwest executives went to U
S West's headquarters recently, they brought bagels. ``There are
few good restaurants in Denver,'' one person said, sighing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
