<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: MAKING POLITICAL HAY ON MOYNIHAN'S FARM  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GAIL COLLINS  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINDARS CORNERS, N.Y. _ Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan's upstate
farm went into full media alert for Hillary Rodham Clinton's visit.
The Moynihan barn was cleaned out to make room for portable toilets
by the senator's chief of staff, who swore he had done it
voluntarily on his day off. The hay was cut, baled and replaced by
a field full of satellite dishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least 60 TV crews!'' cried a man who had apparently gone to
the New York City Police Department School of Crowd Counting. But
there certainly were 30 cameras, and as a whole the turnout was
probably the largest press corps ever assembled for a political
event held in a pasture.
</P>
<P>
   What made the event most significant was not that Mrs. Clinton
was appearing for the first time as the proud possessor of a newly
formed campaign exploratory committee. Nor was it Moynihan's
endorsement, which he almost forgot to deliver. The big moment came
when she finally acknowledged that yes, it was probably a little
peculiar for a first lady to run for the Senate from a state where
she has never lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a very fair question,'' she said in answer to the
inevitable carpetbagging query. ``I fully understand people raising
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The reporters had no tricky questions on her position on the
milk compact or the problems of the Montgomery Otsego Schoharie
Solid Waste Management Authority. Like most of the universe, the
press corps was fixated on the circumstance behind her candidacy,
beginning with Monica Lewinsky (was Mrs. Clinton benefiting from
her status as victim?) and ending with the chutzpah required for a
person to have a Senate Exploratory Committee before she has a
mailing address.
</P>
<P>
   But except for questions relating to Ms. Lewinsky, whose name
causes her to flinch and change the subject, the first lady has a
handle on her problem. She has gone way beyond her earlier attempts
to establish New Yorker status by discussing local agricultural
produce and wearing a Yankees hat.
</P>
<P>
   Instead she is using that old trick _ perhaps better known to
women than men _ that assumes there is nothing more ingratiating
than acknowledging one's ignorance and begging to be educated. Her
plan is to spend the next several months traveling around the state
asking for information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are confident she will be able to meet with New Yorkers and
listen to their concerns,'' her press spokesman Howard Wolfson said
in response to many different questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will these be real New Yorkers?'' asked a TV reporter
suspiciously.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Mrs. Clinton said that having one meeting after
another with average New Yorkers about education and health and
agriculture and transportation was exactly her idea of a fun way to
spend the summer. Anticipating the press corps' collapse into
misery and boredom will no doubt make the prospect all the sweeter.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton ``listening tour'' is actually a clever campaign
device that offers the candidate a chance to do quite a bit of
talking within a noncontroversial first lady format. Her shakedown
session in Oneonta Wednesday featured five local residents talking
about schools while Mrs. Clinton nodded, took notes and delivered
supportive comments (``I'm a very strong proponent of early
pre-K.''). When an education professor talked about local rural
poverty, Mrs. Clinton said she had seen exactly the same problems
in Arkansas. But when a remedial-education teacher moved into more
controversial waters, decrying politicians who were trying to drive
her students out of college in the name of higher standards, Mrs.
Clinton just nodded cheerfully, and thanked her for her comments.
</P>
<P>
   While Mrs. Clinton was working her way around her residency
problem, her potential opponent Rudolph Giuliani, New York City's
mayor, was digging himself into a hole. The mayor is a native New
Yorker, but lately he seems compelled to gild the lily. To hear
Giuliani tell it this week, he is a cross between Johnny Appleseed
and an upstate Amway salesman. He has not only campaigned in
upstate New York, he used to work there! In a bunch of different
places! He is expert in state geography and an outdoorsman familiar
with the local flora and fauna.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a great deal of knowledge of the state of New York _
far more than you actually think I do,'' he told reporters shortly
before he confused a town in the Catskills with a county several
hundred miles farther north. He managed to make Hillary Clinton
look like the candidate who is best at handling the carpetbagging
issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
