<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ISRAEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A SUMMONS TO PEACE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, July 8:
</P>
<P>
   Israel's new prime minister, Ehud Barak, is acting like a
statesman. With an eloquent inaugural speech Tuesday and plans for
a quick round of meetings with Arab leaders before meeting
President Clinton next week, he seems committed to reviving the
stalled quest for Mideast peace.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has wisely decided to complete the unfinished business of
making an accord with the Palestinians and to seek improved
relations with Syria and Lebanon. He also wants to deepen relations
with Egypt and Jordan, moving beyond mere diplomatic recognition
toward true partnership.
</P>
<P>
   In his inaugural message Barak was inclusive and conciliatory,
expressing empathy not only for the Palestinians and other Arabs
but for the defeated Likud Party of former Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and for Israel's disadvantaged minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast to Netanyahu was striking when Barak spoke of his
desire to work in ``partnership and respect'' with the Palestinian
leadership under Yasser Arafat. ``I call on all regional leaders to
take our outstretched hands and build a peace of the brave,'' Barak
declared, setting a tone different from his predecessor's.
</P>
<P>
   Barak begins his peacemaking this weekend, when he plans to meet
with President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt and Arafat. Next week he
expects to see King Abdullah of Jordan and then travel to
Washington for talks with Clinton. With the administration in
accord with Barak's agenda, his talks at the White House are likely
to be more amicable than Netanyahu's visits.
</P>
<P>
   With the Palestinians, Barak's first action will be carrying out
the Israeli withdrawals agreed to at Wye River last fall and then
suspended by Netanyahu. Some 10 percent of additional West Bank
land is to be handed over to Palestinian control and 500 additional
Palestinian prisoners released.
</P>
<P>
   Barak initially hoped to skip these steps and move straight to
negotiations on the difficult issues of Jerusalem, Jewish
settlements, Palestinian refugees, water and possible Palestinian
statehood. But at the insistence of Arafat and Washington, he has
accepted the timetable agreed to last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has made a point of reaching out to Syria, and on Tuesday
he advertised his willingness to reach agreement on the basis of
U.N. resolutions calling for the exchange of occupied land for
peace. That seems a signal that Israel is willing to negotiate the
return of all or most of the Golan Heights in return for firm
security guarantees. Barak has also said he is willing to resume
talks with Syria where they broke off three years ago,
incorporating the preliminary progress that had been made on the
issues of security arrangements and diplomatic normalization.
</P>
<P>
   Syria's president, Hafez al-Assad, has responded positively to
these overtures, and his trip to Moscow this week seems intended to
prepare for negotiations, though his bid for new Russian weapons is
troubling. Talks with Damascus must also involve Lebanon, which
Syria dominates, and from which Barak wants to withdraw Israeli
troops.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has set an ambitious though appropriate agenda.
Peacemaking is sure to be difficult. Israelis and Arabs alike will
have to make painful compromises on sensitive issues. But Barak is
right to embrace the challenge and deserves strong American
support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-07-99 2316EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
