<DOCNO> NYT19990707.0386 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2578 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-BLACKOUT-NYT &LR;      07-07 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BLACKOUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE BLACKOUT AND ITS CAUSES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, July 8:
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers and their political leaders responded admirably to
Tuesday night's power shortages, including a sudden blackout in the
Washington Heights and Inwood neighborhoods of Manhattan. Though
trapped in darkness and suffocating heat, thousands of residents
north of 155th Street displayed the kind of grit and grace that
made for a largely peaceful night. The Giuliani administration,
meanwhile, successfully scrambled to insure public safety and offer
aid and shelter for those who needed it, thereby discouraging the
violence that marked the 1977 citywide blackout. In fact, every
major player in this heat and power crisis performed creditably,
except for Consolidated Edison.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has properly raised questions that must
be on the mind of every resident and business. One is whether Con
Ed's distribution system is adequate to meet foreseeable peak
demands. The other is whether the utility is making the necessary
investments in backup systems so that when one element in its
network fails, another can take its place. This is not an academic
question for a company that is busily divesting itself of its
generating plants in order to focus on the distribution and
transmission of electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Con Ed's response has been unenlightening. At a news conference
Wednesday J. Michael Evans, Con Ed's president, declined repeatedly
to address the mayor's questions. ``We appreciate all the patience
our customers have shown'' was about all Evans would say. This is
an age of advanced technology and sophisticated tools to predict
demand. New Yorkers are thus owed a credible, detailed account of
what caused the malfunction of feeder cables uptown, as well as a
fuller justification for the decision to shut off the power north
of 155th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, New York State's Public Service Commission should
speed its investigation of Con Ed's performance. This is all the
more important because the nation's utilities, including Con Ed,
are transforming themselves from highly regulated monopolies into
market-driven companies. During this transition to a world of
minimal regulation and maximum competition, state and federal
authorities need to exercise continued vigilance to protect the
basic functions of everyday life by insuring a reliable flow of
power. Over the long term, the state will need greater investment
in energy efficiency and on-site power generation from photovoltaic
cells and other sources. These demand-management tools can also
help avert crisis.
</P>
<P>
   In all other respects, the city has much to be proud of.
Ordinary New Yorkers acted with remarkable forbearance. There were
few lootings and only a handful of arrests, thanks partly to
Giuliani's decision to quickly deploy extra police officers over
250 blocks in northern Manhattan. Acting on contingency plans
devised after Chicago's brutal heat wave in 1995, officials ordered
extra ambulances into service and opened 15 schools across the city
where anyone could sleep in air-conditioned comfort. There were,
regrettably, at least eight deaths attributed to the heat. But
without a general display of good sense, the suffering could have
been much worse.
</P>
</TEXT>
