<HEADLINE>
WASTE MANAGEMENT SHARES FALL 36 PERCENT ON PROFIT WARNING
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Texas)   (nk) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Skittish investors sent shares of Waste Management Inc., the
nation's largest trash hauler, into free fall Wednesday, a day
after the company warned analysts that revenue and earnings for the
second quarter were much lower than anyone had expected.
</P>
<P>
   The stock tumbled $19.625, or 36.6 percent, to $33.9375, its
lowest price since the company was formed last July when USA Waste
Services acquired Waste Management Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts, many of whom had had strong buy recommendations on the
stock, flooded First Call Corp., which tracks analysts' estimates,
with downgrades Wednesday. ``This wasn't a reaction to one
quarter's numbers,'' said Charles L. Hill, First Call's director of
research. ``This was a confidence issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Waste Management's second-quarter results are not
catastrophic. The company, which is based in Houston, said its
quarterly revenue would be off by $250 million _ not a death blow
for a company whose annual revenue approaches $13 billion. It said
earnings would come in between 67 and 70 cents a share, much lower
than the 78 cents analysts had expected but well above the 41 cents
a share it earned in the second quarter last year. For the year,
the company now expects earnings of $2.65 to $2.70 a share, up from
$1.82 last year but below analysts' prior expectations of $3.01.
</P>
<P>
   But the company, which had blessed the 78 cent estimate as
recently as May, has not explained why it did not meet its own
predictions. ``We had lower revenues and volume in June, and we're
working to understand exactly what created this shortfall,'' said
Cherie Rice, vice president for investor relations.
</P>
<P>
   That left analysts to come to their own, mostly unflattering,
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The merger just isn't going very well,'' said Douglas R.
Augenthaler, an analyst with CIBC World Markets. ``They haven't
gotten the cost synergies they expected, and they haven't
integrated their information system.''
</P>
<P>
   Augenthaler suspects that faulty data may have wreaked havoc on
routing systems and billing procedures, alienating customers. And
he thinks it kept the company from realizing in time that its own
forecasts were off and that this late realization prompted it to
raise prices in large markets like New York in a futile attempt to
make up the slack. Instead, it alienated customers even further.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were like a basketball player taking the shot from
midcourt at the buzzer,'' Augenthaler said. ``The shot clanked off
the rim.''
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts say the rush to sell stemmed from a belief that
the history of mismanagement, accounting discrepancies and earnings
disappointments that plagued Waste Management before it was
acquired was going to be endlessly repeated. They worry that John
Drury, the merged company's chief executive, who is undergoing
treatment for brain cancer, is not well enough to ride herd on
field operations, and that Rodney R. Proto, its president, is being
stretched too thin as he tries to do two jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real feeling of, `Uh-oh, here we go again,' '' said
James N. Kelleher, an analyst with Argus Research. ``Any other
company, you'd say they just goofed, but this company acquired a
legacy of funny accounting and bad karma.''
</P>
<P>
   As an independent company, Waste Management spent the early
1990s buying up hundreds of waste haulers and chemical waste
treaters worldwide, only to shed many of them when they proved
unprofitable. It had three chief executives in two years; one of
them, Ronald T. LeMay, departed scarcely four months after joining
amid speculation that he was angry over accounting discrepancies.
Last year, the company acknowledged that it had overvalued its
landfills, trucks and other assets, and it revised earnings from
1992 through 1997 downward by $3.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the company's reputation among customers was intact when
USA Waste Services bought it last year, one reason the new parent
chose to retain the Waste Management name instead of its own. That
decision, analysts say, is coming back to haunt it now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
