<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEES PLIGHT OF INDIANS, OFFERS INITIATIVES &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By NANCY MATHIS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINE RIDGE, S.D. _ Tears came to Geraldine Blue Bird's eyes as
she described to President Clinton her hand-to-mouth existence, of
the 27 relatives who live with her in her ramshackle home and the
rundown trailer beside it, of the desperate need for jobs _ and
hope.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Bird, 44, may be a descendant of the first Americans, but
American Indians here on the 7 million-acre Pine Ridge Oglala Sioux
Reservation are last on every chart, and seemingly on everyone's
mind, the poorest of the poor in a thriving nation.
</P>
<P>
   After touring the Igloo neighborhood here, so named because many
homes are converted Army barracks from Igloo, S.D., the president
on Wednesday declared the conditions faced by American Indians to
be appalling and offered a series of initiatives to encourage home
ownership and business development.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you brought jobs here, that's the first step in helping us
out,'' a tearful Blue Bird told Clinton, who held her hand as they
sat on her front porch and sought to console her with a pledge for
help. She's one of 58 people living on the Igloo block, almost all
of them on public assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, only the second president to visit an Indian
reservation in 50 years, later told a gathering of national tribal
leaders, ``We cannot rest until we do better and trying is not
enough; we have to have results. We can do better.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's visit here came on the third day of his
six-state tour of the nation's poorest regions to promote his New
Markets Initiative to attract businesses to these areas and to
shine a national spotlight on those corners of America missing from
the bright economy.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton later flew to Phoenix to tour a Mexican food
manufacturing plant and spoke to business executives about start-up
companies, especially in Hispanic neighborhoods. Gene Humphrey, an
Enron executive, told Clinton that the Houston corporation has
started an equity company that so far as invested in four
businesses, three of them Hispanic-owned.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we're going to do is encourage other
corporations to take the same step,'' Humphrey said. ``It's good
business for us, it's good for the community, and it's good for the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   In Pine Ridge, native dancers greeted Clinton as his helicopter
armada ferried Cabinet members, corporate leaders and members of
Congress to the reservation.
</P>
<P>
   The president toured an old neighborhood and a new one. He also
shared an outdoor stage with tribal leaders, some in traditional
feather headdresses. A teepee served as the backdrop, and buffalo
hides draped the platform rails.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Salway, president of the Oglala Sioux nation, praised
Clinton for ``opening the doors'' for American Indians. He called
Clinton's visit ``a great opportunity to remind Americans that
Indian people walk in both worlds'' of tradition and the
mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton noted that nearly 19 million jobs have been created
since 1993, but American Indians, especially those living on
reservations, remain mired in poverty and unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   In South Dakota, the administration promoted not only private
sector efforts but also action the government can take to provide
building blocks for economic development. In the isolated,
wind-swept plains, the needs start with the most basic necessities
such as housing and drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, an estimated 29 percent of the American Indians are
homeless and 59 percent live in substandard housing.
</P>
<P>
   Salway said 4,000 Sioux here are on a waiting list for homes and
20 percent of the homes lack plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   Alcoholism and other social ills also plague the reservation
here. An estimated 63 percent of the population of the Pine Ridge
reservation lives below the poverty line. Per capita income in 1990
was $3,417, making it the poorest region in the nation, according
to the last census.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have suffered from neglect, and you know that doesn't
work. You have also suffered from the tyranny of patronizing,
inadequately funded government programs and you know that doesn't
work,'' Clinton said. ``We're not coming from Washington to tell
you exactly what to do and how to do it, we're coming from
Washington to ask you what you want to do, and tell you we will
give you the tools and support to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration, placing an emphasis on housing on the
reservations nationwide, announced several initiatives by the
Federal National Mortgage Association (Fannie Mae) and the
Department of Housing and Urban Development to make more
low-interest loans available. There are no banks on the
reservation.
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae will make $6 million in low-interest loans available
to Sioux tribal members, part of a $500 million package for South
Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   HUD, hosting a ``shared vision'' housing conference in nearby
Rapid City, announced a new partnership with private lenders to
help create 1,000 new homeowners on Indian reservations nationwide
in three years by doubling the number of government-guaranteed
loans.
</P>
<P>
   The Agriculture Department also will earmark grants for water
development. Many homes around Pine Ridge have no running water.
The Federal Communications Commission also will work on improving
telephone systems.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Salway also signed an agreement granting empowerment
zone status to the reservation, which makes businesses locating
here eligible for federal tax incentives.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
