<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KAHANE-SUSPECT-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 MAN SUSPECTED OF ROLE IN A KAHANE ASSASSINATION PLOT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Federal prosecutors in Manhattan are investigating
whether a New Jersey man was involved in the conspiracy to
assassinate Rabbi Meir Kahane nine years ago, according to an
indictment unsealed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Mustafa Elnore of Jersey City, N.J., was charged in the
indictment with lying to a grand jury about what prosecutors said
was his role in the murder and what they called his bomb-making
activities and firearms training with a circle of Brooklyn-based
Arab militants in the early 1990s. Some of those militants were
convicted in the bombing of the World Trade Center and a conspiracy
to blow up the United Nations and other landmarks in New York City
in 1993, and of Kahane's killing in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   During his grand jury appearance, Elnore was asked several
questions about his knowledge of the shooting of Kahane in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Elnore, 37, was not charged with any crimes other than perjury.
But at a bail hearing at federal court in Manhattan, a prosecutor
said that his asserted lies ``were involved with and clearly
related to terrorist activities.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, Joshua G. Berman, asked that Elnore be jailed
without bond pending trial, contending that he was dangerous and
might flee the country if released,
</P>
<P>
   Over the objections of Elnore's lawyer, Chief Magistrate Judge
James C. Francis IV agreed to jail Elnore without bond, on the
ground that he might flee. The magistrate did not address the
question of whether Elnore posed a danger.
</P>
<P>
   Elnore's lawyer, Mahmoud Ramadan, said after court that his
client denied lying to the grand jury and also denied the
underlying allegations of wrongdoing. The charges, which the
indictment said stemmed from the original investigation into the
World Trade Center bombing and the plot to bomb the landmarks, do
not specifically cite the current government investigation into the
bombings of the U.S. Embassies in Nairobi, Kenya, and Dar es
Salaam, Tanzania, last August, which killed more than 200 people
and injured thousands.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment also indicated that prosecutors were
investigating whether Elnore was involved in the 1990 murder of
Rashad Khalifa, a Muslim leader in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The government has said in earlier court hearings that el Hage
is being investigated in connection with that murder as well.
</P>
<P>
   During Wednesday's court proceedings, Elnore sat quietly as his
lawyer, Ramadan, disputed the government's assertions.
</P>
<P>
   Ramadan said that Elnore, a native of Egypt who has obtained his
U.S. citizenship, ran his own business and posed no threat to
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's charged with perjury,'' Ramadan said. ``He's not charged
with anything to do with bomb making or firearms.''
</P>
<P>
   But the prosecutor, Berman, said the government had evidence to
prove that Elnore had lied, including photographs and witnesses
that show he was involved in the firearms training and bomb-making.
</P>
<P>
   Berman offered no additional details about the Kahane killing,
but the fact that Elnore was asked about the case in his grand jury
appearance in early 1998 makes clear that the authorities have
never closed the book on the murder, which took place in a
Manhattan hotel ballroom on Nov. 5, 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Another man, El Sayyid A. Nosair, who was acquitted of the
murder in a state trial in 1991, was convicted in 1995 on a federal
charge of murder in aid of racketeering, and sentenced to life in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's indictment suggests prosecutors believe they can
prove that Elnore was involved in a conspiracy to murder Kahane,
who was the leader of the Jewish Defense League.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In his grand jury appearance, Elnore was asked whether he knew
that Nosair had planned to kill Kahane, the indictment shows.
</P>
<P>
   Elnore said no.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked whether he knew Nosair had tried to kill Kahane on
prior occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Elnore said no.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Elnore was asked: ``Did you ever have a conversation
with Nosair prior to the murder of Kahane where you discussed
whether or not he should use a silencer when he killed Rabbi
Kahane?''
</P>
<P>
   Elnore again said no, according to the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   The government said that all three responses were lies.
</P>
</TEXT>
