<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2588 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY08-COX     07-07 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Listen up: Clinton goes 'exploring'
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVENPORT, N.Y. _ Wednesday was a cloudless blue day in central
New York, picture perfect for passing on a political torch and for
answering at least one of the questions swirling around Hillary
Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers may be baffled as to why the first lady would
consider representing them in the Senate, let alone where she'd
live in their great state.
</P>
<P>
   But why, they may wonder, is Clinton's New York trip, kicked off
with a heavily publicized visit to retiring Democratic Sen. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan's farm, called a ``listening tour''? Well, the
reason for that suddenly seemed crystal clear.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody in New York has plenty to say about Clinton and the
2000 Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   ``People call her a carpetbagger, but you know what, Pat
Moynihan was a carpetbagger, too,'' Donna Whitbeck, 44, said
defiantly Wednesday morning, referring to the former Massachusetts
resident who bought property here in the '60s and became her much
beloved neighbor. ``So that's what I think of that whole
carpetbagger charade!''
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted that Moynihan spent much of his boyhood in
New York City, but emotion rather than facts seemed to rule the
carpetbagger debate, at least among the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, when Clinton stopped for lunch with the mayor
of Oneonta at Brooks House of Bar-B-Q, a customer yelled out, ``Go
home!'' Another customer answered, ``You go home!'' The first
yelled back, ``I live here! And I'm not running for senator!'' The
shouting match eventually involved a dozen spectators.
</P>
<P>
   The carpetbagger issue was also the first question raised by the
press at Moynihan's farm.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton brushed aside the point: ``What I am for is maybe as
important, if not more important, than where I am from.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said New Yorkers had some ``very legitimate questions''
about what she believes in and the skills and interests she would
bring to the job. She said she would address them.
</P>
<P>
   She pledged she would be a ``strong and effective advocate on
behalf of the people of New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan essentially endorsed Clinton. ``I hope she'll go all
the way, and I mean to go all the way with her,'' the white-haired
senator told 200 members of the press pack, including 30-plus TV
news crews jammed onto a temporary scaffolding.
</P>
<P>
   They had been gathered for more than an hour in what was a
hayfield the day before, passing the time by jabbering into cell
phones, visiting a lemonade stand run by neighborhood kids, or
explaining why this was such a big story back home in Japan and
France.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she has star power in France,'' Sylvie Kaufmann of Le
Monde newspaper said of the first lady. ``Even before Monica
Lewinsky, people there were intrigued by her because she's a strong
woman, and outspoken and bright.
</P>
<P>
   ``And also,'' Kaufmann confided, ``the belief in France that
she'll run for president someday adds to the attraction of this
story.''
</P>
<P>
   President? Hillary Clinton hasn't even formally announced for
the Senate yet; indeed, it was only on Tuesday that she formed an
exploratory committee. Throughout Wednesday's visit, which also
included a stop at the State University of New York campus for a
discussion of educational issues, Clinton chose her words
carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I run and am honored to be elected ...'' she typically
began one response in a brief question-and-answer session at
Moynihan's farm.
</P>
<P>
   Even the kids running the lemonade stand out of Moynihan's barn
seemed a bit confused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillary Clinton's coming up here today because she's running
for senator,'' said Rebecca Marcus, 9, collecting a quarter from
another thirsty customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't she just coming to announce that today?'' wondered Della
Hodne, 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, she's just coming here,'' Mark Mader, 8, contradicted them
both patiently.
</P>
<P>
   One thing the young lemonade entrepreneurs knew for sure:
Moynihan's wife, Elizabeth (whose idea they said it was they go
into business for a day), probably expected them to keep the money
for themselves, but they had other ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to give all the money to Mrs. Clinton for her
campaign,'' Rebecca announced, pointing proudly to a cigar box
containing about $10 in paper and coins.
</P>
<P>
   No telling what use New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani might
make of news of the campaign contribution. The all-but-announced
Republican contender for the Senate seat, Giuliani is so convinced
the first lady's running that when he's not planning his own
in-your-face fund-raising lunch for later this month in the
Clintons' hometown of Little Rock, he's taking pains to point out
that he's a native New Yorker whose ``very significant knowledge of
the whole state'' is vastly superior to hers.
</P>
<P>
   That may have influenced the Clinton exploratory committee's
decision to issue press passes that have as their background a map
of central New York _ not the New York City area, where Giuliani
lives and Clinton reportedly is house-hunting.
</P>
<P>
   In her informal discussion with school board members, students
and parents gathered Wednesday afternoon at the State University of
New York at Oneonta, she displayed a star pupil style familiarity
with test results, school district sizes and other issues of local
concern as she discussed the need for universal pre-kindergarten
programs.
</P>
<P>
   She also promised to help retain young teachers in classrooms,
bolster public education, and _ in a preview of the health-related
issues she will discuss today _ pledged to reduce the numbers of
Americans who do not have health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Giuliani's geographic gibes may have backfired on him
Wednesday, as the New York Post gleefully reported that the mayor
had mixed up his Monroes.
</P>
<P>
   After Giuliani told reporters he'd beaten the New York heat by
spending Monday way upstate with his son in bucolic Monroe County,
the Post checked out his claim. It seems the mayor actually went to
the town of Monroe, which is in an entirely different county only
40 miles north of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton people had no comment on the Giuliani gaffe. Not so
the press, which spent much of the nearly 90-minute bus ride from
Albany to Moynihan's farm pointing to random fields and shouting
out comments like, ``Look, Rudy once flew a kite there!''
</P>
<P>
   Yet going in and out of Davenport, the buses also passed by
small clusters of people holding anti-Hillary signs (''We need a
New Yorker, not a Clinton,'' said one) and one guy waving an
elephant-shaped placard that simply read, ``Rudy!''
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder folks around here wonder just what, exactly, is
going on in their state?
</P>
<P>
   It's not just the fact that so much mystery and mudslinging has
already built up around an election that is still 16 months away.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the matter of the likely candidates themselves.
</P>
<P>
   For every person here who claims not to like Clinton for
``carpetbagging'' reasons, there's another who doesn't like
Giuliani because he's from _ shudder! _ New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, we feel New York City turns a deaf ear to, well,
everywhere else,'' Janet Tenace, of nearby Colonie, said of the
common sentiment in this section of New York state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have one candidate from Arkansas and another from New
York City,'' lamented Dawn Purcell. ``You wonder, in a big state
like this, can't anyone find a third one?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
