<HEADER>
A2593 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BLACKOUT-1STLD-WRI     07-07 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BLACKOUT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK'S POWER RETURNS AS HEAT EASES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to make insert in 2nd graf for clarity; inserts new 6th graf
on additional regional problems.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After a blackout that lasted nearly 19 hours, power
was restored to most of northern Manhattan Wednesday, but angry
city officials nonetheless threatened legal action against Con
Edison, saying the utility had failed to build a power system able
to withstand intense heat waves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the city of New York is entitled to a more secure flow
of electrical power than Con Edison is giving us,'' Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani said Wednesday, contending that poor planning by the
company had created a life-threatening crisis for the city. ``You
can't have too many nights like the night we had last night and not
expect that you are going to kill people.''
</P>
<P>
   The blackout in the Washington Heights and Inwood neighborhoods
was the most spectacular result of a three-day heat wave that
officials blamed for eight deaths in the city _ six in Manhattan
and two in Brooklyn. Most of the victims were elderly _ the
youngest was 53, the oldest 90 _ and all succumbed after their body
temperatures climbed to extremely dangerous levels. None of the
deaths were blamed directly on the Manhattan blackout.
</P>
<P>
   The blackout occurred when Consolidated Edison workers were
preparing to turn two power cables that had failed in upper
Manhattan on Tuesday night back on when one of the cables failed
again, sparking a fire. Con Ed said that it quickly shut down all
power to the entire area north of 155th Street to prevent further
damage.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond New York, officials said the heat caused seven deaths in
Pennsylvania, four in New Jersey, two in Massachusetts and two in
Washington. Scattered power failures continued to plague hundreds
of thousands of people across the Northeast and mid-Atlantic states
Wednesday, and hospitals continued to treat hundreds of people for
heat exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   New power failures flared in some parts of New York City,
including the Lower East Side, and also in downtown Newark, N.J.,
where blackouts knocked out power to the subway system,
Pennsylvania Station and thousands of homes and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   But temperatures across the region dropped significantly. In
Central Park, Wednesday's high reached a breezy 92 degrees, well
below the 101-degree temperatures recorded there on Monday and
Tuesday. In many New England cities, the highs barely nudged into
the low 80s, and the cooler weather is expected to last through the
week.
</P>
<P>
   Cheers and applause swept through the streets of northern
Manhattan when, at 5:05 p.m. ET, power was restored to 93 percent
of the affected customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lights went on, and the air-conditioner went on, and
everyone started screaming,'' Kelvin Nunez, 24, said outside his
apartment building on 159th Street. ``Then we relaxed in front of
the air-conditioner. It felt great. Cold. Nice. I knew I was going
to sleep well.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the length of the blackout, police reported only a
handful of looting arrests. But shopkeepers in the area, which is
home to many Dominican immigrants and includes some of the city's
poorest and most crowded neighborhoods, were left to contend with
another problem _ substantial stocks of spoiled food. Demetrio
Tavariz, who owns a bodega on 187th Street, was typical. He said he
had lost $1,000 worth of meat and dairy products. ``I don't know if
my insurance will cover it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   City officials also worried about expenses associated with the
blackout. Though no final cost estimate was available, hundreds of
additional police officers were deployed throughout the blackout
area, which encompassed all of Manhattan north of 155th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he had directed city attorneys to research a
lawsuit against Con Ed. The suit would likely have three
objectives: to seek money damages for public costs, to force Con
Edison to come up with a plan to prevent more blackouts, and to
establish an independent monitor to assess the quality of the
company's power system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night was not a natural disaster,'' the mayor said.
``Last night was a man-made disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   For guidance, the city's lawyers Wednesday were studying a
lawsuit the city filed against Con Edison after the 1977 blackout,
which left millions of residents without power for 25 hours.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, the Court of Appeals, New York state's highest
court, ruled that Con Edison's gross negligence led to the power
failure, but the court also held that the utility did not have to
pay New York City for additional police and fire protection caused
by the blackout. The city could, however, recover money for
property damage from the blackout or any resulting looting, the
ruling said.
</P>
<P>
   But officials at the state Public Service Commission, which
regulates utility companies, said that in studies of power failure
rates, Con Edison had the best performance of the state's utility
companies. As is routine for power failures, the commission said it
will examine Con Edison's efforts this week in New York City and
Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will review the utility's actions to ensure that they were
reasonable and that they complied with their operating
procedures,'' said Dave Flanagan, a spokesman for the commission.
</P>
<P>
   And as Giuliani spoke of lawsuits, his aides were acknowledging
that, despite years of complaining about blackouts, they remained
largely uninformed about the quality, design and load capacities of
the city's power grid.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Hauer, director of the Mayor's Office of Emergency
Management, said the city has enlisted consultants to study the
power system. ``The city will now get more involved in
understanding that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Con Edison officials declined to comment on the mayor's threat
of legal action, saying they were focusing instead on restoring
power to customers. But the mayor was not the only public official
consulting lawyers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   David Paterson, an influential Democratic state senator who
represents a portion of Washington Heights, said Wednesday that he
was considering organizing a class-action lawsuit against Con
Edison. He said many residents firmly believed that Con Edison cut
power to Washington Heights to spare the city's wealthier
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll never be able to convince anybody that it was a random
event,'' Paterson said, a remark echoed by other local officials.
``They think it was very deliberate and they think it was a chosen
way to handle the problem at our expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perception in that area,'' he added, ``is that the area
has regularly been denied service and opportunity, and this is just
in furtherance of that same concept.''
</P>
<P>
   A Con Edison spokesman, Joseph Petta, responded: ``If that is
the perception, it is a false perception. There is no reason why
one network would not be maintained as diligently as another area,
regardless of its location.''
</P>
<P>
   J. Michael Evans, president of Con Edison, insisted that the
power network serving Washington Heights and Inwood was designed to
the same engineering specifications and received the same level of
maintenance and equipment upgrades as the company's other networks.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Company officials continued to give sometimes conflicting
accounts of the events that led up to the power failure. On Tuesday
night, Petta said the network crashed on its own because it was
overloaded by demand. Early Wednesday, Petta said the company
itself cut the power to prevent the blackout from spreading across
Manhattan. Later Wednesday, Con Edison denied that concerns over a
broader blackout figured into their decision.
</P>
<P>
   As Evans toured Washington Heights Wednesday afternoon with City
Council Speaker Peter Vallone, the utility executive told reporters
that the company had no choice but to cut power when a small fire
started in a substation that supplied electricity to northern
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very concerned that by continuing to operate the
network, it would overload and damage the facility, and ultimately
make it more difficult to restore service to the citizens of this
area,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But what remained undetermined Wednesday was why Washington
Heights' network began to fail in the first place, and why several
other networks across the city also came perilously close to
failing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't really tell you why,'' Evans said, adding that company
experts would conduct a complete analysis of their equipment and
systems.
</P>
<P>
   City officials, however, were focused on Con Edison's web of
feeder lines, insulated high-power lines that run underneath the
city's major avenues. By Con Edison's count, 50 of the system's
1,175 feeder lines failed during the heat wave.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day Wednesday, Con Ed scrambled to cope with an
unfolding public relations disaster. They issued apologies for the
power failure. They praised the residents of northern Manhattan.
They promised they were doing everything possible to restore power.
Evans, who earned $616,333 last year in salary and bonuses, even
sought to identify with those who suffered through a long, hot
night. He said his own house had been without power on Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife tells me it was very uncomfortable,'' he said, noting
that he never made it home to see for himself because he was
managing the company's response.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
