<SLUG> BC-RESENDEZ-RAMIREZ-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESENDEZ-RAMIREZ URGED TO SURRENDER &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By ERIC BERGER
 &HT;    c. 1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Apparently lacking any substantive progress in finding
Rafael Resendez-Ramirez, federal authorities, along with his
common-law wife, asked the suspected serial killer Wednesday to
turn himself in.
</P>
<P>
   Julieta Dominguez Reyes was expected to make her appeal in
person at the FBI office here, where dozens of news cameras
awaited. But instead she made it through the FBI official leading
the Resendez-Ramirez task force.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has expressed to us her sincere wishes that he would turn
himself in to authorities,'' said Don K. Clark, FBI special agent
in charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has also expressed the fact that this activity has caused
her and her baby a great deal of pain and difficulty in living in
their community now.''
</P>
<P>
   Reyes says her 3-month-old daughter, Lirio Judith, was fathered
by Resendez-Ramirez, whom she said she last saw June 10 at their
home in Rodeo, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Clark would not say whether Reyes was in Houston, but a source
familiar with the investigation confirmed later that she was in
town cooperating with investigators. The source was unsure why
Reyes did not make her plea in person.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities also urged people to continue phoning in tips on the
man believed responsible for five murders in Texas, two in Illinois
and one in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our purpose here this afternoon is to continue to encourage a
higher level of public interest and participation,'' said Richard
Cravener, district director of the Immigration and Naturalization
Service's Houston office.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has received more than 3,000 tips since June 21, when
Resendez-Ramirez was named to the FBI's Ten Most Wanted Fugitives
list. Its last confirmed sighting of the suspect was June 18 in a
Louisville, Ky., homeless shelter.
</P>
<P>
   People with information are urged to contact local police or
call the FBI at 1-800-889-8161.
</P>
<P>
   Cravener, who also spoke Spanish in urging anyone with
information on Resendez-Ramirez to come forward, was apparently
appealing to immigrants _ legal and illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Illegal immigrants, he said, would still get reward money, now
$125,000, for the suspect's arrest, as well as possibly escape
deportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The INS is not in the position of offering amnesty,'' Cravener
said, but added that the government has means to provide temporary
visas to those who cooperate with federal investigations.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
